<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SWEEPS DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Seemingly finished by the heat, by the strength-sapping
humidity, by two goals it never should have surrendered, the Galaxy
_ and the plan to sweep the Dallas Burn in the first round of Major
League Soccer's playoffs _ looked as good as dead Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Then arrived the most remarkable occurrence in a season packed
full of them: Three goals in the final 10{ minutes, the finale on
an unimpeded Clint Mathis run, and L.A. _ somehow, some way _
pulled out a dramatic 3-2 triumph before 8,130 at the Cotton Bowl
to earn a place in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Galaxy's depth that made the difference and left
Octavio Zambrano looking like a genius, his three second-half
substitutions changing the tenor of a match that, at least for the
first 75 minutes or so, L.A. had no business winning.
</P>
<P>
   But after watching the Burn make the most of nearly every
opportunity that fell its way, the Galaxy found its stride in the
final minutes, using strikes by Ezra Hendrickson and Paul Caligiuri
and Mathis' stirring run from midfield to claim the best-of-three
series two games to none.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you,'' said Zambrano, ``it's the crunch when you can
see the real character of some players, and Clint and Ezra both
came through in the crunch. You need that element if you aspire to
go all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been the Galaxy's aspiration since the exhibition season,
and two more victories _ over either Chicago or Colorado starting
Saturday at the Rose Bowl _ will it them back to the MLS Cup on its
home turf, where in 1996 it saw a 2-0 lead disappear in the final
minutes of a loss to D.C. United.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it took advantage of a weary Dallas squad that didn't
have enough juice, or a deep enough bench, to hold onto what looked
like an insurmountable lead.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that way because L.A., too, was exhausted, wilted by
86-degree heat and 70 percent humidity. But three changes _ Mathis
for midfielder Martin Machon and Hendrickson for left back Joe
Franchino in the 57th minute, and Wellington Sanchez for midfielder
Danny Pena in the 63rd _ provided everything it needed to turn
things around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our three guys gave us the shot of adrenaline we needed in a
crucial moment,'' said Zambrano. ``We were tired, no doubt about
it. One time I looked out there and Cobi (Jones), Welton, Mauricio
(Cienfuegos) and Carlos (Hermosillo) were just standing. They were
spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was up to those three guys to make it happen and they made
it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   So did some tactical adjustments. With the Burn sitting back
trying to protect a 2-0 lead _ forged with goals by Brian Haynes in
the 44th minute and Jason Kreis in the 48th _ Zambrano sent
everyone forward except central defenders Robin Fraser and Steve
Jolley. Sanchez, making his second appearance since mid-July,
encountered little opposition in midfield and was able to direct an
attack that spent most of the final 15 minutes camped around the
Dallas box.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrickson halved the deficit in the 80th minute, getting into
the goalmouth to volley home a sharp Cienfuegos cross from left of
the net, and Caligiuri evened things in the 85th, soaring above
Jorge Rodriguez to head in a Cienfuegos free kick earned by Sanchez
on a run from midfield.
</P>
<P>
   That seemed to freeze Burn defenders, who turned into spectators
for Mathis' run in the 88th minute. It started on the right wing,
with Mathis playing two passes with Jolley to open space, the
taking off unchallenged toward Dallas' box.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody stepped up to confront him on the 30-yard run; Jones,
from the left wing, ran through the Burn box, taking defender
Richard Farrer with him, and Rodriguez stepped over to cut off a
passing lane, leaving an open path to the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just opened up in the middle,'' Mathis said. ``I took a big
touch and was about to take a shot, and then (Jones) led Farrer out
of the play and left me some space. So I decided to take another
touch, looked up and saw an opening in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   He got within 14 yards of the goal and curled the ball with his
right foot past goalkeeper Mark Dodd and just inside the far post.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like we self-destructed,'' Dodd said afterward. ``We
played our hearts out, left everything on the field and attacked
with purpose. For whatever reason, we didn't have the discipline,
the organization _ I don't know what. We just didn't have what it
takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, finding ample space behind L.A.'s defense, could have
sent the series back to L.A. for a decisive third game with better
finishing. Chad Deering, moved to the wing in one of coach Dave
Dir's adjustments after Thursday's 6-1 loss, beat Galaxy goalkeeper
Kevin Hartman at the left post in the fifth minute but fired into
the side netting of an open goal; and Kreis beat an offsides trap
to go one-on-one with Hartman in the 26th but did little with the
opportunity, his 13-yarder swept aside by the Galaxy goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes broke the deadlock just before halftime, slipping between
Caligiuri and Pena, streaking into the box and past Hartman, then
firing into an open net.
</P>
<P>
   It was 2-0 three minutes into the second half thanks to a Fraser
miscue to the left of the Galaxy goal. He tried a back pass to
Hartman but hit it poorly, and Mickey Trotman ran onto it as it
reached the 6-yard box. Hartman went out to confront the Dallas
striker, who dropped the ball back for Kreis, who eluded Jolley and
fired into an open net.
</P>
<P>
   That should have been enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those matches,'' Zambrano said. ``One thing
about this team I have to say: It never gives up. There's always an
option, always an opportunity, to still come back and win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
