</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-SAINTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT ESCAPE BY PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ The NFL Films cameras had to work overtime to
capture every moment of Sunday's game between the Patriots and New
Orleans Saints. Artistically, this was far short of ``Gone With the
Wind,'' but for pure entertainment, it was ``Blazing Saddles'' and
better.
</P>
<P>
   It had turnovers, questionable officials' calls, and plays that
perhaps you've never seen before. In the midst of all the chaos, a
27-yard field goal by Adam Vinatieri with three seconds remaining
gave the Patriots an all-too-close-for-comfort 30-27 win.
</P>
<P>
   The win improved the Patriots' rec-ord to 3-1 and dropped the
Saints to 3-1. The Jets' win over the Dolphins left New England in
a tie for first place in the AFC East with Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to execute better,'' said linebacker Ted Johnson,
whose efforts helped stop the Saints' running game dead in its
tracks (39 yards). Once again the Patriots had trouble stopping
their opponents when it really mattered, though, as the Saints
converted 9 of 18 third-down plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game shouldn't be that close,'' Johnson said. ``We hurt
ourselves. There are going to be games when we're not going to win,
but we've got to win the games we're supposed to win and we did. It
wasn't pretty, but given the way the game ended, we'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe (21 of 35 for 317 yards and one touchdown) survived
three interceptions and a fumble that was recovered by New
Orleans's Keith Mitchell and returned 63 yards for a second-quarter
touchdown. Bledsoe led the winning drive, completing four straight
passes for 62 yards to set up Vinatieri after the Saints tied it
with 1:32 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great confidence in my two-minute offense and under two
minutes I expect to be able to score,'' Bledsoe said. ``Vincent
Brisby is a good example. He comes in with two minutes to play and
he makes the key catch of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   After New Orleans tied it, 27-27, Chris Canty couldn't take the
ensuing kickoff past the 20. Bledsoe, in the shotgun, hit Troy
Brown for 9 and 16 yards, Ben Coates for 10, and Brisby for 27 to
the Saints 18.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints, who had been blitzing Bledsoe most of the afternoon,
were selective on the final drive. They blitzed on the second play
to Brown, then on a running play by Robert Edwards that lost 2
yards. A too-many-men-on-the-field penalty put the ball at the 15.
After Edwards, who gained a career-high 97 yards on 22 carries, ran
6 yards to the 9, the Patriots were ready for Vinatieri, whose
winning field goal was his third of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only a few seconds left on the clock and it's the
final play, so sure it's a little nerve-wracking,'' said Vinatieri.
``But the offense did a great job getting the ball downfield and
putting me in a nice spot to kick it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinatieri's heroics were necessary because of one of the more
bizarre plays you'll see. With New England ahead, 27-24, just
before the two-minute warning, Tom Tupa punted from the Saints 45.
Cover man Tebucky Jones caught up to the ball just shy of the end
zone and batted it back toward teammate Larry Whigham, who batted
it to the turf. The ball hit off a Saints player and bounced toward
the Saints' Earl Little, who picked it up. But Andre Hastings, who
had a huge day picking on Chris Canty for six receptions, ripped
the ball out of Little's hands and ran.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots thought the ball was downed. No whistle had blown,
but 99 times out of 100, the ball would have been ruled down.
Whigham claimed he put his hands on Little's shoulders, but the
referee didn't see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to sit it down at the 1-yard line because I thought my
momentum was going to carry me into the end zone,'' said Whigham.
``One of their guys drop-kicked the ball into the end zone and the
other one downed it. I put both of my hands around his shoulders,
because if I hit him, you get a flag.''
</P>
<P>
   But special teams coach Dante Scarnecchia, while acknowledging
that the play is ruled down at the discretion of the official, said
his team needed to finish off the play regardless. ``That's what
I'm (upset) about,'' said Scarnecchia. ``We need to finish plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hastings nearly finished the Patriots, running 76 yards
down the right sideline before Tupa shoved him out of bounds at the
Patriots 25. But the Saints had to settle for a 37-yard field goal
by Doug Brien, tying the game at 27 with 1:29 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots led, 17-14, at the half after New Orleans put
together an 80-yard drive in the final 2:41, scoring on a sharp
1-yard Danny Wuerffel pass to Cam Cleeland with time running out.
</P>
<P>
   But Henry Thomas made a huge defensive play on the first
possession of the second half, picking off Wuerffel on a screen
pass to Lamar Smith. Thomas put a nice spin move on Wuerffel and
ran 24 yards to make it 24-14, Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The teams exchanged field goals to make it 27-17 with 4:44
remaining in the third quarter. Then things started to get a bit
squirmy.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Brown, who had a huge day returning punts (5 for 104
yards), ran one back 38 yards to the Saints 22 after Whigham
pressured Royals and rolled into his left leg, injuring the punter.
There was no penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe followed with his third interception, which went
right through Coates's hands to Tyrone Drakeford at the Saints 25.
</P>
<P>
   Wuerffel (25 of 47 for 278 yards) directed a well-run drive as
he picked on Canty most of the time, including a 22-yard pass to
Hastings to the Patriots 20. He capped it with a 7-yard toss to
Smith, making it 27-24 with 7:44 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   That made all the miscues of the first half, when New England
outgained the Saints, 274 to 122, but only held a 3-point lead,
seem huge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could have scored some early points and I let us down,''
Bledsoe said. ``When you have a chance to make up for those
mistakes, you have to do it. That's what we live for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
