<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOXIC-SCHOOL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSSIBLE CONTAMINATION AT GRADE SCHOOL HAS PARENTS CONFUSED, ANGRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT AND JESSE HIESTAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Nearly two weeks after a legislative hearing
raised concerns of possible elevated toxic contamination at
Jefferson New Middle School in South Central Los Angeles, the
school district is running a battery of new tests to determine
whether the school should be closed.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, it has left notification of parents up to a
state agency.
</P>
<P>
   The suddenness of the new round of testing _ after parents
previously were assured by the district the site is safe, and that
an on-site filtration system was working properly _ has confused
parents and enraged community activists and some area politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure who to believe,'' said Pedro Perez, whose son
attends the school, about a quarter-mile away from their home.
</P>
<P>
   They and other parents said that in the absence of complete test
results and Los Angeles Unified School District assurances, they
wonder whether toxics from the school are to blame whenever their
children come home with rashes or other minor afflictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair. They're risking the health of my children,''
said Maria Elena Aguinaga, 35, who lives just 100 feet from the
school.
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD officials acknowledge there have been problems with the
cleanup of toxic solvents at the site, resulting this week in a
couple dozen citations and a clean-up and abatement order from two
oversight agencies.
</P>
<P>
   But they said there is no indication those problems have
resulted in contamination levels high enough to pose a health risk
to children and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked each of the agencies, is there anything that you
believe suggests we should close the school, and the answer was no,
that they knew of no risk justifying busing 2,000 kids two hours
each day to another school,'' said Barry Groveman, the district's
outside counsel from the Los Angeles firm Proskauer Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-acre site, located across the street from a contaminated
Superfund site, once housed a World War II defense plant, furniture
manufacturers, metal plating operations and a gas station,
according to a report by the state's Joint Legislative Audit
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including state Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Glendale,
said the district should shut the school down until it can
guarantee it is safe for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't taken an aggressive enough approach,'' Wildman
said. ``I'm extremely concerned about the safety of the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD Superintendent Ruben Zacarias said he has a contingency
plan ready if test results expected by midweek show dangerously
elevated toxic levels or if state agencies order it closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew that any state agency said that place is not fit for
kids, I would close it immediately,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 assessment by the district, with state oversight,
concluded that there is no health threat to students.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the concern is the on-site filtering system, or
soil vapor extraction system, which has been shut down periodically
this year. Those shutdowns ``may pose a risk of indoor air
contamination within school buildings,'' the state Department of
Toxic Substances Control said in a letter sent to parents in the
past week.
</P>
<P>
   One of the toxics of concern is methylene chloride, a
carcinogen. It is one of the solvents the vapor extraction system
was supposed to keep from getting into the school's air, according
to regulatory officials.
</P>
<P>
   There is no direct evidence methylene chloride, or any other
contaminant, has migrated from the soil into classrooms during
stoppages of the filtration system, because direct air sampling has
not been required under the system's operating permit, said Barry
Wallerstein, South Coast Air Quality Management District acting
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The air sampling the district has agreed to do this weekend as
part of a plan approved by Department of Toxic Substances Control
and the California Regional Water Quality Control Board is designed
to answer that question, said Angelo Bellomo, vice president of
Environmental Strategies Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the permit likely will be changed to require such
direct air sampling in the future, Wallerstein said.
</P>
<P>
   The problems with the vapor extraction system were detected when
levels of both methylene chloride and total volatile organic
compounds in excess of the permit level were found at a test point
within the VES itself, Wallerstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Those violations are ``technical'' in that they do not suggest
an actual health risk, but nonetheless will be referred to AQMD's
in-house prosecutor for action, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The levels, while violating the permit, were still so low that
had they gone directly into the air they would have been within
safe limits, Wallerstein added.
</P>
<P>
   Groveman said the district has not sent out its own update on
the situation absent a complete review. Further, he said it was
only toward the end of the week that the district's plan to test
the site was approved by regulatory agencies, who themselves had
scrambled throughout the week to deal with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be notifying parents as soon as we get the facts,''
Groveman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bellomo said in addition to air samples, the soil at the site
also will be retested for contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   Toxic Substances Control officials have told parents that soil
used to backfill the site may have come from Caltrans, which could
indicate a higher lead content. The soil was tested previously, but
not with as strict a protocol as Caltrans-procured dirt would have
required.
</P>
<P>
   The Regional Water Quality Control Board is also requiring a
plan to test for hexavalent chromium, another carcinogen, that has
been found in groundwater at the northwestern corner of the school.
No water sampling tests have been scheduled for this weekend, but
they are planned in the longer term.
</P>
<P>
   Perez said he wants to believe the school, which opened last
summer, is safe. But, he said if district officials can't establish
that soon with certainty, ``I'm not going to let my son attend that
school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
