<HEADER>
A9163 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     10-05 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS FOUND A WAY TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ It was not the kind of game you copy onto
videotape cassettes and send home for your friends and relatives to
watch and appreciate. It was not pretty, at least it wasn't pretty
very often.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the way it was supposed to be nor the way it should
have been, but Sunday was the kind of victory that forces teams to
come to your house on some frozen Sunday in January when everything
is on the line and home field counts for something. By then you've
forgotten all about an October afternoon in New Orleans when you
escaped your own errors and won despite yourself.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened Sunday to the New England Patriots. They
won when they could have lost, which says something about them.
They won when not so long ago they would have lost, which says more
about them. They won despite their best efforts to stop themselves
from winning, which says everything about them. What it says is,
barring injuries and acts of God, they're going to win a lot of
games this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My rookie year, my second year, my third year, we probably
would have lost this game,'' admitted Patriots wide receiver Troy
Brown, who is now in his sixth year and glad of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had 10 chances to lose Sunday to a Saints team that
shouldn't have beaten them once if they played 100 times. They
turned the ball over four times. They allowed rag-armed quarterback
Danny Wuerffel to throw for nearly 300 yards. They gave up pass
plays of 32, 23, and 21 yards, and got smoked on seam routes more
often then logic would argue is possible. Worst of all, they gave
up a 76-yard punt return because nobody thought to touch a guy down
on one knee with the ball in his hands in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they played like some of the Patriot teams New
England would like to forget. The difference is they won anyway and
in the National Football League those are often the wins that
separate Super Bowl teams from teams that have to go to Pittsburgh
on a frozen Sunday in January and don't quite survive the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's as difficult as it can get to overcome four
turnovers against an undefeated team,'' Patriots coach Pete Carroll
said after his team had stuffed a 30-27 victory in the satchel by
virtue of a 27-yard Adam Vinatieri field goal with three seconds to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have made it more difficult. But we showed the
will to fight back and overcome adversity we created. We had the
opportunity to seize the game and we didn't. It could have been an
easier day but I'm proud of the way we held on and won.''
</P>
<P>
   They held on by answering whenever the scrappy but undermanned
Saints thought they'd broken through. The first time came after
linebacker Keith Mitchell picked up a Drew Bledsoe fumble and ran
it back for a 63-yard touchdown in the second quarter to give New
Orleans a 7-3 lead. The Saints came right back and intercepted a
Bledsoe pass at their 46. Another score and the Superdome would
have been as loud as a Def Leppard concert.
</P>
<P>
   Instead silence reigned when Ty Law intercepted a Wuerffel pass
three plays later and Bledsoe threw a screen to Derrick Cullors for
43 yards. Next thing you knew it was 10-7 New England because
Vincent Brisby was standing in the end zone with a 6-yard touchdown
catch.
</P>
<P>
   It went that way all day. The inferior but unflappable Saints
scoring points at key moments and the superior but fallible
Patriots responding time and again until they finally checkmated
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the end of the half, for example, New England's
defense made the classic mistake of allowing a team to drive 80
yards for a score as time ran out right after they had pushed their
lead to 17-7. The suddenly re-energized Saints came out to start
the second half trailing by only 3 and believing in themselves.
This could have been a turning point, but the Patriots stymied it
by forcing Wuerffel into an unwise pass under pressure that lineman
Henry Thomas intercepted and returned 24 yards for a touchdown,
putting on a Barry Sanders-like pirouette to elude a tackler along
the way. New England was back in charge.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened? The Saints came right back to score but only
got a field goal after having four shots from inside the New
England 6. And the Patriots answered immediately with three of
their own.
</P>
<P>
   This was the kind of game that frays the nerves of fans and
coaches because those four turnovers and defensive lapses seemed to
have negated a seven-sack day and Bledsoe's 317 yards passing and
Robert Edwards's nearly 100 yards (97 to be exact) rushing and
Terry Glenn's 105 yards receiving when the Saints tied it with 92
seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints did that the way they did it the whole day, by making
a play when none seemed possible. One second a New England punt
seemed to have been downed on the Saints 1. Next moment, Andre
Hastings had stolen the ball from teammate Earl Little and made a
run-for-your-life, 76-yard return to New England's 25.
</P>
<P>
   On many afternoons in many other years, this final folly would
have finished the Patriots. Their defense would have cracked but
this one refused to buckle, allowing a tying field goal but no
more.
</P>
<P>
   On many afternoons in many other years this final frustration
would have led to the offense overreaching and killing itself. But
no more.
</P>
<P>
   Instead an offense that had produced four turnovers refused to
make a fifth. It marched 70 yards in 86 seconds with Bledsoe
dissecting a defense now fearful of rushing him with the wild
abandon it had earlier in the game. So, in the end, it was the
Saints back on their heels, not the Patriots, because New Orleans's
coaches understood who had made New England's life difficult all
day and it really was not them.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a defense in retreat, Bledsoe completed four straight
throws for just enough yardage to set up the winning field goal and
everyone left for the airport happy. In a long season, any team
will have days like this. Even the best of teams will, as the 49ers
showed in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   It is the teams that survive such days who don't have to pack
their galoshes in January and head off to play in stadiums they'd
rather avoid. If that is the way things end up for the Patriots, it
will be because of days like this one when they won simply because
they refused to accept a defeat of their own making.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
