<HEADLINE>
SAINTS LIVED BY BLITZ, THEN LOST WITHOUT IT 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ If he had it to do all over again, he would have
done it differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back,'' said Saints defensive coordinator Zavan
Yaralian, ``I would keep blitzing him again. As the game went
along, I became less enchanted with our blitzes, because they made
most of their big plays when we were blitzing. But, all of the good
things we did today, and we did a lot of good things, came when we
were blitzing.''
</P>
<P>
   Head coach Mike Ditka was right on the money when he said after
the game, ``New England beat us in every phase of the game.
Offense, defense, special teams. The amazing thing was, we still
had a chance to win it at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming into this game, the Patriots were the only team in the
league with no turnovers. They went through three games without a
fumble or interception. But Sunday Drew Blesdoe was responsible for
four turnovers _ three interceptions and a fumble that was returned
for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into the game hoping for turnovers,'' said Yaralian.
``We knew our defense did not match up well against their offense.
There were too many places where they had the edge on us. Our hope
was to get turnovers and make plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strip for a touchdown to give us the lead,'' 7-3 early in
the second quarter, ``was the kind of thing I hoped for. Before the
game, I thought we might battle them into the fourth quarter and
pull out a win. We did. But in the end, we made some fundamental
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where Yaralian could second-guess himself. After the
Saints tied it, 27-27, the Patriots started from their own 20 with
1:21 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Yaralian decided to play it safe. ``In the second half, their
big plays came when we blitzed. We had a couple of guys they were
working on, and we couldn't cover it up. They wanted to go after
them. We wanted to protect them. We couldn't cover the crossing
pattern. Terry Glenn had our guys backing off and when they did, he
cut across the middle. We weren't jumping on him the way we should
have when we're blitzing. Our guys backed up, and he took off
across the middle and made big plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn had four catches for 105 yards, a 26-yard average. So
Yaralian decided to drop into zones. Bledsoe adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that kind of game,'' said Yaralian. ``We did something
on defense. They would adjust. Then we would do something else,
they would adjust. I bet we blitzed them 30 times in the game. When
we got to him, we made the big play. When we didn't, they made the
big play.''
</P>
<P>
   On the last drive, Bledsoe took control. He looked away from
Glenn, who was double-covered. In just 38 seconds, he completed
four passes, two to Troy Brown for 9 and 16, then to Ben Coates for
10, then Vincent Brisby for 27.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coates can kill you,'' said Walt Corey, the former Bills
defensive coordinator, now with the Saints. ``He's so big, and you
know Bledsoe is looking for him, and we still couldn't stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   The catch was Coates's seventh of the day. During the week,
after looking at film of the Patriots' games, the Saints protested
that the officials were letting Coates get away with murder,
pushing off the defenders before making his break to the ball.
Nothing happened to change it. Coates still pushed off and made the
big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Coates catch left New England at the New Orleans 45,
not yet in range for kicker Adam Vinatieri. Yaralian pondered
blitzing, but decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went with a cover-two zone,'' Yaralian said. ``Our guys
just played it wrong.'' He said Bledsoe's completion to Brisby to
the Saints' 18 never should have happened. ``We had two guys there,
and neither one of them played it right. But those things happen.
We made some good plays, we just didn't make enough of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you blitz the way we do,'' said Saints general manager
Bill Kuharich, ``you are living and dying by the sword.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints do not have the players to match the Patriots
straight up. They had to try to win with gimmicks and hustle. They
came close.
</P>
<P>
   New England won this game on defense. Henry Thomas ran back an
interception for a touchdown. The Patriots sacked Danny Wuerffel
seven times, and knocked him down at least 20 times. They held the
Saints to 39 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   However, they should not be happy about the way the pass defense
played. Andre Hastings chewed up Chris Canty. No one could cover
Saints rookie tight end Cam Cleeland, who had eight catches for 64
yards. It was clear that when he needed a play, Wuerffel was going
to look for Cleeland, much like Bledsoe looks for Coates.
</P>
<P>
   At least, the Saints had some excuse for getting beat up a
little on defense. Tom Tupa's punting and the Patriots return game
kept New Orleans on its heels.
</P>
<P>
   But Wuerffel led scoring drives of 80 and 75 yards, almost all
through the air, and the Patriots had better be concerned about the
future because they are going to face a lot better passers than
Danny Wuerffel. But perhaps none more courageous.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
