<SLUG> BC-FBN-SAINTS-HASTINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASTINGS NOT QUITE GOOD ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ He had a sensational day. Six catches for 73 yards
and a punt return for another 76 yards that almost went down as one
of the greatest plays in National Football League history.
</P>
<P>
   But when Sunday's game against the Patriots was over, the
Saints' Andre Hastings apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let my teammates down,'' said Hastings, ``I should have gone
all the way on that play. If I did, we would have won the game.
Look at it in here (the Saints' locker room). It's so quiet because
we lost. If I did better, we would have won. This would have been
different.''
</P>
<P>
   With just over two minutes to play in the game, the Patriots
were clinging to a 27-24 lead when punter Tom Tupa lofted a beauty
that bounced high at the goal line. First Tebucky Jones batted it,
then Larry Whigham, who had a great day on special teams for New
England, leaped high, gliding a foot above the goal line, and
flipped the ball back over his shoulder, trying to stop it on the
1.
</P>
<P>
   The ball landed, bounced off a Saints player, and rolled into
the end zone. No whistle. The Saints' Earl Little picked up the
ball, dropped to one knee, and cltuched the ball to his stomach. No
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Hastings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a thing called the `first touch' rule that Bobby
April taught us when I was in Pittsburgh,'' Hastings said. April
was the special teams coach of the Steelers when Hastings was in
Pittsburgh. They're both with the Saints now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first touch rule is that if a player on the punting team
touches the punt first, then a player on the receiving team can do
anything he wants, and not have to worry, as long as the whistle
has not blown. They (the Patriots) touched it first. The whistle
did not blow. I said to Earl, `Give me the ball, give me the ball.'
I got it from him and started back.''
</P>
<P>
   While Patriot players were jumping around congratulating each
other, thinking they had pinned the Saints on their own 1-yard
line, Hastings knew better.
</P>
<P>
   He started racing along the Saints sideline, picking up blockers
along the way. A touchdown would have put the Saints ahead and on
the verge of an astonishing upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had it ,'' said Hastings, ``I had just one man
left to beat (punter Tom Tupa). I had the choice _ to go inside and
cut back to the middle, or stay outside. I thought I had him beat
to the outside, but he pushed me and I couldn't stay inbounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saints had to settle for a field goal, tying it at 27, and
the Patriots came back with a field goal with three seconds left to
win, 30-27.
</P>
<P>
   But Hastings had no reason to feel bad, other than his team's
loss. He was terrific.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at Mike Ditka's postgame press conference, the coach's
first positive comment came without a question asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre Hastings made some plays out there today that I hadn't
seen before,'' Ditka said. ``He made some catches that defied
logic.''
</P>
<P>
   The punt return is one of the most unusual in the books. But in
this town of voodoo and black magic, crazy things can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a game here when I was with the Saints,'' said Patriots
receivers coach Steve Walters, ``where a guy from the Rams did
something similar and it went for a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Robert Bailey, taking it 103 yards for a score.
Fortunately for the Patriots, they avoided a repeat. Hastings, with
a choice to make, left or right, went right, which proved to be
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tupa had a fantastic game for them,'' said April. ``His punts
were great, and then at the end, he made that play that saved the
touchdown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
