<HEADLINE>
JETS GO WITH PAT HAND TO DOWN DOLPHINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Bill Parcells seemed almost happy late
Sunday afternoon. Not overjoyed, definitely not satisfied. But
happy, or at least not too angry.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells's New York Jets had taken a 20-9 victory over Miami,
thanks to former Patriots Keith Byars and Curtis Martin, and
rejuvenated quarterback Vinny Testaverde. The win gave the Jets a
2-2 record and dropped Miami to 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are kind of starting over,'' Parcells said. ``The defense
made a couple of plays that helped and the offense was good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we do some awful dumb things. Some of these players that
continue to do them, they're going to have to change their ways or
I am not going to be playing them anymore, because it's about to
cost us. We got away with a few things, exercising poor judgments,
mistakes. Veteran players are making them. Not a lot. But four or
five things that, had they not done them, could have made it a lot
easier for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells will not likely follow through on those threats. But he
will use one of Martin's few mistakes for motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many carries he had, I don't know anything,''
Parcells said. ``But he ran out of bounds to stop the clock on his
30th carry, and that wasn't too smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that carry was a 13-yard pass reception on the first
play of the Jets' final possession. Testaverde's right arm was
about to be yanked out of its socket, so he flipped a lefthanded
shovel pass to Martin. Testaverde then tossed a 17-yard completion
to Byars, who set a league record for career receptions by a
running back, as the Jets maintained possession.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde's poise and resourcefulness were welcomed by
Parcells, but he was not so content by the controversy that is
brewing about his starting quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did enough to win the game,'' Parcells said. ``It wasn't
real pretty. We were going to try not to turn it into a passing
game, if we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Testaverde would start next week at St. Louis, Parcells
said, ``I didn't say that. The only persons asking those questions
are you people and my answer is the same. I'm not going to answer
'em anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Testaverde, ``I just want to keep playing well and,
whatever his decision, I'm confident in my abilities. I'll go with
whatever he decides, so it's a win-win situation.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, it has been a lose-win situation. Glenn Foley
started the opening games, but was injured and replaced by
Testaverde for the 44-6 win over Indianapolis two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not to be a game to showcase quarterbacks. Dan
Marino was held to 121 yards passing, and Testaverde had a slow
start, especially before Miami defensive end Jason Taylor injured
his left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were unthreatening offensively as they fell behind to
an Olindo Mare field goal in the final seconds of the first
quarter. But on Mare's kickoff, they capitalized on a
blocking-below-the-waist penalty on Bernie Parmalee to take
possession on the Miami 45.
</P>
<P>
   Ten plays later, Testaverde threw a 10-yard touchdown pass to
Keyshawn Johnson, and the Jets gained momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, their offense continued to struggle, but their defense
turned into a steamroller: Miami's offense produced minus-7 yards
on its last two possessions of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Jets' last two possessions of the half produced
six plays that gained yardage, and Testaverde surrendered a fumble
to Shane Burton. But the Jets gained 22 yards on a face mask
penalty and 28 on a pass interference call, setting up a 47-yard
field goal by John Hall for a 10-3 halftime edge.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's next three possessions produced another minus-10 yards
on nine plays. And Testaverde threw a 16-yard completion to Byars
on fourth and 1 to the Miami 7, setting up a 6-yard scoring run by
Martin for a 17-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Byars had six catches for 71 yards and moved past Marcus Allen
on the career list for running backs with 593 receptions.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jets' slipups, Parcells noted that some players had
donned inappropriate footwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not responsible for dressing them,'' Parcells said. ``We
are not talented enough to just show up and play, and if we don't
understand that we'll lose, and I don't know how it's going to go.
We're 2-2. A lot of teams are 2-2.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
