<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES PUT ON BRAVE FACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Streams of unconsciousness while wondering if Kevin Brown can
pitch on no days rest versus the Braves:
</P>
<P>
   It may take that kind of Herculean effort for the Padres to beat
the Braves in the National League Championship Series. The Braves
are the most methodical team in baseball since the old
DiMaggio-to-Mantle era Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the Braves' only concern is having too many
starters. In beating the Cubs in three straight, the firm of
Smoltz, Glavine and Maddox allowed all of 15 hits. Bobby Cox never
had to ponder whether he should start a Kevin Millwood or Denny
Neagle in Game 4 of the Cubs series.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bochy got two great efforts from Brown, one shaky start
from Andy Ashby, and an unexpected dominating performance by
Sterling Hitchcock on Sunday evening. I'm guessing the Astros won't
rush to see the remake of Alfred Hitchcock's ``Psycho'' this week.
</P>
<P>
   It may be difficult for Bochy to finesse his pitching staff
around the Braves. But before lurching towards Atlanta, Bochy
deserves to be acknowledged for taking a daring risk in moving
Brown's start up.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, it looked like a bad decision. Tied 1-1, most
managers would have been confident they could at least split two
games at home, and then play a deciding fifth game with their best
pitcher on the mound. If the Padres had lost Game 3 Saturday, Bochy
would have been torched.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they won, and Houston came out in Game 4 feeling the
pressure of the situation. Randy Johnson did what was expected, but
the nerves of his teammates showed, in the field and at the plate.
Bochy probably clinched the manager of the year award this weekend,
assuming all of the ballots haven't been mailed. ...
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bochy should pray for precipitation. A couple of
well-timed rainouts could allow him to use a three-man rotation and
spot the gritty, nasty Brown for as many as three starts.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1962 World Series, rainouts allowed the Yankees to start
Whitey Ford and Ralph Terry three times each in a seven-game series
with the Giants. And the Yankees won the series in seven. ...
</P>
<P>
   The American League series could be intriguing, or it could be
boring. The Indians have proved feisty since their return to
prominence, and there's enough bad blood between the Indians and
Yankees to bring out the best in both teams.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Yankees could sweep the Indians in four if their
pitching is as dominant on the field as it is on paper. The Yankees
will use a four-man rotation of David Wells, David Cone, Andy
Pettitte and Orlando Hernandez, have a fifth starter in Hideki
Irabu if one is needed, can rely on a deep set-up cast, and boast
of Mariano Rivera as their closer.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians' starters -- Jaret Wright, Dwight Gooden, Charles
Nagy and Batolo Colon -- do not match up, and neither does the
Indian bullpen. Lefties Wells and Pettitte should nullify the bat
of Jim Thome, the most dangerous stick in the Indians lineup. ...
</P>
<P>
   It would have been nice to see the Cubs and Red Sox go a round
further than they did, but their exits do not diminish their
seasons. It was nice for a few days to even dream about such a
World Series matchup. ...
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Angels should be glad they didn't catch Texas in the
A.L. West, considering how easily the Yankees dispatched the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   One has to wonder if Disney Sports wouldn't agree. The bottom
line-oriented company can look back at the 2.5 million attendance
in 1998 with some satisfaction, and will be counting their revenue
from the pricey new concessions into Christmas. From their
perspective, 1998 was a fine success.
</P>
<P>
   A division title would only have delivered one or two more
playoff games and would have heightened fan expectations to do it
again. Disney always seems more content polishing the bottom line
than winning. ...
</P>
<P>
   Now might be a good time to remind people that the Angels, who
used a platoon of Phil Nevin and Matt Walbeck behind the plate this
season, traded for an injured catcher in Charlie O'Brien, and
started Chad Kreuter in key September games, couldn't find a place
on their team for Padres' series star Jim Leyritz.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, who was traded for Ken Hill in late '97, has been with
five teams in the last three years. It's only fair to also note
that he was never more than a platoon player during his Yankee
years, and that the Yankees didn't keep him even after he had a big
home run enroute to their 1996 World Series title. ...
</P>
<P>
   The offseason should be as interesting for the Dodgers as the
last regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Dodger General Manager Kevin Malone wants to have a manager in
hand by the end of this week. The guy he wants is Montreal's Felipe
Alou. The fact Malone knows his work from their days together in
Montreal is a key factor. If for some reason Alou does not come
west, Malone should seriously consider Davey Lopes, and not just
because he's a former Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   Lopes has interned as a coach now for a decade and is widely
respected by players wherever he has worked. He speaks his mind and
demands a lot. Steve Garvey may have been the star of the Dodgers'
infield for those nine years between 1973 and 1981, but Lopes was
the soul of the quartet. ...
</P>
<P>
   Once a manager is in hand, Malone will seek to resolve the Jeff
Shaw situation and launch a search for a No. 1 starter. Those two
items could be linked. If Shaw is determined to get out of L.A.,
Malone would likely seek a starting pitcher in a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Malone will undoubtedly take a swing at the top two free agent
pitchers, Randy Johnson and Kevin Brown, but both are likely to
sign with their current teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins reportedly have inquired about reobtaining Charles
Johnson, who is arbitration eligible. The Dodgers might consider a
deal, but only if they believe there is a chance of re-entering the
Mike Piazza sweepstakes. And while the Marlins sucked this season,
their minor league pool of talent is considered the best around.
</P>
<P>
   Malone also needs to find a center fielder, because Raul Mondesi
wants to return to right field, which would then move Gary
Sheffield to left. Two potential local angles would be obtaining
ex-Fullerton star Mark Kotsay from the Marlins or the Angels' Jim
Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers may lack a No. 1 pitcher, but they're confident Chan
Ho Park, Darren Driefort, and Carlos Perez are an acceptable 2-3-4.
The Angels need a starting pitcher, and the Dodgers potentially
could offer Ismail Valdes, who is not considered untouchable, Dave
Mlicki or Brian Bohanon. ...
</P>
<P>
   Braves in seven, Yankees in six. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
