r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RATING-LADN     10-05 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RATING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH OFFICIALS CONSIDER LOWER GRADE FOR THE TRULY AWFUL EATERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MELISSA SCHMITT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- John and Julie Burns love to dine out, and they
try to stay away from restaurants that receive a health inspection
grade of less than a B.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as they prepared to enter a sushi bar recently, the Burnses
were confused because the San Fernando Valley restaurant displayed
a card with a number: 58.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does a 58 mean?'' asked Julie Burns, 25.
</P>
<P>
   It meant that the restaurant had no paper towels or hand soap in
the employees' bathroom, filthy cutting boards, live and dead
cockroaches in the kitchen area, and pots and pans that were not
sanitized, to name a few problems.
</P>
<P>
   It also meant that like 265 other restaurants across the city,
it didn't score high enough to get the lowest letter grade: a C.
</P>
<P>
   Under a proposal by Los Angeles County Supervisor Michael D.
Antonovich, those restaurants would be tagged with D's _ for dirty
_ and closed. The board is expected to consider the measure Oct.
13.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer is looking for the letter grade,'' Antonovich
said in announcing his proposal. ``Any restaurant receiving less
than 70 percent has had an easy out under the current ordinance.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Burnses, the measure seems common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't have a grade high enough for a letter, shouldn't
they be shut down?'' Julie Burns asked.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Antonovich's proposal, let alone the entire
letter-inspection program, is necessary remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The number of food-related illnesses reported in the county does
not appear to be on the decline since the program began, said Mike
Spear, director of Environmental Services for the county. ``We
haven't seen anything to reflect that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, restaurants are performing much better on inspection
reports than they did in the beginning. Of the 6,975 facilities
inspected to date, 4,252 received A's, 1,907 received B's and 545
received a grade of C.
</P>
<P>
   County officials said they did not know how much the inspection
program cost, but they say it has been widely popular.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Matthew Kreis, 24, Travis Howard, 26, and Austin Hanks,
28. If the restaurant doesn't make the grade, they said, then it's
not making their dinner either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the food here so much, I don't even think about that A
in the window,'' said Howard while dining at Angel Lena's Soul Food
Kitchen in Sherman Oaks. But Howard said his loyalty, despite the
rice and beans, and those smothered pork chops, is only A _ maybe B
_ deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were a C in the window, it would make a difference,''
Howard said, and Angel Lena's wouldn't be selling him any sweet
potato pie until they made the grade again.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, said Kreis, ``I'd eat in a restaurant that was a C place
if it was the only place around, and I was starving to death.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Valley sushi bar, the problems were so severe
that a C was too good.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means there were many violations,'' said health inspector
Mark Como, who is not one of the inspectors who visited the sushi
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors closed the restaurant for 48 hours for the presence
of cockroaches. The owners attended a hearing, submitted to a
reinspection and were allowed to reopen.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants are only allowed to be re-examined once each year,
at a cost of $161 for a second inspection. That inspection would be
done within 10 days. If the restaurant then passed, a third
surprise inspection would be performed within three months.
</P>
<P>
   All restaurants start with a grade of 100, with points
subtracted for each infraction. There are 44 categories, with items
weighted by importance, Como said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, serving spoiled food would cost 3 points.
Employees not washing their hands before serving would cost 4
points. Reserving food to a customer that was previously served to
another, or using it in food preparation, like salsa for instance,
costs 5 points.
</P>
<P>
   There is no set numerical grade at which a restaurant shuts
down, Como said, adding that any one of five items will close a
restaurant on the spot. They include the presence of rats,
cockroaches or sewage or a lack of hot water.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants are supposed to keep their inspection reports on
hand, readily available for customers to view.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way, they can make the judgment for themselves whether
it's safe to eat in a C or lesser place,'' Spear said. ``Customers
can look at the nature of what was marked off. But if it wasn't
safe, it would more than likely have been closed.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Valley sushi bar, the bottom line is that
standard rules of cleanliness were not being observed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not cleaning. Food is being kept at the wrong
temperature. There are problems with the equipment,'' Spear said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to remember that all inspections are a
snapshot,'' Spear said. ``Things can change on the day we're not
there. Even for the A place.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Shabbouei, owner of California Pita and Grill in Woodland
Hills, is a supporter of the program and believes Antonovich's
proposal will only improve restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Shabbouei displays an A in his window and recently got licensed
as a certified food handler through the health department.
</P>
<P>
   His restaurant never has had a problem with cockroaches, but
Shabbouei said he can understand how it could happen. And the rules
are too strict, he said.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is for one box of produce to come into the
restaurant with a roach. ``That's it. You're shut down. And that
would kill my business. It really would. It would kill me,''
Shabbouei said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
