<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER TIED A BOW ON `GIFT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - The clock read :01.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it,'' Marc Trestman said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Cardinals coaches said they did, too. They were on the
field pleading their case, index fingers pointed to the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Metcalf, ball in hand, had just stepped out of bounds at
the Oakland 36-yard line. The Cardinals thought one second
remained. Enough time to try to tie the score with a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It was over.
</P>
<P>
   To their disbelief, time had expired. Coach Vince Tobin's
calculated and questionable gamble had failed.
</P>
<P>
   As surprise gave way to rising anger _ ``The guy must have been
wearing silver and black,'' Jake Plummer said of the Sun Devil
Stadium timekeeper who didn't stop the clock _ the quarterback
turned from the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders were celebrating on his field.
</P>
<P>
   Jake closed his eyes and bit down hard on his mouthpiece.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the field (one official was hit by a water bottle
thrown by an angry fan), No. 16 suddenly broke into a sprint,
running as if trying to distance himself as quickly as possible
from his most frustrating, and perhaps disappointing, day as a
Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   The ``clock guy'' didn't cost Jake's team this game.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the decision not to let Joe Nedney try a 55-yard
field goal with five seconds left, although the play Jake ran
instead surprised him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of drew it up,'' Plummer said of the simple 2-yard
sideline pass to Metcalf. You mean, it wasn't in the game plan? You
hadn't run it earlier? ``We've never run it before.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake knew who was mostly responsible for the Cardinals' 23-20
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   He was.
</P>
<P>
   He called his performance ``terrible'' _ two thumbs down. While
he accepted gentle words of support and encouragement from his
teammates, he characterized the back pats as ``b.s.'' Bogus
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   His toughest critic, Plummer said, ``I didn't give us a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals could have won _ perhaps should have won _ but
three interceptions sealed their fate.
</P>
<P>
   The home team led, 14-9, in the second quarter when Plummer
floated a pass in the flat to Adrian Murrell. Plummer never saw
cornerback Charles Woodson hiding in the weeds. Woodson picked off
Plummer's pass and ran 46 yards. There was nothing between him and
the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, Raiders corner Marquis Walker stole another
Plummer pass and ran to the Cardinals' 4, where the Raiders scored
again. Oakland, 23-14.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders tried to let the home team come back in the third
quarter, fumbling on their own 16. But Plummer immediately
delivered another pass he wished he could have retrieved the second
the ball left his hand. Larry Centers was open, but the pass was
underthrown. Eric Allen intercepted in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer described his mistakes as if he had carefully placed
each in a box, with tissue paper, and tied the package with a
colorful bow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gift-wrapped them,'' he said of his interceptions, ``and
handed them out.'' He called the last one a ``nice, shiny, silver
gift.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone deserved a gift, it was the Cardinals defense. Led by
Simeon Rice, the defense played its best game of the season and put
the home team in position to win its third game in a row. Can
anyone remember the last time the Cardinals were 3-2?
</P>
<P>
   The table was set. A big crowd. A beatable opponent whose
starting quarterback left the game because of an injury. If the
Cardinals had won, it would have been a rebirth of sorts, a turning
point in the season even more exciting than the hatching of a giant
egg at halftime. Out popped the team's new mascot, a person wearing
a red bird suit.
</P>
<P>
   Like the quarterback, the mascot is a work in progress. He
doesn't even have a name.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals start winning games they should, especially at
home, I'm for calling the bird Jake.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, if this team can't find a running game and the
quarterback keeps throwing touchdowns to the wrong team, my vote in
the name-the-mascot contest is Shredded Tweet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
