<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9175 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CARDS-RAIDERS-AZR     10-05 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CARDS-RAIDERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS CAN'T KICK  
 TIME RUNS OUT (MAYBE) ON TYING FIELD GOAL TRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Was there one second left, or wasn't there?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as if the Cardinals had played a magnificent, flawless
game, only to be robbed by a slow-fingered timekeeper on the
closing play of a 23-20 loss to the Oakland Raiders at Sun Devil
Stadium on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But it put a groan-inducing question mark on a performance that
proved that despite the giddiness of two straight wins, the young
Cardinals (2-3) have not yet arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin tried to give kicker Joe Nedney an opportunity
to send the game into overtime, but in the process, he took the
chance away altogether. With the ball at the Raiders 37-yard line
and 5 seconds remaining, Tobin first sent the field-goal team onto
the field. It would have been a 55-yarder, well beyond Nedney's
career best of 47.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after the Raiders (3-2) burned their final timeout, Tobin
sent the offense back out in the hope of completing a quick out and
knocking three or four yards off a field-goal try. There was little
time for error, and the coach might have miscalculated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be capable of completing a quick out in less than
five seconds,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer, who rallied after putting his team in a big hole
early, completed the pass to Eric Metcalf, who stepped out of
bounds at the Raiders 35, a gain of 2.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bang-bang play. The field-goal try would be 53 yards.
Or so the Cardinals thought.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard clock, however, was full of zeroes, and the
officiating crew didn't dispute it. Thus ended the Cardinals brief
tenure as co-leaders of the NFC East. They fell a game behind the
Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked to me like there was one second left on the clock,''
Tobin said. ``But we didn't get the chance to kick the field goal,
and that is a disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   Referee Johnny Grier said he asked line judge Gary Arthur, who
is responsible for the time, if the game clock was correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said there was no time left, and I went with that,'' Grier
said.
</P>
<P>
   There would have been a slight breeze facing Nedney, just enough
to riffle the streamers atop the uprights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd made it, it would have been an unbelievable play,''
Nedney said.
</P>
<P>
   But the game boiled down to those controversial closing seconds
only because the Cardinals' offense and special teams had made the
kind of plays that players don't live for. Four critical plays _
three of them interceptions by Plummer _ accounted for a 24-point
swing for Oakland after the Cardinals held a 14-6 lead in the the
second quarter:
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf fumbled away a punt, setting up a field goal by former
Cardinals kicker Greg Davis, who was thanked for the memories with
loud boos as he connected from 34 yards (after also converting from
51 and 40) to pull the Raiders within 14-9.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer didn't see Raiders rookie corner Charles Woodson as he
tried to hit Adrian Murrell in the right flat. Woodson picked it
off and took it back 46 yards for a touchdown. Suddenly, the
Cardinals were down, 16-14.
</P>
<P>
   On the very next series, Plummer was about to be swept under
another wave of blitzing Raiders. Hit as he threw, the pass was
intercepted by Marquis Walker and returned to the Cardinals 4-yard
line. That set up a touchdown scramble by Donald Hollas, a backup
quarterback who was forced to play after Jeff George was knocked
out early by a groin strain. Just like that, the Cards were down
23-14.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the third quarter, the Cardinals defense gave Plummer
another chance. Linebacker Jamir Miller forced Hollas to fumble and
linebacker Ron McKinnon recovered at the Oakland 16. On the first
snap, Larry Centers was open in the end zone, but Plummer
underthrew him. The ball was intercepted by cornerback Eric Allen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was gift-wrapping them and handing them out today,'' Plummer
said. ``They really didn't beat us, we beat ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   When Plummer's rough day was combined with a Cardinals' ground
game that covered only 49 yards, it nullified a defensive effort
that limited Oakland to 222 total yards and forced three turnovers
and proved that the Cardinals still have plenty of room for growth
before they're playoff contenders. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
