<HEADLINE>
MORE LEGAL FINAGLING FOR TYSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The &UR; Mike Tyson psychodrama might be headed for a
Nevada courtroom as early as today in a legal attempt to block
public disclosure of a psychiatric evaluation he underwent in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter last week to the Nevada Athletic Commission, Tyson's
latest psychiatrist,  &UR; Dr. Ronald  &UR; Schouten, that a public reading
was ``unnecessary'' and ``contrary to his best clinical
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: There's a lot of embarrassing stuff in the lengthy
evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, doesn't rank as a shock. The worst is always
expected of Tyson. He even expects it of himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to believe anything in the psychological report could
be more negative on Tyson than his own words are in a current
``Playboy'' interview.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's battalion of lawyers should have tried to ban the
magazine before it went to work on the psychological evaluation. By
now, what can the shrinks tell us that we don't know already?
</P>
<P>
   Another licensing hearing has been scheduled in Las Vegas for
Oct. 19. But all the legal briefs and bluffs make that date look
unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens in Nevada, the best guess is Tyson will fight
someone, somewhere, somehow before the end of the year. For one
thing, he has to pay all those lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Before he even gets around to his Clinton-sized legal bill,
however, Tyson has a more pressing matter with the Internal Revenue
Service. His reported tax debt is $13 million. Further reports
indicate the IRS will seize his multimillion-dollar homes in Las
Vegas and Connecticut if he doesn't pay up by Dec. 31. &QL; 
Briefly . . . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it sounds as if ringside commentators have been taking
all the punches. &UR; Evander Holyfield has been written off as a shot
fighter by many after his sluggish victory over  &UR; Vaughn Bean. How
soon they forget. The same thing was said of Holyfield after a poor
performance in a victory over  &UR; Bobby
 &UR; Czyz. Holyfield went on to upset Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix junior-welterweight  &UR; Ahmed Santos of  &UR; Michael
 &UR; Carbajal's Ninth Street Gym is scheduled for an ESPN2 date against
Las Vegas'
 &UR; James Crayton on Oct. 16 at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   There's still no word on Carbajal's opponent for a projected
comeback later this month at Biloxi, Miss. Promoter &UR; Russell Peltz
wanted Carbajal, once the world's best at 108 pounds, to challenge
for the North American Boxing Federation's 112-pound title in his
first bout in more than a year. But first, trainer and manager
 &UR; Danny Carbajal wants to see how his brother looks in a tuneup.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona State Boxing Commission was uncomfortable with last
Wednesday's cage fight card at Club Rio. But the show went on
anyway because fighters were classified as amateurs by promoter
 &UR; Scott Maling, a longtime matchmaker for Commission-regulated pro
cards. A similar show at Celebrity Theatre was canceled in January
after pre-fight publicity attracted the attention of Sen.  &UR; John
McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley's next commission-regulated, uncaged card is
scheduled for Oct. 13 at Midnight Rodeo, a nightspot at 33rd Avenue
and Indian School Road. Six bouts are scheduled by &UR; Willy Borchert,
a longtime Phoenix trainer who entered the promotional wars in
large part because he wanted to give local kids a chance to fight
in front of a hometown crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Pay-per-view television operators report that &UR; Oscar De La
 &UR; Hoya's victory last month over &UR; Julio Cesar  &UR; Chavez generated
between 650,000 and 700,000 customers. Meanwhile, De La Hoya,
already back at work for a Nov. 21 bout with Ghana's  &UR; Ike  &UR; Quartey,
continues to criticize Chavez for not going beyond the sensational
eighth round. ``I would never, ever do that,'' De La Hoya said.
``Even with a broken nose, with both eyes completely shut, I'd
never quit.'' &QL; 
Information from other media sources is included. Norm Frauenheim
can be reached at 602-444-8259 or norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
