<HEADLINE>
KINGS ROOKIES ON THE BUBBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKERSFIELD, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Kings completed the
exhibition schedule Sunday night and the 24-man regular-season
roster appears close to completion as well.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a last-minute trade, the loss of a player or two in
today's NHL waiver draft or the signing this week of free-agent
defenseman Aki Berg, the Kings look to be set in goal and on
defense, with only a couple of question marks at the forward
positions.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question appears to be whether either of rookies
Josh Green and Olli Jokinen _ or both _ will make the roster that
will travel to Edmonton to start the season Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Following a 4-3 win over the Vancouver Canucks before a crowd of
6,660 at Centennial Garden arena, coach Larry Robinson said much
will hinge on the waiver draft. He also said he wants to be
cautious with his team's top prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the season progresses, kids have ups and downs,'' Robinson
said. ``If you can be patient, it makes sense to keep them around.
It doesn't make sense if they're going to play a couple of games,
then sit a couple.''
</P>
<P>
   Green scored the game-winner Sunday, completing a strong
exhibition season. Jokinen, originally not scheduled to play, had
one of his stronger performances, as well.
</P>
<P>
   As for Berg, who is playing in his native Finland, the Kings
must sign him by Friday or lose his services for the season.
General manager Dave Taylor said he isn't optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   In the game, the Kings (6-2-1 in exhibitions) got goals from
Philippe Boucher, Jozef Stumpel, Luc Robitaille and Green to beat
the Canucks (4-3-1).
</P>
<P>
   __ Feeling a draft: Seven Kings, including minor-league goalies
Manny Legace of the Long Beach Ice Dogs and Frederic Chabot, will
be exposed in today's NHL waiver draft. Also exposed are center Ray
Ferraro, forwards Nathan LaFayette and Dan Bylsma, and defensemen
Jaroslav Modry and Mark Visheau.
</P>
<P>
   Visheau, who injured his left thumb in a fight with Stu Grimson
of the Mighty Ducks one week ago, is scheduled to undergo surgery
Tuesday and is expected to miss 7-10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With Visheau out and Rob Blake sidelined by a hip-flexor strain
that the Kings say is mild, the team recalled defenseman Jan
Nemecek from the Ice Dogs. Nemecek, who had two assists, was
expected to be returned to the Ice Dogs after Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bure watch: Canucks general manager Brian Burke on holdout
forward Pavel Bure, who wants out of Vancouver: ``I told the media
the first day of training camp that the next time I talk about
Pavel Bure is to tell you where he's going. I didn't want it to be
a distraction to the team and it hasn't been. If I don't get the
right deal, I've said publicly that he's going to sit the whole
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 0119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9181 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-DEFENSE-AZR     10-05 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-DEFENSE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WANTED: HELP FOR DEFENSE  
 OFFENSE ACCEPTING BLAME FOR THE LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD   
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Outside linebacker Jamir Miller, always honest
and candid, wasn't angry, just frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't blaming the Cardinals' offense for the 23-20 loss to
the Oakland Raiders Sunday, but he also thinks it has to give the
defense more assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't take that many snaps every game,'' Miller said of the
Cardinals' defense, which was on the field for 69 plays, second
most this season. ``It's ridiculous. We need help.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders scored 17 of their points following three Cardinals'
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' defense, meanwhile, gave up only one touchdown,
and that was on a drive that started on their 4-yard line after an
interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't give the game away,'' said Miller, who had 12 tackles
and a sack. ``We can't play like that. Our defense is good enough.
Once we get a lead, we can dominate. But when you give up a lead,
it's hard to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals led, 14-6, before committing four turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   How good was the Cardinals' defense?
</P>
<P>
   They held running back Napoleon Kaufman, the AFC's third-leading
rusher, to 58 yards, 32 below his average.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Tim Brown made only two catches for 13 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks Jeff George, who was knocked out of the game late
in the first quarter because of a groin injury, and his
replacement, Donald Hollas, combined to throw for only 120 yards,
115 below the team average. They were sacked three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense played awesome today,'' said Cardinals quarterback
Jake Plummer, who was intercepted three times, two leading to
Oakland scores and the other in the Raiders' end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamir Miller _ it looked like he was in on every tackle,''
Plummer said. ``The defensive backs played great. We (the offense)
just have to pick up our end of the bargain. We have to go out
there and put points on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals nickel back Kwamie Lassiter intercepted George on
Oakland's opening drive, helping Arizona to a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also recovered two Oakland fumbles, including one
with 1:52 left that gave the offense one last chance.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defensive end Andre Wadsworth sacked Hollas at the
Cardinals 30 and forced the fumble. Cornerback J.B. Brown, starting
for injured Tommy Knight, recovered at the 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came off the back side wide open,'' said Wadsworth, who has
four sacks in the past two games to tie Green Bay's Vonnie Holliday
for the most by an NFL rookie.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals couldn't move the ball closer than the Raiders
38 as time ran out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave our offense the ball back and in a position for them
to get where they needed to get, but they couldn't get there,''
Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   But the defense had allowed the Raiders to run off more than six
minutes before forcing the turnover. Twice the Raiders converted
third downs, including a third-and-13 from the Oakland 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to find a way to get the ball back for our offense a
lot sooner,'' cornerback Aeneas Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Center Aaron Graham exonerated the defense from any blame for
allowing the Raiders to control the clock for much of the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``All day, the defense stepped up and made plays,'' Graham said.
``They gave us great field position. We were just not able to
capitalize. If you get that kind of field position, you have to get
six points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take away the interceptions, we win by 14 points. This was
just a lost opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
