<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO EXCUSE FOR TOBIN'S LACK OF FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - If your kicker has the leg, the decision is
simple.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nedney has the leg.
</P>
<P>
   What he doesn't have is the confidence of his head coach, whose
tactical blunders may have cost the Cardinals a victory on a
pivotal Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   You can blame the timekeeper. You can blame the referees. Or you
can blame the man hugging the clipboard.
</P>
<P>
   And as much as Vince Tobin tried to stand by his sideline logic
in the waning moments of a sickening loss to the Raiders, it is
simply indefensible.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the pregame,'' Nedney said, ``we were swinging from 58
yards and getting it there.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why you kick the football. You don't risk some yahoo
failing to turn off the clock in time. You don't risk the
officiating crew having to sort through the chaos and order time
back on the clock while one team is running off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Not with five seconds left. Not in a game that could've served
as a trampoline for the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``What my reasoning was, it was a 56-, 57-yard field goal
against the wind,'' Tobin said. ``I felt we could get another
three, four yards on a quick out and get out of bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, the kick was 55 yards. The wind was really a breeze, the
kind that wouldn't ruffle a bad toupee. And if Nedney hits the ball
square, another three, four yards isn't going to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, he's a guy who hits for distance, even if his radar
gets a little quirky.
</P>
<P>
   So Nedney is 0 for 5 beyond 50 yards in his career. He didn't
miss on Sunday. And in that scenario, you have to give him his
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is I was in the middle of the field, getting
focused for the kick, then I had to run right off,'' Nedney said.
``People will tell you it's a long shot, a low-percentage kick. But
those are the ones that separate you from other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would've had to hit it perfect. But I would've given it a
ride. I'd have given it the best shot I could. That's what I live
for.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Davis, the opposing kicker, was asked what the odds where
of Nedney nailing the kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forty percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Good enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   And good enough for Tobin, until the Raiders called a timeout.
Which gave the coach too much time to ponder how little he trusts
his kicker.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of faith was evident in the second quarter. The
Cardinals reached the Oakland 35 with the ``wind'' at their back.
On fourth down, Tobin sent his punter onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were ahead at that time, and they weren't doing anything on
offense against us,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Again, precisely the reason to kick. A chance to extend the lead
to 17-9. A chance to see how locked in Nedney really was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little disappointed,'' Nedney said. ``That would've
been a good shot for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this wasn't all about coaching. Simeon Rice jumped
offsides on a third-down stop by the Cardinals, eventually leading
to the Raiders' first field goal. Leading 14-6 with a chance to put
the game away, Eric Metcalf fumbled a punt return. And Jake Plummer
threw three of the most costly interceptions you'll ever see.
</P>
<P>
   All told, they were the kind of plays you expect from a team
still learning how to win. A team not that far from a legacy of
failure.
</P>
<P>
   But the sideline decisions were not the kind you expect from a
seasoned head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the final gripe: Who is Donald Hollas and why
didn't the Cardinals try to knock him into the next millennium from
the moment he entered the game? Why didn't they blitz everyone but
the new mascot in attempt to shake, rattle and roll a second-string
quarterback? Why did they allow him time to get comfortable, time
to work his way into the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that was a factor in the ballgame,'' Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Sure it was. And like it or not, so was Tobin. For the wrong
reasons. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
