<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS PIN HOPES TO IMPROVED DEFENSEMEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It took Darryl Sydor five years of NHL play to finally figure
something out: The game isn't that complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, but the more simple I make the game, the easier
it's become for me, and that's mostly happened since I've been with
the Stars,'' Sydor said. ``We have a real strong philosophy here
that you don't try to do more than you can do.''
</P>
<P>
   That creed has helped mold the Stars' defense into what is
arguably the finest in the NHL. The core group of six defensemen
mixes size, skill and experience, and the organization's depth
gives the Stars a group that will not be significantly hurt by one
or two injuries. But what holds them together is their belief in
one another and their belief that the simple play will usually be
the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt, that's something that I've been able to learn
through experience by having some great teachers here,''
25-year-old Richard Matvichuk said. ``I think calming down comes
with maturity and experience, but what we do here is we play a game
that's very disciplined, a game where you have to be positionally
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   And that goes for everyone. While the Stars love the offensive
creativity that Sergei Zubov brings to the ice, they also expect
Zubov to be defensively responsible. While the organization almost
demands that Matvichuk and captain Derian Hatcher dish out big
hits, it also requires that they don't create an opening by
venturing too far to deliver a check.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that each player can improve in every area,'' said
assistant coach Rick Wilson, the man responsible for assembling the
defense and for making defensive matchups during the game. ``We
demand a lot from the players, but we also know that they have a
lot to give.''
</P>
<P>
   And they might be able to give even more this season. With
Matvichuk (25), Hatcher (26), Sydor (26) and Zubov (28) all in the
prime of their careers, each is expected to be better this season
than he was last.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an honest expectation; we should be better,'' Hatcher
said. ``With our age and the fact we have all played together for
two or three years, there's no excuse not to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a scary thought. Hatcher is ranked eighth among NHL
defensemen by ``The Hockey News''. Zubov is ranked 11th and
finished second in the defensemen scoring race last season with 57
points (10 goals, 47 assists). Sydor was an All-Star Game selection
last season and ranks second in plus-minus among defensemen over
the previous two seasons (plus 54). Matvichuk is coming off his
best NHL year in which he led the NHL in blocked shots (142) and
was fourth in the NHL in hits (222).
</P>
<P>
   The two elder statesmen _ Craig Ludwig (37) and Shawn Chambers
(31) _ each boast a Stanley Cup championship in their past and are
the perfect complements to the top four. Ludwig is tough enough to
take the minutes of Hatcher or Matvichuk if need be, while Chambers
is skilled enough to take the place of Zubov or Sydor in the event
of injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt they're the best in the league; it's
obvious,'' Stars goalie Ed Belfour said of the group that helped
him forge a league-best 1.88 goals-against average. ``From top to
bottom, no other group can match them.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for that is the chemistry that coaches try so
hard to create, but often times has to create itself. Sydor is able
to play a simple game and stay away from the mistakes that haunted
him when he was a member of the Los Angeles Kings because he is
paired with Zubov.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just do what comes natural to me and let Zubie do the
rest,'' Sydor said. ``It just seems to work out well when we're out
there together.''
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk, meanwhile, is able to be one of the top hitters in
the league because he knows Hatcher is behind him backing him up.
While Hatcher's numbers aren't as impressive, his work helps make
Matvichuk a better defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   The third pair of Chambers and Ludwig is similar. Chambers can
use his offensive skills because he knows Ludwig always is there to
back him up. All in all, it's a package that is set up to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go down the line and we should be better as a group,''
Chambers said. ``We know each other pretty well now, the young guys
just keep getting better, we know Eddie better. You don't want to
get too far ahead of yourself, but the bottom line is there's a lot
of talent here.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that simple. FIVE BOUND FOR KALAMAZOO
</P>
<P>
   The Stars on Sunday sent five players to their minor-league
affiliate in Kalamazoo, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Sent down were defensemen Petr Buzek, Richard Jackman and Brad
Lukowich, center Greg Leeb and winger Mel Angelstad. The moves
trimmed the Stars' roster to 28, including injured Joe Nieuwendyk
and Aaron Gavey. The Stars' must have their healthy roster at 24
before the season opener Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
