<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR DEALS WITH SECOND SEEPAGE PROBLEM
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _For the second time this season, water seeping
onto a racetrack owned by Speedway Motorsports Inc. has played
havoc with a NASCAR Winston Cup event.
</P>
<P>
   A faulty sewage pump located off of track property sent water
streaming across the backstretch of Charlotte Motor Speedway on
Sunday, prompting NASCAR officials to throw a red flag and stop the
UAW-GM Quality 500 for 42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Track officials reported that a sewage pump located on U.S. 29,
just north of CMS, shut down early in the afternoon. The
malfunction caused an overflow from a manhole located in the East
Grandstand on the backstretch of the 1.5-mile trioval. Water
spilled over the outside retaining wall above the ``Charlotte''
sign and ran across the racing surface, which is banked at 5
degrees in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Championship contenders Mark Martin and Jeff Gordon were racing
at the head of the field when the water became noticeable down the
1,360-foot backstretch. After several drivers reported that the
water had nearly caused them to aqua-plane out of control, NASCAR
threw a caution followed by a red-flag on lap 94 of the scheduled
334.
</P>
<P>
   Early morning rains had threatened to delay the start of the
race, but it started only a few minutes after the originally
scheduled time of 12:05 p.m., CDT. But this water problem proved
not to be rain-related.
</P>
<P>
   During the delay, Geoff Bodine jokingly suggested that a broken
sewer was the source.
</P>
<P>
   ``I smelled a little odor when I went by,'' Bodine said.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance crews shut the system down and stopped the leak, and
also replaced the defective pump.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Winston Cup qualifying for the Texas 500 at Texas
Motor Speedway in Fort Worth was halted when water began seeping
out of Turn 1, causing several cars to spin and crash. The session
was postponed until the next morning. SMI chairman Bruton Smith
subsequently spent approximately $3 million to install a new
drainage system and reconfigure the 1.5-mile trioval.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you've seen everything until you see something like
that,'' Kenny Wallace said of the latest incident. ``Thank God that
water wasn't in the corner.'' BOBBY LABONTE TAKES BLAME
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the red flag, the race produced 11 pace-slowing
cautions, one under the event record set in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Native Texan Bobby Labonte triggered a grinding, 10-car crash
when he lost control and spun entering Turn 2 on lap 202. Labonte
slid backwards into the outside wall, and the resulting scramble
collected the cars of brother Terry Labonte, Ricky Rudd, teammates
Jeremy Mayfield and Rusty Wallace, Kyle Petty, teammates Dale
Earnhardt and Mike Skinner, Sterling Marlin and Kenny Irwin Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, who qualified third, was running second to Martin when
he hit the spin cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get under Mark in Turn 1,'' said Labonte,
driver of the No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac Grand Prix. ``It
really pushed bad (front end would not turn) when I got underneath
him. And then when I got free of him and turned left underneath him
a little bit, it took all the air off my nose and just spun out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't their fault. It was mine.''
</P>
<P>
   But Labonte, Rudd and race-winner Mark Martin were among those
who said there was oil dumped in Turn 1, apparently from a blown
motor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was oil everywhere,'' said Rudd, winner of last week's
event at Martinsville (Va.) Speedway in the No. 10 Tide Ford
Taurus. ``No one had any control. Everyone sailed off in there and
you really didn't know where you were gonna land after you got into
the corner.'' GORDON STREAK INTACT
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points leader Jeff Gordon was running as ``low'' as
eighth before a late-race charge moved him around Kevin Lepage for
a fifth-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   The pass on lap 331 of the 334 allowed Gordon to record his 15
consecutive top-five finish. Gordon made his charge despite a
damaged left rear quarter-panel that affect the downforce on the
No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Crew chief) Ray Evernham kept telling me I could get the 16
car (Lepage) for fifth place, and I was about ready to spin out as
it was,'' Gordon said. ``I think my car kept getting a little
better and his was going away pretty fast, so I was lucky to get by
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has posted an average finish of 2.06 over the last 15
races, and averaged 175.7 points during the period. NUTS AND BOLTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Burton's third-place finish in the No. 99 Exide Batteries
Ford was his seventh top-10 in the last eight races. He climbed
from seventh to fifth in the Cup standings, matching his best
position of the season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bobby Hamilton's fourth-place result in the No. 4 Kodak Chevy
was his third top-10 in the last four races, and allowed him to
move from 13th to 11th in Cup points.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rookie Kevin Lepage's sixth-place finish in the No. 16
Primestar Ford was his Winston Cup career-best, and second career
top-10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
