<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9201 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYSNOTES-TEX     10-05 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS COULD KEEP AIKMAN FROM RUSHING BACK
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS AND CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman might not
return next week after all.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who has missed the past three games with a fractured
collarbone, said two weeks ago that he had set Sunday's game
against the Carolina Panthers as his target for returning to the
lineup. However, after the Cowboys' 31-10 victory against the
Washington Redskins Sunday, he wasn't so certain.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman is scheduled to have X-rays taken on his shoulder Monday.
And while acknowledging the bone won't be healed for another two
weeks, he said it would be ``very optimistic'' for him to play
against the Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, who has been against Aikman's early
return all along, said Sunday's victory should influence the team
to rest him another week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this gives us an opportunity to not take a chance on
him,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys could rest Aikman three more weeks, considering
after the Panthers (0-4), the Cowboys face the Chicago Bears (1-4)
and then have a bye before meeting the Philadelphia Eagles (0-5).
 &LR; name _ Clarence E. Hill Jr. EVERETT OUT, KIESELAK IN
</P>
<P>
   Right guard Everett McIver is expected to miss the next three to
five weeks with a sprained medial collateral ligament in his right
knee.
</P>
<P>
   McIver was injured with 5 minutes, 20 seconds remaining in the
first quarter. His replacement was Mike Kiselak, a former Canadian
League star, and it was not long before he was tested. On Kiselak's
first play, he blocked Redskins tackle Dan ``Big Daddy'' Wilkinson,
clearing room for a 6-yard Emmitt Smith run. Kiselak also had a bad
play, allowing Wilkinson to escape his clutches for a sack of Jason
Garrett in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   How did Kiselak even get in a Cowboys uniform? Some fan from
East Texas kept sending the Cowboys tapes of Kiselak in the CFL,
scouting director Larry Lacewell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept saying, `You gotta look at this guy,' '' Lacewell
said. ``I blew it off. Finally, I got the film and decided to take
a look and I thought, `Hey, this guy can play.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The fan in East Texas thanks you, Larry. MILLS MAKES PLAYS
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Mills beat Redskins struggling cornerback Cris Dishman
twice for a game-high 72 yards Sunday. Mills' 29-yard reception set
up the Cowboys' field goal in the first quarter. And his 43-yard
reception in the second quarter gave the Cowboys a 17-7 lead. NEAR
TD FOR DEION
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders is making a strong case for
some kind of player of the year award _ defense, special teams. His
first-quarter interception set up Emmitt Smith's 3-yard touchdown
run in the second quarter. And he had a 71-yard punt return for a
touchdown called back because Charlie Williams was holding. RUNNING
MEN
</P>
<P>
   How will running back Smith react the first time Chris Warren
rushes for 100 yards?
</P>
<P>
   Smith got his answer Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, sporting a blue hat and matching blue sun glasses, talked
about how great a combination he and Warren made. And why not?
While Warren's 104 yards on 14 carries came with the game decided,
Smith rushed 28 times for 120 yards to help key the victory against
the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely showed what a 1-2 punch can do,'' Smith said.
``Chris is a great back.''
</P>
<P>
   The 104 yards marked the first time Warren had topped the
century mark in almost two years. The last was a 116-yard effort
against the Buffalo Bills, December 8, 1996. TIGHT ENDS RE-EMERGE
</P>
<P>
   Who said Cowboys coach Chan Gailey isn't part psychologist?
</P>
<P>
   Gailey did a good sucker job on the media and maybe the Redskins
last week when he talked about how the tight ends in the Cowboys
offense are often used as run blockers and didn't really fit into
his passing-game philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys tight end David Lafleur, who hadn't caught a pass since
the season opener, had a career-high four receptions for 29 yards.
And tight Eric Bjornson caught one for 4 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to be involved,'' LaFleur said. ``We understand
the offense and were not going to put the numbers like Eric and Jay
Novacek used to. Our role is to do a lot of blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   But against the Redskins, it was to catch passes as well, as
Gailey, who noticed something in the Redskins linebacker coverage
on film, said he planned all along to included his tight ends in
the passing game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
