<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9208 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX     10-05 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARRETT'S SOLID GAME GIVES AIKMAN TIME TO HEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ In truth, their run-happy, pass-orderly,
defense-miserly 31-10 victory here Sunday probably told us very
little about the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts, after all, were the winless, hapless _ and soon to be
Norv-less? _ Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   But this much we know:
</P>
<P>
   Jason Garrett, quarterback caretaker-in-residence, bought Troy
Aikman another week of bone-mending time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about it is that he threw the ball away when he
needed to throw it away,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said of
Garrett, who went 14-for-17 for 169 yards. ``He played a smart
football game. You've got to give the guy credit. I thought he
played a really smart football game.''
</P>
<P>
   OK. Garrett played a smart football game.
</P>
<P>
   But all things are relative. This was Week 3 of watching Gailey
hand Garrett the keys to the Cowboys' offense, and the new coach
was sounding no differently than any other anxious
man-of-the-house.
</P>
<P>
   It had pleased him that Garrett had the family Studebaker home
by 10 p.m., with all grillwork intact, the radio turned low and no
unrepairable dents in any fenders.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey wasn't ready to issue a blanket blessing of Garrett's
three weeks of substituting.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Gailey said, ``because we didn't win them all. I don't
care who's out. We need to win them all.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, dad. But at least the police didn't have to escort Jason
home.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett's best game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to evaluate games like that,'' Garrett answered.
``I'm really a play-by-play guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at plays, see where you made your mistakes, and then
you move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   A week after he helped squander a golden opportunity against the
Oakland Raiders, Garrett displayed veteran poise and preparation
against the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garrett obviously played as well as anyone could play,'' said
besieged Redskins coach Norv Turner. ``They were able to move the
ball in the first half, and I thought he was the key to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, however, Washington offered only token resistance. The
Redskins are 0-5, but let me suggest they're not as good as their
record.
</P>
<P>
   The medical conclusion is Aikman, suffering from a broken
collarbone, needs to take another week off. Never mind what he said
last week about targeting Sunday's Carolina game for his triumphant
return.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett can handle it. Aikman needs to wait another week, or
two, or four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea about next week,'' Garrett said. ``If he's
healthy, he'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's old thinking. That's Switzer-era thinking. The
``asthma field'' was extinct. The inmates ruled the asylum.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman wasn't a doctor, but he frequently played one on TV. When
Aikman said on the local sports shows he was ready to play, he
played. Same with Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   You would think, however, the new man in charge, Gailey, would
have something to say about that. It should all be required
homework in his Cowboys Assertiveness Training Course. The former
head coach never enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   And for Gailey's part, Garrett and the rest of the offense
bought him another week.
</P>
<P>
   With the offensive line plowing manly sized holes through the
Redskins' defense, the Cowboys' Smith and Chris Warren both ran for
more than 100 yards. The passing game did fine, thank you, on a
diet of Garrett taking short drops and throwing to Ernie Mills,
Billy Davis and David LaFleur.
</P>
<P>
   So, no need to rush things. When he sees the doctor Monday,
Aikman needs to take an X-ray. Take a Valium. Take another week _
or two _ off.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's game, Aikman said, ``I think it's pretty
optimistic to think that I would be able to play next week.''
</P>
<P>
   No big hurry, in other words. He was here. He saw the ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but a trifling thing like a broken collarbone never made
Aikman cautious before. Was he suggesting prudence, someone asked,
because he saw the game that fill-in Garrett played?
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason playing well certainly helps us,'' Aikman said, his head
again displaying its rock-hardness. ``But that has no bearing on
when I can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the issue. The issue is whether the collarbone is
healed.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is also, let me suggest, that another of the NFC
feebles, Carolina, heads for Texas Stadium on Sunday, to be
followed by a Cowboys trip to Chicago, an open week and then a Nov.
2 game in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. The toughest part of that stretch is clearly the open week.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders were a different test last week, we can assume. They
were smart. They were patient. They were lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys might not see another foe like Oakland for two
months.
</P>
<P>
   They need Aikman. They just don't need him yet.
</P>
<P>
   As the head coach needs to inform him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
