<SLUG> BC-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS FIND LIFE'S ELIXIR IN NFC EAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Even this early in the season, it's obvious that
the Dallas Cowboys have located the NFL's version of the Mayo
Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling sick after a lousy loss? Got just the cure. It's called
the NFC East, currently known as NFC Lite.
</P>
<P>
   In their most-impressive victory and 60-minute show of
domination since the 1997 opener in Pittsburgh, the Cowboys
transformed an expected tough game into a giggler here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The bitter disappointment surrounding last week's home-field
loss to Oakland became a distant memory. It was a different
everything and everybody this time, including a composed and sharp
Jason Garrett. Winless and desperate, Washington, old NFC East
enemy, stayed winless and desperate, walloped by the Cowboys,
31-10.
</P>
<P>
   All three victories this season are against divisional brothers,
and by a combined score of 100-27. More vital is that after a
mind-twisting loss in Denver and an angry loss to the Raiders, the
Cowboys have been able to find immediate comfort against East
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   A once-proud division is suffering, but for what it's worth, the
Cowboys are now experiencing the same luxury the 49ers have enjoyed
for years _ loading up on a cupcake division. Except that on most
NFL menus, the Cowboys are also listed as pastry, and that's even
when Troy Aikman is healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey, for now, doesn't seem to mind the perception of
either his team or the division. For the Cowboys to prove they can
still hang with the big boys, it will have to be in the playoffs,
and that comes beyond Christmas. If capable and worthy, there's
ample time and games to prepare for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our best game,'' Gailey said in a happy locker room,
``and I think it showed an improving team. Where we are at the
moment, however, I don't know yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still learning this team, but I'm also a believer that
adversity teaches you more about people than anything else. When
things are not going well, how do they respond? And I'm impressed
with our guys in that area. Really impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, gloom hung over the Cowboys after the Oakland
defeat. Plus, they were coming into Washington, where they hadn't
won since 1994. With an 0-4 record, the Redskins' whole season rode
on this one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing we wanted to happen, happened early,'' safety
Darren Woodson said. ``\RThe Redskins\S got the quick touchdown on
us and were all pumped up.''
</P>
<P>
   But from that early seven-point hole, the Cowboys totally took
over the game. Emmitt Smith (120 yards on 28 carries) headed a
ruthless ground game. He combined with Chris Warren (104 yards on
14 carries) to turn the $57 million worth of defensive tackles _
Dan Wilkinson and Dana Stubblefield _ that Washington purchased in
the off-season into instant Jell-O.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by an offensive line providing running room, Garrett
picked his spots through the air and picked apart the Redskins
secondary. Particularly impressive was how Garrett overcame an
early blunder when he lost a fumbled snap, setting up the
Washington touchdown. Combine that with Garrett's role in the
Oakland loss, and panic could have been an option. ``But Jason
never looked so cool back there,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins needed to establish the same running game the
Cowboys had, but it didn't happen. Nearly half of Terry Allen's 82
yards came on one carry in the second half with Washington down by
two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in here at halftime, up by seven points (17-10), and the
coaches are going a mile-a-minute on all the adjustments,'' Gailey
said. ``Suddenly, I look up, and the entire team had stampeded
right out the door. Somebody had said it was two minutes to
kickoff, and I couldn't keep 'em in here. They kicked down the door
to get back out there. That kinda' shows how the players approached
this game.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been, however, no pattern of consistency thus far.
Open the season with a nice win at home against Arizona; have the
defense get powdered in Denver; bounce back strongly in New York
with Deion and defense; give one away against Oakland at home; and
then do a road dance on the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess what coach Gailey is going to be harping on all this
week: consistency,'' said defensive tackle Chad Hennings. ``There's
no reason this team shouldn't start showing it. The attitude is
there. We're together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider that Sunday's opponent is Carolina at Texas Stadium, as
in winless Carolina (0-4), coming off a 51-23 shelling Sunday by
Atlanta. No, it's not another NFC East get-well card. But if
consistency does surface, Carolina is a victory waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, let the memory of the Oakland disaster serve as a
reminder that the Cowboys are still in an up-and-down mode, until
they prove otherwise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
