<HEADLINE>
RUNNING GAME FLASHES FORMER BRILLIANCE
</HEADLINE>
 SIDER-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVER, Md. _ Cowboys running backs coach Clarence Shelmon
sported a deft, I-told-you-so type of grin in the locker room after
Sunday's 31-10 victory against the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   And it would seem he has every right to smile, considering the
dominant performance of his primary charges. Starting tailback
Emmitt Smith totaled 120 yards and a touchdown on 28 carries and
backup Chris Warren tallied 104 yards and two touchdowns on 14
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Two backs rushing for more than 100 yards in the same game had
happened only twice previously in team history.
</P>
<P>
   But while he commended the performances of Smith and Warren,
saying ``this is exactly why we brought Chris here,'' Shelmon knows
the play of the Cowboys' maligned offensive line and the pregame
strategy of coach Chan Gailey played a large role in the running
game's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offensive line did an outstanding job,'' Shelmon said.
``But we felt we could run the football all along. The game plan
was simple. We ran very few plays. But we used a lot of different
formations. The backs got a feel for the running lanes because they
were running the same play and the blockers were blocking the same
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the Redskins had been allowing 160 yards a game on
the ground and ranked 29th in the league against the run, the
Cowboys should have figured they could run the ball. But they
thought they could run against the Oakland Raiders last week, too.
</P>
<P>
   And with a 2.7 yards-per-carry average the past two games,
nothing was guaranteed. Those numbers came against the New York
Giants and Raiders, who used eight- and nine-man fronts against the
Cowboys in an attempt to put more pressure on inexperienced
quarterback Jason Garrett.
</P>
<P>
   But that was before Nate Newton, 37, much-maligned center Clay
Shiver and former CFL guard Mike Kiselak _ who replaced injured
Everett McIver early in the first quarter _ went to work on the
Redskins' $57 million defensive-tackle duo of Dana Stubblefield and
Dan Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
   Newton, matched up against the 1997 defensive player of the year
Stubblefield for most of the day, looked like the ``Big Newt'' of
old, as the Cowboys ran over the left side for two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted he got help from Shiver, tackle Larry Allen and a
running back on Stubblefied and said the running game still needs
to be more consistent. But Newton warned that people shouldn't
think the Cowboys have gone soft in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are an older team,'' Newton said. ``We still got talent in
the right spot. And as role players, we still got to do what we got
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, who is fast becoming a premier strategist, is helping
them do it. Another significant part of the running-game strategy
against Redskins was to run outside early in the game. The idea was
to wear out Stubblefield and Wilkinson by getting them to run
laterally in an attempt to soften the inside for later in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The plan paid dividends in the second half when Garrett limited
his passes while the Cowboys leaned heavily on the running game. Of
the 224 total rushing yards, 165 came in the second half, capped by
the final 11-play, 96-yard touchdown drive at the end of the fourth
quarter that included no passes and took 6:02 off the clock.
</P>
<P>
   And Shelmon was smiling the entire time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
