<HEADLINE>
A COUCH-POTATO HEAVEN AWAITS BIG 12 FANATICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Replace the batteries in the remote control, program the VCR and
break out the industrial-size bag of Doritos.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest football weekend of the Big 12 season is upon us,
and it figures to be a Saturday made in heaven for sofa spuds. The
list of compelling matchups runs deep enough that Texas-Oklahoma is
reduced to an 11:30 a.m. appetizer on a day when pivotal Big 12
games will be fed to viewers in nonstop fashion for approximately
10 hours on four channels.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the color of your class ring, a case could be made
for any of the three subsequent telecasts _ Nebraska-Texas A&AMP;M
(2:30 p.m.), Kansas State-Colorado (6 p.m.) or Oklahoma State-Texas
Tech (6 p.m.) _ as the main course in a tasty football smorgasbord.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, these four games should help answer lingering
questions about a league heading toward the midpoint of its season
with four unbeaten teams, a revitalized Heisman Trophy hopeful and
plenty of mystery surrounding its weekly outcomes because of
improved play by the bottom feeders.
</P>
<P>
   Among the pressing issues that should be answered this week:
</P>
<P>
   Is Texas Tech a threat to win the South Division, or merely a
5-0 mirage that will vanish now that quality teams begin dotting
the Red Raiders' schedule?
</P>
<P>
   Can Texas tailback Ricky Williams continue to compile enough
superhuman statistics to rebuild a once-shaky Heisman campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Does a change in quarterbacks give Texas A&AMP;M a better chance to
record its first victory against a top-10 opponent since 1989?
</P>
<P>
   How will No. 5 Kansas State respond to the novelty of a road
trip, much less one that mandates the Wildcats actually play an
opponent with a winning record?
</P>
<P>
   These are the questions that try Big 12 souls. Answers won't be
available until Saturday night. For some educated guesses, we turn
to the experts.
</P>
<P>
   Tech coach Spike Dykes, how 'bout those Red Raiders?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing some things better than I expected,'' said Dykes,
pointing to a rushing offense and rushing defense both ranked among
the top five in the nation. ``But we've still got some chinks in
our armor. We're not ready for the big boys yet. But we're close.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas coach Mack Brown, how do you rate your tailback's Heisman
hopes now that he's become the only rusher in NCAA history to
record consecutive 300-yard games?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's among the front-runners. I feel he has to be first or
second, for sure,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum, is your Randy McCown-led offense ready to
rumble with second-ranked Nebraska?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still not very smooth and that really concerns me,''
Slocum said. ``We can't play like we've been playing and stay on
the field with Nebraska.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State coach Billy Snyder, what concerns you most about
playing in a hostile environment against those pass-happy Colorado
Buffaloes?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had 38 penalties in our last three games. We've given up
over 200 yards in the passing game our last two games,'' Snyder
said. ``That tells me there's a lot of work to be done in those
areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there are lots of questions to be answered this week
by Big 12 football teams. Fans are urged to rest their thumbs until
Saturday. You'll need them at full strength for channel surfing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
