<HEADLINE>
TOUGH STRETCH TESTS SEC'S CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
 FOLO-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Southeastern Conference team has won (Florida 1996) or played
for (Florida '95; Tennessee '97) the national championship each of
the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   However, it appears the SEC could be its own worst enemy this
season. The winner of the league's Dec. 5 title game could be more
of a survivor than a champion.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was the start of two pivotal weeks in the SEC. Georgia
won at Louisiana State, 28-27, behind the play of freshman
quarterback Quincy Carter. After spending three seasons playing in
the Chicago Cubs' minor-league system, Carter has led the Bulldogs
to a 4-0 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an opportunity here to do something special, and
when you're a player that's all you want: an opportunity,'' Carter
said. ``This is why I gave up baseball and came back to football.
If you love college football, these are the kinds of things you
live for.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee struggled to win at Auburn, 17-9, Saturday. The
Volunteers won despite 218 yards of total offense and nine first
downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play in this league, you're fooling yourself if you
ever think it's going to be easy on the road,'' Tennessee coach
Phillip Fulmer said. ``A stretch like this is when you find out
about the character of your football team.''
</P>
<P>
   The SEC has four teams ranked in the top 11 _ No. 4 Tennessee,
No. 6 Florida, No. 7 Georgia and No. 11 LSU. Tennessee has beaten
Florida, and Georgia has beaten LSU; Florida plays host to LSU this
weekend, and Tennessee is at Georgia. Georgia and Florida play Oct.
31.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's games again caused some movement in the poll voting.
Ohio State's 28-9 victory at home against No. 7 Penn State boosted
the Buckeyes, while Nebraska's 24-17 nail-biting victory against
Oklahoma State cost the Cornhuskers the ground they gained the
previous week.
</P>
<P>
   Top-ranked Ohio State picked up six first-place votes in The
Associated Press (media) poll; second-ranked Nebraska lost five No.
1 votes. The previous week, the vote flowed the other direction,
with the idle Buckeyes losing six votes.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``ESPN/USA Today'' (coaches) poll, Ohio State picked up
the first-place votes of nine voters who switched from Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead ``Star-Telegram'' college football writer Wendell
Barnhouse takes a look at this week's top games:
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 UCLA at No. 10 Arizona: The Bruins enter a tough stretch.
Next week, high-scoring Oregon visits the Rose Bowl. The Wildcats
are gaining confidence each week.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 Tennessee at No. 7 Georgia: Another Saturday, another SEC
showdown. The winner takes command of the East Division.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Nebraska at No. 18 Texas A&AMP;M: The Cornhuskers appeared to
be hitting their stride until tripping _ but winning _ against
Oklahoma State. The Aggies need to fix their offensive woes.
</P>
<P>
   No. 11 Louisiana State at No. 6 Florida: Last season, the
Gators' hopes of a national championship ended in Baton Rouge, La.
Florida didn't like watching the Tigers celebrate, and coach Steve
Spurrier has a good memory.
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 Kansas State at No. 14 Colorado: After an off week, the
Wildcats face a ranked team for the first time this season.
However, the Buffaloes have appeared exceedingly average while
going 5-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 0211EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
