<HEADLINE>
RAIN OF ERRORS AT ARROWHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ First, lightning struck. Then, Andre Rison
struck. In between, the Seahawks' offense was just stuck.
</P>
<P>
   In another bizarre game in a seemingly endless series of
grotesque games for the Seahawks at Arrowhead Stadium, the Kansas
City Chiefs slapped them with a 17-6 loss in Sunday night's
nationally televised game.
</P>
<P>
   A storm that dumped 3.6 inches of rain on downtown Kansas City
from 7:15 to 9 p.m. forced a 54-minute delay in the game when
lightning struck too close to the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing could delay the inevitable _ the Seahawks' eighth
straight loss at Arrowhead, and their 16th to the Chiefs in their
last 17 trips here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been saying we're not the same Hawks, but we played like
it today,'' defensive end Michael Sinclair said in a Seahawk locker
room filled with silence and overflowing with frustration. ``This
is tough. It's the same old feeling. We came here and acted like we
don't have a clue what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   This loss dropped the Seahawks to 3-2 and into a tie with the
Oakland Raiders for third place in the AFC West entering next
week's game against the unbeaten and division-leading Denver
Broncos at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have got to change. We've got a juggernaut coming in
Sunday,'' Sinclair said of the defending Super Bowl champion
Broncos. ``If we play like that, we're going to be the laughing
stock.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' latest setback at Arrowhead was not without
injuries. Quarterback Warren Moon cracked a rib and wide receiver
Joey Galloway bruised his left knee. Neither finished the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs, meanwhile, improved to 4-1 as Rich Gannon hooked up
with Rison on an 80-yard touchdown pass in the third quarter.
Gannon also scored on a 4-yard run in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, we had some opportunities,'' Seahawks
coach Dennis Erickson said. ``We didn't make plays and they made
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   As was the case in last week's three-point loss at Pittsburgh,
the defense played well enough for the Seahawks to win and made
enough big plays that the Seahawks should have at least been in
this game.
</P>
<P>
   Pro Bowl free safety Darryl Williams recovered a club-record
three fumbles and the Seahawks had five in the game. But all the
offense could muster from the field position supplied by the
defense were a pair of Todd Peterson field goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a team effort, and we didn't get it done,'' Williams
said. ``Some days it's like that. You've got to take advantage of
big plays. Today, we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Joseph gave the offense another chance in the fourth
quarter by returning a punt 66 yards to the Kansas City 17. Again,
the offense failed as Peterson slapped a 38-yard field-goal attempt
wide left.
</P>
<P>
   The game was suspended with 7:10 remaining in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Just after Moon was dropped for a 1-yard loss on a broken play,
referee Phil Luckett was called to the sideline and told to send
the players to the locker room by Art McNally, NFL assistant
supervisor of officials. Fans also were advised to move to the
lower concourse of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had seen some lightning go across the sky and, in my
judgment, the last that we saw was severe enough and too close to
the stadium. I felt it was time to pull everybody out,'' said
McNally, who called Luckett from his seat in the press box. ``We
cannot take a chance with the safety of the players and the fans in
the stands. We decided we would suspend the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the lightning delay, the two teams slipped, slopped and
sloshed to a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon lost the ball on the third play of the game and Seahawks
defensive end Phillip Daniels recovered the fumble at the Kansas
City 17-yard line. Three runs by Ricky Watters moved the ball to
the 4, but Moon's third-down pass to Mike Pritchard in the end zone
was batted incomplete by Chiefs cornerback James Hasty.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson then kicked a 22-yard field goal with 12:05 left in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks almost got the ball back on the Chiefs' second
possession when it slipped from Gannon's hand again on first down.
Sinclair recovered inside the Kansas City 25, but it was ruled an
incomplete pass. Replays showed that Gannon lost the ball on a pump
fake, but the incompletion ruling stood.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City tied the score just before the end of the quarter by
driving to a 22-yard field goal by Pete Stoyanovich. With the
middle of the field looking more like a giant slip-and-slide, the
Chiefs pounded away at the middle of the Seahawks' defense on a
10-play, 45-yard trudge.
</P>
<P>
   Donnell Bennett carried five times for 35 yards before being
forced to the sideline with a bruised right hand.
</P>
<P>
   The rain continued to pelt the field in the second quarter. The
Seahawks' first possession ended with a fumble by Watters, but they
got the ball back three players later when Sinclair forced a
Bennett fumble that was recovered by Williams.
</P>
<P>
   It started pouring rain again when the Seahawks got the ball
with 8:50 left in the half. When several bolts of lightning
crackled too near the stadium, the decision was made to suspend the
game.
</P>
<P>
   When play resumed, John Friesz replaced Moon, who was hurt on
the run just before the delay.
</P>
<P>
   Before the night was over, the Seahawks had used each of their
quarterbacks. And as Chiefs linebacker Anthony Davis bellowed on
his way to the locker room, ``They used all three quarterbacks, and
none of them got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Moon was 0-for-2. Friesz was 8 of 19 for 52 yards. Jon Kitna was
3 of 12 for 42 yards. The Seahawks finished with only 167 yards and
other than Galloway's five catches, only one other wide receiver
caught a pass.
</P>
<P>
   On his first full series, Friesz threw a first-down pass to
Pritchard, who leaped for the ball but had it go off his hands.
Chiefs cornerback Dale Carter made a diving interception of the
carom and a 15-yard face mask penalty against Seahawks tight end
Deems May moved the ball to the Seattle 17. Six plays later, Gannon
scrambled into the end zone to give the Chiefs a 10-3 lead at the
half.
</P>
<P>
   Rison's TD, the Chiefs' longest pass play since 1990, came at
the end of the third quarter as he ran past Williams to take
Gannon's pass wide open. Rison then outran strong safety Jay
Bellamy to the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran play action and we were up playing the run and he got
behind one of the safeties,'' Erickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams admitted the blown coverage was his fault. Everyone
involved agreed the long pass was the difference in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, it turned the momentum around,'' Gannon said.
``We actually had another play called when we were in the huddle.
That other play came in and it was a read route to Andre and he
made a great decision. ... He went right by them and I just tried
to put it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Rison: ``We practiced that play, but it wasn't drawn up on
our script this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' offensive ineptness was exemplified by their first
possession of the fourth quarter. After Galloway picked up a first
down with a 9-yard completion, the Seahawks wound up with a
third-and-35 as tight end Carlester Crumpler false started, tackle
Howard Ballard was flagged for holding, Watters fumbled and then
was dropped for a 7-yard loss after taking a pass from Friesz.
Friesz's third-down pass was incomplete, but at least they didn't
lose yards on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna replaced Friesz late in the fourth quarter, but had a pass
picked off at the Chiefs' 1-yard line by Hasty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about the one thing we've always believed in. You
play one play at a time,'' Chiefs coach Marty Schottenheimer said.
``When it's over you put it aside and go to the next one. They
certainly embraced that philosophy today. It was a pretty strong
performance by our defensive football team.''
</P>
<P>
   And another bitter loss at Arrowhead for the Seahawks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
