</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARK MARTIN WINS, BUT GAINS LITTLE GROUND ON JEFF GORDON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURNBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _Mark Martin carved a 25-point chunk out of Jeff
Gordon's NASCAR Winston Cup points lead Sunday with a dominating
victory at Charlotte Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Martin knows even that will not cut it if he expects to overhaul
Gordon's still sizeable 174-point championship advantage with five
races remaining. But that does not mean Martin is growing
frustrated by his inability to reel Gordon into immediate striking
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I look frustrated?'' a grinning Martin said after his
victory in the UAW-GM Quality 500. ``This is the greatest year of
my life. I don't see how anybody could look at this year and think
that it was a failure. If I never even start the rest of the races
this year, it's gotta be a tremendous success.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's victory on the especially slick 1.5-mile CMS trioval
was his career-best seventh of the season, second only to Gordon's
10. Martin led a race-high 215 of the 334 laps, the eighth time he
has led the most laps this season and bagged the extra five points
that accompany it. Martin now has scored 145 lap-leader bonus
points in 1998, the most of any driver. And his 29th career victory
was his 18th top-10 finish in the last 19 races of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the same driver,'' said Martin, whose team was rebuilt and
relocated from Liberty, N.C., to nearby Mooresville by team owner
Jack Roush during the off-season. ``I'm not driving harder, smarter
or better than I ever have. I'm driving better cars and man, it's
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin and the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus were good enough to
lead on six occasions, including all of crunch time. Martin led 133
of the final 134 laps, including the final 66 to beat Ward Burton
by 1.110-seconds. Jeff Burton, Ward's younger brother and Martin's
Roush Racing teammate, was third, followed by a resurgent Bobby
Hamilton and the ever-present Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon racked up his 15th consecutive top-five finish when he
drove around Kevin Lepage, another Roush driver, on lap 331. That
was worth an extra five points for Gordon, driver of the No. 24
DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo. Gordon needs to
finish fifth or better in the remaining five races to claim his
third Cup title and deny Martin his first.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating there a little bit,'' said Gordon,
referring to his chase of the Roush pack in front of him. ``They're
fast. Mark's got an awesome setup, obviously, and those guys can
really drive. They were really strong today.''
</P>
<P>
   But survival of the strongest also was a factor during a race
that produced 11 caution flags, one less than the event record set
in 1981. The race also was red-flagged to a stop for 42 minutes on
lap 94 when a sewer pump malfunctioned and allowed water to back up
and seep over a portion of the backstretch wall and across the
track.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Gordon were among the leaders who dodged a 10-car
wreck in Turn 2 triggered by native Texan Bobby Labonte on lap 202.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the things that took out some good race cars,
and it should have taken us out,'' said Martin, who was leading
Labonte and the race at that point. ``When I entered the corner I
saw a shiny stripe (of oil) on the racetrack, just a vague shiny
stripe. I decided in a split-second to not turn left and let the
car go into the corner on the high side. My spotter called,
`Inside, whoa!' I knew I had made the right choice right then, and
then he started telling me to hurry up because Bobby was starting
on the inside of me. And if he would have spun in the oil, he could
have spun right into me and crashed me out, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very close situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's winning average speed was 123.188 mph in a race that
took 4 hours, 4 minutes and 1 second to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Ward Burton, meanwhile, led 33 laps and posted his best finish
since his victory at North Carolina Motor Speedway in Rockingham,
N.C., in October 1995. That was 88 races ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat everybody but one car \RMartin's\S and I wanted that
one car awful bad,'' said Burton, driver of the No. 22 MBNA Pontiac
Grand Prix. ``I know I had him beat on motor, there's no doubt
about that. We were just off on chassis a little bit. He just had a
little bit on me in (turns) 3 and 4.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was Ward Burton's first top-five since the
season-finale at Atlanta Motor Speedway in November 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
