<HEADER>
A9231 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      10-05 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEFS SINK SEAHAWKS ON LAKE ARROWHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Another 10 minutes of rain Sunday night, and
Kansas City could have opened its first fresh seafood restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The hastily rearranged halftime show featured Gordon Lightfoot
singing ``The Wreck of the Edmund Fitzgerald.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the best part of the Seahawks-Chiefs water-balloon fight was
that it provided Seattle a climatological preview of the new
roofless football stadium scheduled to open in 2002, not to mention
a name: Waterworld.
</P>
<P>
   True, weather in Seattle doesn't usually happen like this _ 3.6
inches of rain in less than two hours, accompanied by gales and a
light show with percussion that surpassed the best of Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The worst part of the game for the Seahawks was that it was the
same Seattle story in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   For the 16th time in the last 17 games in this place, the
Seahawks went down in the standard ignominious fashion. But instead
of a thud, they went down with a splash.
</P>
<P>
   In a game played mostly at flood stage, the Seahawks managed to
set a low-water mark in a 17-6 defeat. In a season filled with
optimism after a 3-0 start, they have lost two straight road games
to good teams _ the kind of games that they vowed to win to fulfill
the expensively promoted promise of turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't beat us _ we beat us,'' defensive tackle Sam Adams
said. ``If they beat us, we'd be concerned. But we've made the same
kind of mistakes two weeks in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something's got to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, the defense was resolute, except for one hiccup that
allowed an 80-yard gamebreaker of a touchdown pass to Andre Rison.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the offense bordered on the inept.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the thunderstorm was abominable, the ball was slippery and
leaden, the field was sod cheesecake and the pratfalls were
hilarious. But unless they had mud caked over their ears and eyes,
the Seahawks will have a difficult time explaining the false
starts, misreads, blown plays and fundamental mistakes that had
little to do with abysmal conditions. The Chiefs were overboard in
the same brown ocean, and somehow learned to swim.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the environmental burlesque was the Seahawks' Voyage to
the Bottom of the Playbook _ again. Much as it happened last week
in Pittsburgh, the Seahawks were desperate for just one big play to
turn the game around.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the big play went to K.C. when quarterback Rich Gannon
connected with Rison at the end of the third quarter for the game's
second touchdown _ one that might as well have been worth 60 points
instead of six, given the Seahawk offensive breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the weather, but at the same time, the
offense hasn't played well, maybe even going back to preseason,''
said quarterback John Friesz, who played most of the second half in
relief of injured Warren Moon. ``We just haven't played at a real
high level.''
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of the first-half cyclone, the futility was
understandable _ no pass completions, just two first downs and 37
yards rushing by the six-minute halftime, a concession to the
54-minute delay in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last game (against San Diego on Sunday here), I said it was
the worst conditions I'd ever seen,'' Chiefs coach Marty
Schottenheimer said. ``How little I knew.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the airborne water was so dense, the upper deck
stands across from the press box could not be seen. Stadium lights
created a sheen on the rain-soaked field that for a few moments
created a lake-like glare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was praying every time I got under center than I didn't
fumble the snap,'' Moon said. ``The ball was sitting in a couple
inches of water.''
</P>
<P>
   On the final play before play was temporarily halted _
supervisor of officials Art McNally said play either must be
stopped or yardage converted to fathoms _ Moon was sacked on a
busted play, and the hit cracked a rib. He never returned.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky guy.
</P>
<P>
   Unlucky Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half that was mostly free of wind, rain and
standing water, the Seahawks under Friesz squandered multiple
opportunities provided by five K.C. fumbles. The opening series of
the third quarter ended when Friesz missed a wide-open Joey
Galloway on a pass in the flat at midfield, throwing out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as close as I've come to throwing a pass backwards,''
Friesz said of his lost grip on the ball. ``Sometimes when you have
dry hands, it works against you. I think I'd rather have the ball
and my hands wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Foul-weather games are always field-position affairs that turn
on the running game and turnovers. They are manly sorts of jousts
that reveal who can turn calamity into opportunity. All you need to
know about the Seahawks on this black evening was that they had
more yards in penalties (88) than rushing (73). In this four-hour
trudge through sludge, the Seahawks were also revealed to be closer
to their past than their future.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 0221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
