</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-JENKINS-PLAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB'S LEAP KNOCKS HUSKIES FOR LOOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Nine yards to destiny. Nine yards to mount a rocket
booster on Arizona's football season, perhaps giving it life all
the way to Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   When University of Washington players saw on video Ortege
Jenkins' miraculous tote-and-tumble to the end zone Saturday night,
they had reason to be all the more chagrined. Jenkins, the Wildcat
quarterback, retreated all the way to the Husky 20 before making
his dash for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no doubt,'' Jenkins said in the euphoric Arizona locker
room. ``I don't know my vertical jump _ 37 (inches), 38, something
like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   With 12 seconds on the clock and Arizona owning no timeouts,
this is how the play unfolded:
</P>
<P>
   Arizona calls it ``A-2.'' Wildcat wide receiver Dennis Northcutt
and tight end Mike Lucky lined up left as Jenkins' two primary
targets. As the Huskies rushed four linemen, Jenkins backpedaled,
looked left and decided nothing was available.
</P>
<P>
   His right foot crossed the 20, and then he reversed himself,
sprinting up the middle. The Husky linemen were pushed to the
outside, so Jenkins was able to get his charge under way without
changing direction. By the 15, he was past the down linemen.
</P>
<P>
   He bolted straight ahead, and the Husky linebackers, who had
dropped into coverage, confronted him inside the 5, joined by free
safety Brendan Jones. Side by side, inside linebacker Marques
Hairston and Jones hunkered into squat positions at the 2, ready to
hammer Jenkins down. From Jenkins' right side, the other inside
linebacker, Lester Towns, moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Either Jenkins would score, or the game would end. Getting out
of bounds was not an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get squared up to hit him,'' Towns said, as he left
Hec Edmundson Pavilion at midnight. ``I don't know why everyone
went low. If they'd hit him high, he wouldn't have gone in.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins launched himself from the 4-yard line, seemingly into
the night sky. Hairston and Jones were foils, their minimal contact
only increased the arc of Jenkins' somersault.
</P>
<P>
   When he came down, he landed on his feet. Had he needed to, he
could have run to the University Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He jumped so high,'' marveled Jones. ``I give him all the
credit in the world. He did what he had to do to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Incredible,'' said Jeff Woodruff, the Arizona running backs
coach who made his first return to Husky Stadium since his firing
by UW coach Jim Lambright after the 1993 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got hired (last winter), I looked at some of the
big plays of a year ago, and the thing I noticed, the guy made some
spectacular plays off-balance and out of position.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if he's going to play basketball for Lute Olson (Jenkins
has been a deep reserve), he's got to be a pretty good player. When
I talked to Miles Simon and Jason Terry and Mike Bibby, they said
practicing against him was tougher than a lot of guys they played
in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Tomey, the Arizona coach, said he had never seen a more
marvelous play in the crucible of a win-or-lose situation. Asked
what he thought when Jenkins rose at the 4, Tomey said, ``I just
know he's gonna go high.''
</P>
<P>
   Husky Stadium was almost empty when Jenkins, completing
interviews in the end zone, ran joyously up the tunnel. Scavanging
kids begged for his wristbands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't give you this one,'' Jenkins said. ``It's got the plays
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   With plays like his, who needs a script?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
