<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METCALF SAYS FUMBLE STICKS IN HIS MIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 and TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. -  &UR; Eric Metcalf didn't want to talk about his six
kickoff returns for 194 yards Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll remember this game for the fumble,'' Metcalf said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were leading the Oakland Raiders, 14-6, when
Metcalf fumbled a punt early in the second quarter and the Raiders'
 &UR; Kenny Shedd recovered at the Arizona 36.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland scored after that turnover and went on to collect 17
unanswered points in beating the Cardinals, 23-20, at Sun Devil
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll remember it because they got points out of it,'' Metcalf
said. ``It would be different if they didn't score.'' &QL; 
Help missing &QL; 
Former Arizona State cornerback  &UR; Eric Allen's triumphant return to
Sun Devil Stadium on Sunday was just a couple of feet away from
being a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The record will show Allen picked off a scrambling  &UR; Jake
Plummer's underthrown pass to the wide-open  &UR; Larry Centers in the
end zone, taking away beautiful field position at the Raiders'
16-yard line after rookie quarterback  &UR; Donald Hollas had fumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a late read,'' Allen said. ``He was scrambling,
but I didn't even see him scramble. But I knew I had a safety on
top of me, so I played the underneath portion and he underthrew the
pass. I didn't realize it until I saw the play on the replay board,
but our safety wasn't there.'' &QL; 
Missing seconds &QL; 
The Cardinals are still wondering what happened to 26 seconds on
the clock during the Raiders' final fourth-quarter possession.
Oakland's  &UR; Harvey &UR; Williams carried for three yards to set up a
third and 1 at Arizona's 42 with 7:17 left.
</P>
<P>
   After 26 seconds ran off the clock, the referee called an
official timeout and measured for a first down, which was given to
the Raiders, but no time was added back on the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did ask the officials if the clock was right, or if they
shouldn't put more time on it,'' Cardinals defensive coordinator
Dave McGinnis said. ``They just didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those seconds might have proven pivotal at game's end, when the
Cardinals tried unsuccessfully to set up a potentially tying field
goal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
