<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-PLANETS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S MORE GOING ON THAN THE BILL AND MONICA SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes I want to take all of you out behind the barn and slap
a little sense into you, except I haven't lived on land with a barn
since I was a kid and even then it functioned much less as a barn
than a garage. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But where I feel like knocking you conscious is beside the
point. Rather, the point is that for months now you've been so
focused on Bill and Monica and the attendant and repugnant cast of
hundreds that not one of you has remarked to me how astonishing it
is that scientists are on a roll, discovering all kinds of other
planets in the cosmos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As I write this (about 2:35 p.m.), news has just broken that a
team of astronomers using the huge Keck telescope in Hawaii has
found two planets in orbit around sun-like stars. That brings to 12
the number of these planets discovered beyond our solar system in
the last few years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no proof yet that any of these dozen planets has even a
single junior college, Taco Bell or covered parking garage, any one
of which might indicate the presence of life. But you start adding
up planets at this rate and pretty soon the law of averages, if
any, will turn up one with dude ranches and telemarketers galore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about you, but I'm a lot more interested in what
life forms on a planet orbiting the star HD187123 are up to than I
am in what a ditz like Monica Lewinsky is going to do with the rest
of her life besides write tell-all books and host her own talk show
and autograph baseballs in stadiums on Bimbo Night. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As magazine editor Lewis Lapham once said of the late Princess
Diana, I am not engaged by Monica's search for the needle of her
self in the haystack of her press clippings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you think I just made up the name of that star,
HD187123. No, no. Too many columnists have gotten into deep and
justifiable trouble this year for making up stuff. If I can find a
way around that, I won't do it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that HD187123 is the real name of one of the stars
around which a team of astronomers, who mostly are connected with
San Francisco State University, recently found a planet. The other
star with a newly found planet, just for the record, is HD210277. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If I were to make up the name of a star I'd do a lot sexier job
than HD210277. I'd call it something like Flame Pants. But, as I
say, enough about Bill Clinton. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These two newly discovered planets, by the way, have orbits
quite dissimilar from one another. One circumnavigates HD210277 in
437 days, a couple of months longer than it takes Earth to travel
around our sun. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the one around HD187123 is much goofier. It is so close to
its sun that it circles it about every three days. Hoo-boy. Imagine
starting Monday morning in January and slamming into December by
the time you go to bed on Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the best things about the new planet discoveries is that
an amateur astronomer had something to do with them. I have nothing
against professional scientists, except that sometimes they tend to
get a little pretentious. Well, a lot pretentious, actually. But
it's nice to see amateurs do well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This one's name is Kevin Apps, an undergraduate at the
University of Sussex, which as far as I know is still in England. A
year or so ago he saw the list of stars this team of astronomers
planned to check for planets and told them 30 on their list weren't
good candidates. He suggested 30 better ones, and one turned out to
be HD187123. Way to go, Kevin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You know, Bill Clinton should be glad about this, too. It means
that if he ever gets sent to the clink for something, HD187123
won't be his prison number, it already having been spoken for. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
