<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9435 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-05 1639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
( jt ) 
   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Schroeder Ousts Kohl in German Election &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Gerhard Schroeder, a Social Democrat, defeated Helmut Kohl to
become Chancellor of Germany, ending an era in Germany and opening
a new one in Europe, where center-left governments now dominate the
continent's politics.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat of Kohl, the last of the European politicians who
were in office when the Berlin Wall came down in 1989, reflects
Europe's new priorities as it grapples with the competitive
pressures of a global economy, overburdened welfare systems and
high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   And the vote reflected the profound changes in German society
that have followed the fall of the Berlin Wall. The huge cost of
unification, high unemployment in the formerly Communist part of
the country and a shift eastward, away from the conservative
Rhineland, all contributed to Kohl's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; California Sets Early Primary &LR;
</P>
<P>
   With 54 electoral votes, California has long been the 800-pound
gorilla of American politics, except when it comes to presidential
candidates. In an era of increasingly early primaries, the state's
June date made it an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Pete Wilson signed a bill that will make California
more important than ever by moving its primary to the first Tuesday
in March, just after New Hampshire and Iowa. It will join New York
and other Eastern states in what may turn out to be a giant
national primary that ends the process almost before it has begun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fed Cuts Interest Rate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a month, Alan Greenspan, the Federal Reserve
chairman, had hinted that the global financial crisis might force
the central bank to put aside its concern about inflation and cut
interest rates. On Tuesday he acted, leading the Fed to cut its key
interest rate by a quarter point, to 5.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The move should give a small boost to the domestic economy by
reducing borrowing costs a bit for consumers and businesses. But
with concern growing that the global crisis could spread and
endanger the long American expansion, Greenspan mainly wanted to
send a message that he was on the case.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Greenspan Questioned On Hedge Fund Rescue &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Washington tells welfare mothers not to count on government
handouts, so why did the Federal Reserve arrange a rescue for an
investment firm run by and for some of the world's richest people?
That was the question posed to Greenspan by the House Banking
Committee as he recounted the central bank's role in averting the
collapse of Long-Term Capital Management L.P., a hedge fund gone
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan answered that allowing the firm to fail would have
risked a meltdown in the markets, potentially derailing the
economy. There are always going to be failures in the marketplace,
he said, and Congress should not overreact by writing more
stringent financial regulations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Again, a Hint of Hope For Mideast Talks  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration pressed hard for a long-elusive
interim settlement between Israel and the Palestinians. President
Clinton met on Monday with the Israeli prime minister, Benjamin
Netanyahu and, Yasser Arafat, and again Tuesday with Arafat, and
invited them to return to Washington in mid-October to finish the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   That's just before the Nov. 3 Congressional elections, a time
when Clinton hopes to be seen as taking care of business despite
his other distractions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Blast From Space &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Observing repeating bursts of gamma rays from four distant
places in the galaxy, astronomers came up with an explanation, in
theory. When a star explodes, all that remains is a dense object
known as a neutron star. In rare cases, these objects must generate
extremely powerful magnetic fields. Scientists reported they have
compelling evidence of the existence of such stars, called
magnetars.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 27, an intense wave of gamma rays penetrated Earth's
upper atmosphere. It posed no health risk, but the radiation
briefly disturbed the quiet night sky with electric conditions
limiting radio transmission. Magnetars, calculations show, produce
the most powerful magnetic fields ever seen in the universe,
billions of times stronger than any on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; After 29 Years, A Budget Surplus  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It had been expected for months, but President Clinton held a
big ceremony anyway to announce that the dog days of the deficit
were over. For the first time in 29 years, the government would end
the fiscal year with a budget surplus, about $70 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But how long it will last? The president has proposed billions
of dollars in new spending. The Republicans agree with most of
those proposals and want a tax cut to boot.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, the turmoil in the international financial
markets may wipe out the surplus before anyone can enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HMOs Shun Medicare &LR;
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 Medicare beneficiaries will have to find new
health insurance next year because they are in health maintenance
organizations that are cutting back their Medicare operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration told HMOs that they would not be
allowed to increase premiums or cut benefits for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy-Ann Min DeParle, administrator of the Medicare agency,
said HMOs were making ``business decisions'' to withdraw from some
counties after concluding that ``it will no longer be profitable
for them'' to serve Medicare patients there.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mizrahi Shutters Design Shop &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The fashion world braced itself for a duller show season in
Bryant Park tents next month as Isaac Mizrahi, the ebullient
designer thought most likely to inherit the mantle of top designers
like Ralph Lauren and Calvin Klein, announced that he would close
his business. Chanel Inc., his backer since 1992, said it was
pulling out. Paradoxically, sales of Mizrahi's collection,
estimated at $20 million to $30 million, had begun to pick up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Grand Central, at 85, Gets a Facelift &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Built in the heyday of train travel as a lustrous palace of
creamy marble walls and chandeliers, the Grand Central Terminal had
deteriorated in recent decades into a grimy symbol of urban
neglect. Now, at the age of 85, it has been restored to its former
Beaux Arts elegance.
</P>
<P>
   The terminal _ cleaned, polished and modernized at a cost of
$197 million over the last two years _ was rededicated in a
dazzling ceremony featuring trapeze artists, lasers and
whistle-blowing Metro-North train conductors providing authentic
sound effects for the debut performance of ``Grand Central!'' _ the
march.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Potholes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It's not a good time to be a pothole in New York City. For
starters, it's a lot lonelier than it used to be. Back in 1994,
some 200,000 potholes livened up the city's streets, but mild
winters and diligent repair crews have slashed the number,
officials say, to 25,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the big hazard, if you happen to be a pothole, is all those
politicians fighting over who's going to fill you in. Alfonse
D'Amato, campaigning to retain his Senate seat, clearly revels in
his ``Senator Pothole'' image and could at any moment reach for a
shovel.
</P>
<P>
   While D'Amato prefers the metaphorical interpretation _
``Potholes,'' he says, ``represent the hopes and aspirations of our
people.'' _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is taking literal aim at these
little pockets of the New York experience.
</P>
<P>
   Guiliani, tireless crusader against such beloved combat sports
as extreme jaywalking and taxi bumper cars, now envisions a
crater-free utopia, vowing, with Operation Pothole Blitz, to fill
every blemish in the city's streets by December.
</P>
<P>
   So don't be surprised if some innocent pothole, simply going
about its business of jarring hubcaps loose, is suddenly
surrounded, the mayor's limo on one side, the senator's on the
other, shovels dueling in the sunset.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TV Culture &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At a lunch celebrating the start of the new TV season, the heads
of the six network programming departments pondered the future of
the television movie and declared that literature, of all things,
may be the answer.
</P>
<P>
   The networks have all but announced an end to
ripped-from-the-headlines movies, their old staple. Instead, they
intend to make movies of such works as Lewis Carroll's ``Alice in
Wonderland,'' Shakespeare's ``The Tempest'' and Dostoevsky's
``Crime and Punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, all those films will be shown this season on NBC,
which has made the biggest turn toward literary works in recent
seasons, producing successful movies out of such classic literary
material as ``Gulliver's Travels,'' ``Merlin'' and even ``The
Odyssey.''
</P>
<P>
   This season presents more of a challenge. The first literary
entry on NBC's schedule is ``Crime and Punishment,'' to be shown on
Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently worried about audience response to descriptions of a
dark tale of tortured spiritual redemption, NBC is not selling the
show with its usual high-decibel promotion blitz _ no ``Must-See
Dostoevsky!'' Instead, NBC is going for lots of shots of a scary
guy wielding an axe.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems NBC is also worried about how much Dostoevsky the
press can take. In its publicity package for the movie, the network
included the latest Penguin Classics edition of ``Crime and
Punishment,'' all 630 pages of it.
</P>
<P>
   For added insurance, NBC included Cliff's Notes. Yes, THOSE
Cliff's Notes _ the same little yellow-and-black booklets (``Crime
and Punishment'' in 84 pages!) that high school students hide in
their backpacks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
