A9478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-CO     10-05 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: What punishment fits the crime?
 &HT;    (For release Oct. 7, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, here's where we're at:
</P>
<P>
   _ The House Judiciary hearings on Bill Clinton will drag on at
least until the first of the year and perhaps longer, fed
insatiably by partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ross Perot is grabbing any microphone he can get his little
hands on to call for a grass-roots drive to force Clinton from
office.
</P>
<P>
   _ A self-proclaimed grass-roots organization which claims to be
nonpartisan has launched a campaign via the Web that limits
punishment of Clinton simply to censure.
</P>
<P>
   _ And former President Gerald Ford, he who pardoned Richard
Nixon, is calling for the president to stand before the Congress
and receive a public rebuke.
</P>
<P>
   There's something there for everyone!
</P>
<P>
   Probably that's why this sordid chapter of American history will
drag on until the next president is inaugurated in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton is too proud to resign, so incredibly proud that he
will endure the ceaseless humiliation that will follow him for the
remainder of his term.
</P>
<P>
   What likely will have the most popular support is the Censure
And Move On movement on the Web. In the form of a cyberspace
petition, it seeks an end to the vulgar spectacle, regardless of
the offenses of Clinton _ if any.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of its visibility on the Web, the petition
drew 100,000 signatures, seeking a million by Election Day in
November.
</P>
<P>
   This likely will not satiate those who want Clinton served up
with an apple in his mouth. They will continue to press for
impeachment, knowing that the numbers presently are not there but
hoping that along the route, they will uncover even more to turn
the tide against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While resignation certainly is a splendid idea, we really don't
need that movement led by Perot. His TV bites on the issue almost
come off as comical. The carping Mr. Perot long ago lost the
respect of much of the American public. He can blame that on his
own image.
</P>
<P>
   When I read Ford's New York Times essay on rebuking Clinton
before a joint session of Congress, I kept conjuring the image of
Quasimodo, in chains, being mocked by the crowds. Clinton never
would agree to that; impeachment would seem a more tolerable course
to him.
</P>
<P>
   What all this boils down to is that there is no widely accepted
solution to the Clinton scandal. It will not go away, not for a
long time. What it also means is that this nation will remain
gridlocked in internecine warfare while the rest of the world looks
on in astonishment.
</P>
<P>
   With international crises aplenty, the United States hardly can
afford to lapse into an isolationism born of domestic paralysis. It
would be easy to tell those with whom we share this planet that we
have problems of our own and cannot be distracted at the moment,
but the world is on the verge of financial collapse; ethnic groups
still tear out the hearts of other ethnic groups; terrorists remain
fed and protected by rogue nations.
</P>
<P>
   Can Bill Clinton, under siege, lead us through this, can he
effectively push programs through a hostile Congress; can he impose
U.S. will on those who are loath to accept it?
</P>
<P>
   I have my doubts, but that's what we face because no number of
the varied punishment choices, all fueled or opposed by spectrum
politics, will bring closure to that which is eating us alive.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just Clinton who is under pressure; it is all of us.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
