u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN06-COX     10-05 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: No change of underwear in Paris
 &HT;    By JOE MURRAY
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ I'm always happy to arrive in Paris. I'd have been even
happier if my luggage had arrived, too.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought ...?
</P>
<P>
   I got to the Houston airport in plenty of time, a couple of
hours before my plane was to leave.
</P>
<P>
   I checked in at the Continental counter and dropped off my one
piece of luggage, no problem.
</P>
<P>
   The nice lady did mention that I'd have to check in again at the
gate.
</P>
<P>
   She should have added, ''And be there extra early or ye shall
surely die.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's fault but mine. By the time I made it to the gate,
having dawdled along the way, it was still a half hour or so until
flight time, but they'd already given up on me.
</P>
<P>
   They had given my seat away, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   What can you say?
</P>
<P>
   What I said, addressing the fellow on duty at the gate, was:
</P>
<P>
   ''You little rat fink you.''
</P>
<P>
   Which was as mild a comment as I could manage under the
circumstances _ almost a term of endearment compared to what I was
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Let me give you this bit of advice if you happen to be
traveling:
</P>
<P>
   Don't go calling the guy who controls your destiny, not to
mention your luggage, a rat fink.
</P>
<P>
   At the time I didn't think much about it. Since then, I've
thought about little else _ the way his eyes narrowed and his smile
broadened.
</P>
<P>
   He found a seat for me on the plane, no problem, though it
wasn't the seat I wanted, one next to a window so that I could get
some sleep.
</P>
<P>
   It's all but impossible for me to snooze in an aisle seat. Too
much of me hangs out into the aisle, and flight attendants run amok
keep running into me with their food carts.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. You can't have everything if you're flying coach.
Maybe having your luggage on the same flight is too much to expect.
</P>
<P>
   I think they knew it all the time. Even as the plane was
touching down in Paris, there was an on-board announcement for
''Mr. Moo-ree'' to check at the baggage pickup area ... ''for a big
surprise,'' they well could have added.
</P>
<P>
   Right away I should have smelled a rat fink.
</P>
<P>
   No luggage, no explanation. A nice lady gave me a claim check,
and I gave her my hotel address.
</P>
<P>
   She promised I would hear from them as soon as she found out
something. Never mind that she was taking off for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   I spent much of that afternoon and the next day trying to phone
the number I'd been given to check on my luggage and the lack
thereof.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the line was busy. Sometimes nobody answered.
Sometimes I would get a fax signal.
</P>
<P>
   One time a nice lady actually answered, told me to hold on while
she checked and then, evidently, took off for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two hours later my bag finally caught up with me. That's
a long time between changes of underwear. Say la vee. When in
France, do as the French do.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ha-ha, I'm only kidding when I say that the little
guy at the gate in Houston purposely misrouted my luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would be so cruel.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody but a rat fink.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is
</P>
<P>
   senior writer for Cox Newspapers.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
