<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9576 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELL-WANDERS06-COX     10-05 2010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELL-WANDERS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Her story on a note pad:Abuse and, ultimately, abandonment
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There she sat, on the bench in the rain, a new suitcase at her
feet. She looked so very curious that all the Wal-Mart shoppers
couldn't help but stare at her just a little, with a sideways
glance, of course.
</P>
<P>
   She was wearing a pretty jumper, and she sat perched on the
metal seat for a long time _ by some accounts for four hours. She
clutched a doll close to her chest and rocked back and forth. She
put her head down, then swung it back, either in wild abandon or
mental unrest, no one was quite sure which; and it wasn't exactly
like scores of folks were stopping by to find out, to say howdy do.
</P>
<P>
   The first to approach her, really approach her, was Pat Beach,
an assistant manager at the fancy Wal-Mart up in Jupiter (it has a
McDonald's). She saw the woman about 2 o'clock when she went out
for a cigarette break, then again about an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she's waiting for a ride home, Beach thought. Or the bus.
</P>
<P>
   But about midafternoon a shopper, a woman, approached Beach as
she was making her rounds on the Wal-Mart floor. The shopper was
worried about the woman sitting outside, alone, rocking, holding a
doll. It was raining!
</P>
<P>
   So Beach walked right out there into the warm Sunday afternoon
Florida drizzle and stood in front of the curious woman.
</P>
<P>
   And she asked her flat out: ``Are you all right?''
</P>
<P>
   The woman lowered her head, practically all the way into her
lap, and shook her head no.
</P>
<P>
   And that's when Beach called the police.
</P>
<P>
   For the next six or seven hours, indeed until 11 o'clock that
night, police and state workers and even kind-hearted Pat Beach
checked out every little detail, every little hint of truth, they
could draw from this woman who seemed to appear from nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   They checked out the sister she said might live in Fort
Lauderdale and the four siblings she said she had, three of them
with the last name of Briggs. Police called every Briggs in the
phone book.
</P>
<P>
   They explored the possibility she was the woman reported missing
earlier that day from Cabana Colony, an older neighborhood just
north of The Gardens mall.
</P>
<P>
   They called some guy who graduated from Jupiter High School a
few years back because someone said they thought the man had a
mentally handicapped sister.
</P>
<P>
   Dead end, again and again.
</P>
<P>
   The harder they worked, the more confused _ and worried _ they
became.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really had us going,'' says Jupiter detective Amy
Facchine.
</P>
<P>
   The clear signs of thought
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter police officer Brent R. Hoosaccq was the first
official-type person to meet the woman that Sunday in August. By
then Beach had taken her inside, out of the rain, and into the
manager's office where everyone learned in quick fashion that, good
grief, this woman couldn't talk.
</P>
<P>
   She was either autistic or mute, they ventured _ no one was
certain which.
</P>
<P>
   She had a wallet with $750 inside, much of it in $100 bills, but
no I.D. She had a CD player. She had a suitcase with a pillow and a
blanket and all new clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in that suitcase was brand new,'' Beach says.
``Everything.''
</P>
<P>
   But the police officer and the Wal-Mart assistant manager forged
ahead. At one point, some teenagers who work at the store and know
sign language stepped in and tried to communicate with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so proud of our staff that day,'' Beach says now.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually everyone realized that even though this woman
couldn't speak, she could do a couple of other interesting things _
and she could do them well.
</P>
<P>
   She had a good mind. She could think, that was for sure.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, every time this woman wanted to talk she would grab a
note pad right off the Wal-Mart manager's desk and write down her
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Things like: Mommy takes pictures of me and abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time we knew she could write,'' Beach says.
</P>
<P>
   That was also the first time police realized they might have
another kind of a problem on their hands. They called state social
workers.
</P>
<P>
   And she could draw like nobody's business. The character in the
Garfield cartoon strip. Winnie the Pooh. The Disney characters from
Space Jam.
</P>
<P>
   The woman spent the entire day at the pretty Wal-Mart in
Jupiter. She had some McDonald's hamburgers _ on the house. She
walked the floor with Pat Beach, the only person she'd open up to.
Word spread quickly, and all the service personnel at Wal-Mart were
worried sick about the mentally ill autistic woman apparently
abandoned outside their store. Another assistant manager even
reported to work so Beach could spend more time with the mystery
woman, befriend her, draw her out bit by bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person who established any significant communication
with her was Pat,'' Hoosac later wrote in his report.
</P>
<P>
   It was Beach who got the woman's name. What a coup that was!
</P>
<P>
   A name and then two
</P>
<P>
   Her name was Sachel Briggs.
</P>
<P>
   Briggs said she had four brothers and sisters. She told Beach
she'd been to Seattle and Washington and Paris. She told her she
was born at a military base in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``We even got out the map,'' Beach says. She said her father was
dead. Her mother abused her. Her stepfather was an alcoholic. But
whenever any of the investigators got too close, Briggs would
retreat. She'd beat her head against the wall or hide under a desk
and refuse to come out.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, though, when Beach went outside to have a
cigarette and Briggs went with her, they sat on the curb outside
the store and the woman, through motions and written words, said
she'd been dropped off there _ abandoned _ by someone in a red van.
</P>
<P>
   By your brother? Beach asked.
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   Your sister? Your father?
</P>
<P>
   No. No.
</P>
<P>
   Your mother? The woman nodded, emphatically, Yes!
</P>
<P>
   State officials took the woman away that night, to a safe place
where she could sleep, and they called in one of their best case
workers, a veteran with a knack for pulling the truth out of abuse
victims. Thus began the rather frantic, and costly, task of
figuring out just who this woman was and what should be done with
her.
</P>
<P>
   Facchine spent hours tracking every tip, big and small. She
attended meetings called to decide what to do for the woman. She
tracked leads with out-of-state calls. She tried to get close to
her. Nothing panned out.
</P>
<P>
   But within a week or so, pieces of the truth began to emerge,
and they were all rather curious.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out Sachel Briggs was not autistic.
</P>
<P>
   Sachel Briggs was not abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Sachel Briggs was a little smarter _ a lot smarter, really _
than they had first thought.
</P>
<P>
   Sachel Briggs wasn't even Sachel Briggs.
</P>
<P>
   She was a woman named Vicky Lynn Bell who had been reported
missing from a group home in Asheville, N.C., about a week earlier.
She'd signed out to take the bus to Wal-Mart _ there are two in
Asheville _ and had never come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Bell? She's a very nice lady,'' says Stan Bradley, who
runs the Haywood Heights home in west Asheville, where the woman
had last lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very artistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, at least that part was true.
</P>
<P>
   'She's a wanderer'
</P>
<P>
   Vicky Lynn Bell, who they believe turned 40 last January, likes
to move around, says Stan Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if she likes the attention or what,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a wanderer,'' says Colleen Bradley, Stan's wife, who
helps run the group home in Asheville. ``I think she likes that
type of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradleys first met Vicky Lynn Bell this past June, when
someone from the state psychiatric hospital called to say they had
a possible client for them. It was Bell. The Bradleys say Bell has
no known relatives in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Bell took up residence at the group home and made friends in
quick fashion. The most amazing thing about her was her artwork. It
was beautiful. In fact, Stan Bradley's sister-in-law paid Bell to
draw the Winnie the Pooh characters, which she had framed. The
drawing is hanging on her children's bedroom wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just super,'' Bradley said about the painting. ``I was
really impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   But during the six weeks Bell lived at Haywood Heights, she
turned up missing twice. The first time, she signed herself out to
go to the Belecq Cherecq festival, an arts and crafts event in
Asheville. She planned to sell her artwork, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Vicky Lynn Bell wound up in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities there traced her back to Asheville, Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They called and said she wanted to come back,'' he remembers.
``So they put her on a bus.''
</P>
<P>
   When a worker from Bradley's home went to pick Bell up at the
Asheville bus station, ``she wasn't there,'' he said. She'd gotten
off. Somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Within days, authorities called from Boston; they had Bell. This
time, Bradley was more careful. He had authorities put her on an
airplane. He drove more than two hours to Atlanta to pick her up.
</P>
<P>
   Vicky Lynn Bell was back home in Asheville _ until the end of
August when she signed herself out to go to Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later she sat, uttering no sounds, in the rain
outside Wal-Mart. Wal-Mart in Jupiter. Investigators think she sold
her artwork to pay her way here and give herself cash in her
wallet.
</P>
<P>
   A final, accented twist
</P>
<P>
   The woman now known as Vicky Lynn Bell refused written requests
from The Palm Beach Post for an interview. And Florida state social
workers would not discuss Bell's case or release any details of
their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   According to public records, the Social Security number given
for Vicky Lynn Bell is actually registered to a Tiffany R. Adams, a
woman who goes by several other names. The Social Security number
was issued in 1975 in Columbia, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say she remains in the area,'' said Pam Heyer, with the
Florida Department of Children and Families, who refused all other
comment about Bell, citing confidentiality issues.
</P>
<P>
   And Pat Beach? She found out just the other day all about the
woman she befriended that steamy August day. Her feelings were
bruised, but just a bit, because she figures the woman needed help.
And she was glad to have provided it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My emotions ran very high that day,'' Beach said. ``It was
quite the ordeal. But I think she was reaching out for attention,
and that's how I'm going to look at this. That's how I have to look
at this.''
</P>
<P>
   But before we say goodbye to the saga of Vicky Lynn Bell, here's
one last interesting tidbit, one last turn:
</P>
<P>
   She can talk up a storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a very nice British accent,'' says Stan Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other times she left here, she didn't talk for a while,''
he said. ``I don't know if she's being cute, or what.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that state paperwork in North Carolina does not
classify Bell as either autistic or schizophrenic. He says she has
some ``mental issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not a bad person, she's really not. She just kind of
gets out and then forgets where she's supposed to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has her good days and her bad days but, hell, who out
there doesn't?''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Facchine said they got an inkling not too long ago
that Bell could talk. Bell was standing outside the group home
where she's living now _ she wants to stay in Florida and
authorities are obliging _ and a dog ran into the street.
Apparently, Bell hollered for the dog to get out of the road,
Facchine said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is a little strange,'' said Facchine, who
closed out her part of the investigation late last month after it
became clear that the woman was not abandoned or autistic or
abused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to the fact that Bell has deceived investigators regarding
her identity, family, resident address and mental stability, the
investigation into possible abuse physically, mentally and sexually
has been unfounded,'' Facchine wrote. ``There is no evidence to
substantiate any charge of the aforementioned. This case closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Vicky Lynn Bell wanders off again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
