<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The rules -- moving and boxing version
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget therapy and self-help books. People would lead better,
happier, more responsible lives if they put their stuff in boxes
more often.
</P>
<P>
   Simple, I know. But it cannot be denied.
</P>
<P>
   This might be the only good thing to come out of term limits. A
public servant who has to cart his stuff out of an office and put
his plaques in boxes every so often is a person who knows where
he's been. A person who will be more careful of paper in the
future. A person who, with a clean conscience, can tell the special
prosecutor he threw out those documents in the move. All of which
is sure to work for the betterment of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't even matter if you move after boxing, the boxing is
what counts. If for some perverse reason, you were to put
everything you own in a stack of boxes, then turned around and
unpack, you'd be a changed person for the effort. I promise. And a
good thing, too, because a person who would do something like that
could stand some serious changing.
</P>
<P>
   I recently launched into this task with abandon. I attempted to
apply with steely ruthless resolve the
Did-You-Take-It-Out-Of-The-Box-From-The-Last-Move? Rule, and the
even more rigorous
Did-You-Touch-Or-Use-Or-Read-This-Object-In-The-Last-Year? Rule.
</P>
<P>
   No more boxes of mystery parts, no carting the spent shells of
dead and dying batteries from place to place, no more shoe boxes of
twice-stamped eighth-sandwich-free cards. This time will be
different.
</P>
<P>
   The One-Move-And-You're-Out Rule for boxes is prudent and easy
enough. But like all simple rules, it attracts unexpected
complications that lurk in the shadows intent on mugging it.
</P>
<P>
   How about the box of Christmas stuff, for instance? Special
dispensation for seasonal items. How about the box of audio cable,
computer connectors and telephone line? Any one of those things
could transform a person into an audiovisual hero. Special
dispensation for technology. Box of baseball cards? Special
dispensation for objects of great value. Bearlike objects? Same
loophole.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the One-Year Rule that can really change your life. It
forces you to face the fact that barring disease, famine or general
shrinkage, those jeans will never fit you again. That barring
unemployment, illness or long-term loss of electric power, you will
never read Proust or ``Lee's Lieutenants.'' That a frying pan is an
overrated item in the age of microwavable burritos.
</P>
<P>
   The One-Year Rule is a harsh master. But fair.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for its hard dictates, the One-Year Rule grants
freedom from box-hefting, freedom from closet overflows and best of
all, the illusions of a simpler life and new start.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the older you get, the harder it is to follow such a
mandate. It's destructive of the past and when you earned some past
it should not be considered too disposable. The rule presumes you
knew, at some time in the year past, what was worthwhile in your
home. At least among things that can fit in a box. This is not
always the case even in a good year. Especially in a good year.
</P>
<P>
   And it is incompatible with literature. Many books sit on the
shelf just to compliment you for actually having read them at one
time. Others earn their space on the shelf for reminding you of
what you intend to read someday. The One-Year-Rule would devastate
libraries.
</P>
<P>
   I tried the One-Year Rule on the bookshelves and filled two
boxes with exceptions. By the third box I had thought of a good
half-dozen corollaries, exceptions and clarifications to the
One-Year Rule. I realized this inventiveness is wasted outside of
government work, tax law and accounting, but I was determined to be
consistent. At least for one more box.
</P>
<P>
   The One-Year-Rule is yielding fast to the pressures of packing.
I've given up all pretense of procedural fairness and use it only
to indict objects I don't like. The cat-scratch post? A failed
experiment the cat uses only to mock me. It hasn't been touched in
a year. It's history. The painted macaroni picture frame? Silently
condemned. But as for the rest, I'm afraid it will be boxed and
hefted again.
</P>
<P>
   The weight of the past is no metaphor. It's a workout. I do this
enough times and I'm certain to be in shape to deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
