r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETWATCH06-COX     10-05 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scandal coverage doesn't leave Salon a cut above
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh Salon, we hardly knew ye.
</P>
<P>
   No one can blame the editors of the online-only magazine at
http://www.salonmagazine.com for trying to expand its reporting
into the Beltway. In fact, it was Salon's coverage of the Monica
Lewinsky scandal that helped put the e-zine on the map. However, in
its quest for glory, page views and column inches, Salon may have
gone just one step too far.
</P>
<P>
   Salon is a magazine of literature, arts, culture and politics
that has been steadily gaining a loyal readership and attracting
top-notch writers from some of the best alternative and mainstream
media outlets in the county.
</P>
<P>
   Salon articles have been known to circulate via e-mail and hard
copy from friends to co-workers and back again. Loyal readers even
print out articles on everything from Caroline Knapp's essay on
living alone, to Lori Leibovich's twisted take on the MTV awards
and Tom Mashberg's essay sifting through the ashes of The Boston
Globe's Mike Barnicle scandal. The weekly feature ``Mothers Who
Think'' is also one of the site's most popular draws for its smart
and witty takes on motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems that for Salon, good writing read by smart people
was not enough. Salon began to cover politics in the same smart,
sassy style as the rest of the magazine and although some
considered its coverage too pro-Clinton, the same could be said of
many other publications. But everything changed several weeks ago
when the magazine decided to publish an account of Rep. Henry
Hyde's (R-Ill.) affair, some 30 years ago. The story, and the
accompanying editorial from Salon Editor David Talbot made a media
splash of epic proportions.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Salon was that the article drew attention to
the already well-respected magazine. The bad news is that the price
might have been too high. There were those who questioned the
relevance of the story, including the magazine's Washington bureau
chief, Jonathan Broder. Broder, 50, was quoted saying the Hyde
story made the magazine look like ````sex-obsessed hypocrites.''
Broder also called the C-SPAN call-in show Washington Journal to
further enunciate his position. ``There were no public issues
involved. Henry Hyde did not have this woman on his staff, on his
payroll. She was not a foreign agent. She did not go public with
her affair and she didn't sue him for sexual misconduct, so there
was no public issue involved, which I think has to be a standard
journalists use when deciding to write these things.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this sat well with Talbot, Salon's editor, who demanded
and got Broder's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot argues that Broder had to go. ``There are people trying
to shut down Salon because they don't like what we're publishing.
... The last thing we needed was for our Washington correspondent
to add fuel to that fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Broder shot back saying that Salon went with the Hyde story and
much of its Clinton coverage in an attempt to attract readers. ``A
lot of people have determined that sex sells,'' Broder said
Tuesday. ``(Talbot) made a decision that that's where he wants to
take Salon. That's where the money is ... I just don't want to go
there with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Salon's debacle is about the fate of Web journalism as much as
it is about politics. Any Internet analyst will tell you that when
it comes to the Web, sex does sell. Who can blame Talbot for
manipulating current events to draw readers to his Web site where
all you do is read.
</P>
<P>
   Talbot would argue that he's just trying to generate visits, the
online version of publishers saying they're just trying to sell
papers. Broder, the online journalist, found himself caught between
a publisher's desire to grab readers and his own personal code of
journalistic ethics. It's an unpleasant economic reality, but a
reality, nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   What will ultimately happen to Salon? Talbot says he wants to
shift the magazine's focus from cultural and arts reporting to
breaking news, which will surely be a disappointment to loyal
readers. But the scandals surrounding the Salon scandal coverage
may have left the magazine something a little less than it once
was. As Broder put it, ``I think that (the Clinton scandal) is a
very ugly story and very smelly. And anyone who touches it ends up
smelling bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
