A9584 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OKEECHOBEE-MUD06-COX     10-05 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKEECHOBEE-MUD06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wall of muck threatens lake's fish
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 5 miles offshore in Lake Okeechobee, Don Fox leaped from
his skiff onto a beachhead of muck, cattails and scrabbly willow.
</P>
<P>
   At its edge, the mud squished underfoot, threatening to fall
away into the water. Finding a stable spot, Fox plunged a white
measuring stick down to the bottom of the muck pile: 4 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been watching this build up for three years,'' said Fox,
a biological administrator for the Florida Game and Fresh Water
Fish Commission. And more raw material arrives every minute, on
waves carrying silt and grasses.
</P>
<P>
   Bad news, Fox said: ``The lake is forming a new edge.'' A new
bank inside the old one.
</P>
<P>
   What's rising, he said, is a berm 35 to 40 miles long near the
lake's western shore, roughly from Okeechobee to Clewiston. Fifteen
to 70 feet across, it threatens to form an impenetrable wall
between the lake's open water and the shoreline marshes that
provide breeding grounds for fish.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said the berm eventually could turn the marshes into
hardwood swamps, eliminating the fish nurseries and the economy
they support.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and South Florida water managers largely agree on the cause:
Four years of unusually high lake levels have uprooted enormous
stretches of the plants in the marshes _ bulrushes, eel grass,
pepper grass and hydrilla. Waves have mixed the plants with silt
from the lake's bottom, creating the berm.
</P>
<P>
   They don't agree on what to do about it, however.
</P>
<P>
   Fox wants to remove the berm as soon as possible. But Barry
Rosen, a senior scientist at the South Florida Water Management
District, said researchers first must study the berm to make sure
removing it wouldn't cause more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't predict the costs, but said the studies would take a
year or more.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said scientists don't know exactly what the berm is made
of, its precise location, how fast it is expanding or whether it
will fall apart naturally. He said it's possible the berm is no
worse in blocking fish than the thick cattail stands that already
crowded the marshes' edges.
</P>
<P>
   And removing the wall could allow the silt, loaded with
phosphorus, to penetrate the marshes' depths, he said. Phosphorus,
found in manure and fertilizers, already is blamed for cattails'
invasion of the marshes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want any unintended consequences,'' Rosen said. ``If
you took (the berm) out and all of a sudden allowed this
phosphorus-rich water to go into the pristine parts of the marsh
where the fish are breeding, and all of a sudden you had cattails
there, I'd say you blew it.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that such berms often form and dissolve naturally,
and this one may be no different. Fox has little patience for such
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something we need to study to death,'' Fox said.
``That's one of the problems with the district _ research,
research, research.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kissimmee solution
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he advocates a cleanup similar to one that the
district, game commission and other agencies paid for two years ago
in Osceola County, where a berm had built up around Lake Kissimmee.
For $5 million, crews lowered water levels, scraped 24 miles of
shoreline and burned 9,900 acres of cattails and other weeds.
</P>
<P>
   The sediments will keep accumulating, requiring periodic
removal, game commission project leader Mike Hulon said. But he
said the results are worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fish have moved back to zones where they haven't been in 10
years,'' Hulon said. ``A lot of old anglers are saying this is back
to the way the lake used to look.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox acknowledged that natural forces are creating the berm,
aided by the water district, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and
the federally built dike that encircles Lake Okeechobee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death is a natural process,'' Fox said. ``But when you put a
gun to someone's head and pull the trigger, you've helped the
process along.''
</P>
<P>
   Water managers and the corps, which jointly manage Lake
Okeechobee, mostly blame rain for the high water levels that have
troubled it since 1995. But they also fault their water supply
system, which uses the lake as a 730-square-mile reservoir and
often keeps it high as a hedge against drought.
</P>
<P>
   When the corps releases water, it flows down the St. Lucie and
Caloosahatchee rivers _ slowly lowering the lake but quickly
upsetting those waterways' ecological balance.
</P>
<P>
   `It's a mudhole out there'
</P>
<P>
   Last winter and spring, those releases devastated coastal
fishing and tourism. Some scientists suspect that lake water also
caused a plague of lesion-covered fish in the St. Lucie and Indian
rivers.
</P>
<P>
   The lake has suffered just as much from the high water, and both
the berm and the vanishing marshes are proof, Fox said. For
instance, bulrush _ worth $20,000 an acre in its value as fish
habitat _ has lost 96 percent of the 8,800 acres it occupied four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said earlier berms have risen during episodes of high water,
but this one never subsided. He said he has seen it rise more than
a foot in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The berm also alarms Wayne Nelson, a West Palm Beach sport
fisherman and environmentalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the result of 25 years of mismanagement of the
lake,'' Nelson said, endorsing Fox's call for quick action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lake is in the worst shape I've ever seen,'' he said.
``It's a mudhole out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other fishermen, Nelson is skeptical of the theory
that high water killed the marshes. He blames the district, which
sprays herbicides on water hyacinths and other aquatic weeds.
</P>
<P>
   District officials insist they only spray about 6,000 acres a
year, too small a territory to cause such a massive die-off. In any
case, the district passed its spraying duties to the corps
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The corps also is studying a district proposal to keep the lake
lower year-round _ a solution to the woes ailing both the lake and
the rivers.
</P>
<P>
   As for the berm, ``Let's do either one of two things,'' Fox
said. ``Either take it out or plant cypress trees on it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Or condos,'' Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
