<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 10:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9585 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANT-KILLERS06-COX     10-05 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANT-KILLERS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Water district to quit touting plants it kills
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   South Florida water managers spend millions of dollars killing
foreign plants that invade the region.
</P>
<P>
   They also publish a booklet that lists some of those same plants
as examples of water-conserving landscaping.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the water managers say it makes lots of sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should promote plants that we're killing,''
said Dan Thayer, who heads the eradication of invasive weeds for
the South Florida Water Management District.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the district is set to become vegetatively correct. A
new plant guide due in early 1999 will spread the message that the
Australian pine, Brazilian pepper and about 30 other leafy
ne'er-do-wells are flora non grata.
</P>
<P>
   The invaders have few if any enemies in Florida, allowing them
to spread fast and overtake native plants.
</P>
<P>
   State law banned the sale and cultivation of the Australian pine
and Brazilian pepper in 1990. But that information was slow to
trickle into the district's guide to drought-hardy trees, grasses,
vines and shrubs, last updated in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The guide has been slower to include warnings about legal plants
many scientists consider noxious, such as the popular carrotwood
and guava trees.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations among scientists, native-plant advocates,
landscapers and other water management districts have delayed the
booklet's new edition, district water conservation coordinator
Bruce Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all learning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said the guide was meant only to offer information on the
growth, nutritional requirements and water demand of 595 species
that are common in urban landscaping. But the problems began when
some residents interpreted it incorrectly as the district's stamp
of approval.
</P>
<P>
   Even some city governments have tried to adopt the guide as a
list of endorsed plants, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like a Bible of plants,'' Adams said. ``It has some
of the nasties in there because people have those on their
property.''
</P>
<P>
   Thayer, past president of the nonprofit Florida Exotic Pest
Plant Council, said the guide has blunted his attempts to warn
residents about the invaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say, `That carrotwood in your yard is a bad plant,' ''
Thayer said. ``But they'll say, `I got it as a recommendation from
your agency. It's in the guide.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the district has spent $1.7 million killing plants
listed in the guide, with the great bulk of that money going to
Australian pines and Brazilian peppers.
</P>
<P>
   The guide's original version in 1987 also included the
district's No. 1 plant enemy, the melaleuca tree, which has cost
$9.7 million to kill. But in the 1991 version, all melaleuca
information is crossed out to make it illegible.
</P>
<P>
   The '91 guide likewise crosses out information on the Australian
pine and Brazilian pepper _ but only under the heading of
``trees.'' The shrub section still includes full data on both
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The district has printed 12,000 to 50,000 guides each year at a
cost of 55 to 72 cents a copy, ending in 1995, Adams said. It has
about 2,500 copies left and is still distributing them.
</P>
<P>
   The new guide will stamp the pest plants with a warning, and
won't include information on how to grow them, Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be full out that this is a problem plant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer's staff originally called for deleting all mention of the
invaders. But he said now he thinks it's better to teach people
about their dangers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, scientists and landscapers are debating which plants to
label pests. Adams said the negotiations became even more
complicated because the new guide is meant to apply statewide, not
just in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, some species are fast-spreading pests near Miami
but not near Orlando or Jacksonville, where frost controls them.
Some varieties of oyster plant or yellow lantana can crowd out
native plants, but others don't.
</P>
<P>
   The latest proposal lists 33 plants as pests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's make sure we have a scientific basis for this list, not
just a thorn in someone's side,'' said Hugh Gramling of the Tampa
Bay Wholesale Growers Association, who has reviewed the proposed
list. ``Just because a few people say these plants are invasive
does not make them so.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
