A9586 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN06-COX     10-05 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: A generation distrustful of government
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ When I was 7 I knew little of government. FDR
was president and the nation was up to its patriotic neck in World
War II. I'd never heard of politics.
</P>
<P>
   I knew that on Tuesdays I took a dime to school to buy ``war
stamps'' and when I had enough to fill up my book, I could trade it
in for a war bond. I knew that our neighbor, Mr. Sanders, was the
air raid warden for our block, and that Mrs. Albrecht's son, Billy,
had traded in his Ohio State football uniform for one of Uncle
Sam's.
</P>
<P>
   I learned from the movies that America was fighting on the side
of right and our enemies on both sides of the world were godless
warmongers. I knew that when John Wayne wasn't flying P-40s
(``Flying Tigers''), he was building runways on Pacific Ocean
atolls (``The Fighting Seabees'').
</P>
<P>
   And when I sang ``America the Beautiful'' in the elementary
school choir, I believed every last word of it, particularly the
part about being crowned with ``brotherhood from sea to shining
sea.''
</P>
<P>
   I was 7. I trusted my country. I trusted my president. It may
have been the last of an era.
</P>
<P>
   My 31-year-old son never had it so good. We were talking this
morning over breakfast, about the mess in Washington. I listened
and learned. Here's what he had to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the extramarital affair that bothers me the most,
though after watching the demise of my parents' marriage for the
very same reason, I confess to being sensitized to the wretchedness
of the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the lying that bothers me, either. In fact, growing
up in the late '60s and early '70s pretty much taught me one thing
_ politicians are liars, period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my first memories about politics are of Walter
Cronkite with that little icon of the White House behind his left
shoulder, disseminating the events of Watergate on the evening
news. The first president I ever knew was a liar. Is there another
kind, I wondered?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first movie about politics that I remember was a rerun of
`The Candidate' starring Robert Redford. Besides looking an awful
lot like my dad, Redford's character appealed to me because he came
across as a common guy in an uncommon situation. He didn't pretend
to have all of the answers. Most of all, he lacked the
slick-politician persona and the ability to alter his stance to
suit the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won the election, and I remember thinking to myself: Wow!
The good guys do win once in a while. But apparently that's only in
the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too much later there was Iran-contra, complete with a
sitting president lying about his involvement, his underlings
wrapping themselves in the flag and claiming innocence, and the
vice president, his successor, toeing the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though our history books tell us of the privilege and honor of
serving our country, I was left with the impression that folks get
into politics not out of a sense of duty to their fellow men but
simply for the power and money that come with the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``What bothers me most about this mess in Washington is the
president's lapse of common sense and amazingly poor judgment in
his choice of a `femme fatale.' It's tough to believe that a Rhodes
scholar couldn't see that `the stalker,' as her cohorts called her,
might not be the best choice for a discreet affair.
</P>
<P>
   This begs the question: What can Americans expect of his
judgment when he's making decisions regarding policy or military
action for our country?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not suggesting that the lure of a political victory is as
desirable an accomplishment to our president as having sex with an
intern, but how do we know at this point? Will he, in a grand
effort to clean up his past, make a truly shortsighted and
ill-advised decision that could have drastic effects on the
country? Does our nation run the risk of one day being blindsided
by the
</P>
<P>
   consequences of his inability to focus on anything other than
the conquest at hand?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I'm disappointed, but not surprised. Aside from all of
this, he's pretty much acting like any other 20th-century
politician.''
</P>
<P>
   My son talks, and I listen. And as I do, I can't help thinking
what a sad commentary this is on the legacy my generation has left
him. But what else might we expect from a generation who teethed on
Watergate?
</P>
<P>
   When he finishes, I can't help asking: ``Are you a Democrat or a
Republican?''
</P>
<P>
   His answer: ``I'm a GDI.''
</P>
<P>
   I can understand why.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett, a writer and teacher, writes for Cox News
Service. Her e-mail address is: eschuett(at)nwonline.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
