<HEADER>
A9589 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSIDE-PRISON06-COX     10-05 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSIDE-PRISON06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From inside: Anger creates violent culture
 &HT;    By Jorge Antonio Renaud
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editor's note: Jorge Antonio Renaud, 41, is serving a 60-year
sentence at the Wynne prison unit in Huntsville for aggravated
robbery. Renaud was convicted in 1992 of robbing a Mr. Gatti's
restaurant and a Jack Brown Cleaners in Austin, a crime spree he
said was driven by a cocaine habit. He was working at the time as a
copy editor at the Austin American-Statesman. He becomes eligible
for parole in 2006.
</P>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ In 1977, when I first came to prison, the
convict code demanded that my courage be tested. The task fell to
my homeboys. I had seven fights my first day at Ferguson, the
gladiator unit, where inmates 21 years old and younger were
assigned.
</P>
<P>
   I left prison in late 1979 and returned in seven months, to stay
for seven years. Violence escalated dramatically in the mid-1980s
as convicts warred over the spoils left unclaimed when the building
tender system was dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   In August of 1984, my neighbor was stabbed to death on the run
(the hallway outside cells). As I mopped the blood that seeped into
my cell, I composed a poem for Tattoo, whose murder was the 12th in
what would prove a record-setting year for Texas prison homicides.
</P>
<P>
   I left again in 1987 and this time didn't return until 1992. I'd
heard the system had changed. An improved guard-to-inmate ratio had
allowed a clampdown on gang activities. New building
configurations, designed to provide officers unimpeded views of
living quarters, supposedly allowed guards to closely monitor
convicts and respond quickly to disturbances. I expected stricter
but quieter prisons.
</P>
<P>
   I was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, a man with whom I was sharing a cup of cocoa was almost
stabbed to death. His assailant chased him around the day room,
slashing whenever he was within reach. The guards, dozens strong,
stayed in the hall and lobbed gas canisters and insults at us with
equally ineffectual results, intervening only when another convict
snatched the shank away.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a man staggered past me, a 20-cent black pen dangling
from his punctured right eyeball, as rival Hispanic factions _ not
organized gangs, but homeboy groups called ``tangos'' _ rioted on
the Robertson Unit yard. I've seen three racially motivated riots _
Hispanics against blacks.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen innumerable shockingly brutal incidents erupt over the
most trivial insults, and sometimes for no reason other than to get
an inmate off the wing in order to burglarize his cell. I've seen
dozens upon dozens of Anglos broken _ forced to pay cash or provide
sex to stop the beatings they endured daily _ in what seems a
savage payback for the sins of all Anglos.
</P>
<P>
   Prisons are violent arenas. Brutality rarely hides its face
here. But violence in Texas prisons used to be predictable and,
thus, avoidable. You stayed away from drugs and alcohol; you kept
your mouth shut and minded your own business; you demonstrated a
willingness to defend yourself _ and you were allowed to do your
time in relative peace.
</P>
<P>
   This is no longer true. Violence in Texas prisons is so
mindlessly pervasive and its effects so widespread that the
inevitable has happened _ a group of released convicts are charged
with an act so atrocious that it has focused a spotlight on Texas
Department of Criminal Justice conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The response by officials has been depressingly familiar: Give
us more money, and we'll identify the most vicious predators and
build more ``Super Max'' units to bury them in.
</P>
<P>
   This is absurd. You can't lock away 100,000 convicts, and that
is what it would take. Criminal Justice officials _ especially
those watching the gangs _ are too quick to blame prison gangs for
all prison violence, and for the recent murder in Jasper in
particular. Their reasoning runs like this: The three ex-convicts
charged in that incident sported racist tattoos. They were
therefore in a prison gang, or affiliated, and they were simply
practicing what racist prison gangs preach.
</P>
<P>
   This is a dangerous oversimplification. The problem does not lie
primarily with gangs, at least not those identified by the Texas
Department of Criminal Justice. The problem is a huge influx of
young convicts with unimaginably long sentences, who are angry and
afraid and all too willing to band together in groups with racial
or geographical bonds. They cloak their despair in rage, and they
act out that rage on anyone not of their group.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting violence feeds the animosity of others, many of
whom have shorter sentences and carry their hate to the free world.
</P>
<P>
   Racial animosities in prison are intractable and deadly. If
racism is so tangible, so pervasive in the free world that the
country's president feels compelled to appoint a commission to
offer suggestions, how terrible must it be where society consigns
its deadliest men?
</P>
<P>
   And the system has no idea how to deal with it, other than to
integrate its cells and dorms willy-nilly, with only a cursory
attempt to classify convicts. In Texas prisons, the only way to
avoid integration is to stab someone of a different race. You can
tell officials that you are a stone-cold racist; you can have
hideously racist tattoos from head to toe; you can have a
documented history of having participated in racially motivated
riots _ but if the system orders you into a 9-by-12-foot cell with
a man of the race you detest, you must comply or lose class and
good time and privileges.
</P>
<P>
   Such forced intimacy does little but magnify negative
stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-10-04-98 1947E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
