<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9595 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASALLE-SHIP06-COX     10-05 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASALLE-SHIP06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Search to continue for LaSalle's flagship
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Two groups unsuccessful in their quest to find
the long-lost flagship of the French explorer LaSalle announced
that they have joined forces in a renewed search.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Texas Historical Commission and the
National Underwater Marine Agency, a private maritime history group
based in Austin, said their joint venture in waters off Port
O'Connor is the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, state archaeologists unearth history themselves. They
sometimes issue search permits to qualified groups such as the
marine agency, but officials said they cannot remember a joint
search being mounted to find a shipwreck.
</P>
<P>
   Six new underwater ``targets'' _ places where magnetic mapping
shows a concentration of metal that could be the site of l'Aimable
_ have been identified. Specially trained divers could begin
investigating them as soon as today, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery of the wreckage of l'Aimable, which ran aground and
sank in 1685, could provide new clues about Texas' earliest
settlers _ indeed, among the earliest settlers in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking for l'Aimable since 1978, and (the marine
agency) has been looking for it since last summer, so far without
success,'' said Jim Bruseth, director of antiquities protection for
the historical commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we're combining those efforts in cooperative fashion to
extend the state's limited resources and move ahead with the
search, with twice as much effort. We're excited about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gronquist, an Austin lawyer who is president of the
nonprofit marine agency, echoed those sentiments. ``We're looking
forward to getting back at the search,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun County Judge Howard Hartzog, who said his county also is
part of the joint venture signed late last week, said while the six
new targets ``look very promising,'' only a recovery and analysis
of artifacts can verify whether any are l'Aimable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important, historic shipwreck that's out there
someplace,'' he said. ``We want to find it.''
</P>
<P>
   State archaeologists and divers came up empty-handed in 20 years
of searching. But the marine agency, working under a state-issued
search permit, last year hired a Houston firm to conduct aerial
magnetic mapping of the area. That search identified 26 possible
sites.
</P>
<P>
   In February, marine agency divers recovered several
barnacle-encrusted artifacts from the murky waters at one site.
After experts tentatively identified two as 17th century French
firearms, officials on March 2 announced they had found l'Aimable,
an event that made headlines worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Aug. 2, the discovery itself ran aground: State
officials announced that further investigation proved the relic was
a Spanish ship about 100 years more recent than LaSalle's. The
firearms were Spanish, not French.
</P>
<P>
   At several points after the February discovery, tensions flared
between the marine agency and state historical officials _ about
who should announce the discovery and when, about further diving at
the site, even about whether the marine agency's permit remained in
effect for a new search after the ship was found not to be
l'Aimable.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Friday those issues have been resolved with the
joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a cooperative spirit,'' Hartzog said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
