<HEADER>
A9598 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHSCHOOL-GANGS06-CO     10-05 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHSCHOOL-GANGS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School bans red clothing
 &HT;    By Pamela Coleman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Round Rock High School administrators ordered
dozens of students wearing red clothing to change their garments
recently, after school officials prohibited wearing the color on
campus.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 students who wore the color to school were escorted to
the library, where their parents were called and told to bring
different clothing. Those who could not get new clothing were
placed in in-school suspension and told a conference would be
scheduled with their parents, said Principal Sherry Blackett.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said they are concerned about student safety
following a shooting in downtown Round Rock early Sunday that
injured two women, including a Round Rock High School sophomore,
and vandalism at the school. Police said the shooting was gang
related, but would not name the gangs involved.
</P>
<P>
   Blackett said red is a prominent color for the Bloods, Round
Rock's largest gang. However, Blackett did not explain the link
between the vandalism, the shooting and the targeting of Bloods
members or students wearing the Bloods color. ``We simply have
enforced the policy that says any clothing that has gang slogans,
symbols or colors may not be worn,'' said Blackett, who is in her
first year on the job at Round Rock High, which serves more than
3,600 students.
</P>
<P>
   Tally Tripp was among the students ordered to change clothes.
She showed up for class Friday wearing a red T-shirt,and had to
change into another shirt she uses for physical education class.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's mother said she is angered by the rule and can't afford
to buy new clothes for her daughter, whose wardrobe is largely red,
black and gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is such a lesson in absurdity _ where does this
end?'' said Cathy Brunicardi, Tripp's mother. ``If safety is really
an issue here because of colors, than get off the fence, withstand
the political firestorm and institute uniforms. We can't keep
adding colors of clothing to a banned list.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin schools do not ban any clothing based on color, said
district spokeswoman Kathy Anthony. However, other schools around
the country have tried similar bans as a way to fight gang
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Blackett, formerly a Corpus Christi administrator, said the ban
will remain in effect until those responsible for the vandalism are
identified.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Corpus Christi kids were being shot because they were
wearing someone else's color,'' she said. ``I'm asking the
community to understand the safety issue here.''
</P>
<P>
   According to police, the shooting took place at about 1 a.m.
Sunday in the 1500 block of East Main Street. After exchanging
taunts, someone in a car fired a shotgun at a group of people in
and around a parked vehicle, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-year-old woman was hit in the abdomen and chest. A
17-year-old woman was shot in the upper arm. The women, both of
Round Rock, were treated at Brackenridge Hospital and released on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Police have charged five adults and one juvenile with engaging
in organized crime to commit aggravated assault with a deadly
weapon in connection with the shooting, said Sgt. Jack Abbott of
the Round Rock Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Roman, 18; Richard Martinez, 17; Kevin Simpson, 17; George
Wheeler, 18; Bennie Zuniga Oballe III, 18; and a 15-year-old
juvenile each face a first-degree felony charge punishable by five
to 99 years or life in prison and a fine of up to $10,000. All are
from Round Rock except Simpson, who is from Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   Police said three of those arrested are known gang members.
Police have various criteria for identifying gang members
includingparticipation in criminal activity with other gang
members, the way they dress, the colors they wear and their
inclusion on gang membership lists, Abbott said. Blackett would not
say if any of the suspects were students at Round Rock High.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday or early Wednesday, vandals broke into the high
school and caused $10,000 in damage by spray painting red graffiti
in the art and gymnastics facilities, Blackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Blackett met with about 30 students wearing
predominantly red clothing and told them she would ban the color
from campus indefinitely. She later made the same announcement to
the entire student body. ''We're just enforcing the policy in the
student handbook given to every student,'' she said. The handbook
bans gang colors but does not state that red is a gang color.
</P>
<P>
   Interim School Superintendent Mike Jolly said Blackett has the
district's support. ``She's trying to head off a situation. If we
don't escalate it, I think it's going to work just fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ban has drawn the attention of the American Civil Liberties
Union, which will examine the issue on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's very inappropriate,'' said Deirdre Feehan,
litigation coordinator. ``Although we are strongly supportive of
Principal Blackett's attempt to create a safe learning environment
for the kids, we have concerns about way she's going about it.
Wearing red is not a crime and wearing red does not indicate one is
in a gang.''
</P>
<P>
   Blackett said she has received many calls thanking her for
taking the action. ``To most of the students it's no problem,'' she
said. ``A small percent have an issue with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
