r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-CUTS06-COX     10-05 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-CUTS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Insurers told to cut liability rates by 13 percent
 &HT;    By Juan B. Elizondo Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas insurers will cut 13 percent, or nearly
$700 million, from the cost of liability policies next year under
an order from the state's top insurance regulator.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the cuts will mean a $47 savings for the
average Texas driver. That's $247.4 million less for the liability
portion of Texans' auto policies _ the only auto insurance coverage
required by law.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance Commissioner Elton Bomer ordered the cuts, effective
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The reductions are the product of a 1995 law restricting the
number and types of lawsuits filed in the state, as well as the
amount of money that can be awarded to people who file
insurance-related lawsuits. In exchange for the limits on lawsuits
and damages, state legislators required insurers to share with
their customers money they save because of the changes.
</P>
<P>
   The limits on lawsuits and damages commonly are referred to as
tort reform. It's Bomer's job to determine how much insurance
companies have saved each year because of tort reform and how much
they must share with customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pure and simple, tort reform legislation has created a
tremendous savings for Texans,'' Bomer said. ``Fewer frivolous
lawsuits and multimillion-dollar judgments, along with tougher
claims-handling practices, have clearly benefited both insurers and
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Ken Hoagland, a spokesman for Texans for Lawsuit Reform,
``Our old system was rife with abuses that made barrels of money
for plaintiffs attorneys and left consumers and business paying the
bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the enactment of the 1995 tort reform law, Bomer has
ordered insurers to cut rates on seven types of liability insurance
by $2.2 billion, including next year's $697.9 million cut. Texans
and companies doing business in the state are expected to pay $5.4
billion for liability coverage next year. That would make the
$697.9 million cut a 13 percent savings.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Slivinske, a spokeswoman for the Texas Insurance
Organization, an industry group, said Bomer has overestimated the
industry's tort reform savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers benefit from a competitive market, which is the best
regulator of pricing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Johns, another industry spokesman, said Texas insurers
have gone to great lengths to not only share tort reform savings
but also to cut rates due to savings from other factors, such as an
aging population that drives fewer miles, safer cars and improved
highway construction and designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurance rates in Texas are at their lowest level in many
years,'' Johns said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dan Lambe, head of the consumer group Texas Watch, said more
cuts are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no surprise to find out insurers are saving money as a
result of changes in laws that limited their liability,'' Lambe
said. ``What is surprising is to see how the commissioner of
insurance has had to push, prod and threaten insurers before they
will do anything positive for Texas families and policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insurance companies have a long way to go in Texas before they
can claim they are responsive to Texas families.''
</P>
<P>
   D.J. Powers, an attorney for the Center for Economic Justice, an
advocate group for low-income Texans, said more cuts are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commissioner Bomer's inadequate rate reductions have thwarted
the Legislature's intent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Powers said rates for some insurance coverages have gone up
while claims have gone down, allowing companies to collect and keep
more money despite the tort reform liability cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bomer said insurers' tort-related savings have increased each
year since 1995 and that the tort-related cuts also have gone up
each year. For example, in 1996, the first year of tort reform rate
cuts, Bomer ordered insurers to reduce liability rates by $435.5
million. In 1998, the order was $656.4 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four years of tort reform will mean that more than $2 billion
has stayed in the hands of Texas policyholders,'' Bomer said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
