<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REC-CENTER06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former porn dealer opens Florida Christian rec center
 &HT;    By Paul Owers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ A Boynton Beach man whose company was sued
four years ago by Playboy Enterprises Inc. for reproducing nude
photos on a CD-ROM has formed a Christian youth group that plans to
open a recreation center in suburban Lake Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Kasanicky's Rock Youth Ministries is under contract to buy
the former Lake Worth Racquet and Swim Club at Lake Worth and
Coconut roads. The deal for the 5-acre parcel is set to close Dec.
1 for $310,000.
</P>
<P>
   Among the activities planned for the site are hockey,
basketball, skateboarding, swimming, rock climbing and
weightlifting. Middle and high school students would pay $10 a
month to use the facilities. The center, to be called The Rock, has
the backing of about 65 local businesses and churches and is
scheduled to open early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is exactly what we need to get the kids off the streets
and into a positive environment,'' Kasanicky said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Kasanicky, a 32-year-old self-employed computer consultant, said
the idea to start the nondenominational organization came to him
last year shortly after he became a Christian and wanted to
influence children.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, Kasanicky was president of Deerfield Beach-based
Starware Publishing Corp., which lost a $1.1 million judgment in
1995 to Playboy Enterprises for copyright violations and
infringement. U.S. District Judge Kenneth L. Ryskamp ruled that
Starware and Kasanicky willfully violated copyright law when they
published the CD-ROM, which contained photos of celebrities LaToya
Jackson, Kim Basinger and Jessica Hahn.
</P>
<P>
   The parties later settled, and Starware went out of business in
early 1996, Kasanicky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly was a different part of my life,'' he said. ``I
realize now that pornography is very damaging and that it's one of
the evils of our society. I've certainly undergone a lot of changes
in my life, but if you didn't know me at all, my past certainly
would be something to be concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   Those working with Kasanicky on his current venture said they're
confident he has turned his life around and believe he deserves the
opportunity to minister to youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be the first time that someone got a chance to do
something good after doing something bad,'' said Bob Giese,
president of the YMCA of the Palm Beaches and a board member of
Rock Youth Ministries.
</P>
<P>
   Giese noted that the YMCA has hired employees who have had past
personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, people just need a chance to prove themselves,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Gaffey, a Boca Raton mother of four girls, said she met
Kasanicky a few years ago after he started coming to Spanish River
Church. She said she has no qualms about letting her two oldest
daughters, Ali, 13, and Emily, 11, spend time at The Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had heard that he had dabbled in X-rated stuff,'' Gaffey
said. ``But everyone has done something. I know he's a Christian,
and Christ changes your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Evans, a retired eye surgeon and current owner of the
Lake Worth Racquet and Swim Club, said he wasn't aware of the
Playboy lawsuit but still intends to go through with the sale.
Evans bought the club in 1986 for his son. It closed two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already signed a contract,'' said Evans, a Palm City
resident. ``There's not much I can do about that. I'll just have to
see what happens and trust him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasanicky said donations from residents and local businesses and
churches helped raise the $1,000 down payment to buy the property.
The group will pay 10 percent at closing and finance the rest, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Additional plans for the center include a computer lab,
restaurant, a music studio and an auditorium for special events.
Kasanicky said he hopes to begin monthly youth meetings in
cooperation with churches.
</P>
<P>
   Donations, membership fees and food and T-shirt sales will help
finance The Rock, Kasanicky said. On Saturday, some 400 students
and adult volunteers gathered to help renovate the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done our homework,'' Kasanicky said. ``We want to reach
out to all kids and especially to those who don't know God.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
