<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MEDICARE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mental health centers facing Medicare boot
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ More than 100 of the 130 privately run community
mental health centers in Texas may be defrauding Medicare by
failing to provide all required services and could be expelled from
the program.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state officials are alarmed by the explosive growth
in the private centers. Medicare payments to the centers, whose
intensive therapy programs are supposed to keep severely mentally
ill people out of a hospital, have increased nationwide from $60
million in 1993 to $349 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some private centers around the country were using bingo games
and television as therapy sessions or serving people who were not
severely mentally ill, the inspector general of the U.S. Health and
Human Services Department, June Gibbs Brown, said this week. Twenty
centers, including seven in Texas, are being expelled from Medicare
immediately, and 60 others nationwide will be kicked out in the
next few months, federal officials said. The names of the centers
have not been released.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 private mental health centers that collect
Medicare operate across the country, with about 130 in Texas _
including one in Georgetown and one in Bastrop.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have found widespread problems in Texas but have
been hampered by their lack of authority to regulate the private
centers. Medicare is a federal program, and the state has no
jurisdiction to enforce the federal standards. There is no state
license the private centers must obtain.
</P>
<P>
   The private centers are different from the 38 public mental
health-mental retardation centers operating under contract with the
Texas Department of Mental Health and Mental Retardation. The
public centers are regulated by the state, but the private ones are
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Texas had licensure, they probably would have caught these
bogus centers,'' said Spencer McClure, executive director of the
Texas Council of Community MHMR Centers.
</P>
<P>
   After McClure raised questions about the private centers in
1996, state officials urged the federal Health Care Financing
Administration to let them review the Medicare-funded homes.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Health, which was directed by the
federal government to collect basic information from the centers
when they applied for the Medicare program, gained additional
authority in 1997 to visit each center to determine whether it
provided all programs it claimed to offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department visited 165 private centers and applicants
to the Medicare program. Only 27 of the 165 places offered the
services they claimed they provided, said Nance Stearman, director
of health facility compliance for the Texas Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unofficial estimates are that more than 100 community mental
health centers (in Texas) face termination of their Medicare
provider contract because they do not meet the federal
requirements,'' a Texas mental health department report said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Austin area, state health inspectors visited the
Williamson County Behavioral Health Center in Georgetown and the
Bastrop Behavioral Health Center. The on-site reviews found that
the Bastrop center provided all services it claimed to offer but
the Georgetown center did not, Stearman said.
</P>
<P>
   Melody Donges, a co-owner of the Georgetown center, said the
Williamson County center complies with all Medicare requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We meet the core requirements as set forth for community
mental health centers,'' she said. ``We do not do anything
fraudulent. We never have; we never will.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are providing a wonderful service in the area,'' she said.
``We don't anticipate being one of the centers being targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   A key controversy in Texas centers on the Medicare requirement
that private community mental health centers must evaluate patients
for admission to state psychiatric hospitals. That requirement
conflicts with Texas rules, which allow only the 38 public mental
health centers to perform those evaluations.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Burns, owner of the Bastrop center and a director of the
Texas Association for Behavioral Health Care, said Congress did not
intend the public MHMR centers to have exclusive power to screen
patients for state hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be better for Medicare to go after the bad guys
rather than destroying this whole industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
