<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Online publishing has a rich tradition
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Electronic books and magazines are trendy. There are more
publishers on the Web than in New York these days. But publishing a
book electronically isn't a new idea.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the biggest and most important electronic publishing
project began way back in 1971. In those days, the World Wide Web
didn't exist, 1-megabyte files were considered enormous, and
computers were reserved for professionals or hobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   It was within that context that Project Gutenberg began. A
fellow named Michael Hart was given an operator's account on the
Xerox Sigma V mainframe at the Materials Research Lab at the
University of Illinois. The notion was to create electronic texts
of documents in the public domain. Hart laboriously typed in the
text of the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Project Gutenberg is still around.
</P>
<P>
   And _ now that computer memories are enormous and high-speed
modems and data connections make it easy to transfer large files _
you can browse one of the world's largest free libraries in
electronic form from now until the end of your days and still not
read everything available. Go to http://sailor
</P>
<P>
   .gutenberg.org/by-title.html to get a notion of the range of the
titles there.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you can download and read ``The Adventures of Tom
Sawyer'' one week and come back for ``Chemical Strategy in Peace
and War'' the next.
</P>
<P>
   A browser's paradise
</P>
<P>
   Just browsing the titles can be fun. You'll find ``Cicero's
Orations'' located not far away from President Clinton's
inauguration speech. ``The Communist Manifesto'' lives as a
friendly neighbor with ``The Compleat Angler.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the documents can be downloaded to your PC in the form
of plain ASCI text (which can be read by any word processor). Or,
if you want to speed the download, you can get the document in
compressed form as a ZIP file (a program such as PKUNZIP is needed
to decompress it ... you'll find decompression programs at a site
called Shareware.Com at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .shareware.com among other places).
</P>
<P>
   Another terrific source of online books is the University of
Virginia Electronic Text Library. Besides the selection of books in
English you'll also be able to find books and documents in Chinese,
German, French, Hebrew, Latin, Russian, Spanish and the
ever-popular Tibetan and Icelandic.
</P>
<P>
   Check in with Alex
</P>
<P>
   You'll also want to drop in at the Alex Catalogue at http://
</P>
<P>
   sunsite.berkeley.edu/alex/. Like the other sites, you'll be able
to search by author or title, and you'll also find links to other
electronic libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, check out a site called Project Bartleby at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .columbia.edu/acis/bartleby/. As you can see from the address,
it's located at Columbia University's College of Education. The
selection isn't as broad here, but there are some works that seem
unique to Bartleby.
</P>
<P>
   While most of us will prefer reading the old-fashioned way,
settled comfortably in a good chair on a lazy Sunday, electronic
texts have advantages that you may overlook. For instance, if
you're a student, you'll be able to use the search features in your
word processor to find references to specific terms. And, you'll
also be able to cut and paste when you need to quote from some of
these works.
</P>
<P>
   Or, use the electronic text as a sampler. Since books can be
expensive, you can use the electronic version to take a taste of an
unfamiliar work and then decide if you want to invest in the print
edition.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
