<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-REPORT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With release of Office, what else for the Mac?
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Serivce
<TEXT>
<P>
   True to its word, Microsoft this year released a long-awaited
new version of its Office suite of applications for the Mac market.
</P>
<P>
   The suite, which includes Word and Excel, has won generally
favorable reviews, sold well and is credited with helping to boost
Apple Computer's once sagging fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   But does Office represent the extent of Microsoft's renewed
commitment to the Mac platform? Many hope not and are calling for
the world's largest software developer to make more products for
the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   The loudest and most influential voice in this rising chorus is
Don Crabb, who writes a weekly online column.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time for Mr. Jobs (Apple Computer Chief Executive Steven
Jobs) to visit Mr. Gates ... turn on his patented and effective
reality distortion field ... and convince them to start making an
across-the-board Microsoft commitment to the Mac,'' Crabb wrote in
a recent column.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, Microsoft does make a lot of Mac software now. The
list includes such important products as Internet Explorer, Word,
Excel, Front Page and a World War II simulation game called Close
Combat. The company remains the single largest publisher of Mac
software.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there are many Microsoft titles that are not
published for the Mac. They include the database Access, a personal
information manager Outlook and desktop publishing software
Publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Now each of these products would face serious competition from
Mac counterparts such as FileMaker, Now Up-To-Date and Print Shop.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Microsoft President Steve Ballmer recently said as much
in an online interview on Pioneer Planet Web site. ``There's no
economic return,'' Ballmer was quoted as saying. ``The cost of
rewriting the software to run on the Macintosh would be greater
than the (sales) revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   To Crabb that's a lot of hooey. He argues the Office suite is as
expensive and complex to develop as anything, and yet it has proved
hugely popular on the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Less complex and expensive-to-develop education software
titles like Encarta or My Personal Tutor would take fewer resources
to produce, yet they would be category-killers on the Mac,'' wrote
Crabb.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, what Crabb fails to point out is that there are many
Mac developers who wouldn't welcome a greater Microsoft presence in
the market. After all, what Microsoft might be killing is their
software.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9605 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALM-PILOT06-COX     10-05 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALM-PILOT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Many users hold pocket-size computer close to the heart
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There goes Dad, writing in his diary again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I correct my wife. ``It's my personal digital
assistant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear that, Matt?'' my wife calls out to my son. ``It's
his personal digital assistant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah right,'' scoffs my son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well it is,'' I insist and stomp off to the closet of my room.
In my dark seclusion I have to admit my wife and son are right. The
PalmPilot I coddle in my hand has become as personal to me as a
diary.
</P>
<P>
   I use this pocket-size computer to jot down ideas, keep a
running grocery list, record when I've exercised and to remind me
of key appointments. And that's in addition to the PalmPilot's
electronic calendar, address book, calculator and to-do list.
</P>
<P>
   It truly has become my confidant, if a cruel one at times. I
won't soon forget the time it died during a change of batteries,
wiping out all my data. No diary I've ever kept treated me so
harshly. Still I wouldn't turn in my PalmPilot.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not alone in my affection for the PalmPilot. Just listen to
what TidBits writer Jeff Carlson said about this hand-held
computer: ``Take away my blender and I'll switch to a spoon. Try to
take my PalmPilot and I'll reach for a knife.''
</P>
<P>
   You tell 'em, Jeff.
</P>
<P>
   The PalmPilot has become the Mac of the late 1990s, developing a
vocal cult following. And what do followers do in this age? They
publish Web sites in honor of their beloved.
</P>
<P>
   There are scores of them for the PalmPilot, but here are a few
of the better ones: PalmLife at http://www.palmlife.com/; The
Pickled PalmPilot at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .pickled.com/ and Palm Planet at http://palmtopplanet.interspeed
</P>
<P>
   .net/palm/palmplanet.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the PalmPilot so endearing? The reasons are many.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the PalmPilot is the right size. At 4.7 inches tall and
3.1 inches wide and less than an inch thick, it fits in almost any
pocket. It runs on two AA batteries that can power the thing for up
to a month.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the PalmPilot is convenient, made even more so
because it's always on (if the batteries aren't dead) and you can
write on it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not kidding. The PalmPilot really does recognize handwriting
in two ways. You can tap out words and numbers with the PalmPilot's
stylus on a little keyboard that appears on the bottom of the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can write directly on the screen. What you write isn't
English but a shorthand language that's easy to learn and
understand. It's part of the software called Graffiti that comes
with the PalmPilot. Graffiti turns that shorthand into English.
Forget a shorthand symbol and you can call up a directory of the
language on the PalmPilot.
</P>
<P>
   The ability to easily write transforms the PalmPilot from just
an interesting electronic gadget into something truly useful. You
can whip out your PalmPilot and jot down notes, appointments and
reminders nearly anywhere at any time. Then you can save and
categorize this information later at your convenience.
</P>
<P>
   This ease of use, reminiscent of the Mac, characterizes
everything about the PalmPilot. There's four buttons along the
bottom that let you jump immediately to your address book,
calendar, notes or to-do list.
</P>
<P>
   And like the Mac, the PalmPilot display screen includes a top
menu bar. From there you can copy, paste, edit or remove items.
Instead of clicking a mouse you tap the commands with the stylus.
There's also a find command that lets you quickly search for
things.
</P>
<P>
   While Mac-like, the PalmPilot is not particularly Mac-friendly.
For starters, many Mac users have complained it's difficult and
sometimes impossible to back up their PalmPilot data on a desktop
Mac. I experienced this same problem. On PCs, the transfer of data
is a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there much Mac software for the PalmPilot. The opposite
is true for the PC model, which supports scores of applications.
</P>
<P>
   To 3Com's credit, it is trying to correct this imbalance. Last
spring it bought the first-rate personal information manager Claris
Organizer from Apple Computer. The company plans to refashion
Organizer as the core software of the Mac version of PalmPilot.
This software is expected to be released sometime this fall.
</P>
<P>
   PalmPilot's success, the first for a hand-held computer, has not
gone unnoticed. A score of other computer makers, including Casio,
Sharp and NEC, have entered the market with new products. Many of
them are using a specially-adapted version of Microsoft's Windows
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   These new machines are adding things not included in the
PalmPilot. The Casio Cassiopeia A-10, for example, lets you dictate
notes. Other machines have color screens and let you write and
print memos.
</P>
<P>
   None of these competitors have yet knocked the PalmPilot from
first place, with its million-plus sales. Still the race has just
begun.
</P>
<P>
   THE PALMPILOT III AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   Dimensions: 4.7 inches by 3.1 inches and 0.6 inches thick. It
weighs less than 6 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Price: $399; an older, less capable version is still available
for $199
</P>
<P>
   Power: Runs on 2 AA batteries, which power the PalmPilot for up
to a month.
</P>
<P>
   Microprocessor: Motorola
</P>
<P>
   Maker: 3Com, which also owns modem brand U.S. Robotics
</P>
<P>
   Operating system: Unique to the PalmPilot, it's called Pilot
Desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Screen: 160 pixels, black and white, touch sensitive
</P>
<P>
   Capacity: 20,000 names, calendar appointments and other assorted
information.
</P>
<P>
   Availability: There's a model each for Mac and Windows
computers, to which you can back up information. It's sold in most
computer stores, including discount chains such as Home Depot and
OfficeMax.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
