<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TECHMEDIA
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Print
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to find a school today that doesn't have computers.
But what, if any effect, are they having on education? In its
special fall issue on computers, FamilyCircle takes a look at this
important trend. It finds 6.3 million computers were in U.S. public
schools as of the 1996-97 school year. That represents a 186
percent increase from five years earlier. Internet access is also
growing in schools. FamilyCircle found 78 percent of all public
schools had at least one computer with Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Read how Iridium is about to transform the telephone business in
the October issue of Wired magazine. Iridium is a consortium that
last month finished building a wireless satellite service so people
can send and receive telephone calls from anywhere. That means you
can do it from the ocean surface, in the desert or in the middle of
a city center. It's powered by a constellation of 66 satellites.
They communicate with 13-ounce portable telephones. Wired dubs the
venture the first ``pan-national corporation, able to leap
geopolitical barriers in a single bound.''
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Darwinian determinism has come to the computer through a
computer CD called ``Creatures 2.'' It's a sequel to the original
game of the same name in which you breed little creatures called
Norns. Your goal is to create a thriving population of them, which
isn't so easy. It's survival of the fittest, with your Norns
battling weather and other plants and animals for the resources to
thrive. Published by Mindscape Entertainment, this game is
available for Windows machines.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro Interactive has released the computer version of board
game ``Outburst,'' which is an irreverent take on ``Trivial
Pursuit.'' You answer trivia questions while racing against the
clock. A typical question might be something like name 10 other
expressions for ``throw up.'' You get the idea. Available only for
Windows computers, ``Outburst'' retails for $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   If you enjoy R.L. Stine's ``Fear Street'' series of horror
books, you might want to check out the Web site dedicated to the
books. You'll find it at http://www.fearstreet.com/interhome.htm.
The site features sneak peaks at upcoming books, games based on the
books and the ability to write to Stine.
</P>
<P>
   And for you Animorphs fans, check out the Animorphs Network. It
features news about this popular series from Scholastic and
snippets from all the books. You'll also find a preview of coming
titles in the series. The site is at http://animorphs97
</P>
<P>
   .hypermart.net/index2.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
