<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNOBUDDY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's easier to move a PC if you've saved your boxes
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I once calculated that _ in my long life _ I have purchased 18
lawn mowers, 12 refrigerators and six leaf blowers. I have moved
more often than a con man on the lam. I should get a discount at
the rent-a-truck place.
</P>
<P>
   I've learned a lot by moving so often. For one thing, I've
learned that if you drop a futon down the stairs, it is best just
to let it go. Grabbing a speeding futon can be briefly interesting
but highly dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Since I have lived with and around computers since before IBM
introduced the original IBM Personal Computer in 1981, I have also
acquired a fair to middlin' knowledge of how to move a personal
computer. Moving a PC has gotten easier over the years. When I
started with them, a computer's hard disk was as sensitive as a
teenager going through puberty. The slightest jolt could send your
hard disk to computer heaven.
</P>
<P>
   PCs and their hard disks are less sensitive these days, but
moving any electronic gear is still a delicate task. Since most of
us will end up moving a computer one of these days, let me offer
you some tips based on too much experience.
</P>
<P>
   Husted's first rule of PC moving is to save all boxes. Those
boxes with Styrofoam inserts can't be beat for moving computers,
monitors and printers. I know it's tempting to throw all the
packing material away. But they're customized just for your
equipment. It is the perfect way to move.
</P>
<P>
   We talked about hard disk drives, but there's another kind of
drive in your computer: a floppy disk drive. Cut a piece of
cardboard (the kind cleaners use when they fold shirts) and insert
it into the floppy disk drive. That'll keep the magnetic head of
the floppy drive from banging around. Make sure you leave a tab on
the outside of the cardboard so it is easy to remove.
</P>
<P>
   If you're moving from Atlanta to Oregon, you'll need to take
more care than if the PC is going across town. For really long
moves, you have to spend some time worrying about the accessory
cards inside your computer. These cards can become loose in their
slots _ even through they're secured with a screw. If that happens,
your computer will malfunction when you turn it on at the new
location. And in a few cases, the loose card can actually
permanently damage your computer by creating a short circuit.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to attack this problem. You can wait until
you arrive at the new location and remove and then reseat each of
these cards. Or, you can remove the cards before moving (making
sure to pack them in the anti-static pouches that they came in).
For most folks, it makes more sense to leave the cards in the
machine and reseat them when you arrive.
</P>
<P>
   If at all possible, try not to move your PC in the moving van or
a closed truck, especially in the hot summer. The extreme heat can
hurt the machine, and the ride also is much more harsh. The best
way to move a computer is to pack it away in the box and then to
carry the box inside your car.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, unless you are a whiz at assembling and reassembling
computer systems, it's a real time saver to mark all the
connections using stick-on labels. That way, you won't have to
puzzle around with, say, the sound card trying to figure which of
the identical jacks is used for your speakers.
</P>
<P>
   That's it, the short course in moving a computer. If you follow
these tips (and if you can avoid grabbing a speeding futon) you'll
soon be up and running again.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: tecbud(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Bill appreciates hearing from you but cannot respond to all
e-mail. Personal home page: http://www.mindspring.com/
</P>
<P>
   (tilde)bhusted/bills.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
