<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LONGHORNS-DEFENSE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Horns get defensive
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It may be small. It may be fleeting. But it is
progress, and what the Texas Longhorns' defense did in a 59-21 win
over Rice last weekend put a contented feeling in its coach's
heart, which is progress of a whole different kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased, No. 1, with the win,'' defensive coordinator Carl
Reese said. ``Secondly, we didn't stink out the joint.''
</P>
<P>
   Victories come where you can find them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Longhorns (2-2) seach for more progress as they take
on the Big 12's most improved team, the Iowa State Cyclones.
</P>
<P>
   It gets redundant what the Horns' offense must do to win: Get
another serviceable game out of Major Applewhite _ another monster
one out of Ricky Williams _ and score most every time it touches
the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, it's a brave new world.
</P>
<P>
   Against Rice last week, the defense held an opponent to three
touchdowns or fewer for the first time in 14 games, allowed only
218 yards to an option team and had as many sacks as its opponent
had completions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time since I've been here, the players did not
get rattled,'' said Texas Coach Mack Brown, the Iowa State
receivers coach the last and only time the teams have met, a 17-9
Longhorns win in 1979. ``They did a good job adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're trying to take baby steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Five little piggies at a time, who:
</P>
<P>
   _ Went to mark it. Texas must stake out its turf by holding Iowa
State early and building on its collectively fragile confidence.
Iowa State has scored only 20 points in the first quarter, its
least productive period.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stayed home. The Cyclones run a one-back offense about 70
percent of the time and that back, junior Darren Davis, is a
tremendous cutback runner. Misdirections and reverses have killed
the Longhorns this year.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is also a very dangerous receiver. He's second on the team
in catches, turning a swing pass into a 65-yard touchdown against
Ball State last week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ate the most beef. That's the ISU offensive line, which
obviously hasn't let many juicy cuts slip past. The Cyclones line
up 300-pounders from tackle to tackle, who have done an equally
effective job opening holes (5.0 yards per carry) and closing them
(zero sacks allowed).
</P>
<P>
   _ Had none. Clue, that is, about what to do when the ball's in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   All season, Texas cornerbacks have shown an inability to play
the ball instead of the man, instant trouble when quarterback Todd
Bandhauer has been effective taking a three-step drop and throwing
the deep ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been our problem,'' Reese said. ``You can tell by how
many corners we've had out there. You want production. When the
ball's up deep, you'd better be making a play.''
</P>
<P>
   With last week's starter, freshman Ervis Hill, still hobbled
with a sore shin, the Horns plan to use the player he replaced, Joe
Walker, for more than just second-half mop-up duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's got a chance,'' Reese said. ``It's like a new life. It's
like playing poker and you run out of money and somebody just comes
up to you, hands you some money and says, 'Go ahead.' ``
</P>
<P>
   _ Ran all the way home. That's where Williams, the Longhorns
defense's biggest and best weapon, comes in.
</P>
<P>
   The Cyclones rank 55th against the rush, and that's the
lowest-rated unit Williams will face in the next seven games as he
chases Tony Dorsett's NCAA career rushing mark. He knows where home
is.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
