r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARKS-DEFICIT06-COX     10-05 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS-DEFICIT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Auditors uncover red ink in parks
 &HT;    By Mike Leggett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas state parks are operating at an annual
multimillion-dollar deficit, a comprehensive state audit report
shows, and the system could be facing layoffs, park closures or
transfers, and an overhaul of current spending and income programs.
</P>
<P>
   In the report, officials in the state auditor's office said the
Parks and Wildlife Department is failing to accurately count paying
visitors and adequately maintain and operate parks to sustain
visitation levels. Andrew Sansom, the Parks and Wildlife
Department's executive director, requested the audit to determine
why the system is operating at a deficit and to develop a plan for
closing the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors reported that total revenues for state parks fall $10.1
million short of the $51.5 million needed annually for basic
operations and maintenance, even though the department has raised
revenues by at least 85 percent since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The audit, which took nearly a year, recommended a review of the
parks inventory, with an eye toward operations that could be
reduced or altered.
</P>
<P>
   The Parks and Wildlife Department operates parks, natural areas
and historical sites throughout the state. A number of the
historical sites draw few visitors and thus lose money year after
year, the auditors found. Other areas are remote and undeveloped,
and entry fees are too low, despite recent increases, to allow them
to operate at a profit, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is significance _ what assets should the state be
managing,'' Sansom said. ``There are more things we should do, but
we can't do them as long as we're dealing with sites of
insignificance. I'm not going to name specific parks.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a number of park properties have outdated, even
crumbling buildings, water and sewer systems and user facilities,
the audit found. To meet those critical repair needs, the
Legislature has authorized $60 million in bonds, which the
department plans to issue over five or six years. The auditor's
report said the department's repair schedule did not ensure that
critical repairs would be made quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Sansom said his department is faced with a dilemma: The public
demands park access, but the parks do not have a strong financial
base in terms of entry fees. ``You could easily say the state
should keep on managing a San Jacinto Monument or Washington on the
Brazos,'' Samson said. ``We don't charge any entrance fees at those
sites, though.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the real issues is just how many people visit state parks
each year.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the Parks and Wildlife Department has claimed 20
million to 22 million visitors annually, even though revenues
always fell far short of the money that number should produce. The
auditor's report said that the actual number could be 25 percent
lower, or 5 million visitors fewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't have solid numbers,'' Sansom said. ``That was
shown by the disaster we had two years ago with that price
increase.'' Fees were raised, but that didn't substantially
increase revenue totals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do something because the current system is not
giving us the kind of data you need to predict income,'' Sansom
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Cook, chief operations officer and assistant director of the
Parks and Wildlife Department, took over the effective top spot in
parks nearly a year ago, as Sansom and the nine-member commission
tried to begin reining in spending problems. He said the department
is trying to find an effective way to count visitors and thus
budget realistically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We implemented a program so that we will know how many people
paid to get into our parks,'' Cook said. ``We still don't know how
many people there are total, and we need that number because we
have to be able to offer them facilities and services.'' Some user
groups such as youngsters and seniors don't pay the regular entry
fees to state parks. Charlie Hrncir, a certified public accountant
in the state auditor's office who worked on the project, said the
Parks and Wildlife Department's audit was neither the worst nor the
best in which he's been involved. ``There are some challenges
facing the department that are serious, though,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sansom said one of those challenges will be working with state
leaders in the next three to four years to identify parks that
could be closed or that could be shifted to other ownership or
operations responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, we have some parks that are totally within the
boundaries of some cities,'' he said. ``Why should we own that?
We're handing out $15 million a year for local park funds projects,
and maybe that's where some of that should go.''
</P>
<P>
   Closing parks or shifting ownership of some park sites to other
governmental entities _ the State Historical Society has been one
suggestion _ is a politically tricky move. Sansom said no decisions
would be made without the input of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   The department's share of the state sales tax on sporting goods
comes to $15.5 million a year, and parks and wildlife officials
would love to be able to grab a bigger share of that $100 million
pot. However, that probably won't happen until the department
addresses more of the issues raised in the state audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have the option of shutting down,'' Sansom said.
``It's clear that what we do is important to the people of Texas,
and I think clearly that we offer them a great bargain. But we have
to change to continue to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sansom identified three main areas of concentration. ``Shame on
us if by this time next year we haven't developed an accurate way
to count visitors,'' he said. ``We need to speed up our repair
program, and we need to find deficiencies in operations and
staffing. If that means moving more people into the field, that's
what we'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
