<HEADER>
A9612 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-REPORT06-COX     10-05 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-REPORT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Titanic' makes waves by offering closed-captioning
 &HT;    By John Ghirardini
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last year's blockbuster film ``Titanic'' was remarkable: $200
million to make, $1 billion-plus earned so far, 11 Oscars and a
plot that made us believe that in 1912 a steerage passenger
actually could meet and fall in love with someone from the rarified
air of first class.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie was even more noteworthy for another reason.
``Titanic'' was just the second feature film to be closed-captioned
for the deaf and hearing-impaired, following ``The Jackal,'' and
was one of the first ever shown with the captions in a regular
theater.
</P>
<P>
   The patented Rear Window Captioning System shows reversed
captions on an LED text display mounted in the rear of a theater.
Deaf and hard-of-hearing patrons use transparent acrylic panels
attached to their seats to reflect the captions so that they appear
superimposed on the movie screen. The reflective panels are
portable and adjustable, enabling the user to sit anywhere. The
system was co-developed by WGBH television and Rufus Butler Seder
of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   So far, General Cinema theaters in Indianapolis, Sherman Oaks,
Calif., and Lombard, Ill., are equipped with the system, but
Atlanta may not be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is a market we're giving strong consideration to,''
said General Cinema spokesman Brian Callaghan. ``We're still
testing the technology and determining what location works best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts-based theater company is considering the
system for its 15-screen theater planned for Parkway Pointe on Cobb
Parkway, Callaghan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic'' and ``The Jackal'' also were described for the blind
and vision-impaired by WGBH's Descriptive Video Service as part of
the Motion Picture Access Project. Descriptive narration is
delivered via infrared or FM listening systems and headsets that
don't disturb other audience members. The descriptions highlight
key visual elements such as actions, settings and scene changes.
</P>
<P>
   A General Cinema theater in Framingham, Mass., is equipped with
the narration system, but Callaghan said the company would like to
install both systems if possible as new theaters come on line.
</P>
<P>
   Resistance is useless
</P>
<P>
   It's official: There's no escape from e-mail anywhere on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Magellan Corp. has come out with the GSC 100, billed as the
world's first hand-held satellite-based global communicator and the
first of its type to gain FCC approval.
</P>
<P>
   The GSC 100 combines Orbcomm, a ring of low-Earth-orbit
messaging and data communications satellites, with the Global
Positioning System. Explorers in the jungles of Borneo, for
example, can communicate with anyone on Earth who has an e-mail
address, voice or fax service and let them know their position on
the globe to within about 50 feet.
</P>
<P>
   When the user sends a ``GlobalGram'' from the GSC 100, the
message goes to an Orbcomm satellite, which relays it to a ground
station that routes it to the recipient via the Internet. The
process is reversed to receive a message.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail interface lets the user create, edit, forward, copy
and delete messages. The device will save up to 100 messages and
150 addresses, and includes GPS data in the message.
</P>
<P>
   This inability to get away from the Information Age doesn't come
cheap. The GSC 100 itself costs $999.
</P>
<P>
   May the Force be with you
</P>
<P>
   The ``Star Wars'' empire of movies, software, action figures and
the Force knows what has generated enough money in the 21 years of
its existence to buy most of the galaxies far, far away _ and the
local ones, too.
</P>
<P>
   And the whizzes at LucasArts Entertainment are nowhere near
being done. A two-CD interactive ``insider's guide'' due out this
fall is packed with facts and figures, trivia, never-seen film
footage and a preview of the long-awaited Episode I ``prequel''
movie expected to be released in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Behind the Magic'' is organized into sections that
detail characters (including creatures), locations, events and
technology through more than 2,500 photos, 600 pieces of production
art, 30 models, 40 minutes of digitized video, 20 minutes of audio
and 30 ship schematics. There's also a searchable database with
more than 700 entries.
</P>
<P>
   Want to know the difference between a TIE fighter and a TIE
interceptor? Need the skinny on B-wing, X-wing or Y-wing rebel
craft? How about a 3-D walk-through of the Millennium Falcon,
hosted by C-3PO? It's all here, along with lots more you might not
have known you needed to know.
</P>
<P>
   The set will have an estimated street price of $29.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
