<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BELL-WANDERS _ Sachel Briggs wasn't even Sachel Briggs. She was
a woman named Vicky Lynn Bell who had been reported missing from a
group home in Asheville, N.C., about a week earlier. She'd signed
out to take the bus to Wal-Mart _ there are two in Asheville _ and
had never come back. (Minor, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LASALLE-SHIP _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Two groups unsuccessful in their
quest to find the long-lost flagship of the French explorer LaSalle
announced that they have joined forces in a renewed search. (Ward,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHSCHOOL-GANGS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Round Rock High School
administrators ordered dozens of students wearing red clothing to
change their garments recently, after school officials prohibited
wearing red on campus. Blackett said red is a prominent color for
the Bloods, Round Rock's largest gang. (Coleman, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE/ENVIRONMENT (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   PLANT-KILLERS _ South Florida water managers spend millions of
dollars killing foreign plants that invade the region. They also
publish a booklet that lists some of those same plants as examples
of water-conserving landscaping. ``I don't think we should promote
plants that we're killing,'' said Dan Thayer, who heads the
eradication of invasive weeds. (King, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OKEECHOBEE-MUD _ About 5 miles offshore in Lake Okeechobee, Don
Fox leaped from his skiff onto a beachhead of muck, cattails and
scrabbly willow. Bad news, Fox said: ``The lake is forming a new
edge.'' A new bank inside the old one. Fox said the berm eventually
could turn the marshes into hardwood swamps, eliminating the fish
nurseries and the economy they support. (King, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
