<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TROUBLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S PERSONAL SITUATION MAY BE WORSENED BY ECONOMIC CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Although few have so far linked President Clinton's
personal problems with the world's apparently looming economic
crisis, a connection could well exist _ to his detriment.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend, officials of the leading industrial nations met
in Washington and agreed that economic difficulties are worsening.
That may be doubly bad news for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone agrees his high ratings in the polls despite the
Monica Lewinsky scandal revelations stem from the widely held
belief that, whatever else may be said, the president is running
the country well. In turn, this is a judgment based largely on the
high employment and good times most Americans have experienced
during his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But what if a spreading international recession gives a hard
knock to the U.S. economy too? Suppose joblessness rises by 2 or 3
percentage points from its current 4.6 percent rate? Or the
American middle class finds that the large sums it thought it made
on Wall Street have turned into worthless paper.
</P>
<P>
   In such a scenario, popular feeling about the president could
change overnight. After all, many of his predecessors found
themselves suddenly out of favor when times got tough through no
fault of their own. Let's not forget that George Bush appeared
invincible in early 1991 following the Persian Gulf War until the
economy turned sour. Look what happened then.
</P>
<P>
   It is an indelible rule of U.S. politics that the president gets
the pats on the back when the economy is in top gear and the blame
when it runs out of gas. In neither case may he bear much, if any,
legitimate responsibility, of course. But what does it matter? To
this day, Bush is probably mystified over why the recession in
1991-92 made him a one-term president.
</P>
<P>
   In an atmosphere of deepening economic gloom, many Americans who
have been ready to overlook the president's sexual misconduct so
long as he seemed to do his elected job well might begin having
second thoughts. Citizens who face foreclosure of their mortgage or
loss of their job will direct at least some of their rancor at the
White House and will let the Congress know.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the Lewinsky case may well assume even greater
importance, and the president will be in worse trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9660 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     10-05 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Oct. 5, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   METEORS-THREAT (San Francisco) _ A spectacular meteor storm will
ignite the heavens in mid-November, possibly ``sandblasting''
satellites and threatening everyday services from cell phones to TV
shows to data communications. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   STORM-INSURANCE (Pacifica, Calif.) _ Nine families in Pacifica
enjoyed an unobstructed view and the sea song of waves crashing
against the cliff below their homes. They thought the federal
government had insured them against loss if the relentless ocean
wore away the cliff and toppled their houses. Then came El Nino.
And there went their flood insurance. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BOXER (San Francisco) _ Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., is
facing a tough battle for re-election on Nov. 3. She says it's
``important to have diversity in places like the United States
Senate. ... It is not that a woman is better than a man, but she is
bringing a different set of experiences.'' By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-FONG (San Francisco) _ Matt Fong was not a natural
athlete, nor a stellar scholar. But he was determined to survive
the physical and academic rigors that felled nearly half his
classmates at the Air Force Academy. And in due time, he won his
wings. Supporters say the dogged quality evident in Fong's youth
has put him in a position to win his challenge to Sen. Barbara
Boxer, D-Calif. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MOTOR-HOMES (Albany, N.Y.) _ As snowbirds head south for the
winter, America's highways will become loaded with overweight _ and
largely unregulated _ houses on wheels. Some motor homes could be
dangerous. They may be too heavy, making them hard to steer and
prone to blowouts and mechanical failures, according to a report by
John Anderson, of Chuckey, Tenn., a safety wizzard. By JAY
JOCHNOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   JUNK-MAIL (San Antiono) _ Benjamin Franklin was only partly
right when he said that nothing in this world is certain but death
and taxes. He never got any junk mail. More politely referred to as
direct mail, the mass-marketing technique of unsolicited catalogs,
advertisements and letters yields billions of dollars in sales each
year. By DAVID UHLER.
</P>
<P>
   FREER-GALLERY (Washington) _ A railroad man's job loss 120 years
ago proved to be a gain for the nation because it resulted in the
unique collection of Oriental and American art housed at the
Smithsonian Institution's Freer Gallery. The gallery marks its 75th
anniversary this month. By BILL CRAIG.
</P>
<P>
   ENCORE-AZALEAS (Undated) _ Azaleas give us cause to celebrate
each spring. Yet as the flowers fade, many moan that the party's
just over too soon. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-COMPUTER (San Francisco) _ The computing world is finding
out the hard way that the iMac is pretty much an island, entire to
itself. While Apple's new computer has been tearing up the sales
charts, software and hardware vendors have been tearing out their
hair trying to get the iMac to play nice with add-on accessories
and older programs. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM (Carlsbad, Calif.) _ More than two years after
deregulation, the $200 billion telecommunications industry hasn't
produced the riches of services and price reductions it had
promised for all consumers. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DRIVE-PLAY-PREVIEW (Undated) _ Paula Vogel's recent off-Broadway
hit and winner of the 1998 Pulitzer Prize is about the incestuous
relationship between a young girl and her uncle. The play opens in
Houston, starring James Black as Uncle Peck and Sherri Parker Lee
as the niece, Li'l Bit. By EVERETT EVANS.
</P>
<P>
   BALDWIN-PROFILE (Undated) _ And interview with actor Stephen
Baldwin, the youngest of the Baldwin brothers who are creating
their own Hollywood dynasty. By LOUIS PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TOPIARY-GARDENS (Portsmouth, R.I.) _ Edward Scissorhands would
have felt at home in the Green Animals Topiary Garden overlooking
Narragansett Bay. The artistry the movie android displayed in
turning living plants into fascinating shapes can be seen here in
the spiraling shrubs, geometric forms, ornamental designs and in
the menagerie. By MARK SOMMER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Why travel around the world to find a
millennium party? Large-scale celebrations are planned all over the
United States. You can chant in the new century. Drum it in. Or
attend any among thousands of much-touted ``parties of the
century.'' By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ What would you do if you had
four months to live? Over the years, I've met several people facing
that plight, and they've asked me to share my best fishing spot,
the most beautiful hidden waterfall, the most pristine meadow, the
prettiest drive, the most secluded, untouched beach. By TOM
STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ I was maybe 6 years old _ 7, tops.
Ike was president, the heavyweight champion of the world was Rocky
Marciano, the biggest movie star in the world was John Wayne, the
hottest singer was Patti Page. That was what the world was like the
day that Gene Autry knocked me out cold. And _ it scares me to
think about it _ but I remember it like it was yesterday. By DAN
LYYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The two guys who won the
economics prize from the Nobel foundation by all rights ought to
turn in their medals and citations and whatever is left of the
cash. Their investment scheme, called a hedge fund, has crumbled,
kept from total disintegration by a rescue fund put together by
distinguished financial institutions and shepherded by the Federal
Reserve Board. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ It is natural to want to hang a
``monster'' sign around the neck of David Cash Jr., to disavow any
connection between him and the rest of the human race. And, because
there is no law with which to punish him, it is instinctive to hope
that he somehow disappears from our midst as soon as possible. By
STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Public welfare is such an
emotionally charged issue that the Texas Department of Human
Services devotes a large chunk of its Internet Web site to
debunking widespread welfare ``myths.'' By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
