</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TROUBLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S PERSONAL SITUATION MAY BE WORSENED BY ECONOMIC CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Although few have so far linked President Clinton's
personal problems with the world's apparently looming economic
crisis, a connection could well exist _ to his detriment.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend, officials of the leading industrial nations met
in Washington and agreed that economic difficulties are worsening.
That may be doubly bad news for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone agrees his high ratings in the polls despite the
Monica Lewinsky scandal revelations stem from the widely held
belief that, whatever else may be said, the president is running
the country well. In turn, this is a judgment based largely on the
high employment and good times most Americans have experienced
during his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But what if a spreading international recession gives a hard
knock to the U.S. economy too? Suppose joblessness rises by 2 or 3
percentage points from its current 4.6 percent rate? Or the
American middle class finds that the large sums it thought it made
on Wall Street have turned into worthless paper.
</P>
<P>
   In such a scenario, popular feeling about the president could
change overnight. After all, many of his predecessors found
themselves suddenly out of favor when times got tough through no
fault of their own. Let's not forget that George Bush appeared
invincible in early 1991 following the Persian Gulf War until the
economy turned sour. Look what happened then.
</P>
<P>
   It is an indelible rule of U.S. politics that the president gets
the pats on the back when the economy is in top gear and the blame
when it runs out of gas. In neither case may he bear much, if any,
legitimate responsibility, of course. But what does it matter? To
this day, Bush is probably mystified over why the recession in
1991-92 made him a one-term president.
</P>
<P>
   In an atmosphere of deepening economic gloom, many Americans who
have been ready to overlook the president's sexual misconduct so
long as he seemed to do his elected job well might begin having
second thoughts. Citizens who face foreclosure of their mortgage or
loss of their job will direct at least some of their rancor at the
White House and will let the Congress know.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the Lewinsky case may well assume even greater
importance, and the president will be in worse trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
