<HEADER>
A9718 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOPIARY-GARDENS-HNS &LR;      10-05 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOPIARY-GARDENS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RHODE ISLAND ESTATE OFFERS A MENAGERIE IN GREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK SOMMER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, R.I. _ Edward Scissorhands would have felt right at
home in the whimsical Green Animals Topiary Garden overlooking
Narragansett Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The imagination and artistry the besieged android displayed in
turning living plants into fascinating shapes and sizes can be seen
here in the spiraling shrubs, geometric forms, ornamental designs
and in the garden's main attraction, the menagerie. The animals _
which include a giraffe, bear and cub, elephant, boar and swan _
are set in blooming flower gardens among berry patches, rose
gardens and fruit trees.
</P>
<P>
   Green Animals, which boasts 80 pieces of topiary, including 21
animals, is the oldest and most northern topiary garden in the
United States. The seven-acre estate dates to 1872, when Thomas
Brayton purchased the land and asked his gardener, Joseph Carreiro,
who had seen a topiary in the Andes, to create one.
</P>
<P>
   Carreiro was superintendent for 40 years, and then succeeded by
his son-in-law, George Mendonca, who worked there for the same
length of time, and added new topiary, before retiring in 1985. In
1972, Brayton's daughter, Alice, left Green Animals to the
Preservation Society of Newport County, which opened the area to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   About 20,000 visitors annually come to marvel at the topiaries,
according to grounds manager Crisse MacFadyen Genga.
</P>
<P>
   A few chartered busloads of tourists were among the visitors at
Green Animals one early autumn day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always tell people this is the best time to visit, and they
can't believe it,'' said Genga, who for the past 10 years has been
maintaining the garden's forms, including many that have been a
constant here for nearly a century. ``I think everyone is thinking
fall and we're still in full-blown summer. It's one of the best
times to come because we usually don't get a frost before Oct. 31,
when we close.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the topiaries can be viewed immediately upon arrival,
from the little green man standing opposite the main entrance and
gift shop, to the nearby curved archway that beckons visitors
forward to the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately inside is a rose garden, and then fruit trees and
flower beds ornamented with boxwood that were bursting last weekend
with an abundance of colorful plantings, including black-eyed
Susans, verbena, Indian Princess calendulas, Florists' Whites
ageratums, snapdragons, Cherry Pinwheel zinnias and Marien Lemoines
heliotropes.
</P>
<P>
   The topiary gardener's technique is to lead young plants into
animal shapes by letting the branches grow, weave and tie them onto
a frame with fishing line, and cut back the errant growth until the
desired form takes shape.
</P>
<P>
   At Green Animals, the structures used to shape the plants are
well camouflaged. The animals are sculpted from California privet
and yew, and the other topiaries are from California privet and
English boxwood.
</P>
<P>
   Lined up on the perimeter of the area known as the Formal
Garden, where the earliest topiaries reside, are shrubs shaped into
various forms and sizes, including a trophy cup, basket and
oversize and overstuffed chair. There are also shrubs that are
cylindrically shaped, and the first of three spirally sculpted
shrubs that resemble a horticultural corkscrew.
</P>
<P>
   More archways lead to the oldest and most prominent animals,
which date back to 1912. A camel, elephant, lion and 14-foot
giraffe stand mounted atop the bushes from where they have been
formed. They reside among a colorful display of perennials and
annuals, including daisies, blue heliotropes and Confetti lantana.
</P>
<P>
   The upper topiary site, which was added in the 1940s, has a
number of animals bunched together, including a rabbit, horse and
rider, hen, ostrich, reindeer, boar and swan. The most recent
additions, created in the 1970s, are a large, soft-looking bear
with cub, unicorn, dog and rooster.
</P>
<P>
   The animals and other topiary found at Green Animals differ
markedly, according to Genga, from those found at Disney World and
Disneyland, which have helped to popularize this form of landscape
design. The topiaries here are growing in the ground, she pointed
out, while the Disney topiaries often use ficus or ivy around the
frame.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the second animal grounds are an array of horticultural
sights, including an herb garden, gourd arbor, berry patch,
vegetable garden, children's garden, 30-foot reed grass and a fish
pond.
</P>
<P>
   Also open to the public is the white clapboard home once used by
the Braytons, which is bordered by a wide veranda from which
visitors can move to and fro in rocking chairs while gazing out
over the bay. Inside, the 10 rooms, with original furnishings, are
open for viewing, along with collections on the second floor of
turn-of-the-century toys, dolls and dollhouses, and games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the toys are a tin Ferris wheel and 19th-century
horse-drawn hook-and-ladder truck. One custom-made dollhouse,
befitting the excesses of the rich on a small island known for the
princely estates of nearby Newport, had electrical wiring and a
functional doorbell.
</P>
<P>
   There are also several battle-scene dioramas on the second
floor, most with miniature tin or cast-aluminum soldiers, such as
one that depicts British infantrymen at war with Zulu warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Green Animals is one of several topiaries open to the public on
the East Coast. Others include the Vizcaya Museum and Gardens in
Miami and the Magnolia Plantation Gardens in Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The history of topiaries in the United States, however, is a
short one compared to Europe. The word topiarius in Latin means
garden, and topiary gardens can be traced back to ancient Rome,
when Pliny the Younger, who lived from A.D. 62 to A.D. 113, had
one.
</P>
<P>
   Topiaries were commonly owned by royalty and landed gentry in
England and Europe 300 years ago, and today they remain commonplace
in Britain. Topiaries can also be found in a number of other
countries, including France, Italy, Japan, Australia and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Grounds manager Genga said Green Animals saw a surge of interest
after ``Edward Scissorhands'' played movie theaters. Not
surprisingly, it's one of her favorite films.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our hero. That was a great movie, and a lot of people
responded to that when they came to visit,'' Genga said. ``Oh, God.
It's a wonderful movie. I've seen it many, many times.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The Green Animals Topiary Garden is located on Cory's Lane off
state Route 114 in Portsmouth. It is open May 1 to Oct. 31 from 10
a.m. to 5 p.m. Tickets are $8 for adults, $5 for students and $3.50
for children. For information, call the Preservation Society of
Newport, 401-847-1000.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
