<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about an inspiring story! Ken Hakuta has become famous for
the Wacky Wall Walker, those slime-covered plastic creatures that
ooze down vertical surfaces. But Hakuta didn't even come up with
the idea: All he did was license the toy from Japan for a tiny
fraction of the amount he made. Now he's a millionaire!
</P>
<P>
   There are a ton of ideas floating around out there, and 10 of
them can be found in Neil Strauss' article ``Want Some
Million-Dollar Ideas? I Got a Million of 'Em!'' It is one of eight
stories _ WITH ART! _ from The New York Times' ENTREPRENEUR special
news section. The articles and art are available for one-shot
purchase from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   These topnotch features can be a platform for your own special
entrepreneur supplement. (What a great way to please both
advertisers and readers in your area!)
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   ENTREPRENEURS explores a range of topics, everything from the
financial and management challenges facing company owners and
managers to reflections on the culture of self-employment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PLEASE NOTE: All the features, which have been edited for
length, can be found by the slugs listed below. They have been sent
to category codes ``f'' business news and ``l'' lifestyle news. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FOR PURCHASE INFORMATION, call CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
