<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9772 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXTRA-ME-INC.-NYTSF &LR;      10-05 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTRA-ME-INC.-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEIR BUSINESSES MAY BE SMALL, BUT THEIR AMBITIONS RARELY ARE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This is a special ``one-shot'' feature culled from
ENTREPRENEURS, a stand-alone news section from The New York Times,
which explores everything from the financial and management
challenges facing company owners and managers to reflections on the
culture of self-employment. For purchase information _ THE RATE IS
NOT PROHIBITIVE _ contact CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    -----------------ART FOR PURCHASE!-----------------
 &HT;     One color illustration depicting the work involved in running
your own small business. Call White for more information.  
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By BRENT BOWERS 
 c.1998 The New York Times Co.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Even as children, many of them spotted a business angle nobody
else did, and milked it for all it was worth.
</P>
<P>
   At age 10, Harold S. Blue, now the chairman of Proxymed Inc., a
health-care information-services company in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
figured he could make more money if he hired playmates to shovel
driveways instead of doing the work himself. He paid them $3 of the
$5 he collected and even had the presence of mind to ply his trade
outside his neighborhood so that the mothers wouldn't catch on to
his scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was out of high school, Blue owned and operated two
drug stores.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy growing up in a village in India 100 miles north of New
Delhi, Vinod Gupta, the founder of infoUSA Inc., a seller of
business information in Omaha with projected sales this year of
$250 million, caught frogs at a swamp and sold them to a research
laboratory for lunch money.
</P>
<P>
   In college, he rented entire passenger-train cars to make a
36-hour trip to New Delhi, and then sold seat tickets individually
for a quick 25 percent profit.
</P>
<P>
   Not every successful business owner can boast of such an early
flair for salesmanship. But even those who drifted or were pushed
into entrepreneurial careers seem to have a natural bent for
seizing opportunities that make competitors wonder why on earth
they didn't think of that themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Is that what defines them? They are an eclectic lot who operate
ventures that vary from grocery stores to Internet start-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Jonovic, a consultant in Cleveland who has advised
hundreds of family businesses, says he never fails to be astonished
by the ``raw diversity'' of American entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at some of them and you ask, `My God, how'd that
happen?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a country that prides itself on individualism and counts
literally millions of entrepreneurs, it is a question worth asking.
Small businesses, roughly defined as ventures controlled by their
founders and taking in less than $250 million in revenue a year,
are an enormous force in the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   But what drives their owners to strike out on their own rather
than take refuge in the predictability and perks of salaried jobs?
</P>
<P>
   The experts, of course, have their views. Jonovic says true
entrepreneurs are marked by a combination of ``tunnel-vision
dedication'' and supreme self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   David G. Winter, a professor of psychology at the University of
Michigan, said they are propelled by a zeal to excel at whatever
they do, a trait he calls ``achievement motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have this optimism, this exuberance, this boldness,''
Winter said, which can take the form of restlessness, especially if
their business grows into a larger, bureaucratic organization they
can't control. If that happens, he said, ``they may be so unable to
deal with it that they get dismissed by their board. Or they may
quit and start all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said entrepreneurs often display a streak of
authoritarianism because they believe their method is the only way
to do things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing their best is what matters most to them, as opposed to a
concern with friendship or power,'' Winter said.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs, he added, tend to come from middle-class
backgrounds, not blue-collar homes or wealthy families, ``which
still view small business as a step downward into vulgar trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonovic said that many entrepreneurs are tightfisted, not out of
greed but because each dollar they earn represents a small fraction
of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew a successful entrepreneur who ended up in a nursing
home and wouldn't pay for a private room because he wanted to keep
his estate above $1 million,'' Jonovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Entrepreneurs themselves cite a long list of self-defining
characteristics and attributes: decisiveness, resilience, focus, a
love of battle, a penchant for risk-taking, workaholism, good
social skills.
</P>
<P>
   But as they recount their histories, two core themes leap out,
flip sides of the same coin: They want to be their own boss, and
they show an uncanny knack for detecting opportunities that others
missed.
</P>
<P>
   For most entrepreneurs, it all begins with the realization that
working for somebody else just isn't a choice.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to go it alone can be liberating, but it can also
be scary because it means cutting off the corporate safety net.
</P>
<P>
   Eric B. Segal, the president of the Kenzer Corp., an
executive-recruiting firm in New York, recalls the near-panic he
and his partner, Robert D. Kenzer, felt in the early days of
running their company in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Segal had been a corporate executive in the retail industry, but
quit a high-paying job after he got what he viewed as an
insufficient raise. As he and Kenzer scrambled to find clients, he
said, he kept thinking: Where's the check? Where's Mommy?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are rules you learn from working in big business, but
nobody's prepared for flying without the net until you do it,''
said Segal, who is 55. ``It's frightening. I see a lot of corporate
guys who can't make the conversion.''
</P>
<P>
   But many entrepreneurs insist that the absence of security is a
small price to pay for the freedom to operate at their own pace and
on their own scale.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Yellin, a small-business consultant who works out of her
Manhattan apartment, says she is determined to remain a one-person
show earning just enough money to live comfortably and ``feed my
cat Fancy Feasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Yellin is quick to see business possibilities in
humdrum circumstances. A telemarketing specialist who has made an
instructional tape titled ``Warming Up to Cold Calling,'' Yellin,
46, has even figured out how to turn phone pitches she receives at
home to her financial advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of the callers are terrible at selling,'' she said.
``That gives me an opportunity to call their bosses and say, `You
should book me for some training.'''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Brent Bowers, a staff writer for The New York Times, is
co-author with Harold Geneen of the book ``The Synergy Myth'' (St.
Martin's Press, 1996).) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
