</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREER-GALLERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREER GALLERY MARKS 75TH ANNIVERSARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BILL CRAIG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A railroad man's job loss 120 years ago proved to
be a gain for the nation because it resulted in the unique
collection of Oriental and American art housed at the Smithsonian
Institution's Freer Gallery in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The 75th anniversary of the gallery opening in 1923 will be
observed Oct. 11 by a special exhibition of 100 new works acquired
for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   They include examples of sculpture, painting, ceramics,
calligraphy and metalware produced over a period of 4,000 years
throughout a wide area of Asia. Many are associated with royalty,
such as the Emperor Shah Jahan, builder of the Taj Mahal in India.
They will be exhibited through next April 11.
</P>
<P>
   The new works are significant additions to the collection
originally deeded to the nation in 1906 by Charles Lang Freer, who
made his fortune as a manufacturer of rail cars.
</P>
<P>
   When Freer lost his job in an 1878 Indiana rail merger, he
pooled his money with a friend and started a rail car building
enterprise in Michigan that made him rich. Retiring at the age of
45, he traveled throughout the world collecting art.
</P>
<P>
   Freer offered his collection of about 9,000 works to the
Smithsonian in 1904, but the institution's Board of Regents
hesitated to accept it because of conditions attached. They were
finally persuaded by President Theodore Roosevelt who met with them
and, pounding the arm of his chair, told them to accept the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Freer's bequest included money to house the collection in a new
building next to the Smithsonian's ``castle'' on the National Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The gallery's holdings now total 28,000 objects. The original
collection included art from the Near and Far East and a
distinguished group of works by American artists, notably James
McNeill Whistler, who was a friend of Freer's. One of the most
unusual is Whistler's ``Peacock Room,'' reassembled in the museum.
Of great importance to Biblical scholars are the museum's
5th-century Christian manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   The Freer Gallery and the adjoining 10-year-old Arthur M.
Sackler Gallery, devoted to Asian art, are located on Jefferson
Drive at 12th St. S.W. in Washington. They are open free to the
public every day but Dec. 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
