<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE'S PLAY: HIDE-AND-SEEK WITH TAX RUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Natalya could not believe her eyes. There, on the
counter in front of her desk, were several stacks of crisp ruble
notes, the balance owed on a Moscow-based American reporter's 1997
Russian income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take it back,'' Natalya demanded. ``I can't take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Natalya is a teller at the branch of Sberbank, the Russian state
savings bank, located directly on the floor below the state tax
inspectorate. This is a perfectly acceptable place to pay one's
personal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the reporter said. ``This is my tax payment. You have to
take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Natalya rolled her eyes. A colleague clucked her tongue. Was
this guy nuts? No one in Russia pays taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then let's go spend it,'' she said, fairly seriously. ``Let's
go on a cruise. Let's buy a Mediterranean villa. Better we should
have it than one of our leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the reporter said, firmly. It wasn't that much _ about
$3,000. Then again, that's close to a year's salary for a teller at
Sberbank.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're so intent on throwing it away, then why not just
give it to me?'' Natalya insisted as the colleague nodded in
earnest. ``I won't tell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said the reporter, wearily.
</P>
<P>
   He goes through this every year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But this year is special. Russia is in the midst of its worst
economic crisis since the collapse of communist rule in 1991. The
banking system is all but paralyzed, the national currency has lost
60 percent of its value, prices are soaring. The government is
essentially bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Tax collection, always lower than expected in Russia, has
plummeted, because the banks aren't working and it's become
difficult to pay, unless you like carrying large sums of cash
around to banks.
</P>
<P>
   But other than a few poor saps, most of them foreigners like our
reporter friend, pretty much no one is doing that. In this crisis,
Russians are rushing to do whatever they can to not pay. One reason
is that it is so easy to cheat. Most businesses keep two sets of
books, one for the tax inspector, one with the real numbers for the
protection rackets that you have to pay. Most private companies
employ various loopholes to allow their employees to avoid paying
taxes. One favorite tactic was to pay employees a small, official
sum, then make a deposit in a high-interest bank account in the
employee's name. The employee then received interest payments,
which were nontaxable, as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's last chief tax inspector, Boris Fyodorov, vowed to end
this practice. But Fyodorov was fired last week. The new tax boss,
Georgy Boos, has yet to make his plans known.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Boos does, there is another, more fundamental reason
why no one wants to pay: People avoid taxes in Russia because they
figure the state's going to get them anyway. Mother Russia wants
their money, usually in the form of bribes to one or several of her
employees. And then there is the sense many Russians like Natalya
have: that their tax ruble will be squandered on some high-ranking
official's Mediterranean villa.
</P>
<P>
   Some business people, it must be said, believed in the
government of former Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko. You remember
him: the boyish, inexperienced 35-year-old who nonetheless had some
serious plans for getting Russia's economy on track. But
Kiriyenko's government in August unexpectedly devalued the ruble
and defaulted on Russia's foreign and domestic debts, setting off
the current crisis. Just about everyone lost money. Confidence in
the Russian government, never high, is at an all-time low. An no
one expects anything but more pain from the new government of Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who can is getting his money out of the country,'' a
Moscow businessman said last week. ``Some people were starting to
run their businesses in a legitimate way, paying taxes and
everything, but that has ended now. No one believes anything the
government says anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Filipov is the Globe's Moscow bureau chief.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
