<SLUG> BC-THOMAS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBE ERRED IN DENYING BARNICLE HIS SAY ON THE OP-ED PAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACK THOMAS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The exodus of Globe columnists Patricia Smith and Mike Barnicle
has been a bumpy ride for Boston, but keep your seat belts
fastened, because there's another turbulent chapter being written.
</P>
<P>
   By now most of the staff, and many readers, too, are exhausted
by the calamitous and mystifying sequence of events that forced the
newspaper to demand the resignation of two Metro columnists found
guilty of fabricating people and quotations.
</P>
<P>
   This story is a monster that refuses to die: A reporter from
American Journalism Review has been in Boston for interviews. The
Phoenix is preparing an update for Thursday. Boston magazine is on
the newsstand with another long-winded article. Club Passim in
Cambridge sold every ticket for Saturday's presentation of poetry
by Patricia Smith billed as an unflinching look at her resignation
and the firestorm that followed. Barnicle, meanwhile, turned up
again on David Brudnoy's talk show and on WBZ-TV to explain to Bob
Lobel why he's happy the Red Sox made the playoffs. He also popped
up as a guest on WGBH-TV's ``Greater Boston'' for what turned out
to be a flatulent interview with an obsequious Emily Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   Although Barnicle was accused of several violations of ethics,
what forced his resignation was a 1995 column that described two
boys with cancer who became friends at Children's Hospital in 1994.
As Barnicle told the story, after the death of the black child, the
white family gave the black parents a check for $10,000. The column
contained quotations by the parents. Challenged in August, Barnicle
conceded that he'd never spoken to anyone in the family and that
the story had been told to him by a hospital employee, now dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe demanded his resignation, and rightly so, for even if
the story proved true, Barnicle was guilty of dishonesty for making
up quotations and also for writing as though he had interviewed the
family.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, a newspaper in Maine discovered a case that
bore a resemblance to Barnicle's story, although the details were
dramatically different: the Maine family is white, not black; the
amount of the check was $5,000, not $10,000; the boy was 5, not 9;
he died in 1987, not 1994; the cause was heart disease, not cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming vindication, Barnicle submitted a column to the op-ed
page of the Globe maintaining that his original story had been
true, although flawed in the telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used my memory to tell an honest story,'' he wrote in the
column submitted to the Globe. ``But clearly, this cannot be done
any longer in a business intent on wearing a one-size-fits-all suit
of standards. Every single day, good journalists make honest
mistakes reporting news and the letters to the editor box is
swollen with complaints about inaccuracies. Does this mean
reporters fail to grasp the meaning of changing standards? Or is it
simply that they are human?''
</P>
<P>
   The new Barnicle column set off a debate. Some editors said it
should be printed because Patricia Smith had been afforded the
courtesy of a goodbye column in which she apologized for her
misdeeds, although less penitently that many had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Others editors said no, that the Barnicle column added little
new information, that Barnicle's argument was specious. Moreover,
while Smith had acknowledged her transgression, Barnicle insisted
he had done nothing wrong and that, indeed, he was the victim
because his personal and professional life had been savaged for
what he called a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the publisher, Benjamin Taylor, decided the column
would not be printed. A few days later, Barnicle attempted to have
the column published in a full-page advertisement for which he was
willing to pay $36,000. The publisher vetoed that idea, too.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Globe not to make the Barnicle column
available to readers _ preferably on the op-ed page but at least as
an advertisement _ is a misjudgment for four reasons.
</P>
<P>
   First, Barnicle deserves no less an opportunity to explain
himself in a final column than Patricia Smith. It makes no
difference whether he admits to sin or not. The op-ed page is not a
confessional.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the fear that publication of the column would expose
readers to an unreasonable argument serves to underestimate
readers. From time to time they are exposed to unreasonable
arguments on Globe editorial pages without losing their capacity to
judge right from wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Third, by not publishing the Barnicle column the Globe sows
doubt even among loyal readers who may wonder whether the newspaper
has something to hide or whether the newspaper lacks the confidence
to defend its decision.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, the Globe has an honorable history of opening its
pages even to those with ideas that are disagreeable, offensive,
even wrong, and that is a reputation rigorously to be guarded.
</P>
<P>
   If the Globe cannot bring itself to provide space on the op-ed
page for Barnicle's column, it cannot in good conscience deny him
the right to express his thoughts in an advertisement. The Globe
could take Barnicle's $36,000, double it, and donate the sum to a
local university to be used to finance an annual conference on
ethics in journalism that would serve to remind all of us of our
allegiance to truth and to the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Jack Thomas is the Globe ombudsman and represents the readers.
His conclusions and opinions are his own.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
