<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-RETREAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE LEFT MARK ON NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST BASE, Maine _ There's a remote blueberry field here that
was once prime beachfront property, as its flat, wide-open sandy
expanse ringed by woods attests. But that was a long, long time
ago. Today, this sandy beach _ the remains of a river delta flowing
into the Atlantic _ sits 260 feet above sea level and about 10
miles in from the coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the best-preserved elevated shoreline in the
East,'' says geologist Harold Borns of the University of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   It is a graphic reminder of an era 12,000 years ago when the
Laurentide ice sheet that had blanketed North America for 100,000
years suddenly began to melt, dramatically raising the sea level
and pushing the ocean farther and farther inland. At the peak of
its advance, the Atlantic's waves reached nearly to the foot of Mt.
Katahdin, now almost 100 miles inland.
</P>
<P>
   This remote place got its name of East Base back in the 1850s
when Jefferson Davis, before he became the president of the
Confederacy, was a surveyor mapping the Maine coast and chose it as
the eastern end of a long survey baseline. But the unusual expanse
of flat, open meadow amid millions of acres of forest probably
attracted the attention of almost every human visitor to the
region; native Americans may have been harvesting blueberries here
millenia before the first Europeans arrived _ and may even have
noted its beachlike topography.
</P>
<P>
   It is not, however, the only place in the region marked by
seemingly out-of-place topography. New England's hills and fields
are etched with the story of glaciers advancing and retreating,
features intriguing enough to draw the attention of a group of 100
glaciologists, geologists and other scientists who last month
toured the coast while attending a conference on Antarctica at the
University of Maine in Orono. They were closely examining
formations that may help them better understand the geological
features that are being sculpted today by retreating glaciers
everywhere from Alaska to the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   The kinds of details they were looking at in the Maine soil may
play a part in unravelling questions that could have a bearing on
our future. Geologists believe the behavior of the West Antarctic
Ice Sheet, for example, may be critically affected by the precise
characteristics of the loose material underneath it _ material
similar to that left behind by glaciers as they retreated from New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Most prominent of the region's glacial remains are a series of
moraines _ straight ridges of sand and rock that run in dozens of
mostly-parallel lines along a strip 10 to 30 miles wide that hugs
the coast _ each marking a temporary edge of the vast ice sheet, as
it paused briefly in its fitful episodes of advance and retreat.
Like a conveyor belt, the glacier left these long piles of debris
behind as it slowly backed away.
</P>
<P>
   Similar features are seen throughout New England; the islands of
Martha's Vineyard and Nantucket, as well as Cape Cod itself, are
made up of moraines left at the ice sheet's edge.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many of Maine's roads are built along the crests of these
moraines, which provide high, straight and well-drained ridgelines
that extend for miles. But to the geologists, their complex
arrangements and cross-sections, occasionally exposed in a gravel
pit or a road cut, are a textbook _ albeit a sometimes cryptic one
_ on the dynamics of the glacier's centuries of back-and-forth
movements.
</P>
<P>
   After the sea rose and surged inland with the melting glaciers,
it then began a swift retreat _ not because the sea level sank
again, but because the land, relieved of the pressure of a layer of
ice two miles thick, began to rise. As it rebounded, it pushed the
seashore back, past its present boundary and far out onto the
continental shelf. Then, as the land stabilized, the rising sea
again began to move inland, slowly advancing to its present
position.
</P>
<P>
   The recent history of the sea's rise can be read in the dozens
of river estuaries along the Maine coast. As early as 1632, farmers
built dikes along these estuaries, enclosing fields to keep out the
saltwater so they could harvest hay and send it by barge to sell in
Boston's Haymarket.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the old dikes can be dated precisely through town
records, and their changing levels over the years give a precise
chronology of the changes in sea level. Borns and his colleagues
have found that one stretch of northern Maine, for example, has
been sinking at the rate of three feet per century _ a rate more
rapid than anywhere else in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   For scientists trying to decipher the meaning of changes in the
world's ice sheets today, and to forecast what they may portend for
changes in sea level over the coming centuries, understanding the
sequence of events and how quickly changes took place during the
glacial retreat in New England could provide important insights.
</P>
<P>
   The retreat of the Ice Age glaciers very closely resembled the
process that many geologists fear could someday happen in West
Antarctica. ``How soon can it happen, and how fast can it happen?''
asks Terence Hughes, a specialist in glacial movements at the
University of Maine. It's clear that dramatic changes in sea level
took place here over a span of a few thousand years, but recent
evidence suggests that much of the change may actually have taken
place in short, far more rapid bursts.
</P>
<P>
   Studying the retreat of the Laurentide ice sheet from North
America at the end of the last Ice Age may help to provide some
answers. And, says Hughes, ``the record of its collapse is right
here in these fields.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
