<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-PRIMARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA SHAKES UP PRIMARY SCHEDULE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the past 14 years, the presidential campaign
has been dominated by the mostly Southern, mostly conservative
Super Tuesday primary vote. The results now seem predictable: White
House terms for two conservative Republicans, Ronald Reagan and
George Bush, and two terms for one Southern Democrat, Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But with the stroke of a pen by California Governor Pete Wilson,
the presidential campaign has been radically altered. On March 7,
2000, just two weeks after the New Hampshire primary, a mighty,
mostly moderate bicoastal conglomeration of states is slated to
hold primaries that could go a long way toward determining the
nominees of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   While some New England officials expressed horror that
California will be voting on the same day as five ``Yankee Day''
states, the end result might help a moderate Republican or
Democrat, who has done well in the region but has not made as big
an impact on the national stage.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, as sometimes happens with changing political rules,
the result might turn out to be the opposite of what is intended.
</P>
<P>
   The change might make it impossible for all but well-funded
candidates to compete, giving a sizable advantage to wealthy
candidates like Steve Forbes, who financed his own campaign in
1996. A lesser-funded newcomer, on the other hand, would find it
difficult to gain notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that this will change the world,'' Republican
consultant Stuart Stevens said. ``The question is, what is this
world going to look like? I imagine the people happiest about this
is someone like Steve Forbes, a checkbook candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, if Wilson runs in 2000, and some of his allies
privately said he backed the primary plan to boost his chances,
then he would automatically be considered a ``favorite son''
candidate. That might prompt other prospects to write off the
state. Still, such a scenario could boost Wilson into the
front-runner category, if only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   The new primary schedule also affects Democrats. Vice President
Al Gore, probably the best-known and best-funded candidate, is such
an obvious beneficiary of the new calendar that many suspect he
helped engineer the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my adversaries in California have made it clear this
is a Gore initiative,'' said Massachusetts Secretary of State
William Galvin, who tried unsuccessfully to talk California
officials out of moving up the primary date.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides have said the vice president has nothing to do with
the California primary schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible Democratic beneficiary is Senator John F.
Kerry, who would be expected to do well in New England and also
might find a constituency in California and other states voting on
March 7. If Kerry taps the fortune of his wife, Teresa Heinz, he
could run a well-financed campaign blitz. Kerry has not ruled out
using his wife's money.
</P>
<P>
   ``On balance, this would be a strategic asset for John,'' said
John Marttila, a longtime Kerry adviser. ``His record and
background would have great appeal in a state like California ...
and he has raised a lot of money out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But the downside, Marttila said, is ``the fantastic pressure it
will put on fund-raising. This would give Gore an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the advantage of the March 7 grouping may be
overblown for Democrats. After all, former Massachusetts Governor
Michael Dukakis won the Democratic presidential nomination in 1988
under the old schedule that emphasized Southern conservative
states.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest impact is expected to be on the Republican side
because of the opening it may provide for moderates who have fared
poorly in recent presidential campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   If a moderate Republican such as William Weld had been drawing a
campaign game plan, he could hardly have come up with a better
scenario. Under the current plan, the 10 to 12 states that plan to
participate on March 7 are uniquely suited to boost a possible
candidate such as Weld or Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule also would benefit Texas Governor George W. Bush,
due partly to his name recognition and funding. The goveror also
could begin his campaign as a centrist who would not have to move
to the right during the Southern primaries, a strategy that would
help in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   The March 7 primary tentatively includes all the New England
states except New Hampshire, as well as California, New York,
Maryland, Colorado, and Georgia. Moreover, Wilson is trying to get
Oregon and Washington to join in, creating a Pacific primary on the
same day as a big Northeast vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
