<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF GOP GAINS 5 US SENATE SEATS, DEMOCRATS' HOPES SMOKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In next month's election, the key number is five.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republicans gain an additional five US Senate seats on
Nov. 3, they will have 60 _ the number needed to shut off floor
debate and pass whatever bills they want.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Senate Democrats can endlessley debate, or
filibuster, any measure they view as truly objectionable. The
threat of a filibuster is often enough to prompt Republicans to
compromise on, or even abandon, measures that have strong, unified
Democratic opposition.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the media's focus has been on whether the
Democrats will win a few more seats in the House of Representatives
_ or maybe even regain control there _ the higher stakes are in the
Senate, where 60 seats are in striking range of the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   If, on the other hand, Democrats were to gain five Senate seats,
they would regain control of the chamber. And that, of course,
could stop the GOP agenda in its tracks, and could provide an
opportunity for Democrats to get their bills passed and signed into
law by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   These five seats are also important to his future. This
election, as both parties suggest, is a referendum on whether the
GOP has gone too far in its efforts to humiliate Clinton, as it has
proceeded toward an impeachment inquiry. Democratic victories will
answer ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why the president, Hillary Rodham Clinton, and many
other key Democrats are making an all-out effort to bolster their
party's chances of gaining seats in the House and, at the very
least, stop the GOP from adding five Senate seats.
</P>
<P>
   For organized labor and working families, the loss of five
Senate seats to the GOP could be disastrous. That GOP majority
could pass the so-called Team Employees and Management Act _ or
TEAM Act _ which would replace strong unions with very weak, sham
company unions. Not to mention other legislation, already filed,
denying workers overtime pay until they had worked 80 hours in a
week, rather than 40.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican 60-seat majority could repeal the Davis-Bacon Act,
which has long protected the prevailing wage for public
construction projects. With this repeal, the average nationwide
prevailing wage of $30,000 could be reduced even further.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a strengthened GOP could pass legislation weakening
labor's ability to help raise money for its congressional
supporters, or to counter misleading GOP advertising campaigns
aimed at passing anti-union legislation, including a bill that
would abolish the right of workers to organize into a union.
</P>
<P>
   On other matters, a 60-40 GOP majority could help Republicans
pass bills that would allow the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration to fine workers, not employers, for safety
violations _ and exempt employers from complying with OSHA laws.
</P>
<P>
   Pension funds could be raided by employers, and social security
could be privatized. Any Democratic efforts to pass bills aimed at
significantly improving family access to affordable health care
would likely be doomed.
</P>
<P>
   The list of potential disasters goes on and on. But some
Democrats are focusing not only on how they can prevent the loss of
five seats, but also on how to win five seats _ and regain control
of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In a Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee fund-raising
letter, political director Steve Hildebrand suggests several
scenarios to ``Take Back the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hildebrand writes that of the 34 Senate seats being contested
this year, 14 are held by Republicans, 15 by Democrats and five are
``open'' _ that is, with no incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic scenario involves these states:
</P>
<P>
   _Arkansas _ where an open seat is being sought by Democrat
Blanche Lambert Lincoln, a former two-term congresswoman, and
Republican Fay Boozman, a conservative who, according to
Hildebrand, is viewed as being ``to the right of Jesse Helms'' and
is considered extreme even by many Republicans. A Democratic
committee poll this summer gave Lincoln a 31-point lead over
Boozman.
</P>
<P>
   _Indiana _ where an open seat is being sought by two-term
Governor Evan Bayh, a Democrat, and Paul Hemke, a Republican. Bayh,
Hildebrand writes, ``is well-positioned to win this race.''
</P>
<P>
   _Colorado _ where GOP incumbent Ben Nighthorse Campbell is
challenged by Democrat Dottie Lamm, wife of Richard Lamm, the
former governor. Campbell's campaign reportedly suffers ``from his
highly-publicized switch to the Republican Party after winning the
1992 election as a Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   _Georgia _ where Republican incumbent Paul Coverdell, considered
by Democrats to be vulnerable because of his ultraconservative
stands, is up against Michael Coles, a businessman who ran a
credible race against House Speaker Newt Gingrich two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   _Missouri _ where a popular Democratic hopeful, Attorney General
Jay Nixon, is challenging incumbent Senator Kit Bond.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee hopes
to raise enough money to help reelect 15 incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   As Hildebrand and other Democrats know, it will be difficult to
regain control of the Senate, particularly in this, an off year.
But with enough financial support, some Democrats could make the
new class elected this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining some of these five ``best bet'' Senate seats would, at
the very least, offset other losses. But even if the Democrats fail
to gain any seats, keeping the number at 55-45 would at least
assure that the Democratic debate goes on.
</P>
<P>
   That is a far better outcome than seeing the GOP boost its
strength by that key number five.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
