A9842 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-05 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO CAN GET THROUGH TO THIS COLD, HARD CASH? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Refiling to add dropped text)   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It is natural to want to hang a ``monster'' sign
around the neck of David Cash Jr., to disavow any connection
between him and the rest of the human race. And, because there is
no law with which to punish him, it is instinctive to hope that he
somehow disappears from our midst as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-year-old sophomore at the University of California at
Berkeley seems a perfect candidate for societal abandonment, a man
beyond our capabilities to, as Shelley put it, ``forgive wrongs
darker than death or night.'' Guilty of an unfathomable failure of
morality, David Cash remains remorseless and without regret.
</P>
<P>
   On May 25, 1997, in a Las Vegas casino women's room, Cash
watched from an adjacent toilet stall as his best friend restrained
a struggling 7-year-old girl and smothered her screams with one
hand. Although he has altered his story since, saying he never
believed the child's life was in danger, Cash earlier told a Nevada
grand jury: ``I didn't know what to expect _ something bad. I
probably feared the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cash walked out of the restroom and left 7-year-old Sherrice
Iverson to her fate: sexual molestation and death by strangulation.
According to two of Cash's former high school pals, Cash told them
he watched the sexual molestation. Cash himself told Nora Zamichow
of the Los Angeles Times that, just before he and his friend,
Jeremy Strohmeyer, joined Cash's father for a car ride back to the
young men's homes in Long Beach, Cash asked his friend if Sherrice
had been sexually aroused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you ask if the little girl was aroused?'' the Times
reporter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, it's just the way I think,'' Cash answered.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Strohmeyer pleaded guilty to Sherrice's molestation
and murder, and received a life sentence without possibility of
parole. Cash, who committed no crime by refusing to interfere and
by staying silent about the murder, has meanwhile managed to
fashion himself into a one-dimensional cut-out of a fiend. On radio
talk shows, in newspaper interviews, alongside an even-handed but
quietly horrified Ed Bradley during ``60 Minutes,'' the young man
continues to reveal his personal moral vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   He says he feels sorrier for Strohmeyer than for the murdered
child _ after all, he didn't know her. He once said his newfound
notoriety makes it easier to ``score with women.'' He says he just
wants to get on with his life, majoring in, of all things, nuclear
engineering. He says if he had it to do over again, he'd make the
same choices.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Cash turns his pale, unexceptional face to the world
and does not say, ``I'm sorry, I did a horrible thing,'' the easier
he is to hate, the more we want to wash our hands of him. Clearly,
this boy-man is not lying or in denial; he does not believe he did
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   After Cash's ``60 Minutes'' appearance, local television
stations interviewed many of his fellow students. Their reactions
spanned the emotional spectrum, from outrage to indifference. One
thoughtful young man told a TV reporter: ``There is something real
wrong with this guy. He needs help.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he does. Further, we as a society need for him to be
helped. A civilized, healthy society comprised not just of human
animals, but of conscious, moral human beings, needs for David Cash
to comprehend the enormity of his moral breach and to stagger under
the burden of that understanding. We need to witness this more than
we need any physical punishment (legal or vigilante) that might now
be exacted on him. We certainly need it more than we need for him
to ``put this behind'' him, masquerade as a normal person and take
an undergraduate degree in nuclear engineering.
</P>
<P>
   But who will help Cash? Who will try to invade and break open
his frozen heart? Who will attempt to find his soul? If his parents
were up to the job, we likely would have seen something of them by
now. It appears they have not stepped forward to publicly denounce
their son or reaffirm their love for him. Their absence _ as their
boy digs himself in deeper on the talk shows, in the newspaper
interviews, on ``60 Minutes'' _ indicates their impotence, gross
stupidity or suspect moral integrity.
</P>
<P>
   So, to whom does the task fall? Is Cash's best hope for
comprehending what he has done tucked away in organized religion?
In legitimate psychotherapy? Somewhere in the great public
University of California? Isn't there someone among us, some group
of people, who understands what is wrong with David Cash Jr. and
has the experience or expertise to attempt to reach him?
</P>
<P>
   God knows, any member of the human race has the moral authority
to try.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
