<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9848 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ECONOMY-BOS &LR;      10-05 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECONOMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD TURNS SPOTLIGHT   ON A PRECARIOUS BRAZIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO _ The world is watching to see if Brazil can
avoid fiscal disaster. If it falls, it will take with it many of
the regional economies and further threaten a global market
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando Henrique Cardoso was expected to defeat his
nearest rival, Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, easily. ``He's the one
who fixed the economy before and he's the best one to fix it
again,'' said Adalberto Moreisa, a 27-year-old electronics store
clerk.
</P>
<P>
   That is a tall order.
</P>
<P>
   The last three months have brought Carnaval-like gyrations to
its $800 billion economy, the world's eighth largest. The country's
financial market, the Bovespa, has lost more than 30 percent of its
value since the beginning of the year. Interest rates have more
than doubled, to over 50 percent, and foreign investors have pulled
out more than $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the early market panic in August was, as officials here
argued, a result of the crises in Asia and Russia. But Brazil's own
flaws have become more apparent as it has moved into the world
spotlight, and preserving its economy has become a leading topic
among President Clinton and other world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some gains in privatization and economic policies, the
government deficit has mushroomed to $100 billion. The currency,
most agree, is overvalued. And the gap between the wealthy and the
poor has become the largest in the region.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is how quickly Cardoso can unite a fragmented Brazilian
Congress _ notorious for its horse-trading members who seldom
follow party lines _ to pass badly needed constitutional reforms to
reduce the country's whopping deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the fiscal adjustments we need to make depend on how
quickly we can get constitutional reform,'' said Jose Antonio Pena
Garcia, chief economist for BankBoston in Brazil. ``Reform takes
longer here because the president has to negotiate with different
parties and with different interests within the same party.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 parties have at least one representative in
Congress, and politicians switch their affiliations regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso, a former Marxist and now member of the center-left
Social Democratic Party, needs a strong showing by his five-party
centrist coalition to push through constitutional reforms necessary
to lure back frightened investors who have withdrawn billions of
dollars over the last two months and to bolster the country's
shaken currency, the real.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks largely to privatization and administrative reforms that
were adopted in the 1988 constitution, and to a currency
stabilization plan that Cardoso implemented in 1994, Brazil has
enjoyed several consecutive years of economic growth and lower
inflation. But federal spending has risen dramatically, and Brazil
now runs a deficit equaling 7 percent of the country's gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   To cut the deficit, the Cardoso administration has promised to
deliver three major constitutional amendments. The first would
alter civil service rules to trim payrolls by requiring workers to
be evaluated and fired if they fail their reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The second amendment would reduce Brazil's generous social
security and pension system, which now absorbs about 1 percent of
GDP and carries a $24 billion deficit, by capping benefits and
requiring workers to contribute more to help pay for the growing
number of recipients who are living longer.
</P>
<P>
   The third and most controversial plan would simplify the
nation's tax structure and shift a larger percentage of costs for
services to state and local governments.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil imposes about 60 different taxes. This makes tax evasion
easy and pervasive, according to Pena. Although the 1988
constitution provided the provinces with millions of dollars in
additional funds, many locally distributed services, such as health
care, remain heavily subsidized by federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts believe Cardoso can pursuade the Senate,
which is generally pro-Cardoso, to approve the proposals. Eleven
days ago, leaders of the Senate and lower Chamber of Deputies stood
with Cardoso and backed the amendments.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, however, may be among the rank-and-file members
of the lower house, where there is a larger and more vocal
opposition from the left, and from many of the 5,500 municipal
leaders who don't want to shoulder more expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working hard to reduce our expenses, and this is
the opposite of what we're fighting for,'' said Sao Paulo Mayor
Celso Pitta do Nascimento. ``We mayors make a strong group, and we
won't let this pass easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who support the reforms offer dire warnings if the
measures are not passed soon: Investors who have deserted the
markets will stay away, interest rates will continue to skyrocket,
and the real will spiral downward.
</P>
<P>
   David Cleary, a historian at Harvard University, said that a
currency crisis might be the catalyst needed to unite Brazil's
assorted political interests. ``The left-wing will likely make lots
of noise, but the people are worried about losing the gains of the
past few years,'' Cleary said.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree that the real is overvalued, but there is no
consensus about how much it needs to be adjusted. (Currently, $1 US
equals about 1.20 reais.) Economists have predicted devaluations
ranging from 10 to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A devaluation would hurt the United States, which sells a fifth
of its exports to Brazil, because US products would become more
expensive for Brazilian consumers. And the United States is
Brazil's top trading partner after the European Union. Any drop in
the real will also affect other Latin American markets, especially
Argentina and Mexico, which like Brazil have tried hard in recent
years to attract and keep investors' dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Brazil's 163 million people fear that any help from
foreign sources such as the International Monetary Fund would come
with the brutal discipline they experienced in the 1980s, when the
IMF bailed them out from triple-digit inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But Nancy A. Bush, a banking analyst and senior vice president
at Ryan, Beck &AMP; Co. in New Jersey, said Brazil's climate is far
different from a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political situation is stronger now and officials are
being more honest,'' Bush said. ``There are problems, but it's not
like we saw before when even the country's leaders were sending
their own capital out of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Already there are different financing plans being discussed for
Brazil, notably a $30 billion loan package from the IMF, the US
Federal Reserve, and private banks. But the Cardoso administration
has not yet publicly asked for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso may make such a request this week if he avoids a runoff
election for a second four-year term by winning at least 51 percent
of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Any backlash against the incumbent over a currency devaluation
or a stiff IMF package probably will not last long. Unlike
Indonesia's Suharto, who was forced from office because of the
economic crisis, or Russia's Boris N. Yeltsin, whose power has been
severely diminished, Cardoso still enjoys broad popularity,
especially among the country's poorer residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fernando Henrique was the one who strengthened us when we were
weak,'' said Elza dos Santos, a Sao Paulo street vendor. ``We'll
have to see if he can make another miracle happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
