<HEADLINE>
NEW AND RECOMMENDED RECENTLY REVIEWED BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ``Birds of America'' &LR;  by Lorrie Moore (Knopf, $23). In a
collection of stories, the woes and triumphs of characters who
sound like people we know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Lindbergh''  &LR; by A. Scott Berg (Putnam, $30). An understated
biography of an extraordinary life _ the ultimate American hero,
always at the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Complete Novels &LR; , &UR; '' ``Stories, Essays &AMP; Memoir'' &LR;  by Eudora
Welty (Library of America, $35 each). The first living writer to be
published in the prestigious series, Welty deserves such symbolic
permanence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Farming of Bones''  &LR; by Edwidge Danticat (Soho Press,
$23). The 1937 massacre of Haitians in the Dominican Republic
provides the background for this evocative second novel, which
mediates between nightmare and poetry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Bill Evans: How My Heart Sings'' &LR;  by Peter Pettinger (Yale
University Press, $30). This biography is the perfect companion for
understanding the brilliant jazz pianist in the most important way,
through listening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
