A9857 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-WHITFIELD-BOS &LR;      10-05 1732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-WHITFIELD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITFIELD SINGS ON THE `WICKED STAGE' OF CABARET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wesla Whitfield has brought back a lost art by making old songs
sound new every time she sings them.
</P>
<P>
   Perched on stools in rooms still dark but no longer smoky,
Whitfield performs songs as conversations with her husband,
arranger-pianist Mike Greensill; with the other musicians; with the
composers and lyricists; with the audience; and, most of all, with
her own experience. Her voice is deep-rooted as a tree, as
responsive to the breath of emotion as a leaf in the wind, and
sweet as sap. Whitfield sings it like it is; she has known despair
and hope, and she's come out a cockeyed optimist. As she sings
``When You Wish Upon a Star,'' you believe your dreams will come
true because she does, and hers did.
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield, now 51, emerged in the piano bars of San Francisco in
the early 1970s when she was a member of the chorus of the San
Francisco Opera.
</P>
<P>
   (In those days, and indeed until quite recently, her first name,
always pronounced ``Wesla,'' was spelled ``Weslia.'' Not long ago,
Whitfield met the friend of her mother's for whom she was named,
and learned that the older woman spelled her name the way it was
pronounced; Whitfield decided that sounded good to her, and she's
made the change.)
</P>
<P>
   During the '80s, Whitfield became a West Coast phenomenon and
her self-produced recordings began to trickle eastward. By the
'90s, she was touring regularly, appearing prominently in New York.
She has sung in Carnegie Hall, and Hillary Clinton invited her to
sing in the White House. Last year she made her Boston debut at
Scullers, captivating the audience with the warmth of her voice and
personality, the immediacy of her emotions, the gentleness of her
humor. She returns there Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, People published a profile of Whitfield that may
have been the first timemany fans of her recordings learned that
in 1977 she had been shot in the back by kids playing with a gun,
and that she has been paralyzed from the waist down ever since.
This had never been mentioned in the biographical material in any
of her albums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should it?'' Whitfield said recently during a phone
conversation from her home in California. ``It's got nothing to do
with my music. The thing I've come to realize _ you can write this
down _ is that life is unfair. No matter how good I get as a
singer, it is always going to be qualified by my disability, and
that's what's unfair. So my way of railing against it, very gently,
is not to make an issue of it. I cook and run the vacuum cleaner
because I gotta. There's really only one thing I can't do, I can't
walk, and that's not very limiting at all, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield said the impulse to be a singer ``was always there,
from the age of 3. The piano was my first instrument, and I got as
far as John Thompson's Red Book No.4. I was not one of those
brilliant prodigies because my heart wasn't in it, but it was a
fabulous foundation for later. My mother had all this sheet music
in the piano bench, and I used the songs for sight reading, and I
loved them. In high school I sang in the chorus and in my senior
year I was Fiona in a production of `Brigadoon.' My voice was a
high soprano _ it still is, but not in public _ and my heroine was
Beverly Sills. I had a small voice and I learned a million tricks
to make myself heard.''
</P>
<P>
   At San Francisco State, Whitfield majored in music and took
drama classes; from there she went straight into the chorus of the
San Francisco Opera. ``It wasn't as impressive as it sounds, but it
was a union gig, so I made really nice money. I thought singing in
the chorus might get me somewhere, but from the chorus, you don't
graduate into anything. But I was just out of school, and what did
I know? Still, it was a fabulous experience to stand behind such
people as Beverly Sills, Joan Sutherland, and Shirley Verrett, and
I can say that I sang with all three tenors.''
</P>
<P>
   After performances, Whitfield found herself gravitating to the
piano bars. ``In the opera, all anyone thought about was `the
voice'; in the piano bars, the most important thing was the song,
and that's where my heart was. I still warm up with my old
exercises everyday and still sing the little Italian art songs I
started out with _ they keep everything open and free. I want to
keep in good vocal shape because that's the only way I will be able
to convey everything I want to convey. My voice keeps stretching _
I can still sing up to high C, and now I can go down to E-flat
below middle C, which believe me I could never have done back when
I was in college. I vocalise at the top to make the middle
stronger. Because I vocalise, I know I'm not going to get too
tired, or catch up in my throat. My classical training gives me a
fabulous leg up.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Frank Sinatra always liked to say; he wanted to sing
with a pop sound and a classical technique. Whitfield admits she
had something to learn about popular styles. ``I always wanted to
be something other than Kathy Lee Gifford, but I was certainly
going down that road until I met my husband Mike Greensill. I
didn't have any sense of how to interpret the songs in something
other than a completely literal way.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield explains how she works with Greensill. ``We both find
songs we might like, and each of us tries to have a clear idea of
how to do it before we talk to each other. We're going to have to
defend our own point of view, and we say things to each other that
we would not say to any other musician _ getting better at what we
do is the most important thing in the world to each of us. We try
it each other's way _ and I always win. Then he makes an
arrangement, and we rehearse it until we either say it's time to
take it out into the light of day, or throw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Greensill's arrangements are sophisticated, swinging, literate,
and often surprising _ ballads get shaken out; upbeat tunes reveal
a core of sadness. Whitfield had worked with Greensill often before
they married in 1986. ``It wasn't a great romantic moment _ after
all, we were both married to other people at the time. He came into
a club where I was working in 1981 and was invited to sit in. He
did some arrangements for me and I invited him to play for little
gigs I was doing. We began working together regularly and became
very good friends for four years. Then, all of a sudden, we looked
at each other in a different way and realized we were in very deep
do-do. Both of us are very nice people, so we were very proper
about it; we didn't have a dalliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting in 1985, Whitfield and Greensill made their own albums
for sale at their performances. ``We called our label Myoho, a
Buddhist term for `constant reality changing phenomenon.' The CDs
were a calling card, a record of what it is we do. After we had
done three of these, Orrin Keepnews at HighNote got interested in
us, and put us on his label. We've just finished our 11th album,
which should be out by the time we get to Boston. It's called `High
Standards.'''
</P>
<P>
   Recently Whitfield and Greensill have been working on an
autobiographical show, ``Life Upon the Wicked Stage.'' ``We had our
first runthrough last night. I've written the text, which is about
my life and about my life onstage, and we have pictures of me at
various times. I talk and wave my arms around. But mostly I sing;
the songs, and there are 15 or 16 of them, come in at just the
right moment. We're hoping to go around the college circuit and
into concert halls with this. In those venues, people come to
listen instead of drink, and we live for people who listen.''
</P>
<P>
   The heyday of cabaret singing came in the '30s and '40s;
survivors of the era kept the art alive through the 1970s. The new
generation has produced some adroit mimics and some spectacular
exercises in self-delusion, but not much that is personal and
therefore inimitable. Whitfield is an exception _ she has heard
everything and everyone, but she never tries to sound like anyone
else. She feels the real source of the resurgence of interest in
this art form is the literature itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Popular music in the early and middle 1950s was abysmal,''
Whitfield recalls. ``It wasn't Eddie Fisher's fault, the stuff he
sang; even Rosemary Clooney sang junk. In that context rock sounded
very exciting, and I have a great respect for rock of that era _ it
had a beat, but before long the beat obliterated everything else.
The reason the old songs are coming back is its great strength,
something we've also seen in country music, and that's that these
songs tell a story and tell it truthfully. Lorenz Hart writing in
1930 still speaks directly to every man and woman who's ever been
in and out of love. That's why this music is coming back and people
are liking it; that's why Carly Simon is making albums of
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield harbors no illusions about the glamor of nightclubs,
although she loves singing in them. ``In the movies, the girl
singer sings one song in a room that is completely filled and with
a 20-piece orchestra you never see and she's a star overnight. We
all play those movies in our heads, even though the reality is so
different. The small clubs, like Scullers, have always been run out
of love, and that will always be true.''
</P>
<P>
   Today Whitfield performs about 150 nights a year, and would like
to do more. ``We do OK. We'd love more money, of course, but it's
mostly for our own satisfaction. The day will come when I'm not
able to do it anymore, so I have to do it now.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she harbors no bitterness about the 12-year-old boys,
never caught, who shot her that night in 1977. She told People,
``They were kids who were out alone with guns. That tells you
something about what their lives are like. I know _ and this isn't
meant to sound Pollyannish _ that my experiences have been better
than anything that could have come their way. If they are alive,
they are in prison. And I've had this fabulous life.'' Today,
Whitfield says, ``The Boston Globe isn't calling them up. I haven't
been through any more than most other people; what happened to me
was just more dramatic. Yes, it ages you; yes, it molds you; yes,
it mooshes your brain around. That's what life does _ if you're
lucky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
