<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-DREAMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBIN WILLIAMS' JOURNEY FROM HEAVEN TO HELL LACKS ORIGINALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being in heaven alone, without the one you love _ that would be
hell, wouldn't it? It's a great idea for a movie, and ``What Dreams
May Come'' uses this thought as its story. Director Vincent Ward, a
New Zealander with a silvery visual aptitude, has made this theme
his own province in previous work _ he seems to seek it out.
</P>
<P>
   In his film ``Map of the Human Heart,'' he featured a
protagonist who had a taste of heaven and had it snatched it away.
That also happens to Chris (Robin Williams), who meets the woman he
falls in love with while sailing alone _ and his heaven on earth
begins immediately.
</P>
<P>
   After losing their two children in a car accident, Chris and his
wife (Annabella Sciorra) slump into lives of quiet misery. Then
Chris dies while helping at the site of a car crash. (It's the best
scene in ``Dreams''; Ward's ability for shifting mood swiftly
serves him well here.)
</P>
<P>
   Working with a group of technical wizards, Ward has found a way
to create a screen tableau that looks like an Impressionist
painting that hasn't quite dried. It's a visualization of an
incomplete heaven _ Chris' wife was a painter, and he's plopped
down into a realization of one of her paintings.
</P>
<P>
   But before long, ``What Dreams May Come'' settles into an almost
morbid sentimentality. A blurry presence trying to help Chris
reconcile himself to the idea of being dead turns out to be Albert
(Cuba Gooding Jr.), his medical school mentor. (Although at first,
Gooding sounds so much like Michael Jackson that you think his idea
of heaven may be an episode of ``Pop-Up Video.'')
</P>
<P>
   The first section of the movie drips Nutrasweet from time to
time, but you have no preparation for the gooeyness that rolls out
in waves after that. With bodies floating and gamboling as huge,
light-splashed stairs and arches loom in the distance, heaven looks
like the McDonald's at the Mall of America.
</P>
<P>
   When Chris' wife kills herself, he discovers that she's going to
hell _ not just because she's a suicide, but because hell is the
place for people who haven't forgiven themselves, which, of course,
explains why heaven turns out to be so empty.
</P>
<P>
   Chris and Albert, along with a guide (Max von Sydow), make the
journey to reclaim Chris' wife from hell. They pass through horrid
spots that make the voyage a religious version of a mixed metaphor:
They sail over a river full of lost souls, themselves rendered in
black and white, that seems like the River Styx as re-created for
an Obsession ad.
</P>
<P>
   Their boat is appropriately named Cerberus, and you can't help
wondering whether Chris knows of von Sydow's having played Death in
Bergman movies.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps there's such a need for comparisons because ``Dreams''
seems so second-hand, despite fitful moments of originality. Those
brief, unique moments _ be it a damp, painted Dreamland, or Chris'
last view of his kids driving away, both shimmery and sad, or an
expanse of land that turns out to be made out of faces (purgatory)
_ make the prevailing lumpiness all the more frustrating. Ward's
talents don't include consistency, which is his biggest problem in
``Dreams,'' an inoffensive, suburban turn on ``Paradise Lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Matheson, from whose novel the movie comes, has also
written about loss and the journey back to acceptance with more a
bent toward science fiction than we see here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreams'' is supposed to be about resilience, but there are so
many crinkly faces smiling through the tears that it feels
unremitting in its winsomeness. Williams plays it mostly straight
here. He's a nice guy, too nice to be so driven. Everyone in the
movie is very nice, so it robs the actors of weight.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dreams,'' heaven drifts slowly _ very slowly _ into the
Talking Heads definition, a place where nothing ever happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Dreams May Come'' is rated PG-13 for adult language and
scenes of violence and death.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``What Dreams May Come'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 of a possible 5 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Director: Vincent Ward &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Robin Williams, Cuba Gooding Jr. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
