<HEADLINE>
ANTICHOICE REPUBLICANS PLAY DANGEROUS GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- More scenes from Newt Gingrich's dysfunctional
House:
</P>
<P>
   _Late Thursday evening, the forces of revolution and anarchy
inside the conservative movement's tent were able to prevent
legislation paying for the basic operations of the government from
even coming to a final vote. The measure split the Republican
majority more than in half, with the antis in control for the
moment.
</P>
<P>
   _Well into Friday, legislation paying for the country's farm
programs, including special assistance for drought and other
economic disaster victims, languished among Senate and House
negotiators. The intransigent bad guys, as usual, were members of
Gingrich's perpetually petulant majority.
</P>
<P>
   And in both these cases of Marx Brothers government, the major
reason was the same: the dirty, petty, increasingly vicious,
so-called politics of abortion. While one bunch of Gingrich's
majority is obsessed with investigating sex, another seems equally
obsessed with regulating sex and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's problem got a certain amount of media attention
because it combined cruelty with absurdity in an effort to keep
female federal employees from having access to health insurance
plans offering contraceptive services. This bit of government
micromanagement of family life would have occurred at the same time
federal worker insurance plans are competing without right-wing
interference to offer sexually excited guys coverage for their
Viagra pills.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an effort led by Representative Nita Lowey, Democrat
of New York, this attempt has so far gone nowhere and, thanks to
Thursday's chaotic vote, is even less likely to, which one hopes
will permit more attention to focus on the far more pernicious
politics being played with the agriculture legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In this behind-the-scenes fight, the bad guy is Dr. Tom Coburn,
Republican of Oklahoma, who dishonors the Muskogee-based seat held
for a decade by an independent populist adept at bipartisanship,
the late Mike Synar. Coburn's Web site includes a lengthy account
of his activities in promotion of abstinence, but his real work is
in subversion of a woman's constitutional right to choose.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn's latest game is to attach to the farm bill a provision
barring the Food and Drug Administration from doing research,
testing, or anything else (including approval for sale) involving
drugs ``for the chemical inducement of abortion.'' It passed the
House narrowly in June, and supporters refused to let the overall
bill go forward to final passage without it. The Republicans gave
up late Friday, but only after loud protests that they were
delaying aid to farmers.
</P>
<P>
   This is an excellent example of what happens when political
movement language gets into legislation. Another is the political
invention of ``partial birth abortion.'' And in neither case is the
remedy proposed targeted on the outrage claimed by right-to-lifers.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of late-term abortion methods, the bill Clinton
successfully vetoed would have invaded medical decisions early in
pregnancy, and ignored health consequences for women later on _
both concepts being flagrantly illegal under Roe v. Wade and
regularly found to be so by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   In Coburn's case, his proposal may appear aimed at the
abortifacient drug RU-486, but its blunderbuss impact would be much
wider. Opponents, led by Representative Rosa DeLauro, Democrat of
Connecticut, have marshaled an impressive array of evidence _ from
drug companies, the FDA, and the medical community _ that Coburn
would end up targeting drugs whose side effects as opposed to
purpose can include miscarriage.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, as DeLauro has summarized these professional
views, we're now talking about pregnant women with cancer who
undergo a broad variety of chemotherapy treatments; we also could
be talking hypertension, cirrhosis, arthritis, venous thrombosis,
ulcers, epilepsy, uterine fibrosis, ectopic pregnancies, and severe
viral infections. In addition, De Lauro said his proposal would
strip the FDA of its important responsibility to monitor research
and testing the drug companies themselves do on potential new
products designed to induce miscarriages without surgical
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   For all those reasons, it is very hard to imagine anything like
the Coburn monstrosity becoming law. Such a prediction is even
easier in the case of the contraceptive insurance coverage issue,
because both houses of Congress are already on record in support.
</P>
<P>
   However, the real point is the increasing bitterness of
antichoice politics, and the extent to which Gingrich's House
enables the movement's obstructionism. Playing legislative games
with flagrantly illegal and cruel proposals that single out
vulnerable people attempting to exercise a constitutional right is
beneath contempt.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
