<HEADLINE>
HOW TO ESCAPE THE DELUGE OF JUNK MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Refiling to add dropped text)   (EDs: Graphic available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID UHLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Benjamin Franklin was only two-thirds right when
he noted that nothing in this world is certain but death and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   He never got any junk mail.
</P>
<P>
   More politely referred to as direct mail, the mass-marketing
technique of unsolicited catalogs, advertisements and letters
(``Congratulations, Mr. Franklin! You've Won $30 Million!!!'')
hadn't yet been invented when the author, statesman and founding
father wrote about life's certainties in 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   If he had known about junk mail, perhaps old Ben _ who also
served as our country's first postmaster general _ might have done
something about it.
</P>
<P>
   Today, plenty of cost-conscious consumers and coupon clippers
look forward to the daily flow of fliers, advertising slicks and
colorful catalogs in their mailboxes.
</P>
<P>
   For everyone else, however, there are hundreds of books and
Internet sites that offer tips and tricks to stop direct mail,
telemarketing phone calls and unwanted computer e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can stop it,'' said Marc Eisenson, co-author of ``Stop
Junk Mail Forever'' (Telemarketing &AMP; Spam, Too). ``But you've got
to be vigilant and keep on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why junk mail keeps flowing and telephone solicitors
don't take ``no'' for an answer:
</P>
<P>
   _ Direct marketing in the United States yielded nearly $1.3
trillion in sales in 1997, according to a survey by the WEFA Group,
one of the world's largest economic information and consulting
firms.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consumers responding to direct mail solicitations spent $244.3
billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1996, 62.1 percent of all women made a catalog sales
purchase, as did 50.6 of all men.
</P>
<P>
   You live, therefore you get junk mail. It's that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Buy a new car. Apply for a credit card. Fill out a warranty
form. Change your address. Have a baby. When you buy something at a
store and the clerk asks for your name and address, rest assured
you are not being added to the company's holiday card list. Dozens
of daily activities land unwitting people on the massive lists of
the world's direct mailers and marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, the difference between junk mail and direct
mail is in the mailbox of the beholder.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Cox Target Media in Florida, which franchises
the Val-Pak mail operations around the country, said ``people call
all the time to get on the mailing list.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They want the coupons,'' said Chuck Relyea, address
information manager for Val-Pak. The coupons in Val-Pak come from
small local companies, ``mom-and-pop'' businesses that share the
envelope with other advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at ADVO Inc., another big direct mail marketer, say
surveys show that 75 percent of people read advertising mail and 34
percent make purchases based on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often think people don't want clutter in their mailboxes,''
said Brian Sanders, chief marketing officer for ADVO in
Connecticut. ``But the reality is people want information.
Consumers today want to make smart choices when they buy
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Vesna Huzovic, media relations manager for the Direct Marketing
Association, said the organization's 4,100 members ``are trying to
provide a service and give something to somebody who is interested
specifically in that topic area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not trying to send something about cat food to a dog
lover,'' Huzovic said. ``They want that information to go to a cat
lover. If someone called or wrote to the direct mailer and said,
`Stop sending me information about cat food,' they'd be more than
happy to oblige.''
</P>
<P>
   One way to stop the deluge of solicitations is to write to the
association, asking that your name be removed from direct mail
lists (also include your telephone number). The address is: Mail
Preference Service, c/o Direct Mail Marketing Association, P.O. Box
9008, Farmingdale, N.Y. 11735-9008.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
