<SLUG> BC-COACH-ACCUSED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S SPORTS ON TRIAL AS UNC COACH FACES SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ A jubilant coach hugs a smiling player after
winning a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   A photo of that innocent embrace appeared in a glossy guide to
women's soccer at the University of North Carolina. But that was
before the most dominant team in women's sports lost its sense of
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the photo has disappeared, deleted from this year's guide
in response to a lawsuit by two former players who say they were
sexually harassed and emotionally abused by coach Anson Dorrance, a
legend in the world of women's athletics. Dorrance denies the
charges, and the school is standing behind him along with more than
100 current and former players.
</P>
<P>
   As Dorrance fights to clear his name, and the plaintiffs battle
to force his ouster and win $12 million in damages, the lawsuit is
reverberating far beyond Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does it involve a coaching icon, it comes at a time of
soaring popularity of women's sports, a simultaneous drop in the
percentage of female coaches, and a heightened concern about the
balance of sexual power in workplaces, classrooms, and now, even on
playing fields.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the lawsuit has jolted school sports programs
nationwide, particularly among women's teams with male coaches, as
participants wonder how to preserve the bonds between coaches and
players, without trampling appropriate boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one knows what the truth is about Anson Dorrance,'' said
Donna Lopiano, executive director of the Women's Sports Foundation
in New York. ``But it's obvious this whole issue of intimate
relationships by authority figures with students or people who are
working for them is one that is causing great concern and a lot of
soul-searching, and rightfully so.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, though, there are more immediate worries, such as the
reputation of a university steeped in sporting tradition, and the
future of a sports dynasty that has won 15 national titles in 17
years. Former UNC men's basketball coach Dean Smith, a giant in the
game, said only half-jokingly last year that ``this is a women's
soccer school. We're just trying to keep up with them.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the small concerns. Consider the fate of the
hugging photo, which appeared in the team's 1997 media guide.
</P>
<P>
   Neither plaintiff is the player being hugged by Dorrance. Yet,
rather than using it in this year's guide, the school substituted a
photo of Dorrance standing by himself. ``You don't want people
taking things the wrong way,'' said Dave Lohse, UNC director of
media relations for Olympic sports.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in federal court in Chicago, near the homes
of both women, involves two ex-UNC players: scoring star Debbie
Keller, 23, a ``Carolina legend'' who now plays on the US National
Team, and whose No. 8 is one of only six jerseys retired by the
school team; and Melissa Jennings, 19, a non-scholarship goalie
whose teammates questioned her work ethic and who was dropped from
the team in May. Neither would comment on the lawsuit, their lawyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side is Dorrance, 47, a married father of three who
is celebrated in soccer circles as a motivational and tactical
genius. Dorrance's record in 19 full seasons is a staggering 417
wins, 16 losses and 11 ties.
</P>
<P>
   After having weathered the ``humiliating and embarrassing''
first days after the lawsuit was filed in August, Dorrance says he
is determined to prove his innocence. On the advice of his lawyer,
he declined to comment on specific allegations, but denied
harassing players or abusing his authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has hurt my mother and it hurts my family, but the team
has taken care of itself very quickly. This crisis forced us to
band together,'' said Dorrance, whose Tar Heels opened the season
with eight straight wins and a No. 1 national ranking.
</P>
<P>
   He said he plans no change in his style or behavior, with one
exception. In the closest he came to blaming his accusers, Dorrance
said: ``All of us are going to be a lot more thorough about the
sort of people we admit into this environment, this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Keller, he said only, ``Debbie had a fantastic career here
and was wonderfully coachable.'' He had no comment on Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, the women allege that Dorrance on several
occasions made ``an uninvited sexual advance'' toward Keller. It
claims he repeatedly made inappropriate physical contact, touching
her body, and stroking her hair.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit also accuses Dorrance of interrogating his players
about their personal lives and sexual activities; of coercing team
members to report to him the sexual activities of other players; of
making lewd and degrading comments about players; of repeatedly
calling Keller to monitor her personal life; and of sending Keller
an intimidating and harassing e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations involving Jennings revolve primarily around
money and alcohol, and Dorrance and the university already have
acknowledged some mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings asserts that Dorrance ordered her to withdraw $400 from
her bank account to buy Gatorade and supplies for her teammates and
an opposing team when the coaches found themselves without money.
The lawsuit also says Dorrance encouraged her to drink alcohol,
despite knowing she was under age and, as a Mormon, abstained from
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Jennings's father in June, in the midst of failed
discussions to head off the lawsuit, Dorrance apologized for using
``poor judgment'' in asking to borrow money and said he
``understands that alcoholic beverages must not be allowed at any
activity involving team members.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorrance also admits in the letter that he engaged in
``inappropriate'' group discussions ``of a jesting or teasing
nature'' with players, but said he never discussed sex during
one-on-one meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Buried deeper in the 19-page lawsuit _ and almost entirely
overlooked in press accounts _ is an assertion by Keller that some
of Dorrance's supporters suspect might be the real reason for the
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Keller accuses Dorrance of interfering with her efforts to
obtain custom soccer shoes from Nike and Adidas when she was
recovering from a heel injury. Despite winning national
player-of-the-year honors in 1995 and 1996, Keller was prevented by
her heel injury from joining the US Olympic team, costing her a
gold medal in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says that Dorrance blocked Keller's bid for special
shoes as part of a complicated attempt to play the shoe companies
against each other while negotiating a lucrative Nike sponsorship
deal. That deal, a university official said, will pay him roughly
$450,000 over four years, a significant boost over his $50,000
coaching salary.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for Keller and Jennings, Louis Varchetto, said he
could not comment on individual acusations, but said the lawsuit
was based on the entire pattern of Dorrance's behavior. He
dismissed the outpouring of support by the school and UNC players,
comparing the situation to President Clinton's sexual imbroglio.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will blindly follow someone they like, whether they
know the truth or not,'' Varchetto said.
</P>
<P>
   At a team practice last week, talk of the lawsuit was replaced
by the sound of Dorrance calling out commands and advice to two
dozen young women darting about on an immaculately groomed field.
Dorrance was quick to praise a good shot or a smart defense, and
just as quick to order a player to do five sit-ups for failing to
accelerate after passing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Current and former players _ all of whom call Dorrance by his
first name _ were effusive in defense of their coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Anson pats you on the shoulder and says `good job,' he's
just being a coach,'' said senior Tiffany Roberts, a member of the
national team who roomed with Keller and considers her a good
friend. ``She thought it was sexual harassment, but none of us have
had any problem with Anson.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the sidelines sat Dorrance's mother, Peggy, in a straw hat
and tennis shoes. ``This is such a tough time,'' she said, her
voice cracking. ``He has the highest ethical standard of any person
in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   But Craig Jennings, whose daughter Melissa is still attending
UNC, said in a telephone interview from Illinois that Dorrance
exploited his position. ``A professor has power over a student for
one grade. A coach has far more power, and he can use that power
like Anson did, to gain control,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Dorrance, the lawsuit names the school and nine other
university officials, including former University of Massachusetts
President Michael K. Hooker, now UNC chancellor, and assistant UNC
coach Tracy Ducar, who plays with Keller on the national team. The
additional defendants are mostly accused of failing to stop
Dorrance's inappropriate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked at all the evidence, and we don't think there's
anything there to justify the charges,'' Hooker said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear when the case will come to trial. Whatever the
eventual outcome, already the lawsuit has focused attention on the
issue of male coaches of female athletes. It came just three months
after two former Syracuse women's tennis players filed a $25
million harassment lawsuit against the school's male coach.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Lopiano of the Women's Sports Foundation offers a
hard-line set of standards for coaches: ``You shouldn't be alone
with players, one on one. You shouldn't be in equipment rooms with
them. You shouldn't be in social situations. You are a teacher, and
the distance between the teacher and the student is a guarantee of
objectivity and proper limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Other coaches, both male and female, said the case has forced
them to review their actions but would not cause them to adopt a
policy quite so strict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It heightens awareness, and you think about guidelines, but
I'm not going to change my coaching style,'' said US National Team
coach Tony Diccico.
</P>
<P>
   April Heinrichs, a former UNC soccer star who now coaches at the
University of Virginia, said the issue affects both sexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexuality and gender should never be an issue in coaching. If
I were coaching young males, I wouldn't call them stud muffin or
sweetie or good-looking. I wouldn't make reference to their body or
body type,'' she said. ``Once we get away from the specifics about
Anson, maybe the benefit will be that we can start to educate
people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
