<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9866 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAME-TEEN-SPI &LR;      10-05 2086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAME-TEEN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STAR IN WAITING: TALENTS TUG AT TEEN'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWCASTLE, Wash. _ As a little girl _ not long ago _ Vicki Noon
used to clown around for home videos, pretending to be Ariel of
``The Little Mermaid.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ariel on her seaside rock, Vicki would climb atop her bunk
bed and sing achingly in her bright, powerful voice about being
``part of your world.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki is 13 now, and if she became part of our world any faster,
she'd risk getting the bends.
</P>
<P>
   After just a year or so of voice lessons, the Newcastle
eighth-grader has already landed three plum roles, including the
juvenile lead in Seattle's A Contemporary Theatre's fall production
of ``Violet.''
</P>
<P>
   The play, which runs Oct. 22 through Nov. 15, won the 1997 New
York Critics Circle Award for best musical.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Vicki won lead roles in two musicals at the Washington
Academy of Performing Arts. The fast-growing Redmond school was
co-founded by Deborah Hadley, former prima ballerina with Pacific
Northest Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   In late June, a last-minute cast change thrust Vicki into the
role of Dorothy in ``The Wizard of Oz,'' giving her less than five
days to learn a part that normally takes Academykarin: i left
Academy up all the way through because i think it's needed for
clarity--pat students a month or two to prepare. In late August, on
a less frantic note, she played the rags-to-riches heroine of
``Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki is still a little girl in lots of many ways _
freckle-faced, with a thatch of dark, chin-length hair, and glasses
she wears everywhere except onstage. At 5-foot-3, she packs 105
pounds of coiled energy into the compact body of an athlete _
hidden somewhere under her baggy overalls.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, she's a kid who has just discovered she's got talent
that could land her on top of the world. The joy of performing
makes her feel like she's already there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just makes me happy,'' Vicki said, face glowing. ``I love
it. I think it's so much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, she faces tough career choices. On one hand, theater
pros say she has the raw, oversized talent to make it on Broadway.
Some compare her to the young Judy Garland, although there's no
trace of Garland's fragility in Vicki's bubbly personality and
clarion vocal style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a once-in-a-lifetime voice,'' said Jerry Tassin, one of
her Academy mentors. ``This girl has a set of pipes I have not
heard in years. It's a Broadway belt, is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Her singing coach, Ann Evans Zavada, said that in 10 years of
teaching, she has had only two other students of Vicki's caliber,
neither of whom has lived up to their early promise. One was
sidetracked by her social life. The other was a boy soprano who
sang with Seattle Opera until his voice changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Vicki has a clearer understanding of the professional
world and what she needs to do to be involved in it,'' Zavada said.
``And she wants to be involved in it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Vicki also is a nearly straight-A student and
a star soccer player who, according to her coach, could make it to
the U.S. Women's Team if she weren't distracted by pipe dreams.
Last season she scored 23 of her team's 67 goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky's the limit,'' said Norm Robinson, coach of her Gold
Select youth team in Renton. ``Her dribbling skills are incredible.
She has good ball control and she's fast. She has great moves.''
</P>
<P>
   But with theater work stealing time from soccer practice,
Robinson is pressing her to make a choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a little girl with a lot of talent who's getting pulled
in two different directions,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bouoyant, twinkly-eyed and still innocent enough to be thrilled
by her good fortune, Vicki is frank about her dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be on Broadway,'' she said with a happy giggle.
</P>
<P>
   It's a big leap for a girl who, three years ago, was too shy to
sing in a talent show on a vacation cruise. Instead, she joined a
lip-synch contest for adult women _ and won, putting body and soul
into a pantomime of Aretha Franklin's signature song, ``Respect.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year of song and dance training _ with many more to come
_ she has the erect, grounded posture of a gymnast and holds the
stage with quiet confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really nice to have around,'' said Kira Tassin, 14, who
appeared with her in ``Oz'' and ``Annie,'' ``because sometimes when
we have to run through something again, she makes a joke of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Blowing off steam at an early rehearsal for ``Annie'' one day,
Vicki and another girl briefly hammed it up behind the director's
back during a boy's vocal solo.
</P>
<P>
   Threading through the darkened rows of seats, the two girls
shimmied in tandem _ arms outspread, shoulders gyrating in a broad,
chorus-girl sendup. Onstage, the cast cracked up.
</P>
<P>
   Director Kelly Willis whirled around _ long, red hair whipping.
She laughed, then admonished ``Vicki, sit down!''
</P>
<P>
   But it's all business now for Vicki, who's in rehearsal for
ACT's production of ``Violet.'' The show features two veterans of
last fall's New York premiere _ Lauren Ward, who originated the
adult lead role of Violet, and director Susan H. Schulman.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1964, it tells of a young mountain woman who sets out by
bus for Tulsa in hopes of finding a television evangelist who can
heal her disfigured face. Joined by two unlikely traveling
companions, Violet finally comes to understand her own strength and
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   In flashbacks, Vicki plays the young Violet, who is maimed when
her father accidentally hits her in the face with an ax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only in about five scenes,'' said Vicki, who crammed for
her audition during a half-hour with Willis, using the
International Phonetic Alphabet to master a passable Southern
accent. She also twanged her way through the song, ``Delta Dawn.''
</P>
<P>
   ACT casting director Margaret Layne said Vicki seems to produce
her powerful vocals without effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no sense she's pushing to get the volume she does,''
Layne said. ``There's no straining. It's as natural as breathing.
She has a big, bright, unmannered voice that you can't listen to
without smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   She also projects uncanny self-confidence for such a rank
beginner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vicki does one of the most poised auditions that I've ever
seen anyone do,'' Layne said. ``She's very relaxed. I think a lot
of that has to do with the support she gets from her family. They
do a lot to help her keep things in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki and her sister, Andrea, 17, spend time with both parents,
who divorced last year after 18 years of marriage but remain
friendly. Mom Liz Noon, 36, certifies Boeing airplane systems for
the Federal Aviation Administration. Dad Tim Noon, 42, is a Boeing
engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki and Andrea, who wants to be a pediatrician, say they're
very close, though they occasionally squabble over little things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we'll both just crack up,'' Andrea said. ``Our fights
last for about two minutes, then we'll laugh for five.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea said most of her friends don't mind Vicki tagging along
because she's ``amusing.'' But some are annoyed by her tendency to
hog the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Willis and Tassin, who teach dance and musical
theater at the Academy, had to convince Vicki she had a voice worth
developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to sing in front of people at first,'' Vicki
said. ``I know that I have a good voice, but I don't want to flaunt
it in front of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now she says, ``I'm glad I can't see the faces of the
people (in the audience). I think it would scare me if they weren't
liking it or were bored or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki's first big stage role was in the Academy's summer
production of ``The Wizard of Oz.'' It was a nerve-racking affair
that propelled her from the Munchkin chorus line to the role of
Dorothy in distressingly short order.
</P>
<P>
   At dress rehearsal, four days after she got the part, she still
hadn't learned all the songs. The next night, when the curtain
rose, she had it down cold.
</P>
<P>
   Her heroic performance knocked the socks off co-star Greg
Palmer, an independent TV film producer and former KING/5 reporter,
who played the Wizard. He saw her as ``an incredibly hard-working
tot with a singing voice that sounds like she's a 35-year-old
pro.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid has, as far as I can tell, perfect pitch and easily
filled a thousand-seat hall, with or without sound amplification,''
Palmer said. ``She has what could be just a stunning career ahead
of her. I just think there's no limit to how far she can go.''
</P>
<P>
   After ``Oz,'' Vicki's life assumed a whirlwind quality. She and
Andrea were vacationing with their dad in North Carolina this past
summer when ACT called Vicki back for a second audition for
``Violet,'' this time before the director and musical staff.
</P>
<P>
   As one of six finalists, she had no guarantees of anything
except a disrupted vacation and an extra $400 in travel expenses.
In the end, her father drove her to the airport from the beach
house near Cape Hatteras and put her on a puddle-jumper to
Jacksonville, N.C. Traveling solo, she changed planes in
Charlottesville, Va.; Washington, D.C., and Phoenix before arriving
back in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Layne said Vicki managed to project the right combination of
resilience and toughness for the role.
</P>
<P>
   ``And of course,'' Layne said, ``she sings like a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Zavada said Vicki has an ``excellent transition'' between the
upper and lower ranges _ a seamlessness that some women spend years
trying to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   She added that Vicki can span at least three octaves _ less than
Mariah Carey's four, but twice as much as the average person. Her
sound comes from the shape of her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really wide across the cheeks,'' Zavada said. ``The
shape of the (vocal) cords is really the same on everybody. It's
really the resonating chambers that change the timbre and quality
of the sound.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of coaching, Vicki has less vocal tension
and better breath control, which should see her through eight
performances a week in ``Violet.'' But she still has years of
training and hard work ahead of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't encourage her to cruise,'' said Zavada. She tells
Vicki, ``Sure, this is fine, but what's it going to be like when
you're 15, or 17? You have to keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   Tassin, artistic co-director of the Washington Academy, said
it's important to keep Vicki ``unaware'' and suitably humble.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she gets out there and feels she's so successful she's
already where she needs to be, that will be her downfall,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added, ``We have her at a very important time of her
life. The talent is there, she's ready to train. If we get her
through the next few years and give her that solid base, she will
go!''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vicki still has the pressures of school and soccer.
Coach Robinson has complained to Liz Noon about Vicki's absences,
saying it breeds resentment among girls who show up faithfully but
don't always get to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did kind of blow up with each other once,'' Robinson said,
``because I was fed up with her not being at practice, and I had
parents on my back.''
</P>
<P>
   They have since smoothed things over, although Saturday
rehearsals for ``Violet'' have forced Vicki to suspend soccer
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Noon, meanwhile, worries about the emotional wear and tear
of a performing career. This fall he vetoed Vicki's request to skip
eighth grade and go directly into the Academy's performance-focused
high school, the Conservatory. Maybe next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's 13. She's my little girl,'' he said, as Vicki perched on
his knee with her arm around his shoulder. ``I'm worried about her
still.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing I worry about is, how is this affecting Andrea?
It used to be Andrea who had all the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrea, herself a star soccer and tennis player, smiled wanly.
</P>
<P>
   Given Vicki's assorted talents, it isn't exactly ``Broadway or
bust.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this voice or musical theater doesn't work out,'' said Liz
Noon, ``she could be a great engineer, she could be a doctor, she
could be anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added, ``I would like to see her be able to use her
voice because I think that's her biggest talent. And she loves it,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Robinson understands how dreams of stardom can overshadow
the thrill of a well-placed soccer kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kind of dreams,'' he said, ``are great dreams to have.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
