<HEADLINE>
GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !!! 1/2 ``Antz''  Computer-generated imagery makes this bug cartoon
seem a fresh, exhilarating hoot. It reinvigorates the schleppy
nebbish persona of Woody Allen as a neurotic worker ant turned hero
when he falls for a princess, drolly voiced by Sharon Stone. But
mostly, it's the feeling of watching an old tradition scrubbed
clean, shiny with newness, that makes ``Antz'' such a high. (PG)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; !! ``The Impostors''  &LR; Stanley Tucci and Oliver Platt knock
thesmelves out as unemployed actors stowing away on a luxury cruise
liner in the '30s. Initially lively, this farce runs out of steam
fast, scuttling its hope to evoke ``Some Like It Hot'' and the Marx
Brothers' ``Monkey Business.'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FR)!! 1/2 ``What Dreams May Come''  &LR; This film sets a grand new
visual standard for afterlife movies with its heaven seemingly
designed by Monet and Van Gogh and its hell dreamed up by
Hieronymous Bosch. Try as they will, though, Robin Williams and
Annabella Sciora, as a couple trying to reunite after death, can't
provide an emotional dimension equal to the stunning visuals.
(PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !!! ``Lolita''  &LR; While director Adrian Lyne adds too much
literary atmosphere, and not enough humor, this engaging adaptation
of Nabokov's classic has moments of great power. Jeremy Irons is
outstanding as a tragic Humbert Humbert, awash in his tormented
romantic feelings for the young nymphet. (Matthew Gilbert)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; !!! ``Six-String Samurai''  &LR; Terminally hip little
post-apocalyptic send-up of martial arts movies, vintage rock and
the mythification of pop culture artifacts. Jeffrey Falcon looks
like Buddy Holly, acts like Clint Eastwood and is right on the
laconic money as he trudges across a wasteland to Lost Vegas to vie
for Elvis Presely's crown. (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe movie critic Jay Carr's entire archive of reviews may be
retrieved from Boston.com, the Globe's on-line service on the
Internet's World Wide Web; key words ``movie reviews.'')
</P>
