<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9874 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-WAR-CRIMES-BOS &LR;      10-05 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-WAR-CRIMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINKING THE UNTHINKABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID MEHEGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
WE WISH TO INFORM YOU THAT TOMORROW WE WILL BE KILLED WITH OUR
FAMILIES 
Stories from Rwanda 
By Philip Gourevitch. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. 355 pp. $25. 
 
 
WAR CRIMES 
Brutality, Genocide, Terror, and the Struggle for Justice
<TEXT>
<P>
   By Aryeh Neier. Times Books. &QL; 
286 pp. Illustrated. $25. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is a scene in John Hersey's classic, ``Hiroshima,'' where
dazed and traumatized people are wandering away from the ruined
city. They cannot comprehend or articulate what has happened to
them, and when an aid worker asks one man where he is from, he
points to the ruined city and says vaguely, ``There.'' Asked where
he is going, he points the other way and says, ``There.''
</P>
<P>
   Something of that vacant feeling, that sense of overwhelmed
emptiness, may affect readers of Philip Gourevitch's extraordinary
book about the Rwanda genocide of spring 1994. It is absolutely
revealing in its detailed accounting of the horror _ the social and
political background, who did what to whom, the aftermath _ yet as
with all such events, the horror is outside the pale of
comprehension or articulation, in the darkness beyond the communal
campfires.
</P>
<P>
   Gourevitch, a staff writer for the New Yorker, was not in Rwanda
in the hundred days of April-July 1994, when at least 800,000
people were shot, bludgeoned, or hacked to death. He first went
there a year later. But his research, visits to killing sites, and
interviews with survivors and perpetrators yield something close to
an eyewitness account.
</P>
<P>
   In Rwanda, as in Yugoslavia, we imagine the genocide to be a
tribal affair: Hutus killing Tutsis out of ancient animosity. But
those are not distinct tribes, only artificial social and racial
groupings encouraged by the Belgian colonizers. Originally the
Tutsis were herdsmen, while the Hutus were farmers, with lower
status. In recent times the two groups freely intermarried and in
many cases are impossible to tell apart. Yet the status
distinctions remained, and the departing Belgians in 1960 left the
Tutsi elite in charge. A Hutu-led coup soon followed, after which
those Tutsis who did not go into exile became an uneasy minority
treated with suspicion _ and occasional pogroms. ``Killing Tutsis
was a political tradition in postcolonial Rwanda,'' Gourevitch
writes; ``it brought people together.''
</P>
<P>
   General Juvenal Habyarimana, a pogrom leader under his
predecessor, took power in 1973, vowing peace and harmony. His
wife, a Lady Macbeth named Agathe Kanzinga, came to be seen as a
power behind the throne. Around her a Hutu clique arose that fanned
an ideology called Hutu Power. Hutu Power regarded Hutus and Tutsis
roughly as National Socialism regarded Aryans and Jews: The latter
must be eliminated if the former is to survive. By spring 1994 the
hatemongers of Hutu Power had drummed into the people the idea, as
one put it in a speech two years earlier, ``We the people are
obliged to take responsibility ourselves and wipe out this scum.''
When Habyarimana was killed in a plane crash on April 6, 1994
(possibly by his own party), the orders were given, and the
slaughter began.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the massacre are horrifying and by now familiar:
Most of it was carried out by machete, at crossroads, in homes, and
in churches or hospitals where Tutsis had fled for safety. Fields
and streams and wells were filled with bodies. It was like the
scenes of Jonestown magnified more than a thousandfold. As shocking
as the deeds are the range and numbers of people who participated:
People killed their in-laws, doctors killed their patients, church
leaders killed parishioners. The killers included mayors,
schoolteachers, policemen. It seems a psychosis overcame the
people.
</P>
<P>
   There was a carefully prepared universal draft. Gourevitch
writes, ``Rwanda's Hutu Power leaders understood this perfectly.
... The people were the weapon, and that meant everybody: the
entire Hutu population had to kill the entire Tutsi population.
...If everybody is implicated, then implication becomes
meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   How could this have happened? Rwanda was by no means the poorest
of African countries; it had many educated and accomplished people.
Gourevitch hints at an answer that may make us feel better about
our fragmented, atomized society: a pervasive conformity at the
roots of Rwandan culture, which is necessary for survival, and
often admirable, but chilling when turned to diabolical ends. If a
neighbor is threatened and cries for help, one Rwandan explains to
Gourevitch, ``There is responsibility. I cry, you cry. You cry, I
cry. ... We all come running, and the one who stays quiet, that one
that stays home, must explain. Is he in league with the criminals?
... This is community.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing was more or less ended only when the Tutsi-led
Rwanda Patriotic Front army rolled across the country and drove the
Hutu Power into camps in neighboring Zaire and Tanzania. When in
1996 those camps were forcibly closed, 600,000 Hutus returned home
with the promise that there would be no full-scale retribution.
Some Hutu Power leaders were tried and punished, and others
remained in exile, but many smaller-scale killers returned to their
home communities to face the stares of their victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   How is such a return possible? How can any sort of social
cohesion develop after such events? The new government passed a law
that provided for lesser sentences, even forgiveness, for
lower-level perpetrators who confessed _ much like South Africa's
Truth and Reconciliation Commission. The new government took the
position that reeducation of the followers was possible. ``You
don't necessarily just go for everyone you might think you should
go for,'' said Paul Kagame, one of the new leaders. ``Maybe you
create an atmosphere where things are stabilized first, then you go
for those you must go for. Others you can even ignore for the sake
of gradually leading a kind of peaceful coexistence. ... And I
think some people can even benefit from being forgiven, being given
another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   This idea is appealing and also unsettling; we are seeing it, or
have seen it, in many places in the world. Not only in South
Africa, where thugs and killers under the apartheid regime have
received amnesty if they came forward and confessed before the
commission, but also in Israel, Northern Ireland, and Argentina. In
all these places, people have taken the bitter medicine of sitting
down and trying to find a way to live with, or at least tolerate
the existence of, those whom they knew had committed or given
support to outrages.
</P>
<P>
   Aryeh Neiser's wide-ranging and cogent book, ``War Crimes,''
reviews all these historical cases, as well as the denazification
program in occupied Germany, and finds that in every case there
were compromises, that perfect justice, as we might envision it in
ordinary criminal cases, is almost never possible. In Germany, many
low-level bureaucrats and officials under the Nazi regime,
including many judges, were eventually given a clean slate and took
up their places in building the ``German Miracle,'' which was
needed to resist Soviet power.
</P>
<P>
   Neier, formerly executive director of Human Rights Watch, is
restless over too-easy forgiveness, and argues strongly for
creation of an international court of justice. He believes the plan
for such a body, under the United Nations, will be realized by the
end of the century if the great powers support it. But he is under
no illusions that in the case of crimes on a vast scale, such as
those in Bosnia, Argentina, or Rwanda, many of those who helped
implement the evils would be prosecuted. He writes, ``the
overwhelming majority of those who conspired to commit crimes
against humanity (by definition, crimes on a great scale) or
knowingly aided in their commission cannot be prosecuted. ... the
fact that others who abetted the commission of great crimes will go
free makes them innocent only in the formal sense that they have
not been preven guilty in a court of law.''
</P>
<P>
   For the latter, the obloquy of their neighbors may be enough
retribution for both sides, as long as the survivors are given the
truth, consolation, and concrete help. ``Let's say we have a
hundred thousand young people who have lost their families and have
no hope, no future,'' says one Rwandan leader. ``In a country like
this if you tell them, `Go and kill your neighbor because he killed
your father and seven brothers and sister,' they'll take the
machete and do it. ... It will require a lot to make sure that
these people can come back to society and look at the future and
say, `Yes, let's try.'''
</P>
<P>
   But no government policy, no measure of either punishment or
forgiveness, could readily heal the spirit of those who witnessed
the butchery of their families. When he experienced the truth of
the Rwandan genocide, saw the stacks of bodies left in the
Nyarabuye church as a reminder, like Auschwitz, of the genocide,
Philip Gourevitch was reminded of Conrad's character Marlow at the
end of ``Heart of Darkness,'' back home in Europe being nursed by
his aunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not my strength that needed nursing,'' Marlow says,
``It was my imagination that wanted soothing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Mehegan is book editor of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9877 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-ANTZ-TEX     10-05 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ANTZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZING `ANTZ' DOESN'T BOTHER APPEALING TO KIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In many of the journalistic fall film previews, you could find
someone from DreamWorks saying something like this about ``Antz'':
``It's not a cute cartoon. It's an action-adventure movie.''
Translation: ``Everyone expects a cute cartoon, so we'd better do
some spin-doctoring before we take a bath at the box office.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks has reason to worry. ``Antz'' succeeds more for what
its makers want it to do than for what its audience might want it
to do. There's something admirable about that these days, when most
movies play to the lowest common denominator.
</P>
<P>
   And it still delivers, in many ways. It looks stunning. Strike
that _ it looks amazing. The all-insect cast has a level of
expressiveness that it seems to have learned from E.T., the master
at such things, and the backgrounds are so richly detailed that the
movie should win an Oscar nomination for production design, if
that's possible with an animated movie. Teens and adults will also
get off on the film's grown-up jokes and sly film references.
</P>
<P>
   What the movie has to offer younger children _ who will make up
a sizable portion of the audience _ is another matter. Expressive
as these critters are, they're not really all that cute, because
they look like ... well, ants, and sort of science-fiction ants at
that. The movie eschews original songs in favor of oldies and
standards, and except for the show-closing (and inevitable) ``High
Hopes,'' they sound like they'd appeal to Woody Allen (who voices
Z, the film's hero) more than they would to preschoolers.
</P>
<P>
   There's more action than slapstick, and although the battle
scenes are almost as impressive as the ones in Disney's ``Mulan,''
there isn't enough cuteness or humor to balance them out. They're
also relatively gruesome _ with Allen in the lead role, sensitive
types might think they're watching ``Saving Private Wry Ant.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the movie's
individual-against-the-state-and-against-conformity plot. How long
has it been since you saw a family film that felt like a
collaboration between George Orwell and Ayn Rand? Not that Z is a
Randian man _ or ant _ of action. For one thing, he speaks in
Allen's neurotic New York whine; for another, the first time we
meet him, he's talking to his analyst _ a nice in-joke for all the
adults in the audience, as well as the 4-year-olds who like to
double up ``The Lion King'' with ``Annie Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Z isn't a take-charge guy so much as he is a guy who lets events
sweep him along. He drones on disenchantedly about his life as a
worker, but does little to change his lot until bored Princess Bala
(Sharon Stone) goes slumming with the lower ants and hits on Z
because he's the only guy not following the crowd. Z falls for her
instantly, and his crush begins a journey that leads to him being
an inadvertent war hero and a reluctant outlaw.
</P>
<P>
   Because DreamWorks honcho Jeffrey Katzenberg was able to round
up the actors who directors Eric Darnell and Tim Johnson wanted,
the movie feels if it were cast first, then scripted. The cast is
so star-heavy, ``Antz'' feels like the ``We Are the World'' of
animation. Not only does Allen play a lucky neurotic and Stone play
a vampish princess, but Sylvester Stallone (who nearly steals the
film) portrays a buff soldier ant (who, true to Stallone form,
takes a beating) and Gene Hackman plays a power-mad general.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Christopher Walken, as the evil sidekick who talks
... in a series of ... eccentric ... pauses, and Jennifer Lopez as
a worker ant with a great ovipositor. Only Dan Aykroyd and Jane
Curtin, as preppy bees, seem to be playing characters rather than
playing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's pro-individualism theme is a bit ironic, coming from
a company whose motto might be ``What would Disney do?'' (Come to
think of it, there's some messianic subtext going on here, too.)
Well, Disney wouldn't toy this much with a tried-and-true formula,
and you have to give DreamWorks some credit for taking risks.
Disney would have more cute characters, Disney would have more
songs, Disney would have more comic relief, Disney would cut back
on the language, some of which is surprisingly strong. Disney would
probably make more money. But Disney would also try to satisfy
everybody, and DreamWorks _ and directors Darnell and Johnson _
deserve some congratulations for not compromising their vision.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Antz'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 of a possible 5 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Eric Darnell, Tim Johnson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Woody Allen, Sharon Stone &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 83 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ language, animated violence and at least one sexual
reference &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9878 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-COUSIN-BOS &LR;      10-05 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COUSIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRUNG FROM THE MIX OF MONEY AND MADNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
MY FIRST COUSIN ONCE REMOVED 
Money, Madness, and the Family of Robert Lowel 
By Sarah Payne Stuart 
HarperCollins, 244 pp., illustrated, $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Closed societies are catnip to most of us _ locker rooms,
convents, those poky spaces off the Oval Office _ and if cold roast
Boston has any fascination for you, Sarah Payne Stuart is a
clear-eyed and totally unapologetic guide. None of this ``I'd be a
better person if I wasn't to the manner born.''
</P>
<P>
   While she came from old money on both sides of her family, she
was always a poor relation when it came to her bank account.
Crumbs, but very nice crumbs, sometimes came her way. One crumb
should have been John Singleton Copley's portrait of an
18th-century Sarah that had passed, Sarah to Sarah, for
generations. But the husband of the last Sarah in possession
thought young Sarah didn't have the proper wall to hang it on _ as
if Concord, where she lives, was beyond the pale _ and gave it to a
museum. For the greater good, he said. For his own greater glory,
she suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart doesn't resent not being rich, only wishes she hadn't
been quite so poor so long. She has many interesting things to say
about money. Without it, you can't hope to be a snob. Money can
bring happiness, but meanness about money brings only misery.
There's ``no moral basis to New England penury,'' Stuart says.
``Money spent is love bestowed.''
</P>
<P>
   But this penny-bright memoir is not just about money. There was
one dark cloud over the family: Madness to old money was true
allied. The clan's most noted madman was the poet Robert Lowell, he
of the memoir's title, ``My First Cousin Once Removed.'' (For those
of us not schooled in genealogy, the book would have benefited from
a family tree; and the tangle of names makes it easier to refer to
the author as Sarah.) Lowell's own first cousin was the author's
mother; she too went mad, becoming for a time severely depressed,
as did two of her three sons in their teenage years.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah's mother was old money on both sides. Looting British
ships had made Israel Thorndike New England's first millionaire.
The Winslows, who arrived on the Mayflower, had to play catch-up,
but when their ship came in, they could afford to be careful about
whom they would know and whom they would marry. So by habit, they
tended not to hear when Sarah's father murmured that his family
name ``would open any door in the South.'' His family was, if
anything, more snobbish than the Boston crowd, his mother referring
to ``tacky'' people as ``tacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Life in Boston was comfy, predictable. It did not occur to
people to be bored: Moping was discouraged and plugging along was
the best thing. ``Shy means thinking about yourself'' was the way
one family admonished sensitive children, Sarah writes. The boys
followed their fathers to Harvard and the girls went off to
boarding schools from which they didn't necessarily graduate (if
the commencement date got in the way of family plans). It only
seemed that cousins always married cousins, or that ``adventurers''
snapped up the rest. So it is not (probably) the small gene pool
that caused madness. There were lots of depressed Thorndikes, but
Sarah's mother thought her Winslows weren't crazy: ``They just have
a tremendous attraction to crazy people.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was craziness always caused by mothers not bringing up their
children themselves. The generations before Sarah had little
choice, tradition leaving the daily care of babies to the servants,
and most children survived, even thrived. Surely, no blame should
be attached to Sarah's mother, whose hospitalization for depression
removed her from her young children. Yet in the 1960s, when Sarah's
two brothers were themselves in and out of mental hospitals, manic
depression was not thought of as hereditary, Sarah writes. ``Every
week my parents would drive into McLean's to learn what they had
done wrong for fifty dollars an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   For someone who claims Robert Lowell's poetry is a closed book
to her, Sarah has done a fine job searching his poems for clues.
Some of the funniest parts of this funny book concern the family's
incomprehension about ``Bobby,'' as he was called at home. He
always came back for Thanksgiving. No one liked his first wife, the
novelist Jean Stafford, who was thought to be a ``whiner.'' The
second, the critic Elizabeth Hardwick, was Southern enough to
please, and a lady. (To the complaint that Hardwick didn't
understand Boston, Sarah retorts: She did, she just didn't like
it.) As for the Pulitzer Prize-winning poet, there was total
disdain. ``Why doesn't Bobby write about the sea? It's so pretty,''
said his aunt Sarah. They were great pals but, in the end, she cut
him out of her will.
</P>
<P>
   The way Lowell saw his inheritance, negative emotions were to be
conquered, not expressed. He ratted on Boston in ``Life Studies,''
and the family was generally unforgiving. Sarah's pages on ``For
the Union Dead,'' perhaps Lowell's most famous poem, are chilling
confirmation of the worst of Boston. It was Robert Gould Shaw's
abolitionist mother, not Robert, who wanted him to lead a regiment
of black soldiers in the Civil War. He did, and died, we can all
agree, for the greater good. But Lowell saw it as the zealot mother
sacrificing her son for her own ideals, the spirit that taketh
away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
