<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TENORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WE'LL ALWAYS HAVE PARIS ON VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Three Tenors did it again Aug. 18. If you escaped them on
PBS, you can watch Jose Carreras, Placido Domingo, and Luciano
Pavarotti gather in front of the Eiffel Tower on home video any
time you want, or listen to some of the highlights and lowpoints of
the concert on an Atlantic Warner CD.
</P>
<P>
   The first Three Tenors concert at the Baths of Caracalla in Rome
in 1990 became the best-selling classical recording in history _ or
to use a language more appropriate to a marketing phenomenon, the
10 million-and-more copies the performance sold on CD and video set
the record ``of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   The tenors had sung the concert for charity, Carreras's leukemia
foundation; in Rome there was was an audience of 8,000. Each of the
tenors accepted a ``token payment'' reported at $300,000 for the
recording. Fortunes were therefore made by others and not by the
singers, a mistake they were careful not to repeat in the second
concert in Los Angeles in 1994, when it was widely believed that
each of them was paid $1 million upfront.
</P>
<P>
   That event was watched on television by 1.3 billion people, and
a world tour followed; there were
</P>
<P>
   Three Tenors concerts in Tokyo, London, Vienna, Munich,
Goteborg, Dueseldorf, Vancouver, Toronto, Melbourne, Modena, Osaka,
Madrid, Mexico City, and East Rutherford. Zubin Mehta conducted the
first two concerts, James Levine all the others except Melbourne
(he couldn't fly because of a sinus infection. Nothing else stopped
him, even a prior commitment to conduct the Boston Symphony
Orchestra, which he canceled). Financial figures are hard to come
by, but Robert C. Marsh's new book about Levine, ``Dialogues and
Discoveries,'' quotes a New York Times estimate that the tenors
collectively earned $40 million in 1996. Their manager went on the
defensive; according to Marsh, he said, ``If Janet Jackson can sign
a deal for $80 million, the Three Tenors are totally, totally
underpaid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Paris concert, ``a gift to the city,'' according to producer
Tibor Rudas, was heralded in superlatives. ``240 strings will be
plucked during the show,'' proclaimed the official press kit _ they
must have forgotten to count the harp. This was the third Three
Tenors event presented in connection with the World Cup finals
(``Jose Carreras supports Barcelona, Placido Domingo supports Real
Madrid, and Luciano Pavarotti supprts Juventus,'' says the press
kit). ``Hundreds of thousands'' of people crowded the Champ de
Mars, and the broadcast audience was estimated by the recording
company at 1 billion and by the CD booklet at twice that. A Web
site was established at www.3tenors98.com (although it wasn't
functioning last week).
</P>
<P>
   Paris was the first concert since Los Angeles to feature a
significant amount of fresh repertory. No one dreamed of tampering
with the successful basic formula _ each tenor sang two arias and
two lighter selections; the three joined up for a medley in each
half. Some pieces switched ownership; Carreras passed ``Granada''
to Pavarotti, and Domingo gave an aria from Verdi's ``Luisa
Miller'' to Pavarotti, who had the pleasure of singing his rival's
name in the opening line, ``Quando le sere al placido.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavarotti tried on Andrea Bocelli's hit ``Caruso'' for size.
Domingo offered ``Memoires de Danton,'' a power ballad by his son,
Placido Domingo Jr. Carreras showed wisdom in not trying to compete
with his younger self, or with the memory of other celebrated
recorded voices, by choosing two arias even the most dedicated
operagoers are unlikely to know, ```Io conosco un giardino'' from
``Maristella'' by Giuseppe Pietri, a composer unfamiliar even to
the authors of reference books, and ``Intenditi con Dio'' from
``Fosca'' by Carlos Gomes.
</P>
<P>
   Solos in the more popular vein included a song by Grieg composed
in Danish as ``Jeg elsker dig,'' known in English as ``I Love
You,'' and sung by Carreras as ``T'estimo,'' ``Granada,'' and the
Neapolitan song ``Voce 'e Notte (Carreras). Domingo won what must
have been a contest to sing ``Amor ti vieta'' from Giordano's
``Fedora'' _ this aria, like ``O mio babbino caro'' fiercely fought
over by fading sopranos on gala occasions, sounds higher and harder
than it is. Pavarotti pulled himself together for another ``Nessun
dorma''; Levine looked happy and relieved, perhaps because Aretha
Franklin was nowhere in view, or earshot.
</P>
<P>
   Lalo Schifrin, medley-maker to the stars, stitched up two new
ones, a ``Medley of Romance'' (leading off with ``Sous le ciel de
Paris!'' _ and an unacknowledged bit of Bizet) and a ``Medley of
the World'' (which included the World Cup theme song, ``You'll
Never Walk Alone''). Schifrin's occasional attempt to stack up the
tenors together singing harmony was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   The Orchestre de Paris offered Berlioz's ``Roman Carnival''
Overture and the ``Bacchanale'' from Saint-Saens's ``Samson et
Dalila,'' if anybody cared _ neither one appears on the CD, which
is also missing what struck this listener as the vocal highpoint of
the evening, Domingo's fervent performance of ``Rachel, quand du
Seigneur,'' from Halevy's ``La Juive.'' (The CD was compiled by
omitting one aria from each of the singers, so Carerras lost
``Fosca,'' and Pavarotti the ``Luisa Miller'' piece.) For the
purposes of the CD, encores like ``Because'' and ``O sole mio''
precede the ``Medley of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   The video version promises interview and backstage material not
available to the worldwide television audience; presumably it
avoids the staggeringly inane PBS commentary that has become a
traditional part of the fun, like the interview segment of the Miss
America competition. Some of the raw material from the original TV
broadcast must have presented the editors with problems. The
Parisian setting is beautiful, and TV dramatized it impressively
with heliocopter shots, but the camera positions for the concert
were not advantageous; microphones blocked not only unflattering
views of the tenors' chins, but also most of their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Three Tenors concerts are not musical events in an ordinary
sense, and the artistic standards that each of the singers and the
conductor have brought to their other endeavors are more or less
irrelevant to this context. Still, it is saddening to see how
willing they have become to slip below those standards.
</P>
<P>
   This has nothing to do with the fact that all three of them are
headed at various rates of speed down the other side of the hill.
Pavarotti was 62 in July and closing in on his announced retirement
date in 2001. Nevertheless when he gets himself organized, he can
still outsing just about anyone but the ghost of Pava-rotti past.
It isn't easy for him, though, and that makes it hard going for
anyone who loved him in his prodigal prime: Today he makes you
worry on his behalf instead of suffusing you with sunshine. He was
probably the most gifted of the three, and he still sings the top
line.
</P>
<P>
   Domingo, officially 57, also has to work awfully hard these
days, but pumping iron this way is preferable to the way he
sometimes coasted through his vocal prime; he remains the most
serious and versatile artist of the three.
</P>
<P>
   Carreras, only 51, is another story. One admires the courage and
the sweetness of the man, but his voice was in trouble even before
his heroic battle against leukemia; today his willingness to
struggle against the odds compels admiration, and so does his sheer
will to perform, but his voice is shot.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't the vocal condition of the singers _ the
public could not care less _ but that they don't take the arias
seriously enough, and they take the pop music too seriously.
Operatic music is ripped from context and delivered through the
mikes like a rock anthem. The popular music is often unconvincing
in delivery, unidiomatic in rhythm, phrasing, and style _ this
isn't crossover at all, because they sing pop songs like rock
anthems too. Nothing is relaxed, nothing swings, nothing suggests
intimacy or genuine feeling, and everything comes out sounding the
same.
</P>
<P>
   After the New York concert it seemed that the tenors were not
demeaning themselves by singing popular music but demeaning popular
music by not treating it with respect and singing it well. Reading
off telepromters makes a poor substitute for real identification
with the material _ for this amount of money, the Three Tenors
ought to be better prepared. The first concert in Rome had the
virtue of apparent spontaneity; everyone in the Paris concert seems
grimly determined to have a good time, and therefore curiously
joyless.
</P>
<P>
   As the concert progress, it is wonderful to watch the shadows
gather around the Eiffel Tower, and then watch the lights banish
the shadow. Sadly, nothing is going to banish the shadows that are
gathering around the Three Tenors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
