<SLUG> BC-RUSSIANS-FRAUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE PROBE ALLEGES FRAUD BY RUSSIAN EMIGRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A well-known auto insurance fraud scheme that involves billing
insurers for accidents that never happened or were staged has
apparently been adopted by cadres of Russian emigres across the
nation, including a group that allegedly used a Framingham, Mass.
apartment as its fake address.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed by Trust Insurance Co. of Taunton, Mass., 11
Russian natives and a Brookline, Mass. insurance agent are accused
of participating in a conspiracy that allegedly resulted in the
submitting of more than $150,000 in questionable claims during the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
   The claims ranged from non-existent auto damage to unnecessary
medical treatment and equipment, according to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts case, insurance adjusters and official
investigators contend, mirrors a trend they have found on the rise
nationally: Rings of Russian associates submitting reams of
insurance claims for treatment of strains and sprains from minor or
phony auto accidents. Investigators say that if a collision did
occur, there were often no independent witnesses, leading insurers
to believe the accident was staged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are finding that the Russians have become particularly
aggressive in participating in fraudulent insurance schemes of one
sort or another,'' said Michael Diegel of the Coalition Against
Insurance Fraud, a Washingto lobbying and public information
organization composed of insurers and consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   Filing of fraudulent or exaggerated claims and seeking
settlements from fake or staged autombile accidents is a
longstanding tradition encountered by the US insurance industry,
according to analysts, and Russians are certainly not the first to
take advantage of the system.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say insurance companies also share a significant level
of blame for allowing fraud, which by national estimates makes up
11 percent of insurance claims, to permeate the system. Inundated
by claims, insurers have long been willing to get rid of cases by
settling them for reduced amounts, instead of going through the
long, arduous process of investigating them thoroughly and
contesting them through the legal process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a built-in acceptance of fraud throughout the whole
industry and those willing to participate in the fraud _ lawyers,
physical therapists, and chiropractors _ know it and take advantage
of it,'' said one Massachusetts prosecutor, who asked not to be
identified.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Loren Naiman, &UR;  &LR; head of the Los Angeles County district
attorney's auto insurance fraud division, said that his office has
cracked several rings dominated by Russian emigres, each involving
millions of dollars in phony claims.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing other investigators, Naiman said the emigre groups do
not appear to operate under a single boss. Instead, he said, they
are loose confederations of emigres from the same part of Russia
who are bound by language and culture.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian presence in the insurance fraud racket was initially
identified in the mid-1980s, when two brothers, emigres who had
become successful businessmen in Los Angeles, were indicted for
participating in a scheme that defrauded health insurance companies
of an estimated $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers, who are now serving long prison terms, lured
patients into a vast network of clinics dotting Southern
California, putting them through high-tech tests they did not need
but charging insurance companies an average of $8,000 a person.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers' attention to the problem of fraud by Russian-dominated
rings is reflected in recent articles by two insurance
publications. ``Russian Insurance Fraud Growing'' was the headline
last Monday in the trade publication National Underwriter following
a conference of insurance investigators. And an article in last
month's Claims magazine quoted insurance investigators as saying
that Russians have joined Nigerians, Vietnamese, and Hispanics in
operating fraud rings.
</P>
<P>
   Although prosecutors and investigators in Massachusetts have not
charged any Russian emigres with involvement in such rings, they
said they have heard complaints from insurance companies recently
of an influx of suspicious billings from automobile accidents. They
include billings for stolen cars that were never recovered, and
thousands of dollars worth of treatment by physical therapists and
chiropractors, often themselves of Russian descent, for treatment
of strains and sprains.
</P>
<P>
   According to one official, the state is investigating the
activities of two Russian-born medical professionals who insurers
contend have submitted bills on dozens of suspicious claims.
</P>
<P>
   Local groups who provide support to the 40,000 Russians who have
immigrated in the past decade and are living in Greater Boston
contend that few if any of them are participating in fraudulent
activities. ``The people that I see day in and day out are
hard-working and responsible, and would never get involved in such
craziness,'' said Serge Bologov, &UR;  &LR; executive director of the Russian
Community Association of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   While stressing that only a handful get involved in such
criminal acts, Steve Yanofsky of Boston, who tutors Russian emigres
in health care administration, said that most members of the
community quickly realize they can pocket $7,000 to $10,000 easily
by filing questionable claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawyers and (physical) therapists advertise in their
papers and on television. People are not stupid. They know there
are professionals who will take advantage of the situation,'' said
Yanofsky, who immigrated from Russia in 1989. In addition, Russian
emigres, he reasoned, might be more inclined to participate in such
fraud since they grew up in the Soviet Union where ripping off the
system was not viewed in entirely negative terms.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit filed last month by Trust Insurance Co., a modest
two-bedroom apartment in a Framingham housing complex is described
as ``Ground Zero'' in the alleged scheme, which involved 11 Russian
immigrants and the Gene Dvorkin Insurance Agency of Brookline.
According to the suit filed in Bristol Superior Court, the
apartment is occupied by a 24-year-old woman and her mother, who
are not defendants in the suit. Only one of the 11 individuals
charged in the suit ever lived in the apartment for any length of
time. The other 10 all resided in Brooklyn or New York City when
the policies were written in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   According to the suit, soon after securing the policies many of
the individuals filed claims with Trust Insurance, reporting that
they had been involved in minor traffic accidents and seeking
payment for the damage to their cars as well as for their medical
bills. After paying about $100,000 of the bills, Trust commenced an
investigation and found that all but one of the accidents had taken
place in and around Brooklyn and that many of the bills that were
paid, as well as $100,000 in medical bills that were not, involved
questionable treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Dvorkin, a well-established insurance agent for the local
Russian community, denied that he had wilfully engaged in any fraud
or conspiracy with the 11 emigres. While acknowledging that the
policies may have been improperly issued by his agency because of
the fake addresses, he said he should not be blamed because the
alleged conspirators could have hidden their tracks by going
through any of the several individuals in his office able to write
insurance policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have been victims here ourselves,'' Dvorkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said that Trust Insurance may have included him in the
lawsuit to get rid of him as an agent since his policies annually
wind up costing two or three times more in claims than they bring
in in premiums. Also, he said he has been leading a legal fight
against Trust Insurance for denying automatic safe-driving premium
reductions to recent immigrants, including Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Trust said its lawsuit grew solely out of its continued efforts
to ``vigorously'' fight fraudulent claims. ``Aggressive antifraud
actions ultimately benefit Trust, the entire insurance industry,
and, bottom line, the Massachusetts consumer,'' said Trust vice
senior president Paul F. Amoruso.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
