A9895 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS &LR;      10-05 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-QUESTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AGE, AND STATE, OF THE UNIVERSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How old is the universe, and will it continue to expand or
eventually contract back in, like a bungee cord?
</P>
<P>
   A.M.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Give or take a few minutes, the universe is about 10 billion
years old, or 14 billion, or 18 billion, depending on who you talk
to. Harvard astrophysicist Robert Kirshner says we can calculate
its age by looking at bright objects in space, including galaxies
and supernovae.
</P>
<P>
   If we can figure out how far away they are, and how fast they're
moving, we can figure out how long they took to get to where they
are, when they started their journey, and how long things have been
travelling since the Big Bang.
</P>
<P>
   But we can't tell precisely how far away things are, because
we're not sure just how bright they're supposed to be. Kenneth
Brecher, professor of physics and astronomy at Boston University,
explains: ``If we know, for example, that a 100-watt light bulb
gives off a precise amount of light right at the bulb, we can tell
how far away from it we are by measuring how much light has been
lost by the time it hits us. But we don't know precisely how bright
galaxies and supernovae are supposed to be.'' As to whether
everything will keep spreading apart, many scientists think it
will. But some disagree. ``The data for the last 100 years suggest
a &UR;  &LR; (a universe) that will keep expanding,'' Brecher says, but some
think it will ultimately contract.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirshner &UR;  &LR; also believes that expansion will probably continue
indefinitely. To illustrate how the space between objects in space
is growing, he uses the analogy of a playground jungle gym:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as though everything is moving out from a single spot
in the center. Imagine a big jungle gym made of living, growing
bamboo. The space between every crossbar is getting bigger. Each
one is moving away from all the rest. If there were kids on it,
every kid would be getting farther away from all their neighbors.
That's what's happening to the galaxies.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write
to How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      10-05 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD TO RETREMENT LOOKING GOLDEN, SO SPLURGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 42 years old and my wife is 38. We have been employed by
a large company for over 15 years, both love our jobs, and have no
interest in a change. We also believe in saving and keeping our
debt to a minimum. Over the years we have, to our surprise, by just
dragging along amassed a 401(k) account of over $500,000, and a
similar amount in stocks and mutual funds. Our cars are late-model
and we paid cash for them. We are living in what we consider ``our
last house'' and have a reasonable mortgage. Okay, so far, so good.
Our dilemma is this: When should we spend on personal luxury items?
We have been pretty good savers, and it pains us to part with any
of the stash we have built up. The treat in question is a $35,000
car that would be our third. In some aspects, we feel we deserve
it, but on the other hand it goes against our philosophy of having
what we need rather than what we want. The ball's in your court...
Should I take the $35,000 from my stockbroker and clean out the
garage, or should I wait until I'm 65 and have the treat then? Yes,
a great problem to have.
</P>
<P>
   S.L., Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, let's start here: If you were to make no more
contributions to your 401(k) account or other investments, it would
grow to $8,954,302 by the time you're 65; if you were to withdraw
$35,000 and follow the same arithmetic, the number would be
$8,640,901.
</P>
<P>
   (These calculations presume average 10 percent annual returns on
your portfolio, and presume you use other funds to handle taxes
from taxable accounts.) I am not, of course, advocating that you
stop your admirable approach to savings, but simply pointing out
that you have a huge head start against retirement and can
certainly afford to give yourself a treat.
</P>
<P>
   I vote for buying the car, with one caveat. That is that you
treat this as a one-time aberration _ the only invasion of your
retirement savings which you will allow. That's not to say you
should avoid further luxuries until retirement, but that after
this, try to finance them through your current cash flows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 25 years old. I currently have some ``emergency''
savings, but have not begun investing for retirement. I'd like to
start now and take advantage of the many years I have before
retiring. I have been thinking about opening a Roth IRA, since I am
currently in the lowest tax bracket and might as well pay the taxes
now. I have $1,000 to begin with, an will be able to contribute
only $100 a month until I climb the ladder and get a higher- paying
job. Since this is not much money to invest, I'm looking at being
able to get into only one fund, which isn't a very diverse
portfolio. Any suggestions for someone just starting out?
</P>
<P>
   K.M., Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The principal advice I have for a person your age is exactly
what you plan to do _ start out. Time is the most critical factor
in building a portfolio, and the earlier you get started, the less
difficult the task will be later on. If you simply look at a growth
projection of that $1,000 over the time until you reach 65, you'll
see what I mean. If we presume 10 percent average annual portfolio
growth, by the time you're 65, that $1,000 will have become
$28,102, and in the final year of the period, the internal growth
will be more than $2,550.
</P>
<P>
   As for the effect of additional contributions, if you simply
stuck with $100 monthly contributions, the portfolio projection
shows $368,272; if you were able to put in the maximum allowed,
which works out to $166 a month, the total would be $595,029.
</P>
<P>
   I'll give you an example of how important it is to start out
early.
</P>
<P>
   Let's compare the building of that theoretical $595,029 nestegg
to the chore that would face a person who didn't start thinking
about retirement until age 40. With only 25 years to go until the
typical retirement age, that person would have to contribute $482 a
month to end up with the same sum.
</P>
<P>
   As for diversification, I think a lot of people worry too much
about it. Yes, when you've built a sizable portfolio, it's nice to
spread your money out among five or six funds which operate in
difference market sectors and have different objectives. But,
especially when you're starting out, it's also important to
remember that most mutual funds are diversified by nature, holding
portfolios that include hundreds of different securities. So
instead of worrying about diversification I suggest you just stick
to a single fund for the first five years or so. What you'll want
to begin with is a fund which will serve as your core holding once
the portfolio takes shape. Most people pick a good fund in what
used to be called the growth and income category, now usually
identified as a large-cap fund with a portfolio that represents a
blend of growth and value stocks. There are literally hundreds of
such funds to chose among. I think a good start is with a fund
which simply seeks to duplicate the results of the Standard and
Poor's 500 Index, which contains the nation's 500 largest
companies, weighted according to market capitalization. That last
means that you will hold a vastly greater position in the number
one issue, now Microsoft Corp., than in the stocks in the high 400s
of the index. Managing such a fund is more a science than an art,
so you can simply look for funds with the lowest expenses. Two
excellent funds in this category are Vanguard Index 500 and
Fidelity Spartan Market Index, and since they have identical
expense ratios, the choice could as wisely be made with a dart
board as any other method.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm a single 39-year-old who was down-sized back in 1995 from
a relatively low-paying clerical job where I made $30,000 a year.
For three years I worked as a temp in a variety of low-paying,
short-term jobs. Now I seem to be benefiting from the economic
recovery and have a full-time job with benefits, although I'm only
making $24,000 a year. My problem is what to do with a small amount
_ $2,000 _ that I have saved in my 401(k). For 2 1/2 years, my
former employer managed the account and the money was primarily
invested in mutual funds. However, they requested that I move it to
another institution. I am not able to roll it over into the plan of
my new employer for another 11 months, so I have rolled it over
into an account at my bank, where the service fees are almost more
than the paltry amount of interest it earns. Do you have any advice
about where I could roll this over for the next 11 months, obtain
reasonable returns, and not be eaten alive by service fees?
</P>
<P>
   J.M., Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'm with you all the way _ and further. I'd not only move the
rollover IRA to a mutual fund company, but I'd also sever any other
relations _ checking account, savings accounts, safe deposit box,
and whatever else _ that you may have with the bank in question.
Any institution which levies service fees which approach the return
on a $2,000 IRA simply isn't worth your custom.
</P>
<P>
   There are many no load mutual fund companies which levy only
minimal fees _ typically about $10 a year _ to maintain an IRA
account. So even if you put the account in a money market account,
about 90 percent of its earnings would remain in the account.
</P>
<P>
   (But note that the IRA regulations allow you to pay the account
maintenance fees out of your own pocket, and it will not be
considered a contribution to an IRA; people whose goal to reach the
absolute maximum in allowed IRA contributions always pay these
charges rather than allowing the fee to be deducted from the IRA
balance.) There's one important thing to note here. You will be
allowed to roll this IRA account over into your new employer's
401(k) plan only if it was designated as a rollover IRA when you
moved it to the bank, and only if you have made no contributions to
it since you left your former employer. If you decide that you want
to save for retirement this year through IRA savings (thus
maintaining retirement savings even while waiting through the
months before you're eligible for the new 401(k) program, make sure
you do so with a separate IRA account, and that the new funds are
not mingled with the rollover IRA money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
