<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following
 &UR; ScienceTimes &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Oct. 6:
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TILMAN-ECOLOGY (St. Paul, Minn.) _ A Scientist at Work
feature: G. David Tilman, an ecologist at the University of
Minnesota, has discovered that the more species there are in an
ecosystem (up to a point), the more productive, resilient and
stable it will be. This is a question of some importance for
conservation policy, given a running political debate over whether
it is important to preserve as many species as possible. But the
Tilman experiments may have an even more basic value to the young
science of ecology. He is bringing controlled experimentation to
the relatively young science through his work on a 9-square-mile
tract of prairie-savanna ecosystem. By William K. Stevens. (2200
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT (Undated) _ The hand and forearm transplant
performed on an Australian man in France nearly two weeks ago ranks
among the most extraordinary cases in the annals of surgery, one
full of sudden plot twists, colorful characters and international
controversy. The hospital did not say that two days before the
13{-hour operation, the head of the surgical team learned from the
patient that he had a criminal record. An Australian newspaper
later reported that the patient was due in court to face seven
fraud charges. And far from losing his right hand in a logging
accident, as initial reports had it, Australian newspapers said he
lost it using a circular saw in a New Zealand jail. By Lawrence K.
Altman. (1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DEEP-SPACE-1 (Washington) _ The United States is about to
send an experimental probe into space to test some of the favorite
concepts of science fiction. The robot craft will be driven by an
advanced ion propulsion engine, will navigate through space on its
own and will occasionally call home to let people know how it is
doing. Called Deep Space 1, is one of the first missions designed
to send a spacecraft away from the Earth with technology testing,
and not science, as the main objective. By Warren E. Leary. (1650
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CAMBRIDGE-GENE (Cambridge, England) _ Ever since the
structure of DNA was discovered here in 1953, Cambridge has been a
leading world center for molecular biology. And with the help of a
recent bonanza from a long dead American pharmacist, Cambridge
scientists have become leading players in the effort to decipher
the human genome at the Sanger Center. By Nicholas Wade. (1750
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-RADIUM (Undated) _ This year is the 100th anniversary of the
Nobel-prize-winning experiments by Marie and Pierre Curie into the
origins of radioactivity, and their discovery of the radioactive
elements polonium and radium. But, like other discoveries, related
hazards were not discovered for several years _ and some tragedies
followed, including those involving the painters of
glow-in-the-dark watches. By Denise Grady. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-LAZARUS (Undated) _ Many people with AIDS who once were
near death but now are thriving with new medicines are are now
gripped by depression, acute anxiety _ especially over financial
issues _ and other, unexpected emotional problems, clinicians and
therapists said. Some patients have ended long-term romantic
relationships and others have become suicidal, an odd response to
being given a reprieve from death. Authorities are calling it the
Lazarus Syndrome. By David France. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STANDARD FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Looking back at the first
Personal Computing column, it is clear 16 years later that buying a
computer is still a process of trying to understand the value of
imponderables like DVD, PCI, USB and a 100 megahertz bus. Once
consumers sift through all the jargon, the bottom line is that
Windows 98 will not run properly with less than 32 megabytes of
memory, and any serious user will install twice that much _ or 500
times the memory of the most powerful machines described in that
first Personal Computers column. By Rob Fixmer. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on science: Dinosaurs probably
didn't really bump heads; it would have been suicidal. (525 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered: On the making of
butterflies' energy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ This decade has seen a steady decline
in the proportion of Americans who regularly eat breakfast, long
considered ``the most important meal of the day.'' Countless
studies in recent decades have documented the value of breakfast to
a child's ability to learn, think quickly, pay attention and get
along well with others, including a far-reaching recent one. By
Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   POSTPARTUM-SEX-HEALTH (Undated) _ Doctors routinely advise women
to refrain from sexual activity for several weeks following
childbirth, and for most women postpartum pain and exhaustion are
incentives enough to comply. But for those who do not follow
doctors' orders, the consequences can be serious and, in rare
cases, even fatal, according to a recent study. By Susan Gilbert.
(630 words)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-WATCH (Undated) _ Shorts on health.
</P>
