<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATE 2000 CLOSER TO HOME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When last we visited, we were discussing around-the-world
flights on the Concorde, trekking to the Great Pyramids and other
extravagant plans to celebrate the dawning of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Better hurry, too: Some events and tours are filling fast.
</P>
<P>
   But we don't have to cross an ocean or spend a fortune to
welcome the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   We could simply form a circle.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe ``simply'' isn't an appropriate word. The ``Prelude
to the Millennium'' promises to culminate in the largest human
circle ever, an anticipated gathering of 1 million ``Earth
Spiritualists'' in the California desert on sacred ground blessed
by Tibetan monks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Special gifts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to promoters, participants will spread the contents of
``Prelude to the Millennium'' pouches on the ground, thus healing
the Earth and themselves. They will chant about their desires for
the future and, as a bonus, enjoy free concerts and workshops.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, even if you can't attend, you can purchase _ hmmm, are
you surprised that everything isn't free? _ pouches over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This gathering, scheduled Dec. 30, 1999, through Jan. 1, 2000 on
a site still undetermined, is among hundreds of millennium-related
events detailed on a fascinating Web site:
http://www.everything2000.com.
</P>
<P>
   Not into rituals aimed at pagans, Wiccans, shamans and
``free-thinkers''? Perhaps instead you'd like to drum in the
millennium. A celebration headquartered in Taos, N.M., aims to
coordinate individuals drumming all over the nation _ and the world
_ as ``an affirmation of their collective vision for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the road in Albuquerque, a three-day Rock the Millennium
music concert vows to present ``seven to 12 of the biggest names in
classic rock today.'' Invited performers, according to sponsors,
include the Rolling Stones, Lynyrd Skynyrd, Van Halen, Grand Funk
Railroad, Santana, ZZ Top and _ classic rock? _ Willie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   No word yet on whether Willie or any of the others have accepted
the invitation. But just reading promotions for some events is
enough to create a party atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Huge bash &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back in southern California, Party 2000 is projected as ``the
biggest concert and party ever held on Planet Earth.'' It will
feature, we are told, ``the top big-name bands,'' ``the most
awesome stage, field and special effects lighting system ever
designed,'' ``the world's largest fireworks display'' and ``the
world's largest carnival.'' Oh, and I almost forgot, ``the world's
largest barbecue cookout.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't to be confused with ``one of the largest and longest
fireworks and laser displays the country has ever seen'' planned in
conjunction with an ``audio-visual extravaganza hosted by some of
the top names in the entertainment industry'' at the Los Angeles
Memorial Coliseum and Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Given the hype, I can only assume that some boxing promoters are
moonlighting with the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   What could possibly top California's plans? New Yorkers aim to
try with Celebration 2000, billed as ``the definitive
turn-of-the-century party.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the Big Apple, Times Square _ traditional home of the
nation's biggest New Year's Eve bash _ will start its celebration
at 7 a.m., coinciding with the arrival of the year 2000 in the
South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's capital will begin partying even earlier. Special
events are scheduled all year, and New Year's Eve on the Mall will
include a fireworks display and major entertainers _ assuming all
aren't busy in California or New Mexico. According to one report,
President Clinton has asked director Steven Spielberg and
musician/record producer Quincy Jones to coordinate the event.
</P>
<P>
   Other huge parties are planned for Chicago, Miami, Boston and
almost every other U.S. city. Cleveland touts the appearance of
``24 of the largest names in rock.'' Sioux Falls, S.D., is already
promoting ``the biggest party in the Great Plains.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect hundreds of in-state celebrations, too; already announced
is a $30 million grand exposition from Nov. 26, 1999, to Jan. 2,
2000, at Dallas' Fair Park.
</P>
<P>
   Where winter weather permits _ Death Valley, for instance _
national parks also are expected to draw crowds eager to usher in
the millennium's first light over a wide-open landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on going to Walt Disney World, though. Every room in
all 16 hotels at that Orlando-area resort has been reserved for
more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late to book a hotel in other parts of the country.
Yes, a hotel, not just a room. Several properties _ including the
Warwick in Houston _ are entertaining offers to reserve the entire
facility. For those on a budget, countless others will rent you a
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Ritz-Carlton's ``Ultimate Experience'' is reserved for one
couple only at each of its hotels and resorts in the United States
and worldwide. The package includes accommodations in the resort's
premier suite, with private dining room; an 18-karat gold Bvlgari
Chrono watch for men and an 18-karat gold Bvlgari Quadroto watch
with a classic Tubogas bracelet for women; use of a Jaguar
automobile (chauffeur-driven if you prefer) for the weekend; a
magnum of Taittinger champagne and two Baccarat flutes in a
custom-designed gift box; and ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, you get the idea. The cost: $100,000 for a minimum of
three nights. No drumming, chanting or forming circles required.
</P>
<P>
   Our reports the past two weeks on travel-related millennium
plans barely scratch the surface. For those eager to read more,
here is a sampling of Web sites worth perusing. Most provide links
to other millennium sites:
</P>
<P>
   1). http://www.everything2000.com
</P>
<P>
   2). http://www.rockthemillennium.com
</P>
<P>
   3). http://www.party2000.com
</P>
<P>
   4). http://allonetribedrum.com
</P>
<P>
   5). http://www.la2000.com
</P>
<P>
   6). http://www.2000celebration.com
</P>
<P>
   7). http://www.countdown2000.com
</P>
<P>
   8). http://www.destinations2000.com
</P>
<P>
   9). http://www.rust.net/mc2000/
</P>
<P>
   10). http://www.jepa.co.uk/shopping/party.html (an international
register of millennium celebrations).
</P>
<P>
   11). http://www.millenniumsociety.com
</P>
<P>
   A recommended reading resource: ``The Millennium: A Rough Guide
to the Year 2000'' (Rough Guides, $8.95) by Nick Hanna.
</P>
<P>
   One closing thought: Yes, I know, the new millennium doesn't
officially begin until 2001. So do all these promoters. I can't
wait to see what folks plan for an encore. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1421EDT &QL; 
