</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP, HOPE AND GETTING PEOPLE OFF WELFARE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Public welfare is such an emotionally charged issue
that the Texas Department of Human Services devotes a large chunk
of its Internet web site to debunking widespread welfare ``myths.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor people have big families because welfare rewards them for
having babies,'' is but one of many popular notions that, according
to DHS, is untrue.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, the agency reports, the average welfare family has
only two children. And, for the record, the typical monthly cash
assistance for those two children and their mother is $188, one of
the lowest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in food stamps, and the family's benefits increase by $313
a month, which is still hardly a princely sum.
</P>
<P>
   But government handouts to poor people will always be
controversial, mainly because many hard-working citizens who pay
their own way _ and more taxes than they believe they should _ are
resentful of people who get a ``free ride.''
</P>
<P>
   And they will always have elected officials and political
candidates eager to reinforce one welfare myth or another.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, for example, how adamant Gov. George W. Bush was a few
years ago about penalizing welfare moms for having additional
children?
</P>
<P>
   See the ``big-family'' myth above.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature didn't give Bush the family cap that he
demanded. But, aided by the governor's leadership, lawmakers in
1995 enacted some far-reaching welfare reforms aimed at getting
people off the dole and into jobs. The next year, Congress followed
up with even more comprehensive welfare changes with the same goal.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the changes limit the amount of time a
person can receive welfare benefits and require able-bodied
recipients to look for jobs or enroll in education or training
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the changes were significant improvements. But more
needs to be done to ensure that the people who are leaving the
welfare rolls have an opportunity to be trained for _ and receive _
the type of jobs that actually can change their lives. Many of them
will have to settle for minimum wages, but reform will require more
than increasing Texas' supply of burger flippers.
</P>
<P>
   Government can offer incentives, but private employers committed
to hiring former welfare recipients, rather than merely complaining
about government handouts, will be ultimately responsible for
making the changes work.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300,000 people have left the welfare rolls in Texas
during the past four years. Most of those are children, but many
moms are now working instead of drawing welfare checks.
</P>
<P>
   The state's strong economy has helped. But a more significant
test of welfare reform will occur if the economy cools, and jobs
become harder to find.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, has picked up the welfare reform banner again
in his re-election campaign. Last week, he began airing a new
television commercial touting his efforts to give Texans a
``temporary hand up, not a handout.'' And he proposed a mixed bag
of further changes in the welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   Two proposals are particularly positive.
</P>
<P>
   One would allow families at risk of falling back into welfare a
transition period during which they could temporarily continue to
receive benefits while the caregiver begins working.
</P>
<P>
   Another would increase child-care funds for low-income families
by $100 million to help meet a shortfall in providing child care
for the working poor. A welfare mom _ most adult welfare recipients
are single women _ has trouble working or attending classes if she
can't find someone to care for her children. Most welfare mothers
can't afford conventional day care and, despite the``big-family''
myth, don't always have a friend or relative to help out.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of Bush's other proposals, however, may actually hurt
children. One would cut off a family's entire benefit check if the
parent didn't seek a job or enroll in a training program. Another
would impose a similar sanction if a mother refuses to cooperate
with the state in establishing paternity and collecting child
support from a noncustodial father.
</P>
<P>
   At present, the state withholds only the parent's portion of the
check, less than half of the benefit, in either of those cases. The
tougher sanctions are designed to encourage parents to be
responsible and do the right thing, but why should the children
suffer if the parents don't cooperate?
</P>
<P>
   Still another Bush proposal may have only a limited effect on
the welfare system, but it certainly will perpetuate another of
those myths the state's welfare workers keep trying to refute.
</P>
<P>
   This is a proposed ``one strike and you're out law,'' which
would permanently disqualify a person for welfare assistance after
being caught only one time for trying to cheat the system.
</P>
<P>
   Battling welfare ``cheats'' has a lot of popular appeal, and the
state should fight welfare fraud at every opportunity. But,
according to the Department of Human Services, this is not nearly
as big a problem as the governor's new TV ad suggests.
</P>
<P>
   According to the DHS web site, fraud detected in Texas' welfare
programs represents less than 1 percent of benefits. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1423EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
