<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCORE-AZALEAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENERS WANT MORE FROM AZALEA BLOOMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Azaleas give us cause to celebrate each spring. Yet as the
flowers fade, many moan that the party's just over too soon.
</P>
<P>
   For years, gardeners who want more in the way of azalea blooms
have gotten help from `Fashion' and `Red Ruffles', varieties that
flower in fall as well as in spring.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, more help has arrived with a promising new group of
the popular shrubs _ the Encore azaleas. For the most part, the
Encore varieties look like other azaleas we've used for years in
our gardens. There are eight varieties grouped in the ``Autumn''
series available in the Houston area this fall. These Encore
azaleas are within a 2- to 5-foot height range, have mounding,
spreading or upright growth habits and are evergreen. The Encores,
too, have the same cultural needs we give our old reliables.
</P>
<P>
   But the Encores are repeat bloomers. The difference: They flower
on new wood, not old wood as our traditional azaleas. This doesn't
mean an Encore is going to be dressed in full regalia 12 months of
the year. Not even the most avid azalea fan would want this much of
a good thing. What it does mean is that spring brings a flush of
flowers, followed by a period of new growth. The blooms return in
mid- to late-summer and continue through fall. The flowers stop
during cold weather, but in early to mid-spring, another year of
flowering cycle begins.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of colors is excellent _ from pink to orange-red to
purple.
</P>
<P>
   During the past year and a half, six Encore varieties in the
Autumn series have been tested in Houston-area gardens. (Two more
varieties have recently been added to the Autumn lineup.) The
general consensus is that these flowering shrubs are worth a try.
Mercer Arboretum and Botanic Gardens in Houston reports those
tested there have performed well.
</P>
<P>
   Arboretum experts suggest using Encores as highlights in the
garden, as the colors do make the plants special. Those gardeners
who use large azaleas such as the `Formosas' as a hedge are advised
to not replant with Encores as these, at least at this stage of
testing, do not grow as tall. Reported mature height of the largest
Encore variety is about 5 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Those six varieties have done well in our garden, too, and
perhaps deserve an extra check given the wretched climate we've
faced in '98. Extra water, of course, was needed to see them
through record drought and heat. Our Encores receive typical azalea
treatment: filtered sun or bright shade, and a well-draining,
acidic soil that is moist, but not soggy.
</P>
<P>
   The multiseason Encore azaleas are the product of the
hybridizing efforts of Robert E. Lee of Independence, La., whose
interest in azaleas developed as a high school employee at a
nursery. That interest grew as he studied and crossed azaleas with
varying bloom times. Following college, Lee grew and sold azaleas
through his own wholesale nursery.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-summer 1982, while visiting a fellow member of the Azalea
Society of America, Lee spotted a flat of rooted cuttings of
``Rhododendron oldhamii.'' Cuttings in bloom. After observing the
growth and bud development of this species, he began to cross it
with other azaleas with fall-blooming tendencies. His years of work
paid off and in 1992, Lee struck an agreement with Flowerwood
Nursery, a wholesale operation in Loxley, Ala., to continue his
breeding program while selecting the best varieties for the
gardening public. Encore azaleas were commercially introduced in
the Southeast a year ago. This fall, the Autumn series makes its
debut in the Houston area.
</P>
<P>
   Additional varieties may join the Encore lineup in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The Encore varieties in the Autumn series come in eight
beautiful colors:
</P>
<P>
   `Autumn Embers', a deep orange-red that's so rich in color it's
irresistible to a gardener who typically shies way from orange
flowers. The growth habit is low, spreading and dense. The 2 1/2-
to 3-inch, semi-double flowers begin to open in September and the
plants will continue to flower through fall, rest in winter and
begin again in spring. Approximate size at maturity is 3 feet by 4
feet. Think of `Autumn Embers' as the Halloween azalea.
</P>
<P>
   `Autumn Rouge': These began to flower in late July and August in
our garden. The 2-inch, semidouble, pinkish-red blooms will also
flower in fall. Mid-spring promises a good showing, too.
Approximate mature size is 5 feet by 4 feet.
</P>
<P>
   `Autumn Royalty': This azalea began flowering in our garden in
August and is in bloom now. The 3 1/2-inch rich purple blooms are
beautiful against large green leaves on an upright, globose shrub.
Flowering continues until frost and begins again in mid-spring.
Mature height and width is about 5 feet.
</P>
<P>
   `Autumn Amethyst': The 2-inch, single, soft-purple blooms on
this 4-foot by 4-foot plant are iridescent. The elongated foliage
is pointed and has a rough texture. Flowering begins in late July
or August and becomes heavier in fall. Dense and spreading,
`Amethyst' blooms again in spring.
</P>
<P>
   `Autumn Coral': This is another variety that begins to flower in
July or August, continues through fall and repeats in spring. The
3-inch single blooms are a salmon-pink with fuchsia flecking. The
shrub has a mounding growth habit and matures to about 3 feet in
height and 4 feet in width.
</P>
<P>
   `Autumn Cheer': The smallest of the six tested in our garden,
this compact plant only reaches a couple of feet in height and 3
feet in width. The rose-pink single flowers are a charming 1 {
inches across.
</P>
<P>
   The two recent additions to the Autumn series of Encore azaleas
are:
</P>
<P>
   `Autumn Bravo': This upright azalea is approximately 4 feet in
width and height at maturity and produces 2-inch, semidouble,
bright red blooms.
</P>
<P>
   `Autumn Monarch': A larger shrub at 5 feet in height and width,
`Monarch' comes with 3-inch, semidouble, coral blooms with reddish
flecking and ruffled edges.
</P>
<P>
   Fall is an excellent time to plant azaleas here. The keys to
success in growing and enjoying the Encores are the right location
_ and good soil preparation. Plant the shrubs in bright shade,
filtered sunlight or where they will receive afternoon shade. Do
not plant in low areas. Raise the bed if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Work some compost into the soil. Dig a hole twice as wide as it
is deep. Remove the azalea from the container, and loosen the root
ball. Place the plant in the hole, and make sure the root ball is
above the soil level. Push soil back into the hole, gently tamp to
remove any air pockets. Water well and mulch with pine needles or
pine bark mulch.
</P>
<P>
   Do not let the shrub dry out, especially while it is
establishing a root system.
</P>
<P>
   When to prune Encore azaleas? Although these azaleas are repeat
bloomers, the best time to prune is immediately after the spring
flowering period. This will encourage new growth and maximum bud
set. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
