<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAFFODIL BULBS DON'T NEED REFRIGERATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Do daffodils require refrigeration as do tulips? Do they
naturalize here?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, there is no need to refrigerate. Yes, several varieties
of daffodils naturalize here. These bulbs are among the best for
our Gulf Coast gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Buy early- to late-blooming daffodil varieties for extended
spring blooms. Plant daffodils in sun or semishade around
Thanksgiving in well-draining, organic soil with 2 inches of soil
above the bulb shoulder. Use bone meal or superphosphate if
squirrels dig your bulbs when planting.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulb and Plant Mart (see Garden Calendar) offers many
daffodil varieties for garden and container culture. Nurseries,
too, carry numerous selections.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I kill Bermuda grass or keep it from taking over my
St. Augustine? I've been pulling some of it, but it is hard to get
all of the roots, and this is time consuming.
</P>
<P>
   I have three gardenias growing in half-whiskey barrels. The
majority of the time they do great and have really bloomed. But
occasionally the leaves turn brown around the edges or the foliage
turns yellow. I water every other day and sometimes every day. And
I use a soil acidifier. Do I need to worry?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm afraid the only treatments other than physically removing
the Bermuda is to spot treat it with a product that contains
glyphosphate. Roundup or Finale would do the trick, but of course,
these would kill any St. Augustine they touch, too, so you will
have dead zones until the St. Augustine _ or the Bermuda _ regrows.
If possible, try to just hit the Bermuda runners before they make
contact with your St. Augustine. If you use such as a herbicide, do
so before the St. Augustine goes dormant or that dead zone will be
obvious quite a bit longer.
</P>
<P>
   I would not worry about the gardenias. Browned leaf margins is a
sign of environmental change such as wet-dry extremes. You can
prevent most of this with consistent watering and apparently you
are, since the problem pops up only occasionally. It has been
difficult to maintain consistent soil moisture during the excessive
heat and dry periods.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow leaves are a symptom of too much water, but again, if
this is a once-in-awhile thing, don't worry. It could be, too, that
the occasional leaf that yellows, then drops, is simply the plant's
means of shedding old foliage. Hibiscus do this.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow leaves with green veins are a sign of iron deficiency,
but since you're acidifying the soil, it doesn't sound as if this
is your problem.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Virginia buttonweed is the most obnoxious lawn weed, unfazed
by weed-and-feed fertilizers as well as broadleaf herbicides.
Uprooting the weed is not practical except in small areas of the
lawn. Do you have any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   Following the rule that phosphorus is beneficial for flowering,
I have applied solutions of a 12-55-6 on potted plants and
seedlings. I have spaded 12-24-12 granular fertilizer into
vegetable plots. After several years of those applications the
potted plants declined, and the plots no longer supported anything,
including weeds. A soil analysis at Texas A&AMP;M told me that I had
excessive phosphorus as this does not leach away as nitrogen and
potassium do, and that the built-up phosphorus hindered roots from
absorbing trace minerals. I also learned it may take three years to
restore balance. Your readers should be warned.
</P>
<P>
   I have a rotary composter and use its product as mulch and to
spade in as a soil amendment. As a result, tilth is good. Finding a
dozen or so year-old strawberry plants wiped out at the end of
August, I wonder if the weed killers persist, making this compost
toxic to some plants.
</P>
<P>
   A: Virginia buttonweed is a warm-season, fleshy-leafed perennial
that has small white flowers and green seedpods that resemble green
beads. This weed likes moisture. Your best weapon is healthy St.
Augustine. You can encourage good health with proper fertilization,
watering and mowing. Don't overwater. Water deeply when you do to
encourage turfgrass roots to grow deeper in the soil, away from the
often-hot, quick-drying surface. Fertilize your lawn in the spring
once it has greened and is beginning to grow. If you use a mulching
mower in summer, you will leave enough nutrients on the turf to
replenish the soil. Fertilize the lawn again in fall. Mowing height
for St. Augustine is 2{ to 3 inches. If you mow too closely, you
open up areas to weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Pull what you can of the weed, roots and all, when you walk out
to get the mail. Little by little you can eliminate it. The
herbicide Image is said to be somewhat effective in controlling
Virginia buttonweed.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you for your comments about overuse of phosphorus. We have
mentioned such buildup before in this column.
</P>
<P>
   I can't say whether herbicide residuals killed your
strawberries. We avoid adding treated grass clippings or plant
materials to our compost pile because degradability and toxicity
varies considerably among chemicals. If your compost did not harm
other plants, I would tend to think your strawberries died from
other causes. Strawberries need excellent drainage and a sandy,
acidic soil that has good air space to encourage root health. They
like a soil that has been amended with compost. But strawberries
can succumb to soil-borne diseases. And it can be a chore to keep
them going during the hot summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I could use some information on the desert rose.
</P>
<P>
   A: Desert rose, ``Adenium obesum,'' is a sun-loving succulent
with pink, crimson or white flowers and prominently veined glossy
foliage with downy undersides. The thick, bulbous stem contains a
poisonous milky sap. It is not cold-tolerant, so you will need to
provide winter protection.
</P>
<P>
   Give the plant a half day or more of sun. Water during the
growing season, but make sure the soil drains well. Keep the soil
on the dry side in late fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
   Desert rose likes a loose soil. Any good potting soil is fine
for grafted types. Use a cactus and succulent potting soil for
ungrafted types. Apply a cactus fertilizer every three weeks or so
during the growing season.
</P>
<P>
   Prune the plant if it becomes leggy. The milky juice is
poisonous, so wear gloves while pruning.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
