<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9969 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE-COMPUTER-HNS &LR;      10-05 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-COMPUTER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 USERS OF THE POPULAR iMAC COPE WITH SOME GLITCHES  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The computing world is finding out the hard way
that Apple Computer Inc.'s iMac may be popular but not perfect.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest problems with the aquamarine computer is its
lack of a floppy disk drive. Apple has tried to quell critics by
promoting a third-party device that was engineered specifically for
the iMac: the SuperDisk made by Imation. But there are fundamental
problems with that drive: It will not easily install programs from
floppy disks, and it will not install disk-based programs that are
copy protected. Apple and Imation blame each other for the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The disk drive is just out on the market, so users of the iMac
may not yet be aware of the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Since its debut Aug. 15, the iMac has become the
second-best-selling consumer computer in the United States. PC Data
Inc., a Reston, Va.-based market analysis firm, reports that the
futuristic machine accounted for 7.1 percent of retail computer
sales in August, lagging only behind Hewlett-Packard's 6330 desktop
line.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers have criticized the iMac for its lack of a
traditional floppy-disk drive and standard connections for
printers, scanners and other devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``In trying to come out with cutting-edge technology, Apple has
ignored the real-world needs of their existing customers,'' said
Tom Rhinelander, an analyst with Forrester Research, a technology
research firm in Cambridge, Mass. ``It's that typical Apple way,
which has been Apple arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   The iMac connects to other devices via a plug called a universal
serial bus, or USB. The USB is impressive. Developed by Intel, the
USB creates a high-speed connection at least 10 times faster than
the traditional printer port on older Macs. The USB device also
allows a user to chain together more than 120 devices on one port.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there are only a handful of iMac-compatible USB devices
on the market, in part because computer owners already have
traditionally configured printers and other peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most iMac buyers already own older Macintoshes,'' Rhinelander
said. ``And they already have printers and scanners and such that
use the older connections.''
</P>
<P>
   The iMac does feature a CD-ROM drive. Most popular Mac software
programs are now published on CDs. But CDs are a permanent one-time
record media and can't be used to transfer data. Most common
software packages are now published on CDs. Specialized software
and older versions of popular programs are still published on
floppies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The floppy disk is still the overwhelming choice to transfer
data, especially in the consumer market,'' said Jason Thunstrom, a
spokesman for Imation, an Oakdale, Minn., manufacturer of data
storage devices. ``Last year, 4 billion disks were bought around
the world. That should tell you something.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a floppy has been a ``big issue with users,'' said
Ric Ford, who publishes MacInTouch (www.macintouch.com), an iMac
user Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said some iMac owners had been taking radical steps to
solve the problem: Cracking open the iMac's translucent shell and
soldering in an older Macintosh floppy drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think that would void the warranty,'' Ford said. ``So I
don't recommend it.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple has said it did not include a disk drive on the iMac
because _ in the age of CDs and Internet software _ the technology
is outdated.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has publicized strategies for iMac users to get around
this problem: mainly attaching files to e-mail or connecting an
iMac to a network.
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino, Calif., computer maker has also been touting a
new iMac-specific USB floppy drive released earlier this month by
Imation. The SuperDisk is being promoted as the solution to the
iMac floppy quandary. And, in fact, it does copy files to and from
an iMac's hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   But the SuperDisk, at $150, contains a major flaw: Imation
confirms that it won't easily install floppy disk programs into an
iMac. More disturbing to Mac software publishers, the SuperDisk
cannot install copy protected floppy disk programs. Copy protection
_ which keeps users from making bootleg reproductions of programs _
is the lifeblood of smaller software publishers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Imation, the problem stems from the Apple operating
system, which doesn't properly recognize the Imation drive or the
current copy protection codes. ``There's nothing on our end to
fix,'' Thunstrom said. ``The problem lies in the software that
Apple makes.''
</P>
<P>
   Thunstrom said the iMac won't send the command to automatically
spit out disks when installing software published on more than one
floppy. Multiple disk software is the norm in the industry.
Thunstrom said users must copy each disk onto the iMac's hard
drive, and then run the installation program from there. Disk-based
programs that contain the copy protection, Thunstrom said, simply
won't run.
</P>
<P>
   However, to get to this point, a consumer would have to first
try to install the disk-based program, figure out the problem, then
call Imation's help line, 800-888-2700. There is no documentation
included with the drive, or on Imation's Web site
(www.imation.com), which discusses the glitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been starting to get calls about it,'' said an Imation
technician. ``And we're getting more and more calls the longer the
drive's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Copy protection software developers say Apple has been slow to
respond to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult to get (Apple's) attention,'' said Allen
Cronce, president of PACE Anti-Piracy, a leading floppy disk copy
protection software publisher based in San Jose. ``We eventually
had to go to Apple's headquarters ... but by that time, it was too
late,'' Cronce said. ``They were ready to roll with what they
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shebanek, the USB product marketing manager at Apple, said
the problem lies in the software that Imation shipped with the
SuperDisk.
</P>
<P>
   Shebanek said Imation only worked with Apple on making a disk
drive that would copy files, not install programs from them. That
decision, he said, stemmed from Imation's desire to get the device
out as soon as possible after the iMac appeared.
</P>
<P>
   USB problems have also cropped up in the printer arena. Apple
has had to issue a software update to handle USB glitches affecting
printers, especially those advertised as being iMac-compatible from
Hewlett-Packard and Epson. Epson, in turn, has had to publish fixes
to its iMac printer software.
</P>
<P>
   The iMac's USB problems, Ford said, will eventually fade. ``The
companies that want to capture the emerging iMac market will start
publishing on CDs. It's not hard to do, and it's almost as
economical as floppies.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, added Ford, ``there is going to have to be some pain,
I guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
