r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESS-BJT06-COX     10-05 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-BJT06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE TUESDAY BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Tuesday, 10/6, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   DOW _ Stocks are down sharply in the absence of any good news
out of the finance ministers' meeting over the weekend. The Nasdaq
is off almost 90 points, while the Dow is down 147, giving back
virtually off of Friday's rebound. With list of major technology
stocks, showing Monday close and 52-week high. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTONCHICKEN-HARRYS _ Ailing Boston Chicken files for Chapter
11 protection. Harry's Farmer's Market previously sold rights to
develop Harry's concept outside Georgia and Alabama. Will check to
see if any impact possible on Harry's. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WOLFCAMERA _ Wolf Camera has acquired another photo chain _ a
16-store outfit in Colorado. This has been a tremendous year of
growth for Wolf, which is leading the consolidation frenzy in the
specialty photo industry. Wolf started the year with 300 stores and
will end it with 800. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8
p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GA-GAS _ Tuesday is the day the Public Service Commission is
expected to certify companies that want to compete in Georgia's
deregulated natural gas market. So far, 19 companies have filed for
certification. (Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   GA-PHONE-DEREG _ The Georgia Supreme Court has ruled that _
despite steps into deregulation _ phone company rates for local
service are still subject to state control. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   REC-CENTER _ LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ A Boynton Beach man whose
company was sued four years ago by Playboy Enterprises Inc. for
reproducing nude photos on a CD-ROM has formed a Christian youth
group that plans to open a recreation center in suburban Lake
Worth, Florida. Kasanicky said the idea to start the organization
came to him last year shortly after he became a Christian and
wanted to influence children. (Owers, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INSURANCE-CUTS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas insurers will cut 13
percent, or nearly $700 million, from the cost of liability
policies next year under an order from the state's top insurance
regulator. Among other things, the cuts will mean a $47 savings for
the average Texas driver. That's $247.4 million less for the
liability portion of Texans' auto policies _ the only auto
insurance coverage required by law. (Elizondo Jr., Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-MEDICARE _ AUSTIN, Texas _ More than 100 of the 130
privately run community mental health centers in Texas may be
defrauding Medicare by failing to provide all required services and
could be expelled from the program. (Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PARKS-DEFICIT _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas state parks are operating
at an annual multimillion-dollar deficit, a comprehensive state
audit report shows, and the system could be facing layoffs, park
closures or transfers, and an overhaul of current spending and
income programs. (Leggett, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   TECH-TOOLS _ At last, there is hope of a good night's sleep. No
more fear, no more fretting. My computer is ready for the
millennium. Actually, I have never worried about whether my
computer was ready for what us computer geeks knowingly refer to as
Y2K. There is software to prepare a PC for the coming of 2000.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ Electronic books and magazines are trendy. There
are more publishers on the Web than in New York these days. But
publishing a book electronically isn't a new idea. In fact, the
biggest and most important electronic publishing project began way
back in 1971. (Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAC-REPORT _ True to its word, Microsoft this year released a
long-awaited new version of its Office suite of applications for
the Mac market. The suite, which includes Word and Excel, has won
generally favorable reviews, sold well and is credited with helping
to boost Apple Computer's once sagging fortunes. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH _ No one can blame the editors of the online-only
magazine at http://www.salonmagazine.com for trying to expand its
reporting into the Beltway. In fact, it was Salon's coverage of the
Monica Lewinsky scandal that helped put the e-zine on the map.
However, in its quest for glory, page views and column inches,
Salon may have gone just one step too far. (Katz, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PALM-PILOT _ I use this pocket-size computer to jot down ideas,
keep a running grocery list, record when I've exercised and to
remind me of key appointments. And that's in addition to the
PalmPilot's electronic calendar, address book, calculator and to-do
list. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY _ Since I have lived with and around computers since
before IBM introduced the original IBM Personal Computer in 1981, I
have acquired a fair to middlin' knowledge of how to move a
personal computer. Moving a PC has gotten easier over the years.
(Husted, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECHMEDIA _ It's hard to find a school today that doesn't have
computers. But what, if any effect, are they having on education?
In its special fall issue on computers, FamilyCircle takes a look
at this important trend.(And more about technology reports in this
week's media.) (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT _ Last year's blockbuster film ``Titanic'' was
remarkable. But the movie was even more noteworthy for another
reason. ``Titanic'' was just the second feature film to be
closed-captioned for the deaf and hearing-impaired. (Ghirardini,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
