A9999 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PFEIFFER-BOS &LR;      10-05 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PFEIFFER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PFEIFFER' FAILS AT POLITICAL FARCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
THE SECRET DIARY OF DESMOND PFEIFFER 
Starring: Chi McBride, Danncq Florek, Christine Estabrook, Max
Baker 
On: UPN 
Time: Monday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last season, the controversial new TV series was ``Nothing
Sacred,'' a classy drama that put the church up against '90s
realities. The tempest was predictable, with right-wing and
religious associations appalled at the show's blasphemy, etc.,
etc., etc. But the negative press stoked awareness and curiosity
about an intelligent, worthy show.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, however, the squeaky wheel should not get the grease.
This year, the uproar isover a sitcom called ``The Secret Diary of
Desmond Pfeiffer,'' a silly half-hour of sloppy political
incorrectness and slapstick that doesn't deserve an iota of extra
attention. Set in Abe Lincoln's White House, it's a racuous show
that prides itself on holding nothing sacred, from Mary Todd
Lincoln's sexual needs to the power imbalance of Civil War-era
slavery. While it's mesmerizingly bizarre for about one nanosecond
_ a period farce about Abe Lincoln? What kind of meds were the
creators not taking when they came up with this? _ the toe-cheese
and sex jokes are repetitive and moronic. How many times can we
laugh because everyone thinks Mrs. Lincoln is fat and ugly? For
comparing ``Desmond Pfeiffer'' to the movies of Monty Python,
executive producer Mort Nathan deserves to be clopped between a
pair of coconuts.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy is based on the show's attempts to make comedy
in a slavery setting, just as ``Hogan's Heroes'' whooped it up in
Nazi Germany (during a much less sensitized era). Desmond is a
black English nobleman who finds himself penniless and stuck in
America after cheating at a card game. He's Lincoln's butler, and
not his ``slave,'' but he is unable to leave the States. As on the
1979-86 series ``Benson,'' Desmond is the servant but he is clearly
the sanest person in the house, and he even has his own helper, a
runty Marty Feldman look-alike named Nibblet. His last name, by the
way, is pronounced Puh-fifer, without the silent P.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot episode sent to critics, which UPN is withholding
after protests from African-American groups, contains a few
specific racial gags. When faced with a drunken General Grant,
Desmond says: ``With you at the helm, I better brush up on my
cotton-picking skills.'' And when Desmond is caught outside Mrs.
Lincoln's room, he covers himself by pretending to be a slave: ``I
just be loving my massa so, I just be standin' here in case she be
needin' something.'' The episode that served as the premiere has
Lincoln deep into telegraph sex with a mysterious woman. This
obvious situation yields at least one racial joke, as Lincoln, his
hands burned, asks Desmond to send a telegraph message. ``Sure,
make the black guy tap,'' he replies.
</P>
<P>
   Racially insensitive? Maybe. Humorous or eye-opening? No, not at
all. And in general, the show's primary targets are politics and
sex, and not race. Tonight's telegraph-sex plot is the occasion for
predictable jokes about Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky. ``You're
acting no better than a horny hillbilly from Arkansas,'' Desmond
says to Lincoln. At another point he says, ``Mr. President, you
don't have to explain. This isn't the grand jury.'' That's about as
shrewd as the political satire gets. Meanwhile, a sexually
frustrated Mrs. Lincoln exclaims, ``The Civil War! The Civil War!
What about my needs? When do I get the attention of the executive
branch?'' Get the picture?
</P>
<P>
   The cast gives it a lot of gusto, particulary Christine
Estabrook's first lady. The first time she laughs like Tiny Tim
when she's sexually excited, she makes it work, and in the episode
that isn't airing tonight, she does a brave imitation of Marilyn
Monroe singing ``Happy Birthday'' to the president. But the bold
material is simply not sharp enough to qualify as solid satire or
burlesque, and the actors end up looking stranded. The show may be
in-your-puh-face, but it sure isn't puh-funny.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
