<HEADER>
A0004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMIC-WHIZKIDS-BOS     10-05 1613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMIC-WHIZKIDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD, MIT WHIZ KIDS MAY BE THE KEY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin (Harvard 1960) needs the
latest on the global financial crisis, he turns to his deputy,
Lawrence H. Summers (Harvard PhD 1982 and a former Harvard faculty
member). When Summers needs help, he turns to his deputy, David A.
Lipton (Harvard PhD 1981).
</P>
<P>
   If these officials wonder what the critics are saying, they need
look no further than their fellow alumni or former colleagues
Rudiger Dornbusch, Paul Krugman (both MIT), or Jeffrey Sachs
(Harvard).
</P>
<P>
   By now, hundreds of millions of people have been swept into the
financial maelstrom roiling the planet. But no more than a few
dozen are at the center of the effort to figure out what to do, and
an inordinate number of them live, teach, or were trained in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's as it should be, because to a remarkable degree
these are the men responsible for the optimistic economic outlook
that has dominated most of this decade _ the philosophy that sound
money and open markets can usher developing countries into the
global fold and kindle a golden era of growth.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the philosopy has become so closely associated with this
group that it is called the ``Washington consensus'' or the
``Massachusetts Avenue consensus,'' a bow both to the street that
links Harvard University and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology and to a similarly named street in Washington whose
think tanks have served as homes away from home to generations of
Boston economists.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a large extent, Cambridge was the birthplace of the
Washington consensus,'' said J. Bradford DeLong, a deputy assistant
Treasury secretary in the mid-1990s who teaches economic history at
the University of California at Berkeley. ``That's why there are so
many people there who are mystified and trying to work out what's
gone wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   And something has gone terribly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   For after a decade of lifting nations and opening societies, the
consensus now seems to be driving a number of developing countries
into recession and turmoil, and nudging the world toward the
financial abyss.
</P>
<P>
   Such an abrupt reversal of fortune is making this a cruel season
for the Cambridge crowd. Its members have become targets of harsh
criticism and unflattering comparisons, especially with ``the best
and the brightest'' who led the nation into Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people up in Boston have egg on their face,'' said Paul
Davidson, a University of Tennessee economist. ``They should have
known this was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the ``best-and-brightest'' comparison is probably
unfair, and many in the Cambridge crowd did know _ and warn _ of
what could go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that there's a fundamental flaw'' with the
Massachusetts Avenue consensus, said Robert M. Solow, the MIT
economist and Nobel laureate who served as one of President
Kennedy's economic advisers in the 1960s and who has trained or
worked with almost everyone in the current generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think that life, especially financial life, gets ahead of
what you've worked out, or think you've worked out. The
international financial system just got away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to conceive of how tiny _ how nearly claustrophobic _
is the circle that crafted the Massachusetts Avenue consensus and
is now expected to repair its tattered tenets.
</P>
<P>
   While finance officials and central bankers from scores of
countries converged on Washington this weekend for a string of
high-level meetings, while most of the pronouncements were being
made by senior officials like Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan, almost all the heavy policy work was being done by
a group just below the top ranks that is largely populated by
Harvard- and MIT-trained economists.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by now the Cambridge crowd controls the second tier at
all three institutions most directly responsible for coping with
the crisis: the US Treasury, the International Monetary Fund, and
the World Bank. Besides Summers at Treasury, there is former MIT
professor Stanley Fischer at the IMF, and MIT-trained Joseph
Stiglitz at the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to track job switches among group members can be
dizzying. Stiglitz, for example, assumed his current position as
the World Bank's chief economist when Summers vacated the post.
Summers got the World Bank job when Fischer left it.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to trace the group's professional and social ties can be
even more confusing. At one time or another, Fischer and Dornbusch,
both of whom are in their 50s, taught almost all the rest of the
group, most of whom are in their 40s. Fischer and Summers
coauthored a series of academic papers and shared a summer house on
Martha's Vineyard. Summers, Sachs, and Lipton were graduate
students together, and Summers hired Lipton at Treasury after
Lipton had worked for Sachs at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the connections straight is tougher still when one
realizes that the group's field of operation extends well beyond
Boston and Washington. Group members have advised scores of
countries across Asia, Latin America, and Eastern Europe about how
to fix their economies.
</P>
<P>
   But notwithstanding the job changes, professional pairing, and
globe-girdling travel, the Cambridge crowd shares a similar
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys _ and they are all guys _ come at the task of being
an economist with a willingness to talk about policy, and to frame
their theories to influence it,'' said David C. Colander, a
Middlebury College historian. ``Within the world of policy, they
form a very tight oligopoly at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To see how influential the consensus and the Cambridge
economists were requires an understanding of a critical change that
has occurred over the last two decades, one that has been so
thorough that _ until the current crisis _ it seemed as if this was
the way things have always been: Much of the world's population can
now put its money where it wants to put it.
</P>
<P>
   People can exchange their currencies for foreign currencies.
They can generally deposit funds outside their home countries. And
they can invest both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   All of this strikes Americans as commonplace because they have
always been able to move their money, and because most assumed that
such movement is a key part of the market system.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision in the early 1990s by many nations, especially
developing ones, to permit free movement of money and to open their
currency and financial markets to the world represented a dramatic
break with the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody said they had to do that,'' said Yale economist James
Tobin, a Nobel laureate and a longtime critic of open financial
markets. ``Capital controls are perfectly legitimate'' under
international rules, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason that Tobin and an older generation of economists
object to free movement of money is that they believed financial
markets were more prone to destabilizing booms and busts than
conventional markets for goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   But starting in the early 1970s, a new generation began arguing
that domestic financial markets were much more stable than
previously thought, and by decade's end key members of the
Cambridge crowd were applying the new arguments internationally. At
crucial moments over the last 20 years, the Cambridge economists
have written papers, devised models, or offered opinions that fed
the open-market drive, contributions that at least some members of
the group say they regret in light of today's global upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, for example, Krugman wrote an influential
paper that was widely interpreted as showing that financial markets
only punish countries that get their economic fundamentals wrong
by, for instance, running big government budget deficits. And the
MIT economist repeatedly dismissed the idea that markets can be
swept by self-fulfilling panics that punish even nations doing
everything right.
</P>
<P>
   But a self-fulfilling panic appears to be precisely what has now
descended on large parts of the world. ``I was wrong,'' the
normally unyielding Krugman told reporters last week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the global crisis has worsened in recent months, a new edge,
a certain nastiness, has crept into relations among the Cambridge
economists, one that some think signals the beginning of the end of
the group's influence.
</P>
<P>
   Although he professes sympathy for Summers and Lipton, Krugman
has declared that Treasury/IMF rescue plans for Russia and
Indonesia, which the two men helped designed, are failures, and has
said that it is time to try something new.
</P>
<P>
   Although he insists he has no personal animus, Sachs has
launched withering attacks on the IMF, including work by Fischer,
charging that the agency has behaved ``rudely, abruptly, and
arrogantly'' and sought ``to do things to poor countries that we
would never do to ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But before counting the Cambridge crowd out, said intellectual
historian Colander, it is important to remember that these are
among the few people who grasp how the global economy works _ and
that the process of conjuring theories, trying them out, and making
repairs is how international economic policy has always been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last set of arguments they were making seem to have been
the wrong ones,'' said Colander. ``So they are all staking out new
positions to see who can be right next time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how they work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Aaron Zitner of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
Washington.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
