<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 14:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0007 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-SELLING-BOS &LR;      10-05 1776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-SELLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART FOR WHOSE SAKE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A legal battle between Boston's Museum of Fine Arts and a
Lawrence, Mass.-based charitable trust seems, on the surface, the
kind of argument that flares up in preschool between two children
who want to play with the same ball.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of who controls a Monet masterpiece and 16
other paintings _ bequeathed in 1911 by the Rev. William E. Wolcott
of Lawrence to the trust but long displayed at the MFA _ raises
very adult, complex issues about the role of art in society, about
class and privilege, and about how to respect the deceased's wishes
while confronting a century of change.
</P>
<P>
   Trustees of the White Fund want to sell the paintings _ Monet's
``Field of Poppies near Giverny'' and two Pissarros, among them _
to pay for a wide array of arts projects in Lawrence, a move they
say is needed to fulfill Wolcott's last wishes. The works are
estimated to be worth between $5.7 million and $7.6 million _
enough to vastly expand the arts programs in struggling Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   The museum _ which has had posession of the painting for 86
years _ counters that if the paintings are sold, they will leave
Massachusetts and may end up in private collections never to be
exhibited again.
</P>
<P>
   Percolating up through the court filings and legal arguments are
the questions of which brings more value to the individual _ a
world-renowned museum or a community arts center? An Impressionist
masterpiece or being given the opportunity to paint?
</P>
<P>
   Many people in Lawrence, echoing the will of Wolcott, believe it
is the latter. The city, they say, gets little benefit from having
great paintings hanging in a museum 40 miles away. ``I don't think
there is a child in Lawrence who is familiar with the paintings,''
says the Rev. Juan P. Romero, who today preaches from the pulpit
that once belonged to Wolcott.
</P>
<P>
   Defining the true purpose of art is ``infinitely subjective in
nature,'' says James Mundy, director of the Frances Lehman Loeb Art
Center at Vassar College in New York. ``It is very difficult to
anticipate how art will affect an individual. Sometimes it happens
in completely serendipitous ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is standing in your line of sight when you are at a moment
open to enlightenment or intellectual breakthrough. It could be a
Monet on loan to the MFA, or it could be something local.''
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Rogers, the director of the MFA, says that the museum
serves ``an extraordinary community purpose that a small museum in
Lawrence simply cannot. The displays we do are so great _ how can I
put it? _ that they serve the whole of New England, including the
people of Lawrence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is one of the world's greatest encyclopedic art
museums. You weigh that with a community arts center, and I don't
know how you can do that ... They are very different. I do believe
that great museums with really great masterpieces offer
extraordinary opportunities for firsthand encounters with great
art. And great art has the capacity to refresh people spiritually,
physically and mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Hyde, a professor of art and politics at Kenyon College in
Ohio, says the dispute ``reproduces two traditions in the American
sense of the purposes of art.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, there is the late 19th-century idea that fine
art produces fine manners, and that if we wish to have a durable
civilization we should imitate the European nations whose citizens
were governable ... precisely because their senses were gratified
by art. Rev. Wolcott, who gave the paintings under dispute to the
White Fund in Lawrence, belongs fully to this tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other side, we have those whose hope it is to have the
past regularly judged by the needs of the present, and to have art
so judged as well. ... If a city like Lawrence had $6 million which
someone had given them to support the arts, certainly they would
not go out and buy a Monet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Lawrence's proposals) sound like fine ways to use the
money ... (It is) still part of the tradition in America that arts
are supposed to be used for something, like teaching manners,
rather than being valuable in their own right. It is the way in
which art is pitched: People become more creative if they are
trained in arts, whether they end up writing software or designing
automobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   That paintings have created such a struggle does not surprise
Vassar's Mundy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art can stimulate in so many different ways and illicit such
strong feelings,'' he says. ``It transcends itself in these ways
and brings out fascinating aspects of human character, or
institutional character and comportment. It is wonderful that
inanimate objects can spur you to all kinds of things. But I'd hate
to see a court fight over what is best for Lawrence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether what the trustees are doing is in the spirit of the
bequest is something the MFA should not play a role in. It seems to
me that is between the trustees and the people of Lawrence.'' The
MFA, for its part, says it is only trying to uphold the wishes of
Rev. Wolcott.
</P>
<P>
   Wolcott _ in an act that was as impressive for its magnanimity
as for its foresight and sensibility _ explicitly detailed in his
1907 handwritten will what he wanted to happen to the 17 paintings
he had inherited two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   He said the paintings should go to the Museum of Fine Arts in
Boston if _ and only if _ there was no ``public art gallery housed
in a fire-proof building'' in Lawrence, suitable to display the
works. When Wolcott died, there was no such gallery in Lawrence
and, in 1913, the paintings went to the MFA.
</P>
<P>
   But his will made clear that, even if the paintings hung in
Boston, ``ownership and control of the pictures shall be vested
permanently and inalienably in ... (White Fund Trustees) and their
successors.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained: ``My purpose in making this bequest is to create
and gratify a public taste for fine art, particularly among the
people of ... Lawrence. And I give to the said trustees of the
White Fund full and absolute authority in any contingency not fully
provided for ... to take such action as they judge best fitted to
serve the purpose described.''
</P>
<P>
   The MFA believes language in the will makes it impossible for
the paintings to be sold; the trustees say a sale must be
considered because having the paintings hang in Boston does little
to instill an appreciation of fine art in Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year ago, the three White trustees ``revisited
whether we are are doing our duty `to create and gratify a public
taste for fine art,''' says Thomas Caffrey, an attorney and current
chairman of the trustees.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, a move to sell the paintings met with a public
outcry. Indeed, there are some who still get great pride from the
knowledge that a mill town that has been in decline for much of the
20th century would ``own'' such things of value and beauty.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the trustees established a nine-person task
force, chaired by former attorney general James Shannon, to
determine what to do with the paintings. Their report recommends
selling the collection and using the windfall to establish within
the White Fund a separate trust known as the Wolcott Fund of the
Arts. Through grants, the fund would ``encourage the creation and
presentation of excellent art and art education in Lawrence.'' Part
of the money would be used to bolster struggling arts organizations
in Lawrence. And lastly, an arts resource center would be created
at the Lawrence Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA, according to Caffrey, is not receptive to this idea.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps the MFA would like to buy the paintings? On April 30,
before seeking court permission to sell the paintings, White Fund
attorney Richard Renehan sent a letter to the MFA asking museum
officials if they were interested in purchasing any of the
paintings and at what price? The letter asked for a response within
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's response came on May 13, when the MFA filed papers
in Suffolk Superior Court asking a judge to not only block the sale
of the paintings but to find that circumstances do not exist for
``possession of the Wolcott collection to be transferred from the
MFA to any other person or location.''
</P>
<P>
   The response took some by surprise and, to some observers,
reflected haughty disdain for the working people of Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not have to be a class issue, or a contentious issue
between the world renowned home of arts in Boston vs. a blue-collar
city, but some of that has crept into the discussion because of the
attitude the museum has taken,'' says Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Patricia McGovern, the former candidate for governor who
grew up in Lawrence, ``There are style differnces that are very
profound between the cities of Massachusetts like Lawrence and
folks from the cultural world of Boston. There are class
misunderstandings, but there are differences on both sides that
should be overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reasonable people should get together and work through this so
the paintings could stay in Massachusetts and something wonderful
can happen for Lawrence.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, the Kenyon College art professor who specializes in the
funding of art, says that issues of class are very much at work in
this dispute. ``Museums like the MFA were created in the late 19th
century as part of the self-fashioning of a confident upper class.
I don't know how best to describe in terms of class `the people of
the city of Lawrence' as Wolcott calls them, except to say this is
not a city with the kind of extra cash that builds museums.''
</P>
<P>
   The MFA may have been founded by Boston Brahmins, but its
mission, says Rogers, has always been to educate. He notes that the
MFA has had programs with Lawrence schools since the 1980s. Last
year, some 700 Lawrence students visited the MFA. And he rejects
the portrait of the museum as an institution run by a silver spoon
set trying to hang on to a valuable Monet because it is, well ... a
valuable Monet.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the church where Wolcott once preached has, for the
last 20 years, been the Iglesia de Dios de Lawrence. While the
church _ and the city _ has changed considerably since Wolcott's
death, the current pastor of the church, Romero, says the White
Fund Trustees are doing the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best service the paintings can do for the children of
Lawrence is not the present situation,'' says Romero. ``If the
museum wanted to search for what was in the heart of Rev. Wolcott,
they would do otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Matthew Brelis is the Globe's Focus writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
