<HEADER>
A0025 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNDERAGE-DRINKING-BOS     10-05 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERAGE-DRINKING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDERAGE DRINKING A MAJOR CONCERN, STUDY FINDS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The public is so concerned about the social
consequences of teenage drinking that an overwhelming number would
support tougher restrictions on alcohol and higher alcohol taxes,
according to a new national survey.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, commissioned by the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation,
found that 96 percent of the public is troubled by underage
consumption of alcohol. Concern is so great that large numbers of
respondents favor a wide range of get-tough policies, including
curbs on public drinking, strict controls on alcohol sales, and
higher alcohol taxes for prevention and treatment programs.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-two percent would support raising alcohol taxes by 5
cents per drink, if the funds were used to pay for programs that
prevent minors from drinking and to increase alcohol treatment
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The report, being released today, indicates that most US adults
favor bans on televised liquor ads, billboard ads for alcohol, home
delivery of alcohol, and a zero-tolerance policy for underage
drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Americans are not interested in returning to the days
of Prohibition, but this survey demonstrates that the American
public is concerned and wants to see policies put in place that
will help prevent our teenagers from drinking,'' said Nancy
Kaufman, vice president of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II, a Massachusetts Democrat
and proponent of stronger alcohol controls since 1990, was
encouraged by the survey results.
</P>
<P>
   ``These findings demonstrate broad-based support. Ordinary
Americans recognize that alcohol is now the number one killer of
people in this country under the age of 24,'' said Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy has proposed limits on alcohol advertising, health
warnings on alcohol ads, the elimination of the tax deduction for
alcohol ads and promotions, and a ban on alcohol company compaigns
on college campuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can ever get this legislation before the Congress as a
whole, we have always felt we would do very, very well,'' Kennedy
said. ``But the alcohol lobby has been able to stifle the ability
of us to ever get it to the House floor where people would have to
make a stand.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the survey, the support for stiffer policies
crossed political party, gender, and age lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Results show little distinction among those identified as
Democrat vs. Republican or liberal vs. conservative in their
support for tighter controls on alcohol sales and promotion,'' said
the report. ``Overall, Republicans were as likely to agree with
statements suggesting more social controls on alcohol sales and
youth access as were Democrats, and conservatives were as
supportive of stronger regulation as liberals.''
</P>
<P>
   Women, however, were even more supportive of stricter controls
on alcohol sales and promotion than men. Younger people, between
the ages of 18 and 24, were the least supportive of restrictive
alcohol policies.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the respondents said they had experience with
problem drinking because someone close to them or a family member
had a drinking problem in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found the most support for policies that would
restrict public drinking on city streets, parks, college campuses,
and at concerts and beaches, as well as require training for
servers and bar owners.
</P>
<P>
   The least support came for bans on happy hours, state control of
liquor sales, and beer keg sales.
</P>
<P>
   The report found the public receptive to policies making it more
difficult for teenagers to have access to alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   The survey is based on the responses of 7,021 people over seven
months in 1997. The sampling error is plus or minus 2 percentage
points. It was conducted by Mathematica Policy Research Inc. under
the direction of the Alcohol Epidemiology program at the University
of Minnesota.
</P>
</TEXT>
