<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO FAR, TELECOM ACT HAS ONLY HELPED A FEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ More than two years after deregulation, the
$200 billion telecommunications industry hasn't produced the riches
of services and price reductions it had promised for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Industry executives say the pace of deregulation has been slower
than anticipated, in part because the regional Bells and other
carriers have not yet been allowed into the lucrative $80 billion
long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   In California, consumer groups and the state Public Utilities
Commission say competition has been stifled because Pacific Bell
has made it difficult for competitors to access its phone network
and customers. Pacific Bell still has a virtual monopoly on the
residential phone market.
</P>
<P>
   But deregulation has not bypassed all customers. The federal
Telecommunications Act of 1996, which in theory allows the
communications companies to get into one another's businesses over
time, unleashed a flood of technological advancements.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Tobkin, of Bain &AMP; Co.'s telecommunications and technology
practice in San Francisco, said wealthy, technically-savvy
consumers are reaping the benefits of a deregulated marketplace
with services such as cable modems, digital television and
dedicated lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next five years, a lot's going to happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Tobkin noted that consumers who don't need a lot of
technology in their lives _ or can't afford it _ won't see choices
and lower prices anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the average person with a phone on the kitchen wall,
things aren't going to change a lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Covad Communications Group Inc., a Santa Clara, Calif.-based
service provider formed after the telecom act was passed, is one
company that is not offering services to residential customers
because company officials say it is not profitable.
</P>
<P>
   What Covad and other new carriers concentrate on is selling
high-speed digital modem lines to small- and medium-sized
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no regional Bell operating company has been allowed to
offer long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   Some 80 communications executives met here last week at the 21st
Century Telecoms Company Global Executive Symposium. Those
attending the conference said that even though the Bells can't yet
offer long-distance service, they need not fret about competition
from other carriers. The regional Bells still control the lion's
share of local phone markets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to dislodge the big players,'' said Robin
Gaster, head researcher for the Economist Intelligence Unit, which
hosted the conference with Deloitte &AMP; Touche Consulting. ``They're
big. They're tough. They have a lot of money and even more
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Hirschhorn, strategy director for Orange PLC, a global
satellite technology company in London, said new communications
providers should try to pay more attention to the consumer market
and the small office/home office, or SOHO, segment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people doing job-sharing, working out of
their homes,'' he said. ``There's an enormous demand to satisfy
that market.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirschhorn said this market needs wireless and computer-service
providers in particular.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
