<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUTION CAN PREVENT VIRUS WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Has your computer felt well lately?
</P>
<P>
   Had a touch of the flu? Maybe a . . . virus?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we can joke all we want about computers and viruses. But
it's serious business, as proven by a recent survey conducted on
behalf of several major corporations, including Intel, Microsoft,
Price Waterhouse and Symantec.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Computer Virus Prevalence Survey, which was based on
interviews with about 300 technology professionals who oversee more
than 750,000 PCs and servers across the country, concluded that
computer virus infection rates are increasing.
</P>
<P>
   This despite the widespread availability of anti-virus software
and the fact that most new computers come loaded with anti-virus
software.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 survey found more than 86.5 ``virus encounters'' per
1,000 machines per year, which is an increase from last year's
finding of 62.5 encounters per 1,000 machines per year.
</P>
<P>
   The most prevalent viruses were of the ``macro'' variety, and
included WM/Concept, WM/CAP, WM/Wazzu, WM/Npad and XM/Laroux. Macro
viruses usually are written in Word Basic, and hide within
documents such as Microsoft Word files.
</P>
<P>
   The WM/Concept virus, alone, accounted for nearly four
infections per 1,000 computers per month, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Why are virus infection rates increasing? The survey blames a
number of factors, including inadequate policies in offices around
the country to guide workers in their daily use of computers and
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   What's all this mean to the average computer user? Take
precautions, but don't panic.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you have a decent anti-virus program loaded and
running in the background on your machine. Opinions vary on which
is best. Top sellers include Norton's, Dr. Solomon's, F-Prot and
McAfee. There are others as well, including some cheap and/or free
solutions available online.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise caution. Be wary of downloading files or programs from
independent computer bulletin boards or no-name Web sites. Scan
floppies for viruses before using them. Configure your e-mail
program to put any incoming attached files where you can see them
(like on your desktop) and make sure you scan them for viruses
before opening them.
</P>
<P>
   As I said, this isn't anything to panic over. People get run
over by cars every day, but that doesn't stop anyone from crossing
the street. They've just learned to look both ways before stepping
foot off the sidewalk!
</P>
<P>
   If you want to read more about viruses, there are many Web sites
available, including ciac.llnl.gov/ or www.symantec.com/avcenter/. &QL; 
 &QL; 
New Mac OS to debut
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attention Macintosh users: Apple's latest operating system, Mac
OS 8.5, will debut soon.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a Mac user or you'd like to read more about the Mac,
including the new iMac, check out the Macintosh Page on Arizona
Central, the Web site of the Arizona Republic. You can find it at
www.az &QL; 
central.com/computing. Click on the link to the Macintosh Page. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
Voyeur search update
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I wrote about a couple search sites that allow
visitors to watch what others are searching for.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, I've received many e-mails about problems people are
having trying to connect with the sites.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   The first site is webcrawler &QL; 
.com/SearchTicker.html. As I said in the column, there is no
``www'' at the beginning. But people had trouble with the URL
because they did not use an upper case ``S'' and ``T'' in the term
``SearchTicker.'' That makes all the difference in the world. If
you use a lower case ``s'' and ``t,'' you will get an error message
telling you the page no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the second site was our fault. Somehow, we
managed to erase an all-important ``k'' in the URL. The proper Web
address is: www.mckinley.com/. Once there, look on the right side
of the screen for the search voyeur icon and link. That will take
you where you want to go. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye is an online editor and covers computer- and
Internet-related issues for Arizona Central, the Web site of The
Arizona Republic. He can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
