<HEADLINE>
BEING PARTISAN IN SUN CITY IS NO PICNIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The property owners association at Sun City West has a
hard and fast rule forbidding any political party or candidate from
using its recreation facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Association facility space WILL NOT be made available for rent
or use,'' the policy reads, ``by members of the Association for
partisan political purposes or activities (partisan is defined as
having a firm adherence to a party, faction, cause or person).''
</P>
<P>
   This particular restriction has been on the books for as long as
anyone can remember and is strictly enforced against all political
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Except Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize when I moved here that people had such a
funny idea of democracy,'' said Bill Goldfarb. ``Now, I know.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months back, Goldfarb wanted to stage what he calls an
``old-fashioned Democratic Party picnic'' in Sun City West's
Beardsley Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to invite candidates from Paul Johnson (who's
running for governor) on down the line, including my sister-in-law
(Bunny Goldfarb), who's running for the state House,'' Goldfarb
said. ``We got turned down.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldfarb received a letter from the recreation manager stating,
``We are prohibited by our bylaws of the Sun City West Recreation
Center to allow meetings, picnics, events, etc., which address
anything of a political nature. Therefore, your request is
denied.''
</P>
<P>
   Rules are rules, Goldfarb figured.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't give it much thought until he received the October
newsletter of the property owners association, which announced on
the front cover, ``Governor Hull Comes to SCW.''
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Hull, a Republican, has been invited to speak
at the local rec center.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the center's manager determined that Hull's
appearance, less than a month before the election, could be
construed as being of ``a political nature'' and canceled the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, however, he was overruled by the governing
board.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Carole Hubbs explained it this way: ``Our
governor is our governor and that's not partisan politics.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as the governor is Republican, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Hull is supposed to speak at Sun City West on Thursday. The
local Democratic Club has said it will picket the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've checked the registration rolls,'' Goldfarb told me,
``and all of the members of the board are Republicans. Is that how
it works? Is anything OK if you happen to be the party in charge?''
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, yes.
</P>
<P>
   This not only explains why intelligent people can get away with
calling Jane Hull's appearance ``nonpartisan,'' but also why
President Bill Clinton will be impeached. It's not about rules;
it's about who enforces them. Or doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   At Sun City West, Hull will be introduced by Republican state
Sen. Ed Cirillo. The board also has agreed to allow Secretary of
State Betsey Bayless, another Republican running for office, to
speak at the rec center. Nothing partisan about that, organizers
say.
</P>
<P>
   Late last week I spoke with Jerry Medford, a member of the
recreation board who also happens to be a Republican precinct
committeeman and president of the Sun City West Republican Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's not bringing out any brochures or raising any
funds, so I tend to lean that it's not partisan.'' he said. ``In my
opinion, it's showing respect for the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Medford knows how politics works. He's seen it firsthand, having
worked for a time as a Secret Service agent for President Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   I asked if he believed a politician like Hull would make a
speech within a month of an election that had nothing to do with
getting votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You may have a point there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And so, one party gets to make speeches while the other can't
hand out hot dogs and beans. &UR; In case you didn't already know,
politics is no picnic. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
