<SLUG> BC-EDIT_MILITARY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY UNREADY, CLINTON TO BLAME  
 (THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE OCT. 5 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - As the massacre of ethnic Albanians continues in
Kosovo, as blood and glass are cleaned from the streets of the West
Bank city of Hebron, as Iraq stands resolute against U.N. weapons
inspectors, the U.S. military is in its worst shape in decades.
</P>
<P>
   How else do you explain Gen. Thomas Schwartz, the new head of
the U.S. Army Forces Command, telling the Senate Armed Services
subcommittee on readiness that the military's readiness to wage war
has slipped badly under tight budgets and ``the train wreck is
imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   And, that testimony was followed by a presentation from Col. Jim
Green, director of assignments at the personnel center at Randolph
Air Force Base near San Antonio, who told senators, ``I'd say we're
going to a situation that is four times worse than we've ever seen
in the history of our modern Air Force.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Air Force expects to lose 1,951 pilots by 2002,
reducing its strength to about 11,000 pilots. More than a third of
those leaving will be fighter pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Now the president himself is suggesting budget increases to
address aging weapons and to improve the living conditions for U.S.
troops.
</P>
<P>
   So, pardon us if we ask, how did we get into this mess in the
first place?
</P>
<P>
   Who was minding the store as our military preparedness was being
carted out the back door?
</P>
<P>
   To whom do we look for responsibility for this crisis?
</P>
<P>
   Could it be the commander in chief _ the very same fellow who is
taking bows for our robust economy?
</P>
<P>
   We don't mind the bows, even though the Clinton administration
neglects to mention Congress and the Federal Reserve Board _ and
the American worker _ when taking credit for the economy.
</P>
<P>
   What we do mind, and, indeed, what should disturb most
Americans, is that Bill Clinton owes us all one more apology for
what he has done to the national defense. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
