<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ANTZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZING `ANTZ' DOESN'T BOTHER APPEALING TO KIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In many of the journalistic fall film previews, you could find
someone from DreamWorks saying something like this about ``Antz'':
``It's not a cute cartoon. It's an action-adventure movie.''
Translation: ``Everyone expects a cute cartoon, so we'd better do
some spin-doctoring before we take a bath at the box office.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks has reason to worry. ``Antz'' succeeds more for what
its makers want it to do than for what its audience might want it
to do. There's something admirable about that these days, when most
movies play to the lowest common denominator.
</P>
<P>
   And it still delivers, in many ways. It looks stunning. Strike
that _ it looks amazing. The all-insect cast has a level of
expressiveness that it seems to have learned from E.T., the master
at such things, and the backgrounds are so richly detailed that the
movie should win an Oscar nomination for production design, if
that's possible with an animated movie. Teens and adults will also
get off on the film's grown-up jokes and sly film references.
</P>
<P>
   What the movie has to offer younger children _ who will make up
a sizable portion of the audience _ is another matter. Expressive
as these critters are, they're not really all that cute, because
they look like ... well, ants, and sort of science-fiction ants at
that. The movie eschews original songs in favor of oldies and
standards, and except for the show-closing (and inevitable) ``High
Hopes,'' they sound like they'd appeal to Woody Allen (who voices
Z, the film's hero) more than they would to preschoolers.
</P>
<P>
   There's more action than slapstick, and although the battle
scenes are almost as impressive as the ones in Disney's ``Mulan,''
there isn't enough cuteness or humor to balance them out. They're
also relatively gruesome _ with Allen in the lead role, sensitive
types might think they're watching ``Saving Private Wry Ant.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the movie's
individual-against-the-state-and-against-conformity plot. How long
has it been since you saw a family film that felt like a
collaboration between George Orwell and Ayn Rand? Not that Z is a
Randian man _ or ant _ of action. For one thing, he speaks in
Allen's neurotic New York whine; for another, the first time we
meet him, he's talking to his analyst _ a nice in-joke for all the
adults in the audience, as well as the 4-year-olds who like to
double up ``The Lion King'' with ``Annie Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Z isn't a take-charge guy so much as he is a guy who lets events
sweep him along. He drones on disenchantedly about his life as a
worker, but does little to change his lot until bored Princess Bala
(Sharon Stone) goes slumming with the lower ants and hits on Z
because he's the only guy not following the crowd. Z falls for her
instantly, and his crush begins a journey that leads to him being
an inadvertent war hero and a reluctant outlaw.
</P>
<P>
   Because DreamWorks honcho Jeffrey Katzenberg was able to round
up the actors who directors Eric Darnell and Tim Johnson wanted,
the movie feels if it were cast first, then scripted. The cast is
so star-heavy, ``Antz'' feels like the ``We Are the World'' of
animation. Not only does Allen play a lucky neurotic and Stone play
a vampish princess, but Sylvester Stallone (who nearly steals the
film) portrays a buff soldier ant (who, true to Stallone form,
takes a beating) and Gene Hackman plays a power-mad general.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Christopher Walken, as the evil sidekick who talks
... in a series of ... eccentric ... pauses, and Jennifer Lopez as
a worker ant with a great ovipositor. Only Dan Aykroyd and Jane
Curtin, as preppy bees, seem to be playing characters rather than
playing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's pro-individualism theme is a bit ironic, coming from
a company whose motto might be ``What would Disney do?'' (Come to
think of it, there's some messianic subtext going on here, too.)
Well, Disney wouldn't toy this much with a tried-and-true formula,
and you have to give DreamWorks some credit for taking risks.
Disney would have more cute characters, Disney would have more
songs, Disney would have more comic relief, Disney would cut back
on the language, some of which is surprisingly strong. Disney would
probably make more money. But Disney would also try to satisfy
everybody, and DreamWorks _ and directors Darnell and Johnson _
deserve some congratulations for not compromising their vision.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Antz'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 of a possible 5 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directors: Eric Darnell, Tim Johnson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Woody Allen, Sharon Stone &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Length: 83 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ language, animated violence and at least one sexual
reference &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
