u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-NOTES-NYT &LR;      10-05 0174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Pinpointing Lymph Nodes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A new procedure may allow surgeons to reduce the number of lymph
nodes removed in breast cancer surgery, sparing women some pain and
possible complications.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors routinely remove the lymph nodes around the armpit in
case breast cancer has spread to them. Removing the nodes may
improve the patient's chances of survival. The presence of cancer
there also tells doctors how aggressively to use cancer drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In a study reported in the current New England Journal of
Medicine, doctors from the University of Vermont injected
radioactive material around the tumor and then removed only the
nodes that eventually absorbed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quick and easy to precisely locate the node before ever
making an incision. That's the key advantage,'' said Dr. David
Krag, who helped develop the technique.
</P>
<P>
   Krag trained 11 other surgeons to use the method. They reported
the results of testing on 443 patients.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
