<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY06-COX     10-05 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BLACK, HISPANIC LEADERS BLAST SOCIAL SECURITY PRIVATIZATION
STUDY
 &HT;    650&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Black and Hispanic leaders Monday criticized a
study that claimed minorities would fare better under a privatized
retirement system than under the Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   The comments by Julian Bond, chairman of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, and Raul
Yzaguirre, president of the National Council of La Raza, were the
latest in a rising chorus that has criticized claims by the
conservative Heritage Foundation that blacks and Hispanics would do
better if they were able to invest their retirement payments in
personally managed accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Bond noted that many of the individuals and groups advocating
privatization are the same ones that originally opposed Social
Security, civil rights legislation, and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's evident that many ... of the people arguing for
privatization are the same people who have been arguing against
protections for racial minorities,'' Bond said. ``We naturally view
them with suspicion and are not surprised when our suspicions are
borne out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yzaguirre said La Raza has not taken a position on the issue of
privatization, but is concerned that the Heritage study may have
overestimated the ability of the Hispanic community _ which is the
lowest-paid and least-educated minority group _ to benefit from
individually managed investments.
</P>
<P>
   Heritage officials defended their study, issued last January,
which suggested that because blacks have a shorter life expectancy
than whites, they pay proportionately higher Social Security taxes
and receive fewer benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Although it noted that Hispanics receive a higher rate of return
than whites, it argued that because Hispanics are relatively
younger than the rest of the population, they would bear a higher
taxation rate in the future to keep Social Security solvent.
</P>
<P>
   William Beach, director of the Heritage Foundation's Center for
Data Analysis and co-author of the study, said he was ``personally
offended'' by Bond's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I marched in the civil rights movement behind Julian Bond. I
marched against the Vietnam War right behind Julian Bond,'' Beach
said, adding that he and other Heritage officials had ``a lot of
support for what he did in his youth. I'm outraged by his comments,
but that's politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond and Yzaguirre spoke at a news conference hosted by the
Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a liberal research center
that issued a detailed report criticizing the methodology and
conclusions in the Heritage study.
</P>
<P>
   Kilolo Kijakazi, (CQ) who wrote the Center's report, argued that
the Heritage study was seriously flawed because it overestimated
the payroll taxes paid by blacks and underestimated their benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing from an earlier analysis by the Office of the Social
Security Actuary, Kijakazi said the Heritage study assumed that a
20-year-old black male would pay retirement taxes for 45 years,
while the Social Security administration assumed he would pay an
average of 39.1 years. Meanwhile, Heritage assumed that upon
retiring he would live to receive benefits for 2.2 years compared
to the 8.1 years predicted by the Social Security administration.
</P>
<P>
   Kijakazi also argued that the Heritage study did not account for
the cost of covering current retirees _ whose benefits are paid by
current workers _ while switching to a system in which today's
workers invest for their own future retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The Heritage study also omitted the administrative costs of
managing individual retirement accounts, she said, noting a study
by Henry Aaron of the Brookings Institution which concluded that up
to 20 percent of personal investments would be lost in
administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real winners would be the investment firms that stand to
gain billions'' of dollars from private investments, Kijakazi said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Beach said after the news conference that his plan would promote
wealth within the black and Hispanic communities, which are now
prevented from accumulating wealth because of the high rate of
payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The center's report is the latest is a flurry of position papers
in which advocates and critics of privatizing the nation's
retirement system have predicted its effect on the working poor,
who are disproportionately black and Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Cato Institute _ a libertarian research center
that has been leading the effort to shift from Social Security to
personal retirement accounts _ issued a report declaring the poor
could build greater savings and enjoy larger retirement benefits
through individual investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week, the American Association of Retired Persons'
Public Policy Institute issued a report criticizing the Heritage
report for ignoring the risks and administrative cost of private
investment accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how low-income workers _ primarily minorities _
would fare under a privatized system versus the current system is
one of the fundamental issues facing policy makers and lawmakers
who are attempting to reform the program now in order to avert a
major disruption in retirement security three decades from now.
</P>
<P>
   The latest prediction by the Social Security trustees is that if
no changes are made, the system would be unable to fully pay
benefits by 2032 as the ranks of retirees, swelled by the Baby Boom
generation, virtually doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is a general consensus that the rich would do
better under a system of private personal accounts, there is
widespread disagreement over whether the poor would fare likewise.
</P>
<P>
   In his State of the Union address last January, President
Clinton called for a year-long study of the Social Security program
to be capped this December by a White House conference that would
lead to legislative recommendations for Congress. However, with the
president embroiled in possible impeachment proceedings, lawmakers
of both parties have questioned whether that schedule will be met.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development Monday, Sen. Rod Grams, R-Minn.,
announced he would introduce a bill this week to allow workers to
shift 10 percent of their 12.4 percent payroll tax _ including the
amount contributed by employers _ to a private retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   Several other bills have been introduced that would shift a
portion of the payroll tax to private accounts. None are scheduled
to be considered before Congress adjourns this month.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
