<HEADER>
A0195 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTOR-HOMES-1STLD-WRI     10-05 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOR-HOMES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULKING MOTOR HOMES RAISE SAFETY CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Updates with hometown of Anderson, locator on Northway Travel
Trailers.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAY JOCHNOWITZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ William and Mary Alice Peak sank their life
savings into a $100,000 motor home with a dream of spending summers
at their lakeside camp in New York state, and winters driving
across the South.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Peaks, that dream became a white-knuckle nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Their motor home was an overweight behemoth, so overloaded that
its tires blew, its brakes burned, and its transmission smoked.
Fearful of losing control of the nearly 10-ton coach, Peak took the
overdrive switch off the dashboard and moved it to the steering
column so that he could keep both hands on the wheel as much as
possible. Mary Alice would follow in the car with their luggage to
keep the weight in the RV down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our second home,'' said Peak, 68, who says he doesn't
drive the vehicle anymore and can't sell it. ``There's no one in
the world that would buy it. I certainly wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   As snowbirds head south for the winter, America's highways are
loaded with these overweight _ and largely unregulated _ houses on
wheels. Some could be dangerous: too heavy for the chassis, axles
and tires on which they are riding, making them hard to steer and
prone to blowouts and mechanical failures, according to a report by
John Anderson, a disgruntled RV owner who has made a business of
traveling the country weighing RVs and holding seminars on weight
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, who lives near Greeneville, Tenn., weighed more than
6,000 RVs from 1993 to 1997, and found that 64 percent were over
their weight limits. Among the large motor homes, 69 percent were
overweight. Why? In some cases, manufacturers overload the vehicles
with options, in others, it's the fault of buyers who add their own
belongings, from rock collections to pianos.
</P>
<P>
   While fatalities in RV accidents are low _ 216 people died in RV
crashes in 1997, according to the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration _ the leading cause of crashes appears to be drivers
losing control of the vehicle, according to Dana Hogan, a spokesman
for State Farm Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   No special license is needed to operate most motor homes because
they fall under the 26,000-pound limit for a commercial driver's
license.
</P>
<P>
   Industry representatives don't dispute Anderson's figures nor
disagree that there is a weight problem, but they blame consumers
for overloading the vehicles with options and personal items. The
average couple, Anderson said, takes a ton of personal belongings
on board, while people using their RVs full-time store an average
3,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can overload a car, you can overload a pickup,'' said Phil
Ingrassia, a spokesman for the Recreational Vehicle Rental
Association, a trade group for firms that rent RVs.
</P>
<P>
   But experts also point to some manufacturers, who are feeding
consumers' insatiable appetite for fancy options. The trend with
motor homes is big and bigger, noted Jerry Mittman, sales manager
for RV and special vehicles for Ford Motor Corp. in Detroit. The
standard motor home width has gone from 96 inches to 102 inches,
and in recent years, more motor homes are featuring ``slideouts'' _
compartments that extend the floor space to as much as 12 feet that
can also add a half-ton to the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   And consumers are demanding more amenities, like hardwood
cabinets, stone countertops and ceramic floor tiles. The
manufacturers are installing these accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson got into the weight issue after he had problems with
his own 5th-wheeler _ an RV pulled by a pickup truck _ which had a
weight limit of 14,000 pounds. After 11 tire failures and $10,000
in improvements, he weighed it and found it was built 840 pounds
over weight.
</P>
<P>
   In Peak's case, the 37-foot Newmar Kountry Aire he bought from
Northway Travel Trailers in 1991 was just 50 pounds below its
weight limit with full water and propane tanks and a nearly full
tank of gas, according to an engineer's report commissioned by
Peak. That was before the driver even got in.
</P>
<P>
   Peak first took his complaint to an arbitrator, who in 1993
ruled that the manufacturer, the Newmar Corp., wasn't to blame. The
arbitrator, Paul Macey, said it was Peak's fault for choosing the
options that he did. But Peak said all he did was choose items from
the Newmar's standard list _ extras like the slideout and oak
cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   In December, a New York Supreme Court jury agreed with Peak that
the vehicle was unusable. A trial is set for November to decide
actual damages, though the RV itself caught fire while parked in
Peak's driveway last month.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Parker, owner of Northway Travel Trailers in the Albany
suburb of Clifton Park, declined to comment on the case. He bought
the business after Peak made his purchase there. Attorney David
Pentkowski, representing the corporation that owned the business
when Peak bought his vehicle, did not return calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Newmar, the manufacturer, won't discuss Peak's case, but will
say it disagrees with the weight Peak and a Connecticut testing
firm claimed on the vehicle. In a 1994 letter to the state attorney
general, the firm also asserted that even though the vehicle is
officially rated for 19,500 pounds, the limit is understated and
the RV could carry 20,000 to 23,000 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   There is so far no federal move to regulate the industry. Tim
Hurd, a spokesman for the federal safety agency, said there is no
clear evidence that RVs are defective on a wide scale, and the
government for now is leaving it to the industry to police itself.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has responded somewhat: the Recreational Vehicle
Industry Association, a trade group, came out in September 1996
with a recommendation that manufacturers post a more detailed
weight label on each vehicle. Adopted by most major RV
manufacturers, according to RVIA spokesman Alan Piercy, the label
shows the vehicle's net carrying capacity, how much water it can
carry and what it would weigh with the water tank full.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's weighing program suggests there has been a change,
too: While 78 percent of the 1993 models he weighed were
overweight, the figure dropped to 56 percent in 1997. Anderson
isn't sure of the cause, but he does credit the industry with
trying to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of models that pre-date the industry's 1996
labeling program _ an unknown number of overweight RVs that will
likely be on the road for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor, which builds chassis and sells them to RV
manufacturers, said the RV builders are becoming more careful about
using strong enough chassis to support the increased weight of the
vehicles. Ford now requires motor home manufacturers to undergo a
special training program before modifying the company's chassis,
and this year came out with a new line of stronger products.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Mittman said, some manufacturers tended to hold
their costs down by buying lighter, less expensive chassis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The manufacturers have probably gotten more honest in terms of
buying the right chassis,'' he said. ``The customer should feel a
lot safer than they did four to five years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
