<HEADER>
A0209 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSITIVE-TV-LIFEBEAT-     10-05 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSITIVE-TV-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 TURN TV INTO A POSITIVE INFLUENCE  (This ``separate buy'' article
is from this week's LifeBeat lifestyle package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to LifeBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing articles with color art.) 
 By KATHY SENA 
 c.1998 KATHY SENA
 From ParentSource magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've all seen the studies on the number of murders a child will
see on television before he turns 18. We've heard how today's kids
are out of shape because they spend too much time on the couch. And
_ most telling _ we've seen the effects of too much television
ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   One mom calls it ``the zombie stare'' _ the look that comes over
her 7-year-old when he watches Saturday-morning cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   But we know, too, that TV, just like chocolate (thank heavens!),
isn't all bad. As with most things, moderation is the key. In fact,
if we use it wisely, television can open up exciting new worlds for
our kids.
</P>
<P>
   How? Marguerite Kelly, mother of four grown children and
coauthor of ``The Mother's Almanac'' (Doubleday, 1975), has some
helpful words on this subject that concerns many parents.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We hear so much about how TV is bad for kids. What's the best
thing about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Television can inspire. It can make a kid curious. It can
also be a great bonding time for parents and kids. But parents have
to make sure that happens. Watch with your kids. In a subtle way,
you can use a show as a springboard for family discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much TV should children watch?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think five to seven hours per week is plenty for kids under
7. For older kids, eight to 10 hours seems about right. Have your
kids look through the television schedule and mark their shows for
the week. It certainly helps build their negotiation skills!
</P>
<P>
   Q: How important is it for parents to set a good example when it
comes to TV viewing?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's very important. Kids pay much more attention to what we
do than to what we say. Make sure your kids see you doing lots of
enjoyable things other than watching TV _ reading books, enjoying
hobbies, even just getting out of the house for a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My child is afraid of some of the things on the 6 o'clock
news. Frankly, so am I! How do I handle this?
</P>
<P>
   A: More and more parents are not allowing their 6-, 7- and
8-year-olds to watch television news, and I think that's wise. The
murder rate in this country is way down, but you wouldn't know it
from watching the news. If you feel your kids are mature enough,
watch it with them and emphasize that murders, etc. are shown
because they're unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the ``arsenic hour'' o when everyone is tired and
cranky and parents are trying to get dinner on the table?
</P>
<P>
   A: Beware of prime-time shows that are shown during the dinner
hour as reruns. For example, ``Seinfeld'' is a terrific show, but
obviously it's not appropriate for young children. The problem is,
it appears all over the country now in dinner-hour reruns. As
always, you have to monitor what your kids are watching.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, borrow videos from the library _ ``Willy
Wonka and the Chocolate Factory,'' ``Harriet the Spy,'' ``Beauty
and the Beast'' _ and watch one for 20 or 30 minutes each night.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can we make our kids more critical viewers?
</P>
<P>
   A: Laugh at TV! Make fun of it. Make your child feel like he's
in on the joke when you explain how dumb some shows are. Parents
don't realize how much influence they have with their children.
Make your child feel accepted on your intellectual level when
you're discussing the merits of a show. Ask her opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's your strongest piece of advice to parents?
</P>
<P>
   A: Never have a television in a child's bedroom. This tears the
fabric of the family, because it puts parents and children on a
different track. And it separates the family. Everyone goes into
their cells after feeding hour!
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's a good way to turn TV viewing into an ongoing family
experience?
</P>
<P>
   A: Have a weekly ``Family Hang-Out Night.'' Parents can
designate one night each week when the family sits down to watch a
show that everyone's agreed on. Watch the same show each week. Make
popcorn or a snack the kids can prepare on their own or with your
help. Don't answer the phone. Afterwards, families can read
together or play a game or take a walk. Everyone will look forward
to the ritual and the shared time together.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the best way to judge a TV show?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the characters on the show came to your front door, would
you let them in? If not, change the channel!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (KATHY SENA is a Los Angeles-based freelance writer and the
mother of a 2-year-old son.)
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIDEBAR: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   THE RATINGS:
</P>
<P>
   Confused about the ``Educational/Informational'' rating on kids'
TV shows? You're not alone. Here are a few tips to help make sense
of it all.
</P>
<P>
   You've probably noticed a small ``E/I'' symbol in your TV
listing and at the beginning of some of your kids' favorite shows.
According to the FCC, network broadcasters must now provide _ and
use this symbol to identify _ at least three hours per week of
programming that ``educates and informs'' children under age 16.
Cable services are not included.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC's move is good news, says Alice Cahn, director of
children's programming for PBS. But parents still need to be
watchful, she adds. ``It's like when my nephew comes to my house
and I ask him to wash his hands before dinner and he comes to the
table with only the ``front'' of his hands washed. Then he says
'But I only use the front of my hands when I eat!'''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to broadcasters' compliance with the FCC's ruling,
``There's the spirit of the law and then there's the letter of the
law,'' says Cahn. ``We need to hold all broadcasters to a higher
standard of product safety, just as we would for toy safety or
anything else that affects our children's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   So looking for the E/I symbol is a good beginning. But don't
stop there. Here are some other suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Use the E/I symbol as a starting point in helping your child
choose appropriate shows. ``Then check out the show for yourself,''
says Cahn. ``Say to yourself, 'Here's my library of shows. Now I'm
going to pick three.'''
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for shows that make learning fun. ``Every good teacher
you ever had proved that good education is entertaining,'' says
Cahn. ``The same holds true for TV It shouldn't have to be boring
to be informative.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Use TV as a springboard. ``After a kid watches a show on PBS,
for example, he should have a great idea for an activity to do.
That's what TV should offer kids. They should want to turn off the
TV and go *do* something!'' _ Kathy Sena
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
