<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Oct. 11)  
(JT) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Las Vegas Headliners: Monet and Van Gogh &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In most Las Vegas casinos, the only truly valuable artwork is a
royal flush. But on Thursday the 3,000-room Bellagio hotel and
casino will open with, among other attractions, a fine-arts gallery
containing original works by Monet, Van Gogh, Renoir, Cezanne and
Gauguin.
</P>
<P>
   The resort, built by the owners of the nearby Mirage and named
after the village on Lake Como, has its own 10-acre lake with more
than 1,000 fountains whose jets will dance to Copland, Sondheim and
Italian folk songs. A botanical garden will contain seasonal
displays, and along the edge of the lake will be a re-creation of a
Tuscan village with red-tile roofs.
</P>
<P>
   It might be enough to make you think you were in the lake
country _ except for the 36-story tower that contains Bellagio's
guest rooms. Most rooms will have European-style furnishings, and
baths with Italian marble and separate tub and shower. Most notable
among the restaurants will be Le Cirque, a branch of Le Cirque
2000, and Circo, both run by the Maccioni family, serving French
and northern Italian cuisine respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve restaurants offer a range of specialties from seafood to
Asian cuisine. This being Las Vegas, there will be a buffet, too.
The headline show is a Cirque du Soleil performance called ``O,''
with swimmers, divers and acrobats.
</P>
<P>
   The casino, with its canopies and wrought-iron trim, is meant to
evoke the patio of a villa overlooking a lake (the one with the
lounge singers and hundreds of slot machines).
</P>
<P>
   Bellagio is at 3600 Las Vegas Blvd. S., across Flamingo Road and
two millenniums from Caesars Palace. Rates will range from $159 to
$499 a night, although they may be lower or higher depending on
demand. Call (888) 987-6667, fax (702) 693-8546. On the Web, it's
www.bellagiolasvegas.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Philadelphia Packages For Delacroix Show &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Several Philadelphia hotels are offering packages that include
passes to the exhibit ``Delacroix: The Late Work'' at the
Philadelphia Museum of Art. The show, which runs through Jan. 3,
includes about 70 paintings and 40 works on paper produced by
Eugene Delacroix in the 15 years before his death in 1863.
</P>
<P>
   Although the tickets to the exhibit specify a time for entry,
the passes that are part of the hotel packages may be used anytime.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel packages include accommodations for two, breakfast,
parking, passes for the downtown shuttle bus that travels to
popular tourist sites and tickets to the Delacroix exhibit.
Participating hotels are Best Western Center City, $129, (215)
568-8300; Crowne Plaza, $237 Monday through Thursday and $207
Friday through Sunday, (215) 561-7500; Embassy Suites Center City,
$239 until Nov. 21 and then $199 through Jan. 3, (215) 561-1776;
