<SLUG> BC-BY-DESIGN-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TOTE BAGS, A SLIM FIT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To complement this fall's easy, unstructured
clothing, tote bags should be sleek and slim. With flat heels all
the rage, there is no need to carry extra shoes; there should be
room just for papers and reading material _ that's the ideal,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   A new collection of bags by Lambertson/Truex is setting the
style for the modern skinny tote. Its collection at Bergdorf
Goodman is in black leather or calf hair and in leopard-patterned
calf hair ($400 to $465). Bergdorf's also has Fendi's nylon jersey
tote ($350).
</P>
<P>
   Barneys New York has flat totes in black or brown leather by
Dries Van Noten ($525 and $550) and in its private label collection
($295). In Henri Bendel's own collection there is a
crocodile-embossed leather tote ($248). The store also has a
leather tote by Furla ($328) and microfiber bags by Isabelle Fiore
($178) and Kazuyo Nakano ($228).
</P>
<P>
   Dolce &AMP; Gabbana's flat leather totes in two sizes ($455 and
$510) are at Neiman Marcus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0266 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-CASABLANCA-$ADV     10-05 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-CASABLANCA-$ADV07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOOK IS PREQUEL AND SEQUEL TO CASABLANCA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (e) entertainment categories for
release Wednesday, Oct. 7.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``The Lisbon plane soared away from the dense,
swirling fog of Casablanca, up and into the night. ...''
</P>
<P>
   And so begins what author Michael Walsh jokingly calls his
``literary suicide mission'' _ a novel that surrounds the events of
the1942 classic film, ``Casablanca.''
</P>
<P>
   The book entitled ``As Times Goes By'' (Warner Books, $25) is
both a sequel and a prequel to the film _ telling the story of what
happened both after and before the fateful three days when Rick and
Ilsa are so dramatically reunited and so sadly parted on the edge
of World War II. It will be published Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, who was music critic for Time Magazine from 1981 through
1997, knows he now faces tough critics among the millions of movie
buffs who know by heart the film starring Humphrey Bogart and
Ingrid Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows `Casablanca.' Everybody loves `Casablanca,'''
said Walsh. So withering comparative reviews ``are a chance you
take when you get involved in a project like this. I expect my
former colleagues to be fair and accurate. You obviously take a
chance with a shared cultural myth like this. I hope the book
speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, who teaches journalism at Boston University, was
recruited to write the novel by Maureen Egen, the president of
Warner Books, which owns the rights to the film characters and to
any subsequent film to be made from ``As Time Goes By.'' Walsh said
Egen saw something in his earlier novel, ``Exchange Alley,'' that
``made her think I could do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his book is destined to be a movie that will
inspire even more comparisons, the author said ``that's not my
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much harder row to hoe to make a movie 55 years later''
with the original characters still so set in the audience's mind,
said Walsh, 49, in a telephone interview. ``I had the easier job.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the lingering intrigue of ``Casablanca'' involves the
film's unanswered questions: What are the ties between Rick, the
tough saloon keeper, and Sam, his enigmatic piano player? Does Ilsa
love Victor Laszlo, her husband and a Czech patriot dedicated to
freeing his homeland from Nazi occupation? And, of course, do Rick
and Ilsa ever see each other again after the plane disappears into
the foggy night, leaving Rick on the runway in Casablanca?
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Walsh has decided that Rick is a wanted, former
gangster from East Harlem whose real name is Yitzik Baline. The
East Harlem background explains why Sam, his best friend, is a
black man and the gangster past suggests why Rick can't return to
New York. Bogart played a lot of gangsters in other movies, of
course.
</P>
<P>
   And Laszlo's mission must be the assassination of Nazi Reinhard
Hydrich in Prague, the most significant act of the Czech resistance
during World War II. And who better than a streetwise gangster to
help plan a major ``hit?'' So naturally all the film's major
characters must be reunited in this dramatic conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   After being approached to write the book, Walsh said his initial
reaction was: ``What do I have to bring to the party?''
</P>
<P>
   He began to spin out ideas from the period and setting _ World
War II, Europe, New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have an `Oh-my-God' reaction. I had a `Can I do
this?' reaction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never a `Casablanca' cultist,'' he said. So he rented
the movie and decided there was enough material pointing in both
directions to do the book.
</P>
<P>
   Having the main characters already established made the writing
harder, he said. ``When you invent your own characters, ... you
have an initial rapport whith them. Taking other characters,
especially from a movie where their physical appearace was
determined by actors rather than imagined by the author, was a real
challenge. You're not only taking Rick and Ilsa but also Bogart and
Bergman and incorporating them into characters on the page.''
</P>
<P>
   The screenplay for ``Casablanca'' was a collaborative effort of
seven writers and was based on a 1940 play entitled ``Everybody
Comes to Rick's.'' Walsh resurrected one character, an American
named Lois Meridith, who was in the play but not the movie.
</P>
<P>
   However, the book is clearly evocative of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said he hopes ``Casablanca'' fans ``will feel that I have
honored the integrity of the movie, taken care of the characters
while they were in my possession'' and that reading the book makes
them want to watch the movie yet again.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
