<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0284 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIAN-MISS-AMERIC     10-05 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-MISS-AMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISS AMERICA: IT HELPS TO BE AN EVANGELICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York Times
Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative CONNIE
WHITE in Kansas City at (800) 444-0267 or (816) 822-8448, or fax
her at (816) 822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By DIANA BUTLER BASS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    A couple Saturdays ago, my husband and I played a board game
with the television on in the background. As it happened, the Miss
America pageant aired that night. Usually, I don't watch the show
-- placing beauty pageants on a scale somewhere between inane and
degrading.
 &HT;    This year, however, I got hooked. The event opened with the
young women introducing themselves along with their states and
colleges -- a surprising number saying they attended Christian
colleges or Bible schools.
 &HT;    For most of the audience, the names of these rather obscure
institutions probably passed unnoticed. But as Miss Virginia,
Nicole Johnson, proudly proclaimed her affiliation with Regent
University -- television evangelist Pat Robertson's graduate school
-- I confidently predicted, ``She's going to win.''
 &HT;    Two hours later, she was crowned Miss America.
 &HT;    The following Monday, Robertson and his co-host, Terry Meeuwsen,
a former Miss America herself, exulted in Johnson's victory. ``Hey,
you know, Terry,'' commented Pat, ``you see so many Miss Americas
who are Christians and many times, spirit-filled Christians ...
It's almost like an unfair advantage, you think?''
 &HT;    Although I doubt there's a religious test for becoming Miss
America, there is no doubt Robertson's observation was correct.
Over the pageant's history -- and especially in recent years --
Miss America often has been a conservative Christian.
 &HT;    On one level, the trend toward evangelical Miss Americas is not
surprising. After all, beauty pageants -- even those conducted
under the pretense of scholarship -- have fallen into disrepute
with many feminist and post-feminist young women. Besides being a
relic of an age where women were valued for looks rather than
achievement, beauty pageants have turned into a multi-million
dollar industry churning out contestants like assembly line
products.
 &HT;    Who would want to submit herself to years of beauty pageants?
 &HT;    For women who aspire to modelling or other media the answer is
obvious: pageants provide training. But Christian women? The answer
is equally obvious. Of all American women, conservative Christians
are least influenced by feminism and most reluctant to embrace
feminist criticism of traditional femininity -- including critiques
of beauty pageants.
 &HT;    As a result, women from prestige colleges and universities --
where feminist or post-feminist cultures have greater sway -- are
less likely to enter pageants. Women from Christian colleges and
conservative churches -- where feminism is often viewed as inimical
to faith -- seem more likely to enter a pageant, thus forming a
self-selected Christian pool of candidates.
 &HT;    Although evangelicals might attribute Miss America's success to
God, a more mundane dynamic is evident: young Christian women, with
their pre-feminist traditionalism, probably constitute the largest
group (other than models) of beauty contestants. It's no miracle.
It's numbers.
 &HT;    On a different level, however, an evangelical Miss America
should be surprising. After all, conservative Christians believe in
a Bible whose admonitions seem critical of beauty pageants -- such
as ``women should dress themselves modestly and decently in
suitable clothing, not with their hair braided, or with gold,
pearls, or expensive clothes, but with good works, as is proper for
women who profess reverence for God.''
 &HT;    The New Testament praises women (and men, too) for their
internal condition -- ``clothe yourselves with compassion,
kindness, humility, meekness and patience'' -- condemning showy
appearance. The Bible teaches beauty flows from the heart and is
not readily visible to the world.
 &HT;    For generations, conservative Christians took this seriously --
and literally. In evangelical churches, women dressed modestly,
wore little or no make-up, and arranged hair with a minimum of
fuss. Simple dress expressed biblical faithfulness.
 &HT;    If not exactly the devil's work, beauty pageants were worldly.
No good Christian girl would ever display her body -- especially in
a swimsuit -- to be judged. Good works were her attire; God her
judge.
 &HT;    Strangely enough, this view of femininity backs up into feminist
theory. Both Christian tradition and feminism argue that a woman's
value is not determined by her appearance. Rather, a woman's
internal disposition -- intelligence, compassion and values -- and
external accomplishments -- service, charity and achievement --
demonstrate her worth. Looks do not matter; full personhood does.
 &HT;    When feminism, however, came to the same conclusion as biblical
teaching regarding women's worth, conservative Christians rejected
their own message. Instead of maintaining a biblical view of
appearance, one oddly coherent with contemporary feminism, they
embraced America's beauty culture. No longer protesting pageants as
worldly, they paraded down Atlantic City's runway -- praising
Christian girls who won earthly crowns instead of striving for
heavenly ones.
 &HT;    Sorry, Pat and Terry. Nicole Johnson's victory is neither a
miracle nor a victory for Christian values. Claiming Miss America
as your own only proves how far from your own Bible you've strayed
-- and how worldly in your quest for power and prestige you've
become.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Diana Butler Bass
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Diana Butler Bass, Ph.D., writes a religion column for the
Santa Barbara News-Press and is associate professor of religious
studies at Rhodes College in Memphis, Tenn. Her latest book is
``Standing Against the Whirlwind: Evangelical Episcopalians in 19th
Century America,'' published by Oxford University Press.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
