<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-TWINS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREAT OF CANCER DOESN'T SHAKE THE BOND BETWEEN 2-YEAR-OLD TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLEASANT VALLEY, Mo. _ Kaitlin has the doll. Kelsey wants the
doll.
</P>
<P>
   They fight. That's what 2-year-olds do.
</P>
<P>
   But along comes a bully _ leukemia. That's when these twin
sisters grasp hands and hold on tight.
</P>
<P>
   Kaitlin is the one with the disease. Kelsey has stuck by her
side for a year of treatment, and anybody who tries to break up
this alliance is looking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Kaitlin screams a fit if she has to see the doctor or go to the
hospital without her sister. Kelsey doesn't even ask; she just
jumps in the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick,'' Kaitlin says from under a floppy hat that covers
her bald head.
</P>
<P>
   Kelsey nods and puts her arm around her sister. ``She's sick.''
</P>
<P>
   It's crazy to think the girls know what's going on, say their
parents, Elizabeth and Dale Mundell of Pleasant Valley.
</P>
<P>
   They are toddlers _ the target demographic of Rugrats and
Barney. But Kaitlin and Kelsey seem to be fighting for a life's
worth of fun and memories due them as twin sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow...they know that something is wrong and they need to
stick together,'' Elizabeth Mundell said.
</P>
<P>
   The family learned recently that a bone marrow transplant from a
donor in the Netherlands had fallen through. A transplant from a
donor's umbilical cord could give Kaitlin a longer survival time,
but finding a match has been difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The twins are not identical; Kelsey is not a match.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the treatments and the search for a donor continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kaitlin is fine with all this as long as Kelsey is with her,''
Elizabeth Mundell said. ``And Kelsey doesn't seem to mind spending
long days at the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Kaitlin gets weekly chemotherapy at Children's Mercy
Hospital in Kansas City, Kelsey watches from the corner. Sometimes,
Kelsey squeezes past a nurse to give Kaitlin a toy. She takes her
sister juice.
</P>
<P>
   The Mundells were puzzled at first by such camaraderie from
children too young to say the word or know its meaning. But now the
parents cherish the bond and the comfort it brings both girls.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a crazy notion, said Jerry Wyckoff, a child
psychologist. He doesn't know the Mundell family but says twins can
be so close that they pick up on each other's emotions, including
stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``These sisters are getting comfort from each other,'' Wyckoff
said. ``This may not be provable, and these girls certainly can't
articulate it, but something is going on here, and things like that
can occur with twins.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Mundell learned early not to get in the way. He once left
Kelsey at home when he drove Kaitlin to Children's Mercy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we crossed the river, Kaitlin knew where we were headed,
and she threw such a screaming fit I nearly went back home and got
Kelsey.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only time Kelsey hasn't been with her sister was a
night in July when doctors thought Kaitlin would die of a staph
infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see my sissy,'' Kelsey told her mother as family
gathered at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Mundell didn't know whether that was a good idea.
Doctors had pumped so much fluid into Kaitlin to fight the
infection that she was nearly unrecognizable because of swelling.
</P>
<P>
   But her mother took Kelsey into the room in the intensive care
unit. Kaitlin lay still in a drug-induced coma.
</P>
<P>
   Kelsey looked down at her awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my sissy?'' she finally asked her mother.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, Elizabeth Mundell sat in her living room
and talked of her family's troubles. She noticed Kelsey standing
within a nose of the television screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelsey!'' she demanded quickly. ``Back away from the TV _
now!''
</P>
<P>
   Cancer, she explained. Radiation from television screens has
been suspected of causing cancer in children.
</P>
<P>
   Leukemia invaded the Mundell family about a year ago, when
Kaitlin kept falling down at a wedding. And she dragged a leg as
she walked.
</P>
<P>
   The early diagnosis was an inner-ear infection. When medication
failed to help, another doctor examined Kaitlin.
</P>
<P>
   By this time her eyes were bulging from their sockets.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor suspected cancerous tumors behind the eyes. The
family soon made a trip to Children's Mercy, where a doctor ordered
X-rays to confirm the tumors.
</P>
<P>
   No tumors were found. But other tests indicated abnormal blood
counts.
</P>
<P>
   Kaitlin had acute lymphocytic leukemia, a doctor told her
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The news threw the Mundell household into a tailspin. Elizabeth
Mundell had just opened her own insurance business. Her husband ran
a car-repair business.
</P>
<P>
   The Mundells have four other children from previous marriages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I quit and became a regular Mr. Mom,'' Dale Mundell said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaitlin soon began chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Acute lymphocytic leukemia is the most common of childhood
cancers. Cancerous blood cells accumulate in the bone marrow and
spread to the liver, the spleen, the kidneys and the central
nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   Prognosis is typically good. Ninety-eight percent of children
with the disease attain remission in four to six weeks of
treatment, and 80 percent are cured.
</P>
<P>
   But chemotherapy did not put Kaitlin into remission. The failure
put her into the ``high-risk category.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors decided to pursue a bone marrow transplant. Trips to
Children's Mercy for chemotherapy became more frequent.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital staff grew to know Kelsey as well as they knew Kaitlin.
Visits to the hospital can last up to six hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming here has pretty much become their life,'' Dale Mundell
said. ``And the people who work here are almost family now.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day the girls wheeled in aboard a double stroller
pushed by their father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Kelsey. Hi, Kaitlin,'' a nurse greeted them. ``You girls
look so pretty today.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``sticker lady,'' a volunteer who hands out stickers, also
called them by name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelsey didn't like me at first,'' said Abbas Emami, Kaitlin's
doctor. ``She does now, but I think at first she thought I was the
reason her sister was sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Each hospital visit begins when a nurse weighs and measures
Kaitlin.
</P>
<P>
   Kelsey steps up next, and the nurse gladly does the same for
her.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the sisters are on the floor, playing with blocks and
flipping through books.
</P>
<P>
   As they waited for the chemotherapy, Dale Mundell said that
Kaitlin and Kelsey would still have to make regular trips to the
hospital even if a bone marrow transplant brought Kaitlin into
remission.
</P>
<P>
   A stranger overhearing the conversation might have thought both
girls had the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Kaitlin and Kelsey would probably agree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
