<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYERS LEARN IMPORTANCE TO RELIGIOUS HOLIDAYS, PRACTICES TO
STAFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: On Sunday and Monday, members of the Jewish faith
celebrate Rosh Hashanah; on the 29th and 30th they observe Yom
Kippur. Some may be absent from the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   Christians are accustomed to having their important religious
days recognized as secular American holidays. Time off is usually a
matter of routine. But members of other faiths often have to do a
lot of explaining to their bosses. Sometimes, they have to use
personal or vacation days.
</P>
<P>
   As America's workforce grows increasingly diverse, employers are
learning why it's wise to understand different religious holidays
and practices _ and not penalize workers for observing them.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, discrimination on the basis of religion is a
violation of Title VII of the Civil Rights Act. For another, it
makes good business sense in a tight labor market to retain good
workers who might leave if meshing their work and religious lives
becomes difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the Council on Islamic-American Relations, for
example, has gone to bat for several Muslim workers around the
country. Some were women whose bosses saw their hijabs, the
traditional head scarves, and sputtered things like, ``Unless you
take that stupid thing off, you have to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   After the council's intervention (and much corporate
telephoning), the employers allowed the workers to stay and wear
their hijabs, although at least one restaurant company decreed the
scarf must be in the company's colors.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter whether workers are Jewish, Muslim,
Seventh-Day Adventist or an adherent of any other faith. All must
be able to apply for and keep their jobs without fear of career
reprisals because of religious observation. Smart employers know
that diverse employees forge a stronger link to their increasingly
diverse customer base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0253 </DOCNO>
