r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      10-05 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKA PROVES TO BE A GOLD MINE EVEN AT THE TIME OF DEPARTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANCHORAGE, Alaska _ Probably they were fine people, those folks
just arriving with their rod cases, their duffels and their noisy
enthusiasm. Under other circumstances we might even have liked
them.
</P>
<P>
   But in a few minutes they would be climbing aboard the
floatplanes for their flight out to the lodge. Their pleasure still
was ahead, while ours was finished.
</P>
<P>
   So we eyed them sidelong, with furtive envy.
</P>
<P>
   The taxi came and we made our goodbyes, then wedged ourselves in
with our gear and two huge Styrofoam cartons of frozen salmon
fillets.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll still be like a rock when you get home tomorrow,''
Duke Bertke said, and sent us off with a wave.
</P>
<P>
   It was just before noon, and ours was a late evening flight. We
had nearly eight hours to kill.
</P>
<P>
   First we stopped past the airport to drop off our luggage and
our fish. The Anchorage air terminal must be one of very few in the
United States whose amenities for travelers include a walk-in
freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Then another cab delivered us downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Often, at the end of something good, there's only anticlimax and
impatience to be away. But this day was different.
</P>
<P>
   The far northern summer may be short, but the long daylight and
abundant rains produce not only radishes the size of turnips,
5-pound tomatoes and cabbages bigger than bushels. There's also an
exuberance of blooming. At every hand was the riot of flowers for
which Alaska is famous.
</P>
<P>
   And even on a Sunday, Anchorage was a lively place.
</P>
<P>
   We followed the twang of a country song to a big tent on a
pretty square. The music was by a couple in their 70s who'd driven
up from Texas in a camper to visit their Air Force son and his
family, then decided to stay and play a while.
</P>
<P>
   The affair under the tent was a benefit for the Foster
Grandparents program _ a salmon bake, what else? And that accounted
for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly the whole afternoon we spent at the handsome Anchorage
Museum of History and Art, whose extensive collection would put to
shame civic museums in many far larger places. Works by travelers,
adventurers and native artists bring alive the Alaskan experience
from the days of early exploration to the present.
</P>
<P>
   There was just time then for supper, in a nice little cafe that
doubled as a book shop, before heading back to the airport to claim
our bags from storage and our fish from the freezer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid we're overbooked on this flight,'' said the woman
at the airline counter. ``So we're asking for volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the offer?'' asked my daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two round-trip tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To anywhere?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere in the continental U.S. If you're interested, tell
the agent at the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   So we walked back to the gate area, where the real poker game
began.
</P>
<P>
   ``When's the next flight?'' my daughter asked the gate agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hours,'' he told her. ``It makes a stop in Portland.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four of us. We might be interested.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a free round-trip ticket,'' said the agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lady out front said two tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All right. Two tickets then.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere in the U.S., right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not Alaska,'' said the agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told us it was anywhere in the continental U.S., and
Alaska's on the continent. In that case...''
</P>
<P>
   My daughter should have been a professional gambler.
</P>
<P>
   The agent looked down at his passenger list, then out at the
gate area crowded with more people than would fit on the plane.
Four of us together wouldn't solve his problem, but we would be a
good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right,'' he said, in a weak voice. ``We'll throw in
Alaska.''
</P>
<P>
   So as I write these notes we are sitting here in the Anchorage
airport with eight round-trip tickets among us, waiting for a plane
that will deliver us home only a couple of hours later than the
flight we were supposed to be on.
</P>
<P>
   And it's perfectly understood, without anyone even having to say
it, that we'll be using some of those gift tickets to come back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
