<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-INSURANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIFF DWELLERS BATTLE INSURANCE COMPANIES OVER LOSS OF HOMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PACIFICA, Calif. _ Nine families on Esplanade Drive thought they
had bought themselves secure serenity. They enjoyed a panoramic
view of the Pacific Ocean and the sea song of waves crashing
against the cliff below their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, they say, the federal government had insured them
against loss if the relentless ocean wore away the cliff and
toppled their houses. After all, the Federal Insurance
Administration's brochure said their policies covered ``losses
resulting from erosion caused by waves or currents of water
activity exceeding anticipated cyclical levels of erosion
accompanied by a severe storm, flash flood, abnormal tidal surge,
or the like.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the El Nino phenomenon, the unusual warming of waters
in the Pacific Ocean that affects global wind and temperature
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   And there went the flood insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Three insurance companies _ State Farm, Bankers Trust and
Allstate _ are refusing to pay the residents' claims, arguing that
the cliff was eroding before last winter's fierce storms. The news
has come as a stomach-turning shock to the residents who lived on
Esplanade. Three have hired lawyers and are ready to sue. Others
have enlisted the city of Pacifica, which has lodged an appeal with
the Federal Insurance Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I'd have to find some place through the winter, but
I thought I'd be able to get my life settled before this,'' said
Jane Tollini, whose home at 556 Esplanade Drive finally pitched
over the cliff on May 6. ``I had no idea I'd be stuck all through
the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   No spot on the California coast was more photographed or written
about during El Nino's stormy climax than Esplanade Drive, where
homes toppled into the ocean or teetered between land and thin air
as distressed homeowners watched.
</P>
<P>
   The wave action in February and March, coupled with high tides,
was so violent that it tore away about 40 feet of the cliff on
which the Esplanade Drive homes were perched, as much as had been
eroded in the previous 44 years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, three of the five remaining homes are red-tagged and
uninhabitable; the other two don't look like long-term investments.
Most of the west side of Esplanade Drive has reverted to the sand
dune it was in 1948, when the modest two- and three-bedroom homes
were built.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers say the claims are invalid for a variety of reasons:
the cliff had been gradually eroding for years, five of the
residents bought their insurance in the middle of the storms _ when
damage was clearly foreseeable _ and no water actually entered
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Tollini, for instance, purchased a $250,000 flood insurance
policy on Feb. 11 from State Farm for $345. It took effect on March
13. She went about her job as keeper of the penguin exhibit at San
Francisco Zoo feeling protected from financial loss if not from the
elements, and moved into her best friend's house when hers was
uninhabitable.
</P>
<P>
   It was bad enough to see her house fall over the cliff in May,
but in July she got a worse shock. Her claim had been disallowed
because her loss ``was not caused by flood'' and also because the
forces that wrecked it were already in progress when the policy
kicked in.
</P>
<P>
   She said State Farm heavily advertised its flood insurance
during the storms and presumably knew what it was insuring when it
sold her the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we found out that high wave action was included in the
policy, all of us on the block jumped on it,'' she said. The
$250,000 policy limit ``seemed fair,'' although she figures her
house was worth more. ``I'm not looking to get rich on this,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   And she dismissed the insurer's contention that erosion was well
under way before El Nino struck. When she moved into her Esplanade
Drive home six years ago, ``it had 34 feet of fenced back yard and
8 to 12 feet beyond the fence, and for years I watched that very
large back yard stay right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Municipal officials in Pacifica, which is south of San
Francisco, agree. In appealing the coverage denial decision to the
Federal Insurance Administration _ a branch of the Federal
Emergency Management Agency _ Pacifica was relying on a report
prepared by geologist Kenneth R. Lajoie of the U.S. Geological
Survey, who has studied the coast for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main causes of the severe cliff erosion along Esplanade
Drive ... were near-record precipitation, heavy surf and
exceptionally high tides,'' Lajoie wrote. ``The rain saturated the
ground, weakening the poorly (hardened) sediment exposed on the
cliff face.''
</P>
<P>
   Lajoie's report is evidence that the insurance carriers'
conclusion was wrong, said retired attorney Beverly Axelrod, who
lost her home of 14 years when the saturated cliff gave way beneath
it. But ``if we can't convince them through that report, then it'll
be litigation or politics, I guess,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most of the residents of Esplanade Drive, Axelrod
purchased flood insurance five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The final resolution of the Esplanade Drive homeowners' claims
may turn on the definition of the word ``flood.'' It has never been
precisely defined by the courts, according to attorneys for both
the insurers and the homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   ``People understand that when the water gets in your house,
that's a flood,'' said Clarke Holland, the San Francisco lawyer
hired by State Farm in the Esplanade Drive case. ``The more
difficult problem arises when no water gets in your house. Do you
have coverage?''
</P>
<P>
   Holland said that the decision to deny coverage was in fact made
by the government's managers of the National Flood Insurance
Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Routine claims don't go to them, but on claims like Esplanade,
which are clearly out of the norm, State Farm goes to NFIP,''
Holland said. ``It was their decision not to pay those claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Late-purchased policies like Tollini's raise another potentially
disqualifying issue; that is, that coverage is denied because
damage occurred before the policy's effective date.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to her carrier, Tollini's lawyer, Richard Eric Roby,
notes that the policy's coverage is ``limited exclusively to
buildings and personal property'' _ that is, the house itself and
what was in it.
</P>
<P>
   It does not cover the land under her house. In fact, he noted,
her house was still standing until May 6 _ months after the onset
of the violent wave action that ultimately did it in.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA has agreed to spend $13 million for infrastructure repair
and public assistance for El Nino-caused damage, including $1.5
million for a rock seawall at the base of the cliff below Esplanade
Drive.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA may eventually contribute more; Pacifica last month applied
for a grant to prevent disastrous storm erosion in the future. FEMA
will occasionally grant funds to permanently fix problems the
government knows will inevitably recur. The classic example is the
removal of entire towns from the Mississippi River flood plain
following the epic flood of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   If the application is approved, Esplanade Drive residents who
lost their homes would be paid $140 per square foot _ about 50
cents on the dollar value of their homes _ and their lots would
become open space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would turn it into parkland,'' Pacifica Code Enforcement
Officer Sarah Albee said. ``It's a last resort for these people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
