<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0323 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCANDAL-BUSINESS-KAN &LR;      10-05 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCANDAL-BUSINESS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL DOMINATES NEWS, BUT BUSINESS OF GOVERNING THE NATION
CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Capitol Hill the other day, Attorney General
Janet Reno spoke about parental kidnappings and Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan talked about turmoil in the financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Neither mentioned the words ``Monica Lewinsky,'' ``President
Clinton'' or ``impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate talked about Russian missiles falling into the hands
of terrorists. The House debated how much to spend on child
nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   Washington may be fixated on sex and scandal, but it still has a
government to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of work going on around here, but the perception
out there is we're all kind of standing around here chatting about
you-know-who,'' said Sen. Connie Mack, a Republican from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Some are, but that's their lot in life right now. The House
Judiciary Committee, which unloaded yet another raft of sex and
scandal documents Friday about the president's affair with the
former White House intern, will begin deliberations Monday about
whether he should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic members of the committee have been
shuffling in and out of news conferences at which they accuse the
other side of being more partisan. But nearly everybody else on
Capitol Hill was concerned with more mundane matters last week,
such as tax cuts, alcohol abuse on college campuses and the
military's state of readiness, or lack of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our forces are showing increasing signs of serious wear,''
Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, told
the Senate Armed Services Committee. ``Anecdotal and now measurable
evidence indicates that our current readiness is fraying and that
the long-term health of the total force is in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, just down the hall from the military brass, the
Senate Environment and Public Works Committee was talking about the
protection of migratory birds.
</P>
<P>
   Life and death decisions share time in Congress with the tiny
details. The secretaries of state and defense late one afternoon
privately briefed senators for two hours about air strikes against
Yugoslavia. Earlier that day some of the same senators spent 5 1//2
hours debating whether the government should build a 30-mile gravel
road to connect a remote Alaska village with the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, led by Alaska's two GOP senators, want to build
the road. The Democrats, backed by the environmental lobby, oppose
construction in a federally mandated wilderness area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is the Democratic leadership willing to risk the lives of
Alaska's Aleut people under the guise of protecting the
environment?'' asked Rep. Don Young, an Alaska Republican.
</P>
<P>
   It was refreshing to hear more traditional partisan attacks
after so much debate that has centered on the president's sex life.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the Senate lawn, for instance, Sen. Edward Kennedy, a
Massachusetts Democrat, scolded the Republicans at a news
conference one morning for supporting managed-care legislation that
doesn't cover public employees, such as police officers, teachers
and nurses. Unlike his own bill, Kennedy said, the Republican
measure ``does to little to protect patients and too much to
protect the profits of HMOs and other insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Flynn, a police officer from Lowell, Mass. and a supporter
of Kennedy's bill, said: ``People think that Congress is bogged
down with the president and the Lewinsky scandal. As you can see
here today, there are a host of other issues Congress should deal
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn knows about getting your point lost amid the muck. As
national vice president of the International Brotherhood of Police
Officers, he got caught in the path of the Monica Express in August
when he was in Washington to promote the fifth anniversary of the
``Brady bill,'' which restricts handgun purchases.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke at a Rose Garden ceremony with the president. They were
upstaged by speculation that Clinton was wearing a tie that had
been given to him by Lewinsky and that he was sending her some sort
of message before her grand jury appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Pres Hamilton of Thousand Oaks, Calif., who was visiting the
Capitol with his wife last week, said they were glad to see that
Congress had other things to do besides focus on the president's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people stop and think for a moment,'' he said, ``God
knows this country can't come to a screeching stop over that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, whose last day as Clinton's spokesman was Friday,
struck the same note in a briefing last month. ``The federal
government is a large organization that continues to run
irrespective of Monica,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But with a steady diet of scandal news, which has now blossomed
into a story about the possible impeachment of the president, it's
little wonder that many people don't see what else is going on.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a bipartisan higher education bill 96-0 last
week, the product of 18 months of negotiations. On the other hand,
the GOP caucus split on some key funding issues, so it is less
likely Congress will be sending appropriation bills to Clinton any
time soon. The bills are necessary to fund the government.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John LaFalce of New York, the senior Democrat on the House
Banking and Financial Services Committee, said Congress had many
issues before it, ``ten times more important'' than the president's
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of the global economy being one of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan addressed that very point when he appeared before
LaFalce's committee last week. Greenspan defended his agency's role
in the rescue of a huge private investment fund that had lost many
billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Substantial damage could have been inflicted in many market
participants,'' Greenspan said, ``including some not directly
involved with the firm, and could have potentially impaired the
economies of many nations, including our own.''
</P>
<P>
   His testimony was long, detailed and tough for the uninitiated
to wade through. A lot of the speeches on Capitol Hill are like
that.
</P>
<P>
   But as one tourist eagerly remarked after he emerged from the
Senate visitors' gallery, where he had listened to the debate on
the defense authorization bill: ``I could spend a couple of hours
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   And not hear a single word to make him blush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
