A0349 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POTOK-JEWISHSTUDIES-T     10-05 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTOK-JEWISHSTUDIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITER CHAIM POTOK STRUGGLES TO RECONCILE RELIGION, MODERN WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Confrontation has shaped writer Chaim
Potok's world. When, as a 16-year-old Orthodox Jew, Potok
discovered secular fiction, the intellectual collision changed him
irrevocably. When as a young man he spent 16 months on the
battlefields in Korea, the culture shock rattled everything he
thought he knew.
</P>
<P>
   Clash of cultures fills the 69-year-old author's numerous
novels, including ``The Chosen,'' ``The Promise'' and ``My Name Is
Asher Lev.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Potok inaugurated the Jewish Studies Program at Texas
Christian University with a speech on the campus last week, he felt
right at home. After all, he has been exploring the clash of
traditions, cultures and ideas for more than three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The university is conducting a search for a scholar to teach
Judaic studies. TCU's decision to fund a chair in Jewish studies
``seemed an anomaly at first,'' Potok told his audience. ``But in
fact, it's what I've been writing about my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 36, Potok won acclaim for his first novel, ``The
Chosen,'' the story of an unlikely friendship between two Jewish
boys. Danny Saunders is a sheltered but brilliant fundamentalist
Jew destined to inherit his father's position as rabbi but secretly
enthralled by the ideas of Sigmund Freud. Reuven Malter, the
story's narrator, watches his friend struggle to reconcile his
duties to community and family on the one hand and his fascination
with secular thought on the other.
</P>
<P>
   In ``My Name Is Asher Lev,'' a boy discovers his genius for
painting and fights to remain a part of his fundamentalist Jewish
community while pursuing a career that is decidedly antithetical to
religious Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat like Potok's experience.
</P>
<P>
   All modern novels are somewhat autobiographical, Potok said, his
included.
</P>
<P>
   Potok's parents immigrated to the United States from Poland in
the early '20s and settled in the Bronx. Hasidic Jews (part of an
Eastern European movement that stresses religious fervor), they
expected their son to become a Talmudic scholar.
</P>
<P>
   But at 16, Potok experienced his first culture confrontation.
His sheltered world collided with something intrinsically different
when he checked out of the library Evelyn Waugh's 1945 ``Brideshead
Revisited,'' and discovered modern secular literature.
</P>
<P>
   ``What literature did was it introduced me to worlds I could
have never imagined, and these worlds constituted alternative ways
of constructing the human experience,'' Potok said the day before
his lecture. ``And the more I read, the more I began to ask myself
about the validity of my own way. That's the beginning of the
remaking of the map inside your head.''
</P>
<P>
   These confrontations that Potok speaks of are, he says, a
relatively new phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hundred years ago, you grew up, you lived, you died
inside your own world,'' he explained. People didn't travel, few
read, they weren't exposed to new ideas or different cultures. ``In
the world today, especially in Western culture, you grow up in one
framework and very early on you encounter another one. You're
always being challenged by alternative ways of thinking about the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   These collisions can create tension and wreak havoc in lives,
but they also can give birth to extraordinary new ways of viewing
the world: George Gershwin's encounter with jazz and blues gave us
American popular music; Pablo Picasso's discovery of African art
led him to cubism.
</P>
<P>
   Potok's own case exemplifies the personal pain inherent in these
clashes.
</P>
<P>
   Writing was not a career that religious Jews pursued, and
Potok's father was not pleased. ``As far as my father was
concerned, he certainly did not want me to be a writer,'' the
author said. ``Because the kind of serious writing done today comes
to us from the secular-humanist, modernist culture in which we
live. It looks at the world with a somewhat jaundiced eye, at best,
and a really angry eye at worst. Its tone is ironic, its attitude
is at the very least objective, and its way of looking at the world
is considerably less than sacred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, none of this works in a religious world where things are
taken for granted as being sacred,'' he said. ``And my father, who
was pretty knowledgeable, understood this.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Danny Saunders and Asher Lev, Potok strained to reconcile
his fascination with the modern world and his religion. He
ultimately left the Hasidic movement and joined conservative
Judaism. An ordained rabbi, he received a doctorate in philosophy
from the University of Pennsylvania, where he now teaches.
</P>
<P>
   For Potok, writing has been a way of organizing the chaotic
world around him, working through that ever-changing map in his
brain. With each book, the protagonists are older and ``the
problems get more and more difficult to resolve,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his most recently published work, ``Zebra,'' is a collection
of quietly affecting short stories _ with modern, secular settings
_ aimed at a middle-school audience. Each story focuses on a
``crucial moment of crossing in the life of a young person,'' noted
Potok, who says he's not exactly sure why he wrote ``Zebra'' and is
uncertain where the next inspiration will come from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned,'' he said. ``I have no idea where the train is
headed.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
