<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0386 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT-2     10-05 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAND-TRANSPLANT SURGEONS PONDER THEIR SURPRISING PATIENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., France, Great Britain)   (The Science Times)  
(mk) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hand and forearm transplant performed on an Australian man
in France nearly two weeks ago ranks among the most extraordinary
cases in the annals of surgery, one full of sudden plot twists,
colorful characters and international controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 1/2-hour operation was years in the planning, and the
man, Clint Hallam, was chosen for it in October 1997, according to
interviews with members of the international team of doctors who
carried it out on Sept. 23. Hallam, the French hospital initially
announced, was ``a businessman living in Perth, Western Australia''
who had impressed his doctors with ``his personality, courage and
determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallam had been a patient of a major member of the team, Dr.
Earl Owen, a microsurgeon in Sydney, Australia, for more than two
years and had undergone extensive psychological evaluation in
Australia and in France.
</P>
<P>
   But the hospital did not say that two days before the operation,
the head of the surgical team, Dr. Jean-Michel Dubernard, learned
from the patient that he had a criminal record. The West
Australian, a newspaper in Perth, later reported that Hallam was
due in court there in January to face seven fraud charges.
</P>
<P>
   And far from losing his right hand in a logging accident, as
initial reports had it, Australian newspapers said he lost it using
a circular saw in a New Zealand jail.
</P>
<P>
   But the operation proceeded because ``this man desperately
wanted the graft,'' Dubernard said. ``As a doctor, I take care of
everybody and did not change anything'' in his treatment, said
Dubernard, who is not only a transplant surgeon but also a member
of the French parliament and a deputy mayor of Lyons. ``It is a
pity that the Australian newspapers revealed that he had been to
jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Hallam was reported recovering well at Edouard Herriot
Hospital in Lyons, and there was no sign that his body was
rejecting the grafted hand and forearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are surprised he's doing so well and that so far there are
no problems,'' Dr. Xavier Martin, a member of the team, said from
his office at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam's doctors are confident that even if he experiences a
rejection reaction, drugs developed in recent years will enable him
to become the first successful hand transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are quite confident that this man's rejection, which is
probably inevitable, can be controlled,'' said Owen, who helped
pick the team.
</P>
<P>
   At scientific meetings in recent years, doctors have debated the
benefits and risks of hand transplants, but controversy over such
surgery has heated up since Hallam's operation.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say anti-rejection therapy has improved to the point
where hand transplants could be successful, improving the lives of
many patients. Plus, they could open the way to transplanting other
tissues. Dubernard, the head of the transplant team in Lyons, said
about 10 other teams in France, Germany, Sweden, Louisville, Ky.,
and elsewhere were poised to do hand transplants.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, the American Society for Surgery of the Hand
joined the critics, saying the risk-to-benefit ratio for
experimental hand transplants ``has yet to be convincingly
established,'' particularly because the procedure is not lifesaving
and anti-rejection therapy could lead to serious infections and
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The society urged that doctors not try another hand transplant
until the success of Hallam's case could be determined and further
experimental work was performed on animals.
</P>
<P>
   The French team intends to evaluate the technique in two or
three more patients to determine whether it should embark on a
clinical trial of about 50 hand transplants in hospitals in several
countries, Dubernard said.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics faulted the idea of assembling a team from
Australia, England and Italy to do the operation in Lyons, then
allowing it to disperse.
</P>
<P>
   Owen defended the procedure and the way it was carried out. He
said he and Hallam left Australia because organs and tissues could
not be donated there without explicit permission in writing. But in
France, he said, such permission is presumed unless family members
object.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in France is a donor,'' said Owen who has worked in
Lyons with Dubernard on joint projects each year since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with its population of 58 million people, France offered
better odds of a match in terms of size and color of the new hand
and the donor's sex than Australia, with its population of 18.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Hallam nearly did not get a new hand and forearm.
</P>
<P>
   Owen consulted experts in several countries, and chose an
international team. It assembled in Lyons in early September.
Although several team members had worked with each other in the
past, the eight surgeons had not worked together as a team until
they practiced performing the operation in a laboratory in Lyons in
the days before Hallam's operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not privileged to tell you what we did because it would
upset people,'' said Owen, who continued, ``Any form of animal
experimentation upsets people when they hear about it, and then
anti-vivisectionists come out against you.''
</P>
<P>
   After 10 days passed without a suitable donor, Owen said, ``we
decided that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to put the operation off two months and come
back for another 10 days at the end of November,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors began returning home. Suddenly, at about 1 a.m., the
Lyons team was notified about a brain-dead individual.
</P>
<P>
   But Dubernard was in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hari Kapila, a hand surgeon from Sydney, had flown to Paris
and was awaiting Owen, who had gone to Switzerland. The two doctors
planned to catch the same flight for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Marco Lanzetta, a hand surgeon at Monza Hospital in Milan,
had driven back to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nadey Hakim, the head of transplantation surgery at St.
Mary's Hospital in London, had returned to England and was in the
operating room performing the first of two kidney transplants he
would complete by dawn. He left immediately for Lyons and arrived
in time to take part in Hallam's operation, which began about 10
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Bernadette Chirac, the wife of the French president, arrived for
a long-scheduled visit that morning and she watched the operation
for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But just as they were congratulating themselves on their
surgical success came the news reports about their patient.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like Dubernard, Owen was chagrined about his patient's
background. ``We were completely duped for two years,'' he said,
adding that the patient had been in jail at least twice. ``He is a
consummate rogue, '' Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Hallam was accepted as a transplant patient, he went
through psychological testing in Australia. Presumably, the testing
focused less on Hallam's working life than on traits that would
determine whether he could live happily with another person's arm.
Just after Hallam arrived at his hotel in Lyons, and before he went
to the hospital, Dr. Gabriel Burloux, a psychiatrist who is a
leading French expert on body imaging and author of textbooks on
the subject, interviewed him, Dubernard said.
</P>
<P>
   Burloux ``gave us the clean bill of health that this was a very
suitable man with a very strong constitution and very solid in his
resolve,'' Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   It was only when Dubernard talked to him later that Hallam
filled some of the gaps in his background.
</P>
<P>
   The team is not worried that Hallam will disappear into any kind
of criminal underworld. ``He will not be able to get his
immunosuppressants, and he knows it,'' Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, most transplant doctors share the team's view that
a patient's criminal record should not determine eligibility for
surgery. For example, the ethics committee of the United Network
for Organ Sharing, a nonprofit organization that coordinates the
U.S. national organ allocation program, has concluded that an
individual's status as a prisoner should not preclude consideration
for a transplant. The recommendation is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Although doctors strive to relieve suffering, they are as
vulnerable as anyone to disappointments, rivalries, bruised egos
and other human frailties.
</P>
<P>
   For example, doctors at the University of Louisville had
expected to be the first to achieve success in transplanting a
hand. Their team announced last summer that they planned a similar
procedure later this year. Doctors in Louisville were particularly
surprised by the announcement from France because Hallam had
applied to them too for a transplant.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. John Barker, who heads the Louisville team's research
program, also said his team had never heard of the group that
performed Hallam's transplant. He said members had not spoken up at
meetings devoted to hand transplants.
</P>
<P>
   That was because ``it is better to do something than say that
you are going to do something,'' Dubernard said.
</P>
<P>
   And while Owen expressed great respect for the Louisville team,
he added that if Barker had not heard of him, ``he has probably
read only American textbooks.'' He added, ``Have you heard the term
sour grapes?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not in any race with Louisville,'' he said. ``They may
well be in a race with us, but they will never catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   Owen said he had been reimplanting severed fingers and limbs
since 1970 and teaching courses in microsurgery around the world
since 1967. ``You name the country, I have been there,'' Owen said,
and ``mostly, I have been able to teach well enough for them to
take over themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I may be unknown in America,'' Owen said, ``but the rest of
the world recognizes who the pioneer of microsurgery is.'' He said
American hand surgeons ``were five years behind us in Sydney
putting on fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our microsurgery center in Sydney is justifiably famous,''
Owen said.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after Hallam's transplant, Herriot Hospital
experienced a huge power failure during the night, backup
generators failed and 10 patients died within the next two days.
French officials are now investigating the episode.
</P>
<P>
   Hallam slept through the power failure and his care was not
affected, Dubernard said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and nurses work in teams in the same hospital every day,
and in doing so they work like athletes on sports teams. Success in
outcomes can hinge on how well doctors and nurses learn the nuances
of each other's habits and techniques in the operating room and
during the recovery phase.
</P>
<P>
   These are among the reasons why an operation is rarely performed
by assembling a team from different continents. No one knows what
might have happened if a medical emergency sent Hallam back to the
operating room when the principal surgeons were dispersed over the
globe.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, even critics say that does not mean the hand
transplant is not going to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
