<HEADER>
A0396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILAN-FASHION-ART-NYT     10-05 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY MILAN SHOWS HIGHLIGHT CASUAL, YOUTHFUL LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ The first weekend of the spring 1999 showings in
Milan was like the opening act in a rock concert, with lesser
lights warming up the audience for the stars who will perform
later. With the exception of Romeo Gigli and Lawrence Steele, who
showed their signature lines, it was mainly designers' secondary
collections that set the stage for what will follow.
</P>
<P>
   These secondary or diffusion lines are often in the same mood as
a designer's main collection, offering a hint of what's to come
without giving away the plot. Usually, they're aimed at a younger
customer and take a more casual approach.
</P>
<P>
   And young was the attitude of the Miu Miu show, which Miuccia
Prada presented on Saturday. Ms. Prada's models were made up and
styled to look as if they had barely entered adolescence, and they
wore clothes inspired by sports, the military and country dancing.
</P>
<P>
   The sporty clothes _ poplin or neoprene shirts or jackets worn
with short shorts or Bermudas _ were often shown with multipocketed
vests worn in back on webbing belts that tied around the waist or
hips, the way the sleeves of a sweater would be tied around the
waist.
</P>
<P>
   Miu Miu was not all about function, though. There were
fringe-trimmed pants and skirts, and ruffles at the hems of wide
skirts with unpressed pleats. These were shown with peasant blouses
or strapless bandeaux tied with drawstrings, perfect for urban
line-dancers, especially when they were worn with multicolored
snakeskin cowboy boots.
</P>
<P>
   Khaki and olive drab had a pseudomilitary air, feminized by
being fashioned into styles like U-neck dresses with high
waistlines, worn open over shorts.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was a clever blend of the masculine and the
feminine, the functional and the frilly. They were clothes for fun
times, and so were many of the other collections shown in Milan so
far, which were not aimed at the career woman in her 9-to-5 mode.
</P>
<P>
   You're hardly likely to see any of the D&AMP;G skin-tight dresses
over visible bras in a business office, but they'd fit right into
the club scene. Mainly in shiny black stretch satin or cire or
printed with large purple onions or red peppers or tomatoes, the
dresses often sported separate belts with outside pockets. Skinny
pants came with their own pockets, lots of them, though putting
anything thicker than a credit card into one of them would make an
unsightly bulge.
</P>
<P>
   No woman who wears a design by Domenico Dolce and Stefano
Gabbana wants bulges in the wrong place, especially if she's
swathed in gold leather or metallic stripes of red, blue, black and
gold that look like Christmas wrapping. There's nothing subdued
about D&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   Or for that matter, about Blumarine by Anna Molinari. Her sexy
creatures may wear baby blue or powder pink, but it's likely to be
in shiny satin with slits on both sides, or a see-through sweater
that's trimmed in fur, or a dress that's cut like a nightgown and
bordered in lace. Even Blumarine's rose-print patterns and floral
embroideries are anything but naive, cut into body-conscious shapes
and combined with black tulle.
</P>
<P>
   Donatella Versace, in the Versus collection, which she showed
Sunday night in an abandoned warehouse far from downtown Milan, put
two supermodels on the runway, a rare sight this season. But then,
her name is Versace, which has its own star power.
</P>
<P>
   Both of the models _ Kate Moss and Naomi Campbell _ strutted in
tops that were slit down the sternum and skirts that were slit to
the thigh. They and the other models wore colors like aqua, orange,
pink, peach and brown in clothes that hugged the body or slipped
provocatively off a shoulder. Skirts were either as short as a
skirt could possibly be or long and lean, slit to reveal the legs.
Even the boots revealed the legs, being backless with just a ladder
of straps up the calf.
</P>
<P>
   Glitter was kept to a minimum in the show, with just suggestions
of shine, as on the last dress in the Versus collection. At first
sight it made Ms. Moss look downright matronly, all black and long
with a high neck and long sleeves. But when she turned, her back
was bare to the waist. That's more like it, Ms. Versace. Women
don't look to you for sober clothing.
</P>
<P>
   When women want styles that are feminine yet up-to-the-minute
chic, they've been going to Philosophy di Alberta Ferretti, though
for spring the designer mixed her message a bit. There were simple
little shift dresses, neat pants, a front-zipped black leather
jacket, and skimpy shirts worn partly open over hip-slung skirts.
There were shirts and skirts in men's shirting stripes for a hint
of the androgynous, but then the scene shifted to Thomas Hardy
country with long, loose dresses and full skirts over petticoats.
</P>
<P>
   The country-maid dresses and skirts were pretty as a picture in
white with pin-tucking and pleats or in black with quiltlike
trapunto stitching and a frill of white pleats peeking out from
under the hem. But anyone young enough to wear them probably wants
to look older.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Steele, one of the original Americans in Milan, has a
much more sophisticated customer in mind, one who likes to show off
her body in bare tops and ultrashort skirts, and in halter-neck
dresses wrapped and tied with thongs. And Steele thinks she should
feel free enough to wear knits and bias-cut skirts that are as
sheer as gauze.
</P>
<P>
   The best of his clothes took flight. Feathers wafted softly
around bodices or sleeves. And chiffon was cut into layers that
fluttered like feathers and seemed so light that you feared a
sudden breeze would whip them off the models' backs.
</P>
<P>
   Romeo Gigli has gone back to his romantic roots, after last
season's unsuccessful foray into hard-edged chic. Using
gossamer-weight organza, crinkled silks and sheer laces, often with
metallic finishes that gave them a modern edge, he showed loose
shirts and tunics, slender long skirts and calf-length pants in
colors ranging from the palest yellows and beiges to murky blues,
wines and greens.
</P>
<P>
   Delicate embroideries or cutwork decorated some of the jackets,
capelike coats and enveloping shawls. Echoing a trend seen in
London last week, Gigli finished some skirts with rows of
asymmetric lace ruffles.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Gigli's laces were in metallic silver or gold. Most of
his dresses had high waistlines and bare necklines that dipped off
the shoulder and were held up by skinny straps. The show ended with
two all-over beaded dresses, one silver and one gold, with hems
that had been cut into fringelike slivers. The collection was
filled with beauty but tended to be repetitive and went on too
long.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
