<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0408 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TUCCI-MOVIE-LADN     10-05 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TUCCI-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXTREMELY TUCCI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Stanley Tucci says he was born a ``very physical
person,'' which explains a lot of the squirming and fidgeting he
has been doing while sitting in this restaurant corner booth at the
Four Seasons Hotel in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci has been more or less a prisoner here for three hours now,
conducting interviews to promote his new movie, ``The Impostors,''
an old-fashioned farce that celebrates the physical comedy of
people like Buster Keaton, Laurel and Hardy, and the Marx Brothers.
Three hours of sitting is three hours too long for Tucci, who would
like nothing more right now than to run around the block a couple
of times to clear the cobwebs from his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always like this,'' Tucci explains, slumping in the
corner. ``When I'm writing, it's hard for me just to sit there and
concentrate because I like to do things. I exercise as much as
possible, work around the house, do landscaping stuff, whatever. I
think it goes back to the way I was trained as an actor, with dance
and movement. So to just sit at a desk and write ... after about an
hour, I go a little crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tucci had to go a little crazy _ in more ways than one _ to
make ``The Impostors.'' Like ``Big Night,'' the much-loved 1996
indie hit about two brothers trying to make a success of their
gourmet Italian restaurant, Tucci wrote, directed and produced
``The Impostors.'' (``Yup, crazy,'' he says as a method of
explanation.)
</P>
<P>
   He also stars in the film along with Oliver Platt and a host of
Sundance favorites, including Steve Buscemi, Lili Taylor, Campbell
Scott and Hope Davis. The movie was four years in the making,
longer if you consider that Tucci and Platt originally created
their characters years ago when they put on a play together at
Yale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the idea about these guys who were unemployed actors
who do everything but work,'' the 38-year-old Tucci says. ``Since
they can't get a job, they have to go out on the street and act
because they're desperate to hone their craft. They have to act.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucci knows the feeling. It's one reason he made ``The
Impostors,'' which celebrates the joy of acting, in much the same
way ``Big Night'' proclaimed the wonders of pasta, marinara sauce
and a good bottle of wine. The movie is a farce, a rarity in the
film world, even though there are now more studios and more movies
than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone kept telling us you can't make a farce, that no one
will fund it because no one makes these movies anymore,'' says Beth
Alexander, Tucci's producing partner. ``To us, that was reason
enough to try it. Why should we all be making the same kinds of
movies?''
</P>
<P>
   Tucci admits that he has set himself up for a fall, that
sustaining the energy of a farce over a couple of hours is the most
difficult challenge for a filmmaker to tackle. But then, to Tucci,
trying to beat the odds was part of the fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can be so expressive physically, but it's not something
you see much in movies,'' Tucci says. ``And I think it's enjoyable
for people to watch because it hits you on a gut level, no matter
who you are or how you perceive the world. When someone is doing
something physically, you're almost more attentive. Sometimes words
get in the way. People talk too much, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Tucci can be guilty of that, too.
</P>
<P>
   Says Hope Davis: ``He never stops tossing ideas at you, which is
one of the things I love about him. Often we would finish a scene,
and he'd be yelling, `Keep rolling,' and he'd just be shouting out
all kinds of ideas. `Try this! Try this!' And I'd be wondering how
we could use any of what we were shooting because Stanley would be
laughing so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   A different side of Tucci will be seen next month in HBO's
highly anticipated biography of gossip columnist Walter Winchell.
Adapted from Neal Gabler's celebrated book, ``Winchell'' will take
an unsparing look at the man who wielded incredible power from his
syndicated newspaper column for some two decades. Tucci worked on
the project for 10 weeks this past spring and calls it one of the
most difficult roles he has played as an actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winchell was an incredibly complex guy who changed the world,
maybe not for the better,'' Tucci says. ``He was a very insecure, a
workaholic and probably a manic-depressive. And through his column,
he became one of the most powerful men in the world, more powerful
than the people he made and destroyed. What's weird is that today
nobody knows who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucci, who is married and lives in Westchester County, N.Y.,
with his wife and two stepchildren, still has moments when he's
incredulous that people know who he is. Before ``Big Night,'' Tucci
had appeared in some 25 movies and more than 100 television
episodes, but nobody, including casting agents, could remember his
name. In fact, he couldn't find any work at all (``couldn't get
arrested'' is how Tucci puts it) until a high-profile turn on the
short-lived ABC legal drama ``Murder One'' put him in the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Big Night'' continued his winning streak, and
Tucci seems quite determined to make sure the leading roles keep
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I formed a production company is that I
don't trust anybody to employ me,'' Tucci says. ``I used to get
pretty upset when I'd look around and see all the leading men in
movies looking exactly the same. Now, I've got a little bit of
leeway. I'm seeing some things coming my way, and if they don't, I
can always write something for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to ``Winchell,'' Tucci can be seen as a
home-security salesman who stages burglaries to boost sales in the
dark comedy ``The Alarmist'' (opening Oct. 16) and as Puck in
Michael Hoffman's big-screen version of ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream.'' Tucci dyed his thinning hair blond for the latter project,
in which he co-stars with Kevin Kline, Michelle Pfeiffer and
Calista Flockhart. The film is due out next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci is also working on a script based on ``Joe Gould's
Secret,'' a famous profile written by legendary New Yorker writer
Joseph Mitchell. The movie, which may begin filming as early as
January, focuses on Mitchell's relationship with Gould, a 1940s
bohemian. Tucci is going back and forth about whether he wants to
play Mitchell. (``Call it 50-50,'' he says.)
</P>
<P>
   While it's not the big movie that Tucci hopes someday to direct,
it's a project that's close to his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too much work otherwise,'' Tucci says. ``That's why I
could never be a director for hire. I could never devote the amount
of time to something that wasn't my own.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' Tucci continues, ``I've got about a dozen
projects going at once right now, and that's the way I like it. It
takes a long time for something to reach fruition and achieve the
depth and resonance that it should have. I've spent a long time on
this Joe Mitchell thing to get it right, and I did the same thing
with `The Impostors.' I've got to live with something in order to
get it right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
