A0439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATTERNS-FASHIONS-NYT     10-05 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By CONSTANCE C.L. WHITE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; More Makeup at Barneys &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Manheimer, vice president of cosmetics and fragrance for
Barneys New York, noted that when sales per square foot are
compared for various types of merchandise, cosmetics generally
outperform everything else. It is the same for many department
stores, which in the last year have been increasing the space
devoted to beauty. Construction begins this month on a new
apothecary area on the first floor of Barneys Madison Avenue store
and is expected to be completed by Nov. 8, just in time for the
lucrative holiday shopping season. There will no longer be an
entrance through the store into Bulgari next door.
</P>
<P>
   The new area will have an expanded range of bath and beauty
products and will allow Barneys to increase its representation of
cosmetics lines. A few blocks away, Henri Bendel last year
aggressively expanded its cosmetics offerings, replacing
ready-to-wear space with cosmetics shops like MAC, and Macys has
unveiled a sparkling new cosmetics and fragrance area on its first
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Barneys will add a Philosophy shop, and makeup from Fresh, Body
and Soul, Cargo and Le Clerc, among other lines. Kiehl's and
Francois Nars are the store's best-selling cosmetics lines, and the
expansion will allow Barneys to double its Nars space, Ms.
Manheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   Barneys approaches beauty a little differently from its
competitors. The no-spritzing policy will still be in effect, and
the store employs its own beauty sales personnel. Other shops like
Macy's and Bendel's rely on the cosmetics companies to supply
salespeople. And Barneys' aversion to color extends from its
ready-to-wear offerings to cosmetics. The new counters will still
be stocked full of natural-toned hues, although there will be some
concessions made to plum shades as a counterweight to the season's
gray clothes. ``Neutrals for us remain popular,'' Ms. Manheim said,
``though we will be going deeper into plums, which lend themselves
to the trends in fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Soda-Bottle Fashion &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Almost 200,000 Jones soda bottles bearing A/X Armani Exchange
advertising will be distributed around New York through the fall.
While customers are guzzling drinks like ``pineapple upside down,''
they can decide if they want to buy that ribbed sweater pictured on
the bottle. The idea may be extended to Los Angeles and other
markets, Lori Krauss, a spokeswoman for A/X, said.
</P>
<P>
   The black-and-white advertisements featured on 12 of Jones' 16
flavors are drawn from the A/X fall advertising campaign that is
running in fashion magazines. The soda bottle campaign cost A/X
about $4,000, Ms. Krauss said.
</P>
<P>
   The sodas are being sold in outlets where Jones would normally
be distributed, like fancy delis and supermarkets, but they are not
available in A/X stores. ``The theme of the whole campaign was life
style and how do you incorporate A/X into your life,'' Ms. Krauss
said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For Mizrahi, Film and Ballets &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Although Isaac Mizrahi announced last week that he is closing
his fashion company, he does not plan to sit around twiddling his
thumbs. The designer said he is already working on a screenplay
titled ``Wild About Harry,'' a Barry Josephson and Barry Sonnenfeld
picture.
</P>
<P>
   This summer he and Nina Santisi, his former vice president of
public relations, formed Baby, a film production company to be
located in Greenwich Village. Baby has a deal with Dreamworks to
produce ``The Adventures of Sandee the Supermodel,'' based on
Mizrahi's illustrated book published this year.
</P>
<P>
   And Mizrahi is designing the costumes for two ballets by Mark
Morris, his friend. The first is a ballet commissioned by the San
Francisco Ballet, and the other, said the designer, is still a
secret. ``So many opportunities have come my way in the past two to
three years that I have not been able to take advantage of,''
Mizrahi said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
