A0464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-CLERKS06-COX     10-05 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-CLERKS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROTESTORS DECRY LOW NUMBER OF MINORITY SUPREME COURT CLERKS
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Emotional demonstrators marched in front of the
U.S. Supreme Court on Monday to protest the low number of minority
law clerks hired at the nation's highest judicial body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The justices' record on hiring clerks of color is so poor that
if the civil rights laws applied, the Supreme Court would be
vulnerable to a charge that it has discriminated on the basis of
race,'' said Stephan Kline, legislative counsel at the Alliance for
Justice, an association of public interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 428 clerks hired by the nine current justices since they
joined the court, less than 2 percent were African American, 4
percent were Asian American, 1 percent were Hispanic and none have
been Native American, according to a study conducted by the
national newspaper USA Today. One-quarter were women.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's protest, which came as the court held its opening
session of the 1998-99 term, was organized by the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People.
</P>
<P>
   Kweisi Mfume, the NAACP's president and CEO, said having
minority law clerks is especially important as the court considers
such controversial issues as affirmative action, school vouchers
and welfare reform. Clerks help determine which cases the court
will consider and write the first drafts of most decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Under gray, drizzling skies, the protestors marched in a crammed
oval on the sidewalk in front of the court. Many chanted, ``no
justice, no peace,'' as they carried signs that read, ``minority
law students need jobs too'' or ``Supreme Court, no justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the two-hour rally, Mfume and a handful of
others were arrested for crossing police lines as they mounted the
west steps of the court in an attempt to deliver resumes of
minorities they say are qualified to fill the prestigious
positions.
</P>
<P>
   With minorities making up nearly 20 percent of law graduates and
women making up nearly 40 percent, protesters said the ethnicity
and gender of high court law clerks should closely reflect American
society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this court that ruled against (racial) set-asides (for
minority businesses) to put away their set-asides,'' said Rodney
Brown, chairman of the National Black Law Students Association.
``In your own words, justice delayed is still justice denied.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the USA Today study, Justice Antonin Scalia has the
worst minority hiring record among the nine justices, having hired
no minorities in his 13 years in office. Chief Justice William
Rehnquist, who has hired 82 clerks in his 27 years, has hired just
one minority clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Stephen Breyer and John Paul Stevens have the best
records, with 15 percent of Breyer's clerks and 13.1 percent of
Stevens's being minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Off the 33 clerks hired by Justice Clarence Thomas, the only
minority member of the court, 12.1 percent have been minorities,
including one black clerk.
</P>
<P>
   To solve the problem, justices should hire from a larger pool of
applicants, Mfume and other organizers said. About half of the
clerks hired in the last 25 years have come from Harvard, Yale or
Columbia universities.
</P>
<P>
   A Supreme Court spokesperson said the court had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 1755EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
