<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0469 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWNS-SYNDROME-1500(2     10-05 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWNS-SYNDROME-1500(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE WOMEN CHOOSING TO HAVE DOWN'S SYNDROME BABIES
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by DOWNS SYNDROME-TEST) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Conner Moore, 3, helps Barney clap his hands
and stomp his feet _ really fast _ as the purple dinosaur sings,
``If you're happy and you know it ...''
</P>
<P>
   The boy's own almond-shaped eyes sparkle, and his grin shows you
exactly how he feels _ even before he shapes the letter ``B'' with
his right hand and strokes the side of his face, signing his
favorite television character's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's absolutely awesome at signing,'' Shelley Moore says of
her son, who has Down's syndrome. Speech is difficult and delayed
for most people with Down's, so many speech therapists recommended
sign language to help fill the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never, ever regretted that he was born with an extra
chromosome, that he's exactly the way he is,'' Moore says. ``If I
could wave a wand and make Conner different, I would not even
consider it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 25 years since reliable tests were developed for Down's
syndrome, most women who tested positive for a child with Down's
have chosen to end their pregnancies. Now, however, doctors have
noticed a slight shift in the other direction. And, thanks to
medical advances, a huge increase in educational and developmental
opportunities and more social services and family support, people
born with Down's syndrome are living longer, more productive lives.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley Moore was 33 when Conner was born and hadn't considered
the possibility that her baby might have Down's syndrome. Conner
was 6 weeks old when his pediatrician heard a heart murmur and
referred him to the heart specialists at Cook Children's Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   There, tests showed that he not only had multiple heart defects,
which required immediate and extensive surgery, but also Down's
syndrome. About 60 percent of babies born with Down's syndrome _
almost 5,000 each year in this country _ have some form of
congenital heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   John and Kay McGrew knew about Grady's extra chromosome more
than six months before he was born on Dec. 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   They felt shock and disbelief. ``We hadn't even talked about it
ahead of time. We just had amniocentesis because our doctor said
that at our age, we should,'' John McGrew says. He is 44, his wife,
42.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a personal decision (to continue the pregnancy). A lot
of families may not have all the good things going for them that we
have,'' McGrew says. ``We have a lot of support from our families
and good health insurance, and Grady is a sweet, quiet, precious
baby, who hasn't had any of the major health problems associated
with Down's. We were prepared for a lot more difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people born with Down's syndrome have medical problems all
their lives, including a much higher risk for hypothyroidism and
Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   The McGrews had an extensive ultrasound study done after they
learned Grady would have Down's, so they would be ready to deal
with any major heart defects. But not only is his heart fine, his
hearing, vision and breathing are normal, and he is only a little
slow in developing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our baby is so normal, we just treat him normal. He's very
aware and curious. He's trying to walk already. We will take him
wherever he wants to go in life. I hope he goes further than I
have,'' John McGrew says. ``I hope he graduates from college.''
</P>
<P>
   AIMING HIGHER: Higher expectations are making the big difference
in the quality of life for people born with Down's syndrome, says
Dr. Allen Crocker, assistant professor of pediatrics at Harvard
Medical School and a national authority on Down's syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``At present, the cultural norm is to terminate the pregnancy if
the fetus is determined to have Down's syndrome. That's the
expected behavior, but the number who would resist that tradition
is growing,'' says Crocker.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, it is estimated that almost 80 percent of the time,
the fetus is aborted when prenatal testing detects Down's early
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get an increasing number of parents who want to talk after
the tests, who want to know more about what it means to have
Down's, what to expect. And the majority of those who seek us out
for information end up retaining the pregnancy and moving on. That
was a trickle just 10 years ago, but there are more now _ nowhere
near the majority of all those who find out they are going to have
a baby with Down's, but a few more,'' Crocker says.
</P>
<P>
   Support services are now widely available, including improved
community living and educational opportunities. Most of these
children will go to regular public schools and work for a salary.
Many will grow up and get married. Life expectancy is about 58
years, according to Crocker.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 20 years ago, many children born with Down's were
placed in institutions shortly after birth and often died before
they reached adulthood. In the early 1930s, the estimated life
expectancy for people with Down's was only nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole world of the person with Down's syndrome is so much
more valued and so much more attended to. Our expectations are
greater and being fulfilled,'' Crocker says. ``It used to be said
that a child with Down's syndrome would not learn to read and, as a
result, most of them did not. Now most children with Down's
syndrome will graduate from high school and read at the fifth-grade
level.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a ways to go. ``The biggest negative is still the
system,'' says Liz Moore, an assistant director of the National
Association for Retarded Citizens (The Arc), headquartered in
Arlington, Texas. ``We did a national survey last fall, and there
are tremendous waiting lists for the kinds of services needed:
residential placement, job training, jobs themselves, therapy of
all kinds. The world has not kept up with the demands.''
</P>
<P>
   For parents who decide they cannot care for a child with Down's,
Crocker recommends adoption as an option. ``There are a lot of
people who want babies who need them, and babies with Down's are in
such demand there's a waiting list in most major cities,'' he says.
``I could find you a family in 15 minutes that wants to adopt a
baby with Down's. That's a startling departure from 20 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   OUTLIVING EXPECTATIONS: The overall incidence of Down's
syndrome, about 1 in 1,000 live births, has not changed in most
states in the past 10 years, Crocker says, estimating that there
are 4,000 to 5,000 babies born with Down's each year.
</P>
<P>
   Different factors such as the number of older women giving birth
and the number undergoing prenatal screening and deciding to
terminate the pregnancy seem to even out the birth rate, according
to Crocker.
</P>
<P>
   The risk of having a baby with Down's increases for women after
age 35, but about 80 percent of Down's babies are born to mothers
under 35. It's simply a matter of so many more younger women having
babies in general and the fact that screening tests are not
routinely offered to younger women, Crocker says.
</P>
<P>
   What has changed dramatically is the number of people with
Down's surviving childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting rid of institutions did a lot for us,'' says Frank
Murphy, executive director of the National Down's Syndrome
Congress. ``Most babies born with Down's in the last 20 years have
gone home and grown up in a home, not in an institution. That in
itself gives a longer, better life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people are living longer today, partly because of better
medical treatment. Heart defects are being fixed that were
inoperable 20 years ago. A lot of our kids had respiratory and
heart problems that took them early. Medicine has come a long way
for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the educational system has accepted our kids. In 1974, the
first bill passed in Congress giving our kids the right to school.
House Bill 94-142, the Individuals With Disabilities Education Act,
gave them the right to a free and appropriate public education,''
Murphy says. ``They are graduating from high school and becoming
productive citizens like we knew they would be if we gave them a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of his six daughters is 22 and has Down's. ``My
daughter is a taxpayer, not a tax burden,'' he says. ``She has a
job sorting and stocking greeting cards. She takes care of two
different stores. She pays taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Moore puts it, her 3-year-old son is ``differently
abled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conner never ceases to amaze us,'' she says. ``When we got to
the hospital last week, he realized where we were and held up his
little hand to sign `stop,' and said `no' very firmly.'' (He'd had
his fill of needle sticks and hospitals.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want him to learn sign at first, but it's really been
a blessing,'' Moore says. ``When he learned to sign `more' and
`finished,' I realized this is only fair. It's very frustrating not
to be able to tell people what you want. He's learning to
finger-spell the alphabet.''
</P>
<P>
   He also can say ``Mama'' and ``Dada,'' ``Nana'' and ``bye-bye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want people to know these children are normal,'' Moore
says. ``There are 12 kids in Conner's preschool class, and he's
just one of the 12. When we left him the first day, he was sitting
in the middle of the floor with all the other children, singing a
song, willing and eager to learn just like any other normal child
on the first day of school.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The National Down Syndrome Congress is an education and advocacy
organization for people with Down's syndrome and their families.
The group organizes an educational conference each year, publishes
a monthly newsmagazine and maintains a 24-hour hot line. For more
information, call (800) 232-6372.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
