<HEADLINE>
TESTING FOR DOWN'S SYNDROME
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies DOWNS-SYNDROME) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Downs syndrome is a chromosomal anomaly. An error in cell
development results in 47 chromosomes rather than the usual 46. The
extra gene material changes the orderly development of the body and
brain.
</P>
<P>
   Most people with Down's syndrome score in the mild to moderate
range of mental retardation on standard IQ tests. Many have low
muscle tone, which can delay walking and other physical activities
such as holding a pencil.
</P>
<P>
   Amniocentesis was the first fetal test developed to help
determine the presence of chromosomal defects, including Down's,
about 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is still the definitive test and is recommended for women
over age 35, whose babies are at higher risk.
</P>
<P>
   For pregnant women of any age, a blood test known as the
``triple marker screening'' is routinely used to determine higher
risk and the need for amniocentesis. It has been available for
about five years.
</P>
<P>
   While no test is 100 percent accurate, amniocentesis is about
99.9 percent able to detect Down's syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   About half of all fetuses with Down's will also have ``soft
signs,'' such as increased skin folds, dilated kidneys and short
femur bones, which can be detected with ultrasound.
</P>
<P>
   Just this summer, two new noninvasive tests, one a complex
maternal blood analysis and the other an ultrasound study that
measures the bump under the skin at the back of a fetus's neck,
have been reported, but it is expected to be several years before
they are in general use.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
