<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0505 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-WASTE06-COX     10-05 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-WASTE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ALLOWED THEM TO POLICE THEMSELVES, CENTERS BILKED MEDICARE
 &HT;    580&AMP;add. Florida, Texas eds: Story's final grafs list barred
centers.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal officials conceded Monday that they had
trusted private mental health centers to police themselves in a
Medicare program that ballooned from $60 million to $350 million in
five years, with rates of fraud and abuse as high as 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built it, and they came,'' said Penny Thompson, a
government overseer, of the benefit program that spawned a network
of community health centers, especially in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who works for the Health Care Financing
Administration, the agency in charge of Medicare, told a
congressional hearing that after Medicare began offering outpatient
mental health benefits for the elderly, private providers rushed to
set up services and bill the federal government for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   When government investigators began looking into a sample of
programs this year, they found that the mental health services
often amounted to no more than bingo, arts and crafts or other
social events that were billed to Medicare as intensive psychiatric
services.
</P>
<P>
   The schemes to bilk the government are especially prevalent in
Texas and Florida, which together account for more than half the
total billings in the outpatient mental health program, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just stunned that we've got another program that was able
to grow like a weed,'' said Rep. Joe L. Barton, R-Texas, who called
the House Commerce subcommittee hearing after two government
investigations discovered rampant abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a black eye to the federal government to have a program
like this that's just grown totally out of control,'' said Barton.
He displayed a posted invitation from a Washington state retirement
home saying, ``Come join us for coffee, cookies, and conversation
... in the rec center'' with the word ``Free'' prominently
displayed.
</P>
<P>
   The event was not free for the government, however. The facility
billed Medicare $1,300 for psychiatric services for the 35 to 40
attendees. Although that company has been assessed $45,000 in
penalties, few of the others involved in the practice have been
caught until now.
</P>
<P>
   Under lax procedures uncovered by the inspector general of the
Department of Health and Human Services, the mental health centers
merely signed a form attesting that their services were eligible
for Medicare reimbursement and that their facility met local
certification requirements. Often, the doctors who diagnosed the
need for psychiatric treatment were employed by the centers that
offered the services.
</P>
<P>
   The Health and Human Services Department last week notified 20
centers in Texas, Florida and Louisiana that they are ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could say we'll terminate all of the offenders,''
said Thompson, but she said the department did not want to cause
disruption for clients.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by Barton, Thompson predicted that most of the 1,000
community mental health programs would be excluded from Medicare
funding by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Thompson conceded that her department has known about
abuses in the mental health centers as far back as 1994. ``I think
it wasn't acted upon,'' she said, because other problems loomed so
much bigger in Medicare, whose overall spending for the year just
ended was $218 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how much the outpatient mental health program will cost
after new safeguards are added, Thompson said ``much less'' than it
does now.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   But she offered no specific amount, saying that her agency was
instituting a 10-point plan for better oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan is not to develop estimates,'' she said. ``Our plan
is to implement the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Community mental health centers that were notified last week
that they do not qualify for Medicare participation include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Florida: Quality Care Mental Health Management in St.
Petersburg; Daylight of East Pasco, Inc. in Zephyrhills; Serenity
House of Volusia, Inc. in Daytona Beach, Advanced Counseling
Services, Advanced Counseling Services, Inc., in Coral Gables; and
Miami centers including Sierra Norwood Community Mental Health
Center, Ultimate Medical Center, Inc., Cutler Ridge Community
Health Center, Mutual Behavioral Health Care Center, Professional
Therapeutic Alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Texas: Bright Day Treatment Center in Laredo, New Horizons of
Corpus Christi, New Insights Behavioral Center in McAllen, Sun West
Health and Wellness Center Inc. of Brownwood, Texas Serenity
Counseling Services, Inc. in Houston, and San Antonio centers
Classic Community Mental Health Center and Maren Care Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
