<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-BOXER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXER TRIES TO MOVE AWAY FROM CLINTON MATTER IN TOUGH CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As a college senior, Barbara Boxer came
eyeball-to-eyeball with sexual harassment, the issue that 30 years
later she would grapple with in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer described the incident involving a professor at Brooklyn
College in her 1994 autobiography. He ``grabbed me by the shoulders
tightly and leaned over to kiss me. Now I remember his old face
coming at me, my pushing him away, grabbing the door handle and
running down the empty corridor ...''
</P>
<P>
   She never revealed the incident during her five terms in the
House of Representatives nor in October 1991 when she pressed for
public hearings into Anita Hill's sexual harassment allegations
against Supreme Court nominee Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   As Boxer faces a tough re-election contest against Republican
state Treasurer Matt Fong, the harassment issue arises again _ she
is saddled with questions about President Clinton's behavior in the
Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer has been a vigorous political ally of the president while
her daughter, Nicole, married a brother of first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton. The woman who led the charge for Anita Hill and
later pressed for public hearings into sexual harassment
accusations against Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., finds her initial
reluctance to criticize Clinton generating charges of a
double-standard.
</P>
<P>
   As the Nov. 3 election approaches, Boxer says she is asked about
the White House scandal and rather than the her differences with
Fong on issues like gun control and abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tremendous frustration,'' Boxer said. ``It is the
reason I have to raise so much money to go over the heads of the
media (with television advertisements), because I can't get
anything printed that I say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have given speeches _ about 25 speeches _ where I have
blasted Matt Fong's positions on everything from choice to the
environment ... I mean we don't agree on anything. It has been a
surreal experience, this campaign,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton's actions, she said, ``I feel terrible about it,
obviously. I am very sad about it. But I have _ all through this
career in the Senate _ just drawn the brightest of bright lines
between my personal feelings and my duties as a senator.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Boxer, following other Democrats who had rebuked
Clinton, took to the Senate floor Sept. 8 and spoke out against the
president's ``immoral behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My decision has been to be very straightforward about this
relationship, but also not to back off the fact that I think he has
been a terrific president for this country and this state.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton matter aside, critics say Boxer hasn't produced a
major legislative accomplishment in the Senate. They say that's the
harvest of a partisan lawmaker who grabs the media limelight, but
lacks the ability to deliver a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer and her supporters counter that her knack for marshaling
attention to issues, giving voice to liberal Democrats in a
GOP-controlled Congress and landing federal dollars for California
are under-appreciated assets.
</P>
<P>
   Now she finds herself matched in close contest against a
candidate who can claim the diversity banner for himself as a
Chinese American.
</P>
<P>
   For Boxer, 57, backing off has never been one of her traits.
</P>
<P>
   She earned a bachelor's degree in economics from Brooklyn
College. She went to Wall Street to put her husband, Stewart,
through Fordham Law School, but found as a woman she wasn't
accepted into a broker-training program.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she took a job as a secretary and studied for the
stockbroker's exam. By 1963, she had her license, and a broker job.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer and her husband, now an Oakland plaintiff's lawyer, moved
to the San Francisco Bay area in 1965, drawn by the region's
natural beauty.
</P>
<P>
   She was elected Marin County supervisor in 1976, and in 1982,
was elected to the House of Representatives. She was elected to the
Senate six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Peel away the speeches, endorsements and the television
advertisements, and the tally of Senate successes, measured by
Boxer's legislation that became law, is meager.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when it comes to environmental protection, which Boxer
claims as a paramount concern, Sen. Dianne Feinstein delivered the
California Desert Protection Act and spearheaded talks to preserve
the Headwaters old growth redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to have very different ideas about the role of a
senator,'' said Richard Fenno, a Rochester University political
science professor and congressional scholar.
</P>
<P>
   ``One says, `I want to get in there and compromise and be an
effective legislator.' The other says, `I want to be an effective
advocate.' One wants to work the issues. The other wants to
popularize them,'' Fenno said.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer clearly is uncomfortable with comparisons to Feinstein, a
fellow Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, Senator Feinstein and I really like each other. But we
are not joined at the hip ... I don't view that as a negative,''
Boxer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to just come out in front with the issues. I always
have found that the compelling nature of the issue will win the
day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boxer style is to grab a hot-button issue and ride the wave
of public sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara Boxer's strength is sniffing out good issues and
knowing how to play the media with them,'' said San Francisco
Supervisor Michael Yaki, a former aide to Rep. Nancy Pelosi,
D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   While Feinstein could be labeled the Senate's quintessential
moderate, eager to reach across party lines, Boxer has built a few,
less visible, cross-party ties, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has been very responsive,'' said Republican Barbara
Warden, a San Diego city councilwoman who relies on Boxer to get
federal funds for the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reason for liking to work with her is she tells me up front
that it is something she can do or not do. And, if she can,
somebody (on her staff) is working on it,'' Warden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
