<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-FONG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DETERMINED FONG OVERCOMES ODDS IN CALIFORNIA SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was summer, a time when most high school
seniors sun and snore. But Matt Fong was running hard to snap
himself into shape, eyes as always trained on a target.
</P>
<P>
   At his side, running the Oakland hills where they grew up, was
his cousin and mentor, just one year older but enrolled in the
place where ``Kip'' Fong most wanted to be: the U.S. Air Force
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time we ran together, he was clearly hurting after
five miles,'' remembers Bradford Lee, now an Air Force colonel, a
physician and attorney. ``He realized he needed to get in better
shape to make it. He has an incredible perseverance. A lot of
things didn't come easy, he had to work at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong was not a natural athlete, nor a stellar scholar. But he
was determined to survive the physical and academic rigors that
felled nearly half his academy classmates. And in due time, he won
his wings.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the dogged quality evident in Fong's youth has
put him in a position to win a seat in the U.S. Senate. Critics of
the Republican candidate say his political success stems from
another quality of his upbringing: the name of his mother, longtime
secretary of state March Fong Eu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he thinks he can ride his mother's good name to the
polls,'' said another of Fong's cousins, Pattie Fong, a Yolo County
deputy district attorney. ``I respect people with ideas and vision.
I don't see him as having a vision. He's not his own thinker. He's
malleable. I see him as window dressing for the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat turned Republican, Matthew Kipling Fong followed in
the footprints of his mother but diverged into starkly different
ideologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is where he is because of the tie to his mother,'' said
Republican analyst Tony Quinn. ``He is running in the shadow of the
fine reputation March carried as a public servant.''
</P>
<P>
   In a clear instance of maternal pride over partisan politics, Eu
_ a Democrat _ is avidly pitching her son's candidacy, touting the
importance of an Asian-American presence in Congress, the
competence of her son and his commitment to public service.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been imbued with a sense of public trust,'' Eu said.
``Even when he was 12 years old, he said he wanted to be a U.S.
senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong is a graduate of the Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs,
Colo., and earned a master's degree in business administration at
Pepperdine University and a law degree at Southwestern University
School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his four years as state treasurer and one term on the
Board of Equalization, Fong, 44, is widely perceived as a political
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, California's electorate has but a vague fix on the
candidate running even in the polls with incumbent Democratic Sen.
Barbara Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fong is a benign candidate,'' Quinn said. ``It doesn't hurt
that he hasn't been ultra-specific on issues. ... Fong comes across
as a hard-working guy. His interest is tax policy, which is not a
very sexy area.''
</P>
<P>
   To critics, Fong is tentative, overly swift to spout Republican
boilerplate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the most timid candidate running for statewide office,''
said Bob Mulholland, a Democratic Party campaign adviser.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters say Fong is the moderate California is looking
for, a low-key contrast to the bombastic Boxer. While Fong may lack
a charismatic public presence, he has become more adept in front of
a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kind of stiff and uncomfortable; he doesn't seem like the
kind of guy you'd go out drinking with,'' said John Pitney, an
associate professor of government at Claremont-McKenna College and
a former Republican National Committee staff member. ``For some
people, campaign skills come naturally. For Matt they have to be
learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Persistence and calm ambition are Fong's underpinnings. Two
years ago, at the genesis of his Senate bid, he wasn't given much
of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't listen to the naysayers,'' said GOP consultant Dan
Schnur. ``He worked as hard as a candidate can.''
</P>
<P>
   Touting himself as moderate, Fong's platform favors increased
military ending, school vouchers and a flat tax rate of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   He personally opposes abortion but supports a woman's right to
choice during the first trimester of pregnancy. He backs a ban on
so-called late-term abortion and opposes federal funding of
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a committed Christian who (worships) in Whittier at a
Baptist church,'' said the Rev. Lou Sheldon, chairman of the
Traditional Values Coalition. ``We don't agree 100 percent on the
abortion issue but ... it's not a perfect world. It's like you are
sitting in first class, and you don't like the salad dressing, but
the filet mignon and potatoes are great.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that a vote for Fong is less an affirmation of the
candidate than a repudiation of the far more liberal Boxer, who is
finishing her first term.
</P>
<P>
   ``The downside is his candidacy doesn't have a great deal of
magnetism,'' Pitney said. ``Rather, it is propelled by people who
are repelled by Boxer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
