<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT PARTY WINS LOCAL ELECTIONS IN TROUBLED CHIAPAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico _ The government's party has
once again gained overwhelming control over county mayors' offices
and the local legislature in the troubled state of Chiapas,
according to results announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With 90 percent of the votes counted, the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, had won 77 of 103 counties
and 17 of the 24 seats in the state Congress that were up for
election.
</P>
<P>
   In a significant change for this tumultuous state, home to the
Zapatista guerrilla group, no serious violence was reported during
the voting. Instead, apathy was the prevailing spirit, with voter
turnout well below 50 percent in many regions.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI kept its hammerlock even though it is no longer a
majority in Chiapas in terms of the number of votes cast. In the
voting for the state congress, the PRI won 280,921 votes and the
combined opposition took 282,327. But the opposition vote was split
between two parties, the left-of-center Party of the Democratic
Revolution and the conservative National Action Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
