<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0536 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     10-05 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER GAME PLAYERS NEED TO CUT THE CARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Q. There are a couple of people in our department
who spend far too much time playing solitaire on their computers
every day. It's annoying, but we don't feel it is our business to
confront them, nor do we want to rush into management to complain.
How do we get them to stop? K.I.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is not easy to know what to do when there is too much game
playing in your department, whether literally or figuratively.
However, since the solitary actions of these two employees are so
upsetting, the time has come to call them on it.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is for you and some of your associates to meet
with the players and suggest that they start pulling their weight
instead of pulling cards. You can then suggest that they stop
playing unless they are on a break.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes peer pressure can be enough to indicate to these
jokers that playtime is over, particularly if they believe that you
will take further action if necessary. If they play their cards
right, the matter should end at this point.
</P>
<P>
   However, if these players cannot exit the game, you and your
associates should mention this to your manager. By doing so at this
point, you certainly are not rushing the process. After all, the
reality of the situation is that when employees are at work, they
are supposed to work. And, when they are fooling around, management
needs to spend more time wandering around.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am in the middle of a series of interviews for a new
position. I'm interested in the job, and the people seem nice. What
bothers me is my impression of the hours. The supervisor told me he
works 7 a.m. to 7 p.m. daily, and I believe his employees work long
hours as well. My concern is to balance my work schedule and family
schedule. Am I expected to work long hours? M.W.
</P>
<P>
   A. Just as it is the employer's duty to try to figure out if the
applicant meets the job specifications, it is the applicant's duty
to try to figure out if the job meets his or her specifications.
During the initial phase of the screening process, the employer
asks the bulk of questions, and the applicant provides the bulk of
the answers.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the process, it is the applicant who should be asking
the questions. You may be interested in this job and highly
qualified for it, but all it takes is one critical negative
component to turn it into a bad match. Before you accept any offer,
your real job is to make sure the job is acceptable to you.
</P>
<P>
   You already have an indicator that the work hours may be a
problem, so you should ask some specific questions about them. You
may find that the hours are actually in an acceptable range, or
perhaps there is some flexibility. However, if the hours are far in
excess of what you want, and there is no leeway to deal with your
needs, you could not have found out at a better time.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Our organization is undergoing major restructuring, and one
of our co-workers was asked to stay three months beyond the general
end date. Her attitude toward work is questionable and disruptive,
and other good employees with the same responsibilities are being
let go earlier. Do you have any advice for those good employees who
believe they are just pawns in this unfair game of office politics?
M.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. One clear sign of a major restructuring that has become a
major mess occurs when surviving or departing employees view
themselves as pawns. During restructuring, employees seek
communication, equity, respect and support. Anything less is a
profound wound to an organization and one that heals slowly if
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The reality for those good employees who are being restructured
out of the organization is that instead of worrying about end
dates, they should be thinking about beginning dates, namely when
and where their next jobs are going to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are questions about the seemingly preferable
treatment granted to one problem employee, that is not the problem
of the departing employees. In fact, there can be countless reasons
why this particular employee is getting a few extra months, and
they can range from being totally business-oriented to totally
absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it is easy to spend a great deal of time focusing on
this employee, but it makes far more sense for the departing
employees to focus on their new careers and not on hers. And this
same advice applies to the pawns who remain.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
