<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PFEIFFER-TV-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESSE JACKSON JOINS TV SHOW PROTEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH MARDER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; The protest against UPN sitcom ``The Secret Diary
of Desmond Pfeiffer'' gained some national clout Monday as the Rev.
Jesse Jackson joined the call to cancel the new show.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, in town to pay his respects at former Mayor Tom
Bradley's funeral, stopped at Paramount Studios early Monday to
march with and address hundreds of participants in the third
demonstration against the comedy, which debuted Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not looking for censorship,'' Jackson said, ``but there
must be sense in the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   Many local African-American groups, led by the Brotherhood
Crusade, have complained loudly that the show makes light of human
suffering during the time of slavery in this country. ``Pfeiffer''
is about a black British nobleman who escapes to America and
becomes President Abraham Lincoln's butler and one-man kitchen
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Danny Bakewell, the leader of the Brotherhood
Crusade, said they will not be satisfied until the show is taken
off the air.
</P>
<P>
   An effort to target the show's sponsors will begin today,
Bakewell said. Jackson said he will urge that similar action be
taken around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the dollars, it's the dignity,'' Jackson said. ``It's
not the job of an actor, it's the dignity of a people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson turned down a hand-delivered message inviting the
protest leaders to meet with UPN Entertainment president Tom Nunan,
asking instead to meet directly with UPN president and chief
executive officer Dean Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the pain, you have the power, the power to insult us,
and it's unnecessary,'' Jackson said about the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's protest was the latest episode in two weeks of conflict
swirling around the fledgling show. Last week, the Los Angeles City
Council unanimously condemned the program and said the show's debut
should be postponed until a community screening can be arranged and
the Human Relations Committee has time to prepare a report on
whether it is fit for broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood creative community has backed UPN and lashed out
at the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know that there was an Iron Curtain around the city
of Los Angeles,'' said Emmy Award-winning producer Dick Wolf (``Law
&AMP; Order''). ``This is a quick fix of ink in a local market that I
can't believe will have any impact beyond the Los Angeles City
Council.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN president Valentine was incensed that the council would pass
such a motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a terrible precedent to set,'' Valentine said.
``I think he (Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas, who sponsored the
motion) has no business in my business. It's a world where everyone
is looking for 15 minutes of media attention and it's very easy to
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine called the council's vote ``a sneak attack on the
First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said the council's vote is laughable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presumption of politicians to think they have any right to
say what goes out on broadcast networks is beyond ludicrous,'' Wolf
said. ``It's beyond any level of hubris and self-important
egocentricity and temerity to think they have the right to do
something like this. What planet are they living on? Not the planet
the United States is on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
