<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0588 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-HNS &LR;      10-05 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE JUDICIARY COMMITTEE FAILS TO RISE ABOVE PARTISAN BICKERING
OVER IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They invoked the wisdom of Constitutional framers
Alexander Hamilton and James Madison, spoke reverently of Peter
Rodino, the man who chaired the Watergate hearings, and sprinkled
in references to the Civil War and civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the House Judiciary Committee clearly hoped to
take their place in history Monday as they convened to authorize an
impeachment inquiry into charges against William Jefferson Clinton,
only the third president to face the prospect of removal by
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite the gravity of the business and the constant
references to high-minded principles, the committee failed to rise
above the partisan bickering that has sullied the ideologically
fractured panel in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The 37 lawmakers split predictably along party lines as they
delivered perfunctory five minute speeches at the outset of the
hearing, held in a cavernous chamber in the Rayburn House Office
Building across the street from the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The vote to proceed with the GOP-crafted inquiry was not in
doubt as the 20 Republicans, who sat to the right of Chairman Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., had the numbers to roll over the 16 Democrats, who
sat to the chairman's left.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the public who wandered over to catch the
proceedings on this gloomy drizzly day left as cynical as they had
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same old baloney. The Democrats say one thing. The
Republicans say another. It doesn't impress me,'' said Maxine
Schneider, a visitor from suburban Chicago who watched the opening
statements on television screens in a sparsely filled room reserved
for overflow crowds.
</P>
<P>
   While Schneider said she believed Clinton should face some sort
of penalty for his actions, both she and her husband, Marvin, who
are Republicans, said they opposed impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But inside the committee room, lawmakers insisted that they
would not be swayed by public opinion, claiming they had a higher
duty to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, said one Republican lawmaker, Howard Cobble of North
Carolina, opinion was too divided in his district. He related how
one person recently called to warn him not to return home if he
didn't vote for impeachment while another threatened she would
never vote for him again if he did not end the proceedings. He
noted that a third constituent voiced the hope that the congressman
would just die of prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers conducted their debate under the stately portraits
of Hyde and Rodino, a reminder of the link between Watergate and
the present.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Rodino's Judiciary Committee that voted to impeach
Nixon almost a quarter of a century ago, the current panel includes
few moderates who could steer the committee toward compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Instead the members are more representative of the most active
and ideological wings of the respective parties.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one woman, the Republicans are white Christian males
from suburban and rural districts. The Democrats hail largely from
urban districts and include six blacks, six Jews, three women and
an openly gay male.
</P>
<P>
   The daylong hearings drew the attention of the national media,
with the cable news networks broadcasting the proceedings live. And
when the committee took a lunch break lawmakers flocked to the
cameras to make sure their messages were repeated back home on the
evening news.
</P>
<P>
   By midday, however, most journalists had vacated their seats in
the hearing room as lawmakers droned on about the pros and cons of
Republican resolution and Democratic alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   While there was not an overwhelming crush of visitors vying for
seats at the hearings, some of those waiting to enter said they
hoped to witness history.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Seymour, 19, a student at the University of Pennsylvania,
showed up with two classmates as part of a political science
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our Watergate since we weren't alive during
Watergate,'' said Seymour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a political junkie,'' said Harold Landreneau, a 29-year
old visitor from Houston who dropped by the hearing after a stop at
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Landreneau said he did not believe the committee should impeach
the president, arguing that what Clinton did does not rise to the
level of high crimes and misdemeanors.
</P>
<P>
   Paul and Kathy Schwabe, of San Jose, Calif., also stood in line
to get into the hearing even though both said they were tired of
the media coverage of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why they were there, Paul Schwabe sarcastically remarked
that he wanted to ``see the government waste some more money.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schwabe acknowledged the scandal had its allure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are tired of it, yet we're standing in line,'' he
said. ``Kind of hypocritical.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
