A0603 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-ADVICE-COX     10-05 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-ADVICE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sag in stock market suggests a time for defensive tactics
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Level with me. How bad is it?
</P>
<P>
   That could easily be the average investor's plea for guidance
after 2 1/2 months of volatile stock trading.
</P>
<P>
   And the answer is: Bad enough.
</P>
<P>
   We won't know how bad until it's over, but this is certainly
Wall Street's worst battering since the bear market in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market has given back most of its gains for the year.
The U.S. economy is slowing, and parts of the world are in danger
of financial collapse.
</P>
<P>
   This is a new environment for the estimated 67 million
individuals in the United States who own stocks and mutual funds.
While there's widespread agreement the long-term picture still
looks good, investment advisers say this is an important moment in
market history, when individuals need to keep their cool.
</P>
<P>
   This would seem to be the right time for the defensive maneuvers
that have been drummed into our heads over the years: Have a plan,
diversify, invest long-term and don't panic.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who act on fear and sell in a down market are turning
paper losses into real ones, said Jack Calhoun Jr., vice president
of Capital Directions, an Atlanta-based investment adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are also creating a dilemma for themselves because they
must decide when to get back into the market,'' said Calhoun. ``And
because the stock market often makes its upward moves quickly, it's
very likely that the market may recover most of its losses before
the investor moves back into stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Hans Stoll, director of the Financial Markets Research Center at
Vanderbilt University, suggests investors think in terms of ``two
pots of money: a long-run pot for retirement, which you don't
touch, and a pot to play with, when there are buying opportunities
in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The best course is not to tamper much with long-term holdings,
but the short-term portfolio can be adjusted for market conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A major decision is how to allocate investments among stocks,
bonds and other assets, including money market mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury bonds are less risky than stocks, but they yield less,
for the same reason. Still, many investment advisers recommend at
least a portion of any balanced portfolio should include bonds.
</P>
<P>
   A Bloomberg News survey of asset allocation recommendations of
15 major Wall Street brokerages in late September showed an average
mix of roughly 62 percent stocks, 30 percent bonds and about 7
percent cash.
</P>
<P>
   But the individual stock recommendations ranged from a low of 40
percent by Merrill Lynch analyst Charles Clough to a high of 80
percent by Lehman Brothers strategist Jeffrey Applegate. All-stock
portfolios are regarded as highly aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   Braving potential downturns
</P>
<P>
   As for which stocks or sectors to own, a favored defensive
approach is to buy the stocks of utilities and other companies that
provide consumer staples such as food, beverages and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Companies in those industries are among the least likely to
experience declining profits _ at least, their profits will drop
less than those in other sectors, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether times are good or bad, people still need to eat, drink
and go to the doctor. The demand for these products and services is
fairly static,'' said Sam Stovall, a Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst who
follows industry trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utilities perform well for two reasons: Demand is static, and
they pay dividends, which makes them more attractive when share
prices are falling,'' said Stovall.
</P>
<P>
   Precious metals such as gold _ or rather the stocks of precious
metals mining companies _ have also attracted investors as a
defensive move.
</P>
<P>
   Gold has historically been regarded as a hedge against inflation
and volatility, although the sustained period of falling inflation
during the 1980s and '90s has greatly diminished that role.
</P>
<P>
   While the short-term advice seems to be slanted to the cautious
side, some analysts find more reason for optimism than fear in
investor psychology, which can move the market.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer researcher J. Walker Smith, managing partner of the
Atlanta office of Yankelovich Partners, doubts the current turmoil
will end in the panic selling that has often occurred in past bear
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a new dynamic to how people look at their finances,''
said Smith, whose firm researches investor behavior for a number of
financial clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``They believe they are a lot more savvy than (their
predecessors), that they know how to deal with bad times as well as
good times,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude fits what Smith referred to as the paradoxical
pattern of the baby boom generation in particular _ the generation
credited with helping to fuel the 1990s bull market with its stock
and mutual fund buying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does a declining market undermine the confidence of baby
boomers in where things are going? I think it makes them feel worse
about their current finances but not necessarily about their
prospects,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have learned to view life as a paradox, that bad always
comes with good,'' he said. ``While the market is weak now, that's
almost what people expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
