A0604 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-BARGAIN-COX     10-05 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-BARGAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Caution in order when bargain-hunting
 &HT;    By Robert Luke
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time to bargain-hunt?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But before you do, consider these tips from the experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patience is a virtue _ that's the first rule,'' said Charles
B. Carlson, consulting editor of Dow Theory Forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tendency is to jump in too early,'' Carlson said. ``If
you're buying in a bull market, you have the upward primary trend
in your favor when you're bargain-hunting. In a bear market,
however, the notion of a bargain can be kind of difficult to
discern because markets tend to move to extremes.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we've seen how the extremes can run to the upside, I
don't think we've really got a true picture of how extreme
valuations can go on the downside,'' Carlson continued.
</P>
<P>
   So keep your powder dry, advised H. Bradlee Perry, retired
chairman of David L. Babson &AMP; Co., a money management firm in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those who want to buy, I wouldn't fire off all my
ammunition right now,'' Perry said. ``We've taken the insanity out
of (stock) valuations. But, generally, I would not say we're into
bargain land yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlson concurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, you've formed some reasonable price in your head
about what you're willing to pay,'' he said. ``But know that you're
not going to necessarily buy it at the bottom. Also know that what
may seem cheap now may become even cheaper. And it would be a shame
to use up all your buying power all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   So spread your buying over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use some time diversification,'' Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   He recommends extra care in bargain-hunting for stocks that have
plummeted for a reason, such as weaker-than-expected earnings.
</P>
<P>
   One key question to ask: Are the problems temporary?
</P>
<P>
   ``I generally like to see some improvement in a company's
earnings momentum before buying,'' Carlson said. ``It doesn't
necessarily mean the company's earnings are growing, just that
there seems to be improvement from quarter to quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Careful analysis of the company and its industry is essential.
</P>
<P>
   Carlson provides these tips for bargain-hunting among stocks
that have crashed for cause:
</P>
<P>
   -- Invest in those with clean finances. It often takes time for
companies to turn around. Companies with lots of cash and little
debt have the ability to weather the storm.
</P>
<P>
   -- Choose stocks with restructuring possibilities. It may
require a special event to get a crashed stock going. A firm with
diversified business interests, for example, has the ability to
generate excitement by announcing a restructuring or asset sale.
</P>
<P>
   -- New management often signals a turn. The hiring of a new
president or chief executive is often the time to re-examine an
out-of-favor stock.
</P>
<P>
   -- When investing in depressed stocks, it's always a good sign
to see corporate insiders betting on a turnaround by buying stock.
</P>
<P>
   -- Looking at a chart of a stock's price movement is often
useful in determining the best time to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, it's better to buy a crashed stock after it's been
trading in a relatively narrow price range _ perhaps 5 percent from
the top of the range to the bottom _ for at least three months. At
that point, investors have some level of comfort that perhaps the
worst is behind the company.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
