<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-GASTOCKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Imnet quarter's leading gainer among Georgia stocks
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The secret to success in the third quarter among Georgia stocks
was to own shares of companies attractive to other corporations, or
which do little or no business overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Imnet Systems (IMNT), which reached a deal in late July to be
acquired by HBO &AMP; Co. (HBOC), was the leading gainer among state
stocks in the third quarter. It rose 79.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring Enterprises (MSPG), riding a wave of Internet
interest and three straight profitable quarters, rose 21 percent
for the quarter. It remains the biggest gainer year-to-date among
stocks trading for more than $2, with a gain of 270 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also claiming noticeable gains were two health-care-related
stocks: Serologicals (SERO) and Immucor (BLUD).
</P>
<P>
   Serologicals, whose fiscal first-quarter earnings jumped 52
percent and its second-quarter results climbed 38 percent, saw its
stock rise nearly 17 percent in the latest quarter. The company
provides human antibody-based products and services.
</P>
<P>
   Immucor announced an acquisition, won Food and Drug
Administration clearance to sell its ABS2000 blood test instrument
in the United States, and increased the size of its stock
repurchase program. The stock rose 12.2 percent in the
July-September period.
</P>
<P>
   Two companies with communications in common also rose.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth (BLS) gained 12.1 percent in the quarter, while Cox
Communications (COX), one of the country's largest cable operators,
added 12.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The strong economy in the Southeast and its relative insulation
from overseas problems has helped BellSouth. Cox Communications,
meanwhile, has begun to offer telephone service, digital television
and Internet access in some of its markets. Cox Communications is
controlled by Cox Enterprises Inc., which owns The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Mapics (MAPX) scored a gain of a little over 12 percent, as the
software company's revenue and earnings growth won notice on Wall
Street. Its products are designed to help mid-size companies boost
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Recovery Group International (PRGX), a company that
provides accounts payable and other recovery audit services, gained
almost 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Synthetic Industries (SIND), which counts itself as the
second-biggest producer of polypropylene fabrics and fibers in the
world, finished the quarter up 11.6 percent. Its products are used
for carpet backing, erosion control and in furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 10 were JDN Realty (JDN) and Flowers
Industries (FLO).
</P>
<P>
   JDN Realty, a shopping mall real estate investment trust, gained
8.7 percent. A number of analysts and money managers have been
suggesting investors look at REITs, because of the yields
available. JDN Realty had a quarter-ending yield of almost 6.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers Industries, up 6.7 percent, has gotten a big boost from
its controling stake in Keebler Foods, and in late September was
upgraded to ``accumulate'' from ``hold'' by Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market's problems showed up in a slowdown in initial
public offerings. Only two Georgia-based companies went public in
the third quarter, according to data from Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   Towne Services (TWNE), which sells electronic processing
products and services to financial services companies, went public
at $8 a share at the end of July. It closed the quarter at $5.50.
</P>
<P>
   BioShield Technologies (BSTI) went public Tuesday at $10 per
share. There was no indication of any trading Wednesday in shares
of the medical technology company.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
