</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-MARKETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Market is going to have to earn its way out of trouble
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably the best thing that can be said about the stock market
is the high valuations everybody complained so much about are not
so high any more.
</P>
<P>
   The price-to-earnings ratio of Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
fell from a record 28.7 in the second quarter to 24.2 at the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
   The price-to-earnings ratio _ P/E _ is the way analysts measure
the value of a stock relative to the per share earnings of the
company that issued it. The ratio measures how many dollars the
investor is willing to pay for a dollar of profit.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the comedown, the S&AMP;P 500's P/E is still above what
it was a year ago _ 22.8 _ and well above the index's long-term
average of about 15 _ what's considered appropriate. And analysts
suggest if the market is to extend the bullish rise that began in
the early 1980's and accelerated in the '90s, then stock prices
must get more in line with corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   However, if third-quarter earnings turn out better than most
analysts anticipate, that could set the stage for a stock market
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big ``if.''
</P>
<P>
   Most analysts contend the eight-year bull market propelled stock
prices so high it will take more than the summer and fall market
drop to make them right.
</P>
<P>
   And even if that weren't the case, the chances corporate profits
will be very strong any time soon are regarded by analysts as slim
and none.
</P>
<P>
   That's because U.S. corporations find themselves in a bind.
Earnings growth can't accelerate much until revenue growth does.
And for lots of reasons _ especially competition from Asia _ U.S.
companies are constrained from raising prices and therefore
increasing revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since late 1997, many commodity and natural resource companies
have suffered precipitous drops in pricing power, much of it due to
the crisis that had begun in Asia in the early part of last
summer,'' Prudential Securities analyst Greg A. Smith explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Asian crisis no longer an Asian crisis but an Eastern
European-Latin America-Mexico-Canada currency and financial market
crisis, it's difficult to see how companies' pricing power would
improve as we move into 1999,'' Smith added.
</P>
<P>
   That dismal outlook doesn't bode well for the stock market,
although not all analysts are so pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson-Humphrey strategist Robert S. Robbins argues earnings
are earnings, and unless they turn into losses, ``declining
earnings'' won't be that much of a drag on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   But the third-quarter earnings reports will be a big pill for
investors to swallow, according to First Call, which tracks
analysts forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston-based organization said earnings for S&AMP;P-500
companies are expected to post the first year-over-year decline
since late 1991, when the economy was still emerging from a
recession.
</P>
<P>
   But Robbins said year-over-year comparisons should begin looking
more favorable starting with the fourth quarter, since it was in
that quarter of 1997 that Asia's problems began slowing profit
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The First Call consensus for 1998 and 1999 is for annual
earnings growth of 4.5 percent and 6.4 percent, respectively, vs.
9.3 percent in 1997. Robbins noted this is subject to further
reduction, but he also added analysts' estimates are often high,
especially when expectations are weakening.
</P>
<P>
   All this uncertainty makes it difficult to predict how long the
current state of affairs in the market will last, analysts say. Is
the worst of the selling over, almost over or not over by a long
shot?
</P>
<P>
   One of the most frequent forecasts from Wall Street gurus is
stocks are still too pricey for the selling to be over, but they
have dropped low enough to be attractive to buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The result will be a trading range for the rest of the year at
least, typically defined as 7,000 to 7,500 on the low side to 8,000
to 8,500 on the high side, with the potential to break out of the
range on either side.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe investors face a period of adjustment
because a fundamental change has occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with most of the 1990s _ especially the 1995-1997
period _ the future will be marked by slower, and historically more
normal, annual earnings growth, stock returns and economic growth,
the analysts think.
</P>
<P>
   The longer-term fundamentals are still favorable, however, and
analysts think stocks will return at least 5 percent through the
first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In this century, stocks have returned about 10 percent per year,
on a compounded basis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
