</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-PROFITS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expectations for third-quarter earnings turn sour
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The profit outlook for U.S. companies going into the final
quarter of 1998 does not look good.
</P>
<P>
   First Call, a Boston-based research group that tracks analysts'
earnings forecasts, said Wall Street looks for the earnings of
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies to decline at least 1.4 percent in
the third quarter, and possibly 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the first year-over-year decline since the third
quarter of 1991, when the economy was just coming out of a
recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Asia is the main factor in all of this,'' said
Charles L. Hill, research director. ``What originally had been
viewed as something that most people thought wouldn't have a
significant effect on U.S. earnings now may be headed for at least
a three-quarters problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnings rose only 3.8 percent in the first quarter, 3.5 percent
in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said analysts' fourth-quarter projections of 10 percent
earnings growth are excessive and will shrink as the months pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would expect that fourth-quarter earnings growth would come
down to the low single digits,'' said Hill.
</P>
<P>
   First Call's annual projection for earnings growth in 1998 is
4.3 percent vs. 11 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts become more optimistic as they look ahead to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus estimates for the first and second quarters are
15.1 percent and 19.4 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
