<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0317 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0609 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IQ-ROUNDTABLE-COX     10-05 3044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IQ-ROUNDTABLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money managers keeping wary eye on global turmoil
 &HT;    By David McNaughton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With turmoil in the world's stock markets as a backdrop, five
money managers gathered Sept. 21 to share their thoughts about the
state of affairs and offer their recommendations to long-term
investors. Cautious to a degree about the near term, they were
generally optimistic about long-range prospects. And one theme kept
surfacing in their discussion with Cox writer David McNaughton: The
sharp drop in stock prices has created bargains not seen in a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Let's start with the hardest question. What are you telling
your clients when they ask if we're in a bear market, how long it's
going to last, and what's going to be driving the market?
</P>
<P>
   Sandra W. Majors (Sandra W. Majors, Inc.): I, as a professional,
can't answer the question of whether we are in a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   I think if we just look at our own country, our own situation,
we have enough to deal with, with all the unsettling news in
Washington. But, unfortunately, we can't operate in a vacuum, and
we have a very unsettling foreign situation kind of tumbling around
us, from Russia to problems in South America, to Japan, to other
areas that once we could look to and not feel their problems.
</P>
<P>
   Until we get a read on how earnings are going to come out in the
third quarter, it will be difficult to tell if we end up in a bear
market, or the duration of that bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Z. Allen (Globalt, Inc.): I think earnings are the big
issue. If you would have had us here a few months ago, we would
have been very worried about expectations. Now, earnings
expectations have come way down. And for the first time in as long
as we can remember, what is referred to as the bottom-up estimates
for the Standard &AMP; Poor's (index companies) created by individual
analysts are lower than the top-down estimates for the S&AMP;P for this
year by strategists.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good sign that reality has seeped in. We think a lot of
that has been priced in stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense to us that the market probably would need to
spend time repairing some of the vast internal damage by at least
revisiting the 7,400-7,500 level of the Dow. But it's not out of
the question that the market could go back to where it was on gray
Monday last year, which got us down to 6,900. That was a cathartic
point in the market, and if that happens again, that would not be
significantly below were we are now, and it would probably further
improve the health of the market for the intermediate term.
</P>
<P>
   Charles B. Morris, Jr. (Morris Investment Counsel): Are we in a
bear market? It's a yes and no, because there are two markets. One
market is the Nifty Fifty, the Microsofts, Dells, Ciscos. And we're
not there.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the market? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   How long will this last? We can't answer that. It's driven by
the turmoil in the international markets, which is a function of
the lack of currency stability.
</P>
<P>
   Nola Maddox Falcone (Evergreen Asset Management Corp.): I agree
with Charlie. The level of the market is really contingent on the
speed of the major industrialized nations in working cooperatively
to remove the panic from the international currency markets. As
long as there is chaos in the financial structure, there will be
volatility in the markets. The key is the banking situation in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Scott C. Satterwhite (Artisan Partners): With respect to what's
going on in the emerging markets and what you're seeing in the
economy relative to corporate earnings, that's sort of Round 1. The
effects are the loss of export markets, import competition and
lower commodity prices. It's hard to imagine those effects are
going to get a lot, lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   You're starting to move now into Round 2. You're starting to see
some layoffs at some of the affected industries and capital
spending cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, what all these changes mean to individual investors is
that we are in a period where the earnings environment is tough.
It's certainly a lot harder for a company to make money today than
it was three months ago. And it's probably not going to be any
easier three and six months hence.
</P>
<P>
   There's no reason to be negative on a three- to five-year view.
But getting there might not be as much fun as it was in 1995
getting to 1998. That was a good three-year period. This is going
to be a tougher three-year period. But there are investment
opportunities, as there are always investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   This is a much better time to be a three- to five-year investor
than it was a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Q:Generally, you as money managers seem optimistic about the
longer term. What positives for the market do you see?
</P>
<P>
   Falcone: U.S. banks are in the best shape they have been in, in
any crisis, for a very long time, because of the consolidation that
has occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The inflation issue is positive for us, the low inflation.
Another positive is technological innovation. If we continue to
have technological innovation, that will kind of keep us from
falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   Another positive is the merger and acquisition trend.
</P>
<P>
   Majors: Long term, definitely we're all very positive on the
market. What I think we're talking about is shorter- term, possibly
intermediate-term (caution), because we don't know how all of this
will unfold. We don't know, if Brazil defaults on its debt, how
that will affect the rest of South America. We don't know what will
happen if we find out, in earnings from some of our domestic banks,
that we have more Bankers Trusts out there. We just don't know the
full extent of the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Allen: A primary silver lining is that U.S. companies, because
they are cash-rich, have been in a position to strike bargains for
the last year in buying assets, in buying entire businesses, in
gaining market share. They are facing weakened competitors, and in
many cases they have lost some of their competition altogether
through the turmoil that has affected other regions.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of this, we think that you can look down a long list
of U.S. companies, spanning all economic sectors, where we'll be in
a very good position, longer term.
</P>
<P>
   Morris: It's hard to say if I'm optimistic or pessimistic, in
the setting of the international situation, because who can predict
whether Japan, Russia, the United States, Germany, whoever, will
get their political and economic leadership acts together?
</P>
<P>
   But if it gets down to individual securities or types of
securities in the U.S. financial markets, there are some tremendous
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Q:So what securities are you recommending to investors with a
long-term view?
</P>
<P>
   Morris: For those who are interested in getting a 5, 6, 7
percent yield up front and want diversification in the portfolio
from growth equities, and want that income, maybe also want the
securities for defensive purposes, and also some attractive total
returns, you can go into the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to go there. Either directly, owning the
individual securities, or though a mutual fund. For the individual,
in most cases it's difficult to get the diversification and the
liquidity, plus minimal transaction costs, by going to direct
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   So that leads you into mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   I strongly recommend going into just Treasurys, and there is a
group of funds that has Treasury-only mutual funds, and that's
Vanguard. Coincidentally, these are no-load funds and have the
lowest fees available.
</P>
<P>
   They have a short-term Treasury fund, an intermediate-term
Treasury fund and a long-term Treasury fund.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to own individual securities, I strongly recommend
going to the Treasury Direct program. You can get any maturity for
as little as $1,000, and in $1,000 increments. I strongly recommend
investors go the Web, the site is http://
</P>
<P>
   www.publicdebt.treas.gov. It tells you what you need to know
about the Treasury Direct program.
</P>
<P>
   The only other sector I would suggest investors consider in the
fixed-income world would be municipal bonds, which are roughly in a
3.5-5 percent yield range. And there, unless you have a
multimillion-dollar portfolio, I would suggest going to mutual
funds.
</P>
<P>
   There are some stocks where investors can get 6-7 percent
yields. Two are electric utilities. One is Ameren. Another is
Interstate Energy. Also, there's AGL Resources.
</P>
<P>
   In the real estate investment trust world, there are many, many
high-yielding equities. There's one based in Augusta _ Merry Land
(&AMP; Investment). It is being acquired by a larger REIT, Equity
Residential Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Falcone: We look at stocks that really have already been in a
bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerages are now in a consolidating mode, and I wouldn't be
surprised, somewhere down the pike, if A.G. Edwards consolidated
with someone. It's (selling) for about two times book (value), and
the most recent takeovers in the brokerage industry have been
around three times book.
</P>
<P>
   There's Raymond James. I don't really think that's a takeover
(candidate), but it is doing a big (stock) buyback. PaineWebber is
another one that we think is a likely takeover.
</P>
<P>
   We bought a position in SunTrust (Banks), which we like a lot.
It's selling for a little over two times book. It's always rumored
as a takeover.
</P>
<P>
   We're always looking for technology innovations, and we like
Scientific-Atlanta a lot. They have the most sophisticated TV
set-top digital interactive boxes. They're ahead of their
competition, and they've got the orders now on the docket, and they
are ramping up in October from 7,000 units a week to 20,000 units a
week.
</P>
<P>
   There's also Caterpillar. It got (beaten down) because of the
concern about Asia, but they are going to benefit from the highway
bill. They've done some interesting restructuring, and they also
have some buyback of shares.
</P>
<P>
   Union Pacific is one that's really in the doghouse. That's
something you buy and put away for a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Saks, which is the (renamed) Proffitt's, is a great value and
growth stock combined.
</P>
<P>
   And Williams. They have magnificent management. They do
pipelines, and they're also into fiber-optic communications.
</P>
<P>
   If you just look at undervalued assets, there's Atlantic
Richfield. Cabot Oil &AMP; Gas is another one. My calculation of the
value of oil and gas in the ground, minus the debt, is $26 (for
Cabot). It's selling at $16.
</P>
<P>
   The last one, benefiting from the merger and acquisition trend,
is Mercantile Bancorporation in St. Louis. It's selling for about 2
1/2 times book (value). We think it could go to 3 1/2 to 4 times
book if it gets sold.
</P>
<P>
   Allen: We think there is much appeal within large caps and the
upper tier of mid-caps. So we are not recommending delving into
small-cap equities, nor do we think it's necessary, given the
opportunities that have just been presented to us.
</P>
<P>
   We want to have brand names, to the extend the brand is nearly
synonymous with the product, like American Express is with credit
cards, as Xerox is in duplication, as Citicorp is. Also an
interesting idea is Tiffany, because of the way they restructured
their product line to adapt to all of the markets where they are
represented.
</P>
<P>
   Within the information age group of companies, there are Cisco
Systems, Microsoft, Time Warner, Computer Sciences and Walt Disney,
which is targeting its Internet expansion to perhaps 10 to 15 years
down the road when now-young people, who are very adept at the
Internet, are going to be using the Internet for other purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Also, there are companies that are well positioned, relative to
the demographics in the U.S., and especially the U.S. baby boomers,
and also to the aging populations in the other industrialized
countries.
</P>
<P>
   That would include Guidant and Arterial Vascular Engineering,
Baxter International and (Eli) Lilly, which maybe hasn't gotten as
much press as Pfizer. Also, AFLAC, which is participating in the
increased health care needs here, and also in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In financial services, I certainly agree with the comments that
Nola made. We would extend that to include Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, as well as State Street Bank.
</P>
<P>
   And in the leisure area, getting past any near-term concerns
about a slowdown in the U.S. economy, we would think with any kind
of a longer-term outlook, you could look at AMR as well as Delta
(Air Lines). Disney and Time Warner also are leisure providers and
dominant companies.
</P>
<P>
   And in personal care products, a stock that has been recently
put into the bargain camp: Gillette.
</P>
<P>
   Majors: On the bond side, because I don't see the world
situation calming down much in the near future, I could almost make
a strong case for the use of Treasurys. I would approach it in a
way that could be very beneficial for people who are averse to
guessing whether to go to the long-term end of the market or the
short end, or the intermediate. I would ladder (the Treasurys)
between, say, two years and eight years, putting some at two,
three, four, five, six, seven, or eight, if people are in the
fixed-income arena.
</P>
<P>
   On the equities side, I stick more to the large-cap and
intermediate-cap names. A few of the names I had written down
include American Home Products in the drug area. I look at where
companies have traded relative to the market. It's trading near its
relative P/E.
</P>
<P>
   Merck is another one. Merck spends almost 25 percent of its
earnings on research and development and continues to crank out
drug after drug after drug.
</P>
<P>
   In the food processing area, a company I currently like is
Earthgrains, the third-largest fresh-baked goods producer in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   In business services, one of the companies I've been buying over
the last year is Equifax.
</P>
<P>
   And in the financial services industry, I also like the
brokerage industry. T. Rowe Price is at a 22 P/E and is slightly
below its historical P/E right now. The return on equity for that
company is 30 percent, they manage $99 billion, they have 70
different mutual funds, and half of those mutual funds are
represented by retirement funds.
</P>
<P>
   Satterwhite: I guess in the world of stocks, bonds and cash, I
think you should probably still own less than an average amount of
stocks and probably less than an average amount of bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The stock portfolio, I would think, would be slanted toward the
small-cap end of the market, where the hard values are, and
whatever cash you have kicking around, my sense would be, you would
wait for better opportunities in big-cap stocks.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of opportunities in the market, I classify them three
ways.
</P>
<P>
   One is what I call ground-zero stocks. These are the stocks of
companies that are absolutely in the way of all the problems _ the
commodity-oriented stocks, companies that are being hit by import
competition, companies that have lost export markets because of the
Asian situation, where the earnings pressure is currently the
greatest.
</P>
<P>
   In the oil and gas area, (there are) Synder Oil and Forest Oil.
Both of these are small-cap exploration and production companies.
They both sell at or below their net asset values, which would be
the value of their oil and gas in the ground, less debt.
</P>
<P>
   Another ground-zero industry is semiconductor equipment. There
is a huge glut in production capacity. So they've not only been
slogging through an inventory glut, now you have loss of market as
well.
</P>
<P>
   You have the opportunity to buy companies at reasonably large
discounts to hard book value. And these are companies that have
relevant product lines, product lines that are going to be needed
for the next generation of semiconductor manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley Group is one I own. FSI International is another.
</P>
<P>
   A third area is steel, and this one is a little spookier because
you don't necessarily have the wind at your back to as great an
extent, I believe, as you do with semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   But nonetheless, I think these stocks have been abused,
particularly since June or so.
</P>
<P>
   One that I think you can support on an asset value basis, LTV,
is a typical sort of integrated steel manufacturer. What maybe
separates it a little is they have some interesting assets that are
not related to the integrated steel operation. They have $4 in cash
on the balance sheet, and they have $5 per share of assets that
aren't integrated steel assets. They own, in a joint venture, the
Trico mini-mill operation in Alabama. They own a metal building
(systems) company, and they also have a joint venture with
Cleveland-Cliffs, on an iron venture that sells into the mini-mill
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Another idea is Schnitzer Steel Industries, which is primarily a
scrap processor, probably the best-positioned scrap processor in
America. They own a lot of great gathering and processing assets.
And it is probably in the best position to supply foreign mills.
Now, the trouble is, the foreign mills don't want any scrap. But if
you look out there long enough, over a three- to five-year period,
we'll probably set some settling out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   A second pocket of value, maybe it's a canyon of value, is in
the whole microcap area.
</P>
<P>
   One we recently started buying is Harding Lawson Associates
Group. It's a hazardous waste consulting and remediation company.
This industry has been under a lot of pressure for a number of
years due to too much supply in the marketplace. But consolidation
has begun in the industry. So there's some interesting
value-realizing events going on.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy Harding Lawson for $6. The current assets, minus all
the liabilities, is $7. There's $3 of cash on the balance sheet, no
debt, and the company is not discouraging anybody from believing
that 85 cents (per share) is next year's earnings.
</P>
<P>
   CFC International is another one. This is a company that
manufactures relatively complex chemical coatings. It manufactures
holographic products. You see its holographs on the Coor's box. You
see them on a tube of Aquafresh and some of the other toothpastes.
</P>
<P>
   Its coatings go on ready-to-assemble furniture. It also makes
the magnetic strip on the back of your credit card. A great line of
products and a very high return on equity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
