<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hitching on to a trend good long-term strategy
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A short-term defense is not the only strategy investment
advisers recommend for a down market.
</P>
<P>
   Since you're probably rethinking your stock holdings anyway, why
not look at stock selection on the basis of ``themes,'' or
longer-term trends that should hold up well into the 21st century?
</P>
<P>
   John M. Eade, research director of Argus Research, advocates
thematic investing geared to trends unlikely to be affected by
economic cycles or market uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   He cites five themes:
</P>
<P>
   -- Bank consolidation. This especially involves super-regionals
such as NationsBank and First Union.
</P>
<P>
   -- Deregulation in communication. The Telecommunications Act of
1996 will open new competition for well-positioned companies such
as Bell Atlantic and GTE, its planned merger partner, MCI WorldCom
and AirTouch Communications.
</P>
<P>
   -- Technology and productivity. Computer technology has enabled
the economy to grow without inflation. Improvements are ahead in
semiconductors, software, communications equipment. Compaq
Computer, Intel and Oracle are cited here.
</P>
<P>
   -- Demographics. Baby boomers are in their peak earning and
saving years, which is positive for consumer service firms:
financial, leisure, retail. Home Depot, Marriott International,
McGraw-Hill, Sears, Roebuck and Starbucks are mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   -- Rising health care costs. This goes hand in hand with the
baby boom trend. Breakthroughs have occurred in pharmaceuticals
aimed at previously unmet medical needs. Among companies mentioned:
Bristol-Myers Squibb, Johnson &AMP; Johnson and Warner Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
