A0611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN06-COX     10-05 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``S'' for sufficent, not small
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I asked the clerk where I might find the garment in
question, she muttered something and raised a big arm toward the
far end of the store.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was she said failed to register, but I headed that
way, past the camping gear, past the football jerseys, past the
hockey sticks, toward a sign that said ``Lingerie.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course. I should have known.
</P>
<P>
   I'd never heard one called that before, but it had been a while
since I went shopping for a jock strap.
</P>
<P>
   I should have known is right. No jock straps were to be found
among the lingerie, nothing even close. Only frills that wouldn't
be up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   In shirts I wear a 14 1/2-inch neck and a 32-inch sleeve. In
sport jackets a 38 short. In slacks a 30-inch waist (and holding)
with a 30-inch length. I looked for something that said Waist 30.
</P>
<P>
   On reflection I realized there's more to a jock strap than
simply the waist. But I didn't know how they were measuring it
these days. Mass? Volume?
</P>
<P>
   It turns out it was quite simple. At this store, at least, the
jock straps (they were around the corner from the catcher's mitts
and face masks) came in four sizes: regular, large, XL and I think
I actually saw a few that said XXL. Pick which one you are.
</P>
<P>
   I knew I didn't need the XXL and I didn't need the XL either. I
didn't even need the large. It's no big deal. I'm a regular guy in
every other respect, so it seemed reasonable that I'd be regular in
this one, too.
</P>
<P>
   But I wondered: What if I did need a, well, small jock strap. I
speak hypothetically, of course. ( Small? Are you kidding?) What
if?
</P>
<P>
   A man could of course always go to the boys' department, and
from there to his therapist. The boys department did have large,
medium and, for the little guys, small. ``I'm buying my boy an
athletic supporter,'' he could tell the clerk. ``Um, I think large
should be about right.''
</P>
<P>
   What man wants to be a Small? You can say small is beautiful and
less is more, but regular is better.
</P>
<P>
   I've noticed it's the same with pizzas. No one wants it small.
You're wondering what pizzas have to do with athletic supporters.
More than you'd think. I don't know anyone who has the trouble we
do ordering a silly pizza, with one child wanting extra cheese and
nothing else, another insisting on sausage, pepperoni and ham, the
first clamoring for Papa John's, the second for Pizza Hut and the
chump paying the bill holding out for Rocky's. It gets complicated.
</P>
<P>
   The other night, after Pizza Hut swept Rocky's two heads to no
tails and then bested Papa's John's in a disputed best of five, I
said to the woman taking our order, ``Tell you what. Give us one
small with ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have small,'' she said in a hurried voice. ``We have
medium and large.''
</P>
<P>
   Phones were jangling in the background. I could see her, phone
to her ear, tired, people shouting in five directions. I didn't
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you have a medium if you have a large but no small?
What's your frame of reference?'' (These things really irritate
me.)
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it is. What would you like on that medium?''
</P>
<P>
   You don't give logic lessons to the woman taking your pizza
order, and you don't ask the guy selling jock straps why no man
needs a small. Unless he shops in the boys' department, a man has
the comfort of knowing he is at least regular, yessir.
</P>
<P>
   It's like the Bentley automobile. It sells for well into six
figures and the company won't tell the car magazines how much
horsepower its big engine produces. Let Mercedes-Benz and the rest
crow about their numbers. Bentley merely says, with a confident
sniff, ``S'ficient.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an idea. XXL for the circus sized, XL for what every man
wants to imagine, L for some, M for the many and the medium and S
for the Sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the regular fits fine, just fine. A little loose,
but I think they run large. I'm sure it'll shrink after it's
washed.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
