<HEADER>
A0615 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN-HNS     10-05 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS TRY TO WORKOUT COMPROMISE WITH WHITE HOUSE TO AVOID
GOVERNMENT SHUTDOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With only four days left before Congress' scheduled
adjournment for the year, Republican leaders are trying to work out
spending compromises with the White House to avoid a government
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   Although some conservative Republicans still hope to attach
anti-abortion language and other controversial riders to the nine
pending appropriations bills, their leaders are pushing to avoid an
an election-eve showdown with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``There shouldn't be any government shutdown,'' Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time he charged that the Clinton administration
may try to force a shutdown in hopes of using it to the Democrats'
political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Lott suggested that congressional Democrats, eager to shift
public attention away from the Monica Lewinsky scandal, have been
urging the president to veto some of the spending measures to
highlight their differences with Republicans on issues such as
education.
</P>
<P>
   That concern was also raised by House Speaker Newt Gingrich,
R-Ga., in a meeting with GOP members. He urged them to refrain from
loading up spending bills with favored amendments so as not to give
Clinton ``any excuse'' to follow through on threats to veto some
appropriations measures.
</P>
<P>
   Most members agreed with him, and late last week the House
passed a $56 billion farm bill after stripping out language that
would have prohibited the use in this country of the
French-developed abortion pill RU-486.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough thing for some members to do because they
feel so strongly about it,'' said one Republican leadership aide.
``But it shows how we're trying to send him clean bills so that he
doesn't have any excuse not to sign them.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who still enjoys high job approval ratings despite talk
of impeachment, has signaled his displeasure with a number of
spending bills over matters ranging from abortion and environmental
language to the size of the emergency aid package included in the
farm bill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with Democratic congressional leaders Monday to
discuss the appropriations process. Afterward he threatened again
to veto legislation that ignores his proposal to hire more teachers
and build new schools or that includes a GOP proposal to cut taxes
by $80 billion.
</P>
<P>
   He called on Republicans to finish their work before the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is running short,'' he said. ``Congress has important
work yet to do.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., charged that
Republicans have already ``wasted the entire year and have left the
heavy lifting'' on spending measures until the final week of the
session.
</P>
<P>
   The appearance by Clinton, Gephardt and Senate Minority Leader
Tom Daschle, D-S.D., was designed to put pressure on Republicans,
many of whom are still fighting among themselves over various
spending measures in the closing days of the session.
</P>
<P>
   For example, differences still remain between Republicans over a
bill designed to increase competition in the financial services
industry. Texas Sen. Phil Gramm has threatened a filibuster against
it because of concerns about the impact on local lending
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   A Gramm filibuster would also interrupt a tight schedule that
Senate and House leaders are trying to impose as members rush to
complete their legislative business to hit the campaign trail
before the Nov. 3 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his concern over some measures, the White House denied
Monday that Clinton would like to provoke another fight with
Congress that would lead to a shutdown like the two that occurred
in late 1995 and early 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in no one's interest to shut the government down,'' White
House spokesman Joe Lockhart said, adding that the White House has
``no intention or policy of shutting the government down.''
</P>
<P>
   The shutdown three years ago turned out to be a nightmare for
Republican lawmakers, who most Americans ended up blaming for the
budget deadlock that kept federal agencies and departments closed
for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart called on Congress to finish its work on the current
spending bills, noting that internal divisions within the
Republican majority's own membership rather than with Democrats had
caused many of the delays.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Congress has passed only four of the 13 major
appropriations measures for the 1999 fiscal year, which began on
Oct 1. The four measures approved include funding for defense,
military construction, energy and water resources, and legislative
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders acknowledged nearly two weeks ago that there
was virtually no chance Congress would complete its work on the
remaining spending bills before Oct. 1. To keep the government
open, the lawmakers passed a temporary spending measure that was
signed by the president. But it expires Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that there is little chance of finishing work on the
appropriations bills before then, Republican leaders are likely to
wrap at least five of them, and maybe more, into one large omnibus
measure that can then be sent to the president.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton might accept a large stopgap
package that would temporarily fund the government until a new
Congress returns next year to deal with left over appropriations
But Lockhart said it would be better for the nation if the Congress
that's now operating ``in overtime'' not be allowed to get ``more
time'' to finish up its legislative business. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
