<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A ``ER'' clone makes it way to the ``Star Trek: Voyager''
network
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have to love UPN. It's out there flailing away, tossing out
preposterous sitcoms and dramas, hoping with all its might that
some show _ any show _ will stick.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's newest example is ``Mercy Point'' (9 p.m. EDT on UPN).
</P>
<P>
   It wants to be an ``ER'' clone way, way _ way _ out there in
space, boldly going where no man but Capt. Kirk fears to tread.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Point, you see, is a hospital ship floating somewhere out
there at the edge of the known galaxy and full of doctors, nurses,
psychologists and, you knew this was coming, aliens. You can spot
the aliens because they're the ones with big bulbous heads or 16
fingers and tentacles for feet.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Point is a serious place. Serious serious. It's work,
work, work.
</P>
<P>
   There's lots of official hospital techno-jargon involving hemo
scans, parallel linkage and o-stat processors.
</P>
<P>
   We don't exactly know what all those are, but don't they sound
cool?
</P>
<P>
   Our crew of doctors _ even the ones with tentacles for feet _
are always saving lives no matter what the lifeform.
</P>
<P>
   A pregnant woman's in serious jeopardy. No problem. It's time
for a zero gravity operation that yanks that fetus from her body
and places it inside a warm, comfy and gross-looking artificial
womb.
</P>
<P>
   And this show's full of life's age-old ticks. Sisters who can't
get along. Doctors whose former lovers show up. Lustful hallway
lip-locks. And, of course, a killer virus on the loose.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, somebody's about to go into a peroxyl phase
reversal.
</P>
<P>
   We don't know what that is either, but doesn't it sound cool?
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Moshea meet Brandy
</P>
<P>
   Told she looks like singing sensation Brandy, high school kid
Moesha Mitchell (played by Brandy) acts put out. ``Please ,'' she
says. ``I don't look like Brandy ... I'm cuter than her.'' But the
two finally meet backstage at a concert, eye each other
suspiciously, then decide neither looks like the other. That's the
stunt that kicks off the third season of UPN's ``Moesha'' (8
tonight EDT on UPN), which starts with the 17-year-old title
character trying to figure out the right thing to do when her
college-age boyfriend invites her to a cabin for the weekend, then
ends with Brandy performing ``Have You Ever'' from her
platinum-selling album ``Never Say Never'' for Moesha and her
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _Drew Jubera, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
