<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Dawn' sifts the midnight of Savannah
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long before John Berendt made Savannah, Georgia a major tourist
attraction with ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil,''
another outsider literally put the coastal city on the map. In the
October Smithsonian ($4), a fascinating excerpt from Patricia
O'Toole's book, ``Dawn in the Garden of Good and Evil,'' describes
James Oglethorpe's thwarted attempts to provide a haven for the
poor from London's overcrowded slums. The English aristocrat's
solution was to ship them off to the New World, give them tools,
food and shelter, and let them produce materials such as raw silk
for England. And, to provide for the moral and physical well-being
of the settlement, slavery and hard liquor would be outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   Oglethorpe's plan was well-intentioned, but he didn't take human
nature into account. The settlers used every opportunity to sneak
across the border into South Carolina, where liquor was plentiful.
As they drank, they saw what a luxurious life the Carolina planters
had with slaves doing all the hard work. Within a few years,
poverty in Savannah was rampant and slavery was finally introduced
as a means of attracting investors. By 1748, Oglethorpe's dream was
just a shadow.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEWSWEEKLIES: It's difficult to imagine, but there is not a
single picture of Bill Clinton, Monica Lewinsky or Kenneth Starr on
the covers of the three big news magazines. There's still plenty of
coverage of the Tripp tapes inside, but apparently the editors
decided the public was ready for other topics.
</P>
<P>
   If anything will distract us from the White House scandal, it's
the economy. Maybe that's why Newsweek ($2.95) features a
doom-and-gloom cover story on ``The Crash of '99.'' It doesn't have
to happen, says economist Robert J. Samuelson, but it might.
</P>
<P>
   Time ($2.95), meanwhile, offers a compelling look at a week in
the life of Duke University's Medical Center. Equipped with pagers
provided by Duke, reporters and photographers went on rounds with
the doctors and examined everything from the effects of managed
care to the role of religion in a patient's recovery.
</P>
<P>
   At U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($2.95), writer Charles W. Petit
digs into our history to discover that the New World may be 20,000
years older than experts thought. Who were the first Americans?
Some archaeologists are challenging the theory that they were
fur-clad big-game hunters who crossed over the Bering Land Bridge
to hunt giant bisons and wooly mammoths.
</P>
<P>
   OH, JACKIE: Even in death, Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis will not
be allowed to rest in peace. In a steamy excerpt from Edward
Klein's new book, ``Just Jackie: Her Private Years,'' People
($2.79) reveals the newly widowed first lady desperately seeking
comfort in the arms of a Secret Service agent and beginning an
affair with John Carl Warnecke, the architect who designed JFK's
grave site.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK READS: The New Yorker's ($3) David Remnick, author of a
soon-to-be-published biography of Muhammad Ali (``King of the
World,'' Random House, $25), eloquently describes how a young boxer
named Cassius Clay invented himself as the most charismatic athlete
of the century. ... So you think Bill Gates is the richest man in
America? Not according to American Heritage ($4.95). The Microsoft
magnate ranks fifth behind John D. Rockefeller, Andrew Carnegie,
Cornelius Vanderbilt and John Jacob Astor on the list of the
richest Americans of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
