<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES FINANCIAL LEADERS TO HALT SPREAD OF GLOBAL ECONOMIC
CRISIS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, pressing his proposal for new
emergency aid to fiscally faltering nations, called on
international financial leaders Monday to ``do whatever it takes''
to protect against the spread of the global economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that as formidable as the challenge may seem,
it is well within our grasp,'' Clinton said at the beginning of a
U.S.-sponsored meeting of the finance ministers and central bankers
of 26 rich and developing nations. After his speech, Clinton began
private consultations with the group.
</P>
<P>
   The president's remarks come after a generally noncommittal
international response to his call last week for new emergency loan
authority to shore up the economies of nations that face being
engulfed in the international fiscal crisis and cannot service
their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sought to make a virtue of the richest nations' promise
to study his proposal. He said he was ``pleased to hear'' that the
Group of Seven leading industrial democracies and the management
committee of the International Monetary Fund ``have agreed to look
at ways of strengthening our capacity for stability ... (and) to
help countries ward off financial contagion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must find ways that do not penalize those nations who
follow strong economic policies in times of crisis,'' Clinton said.
``They will minimize the frequency, severity and human cost of the
financial crisis. They will put in place social structures to
protect the most defenseless. And they will promote broad
democratic support which is necessary for economic change.''
</P>
<P>
   The president is scheduled Tuesday to continue his personal
intervention in the growing global economic crisis with an address
at the opening session of the annual meeting of the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, Clinton's chief economic adviser, suggested any
resistance to Clinton's proposal was prompted by the need to review
the plan as part of a complicated overhaul of international
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the long-term structural reforms that are
going to be very difficult and complex, and that will take
significant time to develop,'' Sperling said.
</P>
<P>
   Financier George Soros, the billionaire currency trader, said
Monday that the U.S. proposal was ``on the right track, but he
contended financial leaders from the wealthiest nations should have
settled differences on the U.S. plan rather than promising to
explore it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those people should have been shut into a room and hammered
this thing out and come out with a decision,'' Soros said.
</P>
<P>
   Some international economic leaders indicated they were
withholding judgment on the Clinton initiative until the president
can settle his dispute with the House of Representatives over a
delayed U.S. payment of $18 billion to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is insistence by the Republican-controlled House to
deny funds to international agencies advocating family planning
that includes abortion. Sperling said Clinton would not back off
his opposition to the prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers said the dispute
harmed the U.S. ``capacity to respond to the current crisis, our
capacity to maintain confidence ... in the current crisis and our
capacity to exercise influence on the IMF and the monetary system
of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. markets did not respond well to the indecision of the
international economic leaders. The Dow Jones industrial average,
which had been off more than 230 points in midsession Monday, ended
down 58.45, or 0.8 percent, at 7,726.24.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's addresses are part of a flurry of economic
developments surrounding the annual meeting of the 182-nation IMF.
The group's policy-making body said Sunday that the global economic
outlook has ``worsened considerably'' over the last six months.
</P>
<P>
   But even with that despairing assessment, the IMF interim
committee signaled it could not settle on a firm recommended course
of action. The committee noted only that the spreading economic
crisis ``lends urgency'' to calls for strengthening the
international financial system.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced Clinton plans to visit Japan, the Far
East's faltering economic linchpin, in late November after
attending the annual meeting of the Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation forum in Malaysia. Clinton will also visit South Korea,
another nation hit hard by the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Summers renewed the U.S. call for the Japanese to ``take strong
steps to stimulate their economy, to bring fiscal stimulus on line
rapidly and to work to strengthen their banking system.''
</P>
<P>
   On another international economic front, the Clinton
administration expressed relief that President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso of Brazil won a second four-year term in an election
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, Latin America's largest economy, soon may need an
emergency line of credit from international institutions worth
about $30 billion, but Summers said ``the international community
greatly respects what has taken place in Brazil and is certainly
prepared to be supportive of Brazil at this important juncture.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
