<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0678 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LAWYERS-BOS &LR;      10-05 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LAWYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS IN HISTORIC CASE STICK TO THE SCRIPT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Clinton-Offenses)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a casting of lawyers straight from a John
Grisham novel, featuring opposites of the legal profession arguing
the case of a lifetime: for and against an impeachment inquiry of
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   David P. Schippers, a little-known 68-year-old Democrat who once
helped bust up the Chicago mob, was deployed by Republicans on the
House Judiciary Committee as their prosecutor. Democrats countered
with a consummate Washington insider, Abbe Lowell, 46, a frequent
TV talk show guest who once defended House Speaker Jim Wright in an
ethics case before Wright resigned in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no courtroom, and no one was pretending that the
legal fight would be fair and even. The framers of the Constitution
made clear that impeachment _ even while requiring credible
accusations of ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' _ is a political
decision. Republicans control the committee and have made clear for
days that they intend to follow Schippers' recommendation that an
inpeachment inquiry be launched.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers was first on the attack _ and first to stumble.
</P>
<P>
   After repeated assertions of his impartiality, Schippers
inexplicably ended his hour-long argument by offering his personal
views on the case, saying the committee must protect the nation
from ``the winds of evil and tyranny.'' That earned him a rebuke
from the man who hired him, committee Chairman Henry Hyde of
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know he was going to do that,'' a visibly startled
Hyde said in a stage whisper to the ranking Democrat,
Representative John Conyers of Michigan. Hyde then ordered that
Schippers' personal remarks be stricken from the record, an
admonishment that was clearly embarrassing to the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell then argued the Democratic case by employing the
unavoidably awkward defense that Clinton may have lied and acted
improperly but did not commit an impeachable act.
</P>
<P>
   The key difference between the arguments delivered by the two
lawyers was over what constitutes an impeachable offense. Each
cited the vague standard that a president can be impeached for
``high crimes and misdemeanors'' _ to make his case.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers repeatedly said there was ``substantial and credible''
evidence that the president may have committed perjury and
conspired with others to cover up his sexual relationship with
Monica S. Lewinsky. As a result, Schippers declared in a monotone
voice, there is enough evidence of possible impeachable acts to
proceed with an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   At some points, Schippers used legalistic language to poke holes
in Clinton's defense. ``The president described himself as a
non-reciprocating recipient of Miss Lewinsky's services,''
Schippers said, referring to Clinton's insistence that he did not
have sexual relations with Lewinsky even though she performed oral
sex on him.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, while not directly disputing that Clinton had a sexual
relationship with Lewinsky, made a two-part argument against
proceeding with the inquiry. First, Lowell said, the committee
should delay any action until it has decided what constitutes an
impeachable offense. Any other course, Lowell argued, would be
premature. Second, Lowell said, Clinton shouldn't be impeached
because the alleged actions don't rise to the level of ``high
crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell, for example, said Clinton's initial denials of an affair
with Lewinsky ``were misstatements about a consensual
relationship'' and did not rise to the level of an impeachable act.
</P>
<P>
   While the two lawyers' words rang with history, the performance
was a distinctively Washington set piece, with the legal arguments
likely to make little impact on politicians who will decide whether
to proceed with the impeachment inquiry. Indeed, while Schippers
and Lowell argued over what is an impeachable offense, many of the
37 members of the Republican-controlled committee had made clear
for days how they would vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both counsels ended up playing station identification, saying
what you would expect,'' said Laurence Tribe, professor of law at
Harvard University. Tribe decried the way Republicans moved toward
a vote on the impeachment inquiry without following a Democratic
suggestion that the committee first agree on what is an impeachable
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had agreed to focus on that initial question, then the
counsels would have an understandable role,'' Tribe said. ``Instead
there is this notion you can have an investigation into whether a
standard has been violated but not tell anyone what the standard
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Schippers, who during the 1960s was the chief of the Justice
Department's Chicago organized crime section, became friends with
Hyde with the two served together on a Chicago anti-crime panel in
1969.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Schippers struck a somber, professorial tone for most of
his hour at the witness table, as he spelled out one alleged
impeachable act after another. Unlike a normal court room, in which
an opposing lawyer is allowed to object to statements and appeal to
a judge, the Judiciary Committee forbade any interruption. Thus,
Lowell was not allowed to object to Schippers' tactics or his
occasional use of hearsay to make his case.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when Schippers said that Lewinsky's assertion that
the president had touched her breasts was ``corroborated by several
of her friends,'' Lowell was not allowed to object that these
friends could not have seen the private encounter.
</P>
<P>
   But later, Lowell's voice dripped with sarcasm as he suggested
the Republican case for impeachment boils down to ``who is telling
the truth about who touched who, when and where.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lowell sounded as uncomfortable as many of Clinton's
Democratic defenders as he sought to argue that a president who
lies is not necessarily one who should be impeached. Noting that
the Judiciary Committee in 1974 did not approve an article of
impeachment regarding former President Nixon's false statements to
the IRS, Lowell said: ``If President Nixon's alleged lies to the
IRS about his taxes were not grounds for impeachment in 1974, how,
then, are alleged lies about President Clinton's private, sexual
relationship with Miss Lewinsky grounds in 1998?''
</P>
<P>
   The most awkward moment for Republicans came when Schippers'
delivered his surprisingly personal coda to his otherwise
legalistic statement.
</P>
<P>
   After declaring that his guiding principle had been ``a search
for the truth fairly and impartially,'' Schippers ended his
statement by announcing that he wanted to say something ``as a
citizen of the US who happens to be a father and grandfather.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The laws of this country are the great barriers that protect
the citizens from the winds of evil and tyranny,'' Schippers said,
quoting from the play, ``A Man for All Seasons.'' ``If we permit
one of those laws to fall, who will be able to stand in he winds
that follow?
</P>
<P>
   ``Members of this committee, you are being watched... by 15
generations of our fellow Americans, many of whom are reposing in
military cemeteries throughout the world, are looking down on you
and judging what you do today.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Democrats and Republicans seemed startled by the remarks.
Within moments, Conyers walked over to Hyde and said something
privately to him. Then Hyde, who has said he wants to be
bipartisan, said he found ``some substance'' in he complaint raised
by Conyers and ordered that Schippers' personal comments be
stricken from the record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
