<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-G7-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET REACTS TO G7 NEWS, DOW DROPS 58 POINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disappointment over prospects for a global solution to the
world's economic crisis sparked a huge selloff in stocks Monday as
investors rushed to put their money into the relative safety of US
Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dow Jones Industrial Average managed to bounce back
from a 200-point deficit earlier in the day, the technology-laden
Nasdaq composite index fell 4.9 percent, its worst beating since
August 31, when it fell 8.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As stocks tumbled, bond prices soared in the biggest rally in 10
years. The bellwether 30-year Treasury bond surged 2 5/32 points,
or $21.56 per $1,000 bond, pushing the yield down to a record 4.71
percent, from 4.85 percent on Friday. The yield is the lowest in 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   After initially falling 232 points, the Dow, an index of 30
large industrial companies, finished 58 points lower at 7,726. The
Dow remains about 200 points below where it started the year and
1,600 points beneath the July 17 record close of 9,337.97.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks suffered the biggest losses, as the Nasdaq
slumped 78.29 points, or 4.8 percent, to 1,536.69. Even the
industry's biggest stars weren't spared, as shares of Cisco Systems
Inc., Dell Computer Corp. and Microsoft Corp. all tumbled.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. dropped 2 15/16 to 101 9/16 and Cisco lost 7
7/16 to 48 5/16 and Dell dropped 5 to 57 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (begin optional trim) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among Massachusetts-based technology companies, the biggest
victims were Avid Technology Inc. and Aspen Technology Inc. Both
companies warned of lower profits for the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Tewksbury-based Avid, which makes digital editing equipment,
tumbled 9 5/16 to 13 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge-based Aspen, , which makes software for the oil and
energy industry, has lost two-thirds of its value in two days. On
Monday, it fell 7 15/16 to 6 7/8, after the company said it would
lose about 26 cents a share for the period ended Sept. 30. Analysts
had been expecting a profit of about 6 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Aspen said it expects revenue for the quarter to be $46 million.
The company also said it was re-evaluating its business prospects
for the rest of the year.
</P>
<P>
   EMC Corp. of Hopkinton, which makes computer storage equipment
for businesses, lost 4 3/4, closing at 48 5/8. Shares of Keane Inc.
of Cambridge, a technology consulting firm, continued their recent
slide, falling 4 5/8, to 28 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (end optional trim) &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the stock market slide suggests that investors
don't think the world's leaders are doing enough to tackle the
growing economic turmoil overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There continue to be concerns in the market that inadequate
policy responses are being taken by the central banks globally, or
by the IMF, and fears that whatever policies they come up with will
fall short of what's needed to offset the problems of bad loans in
emerging markets and hedge funds,'' said Sylvester Marquardt,
research director of John Hancock Funds.
</P>
<P>
   A weekend meeting in Washington among leaders of the Group of
Seven largest industrial nations failed to turn up any concrete
plans for tackling the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The technology sell-off, in particular, was also attributed to
slowing demand for computers, software and services in Asia and
other parts of the world that caused many companies to warn of
lower quarterly profits.
</P>
<P>
   When a company issues such a warning in a volatile market,
``it's the kiss of death,'' said Giles McNamee, senior vice
president and director of technology investment banking for First
Albany Corp. in Boston. That sentiment quickly spreads to other
technology companies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are expecting the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason technology stocks have plunged so dramatically, he
added, is that prices had been driven up by investors who were
anxious for a big payoff but didn't really understand what they
owned. Now, in a panic about the market's overall direction, they
are dumping their holdings at big losses, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're throwing out all the babies and all the bathwater,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in the technology sell-off, according to William
Becklean, a managing director of Boston-based Tucker Anthony Inc.,
was the fear that banks and investment firms _ traditionally
aggressive spenders on technology equipment _ would clamp down on
purchases because of their investment exposure to risky hedge
funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
