<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVIL SUIT AGAINST AU PAIR PROCEEDS   IN HER ABSENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Although she returned home to England almost four
months ago, the legal saga of former au pair Louise Woodward
continued in her absence in a Boston courtroom Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a year after a jury convicted her of killing 8-month-old
Matthew Eappen, US District Judge William G. Young &UR;  &LR; said he will
determine the amount of damages that the child's parents are
entitled to in the wrongful-death suit they filed against Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward has chosen not to contest the suit by Sunil and Deborah
Eappen, which alleges that Woodward is responsible for the fatal
injuries the infant suffered in his Newton home while under her
care. No one appeared in court on Woodward's behalf Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Young has already issued a default against Woodward. Monday he
directed the Eappens' attorney, Frederic L. Ellis, to file a motion
for judgment and an assessment of damages by Nov. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis is seeking an unspecified amount of compensatory and
punative damages on the Eappens' behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But Young observed Monday that it is unlikely the couple will
collect on any judgment because there is no evidence Woodard has
``assets of any significant size.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of the Woodward family in England have said that she
continues to disclaim any responsibility for the child's death and
abandoned her defense in the civil case only for lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to England in June after the Supreme Judicial Court
upheld her manslaughter conviction and 279-day sentence. The
wrongful-death suit was filed hours after the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis again emphasized that the Eappens decided to sue Woodward
to prevent her from profiting from the death of their son and the
international publicity surrounding the ensuing trial. He said he
wanted to ensure that Woodward ``is not driving around in a
Rolls-Royce three years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis declined to say whether he has ferreted out any book or
movie deals Woodward may have signed since her release. The Eappens
have said that any award they recover will be donated to a
foundation they have launched to fight child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward and her parents have repeatedly insisted that her story
is not for sale. Young already has frozen Woodward's assets in the
United States and enjoined her from spending any money she receives
for her story.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis said it is still unclear whether any award would be
collectible in England. But he said having a judge, rather than a
jury, determine damages may cut in his favor; British judges, he
said, may look more favorably on such a judgment.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's hearing, the judge denied Ellis's request to take
sworn depositions to help establish Woodward's culpability and set
punative damages. Young said the transcript from Woodward's
criminal trial will give him all the information he needs to
determine the extent of Woodward's culpability.
</P>
<P>
   Young said Ellis is free to take depositions after the judgment
to try and locate Woodward's assets to pay any award.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, a jury convicted Woodward of second-degree
murder and sentenced her to life in prison. But Judge Hiller B.
Zobel reduced her conviction to manslaughter and her sentence to
the time she had already served.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Woodward shook the baby and slammed him against
a hard object, fracturing his skull. The defense said Matthew's
injuries were pre-existing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
