<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPREME-COURT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT TO RULE WHETHER JUDGE ERRED IN CASE OF TEXAS DEATH ROW
INMATE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Supreme Court, in the case of a Texas
death row inmate, has agreed to decide whether a judge erred by
failing to tell jurors of a mandatory life sentencing provision had
they chosen not to condemn him.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. district court jury in Lubbock found Louis Jones Jr.
guilty of kidnapping Air Force private Tracie Joy McBride, 19, from
a laundry room on the Goodfellow Air Force Base in San Angelo,
beating her over the head with a tire iron and leaving her body
under a bridge in February 1995. The jury, which rendered its
verdict Oct. 23, 1995, returned nearly two weeks later to recommend
that Jones, of San Angelo, be sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
   In his appeal to the high court, Jones argues that the judge,
Sam R. Cummings, should have instructed the jurors that their
failure to rule unanimously for death would result in a
court-imposed life sentence without possibility of parole. The
jurors chose to condemn him, even those prone to spare his life,
out of fear that any decision but death might have resulted in a
lenient prison term, Jones says through his attorney, assistant
federal public defender Timothy Crook of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The erroneous interpretation of the jury instructions ... in
this case gave the death-prone jurors a big stick to wield over the
heads of those jurors leaning toward a life sentence,'' Crooks
wrote in urging the justices to hear the appeal. ``The (in reality
nonexistent) threat of non-unanimity resulting in a less-than-life
sentence coerced the life-leaning jurors into voting for a death
verdict to avoid the more unpalatable (but actually nonexistent)
option of a less-than-life sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals has rejected Crooks'
argument, saying the judge's failure to alert jurors to the
possible life sentence had no legal effect on the jury's
recommendation for death. In its decision, the 5th U.S. Circuit
gave little weight to affidavits from two jurors saying they would
have spared Jones' life had the judge said life in prison without
parole was the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, which prosecuted Jones, unsuccessfully
urged the Supreme Court to let the death sentence stand. The
department, through Solicitor General Seth Waxman, said the
justices have never held that the Constitution requires judges to
instruct juries that a life sentence will result if they fail to
reach a unanimous decision regarding death.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the contrary, the court has noted that, even when jury
deadlock returns the matter to the judge for sentencing, the state
has in a capital sentencing proceeding a strong interest in having
the jury express the conscience of the community on the ultimate
question of life or death,'' Waxman argued. ``(Jones') proposed
instruction would undermine that strong interest by discouraging
deliberations to achieve jury unanimity.''
</P>
<P>
   The justices, who have not yet scheduled arguments in Jones vs.
United States, are expected to render their decision by next
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The high court, acting on the first day of its 1998-99 term on
Monday, refused to hear the appeal of a Baptist minister from
Dallas who was found liable for malpractice and breach of fiduciary
duty for having sex with two female church employees who had sought
marriage counseling from him. Shelby Baucum, minister of
administration and education at the Casa View Baptist Church,
argued that the constitutional First Amendment right to free
religious exercise barred courts from interfering with his
``spiritual'' counseling of Robyn Sanders and Cynthia Mullanix.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. District Court for Northern Texas ordered Baucum to pay
$115,000 to each woman. The 5th Circuit upheld the verdict,
rejecting Baucum's argument that his behavior enjoyed
constitutional protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First Amendment does not categorically insulate religious
relationships from judicial scrutiny, for to do so would
necessarily extend constitutional protection to the secular
components of these relationships,'' the 5th Circuit ruled. ``To
hold otherwise would impermissibly place a religious leader in a
preferred position in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   In other high court action, the justices told the 5th U.S.
Circuit to reconsider its March 6 decision that barred a former
Plano building inspector from suing the city for the sexual
harassment she allegedly endured from a supervisor. The U.S.
District Court for Eastern Texas, followed by the 5th U.S. Circuit,
ruled that Plano could not be held liable for harassment because
city leaders had no actual knowledge of the harassment.
</P>
<P>
   However, those lower court decisions were rendered before the
Supreme Court ruled in June that cities could be held liable for
harassment by municipal supervisors even if city officials were
unaware of the misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   In Wilson vs. Plano, Texas, Susan Wilson claims that her former
supervisor's boss made unwelcome sexual remarks and touched Wilson
several times in an offensive manner. The city claimed it had no
knowledge of Jack Newton's alleged actions until Wilson filed a
sexual harassment complaint with Plano after she resigned. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
