<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE STEPS UP ATTACKS ON GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the House Judiciary Committee began its
impeachment debate Monday, the White House stepped up its attacks
on Republicans, accusing them of allowing the issue to overshadow
the nation's other business.
</P>
<P>
   Top Democrats in the House and Senate rushed to the White House
to join President Clinton in criticizing Republicans for not
passing spending bills to keep the government running and trying to
provoke a government shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   At the hastily arranged meeting with Clinton, the Senate
minority leader, Thomas A. Daschle of South Dakota, and the House
minority leader, Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri, called on
Congress to approve the president's fiscal 1999 budget and
legislative proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop playing politics, pass legislation, and let's make some
progress,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for his part, said the Republican majority has failed
to pass 11 of the 13 spending bills and urged them to do so by
Friday, when lawmakers are scheduled to recess for the year and a
stop-gap spending measure the president recently signed expires.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to work with Congress to get this important work
done,'' Clinton said. ``There is still time for us to put the
people of our country ahead of politics, and I hope we'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the historic proceeding of the Judiciary Committee unfolded
live on cable television, a determined Clinton tried to show he was
not distracted by the possibility of becoming the third president
in US history to face an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Besides meeting with Gephardt and Daschle, Clinton spoke by
phone to Russian President Boris Yeltsin about the pending military
action in Kosovo and attended a special meeting of finance
officials from 22 nations on the world financial crisis. He also
appeared at two Democratic fund-raisers _ a luncheon and a
reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not spending any time focusing on what's going on up on
the Hill,'' said White House press secretary Joseph Lockhart.
Later, he said: ``But I don't want to leave you with the impression
that he has spent no time on this.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Clinton continues to lobby congressional leaders,
pressing against the opening of a formal inquiry and impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the White House dispatched four staff members _ lawyers
and legislative liaisons _ to Capitol Hill to monitor the Judiciary
Committee hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've now had four hours or so of opening statements, and
they've yet to spend a minute talking about what is a reasonable
standard for impeachment,'' Lockhart said Monday afternoon.
``They're putting the cart before the horse.''
</P>
<P>
   With Democrats on the Judiciary Committee already on the same
page as the White House in arguing that Clinton's relationship with
former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky does not rise to the
level of impeachment, the administration turned its focus to a
united front against the GOP in the policy debate.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, White House officials discussed how they
needed Democrats to join them in criticizing Republicans for
failing to approve the president's budget, including his proposals
for education, a patient bill of rights, and setting aside the
budget surplus for Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that effort, White House officials contacted the
Democratic leaders. Daschle and Gephardt met Clinton after the
Monday fund-raising luncheon and rode back to the White House,
where they talked briefly before delivering joint statements on the
South Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt singled out Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Senate
majority leader, for special criticism, saying he was playing
``showdown politics over a government shutdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott angered the White House and made some Democrats nervous by
saying on a Sunday talk show that he was not certain he could trust
the Clinton administration to get a budget agreement. Lott said he
had been told by a White House official that the administration was
prepared to shut down the government if it would be to their
political advantage. White House officials denied that and said
that chief of staff Erskine Bowles was misquoted.
</P>
<P>
   After calling the Republican majority ``the worst Congress that
has ever sat in the United States Capitol,'' Gephardt said if a
government shutdown occurs, ``it will be a failure of one group and
one part of our government and one part only, and that is the
Republican leadership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
