<SLUG> BC-JOAN-ALLEN-IN-PLEASANTVILLE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOAN ALLEN: THE ACTRESS'S ACTRESS TAKES A DETOUR TO
`PLEASANTVILLE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Joan Allen with William H. Macy in a
scene from ``Pleasantville.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Joan Allen knows about small towns.
 &HT;    ``I grew up in Rochelle, Ill., a city of 8,000 people about 80
miles west of Chicago,'' says Allen, a Tony Award winner and
two-time Oscar nominee. ``My dad worked at a gas station, so like
Opie would visit Andy at the jail, I'd hang out with my dad at the
gas station.
 &HT;    ``It was a quiet, safe way to grow up.''
 &HT;    Now a New Yorker, Allen revisits that Mayberryesque childhood in
her latest film, ``Pleasantville.'' Due in theaters on Oct. 16,
writer/director Gary Ross' film stars Tobey Maguire and Reese
Witherspoon as siblings David and Jennifer _ she a high-school
tramp and he a bored kid who kills time watching repeats of a 1950s
black-and-white sitcom called ``Pleasantville.''
 &HT;    In Pleasantville it never rains, the temperature never deviates
and the ice-cream shop never closes. In fact, nothing ever changes
... until David and Jennifer magically land in the
``Pleasantville'' universe and become the picture-perfect children
of uberparents Betty (Allen) and George Parker (William H. Macy).
 &HT;    The kids infuse Pleasantville with some life and, literally, a
little color.
 &HT;    ``To me, the film is about embracing the multitude of feelings
we as humans possess,'' Allen says, relaxing at Manhattan's Essex
House hotel. ``It's about tolerance and acceptance of who we are as
people.
 &HT;    ``Order and perfection seem nice in theory,'' she says, ``but
they can also be very limiting, and Gary explores all of that quite
beautifully.''
 &HT;    The actress remembers such shows as ``Father Knows Best'' and
``Leave it to Beaver,'' but she resisted mimicking any of the era's
prototypical sitcom moms.
 &HT;    ``When we started, I asked Gary if he wanted me to base Betty on
somebody in particular, like Loretta Young or Donna Reed,'' she
recalls. ``He said, `No, no. We know what those characters are
like. We're going to make our own character, but in the mold of
that '50s sitcom mother.'''
 &HT;    In a way, the story is a coming-of-age tale _ but for the mother
as much as for the children. Exposed to the real world through her
new ``children,'' Betty enjoys a rebirth, discovering her own
sexuality _ which, of course, doesn't exist in the 1950s-television
world _ and gradually herself turning from black-and-white into
color.
 &HT;    ``We tried different degrees of intensity,'' Allen says. ``We
experimented to figure out what was too little and what was too
much. We played with humor, pathos and anger.
 &HT;    ``And it became a pattern,'' she says. ``It always came back to
`We have to keep Betty in mind.' We had to go back to her voice, to
her temperament, until it felt right, until it was Betty.''
 &HT;    Growing up, Allen watched television, but it was televised
movies that captured her.
 &HT;    ``I remember being a teen-ager and stumbling onto Katharine
Hepburn doing `Long Day's Journey into Night' (1962),'' she
recalls. ``I thought, `Oh, my God!'
 &HT;    ``I so loved the material and Hepburn's performance,'' the
actress says. ``I think I already wanted to act by then, but those
`Oh, my God' moments added fuel to my fire.''
 &HT;    Allen acted in several shows in high school, then attended East
Illinois University in Charleston. Still in college, she joined her
friend John Malkovich's Chicago-based Steppenwolf Theater Company,
where she eventually starred in ``Burn This'' and ``Of Mice and
Men,'' among others.
 &HT;    Success did not come overnight, however.
 &HT;    ``I was a secretary for many, many years,'' she says. ``Even
when I was with Steppenwolf I worked as a secretary, because we
hardly got paid anything, certainly not enough to live on.
 &HT;    ``I moved to New York in 1983,'' the actress adds, ``and after
that I made my living solely as an actor.''
 &HT;    Allen won a 1987 Tony for her Broadway debut in ``Burn This,''
and earned another nomination for ``The Heidi Chronicles'' (1989).
Between stage stints, she landed supporting parts in such films as
``Compromising Positions'' (1985), ``Peggy Sue Got Married'' (1986)
and ``Tucker: The Man and His Dream'' (1988).
 &HT;    ``My film career slowly evolved,'' Allen says. ``I actually
haven't done a play since 1990, and I've done about a film a year
since then.''
 &HT;    That pace suits Allen just fine.
 &HT;    ``I don't get offered every film, and I don't want to do every
film,'' she says. ``I'm pretty selective about what I choose to do,
and I don't think that'll ever change.''
 &HT;    Allen wowed audiences with the heavy-duty triple header of
``Nixon'' (1995), ``The Crucible'' (1996) and ``The Ice Storm''
(1997), securing Oscar nominations for the first two and howls of
protest that she wasn't nominated again for ``Ice Storm.''
 &HT;    She still hasn't won one, however.
 &HT;    ``Losing wasn't painful, but there is a certain amount of `Aw,
gee' after they say the name of the winner,'' she says. ``Everybody
was saying that Lauren Bacall was going to win the year I was
nominated for `Crucible,' so I didn't think I'd win. The one I felt
bad for was Lauren. With `Nixon,' it was disappointing in the
moment, but the party was nice.
 &HT;    ``If I get nominated again,'' she adds, ``after all the work it
takes to get ready, it might be nice to win next time.''
 &HT;    Allen giggles. Yes, it's true _ Joan Allen, so often grim and
tight-lipped onscreen, can actually laugh and smile. In fact, she
does it often.
 &HT;    ``I've gotten to do some truly quality work, but I did sense at
a certain point that I was falling into a serious mode,'' Allen
says. ``That's what attracted me to `Face/Off' (1997).''
 &HT;    In that John Woo actioner, Allen was cast as the wife of police
detective John Travolta and, in a way, terrorist Nicolas Cage. Even
amid the flamboyant fight scenes for which Woo is known, she
brought a surprising credibility to a story which, after all,
involved the surgical exchange of faces.
 &HT;    ``Even though I had a dramatic role, and my action
responsibilities were minimal, to say the least, it was a
completely different type of film,'' the actress says. ``A lot of
people saw `Face/Off,' so it gave me greater visibility.
 &HT;    ``Let's face it, a lot of people never saw `Crucible,' never saw
`Nixon,''' she says. ```Face/Off' appealed to a whole other segment
of the movie-going audience, and I was happy for that.
 &HT;    ``Would it be fun to break out and do a comedy-comedy? Sure,''
she says readily, ``but it would depend on finding a director I
could trust, and on the other cast members involved.''
 &HT;    Allen hasn't worked since completing ``Pleasantville'' a year
ago, and she's in no rush to. She'd rather spend time with her
husband, actor Peter Friedman, and their daughter, Sadie.
 &HT;    ``I waited a long time to have a child,'' Allen says softly,
``and I love her. I'm probably only going to have one child, and I
don't want to miss out on her.''
 &HT;    But there's one upcoming film that Allen is champing at the bit
to make.
 &HT;    ``I'm attached to a film about Veronica Guerin, who was a
hotshot Irish journalist,'' Allen says. ``She wrote about crime
figures in Dublin and the drug trade, and she was fearless.
 &HT;    ``These crime figures warned her that she was pushing too hard
and that harm would come her way if she didn't relent,'' she says.
``But even though she had friends and family she adored, she didn't
relent and she was murdered.
 &HT;    ``If all the pieces fall into place, I'll do that,'' the actress
says, ``because this woman's story so fascinates me. Why would she
throw everything away?''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
