<SLUG> BC-IAN-MCKELLEN-IN-APT-PUPIL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 IAN McKELLEN TAKES ANOTHER WALK ON THE DARK SIDE  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Ian McKellen in a scene from ``Apt
Pupil.'' 
 By JEAN OPPENHEIMER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    There's something about Ian McKellen which seems to draw him to
the dark side of life.
 &HT;    He's played sinister villains on stage _ Salieri in ``Amadeus,''
Iago in ``Othello'' _ and on screen _ Richard III and, in ``Last
Action Hero'' (1993), Death himself.
 &HT;    But his latest villain may be the scariest yet. In ``Apt
Pupil,'' opening Oct. 23, he plays Kurt Dussander, a Nazi war
criminal who has lived quietly _ and unrecognized _ in the United
States for decades. At last he is unmasked by a high-school student
_ but the catch is that the boy doesn't want to turn him in, but
rather to learn details of the Nazi atrocities he'd committed.
 &HT;    Based on a Stephen King novella and directed by Bryan Singer,
who helmed the 1995 thriller ``The Usual Suspects,'' ``Apt Pupil''
is an unusually disturbing _ and powerful _ film.
 &HT;    ``This is a nasty little story, and it will have
reverberations,'' McKellen acknowledges.
 &HT;    The British actor is in Los Angeles to star in a stage
production of Henrik Ibsen's ``An Enemy of the People.'' Dressed
casually, with wire-rimmed glasses framing his expressive blue
eyes, he has the manner of a slightly aloof university professor.
 &HT;    ``The shocks and nastiness didn't affect me,'' McKellen hastens
to add. ``I genuinely didn't know when I was making the film what
it was going to be like. Bryan knew. He was very particular about
what he wanted from the actors, but in terms of how it was going to
cut together and to what effect, I decided to remain indifferent to
that.''
 &HT;    Although he has now seen the completed film twice, McKellen is
reluctant to discuss it, saying only that he believes the film does
have a moral purpose.
 &HT;    ``As filmmakers,'' he adds, ``the only question we need to ask
is to what purpose are we trying to affect people?''
 &HT;    Asked that very question, however, he dodges the issue.
 &HT;    ``I don't think it appropriate for me to answer,'' he says,
``because I didn't write or direct the film.''
 &HT;    No matter how you look at it, ``Apt Pupil'' is difficult to sit
through _ the casual cruelty and brutality on display is horrifying
_ but it's also riveting, with McKellen's aged Nazi the complex
enigma at its core.
 &HT;    It's the latest star turn from an actor who has been dazzling
audiences for nearly 40 years. Born in the industrial north of
England in 1939, McKellen first performed in school plays and then
at Cambridge University, where he majored in English literature. In
lieu of formal training, he spent the next three years touring with
regional theater troupes.
 &HT;    In 1964, his first London appearance earned him an invitation
from Laurence Olivier to join the newly founded National Theatre
Company. McKellen later also worked with the Royal Shakespeare
Company and the Actors Company, which he co-founded in 1972.
 &HT;    On stage, McKellen has shone as Richard II and III, Hamlet,
Macbeth and Iago. He won a Best Actor Tony for his role as Salieri
in the Broadway production of ``Amadeus'' (1981).
 &HT;    Until recently his film career had consisted primarily of fine
performances in small roles in not-very-successful films. In 1995,
however, he scored a coup in ``Richard III,'' which McKellen not
only starred in but also wrote, recasting Shakespeare's historical
drama to set it in an imaginary fascist England, circa 1939.
 &HT;    That outing seems to have caught moviemakers' eyes. Besides
``Apt Pupil,'' McKellen will also be seen this fall in ``Gods and
Monsters,'' a fictionalized drama about James Whale, the troubled,
gay director of ``Frankenstein'' (1931) and ``The Bride of
Frankenstein'' (1935).
 &HT;    A burgeoning film career isn't all good news, because McKellen
has many demands on his time. In the last decade he has devoted
himself to a crusade for gay and lesbian rights in Britain. Since
publicly acknowledging his own homosexuality in 1988, he has been a
leading voice for the gay community, enjoying a stature only
enhanced by his 1991 knighthood.
 &HT;    ``Trying to make the world a better place for lesbians and gays
is as important to me, and as fulfilling and rewarding, as
acting,'' he says. ``I know it has an impact on the world, in a way
that I couldn't honestly say my performance of `Richard III' is
going to do.
 &HT;    ``I know people's lives are changed because I and others have
done certain things _ changed laws, for example. And that feels
more significant to me than anything else I have done.''
 &HT;    McKellen has twice met privately with British Prime Minister
Tony Blair, the Labour party leader whom he considers more
sympathetic to gay issues than Tory predecessors such as John
Major.
 &HT;    ``Compared with John Major,'' the actor says, ``Mr. Blair is an
expert on what troubles gay women and men in Britain, vis a vis the
law, because he has gay friends and because he lived in Islington,
which is one of the gay middle-class centers of London.''
 &HT;    McKellen doesn't expect Blair actually to provide leadership on
gay issues, he adds. Rather, he believes the prime minister is
adept at responding to already-existing movements and trends, such
as the gay movement.
 &HT;    ``He is very much in favor of the integration of everyone _
white, black, gay, foreign,'' McKellen adds with a note of resigned
caution. ``But when you look at the details of it, it's a little
bit sluggish.''
 &HT;    McKellen pauses a moment, and when he continues he sounds almost
wistful.
 &HT;    ``I'm old Labour,'' he says. ``I believe in free education, free
health care and parks, cheap theaters and money spent on the arts.
And the way they all have been funded is disintegrating. It's
difficult for people like me to adjust and to see whether the
amount of good that is being done outweighs what I think are some
of the disadvantages.''
 &HT;    McKellen brightens when the discussion turns to a surprising
interest: his website, which the actor designed and created himself
_ unlike most actors' ``official'' sites, which are the work of
studio flacks or fan clubs.
 &HT;    ``It's a much bigger audience than a book,'' he says
enthusiastically. ``It's really a sort of hobby for me. I can put
programs, photographs and reviews on it, and they are accessible to
anyone who might want to look at them. One day I would like to make
myself write something regularly for it.''
 &HT;    Finding the time to do anything more for the site _ which may be
found at www.mckellen.com _ would be difficult, McKellen
acknowledges, because of his frenetic professional pace. Even his
personal life takes a back seat, he says, which probably explains
his lack of any long-term romantic relationships in recent years.
 &HT;    ``I am trying to be more open to meeting people,'' he says. ``I
need to give more attention to things which have nothing to do with
my career.''
 &HT;    But for now, he's doing so more in theory than in practice. Even
after two years of nonstop stage and screen work, the actor isn't
taking any time off.
 &HT;    ``I know I should be sitting back and taking some time and
enjoying,'' he says. ``But, instead, I'm off to Leeds with a small
company of 10 actors and we are doing three plays, one right after
the other.''
 &HT;    The world on the other side of the footlights will, it seems,
have to wait.
 c.1998 Jean Oppenheimer  
