<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHAEL-BOATMAN-IN-SPIN-CITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL BOATMAN: THE `SPIN' DOCTOR IS IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Michael Boatman in a scene from ``Spin
City.'' 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The climb to stardom demands sacrifices from everybody who
dreams of it. Some sacrifice their illusions, some their families,
some their integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Boatman sacrificed his hair.
</P>
<P>
   Like Yul Brynner, who shaved his head for his career-defining
role in ``The King and I,'' ``Spin City's'' Carter Heywood is
instantly identifiable by his polished pate. But Boatman insists
that he had nothing of the kind in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I ended up shaving my head had nothing to do with
`Spin City,''' he says. ``Actually, I did it to land a movie
audition I wanted. The producers wouldn't see me, because they were
familiar with my work and liked me but thought I had the wrong
look. So I said to myself, `I'll give them a look.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get the job,'' he adds, ``but then `Spin City' came
up one week later and my hair hadn't grown back yet. And since it
kind of worked for the character, I stuck with it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the challenges of the role extend well beyond the barber's
chair. As special assistant for minority affairs in New York's
highly dysfunctional mayor's office, Carter represents prime time's
first stab at a gay, African-American character.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, Boatman has both the grace and the talent to
sidestep the stereotypical risks of a double-minority role and
concentrate instead on Carter's overall complexity.
</P>
<P>
   ``What initially attracted me to the role,'' he says, ``was that
here was a complicated, funny, somewhat neurotic, gay,
African-American activist in New York City. I mean, my God, the
whole package was just so interesting, and the potential was just
sort of limitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I knew that people were going to focus on the gay
aspect of it,'' he says. ``But there's so much more to Carter than
just that, and I think that's due to our great writers. They were
interested in creating a really believable group of characters _
people who, just like in real life, are defined by much more than
whatever their sexual orientation might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most powerful statements that people have made to me about
Carter are always along the lines of, `Well, he's definitely not
what I would think or what I would expect.'''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of his colleagues _ including Mayor Randall Winston
(Barry Bostwick), Assistant Mayor Mike Flaherty (Michael J. Fox)
and homophobic housemate Stuart (Alan Ruck) _ Carter remains
perpetually unlucky in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of it this way,'' Boatman says. ``We're all very
driven people in our work. We're all very successful. But I do
believe we're all completely socially retarded. I think the writers
stumbled upon that theme because they found success in it with
regard to Mike's character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's that way,'' the actor adds. ``I've heard a
couple of critics say, `Well, why can't Carter have a substantial
positive, healthy relationship with a gay man?' But there's nothing
funny in that. I mean, it gets boring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for the only gay, and only African-American, character
on the show to have a nobly sort-of-healthy relationship would have
been a real dead end,'' he says. ``On American television, whenever
there's a minority character, they're so afraid of offending
whatever minority that person represents that they take all the fun
out of it. They take all the humanity away.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I like delving into a flawed guy like Carter, because it's
not something you get to see very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ``Spin City'' isn't the only opportunity Boatman has
to explore character flaws. During his summer break, he transported
his family from New York to Los Angeles so that he could continue
his recurring role as uptight _ and decidedly straight _ business
manager Stanley Babson on the hit HBO sports-agency sitcom,
``Arli$$.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a decade of theatrical training has, he says, made it
relatively easy for him to shift from one character to another,
Boatman admits to occasional crossed wires.
</P>
<P>
   ``On `Arli$$,' I sometimes find myself doing Carter things, and
I have to stop that,'' he says. ``I've made very specific choices
about both characters with regard to their kicks and nuances and
odd behaviors. But every once in a while I'll do something as
Stanley that I know works for the scene and is going to be funny,
and then think, `Oh, God, that was a Carter thing!'
</P>
<P>
   ``Though it's probably apples and oranges to people watching,''
Boatman adds, ``to me it's kind of tricky, because what I love as
an actor is trying to be as different as I possibly can from role
to role.''
</P>
<P>
   These days crossovers between series are all the rage _ even
shows on different networks can cross over. The worlds of ``Spin
City'' and ``Arli$$'' aren't so different that, say, a campaign to
build a new stadium might bring Boatman's two worlds into
conjunction.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the question: Assuming digital magic made it
possible for them to meet, would Carter and Stanley get along?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Boatman says. ``Carter is a
dyed-in-the-wool liberal who's a great believer in the
liberal-slash-Democratic agenda. Stanley is an absolutely robotic
Republican, faithful to the party and its views to the very end.
That alone would be enough to keep them very far apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Concurrent success as both Carter and Stanley notwithstanding,
Boatman cites neither as his most significant achievement. Instead,
he points with fatherly pride to his 2-year-old daughter, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Since Boatman originally hails from Chicago and plays a key role
in a sports-themed sitcom, it seems impossible that it could be
sheer coincidence that his first child shares her name with a
certain high-profile basketball star from the Windy City.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a slight coincidence,'' he admits, ``but it's not
what you think. I once knew a woman in acting class in Chicago
whose name was Jordan. There was no dating or anything like that _
I just knew her from class and liked the name. That was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, everybody says, `You're from Chicago, you must love
Michael Jordan,' and everybody assumes that I'm a big basketball
fan,'' Boatman adds. ``In actual fact, I couldn't possibly be more
inept on a basketball court.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of Canadian TV Guide, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
