<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0709 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-WELLS-BOS     10-05 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-WELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID WELLS: DECEIVING LOOKS, DECEIVING PITCHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He looks more like a Thursday night softball pitcher
with one eye on the ball and the other on the neighborhood tavern.
</P>
<P>
   Overweight, his shirt unbuttoned at the top and sometimes
untucked at the bottom, David Wells looks more like a child of
bikers (which he is) and devotee of Metallica and the Who (which he
also is) than a white-hot major league pitcher for the dreaded,
tradition-empowered Yankees (which he also is).
</P>
<P>
   Appearances in this case not only are deceiving, they are dead
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Wells delivered a gem in Game 1 of the American League Division
Series, shutting out the mighty Texas Rangers for eight innings
with his oddball assortment of pitches, speeds, and locations on
the way to a 2-0 victory. It was the latest of many vintage
performances from the 35-year-old lefthander, who, in his second
year in pinstripes, may finally have found a home after 10 years
and four previous big league stops.
</P>
<P>
   He may be goofy, different, emotional, wild. Hey, he's a lefty.
His nickname is ``Boomer.'' In New York this season, he has been
all of the above while also becoming the 14th man to pitch a
perfect game (May 17), retiring 33 straight hitters, and starting
the All-Star Game in Colorado. For the season, he was 18-4 with a
3.49 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said a lot of things about David Wells the last couple
years,'' said manager Joe Torre, cracking a sly smile. ``The
difference in him this year from last year is that when he doesn't
have his best stuff or when he is running out of gas, he is still a
battler. He finds a way. I didn't see that last year. It's a
180-degree turnaround.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Wells will start Game 1 of the American League Championship
Series tonight against the Cleveland Indians here. That's just the
way he wants it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the opportunity to succeed and fail,'' Wells said. ``I
think it makes an individual stronger. Some people can't handle the
pressure. I want it. I can relate to it. I want to be that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells and New York seem like such an obvious match that it's a
wonder it took him so long to get here. In the previous three
years, he had been on four teams (New York, Baltimore, Detroit,
Cincinnati) after spending the early years of his career in
Toronto. His numbers were never gaudy, and there were always doubts
about his, er, commitment to fitness, shall we say? Prior to this
season, his career won-lost record was 106-85.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays simply released him after the 1992 season. Detroit
waited until two days before the start of the 1993 season before
signing him as a free agent, then traded him to the Reds the next
year, a move to bolster Cincinnati's postseason chances. The Reds
traded him to Baltimore, where he spent one year (1996) and beat
the Yankees in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   New York signed him to a three-year deal before the 1997 season.
The Yankees got a decent season (16-10) from him last year, but how
many were prepared for what he submitted this season? Until Roger
Clemens blew away the field, Wells was one of the leading
candidates for the Cy Young Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming to the Stadium every day, for me, it's unbelievable, an
honor,'' said Wells, a baseball history buff. ``To play here, with
all those great performances before, well, I have to try and take
it in stride. There are a lot of legends here. A lot of heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Yankees are playing not only against the Red Sox, but
also against those heroes. Wells's achievements were only a part of
their fabulous 114-win season, which also saw Bernie Williams win
the batting title. But, entering the postseason, the players knew
that nothing less than a world title would suffice; otherwise, the
regular season would be rendered moot.
</P>
<P>
   Torre had plenty of time to set up his playoff pitching
rotation. He could have gone with veteran David Cone, a 20-game
winner, to open the series. He could have turned to 1996 hero Andy
Pettitte. He didn't. He went with Wells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have twice as much faith in him this year,'' Torre said.
``He's a much, much tougher pitcher. He always had good stuff, but
he sometimes would get frustrated and lose his energy. This year
that energy is devoted to getting through.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells has done that and more. Given the opponent and the
situation, his Game 1 performance ranked up there with his best
outings of the year. It's all falling into place for him now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I wanted to be my whole life,'' he said. ``Now
that I have the opportunity, I want to give it my best.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting otherwise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
