<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CRISIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCE OFFICIALS SAY CRISIS   PLAN WILL WORK _ IN TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Finance officials from 22 countries gathered Monday
to discuss ways to prevent future global financial crises, while
trying to assure investors that they also have a credible plan to
revive the economy from its current slump.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are doing important work, perhaps the most important work
the world can be doing at this moment in history,'' President
Clinton told the so-called Group of 22 industrial and emerging
nations, gathered at the Sheraton Luxury Collection Hotel. ``The
institutional reforms that flow from this work will shape the
global financial system for the next half-century.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Treasury Department called six months ago for the
meeting, which includes officials from the Group of Seven major
industrial nations, or G-7, and from 15 emerging market countries.
Their goal is to find ways that governments, private companies and
agencies can work better to prevent future crises.
</P>
<P>
   But fears that a G-7 meeting Saturday yielded no solid solution
to the current downturn helped push the Dow Jones industrial
average down 233 points Monday, though the index recovered to close
at 7726, down 58 points.
</P>
<P>
   In separate press conferences, finance ministers asserted that
the G-7 had made significant steps toward ending the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot expect us to pull rabbits (from a hat) that dazzle
us with their white fur and settle the situation overnight,'' said
Dominique Strauss-Kahn, finance minister for France. Strauss-Kahn
also said finance officials are contending with the fact that some
investors are ``no longer rational'' in selling off stocks.
</P>
<P>
   At a White House briefing, Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers said the G-7 had agreed that the major industrial nations
should be more concerned with growth than inflation, a signal that
each country's bias should be toward lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   He said the group also agreed to ``explore'' President Clinton's
proposal to establish a new line of credit, using no new funds, at
the International Monetary Fund to help nations before they run
into financial crises. Currently, the IMF generally makes loans
once a country is already in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of 22 nations was called to consider reports from
three ``working groups'' on changes to global investment rules and
to international agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The reports, which will be revised and presented to heads of
state by the beginning of next year, call for better
``transparency,'' or stronger international standards for financial
accounting and disclosure that give investors better information
about what countries and companies are running into financial
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transparency will not prevent more financial crises, nor
</P>
<P>
   will it resolve crises. . . But greater transparency can help
reduce the frequency of crises and can also reduce the severity of
crises by minimizing the scale of surprises that hit the markets,''
said Mervyn King, deputy governor of the Bank of England.
</P>
<P>
   The group also called for countries to disclose more data on
their banking systems and foreign exchange reserves. Its report
noted that while Thailand said it had $32 billion in reserves in
July 1997, it also had claims on those reserves of $29 billion.
South Korea reported gross reserves of $24 billion at the end of
November 1997, but almost two-thirds of that had been deposited in
overseas branches of Korean banks to assist them in meeting their
debt payments.
</P>
<P>
   Had those countries reported their reserves more accurately,
they might have been forced to make better policy decisions that
would have prevented problems later on, one report said.
</P>
<P>
   The working groups also called for a study of how to compile and
publish data on the international exposures of investment banks,
hedge funds and other institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
