<HEADER>
A0737 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GATECH-NCSTATE-CO     10-05 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-NCSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For N.C. State's Holt, consistency matters most
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Torry Holt may be the best wide receiver in college
football this year, as well as a splendid punt returner and a
Heisman Trophy candidate. But one thing he's apparently not good at
is remembering names.
</P>
<P>
   After North Carolina State upset Syracuse last week, Holt was
asked to assess new placekicker Dan Deskevich, a walk-on who hit
four extra points and a field goal in a 38-17 rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who?'' Holt blurted out, then covered his mouth to hide an
embarrassed grin.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to more familiar foes, Holt is equally
non-specific. Since ripping through Florida State for three
touchdowns in a stunning upset of the Seminoles last month, he has
been queried repeatedly whether he thinks anybody can cover him
one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there is,'' Holt said. ``I'd love to go against
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it's unlikely N.C. State will meet Georgia and Champ
Bailey in a bowl game, and he's already proven himself against Dre'
Bly of North Carolina and Virginia's Anthony Poindexter, Holt may
not get the chance until he gets to the NFL. For the 23rd-ranked
Wolfpack, maintaining consistency has never been more important.
</P>
<P>
   Like Georgia Tech, which comes to Carter-Finley Stadium on
Saturday, N.C. State is hitting a mid-season stretch that could
sort out its bowl ambitions. Its last post-season game was a win
over Mississippi State in the 1994 Peach Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The week after beating FSU, N.C. State traveled to Baylor, fell
behind 26-0 and scrambled back only to lose 33-30 as a game-tying
field goal attempt was blocked in the dying seconds. The Wolfpack
also had to rally to defeat Ohio University in their season opener,
finally surging ahead after blocking a punt and returning it for a
touchdown in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is. If I knew, it wouldn't have
happened,'' Holt said of the inconsistency. ``At Baylor, we weren't
as hungry as we were against Florida State and Syracuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack is a mystifying team in other ways. Until breaking
out for 226 yards against Syracuse, their rushing game was
non-existent. A rebuilt secondary, dubbed the ``Rough Riders,''
leads the country with 12 interceptions, but the defense is one of
the poorest against the run in Division I-A.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the real team,'' head coach Mike O'Cain said
after the Syracuse game. ``We don't have a tremendously talented
team, so we have to beat people with emotion. We have to make sure
we do that every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt has been the electrifying constant. He racked up 225
receiving yards at Baylor to set a school single-game record, and
against Syracuse became N.C. State's all-time receiving leader with
2,369 yards. His speed is too much to handle in single coverage,
but he exploits zones with ease. Syracuse dropped back to avoid the
long bomb, but was repeatedly burned as Holt sliced and faked his
way past several layers of defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Against Syracuse, however, it was quarterback Jamie Barnette who
did the most damage, throwing for 282 yards and two touchdowns and
running the option stylishly, easily outshining Donovan McNabb with
85 yards rushing to boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it easier for me when we have a lot of guys making
plays,'' Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   The maturity of Barnette, thought to be too small at 5-foot-11
to be a good ACC quarterback, has been a critical development.
Tossed into the fray two years ago as a raw redshirt freshman, he
has molded himself into a near mirror-image of Georgia Tech's Joe
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie never ceases to amaze me,'' O'Cain said. ``He always
keeps his options open, and makes the plays when you need them.
Torry's the game-breaker, but Jamie keeps it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what the Wolfpack need most as they head into the meat
of their ACC order. After playing at Duke next week, they travel to
Virginia and Clemson before October is out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I really believe we're on the right path,`` Holt said.
``We just have to continue doing what we've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
