<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Does impact of libertarians invite equal time?
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Anyone planning a major political forum in Georgia
this fall has had to deal with the Bert and Jack question.
</P>
<P>
   Should Bert Loftman and Jack Cashin, the Libertarian Party's
candidates for senator and governor, be included on the stage with
their more advantaged Republican and Democratic rivals, or do they
just get in the way of voters trying to chose between the
candidates with realistic chances?
</P>
<P>
   The impact they've had on Georgia politics in this decade _
throwing the 1992 U.S. Senate race into a runoff and prompting
Democrats in the Legislature to dump the old majority requirement
in federal general elections _ makes a persuasive argument that the
Libertarians shouldn't be shut out. On the other hand, there's only
a limited amount of time in these debates and they can chew up lots
of it.
</P>
<P>
   And they are getting better at it. Loftman inserted himself so
forcefully in Sunday night's Senate debate on an Atlanta public
television broadcasting channel that Democrat Michael Coles asked
him the key question _ about whether patients should have the right
to sue their HMOs or insurance companies _ that he should have
asked Republican Sen. Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   You can't blame that on the Libertarian, however.
</P>
<P>
   Coles brought the people featured in his recent commercials
about HMO abuses to the studio, and seemed to be setting this up as
a debate in which he'd attempt to paint Coverdell as the Senator
from Insurance. But then the self-made businessman meandered into
less vital arguments with Coverdell over his votes on PeachCare and
veterans benefits. He even took the bait and prolonged another full
airing of the regrettable drug test dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell proved to be a much more formidable debater than he
was when he faced incumbent Democrat Wyche Fowler in 1992. Six
years in the Senate has given him a more confident delivery, and he
still has his old canniness, as he showed when he declined to ask
Coles a question and further diminished the Democrat's air time.
</P>
<P>
   If Loftman hadn't been there Coles and Coverdell would have been
able to talk more, but that doesn't mean they would have said as
much.
</P>
<P>
   Loftman may not have had all the right answers, but he asked a
lot of the right questions. He forced the Democratic and Republican
candidates to talk about ideas, pushing them out of the rigid you
did-I didn't box that so many debates have become.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody sees today's political ads, Loftman says, and most who
could don't vote. He argues that limiting public debates only to
Democrats and Republicans simply deepens the alienation many voters
feel.
</P>
<P>
   In this month when the quality of the nation's political
dialogue appears destined to reach an all-time low, there's
something bracing about a candidate who'll stand up and advocate
the repeal of the 16th Amendment. Whether that's good idea or not,
it helps to create the sort of political debate you could let your
kids listen to.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution political editor Tom Baxter
provides opinion, analysis and commentary in his column.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
