u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SPENCER-COX     10-05 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SPENCER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yankee's newest hero just may be the real dea
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees have just eliminated the Texas Rangers in
three games, and the New York clubhouse stinks of champagne. Many
players are spraying bubbly at a teammate, who takes the dousing
with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer, a sticky mess from head to toe, is having the
time of his 26-year life. In the series with Texas, the rookie who
spent nine years in the minor leagues blasted two homers,
accounting for four of the club's nine runs, to continue his
stranger-than-fiction story.
</P>
<P>
   Forget Mantle and the Babe. New York's new player to toast is
more like Roy Hobbs, who shattered light towers with homers in
``The Natural,'' or Joe Hardy, who exchanged his soul for a shot at
stardom in ``Damn Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In 20 years, I don't think I've ever seen anything like
that,'' longtime Yankees owner George Steinbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Yankees manager Joe Torre: ``He doesn't ever seem to get
fazed.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer was not called up from the minors for good until
September. He proceeded to hit eight homers, including three grand
slams, in the last 10 days of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates said, ``I'll tell you what, he
doesn't get cheated. He knows what that piece of wood is made for,
and it's not for cleaning his teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball lore is filled with flukes. In 1957, Bob (Hurricane)
Hazle came up late in the season for the Milwaukee Braves, hit .403
with seven home runs in 41 games and played in the World Series.
But he appeared in only 63 more major league games.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer does not put himself in that category.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you were to ask anyone who has played with me, they
would say I am for real,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Braves scout Bill Lajoie, the right-hand man for Atlanta general
manager John Schuerholz, agrees. ``If you ask me, he looks like he
may be for real,'' he said. ``When I first saw him, he could hit
the heck out of pitches in on the belt buckle and not much else.
But now I'm seeing him hitting balls out off the plate, going the
other way, and basically showing he has a pretty good idea up
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some players require several seasons to develop. (Example: Sammy
Sosa.)
</P>
<P>
   But even the late bloomers usually do not take nine years to get
to the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't just get this all handed to me,'' Spencer said. ``I
worked my butt off to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer was not considered much as a prospect because, while he
had the ability to hit, he is slow and has a below-average arm.
</P>
<P>
   He signed with the Yankees in 1990 as a 28th-round pick out of
El Cajon (Calif.) who passed up a college football scholarship to
Utah and Montana and took a $25,000 signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't help himself early in his career when, at a minor
league spring training camp, he was laughing on the field when
Steinbrenner walked up behind him and asked him what was so funny.
Spencer froze, which pretty much described his career at the time.
He hit just three homers in his first 618 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Before the 1995 season, general manager Gene Michaels met with
Spencer and gave him an ultimatum. It was either start producing or
go elsewhere. Spencer got the message.
</P>
<P>
   During his sixth straight year at Class A, he learned how to hit
more than just the fastball, got stronger and extended his swing.
The result was a .300 average with 16 homers and 88 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   The organization started to notice and promoted him to Class AA
in 1996, where he hit 29 homers. Last year, he drilled 30 homers
for the Yankees' Class AAA team in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer again began this season at Columbus, but when Chili
Davis was hurt he got his first taste of the majors. He was
recalled and sent down three times before arriving in September to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas series began with Spencer on the bench as Chad Curtis
started. He got the start in Game 2 and put the Yankees ahead with
a solo homer.
</P>
<P>
   Then he put away the clinching game with a three-run homer in
the sixth inning. The ball didn't shatter lights, as Hobbs' did,
but Spencer still made headlines in the New York tabloids. One
summed up the game as a ``Shane-Saw Massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just grinning when he runs around the bases,'' Yankees
right fielder Paul O'Neill said. ``It's fun to see, especially for
a guy who's paid his dues in the minor leagues. You need stories
like that in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
