<SLUG> BC-GA-GAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PSC expected to allow 19 companies to market natural gas
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Today, Georgia's Public Service Commission is expected
to give the green light to 19 companies to immediately begin
selling natural gas to 1.4 million Georgians.
</P>
<P>
   The PSC is expected to follow a staff recommendation that all
the marketers' applications be approved, said spokesman Shawn
Davis. Conditions, however, may be added to some of the
certifications.
</P>
<P>
   The marketers will be permitted to start quoting prices and
making deals as soon as the commission acts at a morning meeting.
But TV ads planned by most major players do not begin until next
week.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is also expected to approve a multimillion-dollar
promotional campaign planned by Atlanta Gas Light Co. that is
intended to educate consumers about deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   The company wants to spend $12.3 million over two years and bill
ratepayers over a five-year period at a cost of $8.80 for each
residential and small-business customer, or $1.76 annually.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1997 law, Atlanta Gas Light will become a distribution
company responsible only for delivering gas to consumers over its
pipeline system. Marketers will take over the sale of the commodity
to AGL's 1.4 million customers at deregulated prices.
</P>
<P>
   In order for consumers to begin receiving gas when deregulation
begins Nov. 1, they will have to sign up with a marketing company
by Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   But it could take a year or more for deregulation to be fully
phased in. Consumers who do not choose a marketing company will be
assigned one at random by the PSC.
</P>
<P>
   A total 28 companies initially applied for certification to sell
gas. But nine withdrew their applications, including Houston-based
Enron Corp. and San Francisco-based PG&AMP;E, both major players in
national energy markets.
</P>
<P>
   Among those expected to receive approval today is the marketing
subsidiary of AGL Resources Inc., parent of Atlanta Gas Light Co.,
and affiliates of Shell Oil Co., South Carolina-based SCANA Energy,
Duke Energy, Florida Power &AMP; Light, Columbia Energy of Ohio and two
Georgia-based companies, Optimum Energy Sources and PS Energy
Group.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
