<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-PHONE-DEREG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    High court rules against Alltel in overcharge case
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The state's highest court has ruled Alltel must lower
rates to make up for about $50 million in overcharges, but Alltel
maintains the battle is not over.
</P>
<P>
   In a 4-3 decision announced Monday, the court endorsed the
Public Service Commission ruling, which had decided the rates
charged to Georgia customers by the Little Rock-based company in
1996 were excessive by about $24 million a year. The PSC ordered
the company cut rates, and the company filed suit to overturn that
order.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's Supreme Court decision apparently requires Alltel to
cut its access fees, which are charges paid by long-distance
companies. Those reductions are supposed to be passed on to
customers. Alltel has 446,000 local telephone customers in Georgia
_ most of them rural.
</P>
<P>
   But the company believes it is ``questionable'' whether those
customers would see rate reductions, arguing long-distance
companies are not compelled to trim their rates, said Skip Frantz,
Alltel executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Phone company rates in Georgia have typically been overseen by
the PSC, which would permit a set profit. But 1995 changes in the
law allowed companies to shift to new rules that allow greater
flexibility in how rates are set. When Alltel filed for the right
to change, the PSC investigated and found its earnings excessive.
</P>
<P>
   Alltel argued the PSC lost its authority to investigate its
rates the moment the company's request was filed for operating
under the new rules. The PSC argued it had 30 days to take a look.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled the PSC was right, upholding a previous
decision by the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Alltel has filed a motion asking the Supreme Court to reconsider
the issue and reverse itself. ``This was a very narrowly decided
opinion, with a strong dissent,'' Frantz said. But should the court
reject that motion, the case would return to Fulton County Superior
Court, where the suit began. Alltel believes it can still prevail
by arguing other issues on which the justices did not rule, Frantz
said.
</P>
<P>
   PSC spokesman Shawn Davis said a reversal at the lower court is
unlikely. ``I think the primary issues have been decided by the
Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
