<SLUG> BC-JUDICIARY-BARR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr on Clinton investigation: 'A cancer on the presidency'
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Georgia Republican Bob Barr stayed true to his
feisty form Monday as one of President Clinton's most outspoken
critics. As the House Judiciary Committee contemplated whether to
begin an impeachment inquiry, Barr sounded like someone ready for a
final vote on the president's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are witnessing nothing less than the symptoms of a cancer
on the American presidency,'' Barr said, adapting a memorable
phrase from Watergate on a day rife with comparisons to that
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's colleagues in both parties warned against judging Clinton
prematurely, lest the American public reject the process as overly
partisan.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, the 49-year-old former federal prosecutor, assumed as fact
several pieces of information that are very much in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Paula Jones's claim that Clinton harassed her
sexually when he was governor of Arkansas, Barr offered a summation
of the case against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton, first as governor and then as president, using
power entrusted to him, coarsely demanded personal favors from
individual citizens,'' he said. ``Yet instead of apologizing, Bill
Clinton continued to abuse his office to smear that citizen's name
and block her access to justice. Instead of telling the truth to
the court and a grand jury, the president lied. Instead of
cooperating with the court, he obstructed its efforts. At this very
moment, government and private employees are working under his
direct orders to block this committee's effort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The graphic nature of Starr's report was unavoidable, Barr said,
because of Clinton's ``sorry attempt to deny reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27th speaker on a momentous morning, Barr infused his talk
with dire references to the future of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the ability to destroy one life or billions,'' Barr
said of Clinton and his role as commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, Barr said, ``If we fail to address such
charges, we will soon be left standing dazed and befuddled among
the smoldering ruins of a great democracy,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   He also invited any Clinton defenders who would argue the
president's behavior does not matter to ``summon up whatever
tattered remains of honor they have left,'' and leave the room.
</P>
<P>
   No one took him up on that.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
