<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLFCAMERA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wolf Camera to buy chain in Colorado
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The buying spree continues for Wolf Camera, which said
it will acquire Waxman Camera, a 16-store specialty photo chain in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes just weeks after Wolf closed its purchase
of Eastman Kodak's 449-store Fox Photo chain and is the latest in a
string of acquisitions that has increased the company's store base
150 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Terms were not disclosed for the purchase, which more than
doubles Wolf's presence in Colorado and advances the retailer's
strategy of acquiring well-established independent photo dealers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waxman is to the Denver and Boulder area what Wolf is to
Atlanta,'' said Wayne Freedman, senior vice president of marketing
for Wolf, which has its corporate offices in Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf is closing in on Beltsville, Md.-based Ritz Camera, the
country's largest photo retailer with 810 stores. With Waxman, Wolf
will have 766 stores in 34 states. Wolf began the year with 300
stores.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of the largest photo retailers have rapidly
consolidated the industry as it faces mounting competition from
mass merchants. Drugstores, in particular, have cut into the
customer base as they increasingly open one-hour photo processing
labs. And new technology such as digital photography and 24mm film
is making it too expensive for smaller retailers to operate.
</P>
<P>
   The mergers could be winding down, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to survive is to combine, but with all of the
recent consolidation, there aren't that many specialty retailers
left,'' Freedman said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
