<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0744 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOW-06-COX     10-05 0412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nasdaq takes a drubbing
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Investors continued to show their disappointment at
economic policy-makers on Monday with widespread selling, although
late bargain-hunting narrowed losses among the blue-chip stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The late rally did not help technology stocks as much. There,
the selling gave the Nasdaq composite its fifth worst point
decline. The index lost 4.85 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The targets of investor ire Monday were finance ministers and
central bankers of the world's industrialized nations, who failed
over the weekend to agree on a financial package to rescue troubled
economies in Asia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, investors were disappointed at the Federal Reserve,
whose quarter-percentage-point cut in short-term interest rates was
regarded as too small to protect the U.S. economy from the threat
of a globally-induced recession.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, two of the market's staunchest bulls continued to
make optimistic forecasts in advance of this month's release of
third-quarter earnings reports, Dow Jones News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs' strategist Abby Joseph Cohen told the National
Association of Business Economists that investors might be in for a
``pleasant surprise'' from 1999 corporate earnings, when profits
are compared with weaker year-earlier numbers. She said ``operating
profit growth has decelerated but remains positive.''
</P>
<P>
   A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons chief market strategist Alfred Goldman,
meanwhile, said the market's sell-off on Monday may set the stage
for a rebound that could take the Dow to 9,000 by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   That would be about 338 points below the Dow's all-time high on
July 17, but well above the recent trading range of 7,600 to 8,100.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman said investor sentiment is ``extremely pessimistic and
stocks are very oversold,'' which are preconditions for a rebound
in the market.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow fell as much as 233 points on Monday before late buying
narrowed the loss to 58.45 points. Last week the index fell more
than 200 points on Wednesday and again Thursday before rallying by
152 points on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market continued to attract investors looking for a
safe haven, which pushed yields on the bellwether 30-year Treasury
bond to an all-time low of 4.72 percent, just four days after the
yield dropped below 5 percent for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
