<P>
   EMBASSY-BOMBER (Moroni, Comoros Islands) _ Nearly two months
after the bombings of the American embassy in Kenya and Tanzania, a
picture of those charged in the case is slowly emerging. They
hailed from different countries, labored in various professions but
shared a devotion to radical Islam and a striking ability to keep
family and friends in the dark about what American prosecutors
charge were their true activities. Comoran officials are
embarrassed that Abdallah Mohammed Fazul (who was indicted in the
United States under the name ``Haroun Fazil,'' an alias he
apparently used in Kenya) has turned the world's eyes on them. But
they say he is a true product of the forces that shaped his
tropical nation -- poverty, Islam, racism, and French colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GOVS-RACES (Atlanta) _ With governor's races in 36 states,
including each of the eight largest, this year's campaigns will
determine whether the Republican Party maintains the remarkable
hegemony it has gained in statehouses over the last four years. By
Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `p' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OVER-THE-HILL-GANG (New York) _ Five men from Brooklyn are
arrested for a series of burglaries in the New York City region
that may date back 15 or 20 years. The men were characterized by
some as the ``Smash and Grab Gang,'' because they would typically
break one window and be out with jewelry, furs, money and antiques
and be out of the house in less than 5 minutes. But one prosecutor
today called them ``The Over-the-Hill Gang,'' because they are all
in their 50s. One has had a stroke and is in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 9 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
