<SLUG> BC-MA-EMIGRE-FRAUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBERS TO REVIEW ALLEGATIONS AGAINST RUSSIAN EMIGRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Insurance investigators will take a closer look into
allegations that 11 recent emigres from Russia and a
Brookline-based insurance agent conspired to file more than
$150,000 in questionable claims against defraud Trust Insurance Co.
of Taunton for staged or phony accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Skelly, chief of the Insurance Fraud Bureau of
Massachusetts, said Monday that the case, which prompted a civil
law suit filed by Trust last month, will be assigned to bureau
investigators this week.
</P>
<P>
   Skelly said his investigators checked the allegations several
months ago when Trust brought them to his attention. At the time,
his agency determined there was not enough evidence to build a
solid criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot more to prove a criminal case than it does a
civil one, so it may be that we cannot proceed,'' Skelly said.
``But the allegations are serious enough that we'll take another
look.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency, could recommend that the Attorney General's office
prosecute the case if the investigators find evidence of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Trust's lawsuit alleged that the Gene Dvorkin Insurance Agency,
who wrote policies for Trust, had sold autombile insurance in 1995
and 1996 to 11 people _ all recent arrivals from Russia who listed
a single apartment in Framingham as their address.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the group has been traced to previous addresses in
Brooklyn and New York City when the policies were sold. During the
next two years, the group began filing more than $150,000 in
medical and property claims for accidents that mostly took place in
the New York City area.
</P>
<P>
   In its investigation, Trust concluded that the accidents either
did not happen or were staged. It also found that the claimed
injuries were non-existent or were far less severe than warranted
by the prescribed medical treatment, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Dvorkin, who sells auto insurance to approximately 2,000 Russian
immigrants living in metropolitan Boston, has denied that he had
willingly participated in any fraudulent scheme.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Trust had sued him in retaliation for contesting a
company policy which automatically bars safe-driver credits to
recent emigres seeking auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Trust executives denied Dvorkin's charge and maintained the
lawsuit is part of its ongoing fight against fraudulent claims. But
they acknowledged that Trust was looking to drop Dvorkin and four
other independent agents who write policies in high-risk
neighborhoods because they allegedly failed to abide by industry
guidelines _ including inaccurate records and failing to cancel
policies for non-payment of premiums.
</P>
<P>
   That effort was derailed, however, when Dvorkin and several
other agents went to Commonwealth Autombile Reinsurers _ a
little-noticed, quasi-public organization that oversees insurers'
high-risk pool. They complained that Trust ignored state
regulations when it refused to give safe-driver credits to recent
emigres.
</P>
<P>
   William E. Ryan, Trust's assistant vice president for
governmental affairs, said the dispute underscores the need for
legislation that would set out clear, consumer-oriented rules of
procedure for CAR's operation. Such legislation has passed the
Senate but is stuck in the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William R. Keating (D-Sharon), the bill's sponsor, said the
way CAR currently operates ``is far too arbitrary and away from
public scrutiny. It is in the public's interest for insurance
companies to fight fraud vigorously and for that to happen there
has to be clear rules of procedure within CAR.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
