<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACHMENT-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL VOTES TO HOLD IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: SUBS grafs 1-3 with committee vote; adds optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A deeply divided House Judiciary Committee on
Monday authorized an impeachment inquiry against President Clinton
for lying and obstruction of justice in the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-dominated committee voted 21-16, along party
lines, to approve the inquiry, which the full House is expected to
approve later this week. It would be the third time in U.S. history
that the House has considered impeachment proceedings against a
sitting president.
</P>
<P>
   Despite efforts by Democrats to set a deadline for the
investigation, the resolution contains no limits on the time or
subject of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   During a day-long marathon hearing, Republicans argued that as
commander in chief, President Clinton must be held to the highest
standards in terms of his personal conduct and adherence to the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are constantly reminded how weary America is of this whole
situation and I daresay most of us share that weariness,'' said
Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill. Nevertheless, he
added, ``it is imperative we be able to look back at this episode
with dignity and pride, knowing we have performed our duty in the
best interest of the entire country.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats countered that Clinton's effort to hide his sexual
relationship with Lewinsky was evidence of nothing more than a man
covering the tracks of a personal indiscretion, hardly the stuff of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Watergate, it's an extramarital affair,'' said the
committee's senior Democrat, Rep. John Conyers of Michigan. Conyers
is the only committee member who was on the panel the last time it
authorized an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's vote that day, Jan. 31, 1974, set in motion
impeachment hearings on the Watergate scandal that preceded the
resignation of President Richard Nixon seven months later. More
than 100 years before that, the House voted to impeach President
Andrew Johnson. The Senate in 1868 fell one vote shy of removing
Johnson from office.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Republicans turned back two alternative Democratic
resolutions. The first would have set a deadline of Nov. 25 for the
inquiry unless the House granted an extension, and would have
required the committee to hold hearings on the Constitution's
standards for impeachment before determining whether any of
Clinton's actions are impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   The second would have declared the Sept. 11 report of
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr on the Clinton-Lewinsky affair to
be fact. Then the committee could focus on whether the Starr report
_ the basis for the impeachment inquiry _ is sufficient grounds for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the committee Republicans' top investigator, David
Schippers, set out 15 instances in which Clinton's conduct in the
Lewinsky matter ``may constitute grounds to proceed with an
impeachment inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   They covered most of the now-familiar elements of the affair as
documented in Starr's report to Congress, as well as the thousands
of pages of grand jury transcripts and documents the committee
released in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Among the charges in the Schippers report: Clinton lied under
oath during his January deposition in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit, and his August grand jury testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The report also accuses Clinton of conspiring with Lewinsky to
concoct a ``cover story'' to conceal their relationship, hiding
gifts to Lewinsky, and helping her find a job in New York in
exchange for silence.
</P>
<P>
   But Schippers dropped two of the 11 grounds for impeachment
cited by Starr in his Sept. 11 referral. Starr had accused Clinton
of abusing his constitutional authority and obstructing justice by
refusing to testify before the grand jury for seven months and
lying to White House aides, who repeated his false statements.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the committee's Democrats, Abbe Lowell, countered
that a ``laundry list'' of laws Clinton may have broken is
insufficient for the Constitution's impeachment standard of ``high
crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all offenses are `high crimes and misdemeanors,' and not
all `high crimes and misdemeanors' come from criminal conduct,'' he
said, quoting founding father George Mason as saying impeachment is
for ``great and dangerous offenses to subvert the Constitution,''
and Alexander Hamilton: Impeachment remedies ``injuries done
immediately to the society itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's misstatements in the Jones deposition about his
relationship with Lewinsky were irrelevant because the federal
judge in that case, Susan Webber Wright, ruled in January that the
Clinton-Lewinsky relationship was ``not essential'' to resolving
the Jones case, Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   And Starr's report did not include Lewinsky's statement that
``no one asked me to lie, and I was never promised a job for my
silence,'' Lowell added.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the hearing opened, Republicans focused their attack on
perjury charges against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president serves as a role model for us and our
children,'' said Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas. ``He influences the
lives of millions of Americans ... Actions do have consequences;
the difference between right and wrong still exists; and honesty
always counts.''
</P>
<P>
   In a reference to former White House Counsel John Dean's
statement to Nixon during Watergate that a ``cancer'' was growing
on the presidency, Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., said the nation is
``witnessing nothing less than the symptoms of a cancer on the
presidency. If we fail to remove this cancer, it will expand and
destroy the principles that matter most to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats concentrated their fire on Starr and their view that
impeachment is only for serious misdeeds that threaten the nation's
political fabric, not a president's indiscretion with a young White
House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president had an affair,'' said Rep. Robert Wexler,
D-Fla., his voice rising in emotion to a shout. ``He lied about it.
He didn't want anyone to know about it. Does anyone reasonably
believe that this amounts to a subversion of government? Does
anyone reasonably believe that this is what the Founding Fathers
were talking about?''
</P>
<P>
   Wexler called Starr's four-year probe of Clinton that culminated
in the Lewinsky report a ``politically inspired witch-hunt that
rivals McCarthyism in its sinister purpose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
