<HEADER>
A0767 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-HUMOR-ART-670&AMP;     10-05 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-HUMOR-ART-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RUBLE IS ON A TILT, BUT THE RUSSIANS ARE KEEPING THEIR BALANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo of Viktor Shenderovich, the Moscow radio-TV
personality, is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(fb) 
By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It's drive time, and Muscovites are heading home after
another day of crisis. After the news, all of it bad, an ad comes
on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruble is falling,'' says the cheerful voice from a private
dental clinic, ``but with us, at least your teeth will stay in
place.''
</P>
<P>
   The next ad urges crisis-weary listeners to get away from it all
and book a Turkish vacation, now just a dream for what was once
Moscow's middle class. The music starts again. The first song,
sponsored by a cellular phone company now battling to hold on to
its newly poor clientele, is ``Sacrifice'' by Elton John.
</P>
<P>
   So goes another crisis in Russia, a time when people dip into
deep national reserves of fatalism and retrieve a special mix of
resolve and self-deprecating humor that thrives best when things go
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``A crisis is nothing special for Russians,'' said Viktor
Shenderovich, creator of the popular satirical show ``Puppets,''
who spent two hours telling old and new jokes at a Moscow supper
club recently. ``As long as no one is shooting at us or sending us
to labor camps, as long as we can find food for our children, we
just live life as we have always lived it.''
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did the ruble collapse, businesses close down and
inflation shoot up than the jokes started flowing, along with a
steady stream of practical advice on how to cope with the stress of
it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing your job is always a stimulus for new projects,'' says
Profil magazine, a weekly that not so long ago catered to the whims
of Moscow's free-spending arrivistes. ``So, you ask, what do we
eat? Almost every normal person has some money set aside for black
days.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein of roll-with-the-punches advice, the magazine
dropped its usual review of high-fashion boutiques and steered
readers to a more useful line of shopping _ ``armored equipment for
home use.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last month we have become decisively convinced that
keeping money in the bank is an inadmissible luxury,'' wrote the
writer of the Let's Go Shopping section. ``It's better to keep your
treasures at home, `in your sock,' according to the old Russian
tradition. But you can also keep it in a safe. This is much more
modern and reliable.''
</P>
<P>
   The jokes, told on the air, on the streets and in the corridors
of Parliament, are also about the gathering gloom. One businessman
calls another to check in on how he's doing. ``Great,'' comes the
answer. ``Sorry, wrong number,'' the caller says and hangs up.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the one about the woman who walks up to the teller
at a bank. ``Whom do I see about opening a bank account?'' she
asks. ``A psychiatrist,'' comes the answer.
</P>
<P>
   There are old jokes, recycled to fit today's leaders. President
Boris Yeltsin addresses the nation. ``For years we have stood on
the edge of an abyss. Now, fellow countrymen, we have taken a great
step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to crisis, Russians will boast that they are
world-class professionals. The elderly remember World War II and
stock up on buckwheat, potatoes, salt and matches. Housewives,
wedded to the joy of a newly acquired washing machine, buy boxes of
imported detergent. Young couples, aghast at the thought of washing
dirty diapers, stuff their wardrobes with the disposable variety,
which appeared in Russian stores only a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Having taken care of the essentials, people settle in for the
long haul _ in this case, bracing themselves for another round of
inflation like the one that emptied their pocketbooks in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back to the future'' is the popular phrase among television
commentators and headline writers, which often give a sarcastic
twist to the day's events. (A recent front-page headline in
Argumenty i Fakty, Russia's most popular newspaper: ``If the Crisis
Is All in People's Heads, Why Hit Them on the Head So Hard?'')
</P>
<P>
   ``People are again discussing how many pounds of potatoes a
balcony can hold before it collapses,'' was the wry comment from
Mikhail Osokin, a television anchor, at the end of a recent evening
broadcast.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One of the unnerving aspects of this crisis is how invisible it
is. Even when people were rushing to their banks trying to withdraw
their savings, they did so in quiet clumps while other Muscovites
walked briskly by, seemingly unperturbed.
</P>
<P>
   On the night that Shenderovich was telling funny stories, the
atmosphere at Petrovich _ a basement supper club named after an
Everyman cartoon character _ could have been a scene from the ``new
Russia,'' the period, now ending, when this city seemed to be
inching its way to normality. Mobile phones still jingled during
his monologues as he mocked, in turn, Russia's new rich, old-style
bureaucrats and out-of-touch politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But the well-dressed crowd laughed easily at the jokes, even
when they were about people like themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Russians are not in places like this,'' said Elena
Korjenevich, 22, a marketing specialist for Coca-Cola, who had
joined friends for an evening out. ``They are home in their
kitchens. The ones who are here are thinking about today. If they
have money, they spend it. They don't think about tomorrow. It is
the crisis psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, despite the outward calm, there are inklings of panic.
But like dissidence in Soviet times, panic here takes place
privately, at home.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 534 Muscovites reached by telephone by the Russian
Market Research Company found that 61 percent had been hard-hit by
the crisis, either because of salary cuts, loss of savings or a
job. Only 7 percent said they had avoided its impact.
</P>
<P>
   Every third family said they had tried to stockpile food,
fearing shortages and price rises in equal measure. Twenty-two
percent of those questioned said they had ``general feelings of
agitation, or even panic.''
</P>
<P>
   The first rush to stock up kitchen shelves, wardrobes and
balconies with all sorts of goods has subsided somewhat, followed
by price shock. With some domestically produced foods, goods and
services still holding at previous levels, consumers are once again
faced with a dizzying dislocation of prices. Six pounds of meat
bought at a local market can cost as much as a bottle of imported
shampoo. A pack of chewing gum costs as much as two loaves of
bread.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is particularly funny, but people make do, counting
on their own ability to survive. How the country as a whole will
fare is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   One joke making the rounds sets out two scenarios for Russia's
escape from its current predicament. The more optimistic of the two
is that aliens arrive from another planet to sort out the crisis.
The second, more pessimistic version has Russia saving itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 2014EDT &QL; 
