<HEADLINE>
NATO FINDS GREATER ROLE IN BOSNIA FOR ITALIAN POLICE UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ When an angry crowd of Bosnian
Croats put up a roadblock on the main road south of Mostar the
other day, commanders of NATO's peacekeeping force here refrained
from flooding the area with their troops, as they might have not
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they sent in the Carabinieri.
</P>
<P>
   In a subtle, scarcely noted shift in NATO's operations, the
Carabinieri Corps, Italy's domestic military police force, has
arrived in Bosnia to form the core of a new battalion that NATO's
commanders hope will take on the sorts of law-enforcement jobs they
are loath to give their combat forces _ from quashing riots to
protecting refugees trying to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The battalion, known as the Multinational Specialized Unit,
includes some 380 Carabinieri officers, as well as 70 gendarmes
from Argentina and 23 military policemen from Romania. All of them
have been trained in their own countries to act, essentially, as
domestic armies, trained to deal as much with civilians as with
enemy troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The true military tasks are finished here,'' said the
battalion's commander, Col. Leonardo Leso of the Carabinieri.
``Now, Bosnia and Herzegovina needs to restore the public order.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has no domestic force like the Carabinieri and
has not contributed troops to the new unit, except for a couple of
liaison officers at the unit's headquarters at a base near the
capital, Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO's American commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark, strongly
advocated the creation of the force, saying it fills a gap between
NATO's force and the local authorities who are supposed to enforce
the civilian aspects of the Dayton peace accords. Secretary of
Defense William Cohen also went to lengths to highlight the unit
during his recent visit to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three years after the arrival of NATO's peacekeeping
force, the unit's paramilitary approach may offer a largely
European alternative to keeping large numbers of combat troops in
Bosnia. There are roughly 33,000 NATO-led troops there now,
including 7,700 Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those forces are more capable of providing the kind of broad
support to civil implementation that's required,'' General Clark
said in a recent interview.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The battalion remains a part of NATO's Stabilization Force and
still operates under its command. Its first units arrived in
August, but its first operations began, uneventfully, during
Bosnia's national elections last month. The operation the other day
was the first that involved violence.
</P>
<P>
   The battalion's troops arrived after a group of Bosnian Croats,
including women and children, blocked the main road south of Mostar
to protest an attempt by Muslim refugees to return to their homes
near the village of Capljina. Although the Dayton accords provide
refugees the right to return, the local Bosnian Croat police did
nothing to intervene, NATO officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Carabinieri arrived, two hours of negotiations followed
before the troops forcibly cleared the road. In the melee three
soldiers were hit by stones, but none were seriously wounded, a
NATO spokesman, Maj. Richard Saint Louis, said.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the size of the battalion is likely to grow as
NATO's commanders put more emphasis on operations like escorting
refugees or war crimes investigators. Slovenia has pledged to
provide forces to the battalion, and others with similar forces at
home, like Spain and France, are also expected to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   Leso said that as NATO's role in Bosnia evolved from enforcing
the peace to rebuilding the country's shattered society, the
battalion would be used more and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more means to convince people,'' he said. ``We can
shout or shoot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
