<HEADLINE>
HARLEM RENAISSANCE BLOOMS IN `BLUES FOR AN ALABAMA SKY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Pearl Cleage brings a fresh slant to the fabled Harlem
Renaissance in ``Blues for an Alabama Sky,'' her neatly written
play making its Houston debut in an able production at the Ensemble
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Writers such as Langston Hughes, Claude McKay, Countee Cullen,
Zora Neale Hurston and Jean Toomer (among others) set the stage for
Harlem's creative surge of the 1920s _ producing the first
significant body of work describing black life from a black
perspective. Amid the daring and social ferment of the '20s, other
figures rose to prominence, such as entertainer Josephine Baker,
who became the toast of Paris. For a time among certain circles, as
Hughes put it, ``the Negro was in vogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cleage sets her play in 1930, as the Depression tightens its
grip and the high-stepping of the 1920s gives way to the sober
trudge through the 1930s. Cleage peoples her play with colorful,
diverse and believable characters, depicting varied attitudes and
philosophies within the black community.
</P>
<P>
   Touched by the spirit of the Harlem Renaissance, yet realizing
change is in the air, these characters are at the point of making
changes in their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   The play's center is the loving, platonic relationship between
showgirl Angel and costume designer Guy, soul mates who fled
together to Harlem from the rural South. It's clear that Angel
would like their relationship to be more than platonic, but Guy, a
self-described ``notorious homosexual,'' is equally clear about his
own identity.
</P>
<P>
   As the play begins, Angel has just been dumped by her gangster
boyfriend and lost her job at the nightclub. Guy has lost his
position, too, by standing up for Angel. But he assures Angel that
all will be well; he has been sending costume sketches to Baker in
Paris and expects that, any day, she will summon him to become her
designer. Angel has heard Guy's big dream before _ and doubts it
will become reality.
</P>
<P>
   Delia, a friend who lives in the flat across the hall, is a
genteel crusader for women's rights, a disciple of Margaret Sanger
working to establish the first birth control clinic in Harlem. Sam,
known as ``Doc,'' is the hard-working, hard-drinking physician who
offers to assist Delia in her campaign for family planning. In the
process, and rather unexpectedly for both, they fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   Into the midst of this free-thinking set comes Leland, an
old-fashioned country boy newly arrived from Alabama, who begins a
flirtation with Angel. Weary of her string of gangster boyfriends
and her past as a prostitute, Angel is ready to fall for the
gentlemanly Leland.
</P>
<P>
   But Leland's narrow views put him on a collision course with
Angel and her friends, for things like homosexuality, birth control
and abortion are beyond his ken. The clash guarantees a bumpy
course for Angel and Leland's romance, also setting the stage for a
tragic turn.
</P>
<P>
   Cleage, whose ``Flyin' West'' was seen at the Ensemble in 1995,
has filled ``Blues for an Alabama Sky'' with strong writing. The
characters are well-rounded, persuasive and appealing. The action
rings true. The dialogue is natural and flavorful, with many
standout passages: the wry banter between Angel and Guy, the sexy
flirtation of Angel and Leland, the skillfully underwritten love
scene between Delia and Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Cleage suggests the larger social currents of a volatile period,
raising issues still valid today.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Morris has directed Cleage's script naturally and
unobtrusively, bringing thoughtfulness to the play's issues and
delicacy to the well-limned relationships.
</P>
<P>
   An excellent cast brings Cleage's characters to vivid life with
no false notes. BeBe Wilson is marvelous as Angel _ tough, saucy,
just a bit soured on things but still resilient.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Washington understates deftly as Guy _ natural, relaxed,
appealing and self-aware.
</P>
<P>
   Melita Hawkins makes a fine Delia. She reflects the sense and
sweetness of a devoted crusader who is herself demure, reticent and
ladylike.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Stansberry brings a quiet strength and seriousness to Sam,
the ``Doc'' who pragmatically faces matters of life and death, but
just as pragmatically recognizes that when he is off duty, it is
time to ``let the good times roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert J. Marshall plays Leland with affable, well-meaning
earnestness, but also makes it clear that he is on a different
wavelength, bewildered by his new Harlem set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blues for an Alabama Sky'' is a refreshing look at a
fascinating time and place in the American experience, a welcome
depiction of black lives not usually explored on stage or screen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
