<HEADLINE>
STAMP HONORS ERA, NOT THE PEOPLE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   D &UR; orothea Lange &LR; 's heartbreaking photo ``Migrant Mother'' is the
image on one of 15 stamps honoring the '30s, issued with fanfare
last month by the Postal Service. This week, a woman who as a
little girl is pictured on the stamp said she was disappointed that
her late mother, who raised a family during the toughest decade of
the century, received less attention than the imaginary hero
Superman.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph, taken by Lange in 1936 for the Farm Security
Administration, featured  &UR; Florence Thompson &LR;  of Modesto (who died
in 1983) with three daughters.  &UR; Ruby Sprague, &LR;  (on the right), &LR;  has
died of cancer;  &UR; Katherine McIntosh &LR;  (on the left) and  &UR; Norma &LR; 
 &UR; Rydlewski &LR;  (in Thompson's arms) are still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very uncommon for the Postal Service to print stamps of
individuals who have not been dead for at least 10 years,'' reader
 &UR; Emmett Corrigan &LR;  wrote a few days ago. ``Never heard of it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Horace Hinshaw  &LR; of the Postal Service insists that the stamp
isn't honoring the people it depicts ``but rather the event: the
Depression era. ... To be honored with a stamp, a person must have
been deceased for 10 years, with the exception of a past president.
... There is no stamp that features people who are still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh, 67 sees it differently: If the photo was about an era,
the era was about the people who endured it. McIntosh, who lives in
Modesto and works for Frito-Lay, says the Postal Service hasn't
properly honored her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the year, when the subjects were asked for permission
to use the picture, they agreed to keep the news quiet. Then they
learned that first-day-of-issue ceremonies would take place in
September in Cleveland, &LR;  because Superman, one of the other stamp
``honorees,'' had first been drawn there. McIntosh and Rydlewski
paid their own way to be on hand.
</P>
<P>
   During the festivities, however, ``there was nothing mentioned
that we were there,'' McIntosh told Personals. ``We were very
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to honor Mother, but it was all for Superman. He's a
fictitious character. We were very upset.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh says she can't understand the Postal Service's
insistence that the image is not about people.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother's picture shows up everywhere, she said, ``even in
Russia, I've heard. And my little grandson has a dictionary in his
school, and under the word `haggard' is that picture. Her face will
never be forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The Yale Daily News has joined the Georgetown student
newspaper in calling on  &UR; President Clinton &LR; , an alumnus of both
institutions, to resign. Nonetheless, Bill and  &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR; 
are planning to attend their 25th reunion at Yale Law School next
week. ``People are entitled to their views,'' White House
spokeswoman  &UR; Amy Weiss &LR;  told the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Bozeman, Mont., Judge  &UR; Frank Davis  &LR; has ruled that  &UR; Pat &LR; 
 &UR; Shannon &LR; , who had a 29-year affair with  &UR; Charles Kuralt &LR; , is not
entitled to a painting, a desk, a desk chair and a rug. The judge
had ruled earlier that she wasn't entitled to 90 acres of land
around a house she and Kuralt had occupied.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the state senatorial race, District 40, Democrat &UR; Steve &LR; 
 &UR; Peace  &LR; is running against Republican  &UR; Bob &LR;   &UR; Divine &LR; .  &UR; J.P. Murphy &LR; 
 &UR; III &LR;  is envisioning their version of mudslinging debates: ``You go
first.'' ``No, you first. I insist.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHANGHAI DIARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Greg Chew &LR;  of Day Advertising, who went with  &UR; Willie Brown &LR;  to
Shanghai last week, reports a few highlights:
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at welcoming ceremonies gasped at the arrival of a
motorized cable car, complete with bell-ringer; spectators at a
fashion show were awestruck by the participation of sole male model
 &UR; Willie Brown &LR; , who was decked out in green silk, ``almost but not
quite an emperor's outfit,'' said Chew; the masses at a San
Francisco food and wine reception consumed Mexican food, Chinese
food (!), delicacies from Fisherman's Wharf and Gallo Cabernet
Sauvignon.
</P>
