<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TV COVERED THE IMPEACHMENT DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The impeachment debate in the House Judiciary Committee received
gavel to gavel coverage on cable news channels Monday, and a few
minutes of live coverage on the ABC network. Neither NBC nor CBS
had any live coverage of the debate, though the two networks did
provide a form of live coverage Monday night for the vote by the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   CBS interrupted its programming for five minutes to cover the
vote, and NBC used a part of its screen for a written report on the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ABC spokeswoman Eileen Murphy said that because of ``Monday
Night Football,'' the network would not do a live report on the
vote. But the network's ``Nightline'' program was to be based on
the debate last night.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC, Fox News and Court TV provided live coverage.
</P>
<P>
   CNN also focused most of its attention during the day on the
debate, though it did break away for regular programs like its
legal discussion program, ``Burden of Proof,'' which focused on the
debate, as well as for brief reports on other stories in the news.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
