<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0857 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HOUSE-BOS &LR;      10-05 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OK'S IMPEACHMENT PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee, poised to launch
historic proceedings that a Republican member warned ``will be a
difficult ordeal for all Americans,'' voted Monday night to
recommend a full-scale inquiry into whether President Clinton's
alleged attempt to cover up an extramarital affair warrants his
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled panel, nearly unanimous in disdain for
Clinton's misdeeds but deeply divided over how to punish him, voted
21-16, along party lines, to seek an open-ended impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-hour skirmish that foreshadowed a prolonged partisan
showdown over the sex scandal, the panel called for the inquiry
after its chief Republican lawyer, David P. Schippers, asserted
there is ``substantial credible evidence of 15 separate events
involving President William Jefferson Clinton that could constitute
felonies'' and grounds for his possible impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to approve the committee's recommendation
by the end of the week, setting up the third presidential
impeachment investigation in US history.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has denied the charges, including several counts of
perjury, attempts to obstruct justice, and witness tampering. But
no one, not even members of the president's inner circle, expects
him to emerge unscathed from the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is also bracing for a possible backlash as the
potentially explosive investigation unfolds. ``This will be an
emotional process, a strenuous process,'' said the committee's
chairman, Representative Henry J. Hyde of Illinois. But Hyde urged
his colleagues not to abdicate their ``inescapable responsibility''
to conduct the high-stakes inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Before the final vote Monday night, the committee voted along
party lines to reject several Democratic alternatives to the GOP
plan, including a proposal that would have set a Thanksgiving
deadline for the probe. Although the GOP plan sets no deadline,
Hyde has said he hopes to complete the inquiry by New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic amendments also would have required the panel to
determine what constitutes an impeachable offense before lawmakers
launch the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all I know, there may be grounds for an inquiry,'' said
Representative William D. Delahunt, a Quincy Democrat. ``But before
the committee authorizes proceedings that will further traumatize
the nation and distract us from the people's business, we must
satisfy ourselves that there is probable cause to recommend an
inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde led the opposition to the Democratic proposal, saying the
GOP plan includes the standards the Judiciary Committee followed
when Democrats controlled the panel during the Watergate hearings
in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, said Representative Lindsey O. Graham, a South
Carolina Republican, Clinton's fate may turn on whether the
committee determines the allegations stemming from his illicit
affair with former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky are more
similar to ``Watergate or Peyton Place.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was clear to many Democrats. Waving a copy of the
Constitution above him, Representative Robert Wexler of Florida
accused the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr, of conducting
``a politically inspired witch hunt that rivals McCarthyism.''
</P>
<P>
   Wexler asserted the Lewinsky-related charges do not constitute
``high crimes and misdemeanors,'' the standard for impeachment.
``Impeachment is not about adultery,'' Wexler shouted. ``It is
about subversion of government. The president had an affair. He
lied about it ... . Does anybody reasonably believe that this
amounts to subversion of government?''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's GOP legal staff agreed that two of Starr's 11
allegations that Clinton committed possibly impeachable offenses
did not warrant the panel's scrutiny. Rather than pursue charges
that Clinton abused the power of his office by essentially
asserting his legal rights, Hyde indicated the panel will dismiss
them.
</P>
<P>
   But Schippers added several other counts to Starr's array of
charges. Notable among them was an allegation that Clinton engaged
in a conspiracy with Lewinsky and others to obstruct justice by
trying to conceal their sexual liaisons. Schippers did not name
anyone as a co-conspirator, although he described Clinton's friend,
Vernon E. Jordan, and his White House secretary, Betty Currie, as
active participants in activities related to the alleged
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky has received immunity from prosecution in exchange for
her testimony about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Schippers' additional charges involved Clinton's alleged
perjury and other purported efforts to conceal the Lewinsky affair
from lawyers in the former sexual harassment case brought against
him by Paula Corbin Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The new charges also involved Clinton's testimony in August to a
federal grand jury investigating his affair with Lewinsky.
Schippers alleged, for example, that Clinton may have lied to the
grand jury when he testified that Lewinsky's false affidavit in the
Jones case was ``absolutely true.''
</P>
<P>
   Schippers triggered outrage among several committee Democrats
when he ended his presentation by warning the panel about the
gravity of the allegations against Clinton. He said they should
honor the spirit of ``15 generations of Americans, many of whom
repose in military cemeteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid protests from Democrats, Hyde ordered Schippers' comments
stricken from the official record. However, Representative Bob
Barr, a Georgia Republican who ranks among Clinton's leading foes,
later adopted Schippers' comments as his own and inserted them in
the committee record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are witnessing nothing less than the symptoms of a cancer
on the American presidency ...,'' Barr had said earlier in the
hearing. ``If we fail to address such charges, we will soon be left
standing dazed and befuddled among the smoldering ruins of a great
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In a rebuttal, the committee's chief Democratic lawyer, Abbe
Lowell, accused Starr of creating a ``grave constitutional crisis''
by exploiting Clinton's attempt to hide an embarrassing adulterous
affair from his family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell accused Starr and Schippers of using a common
prosecutorial strategy against Clinton by seizing several core
allegations (perjury, obstruction of justice, and witness
tampering) and developing several additional counts to make the
case ``look more serious or foreboding.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowell said Schippers had done little more than ``subdivide''
Starr's allegations to produce additional counts. He also
criticized committee Republicans for refusing to define what
constitutes an impeachable offense before launching a full inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the equivalent of a ship's captain leaving on a
difficult, uncharted voyage and hoping to find his compass
somewhere along the way,'' Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   In a symbolic gesture, committee Republicans sat before a table
stacked with worn volumes of the 1974 Watergate report. On the wall
behind them was a large portrait of former Representative Peter
Rodino, a New Jersey Democrat, who presided over the Watergate
hearings, which hastened Nixon's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Bill McCollum, a Florida Republican, countered
critics who have argued that perjury is not a serious offense by
saying 115 inmates are currently serving federal prison terms for
perjury convictions.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is found to have committed perjury, McCollum said,
``That's enough for us to impeach and enough for him to be thrown
out of office.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat,
downplayed the charges. ``Mr. Starr, reflecting his bias, follows
the principle that if you don't have anything bad to say, you don't
say anything at all,'' Frank said. ``But that ought not to be the
cue for this committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats denounced Clinton's actions in the Lewinsky
matter and some of his legal defense tactics. ``He had an
adulterous affair with a White House employee half his age, then he
misled the American people ... and engaged in a dangerous game of
verbal `Twister' in his sworn testimony,'' said Representative
Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said the committee should conduct a ``thoughtful and
fair'' inquiry,'' then ``sanction the president in a manner
commensurate with the seriousness of his wrongdoing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
