<P>
   JUDICIARY _ The House Judiciary Committee begins weighing
whether to proceed with impeachment inquiry of President Clinton.
(Carr/Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   JUDICIARY-SCHIPPERS _ Few counties are as important to the
Democratic National Committee as Cook County. The Illinois county
surrounding the city of Chicago was where the famed Mayor Richard
J. Daley ran his beloved Democratic Machine for the better part of
this century. David Schippers is part of that fabric. The South
Side Irish lawyer is as Democratic as they get. His first cousin is
the chairman of the Democratic Party of Cook County and he has been
a loyal party supporter. And that is what makes Schippers such an
interesting profile. The man who made his name taking down
Chicago's Mafia is now heading up the special congressional
Republican task force to determine wwhether there is grounds for
the president to be impeached. We profile Schippers and Democratic
Counsel Abbe Lowell. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   JUDICIARY-BARR _ A look at Ga. Rep. Bob Barr's opening
statement. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-FRAUD _ WASHINGTON _ A government investigation has
turned up massive fraud in Medicare payments to mental health
providers at community centers in Florida, Texas and other states.
In one study, 90 percent of providers and services were ineligible
for Medicare funding, a conclusion that has been called the worst
in Medicare history. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   COURT-CLERKS _ WASHINGTON _ NAACP President and CEO Kweisi Mfume
leads a demonstration to ``protest the shameful record in hiring
minority clerks'' of the Supreme Court Justices. (Monroe, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY _ WASHINGTON _ Black and Hispanic leaders Monday
criticized a study that claimed minorities would fare better under
a privatized retirement system than under the Social Security
program. The comments by Julian Bond, chairman of the NAACP, and
Raul Yzaguirre, president of the National Council of La Raza, were
the latest in a rising chorus that has criticized claims by the
conservative Heritage Foundation that blacks and Hispanics would do
better if they were able to invest their retirement payments in
personally managed accounts. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Column on the Senate race in Georgia,
Sunday's TV debate and the presence of Libertarian Bert Loftman in
the race. What's the impact of having a third candidate in the
race? (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN PRISON GANG SERIES
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PRISONGANGS _ At a time when the gangs are being blamed
for increasing violence in and out of prison, the reality in the
maximum-security lockups where gang members are segregated is
orderly, almost serene. The eerie calm highlights the central role
gangs have come to occupy in some Texas prisons. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GANG-CODES _ HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Inside the back flap of the
card were scribbled numbers carrying a much more ominous message.
``Code,'' explains Irma Fernandez. Until recently, Fernandez headed
the five-member unit at the Estelle prison here _ part of the more
than 50 specially trained corrections officers across Texas who
pore over thousands of pieces of mail each day, intercepting and
deciphering coded messages. (Ward, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE-PRISON _ HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ In 1977, when I first came
to prison, the convict code demanded that my courage be tested. The
task fell to my homeboys. I had seven fights my first day at
Ferguson, the gladiator unit, where inmates 21 years old and
younger were assigned. (Renaud, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-INMATES _ AUSTIN _ After spending the past four years in
prison, Brian Collins, 31, knows the routine well. ``A guy comes in
from the streets (and) the first thing that happens is he gets
checked _ by blacks, whites, everybody,'' said the Mineral Wells
resident who is serving 10 years for theft. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   INMATE-GANGSTERS _ Henry Granado Jr., convicted Austin burglar,
admitted member of the Texas Syndicate prison gang, could be the
king of second chances. If Granado was involved with the Texas
Syndicate as a result of one of his prison stays, as authorities
suspect, parole officials said they never considered that before
they released him each time. Under new rules being drafted, that
will change. (Ward, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   STREET-GANGS _ In what authorities warn is a growing menace,
prison gangs driven by racial and geographic animosities are coming
of age in Austin and most other major Texas cities. In the past few
years, some prison gangs have begun recruiting members of youth
street gangs as soldiers in a growing crime network seeking to gain
control of Texas' illegal drug markets. (Ward, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PBP-ELECTION _ TALLAHASSEE _ With the election less than a month
away, this much is already known: Florida's next attorney general
will have a name that starts with a ``B'' and ends with ``Worth''
and believes that at least some voters mistake his opponent for
him. Democrat Bob Butterworth, 58, is seeking his fourth term as
the state's top lawyer, the man in charge of ensuring that
criminals lose their legal appeals, that consumer laws are adhered
to and that the state's laws are upheld when challenged in court.
Republican David Bludworth, 56 and for 20 years the state attorney
for Palm Beach County, wants to replace him on the Cabinet and give
Florida the first Republican attorney general in decades. (Shirish,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   PBP-CATS _ Henry Flagler museum director John Blades has called
off the dogs, so to speak, temporarily because an anonymous person
has agreed to take the cats running around the grounds. He won't
say who for fear that cat activist Catherine Bradley will dissaude
them as she did to a Boca Raton woman last week. Blades said he has
gotten lots of support from museum members and objectors aren't
members anyway. (TJom, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
