<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Both teams saluting Strawberry
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ Everyone is talking about Darryl Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Indians are showing their respect for the Yankees
slugger, who underwent surgery to remove a tumor from his colon on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Indians starter Bartolo Colon is wearing Strawberry's number
(39) stenciled under his hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a big fan of his since I was a kid and I got a
chance to talk with him this year,'' Colon said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Strawberry remains in good condition at
Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center as doctors said there was no
visible evidence during surgery that the cancer had spread beyond
the colon. However, it will be another week until tests results
come back and doctors know for sure the severity of the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry continues to be visited by his teammates, and even
owner George Steinbrenner has dropped in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can talk all we want to, but it's a scary situation,''
Yankees right-fielder Paul O'Neill said. ``It started off on a good
note, obviously. The surgery is the No. 1 step. From what the
doctors said, there were no setbacks. You go on from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Advice for Strawberry
</P>
<P>
   Two Octobers ago, Frank Torre, the brother of Yankees manager
Joe Torre, was awaiting a heart transplant and it became a big
national story. The same has happened this year to Strawberry but
Frank Torre said the outfielder should concentrate on getting
better and the media should leave him alone. ``If you really love
Darryl Strawberry and you really want him to recover, then forget
he exists for the next four or give days,'' he said. ``He'll be so
exhausted just from speaking for a few minutes. To hell with
baseball right now.'' With a new heart, Frank Torre is doing just
fine and will be in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn
</P>
<P>
   Yankees third baseman Scott Brosius, who hurt his ankle in Game
3 of the division series, had it X-rayed and the result were
negative. Still, Brosius is expected to play tonight with a heavily
taped ankle. . . . With Strawberry out, outfielder Ricky Ledee will
be activated. During the regular season, Ledee, once considered the
club's top prospect, hit .241 with one homer and 12 RBIs in 42
games. . . . The reason Andy Pettitte, now pitching Game 3, and
David Cone, now pitching Game 2, were flip-flopped in the rotation
was because Cone threw only 83 pitches in the division series. This
will mean with David Wells will pitch the opener and a Game 5, if
necessary, Cone will go in Game 6 and Pettitte in Game 7. Rookie
Orlando Hernandez, who did not pitch against the Rangers, gets Game
4. . . . Indians right-hander Jaret Wright, who gets the start
against the Yankees tonight, was 2-1 with a 3.66 ERA during the
regular season against New York. He beat the Yankees twice during
the postseason last year. . . . Indians right fielder Manny Ramirez
has 11 postseason homers, tying him for fifth on the all-time list.
Mickey Mantle and Reggie Jackson lead with 18.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
