<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-YANKEES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Odds stacked against Indians
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees and Indians open their American League
Championship Series tonight, and few people are giving Cleveland
much of a chance.
</P>
<P>
   This is an old storyline for the Tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when they faced the Yankees in the division series,
the Indians were written off after falling behind two games to one.
Didn't matter. Cleveland won.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Indians were underdogs in the ALCS to Baltimore. Didn't
matter. Cleveland won.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never worry about what everyone says because this game is
played on the field,'' Indians manager Mike Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the Yankees favored again, many forecasts include
the word sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Said Rangers slugger Juan Gonzalez after his team was whiplashed
by New York in the division series, ``If the Yankees continue to
pitch the way they pitched against us, they can sweep all the way
without losing a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the clubs is best illustrated by pitching. In
the first round, the Yankees allowed one run, the Indians 20. The
Yankees will send out starters David Wells, David Cone, Andy
Pettitte and Orlando Herandez, while the Indians counter with the
less intimidating Jaret Wright, Charles Nagy, Bartolo Colon and
Dwight Gooden.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Cleveland is resilient.
</P>
<P>
   Of the last four playoffs series they have won, the Indians lost
the first game. They also play well on the road, having proved that
with two wins in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just refuse to accept defeat until the last out is made,''
outfielder David Justice said. ``This team has a lot of talent and
a lot of pride.''
</P>
<P>
   As if their talent weren't enough, the Yankees have some extra
incentive after losing to the Indians last October when they were
going for back-to-back titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly something that you could speculate about, that
if we had gotten by Cleveland and got to the World Series, we could
be playing for No. 3,'' Cone said. ``But it didn't happen. Maybe
this is why we won 114 games. Maybe last year was such a slap in
the face that guys were motivated in the off-season.''
</P>
<P>
   Another motivating favor is Darryl Strawberry, who will be
watching from a New York hospital after having surgery to remove a
cancerous tumor from his colon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the American League champions last season, so we're
the ones defending this,'' Indians general manager John Hart said.
``That's the way we're looking at this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
