<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-PADRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Padres sit Brown in Game 1
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Take Livan Hernandez, Edgar Renteria, Eric Gregg,
Moises Alou and any other demon that tore at the Braves' trousers
as they were chased out of the 1997 NLCS and send them all to the
corner of the dugout. No one player did more to bring about
Atlanta's ouster last October than Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the Braves were dubious to news that the San Diego Padres
are sitting their ace in Wednesday night's Game 1 of the National
League Championship Series. Andy Ashby (17-9) will face John Smoltz
(17-3) in the opener before Tom Glavine takes on Brown Thursday,
all but eliminating Brown starting three games this series, unless
the Padres expect to bring him back on two days rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a lot of success against us the last couple years,''
Chipper Jones said. ``The series will probably hinge on whether or
not we can beat him.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was just used twice on three days rest in a 10-days
stretch and against Houston in the League Division Series he showed
little wear. He struck out 16 in Game 1 (118 pitches) and though he
allowed a run on a bases-loaded walk in Game 3 (100 pitches), he
won both times. San Diego manager Bruce Bochy hedged on what to do
but the matter seemed settled when the Padres charter hit
Hartsfield International Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin went beyond the call of duty and by Saturday, he was
running on fumes,'' Bochy said. Greg Maddux is slated to face
left-hander Sterling Hitchcock in Saturday's Game 3 in San Diego.
Bochy's plans after that will be dictated by how Brown performs in
his first start and the Padres' standing in the series. In last
year's NLCS, the Marlins only needed two starts out of Brown. He
beat Maddux in Game 1, 5-3, and then nailed down the pennant
against Glavine 7-4 in Game 6. Both starts were at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're going to be different this year,'' said Javy Lopez.
``We already had that bad experience and we don't want to go
through that again. They (the Padres) beat Randy Johnson twice. Why
can't we beat Kevin Brown twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
