<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-TENN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putting bitter back in rivalries
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia coach Jim Donnan will take some things
personally. History shows that college football rivalries are one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his 30-year career as an assistant and head coach,
Donnan has served as a drought breaker of sorts. Georgia fans are
hoping that trend remains true Saturday at Sanford Stadium when the
seventh-ranked Bulldogs host No. 4 Tennessee, which has won seven
straight games in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game in our league counts, but anytime you've had a
tough time with a team, you work twice as hard preparing,'' Donnan
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s, Oklahoma had one of college football's
greatest dynasties. But for three straight seasons (1981-83), the
Sooners couldn't get past archrival Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma finally beat the Cornhuskers in 1984, and Sooners coach
Barry Switzer hired Donnan as his offensive coordinator the
following season. The Sooners won three straight games in the
series with Donnan on board.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Donnan left Oklahoma for his first head coaching job at
Division I-AA Marshall, which had lost 13 of 14 meetings to
Southern Conference rival Furman. But the Thundering Herd's
fortunes turned immediately under Donnan, who won five games
against the Paladins in his six-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Oklahoma, we felt like we not only needed to recruit
better, but we also need to build our weight program around what
Nebraska was doing,'' Donnan said. ``We felt like we could always
run with Nebraska, but we just weren't strong enough. When I got to
Marshall, we felt that Furman was the premier team in the league,
so we built our offense around beating them.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnan faced a similar situation when he came to Georgia in
1996. Florida and Tennessee have been the dominant teams in the SEC
this decade. During the '90s, the Gators have compiled a 55-7
league record; Tennessee is 48-13-1. Meanwhile, the Bulldogs have
been mediocre at 29-32-1.
</P>
<P>
   Donnan addressed the problem through recruiting, adding speed at
the skill positions and signing several linemen. In two-plus
seasons, it appears the Bulldogs are closing the gap.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia finished second to Tennessee in the SEC East last year
with a 6-2 league record. The Bulldogs also ended their seven-year
drought to Florida with a stunning 37-17 upset in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done (at Georgia) is build our scheme around
beating Florida and Tennessee,'' Donnan said. ``We haven't done it
against Tennessee yet, but hopefully we've done enough to be
competitive this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Bulldogs players admit they were intimidated by Florida,
which beat Georgia by an average of more than 26 points from
1990-96. But they insist the same isn't true with the Volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly felt that there was some (intimidation) with
Florida before last year,'' senior strong safety Kirby Smart said.
``Tennessee's just been weird. There were bad matchups. (Vols
All-America quarterback Peyton) Manning played well and really
ripped us apart. I think one of the big things with Tennessee is
that we hadn't played a big game before playing them in the past.
Now, we've played that big game against LSU.''
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers probably enter this week's SEC showdown with a
fragile psyche following Monday's loss of star tailback Jamal Lewis
to a season-ending knee injury. But can Georgia overcome the demons
of a seven-game losing streak?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're intimidated,'' offensive tackle Matt
Stinchcomb said. ``This is obviously a big game for us. It's big
for me. It's the last shot (against Tennessee) and I'm 0-3 so far.
This group of seniors wants it pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
