<HEADLINE>
BOEING DELIVERIES DOWN 10 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. said Monday it delivered 123 airplanes
in the third quarter, or about 10 percent fewer than in the
previous quarter. Analysts said the decline in deliveries, while
troubling and worse than expected, reflects the deepening financial
crisis in Asia and not continued production problems.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be difficult for Boeing to make its earnings goal of
$1 a share this year if Boeing can't sell completed planes that
were intended for Asian customers, they said.
</P>
<P>
   As of Sept. 30, the end of the third quarter, Boeing had 36
undelivered planes in desert storage, which is up from 20 in
storage at the end of the second quarter. More planes are being
sent to the desert because some Asian carriers don't have the money
to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Thai Airways International said it would cancel
or delay delivery of 15 jets made by Boeing and European rival
Airbus Industrie. ``Boeing is going to be challenged to get those
airplanes in storage delivered,'' said Peter Jacobs, industry
analyst with Ragen MacKenzie in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing said it still expects to deliver 550 airplanes this
year, though doing so means the company will have to deliver a
record 61 planes a month for the rest of the year. It delivered 368
planes in the first nine months, including 137 in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Chairman Phil Condit cautioned several weeks ago that
Boeing would not deliver as many planes in the third quarter as it
had hoped. At the time, many analysts had been expecting Boeing to
deliver as many as 160 planes in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Condit's warning, analysts had already lowered
their third quarter earning estimates before Monday's delivery
figures were announced. On Wall Street, Boeing shares rose 11/16 to
$33.75.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Nisbet, aerospace analyst with JSA Securities, said he will
stick with his estimate that Boeing will earn about 21 cents a
share for the third quarter. He had previously lowered his estimate
after Condit's warning.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said he was forecasting Boeing would deliver 135 planes
in the third quarter. Even though that figure proved overly
optimistic, Jacobs said that for now he is sticking with his
estimate that Boeing will earn about 25 cents a share for the third
quarter. That is down from his estimate of about 32 cents a share
before Condit's advisory
</P>
<P>
   ``The shortfall in deliveries mainly is planes that have either
modest or no profit margin contribution,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   He also believes Boeing will still end the year with earnings of
about $1 a share.
</P>
<P>
   But part of Boeing's forecast that it will deliver 550 planes
this year depends on the company delivering most of the planes now
in storage.
</P>
<P>
   The planes in storage, Boeign said, include 10 classic models of
the 737 and eight next-generation models of the 737, as well as
nine 747s, one 767, three 777s and five MD-90s.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Boeing said ``the majority of these airplanes
are awaiting final customer-financing arrangements, most of which
are expeceted to occur in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the planes in storage are deliveries that Boeing delayed
until customers could obtain financing. But in other cases,
customers no longer want the planes they ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boeing must try and find a new home for those planes (that
customers no longer want,'' Jacobs said. ``That will be more of a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boeing delievered 89 planes in the third quarter as
the company was reeling from a series of production problems that
eventually resulted in Boeing's first operational loss in a half
century for 1997
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Monday that Boeing appears to have worked through
those problems, but it will still be tough to produce those 550
planes this year, they said. That's because production lines
usually shut down for two weeks in December for the holidays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
