<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0890 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-05 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TWO VIEWS OF ONE CONCEPT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY LEWIS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ We have before us today, in dramatic opposition, two
views of what it means to be a conservative and a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   One respects institutions, cares about fair means as well as
ends, puts country before party. The other has no regard for
institutions or fairness, believing that the end of winning
justifies any means.
</P>
<P>
   The first is Gerald Ford. The second is Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   President Ford, writing Sunday on the Op-Ed page of The New York
Times, conveyed a sense of honor that has been achingly absent in
the sordid months of debate about President Clinton and Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come,'' Ford said, ``to pause and consider the
long-term consequences of removing this president from office based
on the evidence at hand.'' He foresaw, if Congress goes down that
road, ``a protracted and increasingly divisive debate over those
deliberately imprecise words `high crimes and misdemeanors.'''
</P>
<P>
   Instead Ford suggested that, after the House Judiciary Committee
considers possible ground for impeachment, Clinton appear at the
end of the year in the well of the House. There he would receive
``a harshly worded rebuke as rendered by members of both parties
... By his appearance the president would accept full
responsibility for his actions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let it be dignified, honest and above all cleansing,''
President Ford wrote. ``The result, I believe, would be the first
moment of majesty in an otherwise squalid year.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could doubt him when he said he had no political agenda
and no ``interest in `rescuing' Bill Clinton. But I do care,
passionately, about rescuing the country I love from further
turmoil.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Kenneth Starr. He was a fine judge. But in the
role of independent counsel, over these last four years, he has
become a caricature of a prosecutorial zealot.
</P>
<P>
   In his relentless desire to destroy President and Mrs. Clinton,
Starr has damaged the institution of grand jury secrecy that
protects us all. He has deprived this and future presidents of the
right to consult White House lawyers in confidence. He has filed a
report to the House with irrelevant salacious detail in order to
humiliate his target.
</P>
<P>
   Those are just a few examples of Starr's overreaching tactics.
And now we know more.
</P>
<P>
   On June 29 Starr argued in the U.S. Court of Appeals in
Washington that White House lawyers should be forced to testify in
his investigation of the president. He conceded that Clinton would
be entitled to talk to them in confidence to defend against
impeachment, but he said impeachment was ``too remote a possibility
to be considered by the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Just three days later, we have learned, Starr asked another
court to approve his use of secret grand jury material in his
planned impeachment report to the House. So he lied to the Court of
Appeals. Or, more charitably, he was sleazy.
</P>
<P>
   An important article in The New York Times, by Don Van Natta Jr.
and Jill Abramson, disclosed something else. Three right-wing
lawyers helped Linda Tripp and got word to Starr's office about her
accusations at least a week before she telephoned the office on
Jan. 12 _ which was when the Starr report said the office got into
the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   One of the three was a partner in Kirkland &AMP; Ellis, the law firm
in which Starr remained a partner until July 31 of this year.
Moreover, at least two of the lawyers also did work on behalf of
Paula Jones. A section of the Independent Counsel Act forbids a
counsel, or anyone in a law firm with which he is associated, to
represent any person ``involved in any investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether those maneuverings violated the act is impossible to
answer at this stage. But if Starr had disclosed the pre-Jan. 12
involvement, Attorney General Janet Reno might well have thought it
wise to ask another lawyer _ one more detached _ to undertake the
Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   We ought to know more, much more, about the relationship among
Paula Jones' lawyers, Linda Tripp, her entourage and Starr. In
fairness, he should answer questions under oath. But we should
follow the example of Ford, eschew zealotry and strive above all to
end the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
