<HEADER>
A0891 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN06-COX     10-05 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Traffic trashes a southern tradition
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Atlanta has lost most of its allure as commuting has
grown more difficult,'' carped The Economist magazine recently,
citing cities around the world _ from Sao Paulo to Singapore_ where
traffic jams have become a way of life.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to shout back that we're still pretty alluring here in
the metropolitan South. It's just that we eat fried green tomatoes
as an hors d'oeurve now instead of at breakfast with our grits.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, though_trafficis changing southern lifestyles. We don't
have time for grits; we don't have time for breakfast at all. We
have to start driving to work before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   The Economist slam is just the latest of a series of negative
jabs about Atlanta's congestion. The bad publicity has gotten the
attention of business leaders. The Metro Atlanta Chamber of
Commerce formed the Metro Transportation Group earlier this year
with the aim of presenting a new governor with some possible metro
congestion solutions. Listening in this week on the group's
discussion of specific targets, I'm encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, members seem inclined to dump the ``local
control'' excuse for never-ending sprawl, a leftover from the
Populist era when locals didn't trust higher-ups, be they state or
federal. Here in the land of green tomatoes and grits, we now know
only a stronger state hand can save us from choking on our
prosperity. If it weren't for federal Clean Air Act mandates, state
transportation officials would holler for more asphalt to the last
gasp.
</P>
<P>
   The Metro Group wants to add clout to regional plans, something
other cities did long ago, and members want to figure out how to
fund ``a world class transit system.'' Atlanta's regional planning
structure is fatally flawed. Despite its well-meaning staff, the
Atlanta Regional Commission Board is dominated by county
commissioners obligated to local constituencies and cozy with
developers. Over the years, the state DOT has made the most of
parochial politics: counties present their lists of desired new
roads, and the ARC votes to approve most of them. Even before the
ARC votes, there are bilateral agreements between the counties and
the state DOT on pet projects. The deal-making system works against
the regional good.
</P>
<P>
   The model that should be in place is one that elevates regional
priorities and regional funding. In San Diego, San Francisco and
Portland, the metropolitan planning agency, not the state DOT,
controls the regional federal and state funds.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, like most southern states, will receive more federal
transportation dollars than ever before this year, but the federal
Environmental Protection Agency says they can't be spent on new
road projects until ozone pollution is brought under control. A new
regional transportation structure not subject to manipulation by
the developer-prone DOT is needed.
</P>
<P>
   The second challenge is a more viable transit system. Atlanta's
system is stunted because development around train stations wasn't
encouraged and because racial undercurrents kept the trains from
expanding to the suburbs. As Jeff Rader, transportation specialist
with the Atlanta Chamber says, ``Transit is like a hot-house
flower. In the right environment, it can flourish.'' Metro Atlanta
offered a chilly environment for mass transit.
</P>
<P>
   The Metro Group wants a dedicated source of state funding for
transit. Georgia Democratic gubernatorial candidate Roy Barnes
supports earmarking the state sales tax on gasoline _about $40
million a year_ which would require legislation, not a change in
the constitution. Meanwhile, frontrunner Guy Milner, the GOP
candidate, is focusing on eliminating the car tax, not some of the
cars.
</P>
<P>
   But the Metro Group is chock full of conservative business types
who could influence Millner. So, regardless of who wins the Georgia
governor's race, a new generation of commuters may savor grits for
breakfast again before the millennium_and fried green tomatoes too_
at home or on the train.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   e-mail: mmezzard(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
