<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-VANGUARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T TO ACQUIRE VANGUARD CELLULAR SYSTEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Expanding its wireless network in the Northeast from big cities
into smaller markets, AT&AMP;T Corp. said Monday that it had agreed to
acquire Vanguard Cellular Systems Inc. for about $900 million in
stock and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Vanguard could allow AT&AMP;T to further exploit the success
of its new Digital One Rate pricing plan. That plan has shaken up
the wireless communications business by eliminating long-distance
fees and ``roaming'' charges for using phones outside of home
areas.
</P>
<P>
   While customers who use the new program pay a flat fee for calls
to anywhere in the nation, AT&AMP;T must still pay extra when those
customers use other companies' networks. That means AT&AMP;T can lose
money when its customers range far afield.
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring Vanguard could help solve that problem. Under the
brand name Cellular One, Vanguard operates wireless systems along
the Maine coast, in Pennsylvania around Allentown and around
Charleston, W.Va. Those systems would help link AT&AMP;T's systems
around New York, Pittsburgh and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will we save expenses there? Absolutely,'' Dan Hesse,
president of AT&AMP;T's wireless unit, said in an interview. ``But the
primary reason we're acquiring Vanguard is that it fits into our
footprint and allows us to provide seamless service.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, Vanguard's shareholders could elect
to receive either $23 in cash or .3987 share of AT&AMP;T for each share
of Vanguard. AT&AMP;T's shares closed at $58.625 on Friday, making the
stock component of the deal worth about $23.37 for each share of
Vanguard. But the deal says that half of the overall payment will
be in stock and half in cash, so some Vanguard stockholders may not
be able to get what they want.
</P>
<P>
   The companies expect to complete the acquisition in the first
quarter of 1999. Hesse said the deal could mildly dilute AT&AMP;T's
earnings for the first year after completion. AT&AMP;T will also assume
Vanguard's debt of about $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T was advised by TD Securities. Vanguard, based in
Greensboro, N.C., employed Wasserstein Perella &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than stay independent or stay on our past laurels, we
decided to seek a transaction where we could become part of
something lasting,'' said Stephen Leeolou, Vanguard's chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications Inc., which owns wireless businesses in the
Boston area and in western New York, and has agreed to acquire
Connecticut's dominant communications company, was seen as a
logical bidder for Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the process said SBC considered acquiring
Vanguard a few years ago and passed. They added that AT&AMP;T was the
only bidder with a serious telecommunications background this time
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good strategic move for AT&AMP;T,'' said John Bensche, a
wireless communications analyst at Lehman Brothers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
