<HEADER>
A0893 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX     10-05 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Anti-environment mind games
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only a guess here, but if the current majority in Congress had
its way the Environmental Protection Agency would be the size of an
Orange Julius day crew, just without the snazzy uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   EPA would be downsized _ the P gone _ and privatized, maybe to
be run by Dow Chemical, Exxon or RJ Reynolds.
</P>
<P>
   That the EPA still has its middle initial is a credit to voters
who chose Bill Clinton for president in 1992 and 1996. What the
Republicans are trying to do to the EPA right now is good reason to
wish new vitality for Democrats. They need vigor to combat
budgetary hooliganism that gets cover in a Capitol veiled in Silly
String.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks mainly to the Democrat in the White House, the new
Republican majority in Congress could not carry off designs to
emasculate the EPA in 1995 by cutting its budget by one-third.
</P>
<P>
   That defeat caused the GOP to retreat from environmental
scorched-earth budget tactics, to choose more limited skirmishes to
show that the party that controls purse strings shall command how
the EPA shall act.
</P>
<P>
   The weapon of choice now is the budget rider, language attached
to allocations that tells recipients what they can or cannot do
with the money authorized. Riders scattered throughout eight budget
bills for different departments are attracting veto threats from
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   One such rider was removed recently from the teh appropriations
bill for Veterans Affairs-HUD and independent agencies, which
include EPA. The rider effectively would have placed a gag order on
the EPA on the issue of global warming _ no educational activities,
including workshops and conferences.
</P>
<P>
   In July the House stripped the gag rule 226 to 178.
</P>
<P>
   While that rule was stripped, report language (words to explain
the intent of legislation) in the same bill remains that
effectively would prevent the EPA from doing anything ``in
contemplation'' of regulations to curb global warming. That's
right. Don't even think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Since Congress hasn't signed on to the Kyoto Protocol measures
to which President Clinton agreed on curbing greenhouse emissions,
bill authors don't want a taxpayer-subsidized thought going toward
the subject. This, though Congress has asked the administration to
explain how it intends to implement the Kyoto accords. Seemingly,
such a request would require contemplation by EPA.
</P>
<P>
   People in the EPA would be left in a quandary with a requirement
such as this, since contemplation of any type of air pollution
regulation could be construed as violating this insane prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   After all, reducing emissions isn't just a matter of combatting
greenhouse gases like carbon dioxide and methane. It's also a
matter of curbing particulates and toxins like lead and mercury.
Just what can the EPA contemplate, Mr. Congressman?
</P>
<P>
   High in the Colorado Rockies, a think tank called the Keystone
Center brings together players from government and industry to find
mutually satisfactory solutions to environmental issues like air
pollution and global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Observers of this commendable process say the mind games written
into the budget bill might put an end to the EPA's role in the
Keystone Center's brainstorming and sharing sessions on air
pollution. You wouldn't want to bend a contemplation ban.
</P>
<P>
   To have an agency assigned to protect the environment and to
forbid it from ``contemplating'' solutions to what vast numbers of
climatologists warn is a grave global problem? That is stupidity
beyond contemplating.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald. E-mail:
jyoungmail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
