   (NYT8) LONDON -- Oct. 05, 1998 -- LONDON-FASHION-1, 10-05 --
Aberrations aside, Hussein Chalayan offered an intelligent way for
women to dress as the millennium approaches. His line could well be
considered a vision of the future for the '90s generation. A blue
two-piece dress by Chalayan, left; Burberry reinvented: A
caramel-leather jacket over voile over plaid. (Jonathan Player/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CLEVELAND -- Oct. 05, 1998 -- IVES-CONCERTO, 10-05 --
Piano soloist Alan Feinberg and the Cleveland Orchestra performing
Charles Ives' ``Emerson'' Concerto in Cleveland on Sunday. This
20-minute piece for piano and orchestra had its first performances
over the weekend at Severance Hall thanks to a musicologist named
David Porter, who has assembled Ives' many shreds of evidence and
parsed his hieroglyphics into an apparently coherent form. (Roger
Mastroianni/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 05, 1998 -- NUREYEV-BIOGRAPHY, 10-05 --
Diane Solway, author of a new biography of Rudolf Nureyev, in her
Manhattan apartment. Her book, ``Nureyev: His Life,'' asserts that
Nureyev's escape resulted from miscalculations and squabbling among
officials of the Soviet Embassy, the Kirov Ballet's artistic
leadership and the KGB. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Oct. 05, 1998 -- COYNE-SCULPTURE-2, 10-05 --
Petah Coyne with her ``BZ CD Put-Put'' at Galerie Lelong in
Manhattan, where her show runs through Oct. 16. For her current
exhibition, Ms. Coyne simply began working. There was no moment of
inspiration. She arrived at these sculptures intuitively, by trial
and error, in a two-year labor-intensive process that eventually
involved 30 helpers, mostly unpaid interns. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Oct. 05, 1998 -- COYNE-SCULPTURE-1, 10-05 --
Petah Coyne installing ``BZ CD Put-Put'' for her exhibition at
Galerie Lelong, which runs through Oct. 16. Ms. Coyne's layered
tableaux are dreamy and mystical, evoking spirituality and
afterlife. None of her work is really planned, though Ms. Coyne
tries to peer into her own mind by changing materials every few
years. ``It's like having the rug pulled out from under me,'' she
says. ``It makes me focus on what I'm trying to say.'' (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CAMBRIDGE, England. -- Oct. 05, 1998 --
SCI-CAMBRIDGE-GENE, 10-05 -- Drs. Alan Coulson, right, and John
Sulston on the grounds of the Sanger Center. Ever since the
structure of DNA was discovered here in 1953, Cambridge has been a
leading world center for molecular biology. And with the help of a
recent bonanza from a long dead American pharmacist, Cambridge
scientists have become leading players in the effort to decipher
the human genome. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) EAST BETHAL, Minn. -- Oct. 05, 1998 --
SCI-TILMAN-ECOLOGY, 10-05 -- Dr. G. David Tilman, an ecologist at
the University of Minnesota, examining Golden Rod as part of a
biodiversity study in an experimental field at the Cedar Creek
Natural History Area in Minnesota north of Minneapolis. Tilman's
goal is to help make ecology a rigorous mathematics-based
discipline like, say, physics. ``Where things fall apart is where I
get excited,'' he says. (Steve Woit/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 05, 1998 -- SCI-AIDS-LAZARUS, 10-05 --
John Lesnick, 45, at an AIDS hot line office. Protease inhibitors
helped him extend his life, but Lesnick is under more psychological
stress now than ever. ``On the surface it's wonderful to walk down
the street, see myself in a store window and think, 'God that's
me!' `` he says. ``But there's an awful lot below that surface. All
my friends are dead. I haven't had sex in six years. How do you
begin being a human being again?'' (Edward Keating/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
