<SLUG> BC-COURT-CLERKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protesters claim bias at court
 &HT;    By Nichole Monroe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ Emotional demonstrators marched in front of the
Supreme Court on Monday to protest the low number of minority law
clerks hired at the nation's highest judicial body.
</P>
<P>
   ``The justices' record on hiring clerks of color is so poor that
if the civil rights laws applied, the Supreme Court would be
vulnerable to a charge that it has discriminated on the basis of
race,'' said Stephan Kline, legislative counsel at the Alliance for
Justice, an association of public interest groups.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 428 clerks hired by the nine current justices since they
joined the court, less than 2 percent were African-American, 4
percent were Asian-American, 1 percent were Hispanic and none has
been Native American, according to USA Today. One-quarter were
women.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP head Kweisi Mfume and other organizers said justices
should hire from a larger pool of applicants. About half of the
clerks hired in the last 25 years have come from Harvard, Yale or
Columbia universities. Mfume said the issue of minority law clerks
is especially important as the court considers such controversial
issues as affirmative action, school vouchers and welfare reform.
Clerks help determine which cases the court will consider, and
write the first drafts of most decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
