<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0419 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0897 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIANA-PLAY07-COX     10-05 1762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIANA-PLAY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The debut of a princess
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it a Cinderella story. Or maybe just a princess story. But
it is certainly a dream come true for actress Kendra Munger, 25,
former apprentice at the Jupiter Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   Monday evening at the Grove Street Playhouse in Greenwich
Village, she opened in a new musical, Queen of Hearts, her first
role ever on a New York stage. No, not as the third chorus singer
from the left, but starring in the title role _ as the late Diana
Spencer, former Princess of Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Although her debut was at a tiny 73-seat, off-off-Broadway
theater, Munger has had to bear up through a media frenzy usually
reserved for Andrew Lloyd Webber's multimillion-dollar phantoms and
felines.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been so much coverage, and the way that I dealt with
it was I just didn't let myself think about it,'' Munger says. Not
easy when you get a panicked call from your producer warning that
there are London tabloids hot on your trail, looking for a scoop
about this Connecticut lass who dares to play their beloved Diana.
</P>
<P>
   By now Munger has become a pro at television, taping more
interviews than many a stage veteran has in an entire career. ``I
was on Access Hollywood, I was on CNN, Fox Cable News. We filmed
stuff for Extra, but I haven't seen it on yet,'' says Munger with a
nervous giggle.
</P>
<P>
   Nervous perhaps, because she knows that such attention could
backfire on the production. ``That scares me a little,'' Munger
concedes. ``I worry that people's expectations will be extremely
high. It worries me that the general public will be coming,
thinking they'll be seeing some Broadway-quality production. It
can't be. We don't have that budget at all.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, though, Munger is just relieved that the
production is happening at all. This Cinderella almost got the
pumpkin treatment when war broke out during rehearsals between
Queen of Hearts' writers and its producer. Charges and
counter-charges of ``erratic,
</P>
<P>
   volatile and irrational behavior'' almost halted the show before
it opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't sided with anyone, because I don't honestly
understand what the whole thing is about,'' Munger says. ``It's
like anything we hear from one side is completely contradicted by
the other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the creative team was encouraging the actors to
leave the production,'' Munger says. ``I've received so much
publicity, I don't feel comfortable with the idea that a show
doesn't go on because I back out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the theater, Miss Munger. Trade in your tiara for a
protective helmet.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after graduating from Skidmore College with honors in
theater, Munger auditioned in New York for the one open space in
Jupiter Theatre's 1994-95 apprentice class. ``That was the first
audition that I went to in the big, bad city,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Norb Joerder, the defunct dinner theater's resident director,
``was choreographing some simple little routine to Tea for Two and
I was not even getting it,'' she says forlornly. ``So I thought I
had done a terrible audition, and I remember writing my boyfriend,
saying, `You don't have to worry. I'm not going to be taking off
for a year.''' Of course, she got the job and left for South
Florida a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jupiter was a nice introduction into the professional
world,'' says Munger, ``a real training experience. We weren't
treated badly as apprentices, because they couldn't have run the
place without us, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sommerville of Tequesta, a freelance director and acting
teacher who worked closely with the Jupiter apprentices, recalls
Munger as a standout of the group. ``Because she was so quiet and
approached everything from an intellectual level first. She was
very quiet, very elegant, but you could tell that that brain was
just churning away. Everything about her was just very truthful,
onstage or off.'' As to her latest role as Diana, ``It's the most
perfect casting in the world,'' Sommerville says.
</P>
<P>
   During that year, Munger appeared in Mame, The Secret Garden,
It's A Wonderful Life and My Fair Lady, usually in the ensemble and
occasionally understudying a major role. She had to struggle to get
the understudying assignment as Eliza Doolittle, and her mother
cites that as a sign of her personal growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they were going to give it to an intern,''
recalls Doris Munger, a former airline flight attendant living in
New Canaan, Conn. ``She's always been kind of shy and retiring, but
she felt she deserved that and could do it, so she really went and
pleaded for the role. That's where I saw her growth really, in
seeing her develop the tenacity to stand up for herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask the younger Munger what her most vivid memory of the Jupiter
Theatre is, though, and she'll mention being in the children's show
Jack and the Beanstalk on the day the theater caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   Munger was backstage when she heard an unexpected silence. ``And
I thought, `Oh, somebody dropped a line,' and then I heard them
say, `Fire, there's a fire,' and soon the whole curtain was in
flames. So basically I was yelling at everyone to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a baptism by fire did nothing to extinguish her
determination to become an actress. ``Ever since she was a little
girl, it's been the only thing she ever wanted to do,'' says Mrs.
Munger.
</P>
<P>
   After Jupiter, Munger worked at other dinner theaters and toured
the country with one-afternoon-stands of children's shows.
Eventually, her voice teacher advised her that she needed to land a
role in New York to attract an agent and move her career forward.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Munger was thumbing through the classified ads in the
trade paper Backstage when an audition notice for Queen of Hearts
caught her eye. Hoping she could land a supporting role in this
Princess Di musical, she headed for the open, non-union casting
call.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I auditioned for it, it was honestly just because it was
something in New York,'' she insists. ``I didn't think I'd get
called back for Diana.'' Other actresses looked more like the
princess than she did, says Munger, but after a five-hour-long
callback audition where she read most of the 95-page script, the
part was hers.
</P>
<P>
   Every parent probably thinks of her daughter as a princess, and
Mrs. Munger is no exception. ``I think she's always had a certain
bearing. She does have the build and the coloring, and the haircut
doesn't hurt either,'' Kendra's mother says, referring to a Vidal
Sassoon Di cut that completes the stage illusion.
</P>
<P>
   Munger recalls that her folks gave her a book about Diana some
15 years ago, but she would hardly describe herself as obsessed by
the princess. ``I didn't follow her, but she was always there,
y'know? It was kind of hard to miss her. I have a memory of
watching the wedding, and I must have been 8. And I remember
thinking, `Oh, I want to have a dress like that, and I want to get
married to a prince.' I think that my generation of girls were the
ones who were hit hardest by it,'' says Munger, referring to
Diana's abrupt death a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Playwright Stephen Stahl, who was also Queen of Hearts' director
until his recent ouster, began writing it as a non-musical long
before Diana's demise. ``Once she died,'' says Munger, ``he felt he
needed to make it a musical to make it less heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   The musical, the actress says, is very favorable to Diana. It
does not shrink from the royal couple's marital difficulties or her
imperfections, but it sides with her, telling matters from her
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   As Queen of Hearts opens, Diana has just been killed. ``She's
sort of in that state of limbo that people describe, where her life
is flashing in front of her,'' says Munger. Answering her cries for
help is another princess who expired in a car crash _ Princess
Grace of Monaco _ acting as Diana's guardian angel to guide her
through a tour of her life.
</P>
<P>
   If this strikes you as sounding like A Christmas Carol, you're
not the only one. ``Exactly,'' agrees Munger. ``She goes back to
her Christmas Past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last image you see of Diana, she's very happy, she's with
Dodi (Fayed) and I sing this song called It's My Time, this great,
upbeat song. That makes it really ironic, because we know what lies
ahead for her,'' says Munger. Then, following reports of Diana's
death, ``it has bits of the Earl of Spencer talking at the funeral
and then, at the very end, Princess Grace leads Diana into the
light.''
</P>
<P>
   Try acting that scene with a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   Lyric soprano Munger carries much of the show's singing load,
including a love duet with Fayed (You Are My World) and a touching
ballad at the bedside of an AIDS patient (Time To Let Go). There is
even a musical number that she sings while playing with her sons,
William and Harry (Back To My Babies). ``You almost feel like I
should have a hat and cane,'' Munger says.
</P>
<P>
   Besides learning these songs, dealing with interview requests
and watching the skirmish between the producer and the writers,
Munger has had to come up with a believable British accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that people are always very hard on that, especially
when you've got an American playing a British person,'' says
Munger, who studied one summer at the London Academy of Music and
Dramatic Art. Where most productions would have hired an expert to
train the cast, it simply wasn't in Queen of Hearts' budget. ``I
literally went to a professional dialect coach and gave him $185
for an hour,'' explains Munger. ``And I've rented some videotapes
of (Diana), too.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, she's been too busy to worry about the eventual fate of
Queen of Hearts. ``I hope they'll like it,'' Munger says of the
critics. ``I hope that the expectations aren't too high.''
</P>
<P>
   Pushed off from consideration at the moment is the next step for
the show, which might move to a larger New York theater for an
open-ended run or perhaps transfer to London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just focusing on this production,'' says Munger. ``It
would be nice to get good reviews, of course. Maybe I won't read
any unless somebody says one's good, so I don't get my feelings
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens to the show, Munger's future
prospects look good. She will certainly get her wish, that the
theater world's eyes will be on her this week. And yes, just in
case the musical and its star get thumbs up, the debuting performer
has kept her calendar clear to continue her ride with Princess
Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
