<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-LAMBERT07-COX     10-05 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-LAMBERT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doyenne of fashion
 &HT;    Has sidebar: LAMBERT-TIPS
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``I don't have makeup on. Do you mind?''
</P>
<P>
   She sits, slowly. Eleanor Lambert has penciled in this breakfast
visit as her first activity of the day, just before going to her
office to meet with her accountant. She still keeps 40-hour weeks.
She is 95.
</P>
<P>
   She recently had cataract surgery on her right eye and keeps
wiping it. ``I hope he doesn't make me look ghastly,'' she says,
watching the photographer who is preparing to take her picture.
</P>
<P>
   It is a passing thought. ``Let's go on,'' she says, going back
to her topic.
</P>
<P>
   She was talking about fashion.
</P>
<P>
   She has always been talking about fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert is a fashion publicist, but that doesn't explain much.
Then again, it's hard to fit this on a business card:
</P>
<P>
   Co-founder, the Metropolitan Museum of Art's Costume Institute,
1937.
</P>
<P>
   Founder, the International Best-Dressed List, 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Founder, fashion's Coty Awards, 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Founder, the semi-annual New York fashion week, 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Founder, the Council of Fashion Designers of America, 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Hostess, kickoff brunch for fashion week, every year.
</P>
<P>
   But no brunch on this particular week, even if there are shows.
A dozen or so designers, including Donna Karan and Calvin Klein,
have jumped schedule and are showing collections now instead of in
November. Good for business, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert is not impressed. Calvin sent her an invitation. She's
not going.
</P>
<P>
   She has her ideas about how fashion should be. But she pauses
and looks across her small sitting room and out at Central Park,
which is a blur to her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think geriatric advice is always looked at with disdain,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   But what the hell.
</P>
<P>
   She returns to the room wearing lipstick, earrings and blush.
She sits back in her chair and props her left foot in a crook of
the coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Fashion) shows now, they do everything on such a grand
scale,'' she says. ``There's lights and music, but no commentary.
Nobody tells you whether the fabric is wool or crepe. It's just
pretty girls walking up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert got into fashion because she thought of it as art. She
left her mother and her Indiana home and studied at the Art
Institute of Chicago. She wrote about clothing design for
newspapers to earn money to reach New York.
</P>
<P>
   She barely knew her father _ he left three months after her
birth _ but she worked like him. Henry was an advance man for the
Ringling Brothers circus and went from town to town.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert went into public relations and worked 57th Street,
finding artists to represent at $10 a week. Then designers. It grew
from there.
</P>
<P>
   She married Seymour Berkson, an executive with Hearst
newspapers, in 1936. He died in 1959. Now, from where she sits, she
cannot tell his photo on a nearby table from that of their son,
William.
</P>
<P>
   She continues.
</P>
<P>
   These days, young designers don't get enough training before
launching their own collections, she says. And shows should keep
out the designer's groupies _ ``those silly fools who yell and
scream and have nothing to do with fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   She dismisses one designer as being ``into gurus,'' and says
that while Calvin is ``an interesting fellow,'' his clothes look so
much alike.
</P>
<P>
   She even misses the pink filters on the lights that gave clothes
in fashion shows that ``glamour look.''
</P>
<P>
   She leaves and comes back with a necklace and sits. She arranges
her sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``People today think you can just tear the clothes apart and
it's fashion,'' she says. ``It's a slapdash approach to creativity.
The problem is, there are only a dozen truly creative designers
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Beene, for one. Anna Sui. Oscar de la Renta. Bill
Blass. She still represents Blass.
</P>
<P>
   For all her ``don'ts'' and ``shouldn'ts,'' she loves fashion.
She helped launch the careers of ``Bill,'' ``Oscar,'' Yves St.
Laurent, Pierre Cardin and Valentino, introducing them to the
press. That's what her biography says.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert has been gesturing. She arranges her sleeves again. She
asks the photographer, ``Did I spoil the line?''
</P>
<P>
   She never modeled clothes. She never designed them, either. No
talent, she says.
</P>
<P>
   But she helped pick out Grace Kelly's bridal wardrobe. And she
gave good friend Judy Garland fashion advice.
</P>
<P>
   Garland's husband, Vincent Minnelli, was one of Lambert's
clients. And Lambert met Kelly at a party and offered to escort her
around Seventh Avenue boutiques for wedding clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The pantsuit Lambert is wearing today is a copy of one she
bought years ago in Palm Beach. She had it remade in gray silk. It
is a uniform of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the proper thing for old people to do,'' she says.
``You can't be utterly couture at an advanced age. People would
look at your clothes and see now, then look at your face and see
then.''
</P>
<P>
   She leaves and comes back with her black cane. Time to go to
work. Time for small talk in the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was in town yesterday. Lambert remembers
meeting Hillary Clinton. ``I'm from Indiana,'' Lambert says. ``I've
seen every corny Midwestern politician. She took my hand in hers
and said, `I've followed your career.' I knew that wasn't true.
Both of us felt silly.''
</P>
<P>
   She needs no help up the stairs to the sidewalk. She pauses
there for another photo. She waves on a passerby who pauses
politely: ``Don't let him stop you.'' She calls again for her car.
</P>
<P>
   In the car, she worries about not being helpful. She wants to
arrange another interview for her guests. She pulls a cell phone
out of its tiny Chanel bag and hands it to the photographer. ``Do
you know how to use that phone?'' She knows the number by heart.
</P>
<P>
   More small talk. She'll be in Vero Beach at Thanksgiving for one
of her clients. She's supposed to be writing an autobiography in
her spare time. She never learned to drive.
</P>
<P>
   The car stops near Bergdorf Goodman. She has sent her visitors
to meet one of her 20 or so clients. It turns out to be Joan
Helpern, the Joan of Joan &AMP; David shoes. Joan laughs. Ah, Eleanor!
</P>
<P>
   ``She's really able to unite people,'' Helpern says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
