A0902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVREVIEW-MERCY07-COX     10-05 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVREVIEW-MERCY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    23rd century hospital worth a visit
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bloodied patients suffering from multiple compound fractures.
Harried doctors barking, ``I'm going in!'' Newborns undergoing
life-threatening surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds a lot like ER, doesn't it? Well, that's the point. Mercy
Point, to be exact. If Star Trek: Voyager and ER were ever
combined, the show would look a lot like UPN's promising new
medical drama. Mercy Point (9 p.m. Tuesday) marries all the
gee-whiz sci-fi elements (alien surgeons, for instance) with the
taut drama associated with medical shows (pregnant women battling
for their lives while sweat-drenched hubbies await the outcome).
</P>
<P>
   While the Mercy Point doctors still treat human patients in
cardiac distress (oh, they run into an alien or two, as well), they
do it hi-tech style. Well, it is the 23rd century, after all. That
means head nurses are cyborgs (and not bad looking, either) and
doctors scrub up in seconds by merely putting their hands inside a
machine.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Point is the name of a deep-space hospital where a team of
talented doctors works to save lives and work out all their
personal problems. And, boy do those doctors have personal
problems!
</P>
<P>
   Let's see . . . there's Grote Maxwell (the always reliable Joe
Morton), the hospital's take-charge alien physiologist who hasn't
seen his family in years.
</P>
<P>
   There's Haylen Breslauer (Maria Del Mar), the intense director
of medicine who can't stand Dru (Alexandra Wilson), her half-sister
and the hospital's new intern. Finally, there's Caleb ``C.J.''
Jurado (Brian McNamara), the George Clooney wannabe who lives life
on the edge and messes up his love life a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Mercy Point comes at you with an intense, never-let-up pace. If
subsequent episodes are as slick, stylish and well-acted as the
pilot, we won't mind frequently checking into this futuristic
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   --ENDIT--
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-10-05-98 1659E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
