<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRONING-PERSONALITY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEY, BABY, WHAT'S YOUR STEAM SETTING?
 &HT;    How ironing determines personality, and other pressing matters
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the latest wrinkle in do-it-yourself psychology ... oh, never
mind.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say there's a new way to discover yourself, and it
has to do with your iron.
</P>
<P>
   What's an iron? Congratulations. According to a new survey, you
fall into the resisting-responsibility, dependent role. You
slacker.
</P>
<P>
   The survey by the makers of Black &AMP; Decker identifies three
other types of people. Which are you? Try question No. 2 of the
Ironing Personality Indicator (IPI):
</P>
<P>
   I do my best ironig:
</P>
<P>
   a.) On the bed or any other convenient surface that's close by.
</P>
<P>
   b.) At the ironing board where I can really focus and do it
right.
</P>
<P>
   c.) In the shower with the power of natural steam.
</P>
<P>
   d.) None of the above.
</P>
<P>
   If you picked ``a,'' you are always trying to please others.
</P>
<P>
   If ``b,'' you like to be respected and in control.
</P>
<P>
   If ``c,'' you are a trailblazer, charming and unique.
</P>
<P>
   If ``d,'' see paragraph 3. (Slacker.)
</P>
<P>
   The source of this information is New York-based psychologist
Vivien Wolsk, who researches what she calls Emotional Fitness
Training.
</P>
<P>
   Which has something to do with improving self-esteem through
chores. ``I have a good feeling about ironing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Her personal emotional workout is a good round of doing dishes _
``getting rid of the dirt in my life'' _ and saying positive things
to herself in the mirror. A mantra, so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   And the mantra? ``I can really improve the world around me. I'm
going to make it fit for me.'' Pretty wordy. ``Well, it's `I can
make a difference.'''
</P>
<P>
   The top stress-relieving chores, she says, are ironing,
window-cleaning, doing laundry, scrubbing floors, vacuuming and
scraping paint.
</P>
<P>
   There's something fulfilling about achieving something _ no
matter how small _ compared to pushing away at a meaningless
machine at the gym, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why she'd hand President Clinton a bucket and sponge.
``Scrubbing floors would be good for him,'' Wolsk says, ``getting
down on his hands and knees so he really comes clean.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll stop right there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
