<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0425 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINDBERG-BIOGRAPHY07-     10-05 2284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINDBERG-BIOGRAPHY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lindbergh: nerves of steel, a heart to match
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it came his time to die, Charles Augustus
Lindbergh made his own arrangements. He picked out the grave on the
island of Maui where he would spend eternity. He supervised the
construction of the coffin. He chose the clothes he would be buried
in. He even specified how the shroud was to be folded.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted no embalming, he told his family. He wanted them to
bury him within hours of his death. His goal was to return to the
earth he loved as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 26, 1974, Charles Lindbergh got what he wanted. He
usually did.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh managed his death in the same exhaustively detailed
way he managed everything, completing one final act of focused
detachment, one final act that demonstrated the love and devotion
he felt for his family but could rarely verbalize. As he lay dying,
Charles Lindbergh gave Anne Morrow Lindbergh and their five
surviving children something to do besides hold down an agonizing
death watch.
</P>
<P>
   This amazing life receives its full due in A. Scott Berg's
Lindbergh (Putnam, $30), by all odds the nonfiction book of the
year. Berg's achievement is that he makes an essentially cold,
self-absorbed man continually interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh was easier to admire than to like. He was the sort of
man who found it impossible to lose himself in a movie _ it wasn't
real _ the sort of man who kept and filed every scrap of paper, the
sort of man who gave his children long lists of duties they were
expected to perform, the sort of man who even tried to control his
unknown biographer by leaving him notes.
</P>
<P>
   Rigid, anal, without anything that might be recognized as a
sense of humor, Lindbergh emerges from the pages of Berg's splendid
book as a joyless, furrowed-brow character out of Lake Wobegon,
Minn. _ earnestness gone berserk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was emotionally stunted,'' says Berg. ``He grew up alone,
in a cold house with mismatched parents, and he tuned it all out.''
</P>
<P>
   What Charles Lindbergh didn't perceive didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   This is why he could triumph doing something that other men had
died attempting _ fly across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   He did this by focusing on his version of reality: the bolts,
the struts, the thin fabric that made up The Spirit of St. Louis,
the gas that filled its tanks, the fight to stay awake, the
position of the sun. Dying was not part of his equation _ therefore
it was banished from consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh's passage to Le Bourget airport in May 1927 signaled
the arrival of a new order just as surely as the sinking of the
Titanic signaled the death of the old. He had sparked the modern
aviation industry and, however unwillingly, the modern age of
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in an age of instant fame,'' says Scott Berg.
``Lindbergh performed a death-defying deed, he did something no one
had done before. Beyond that, he was the first man to be stalked by
the press _ all the codes of ethics went out the window, both when
he flew to Paris and when his son was kidnapped and died.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chase that killed Diana started the night Lindbergh landed
in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   He never said `I was wrong'
</P>
<P>
   _ and he never cried
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lindbergh always gave the impression of a plain-spoken
farm boy with a mechanical gift. Actually, he was the son of a
Minnesota congressman, and if he wasn't exactly born with a silver
spoon, he certainly had one of finest pewter. But that was never
good enough for Lindbergh, who was determined to achieve on his
own.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1924, the 22-year-old Lindbergh enlisted in the Army
Air Service and graduated first in his class. Bored with flying
mail, he began planning to capture a prize of $25,000 for the first
aviator to fly nonstop between New York and Paris. The odds weren't
good; Lloyd's of London was offering 10 to 1 against.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh didn't care. He took off from Roosevelt Field on Long
Island at 7:54 a.m. on May 20, 1927, and landed in Paris at 10:24
p.m. the next day. More than 150,000 people greeted him. The world
adored him. He was only 25, and, along with Babe Ruth, the
personification of America.
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, he married Anne Morrow, the daughter of the American
ambassador to Mexico, Dwight Morrow. Now the American prince had a
princess, and they became the First Couple of Aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh went from strength to strength, proselytizing for air
travel, helping form Pam American airlines. With the birth of the
Lindberghs' son, Charles Jr., in June of 1930, there was an heir.
</P>
<P>
   But less than two years later, on March 1, 1932, the child was
kidnapped from his second-floor nursery in the Lindbergh home in
New Jersey. A few months later, the badly decomposed body was
discovered a few miles from the house. A German carpenter from the
Bronx, Bruno Richard Hauptmann, was arrested, tried and executed
for the crime _ in a media circus every bit as sensational as the
O.J. Simpson trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Bruno Hauptmann's was the trial of the century,''
says Berg. It must have been an appalling process for someone as
deeply shy as Lindbergh, compounding the incomprehensible death of
his child. As always, Lindbergh was impossible to read publicly,
and nearly as opaque privately.
</P>
<P>
   He never cried about the death of his son, his wife's diaries
reveal, not once.
</P>
<P>
   After Hauptmann's execution, Lindbergh and his wife left America
for a time, and it's clear that his alienation fed what would
become a sad infatuation with Nazism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in quest of law and order, peace and quiet, and he saw
those things in Germany, while overlooking the great crimes that
were being committed at the same time,'' Berg says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that he was pro-German; he saw them moving forward as
opposed to England and Russia, who weren't going anywhere. Germany
had been defeated in World War I, but now they were prosperous.
They were building airplanes!''
</P>
<P>
   So, at the end of the tumultuous '30s, Lindbergh came out as an
isolationist, quite a popular stance at the time. Europe's business
was Europe's, Hitler's was Hitler's. What did the business of a
corrupt old order have to do with America?
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh became a stalwart member of the group known as America
First _ among the other members were Sargent Shriver and Gerald
Ford _ and made a series of appearances that culminated in the
disastrous speech he gave in Des Moines in July of 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, scanning the words, you can only shake your head at
sentiments echoed today only in the tracts of white supremacists:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tolerance is a virtue that depends upon peace and strength.
History shows that it cannot survive war and devastation. A few
far-sighted Jewish people realize this, and stand opposed to
intervention. But the majority still do not. Their greatest danger
to this country lies in their large ownership and influence in our
motion picture, our press, our radio and our government.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh went on to say that the English and the Jews, ``for
reasons which are understandable from their viewpoint as they are
inadvisable from ours, for reasons which are not American,'' were
pushing America into war.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Roosevelt took Lindbergh's speeches personally, and he
seems to have been one of the few people the president actively
disliked (Joe Kennedy was another, for more or less the same
reasons).
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt believed Lindbergh was genuinely dangerous, and he was
probably right. Had Lindbergh begun his efforts a few years
earlier, it might have been that much harder for Roosevelt to get
anywhere at all with an already isolationist Congress.
</P>
<P>
   After Pearl Harbor, Lindbergh tried to get into the Air Corps,
but Roosevelt personally put out the word that Lindbergh was not to
be allowed to serve his country.
</P>
<P>
   He eventually became a test pilot in private industry, and, late
in the war, slid into the Marines through the back door and flew
more than 25 combat bombing missions as a civilian. Aside from his
indomitable will and stamina _ before the 33 hours it took to fly
to Paris, he had been up for 23 hours getting ready _ he was a
truly superb pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences of Lindbergh's alliance with, at best,
wrong-headed fools and, at worst, fascists, were catastrophic. He
never really recovered his public standing, despite a series of
excellent books _ he was a painstaking writer who never needed a
ghost _ including The Spirit of St. Louis, which won the Pulitzer
Prize in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Although he never recanted his association with America First,
or the remarks about Jews, he carefully excised various comments
about Jews from his diaries when they were published in the early
'70s. Berg prints them. While not rabidly anti-Semitic, they
clearly show that Lindbergh regarded Jews as the seasoning in
society's stew _ lightly sprinkled, fine, but too many spoiled
everything. Cumulatively, Lindbergh's public and private remarks
demonstrate the genteel but debilitating anti-Semitism that was
pervasive in all aspects of American society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lindbergh had no sense of politics,'' says Berg. ``He didn't
think through repercussions. He said what he thought and it cost
him his popularity. `I told the truth,' he told his wife. `Why
didn't they listen to the whole speech? Don't the Jews realize
they'll just bring more trouble on themselves?'''
</P>
<P>
   The phrase ``I was wrong,'' never passed Charles Lindbergh's
lips, about America First or anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' says Berg, ``you have people hanging on your every
word every day of your life after you're 25 years old. It can
promote an unhealthy certitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles and Anne: Shyness in common
</P>
<P>
   Emotionally, Lindbergh was a Victorian, a 19th-century man; his
wife was an archetypal 20th-century woman, with all of the
conflicts, needs and surging emotions of a woman who wants to be
more than a wife and mother.
</P>
<P>
   One on one, his will was the stronger, and she was forced to
adopt a submissive role. Yet, at the same time, he continually
pushed her toward her own destiny, her writing, which culminated in
lovely books, most prominently Gift From the Sea.
</P>
<P>
   By the early '50s, the marriage wound down to the status of
name-only, and they went their own ways _ Lindbergh on his
incessant travels in pursuit of his autodidact's education in
anthropology and conservation, Anne to her writing and a serious
affair with her internist.
</P>
<P>
   Given their vast differences, what kept the marriage going as
long as it did?
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnetism was powerful,'' says Berg. ``They were two
genuinely shy people, and they stuck together. Each of them
worshiped the other. He was drawn to her poetic nature because it
was something he completely lacked, and she was drawn to his
outdoorsiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her prose, of course, is wonderful, and her writing began with
their flying trips. He gave her life experience; he got her out of
the room. If it hadn't been for Lindbergh, she would have been
Emily Dickinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, I think they had a hot, sexual marriage. And
after a point, when he just didn't want to be around anymore, I
think she seriously considered leaving him, but there was a
problem: she always loved him. She made a vow, and she stuck to her
ows. And Anne had a hair-shirt attitude, I think; she got off on a
little pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh could always justify his frantic aversion toward
staying in one place by saying he was running toward something, not
away from anything, but Berg believes he actually spent his life in
flight from emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as the family got domestic or touchy-feely, he was out
the door. And yet, when all was said and done, those kids had two
loving parents _ it was a safe, stable home, with a great gene
pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg doesn't pretend to a bogus omniscience; although it's
almost certain that Hauptmann must have had accomplices in the
kidnapping of Charles Jr., for instance, Berg says simply that
we'll almost certainly never know who they were.
</P>
<P>
   Lindbergh was, as might be expected, a tough father, full of
very high expectations. There's a quietly horrifying vignette in
the book, when Lindbergh begins idly tossing a pillow at one of his
children who's just started walking. The pillow knocks the child
down. He gets up. Over and over, Lindbergh tosses the pillow at his
child, knocking him down each time. Assertiveness training or a
touch of sadism?
</P>
<P>
   Debate was never in the equation, and, when Scott, the youngest
of Lindbergh's sons _ counting Charles Jr., there were six children
in all _ defied him, they didn't speak for four years. It goes
without saying that Scott was the child most like his father.
</P>
<P>
   People who are uncomfortable with human beings often gravitate
to animals, so it is not surprising that the most emotional entry
in Lindbergh's decades of diaries concerns the death of the massive
German shepherd Thor that Lindbergh bought for protection after the
death of his child. The dog adored Anne above all others, and gave
her the protective, enveloping attention her husband never could.
</P>
<P>
   As told by Scott Berg, the story of Charles Lindbergh's life and
death is a moral tale about the the rewards and perils of being
completely focused on the external world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lindbergh had a thing about balance,'' says his biographer.
``He believed that one should live a balanced life. And the
adulation he received was so extreme that I think part of him
figured that there had to be an equal and opposite reaction. There
was a price to be paid for everything he had, and he certainly paid
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
