<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-CARS-GADGETS07-CO     10-05 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-CARS-GADGETS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Back-seat TVs - and air bags everywhere
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tired of trying to watch the kids and the road at the same time?
Let them watch TV.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile's Silhouette Premiere minivan (about $31,000) offers
a 5.6-inch color monitor that flips down from the ceiling, facing
the rear seats. Unless you have a really long cable, you won't get
Sesame Street, but it has a video cassette player and hookups for
Nintendo and other games. Mom and Dad get their own radio/tape/CD
earphone jacks as sanity protection.
</P>
<P>
   Similar systems have been available as add-ons from electronic
stores, but this is the first one installed at the factory and
covered by the vehicle warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Boring as it may be, most other new-car gadgets and gimmicks
actually have to do with driving. Or crashing.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you're getting used to the idea of an air bag
exploding in your face, here come more of them aimed at your sides,
feet and head.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in the premium price range, manufacturers like
Mercedes-Benz and BMW are touting new places, sizes and shapes for
inflatable restraints. Volvo also adds a ``whiplash protection
system'' that automatically reclines the seat-back to reduce strain
in a rear-end collision.
</P>
<P>
   Rather avoid collisions altogether?
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury Mountaineer and Ford Explorer SUVs and Ford's
restyled Windstar van offer a sonar-activated Reverse Sensing
System that beeps when the driver's within 6 feet of backing into
something (or someone). The beeps become faster, and then
continuous, as a collision gets closer. BMW's top models have a
similar Park Distance Control that warns of obstacles in either
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz, of course, wouldn't be rude enough to remind
drivers to slow down when the car could just do it for them. The
cruise control on the company's new full-size, S-class sedans
automatically keeps a safe distance from the car ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Need some help making your way around town? A computerized
navigation system is the only option on the Acura 3.2TL.
</P>
<P>
   If you can wait another year, Cadillac promises a treat on
several 2000 models for old-fashioned types who want enough
information to make their own decisions: infrared night vision.
</P>
<P>
   A glowing black-and-white image like the ones in those Desert
Storm videos will appear at the bottom of the windshield, allowing
drivers to see five times farther ahead than with headlights alone.
</P>
<P>
   And for those who want to just lean back and get comfortable,
the Lincoln Navigator and Ford Expedition offer power-adjustable
pedals. An electric control slides the brake and gas up to 3 inches
closer, so the driver can sit farther from the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
