<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0909 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCHUMER-400&AMP;A     10-05 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHUMER-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER SAYS CLINTON'S ACTIONS DO NOT WARRANT IMPEACHMENT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his first detailed remarks on the Monica
Lewinsky matter, Rep. Charles Schumer said Monday that President
Clinton's lies about his extra-marital affair were wrong and
possibly illegal but did not warrant impeachment. He called instead
for some lesser form of punishment, perhaps censure or a rebuke.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer, a Democrat from New York who is running for U.S.
Senate, also questioned the impartiality of Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel, accusing him of having ``seriously
overreached'' in his investigation and of presenting ``flimsy
evidence'' in his voluminous report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time we move forward, and not have the Congress and the
American people endure a specter of what could be a year-long focus
on a tawdry but not impeachable affair,'' said Schumer, offering
one of the more ringing defenses of the Clinton presidency among
members of the House Judiciary Committee Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As Schumer made his comments Monday, his campaign was preparing
a major fund-raising event featuring the president in New York City
next Monday, providing further evidence that even when wounded,
Clinton remains a popular and potent political force in New York
State. The full House is scheduled to vote on whether to begin an
impeachment inquiry of the president this Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from a prepared statement, Schumer warned the committee
Monday that important issues ranging from education to health care
had been shunted aside by the powerful wake of the Lewinsky
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world economy is in crisis and cries out for American
leadership without which worldwide turmoil is a grave
possibility,'' Schumer said. ``This investigation, now in its fifth
year, has run it's course. It's time to move on.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Schumer, who is known for having once theatrically waved an
assault weapon at a Judiciary Committee hearing but whose
attendance this year has been severely truncated by the rigors of
his campaign, left soon after making his statement to meet with
reporters, even as other committee members remained to listen to
their colleagues' statements.
</P>
<P>
   The president's problems have hung like a dark cloud over the
New York Senate race all year, leaving strategists for both Schumer
and the Republican incumbent, Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato, unsure of
who was threatened more by the storm. As a result, neither man has
said much to defend or criticize the president until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The president's problems most clearly posed a dilemma for
Schumer, who has been a strong supporter of Clinton and whose
evident desire to recruit the president's help on his campaign may
have been hamstrung by his seat on the Judiciary Committee
overseeing the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Schumer said Monday that his decision to oppose
impeachment unequivocally had in a way liberated him. ``I made up
my mind yesterday and I slept like a baby last night,'' he said to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer said he felt that the average person would receive no
punishment for telling lies about an extra-marital affair, even
under oath. But because presidents ``should be held to a higher
standard,'' he said Clinton should receive a ``significant
punishment'' short of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters Monday if there was not a conflict of
interest in his sitting in judgment on a president who was giving
him campaign assistance, Schumer emphatically said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think New Yorkers are fair and they are going to judge what
I said based on the merits,'' he said. ``We'll have to let the
chips fall where they may politically.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schumer's advisers clearly believe that the chips will fall
in their favor. They contend that D'Amato will now feel pressure
either to defend the president, which could anger D'Amato's
conservative base, or to defend the Republican leadership pushing
for impeachment, which could infuriate swing voters who still like
Clinton, or at least his policies.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato displayed some concern about the issue in remarks to
reporters Monday following a Manhattan campaign event where he
received an award for helping direct federal mass transit funds to
the New York metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would try to make impeachment a campaign issue,
D'Amato said no, and instead accused an unnamed adviser to Schumer
of encouraging reporters to write about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has this guy who does it continually, puts out these
nonsense rumors and things,'' D'Amato said. ``We haven't done it
and I don't intend to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by a reporter who this adviser was, D'Amato replied, ``If
you don't know, then he hasn't approached you.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-term Republican also said that he was ``not going to
be critical'' of Schumer's remarks on impeachment, adding that he
would not offer his own opinion because he may be required to vote
on whether to remove or punish the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the Senate, then I'll act in a manner in
which the facts and times dictate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato also continued his attack on Schumer's spotty attendance
record this year, releasing a new radio ad that charges that
Schumer has missed more votes, 110, in the past 12 months than
D'Amato has missed in the past 12 years. The Senate votes much less
often than the House.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer has accused D'Amato of distorting his record, noting
that his attendance for votes during 18 years is more than 90
percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
