<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-CARS07-COX     10-05 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-CARS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Are you ready for a TV in the back seat?
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Warning: Reading beyond this point could be expensive.
</P>
<P>
   You know what happens when you read about new cars: You want to
go look at them. And you know what happens then.
</P>
<P>
   No spinning watch holds the hypnotic power of deep-gloss paint
magnified by a showroom window. Are you prepared to surrender the
next 48 months of your life?
</P>
<P>
   Don't be so quick to answer. You've risked reading this far, so
you might as well take in all of what Accent's automotive spy corps
has uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   Some '99s have been cruising around for months: You've probably
seen the Mazda Miata and Mercury Cougar, at least in commercials.
You'll start seeing the rest soon.
</P>
<P>
   The most familiar feature: the price. Not many are going up, and
lots of models will actually cost less than last year or get
additional equipment at no charge. Interest rates are lower than
they were last fall, too.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Child, news editor of the trade journal Automotive News,
summarizes the theme for '99 as ``a return to comfort'' and he
credits the demands of aging Baby Boomers who dominate the market.
It's because of them that you'll see more:
</P>
<P>
   Luxo-trucks: Ford needed little more than a few yards of leather
to turn its brawny Expedition into the Lincoln Navigator, one of
last year's biggest hits. Look for more posh and pricey
permutations of popular SUVs and minivanscq, including the new
Cadillac Escalade.
</P>
<P>
   Luxo-cars: There's a crowd gathering on both sides of the
$30,000 entry mark, with new models from BMW, Acura, Volvo and
others. Cadillac jumped in last year with the Catera. Lincoln's LS
is due later in 1999, probably as a 2000 model.
</P>
<P>
   Power: Many models will get more, even in the face of mileage
and environmental demands.
</P>
<P>
   Pizzaz: Hard to quantify, but you know it's important when even
Volvo is trying to look stylish. The very eye-catching Mercury
Cougar will be a clue to future Ford styling, if it's a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some of the cars that show off these trends:
</P>
<P>
   Volvo C70: Those sensible Swedes go wild with a swoopy,
four-seat convertible. A turbo-charged 5-cylinder engine is
standard. Vroom with a view, for about $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jeep Grand Cherokee: The second best-selling SUV (after the Ford
Explorer) is completely restyled to look instantly familiar. Best
new feature: The spare tire's under the load floor so it doesn't
crowd cargo space. And the price is down $250. From $26,220.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac Escalade: The first Cadillac truck for people who can
still sit up is a thinly disguised GMC Denali, which is a thinly
disguised Chevrolet Tahoe sport utility vehicle. All the
road-hugging weight of a '60s DeVille but less road-hogging length.
The name means to climb with a ladder. About $47,000.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo S80: A big, front-drive replacement for the S90 comes
loaded with luxury equipment and, surprise, new safety features.
And it looks, um, different. From about $36,400.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet Silverado/GMC Sierra: You don't care about pickup
trucks? You're outnumbered. The No. 2-selling vehicles in the land
get more power, better mileage and a more carlike ride. From about
$14,000 for a basic work truck; more like $20,000-plus for a
suitable sedan substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler 300M: Trying to do with a name what Volkswagen did with
a body, Chrysler borrows an image from the 1950s, when its 300s
were big and fast. This one's actually a bit shorter than other
full-size Chryslers, but it's still quick. About $28,500.
</P>
<P>
   BMW 3-series: The favorite car of yuppies and Boca high
schoolers gets new four-door versions with more interior room and
optional rear-seat, side-impact airbags. About $27,000 for the
323i; $34,000 for the more powerful 328i.
</P>
<P>
   Acura 3.2TL: New style, more power and a much lower price. A
direct competitor to the BMW 3-series, it comes only one way:
loaded. The only option: a computerized navigation system. And it's
about $4,000 less than last year. About $28,000.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz CLK320: Can a Mercedes be a bargain? The company's
last four-seat convertible cost about $80,000. This one's a few
inches smaller, but otherwise comparable in performance and it
comes loaded with equipment for about $30,000 less. Yes, a bargain,
at $47,200.
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac Grand Am/Oldsmobile Alero: Variations on GM's midsize
theme, both promise tighter construction and more Euro feel. The
Alero is quite understated; the Grand Am GT is for people who like
the attention you'd get wearing a zoot suit. From about $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota Camry Solara: America's best-selling but possibly dullest
car gets a designer makeover and comes out looking rich. Two doors
only, but either four or six cylinders. From just under $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Mustang: The Boomers have turned their aching backs on the
pony cars that were created for them, and many expect the Camaro
and Firebird to be gone by year's end. But Ford's trying to
reignite the Mustang fire with sleeker styling and, of course, more
horsepower. From under $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
