<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0908 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-UPN07-COX     10-05 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-UPN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPN still looking for an identity _ and an audience
 &HT;    By Kevin Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a story, of three lovely networks. OK, enough of that.
Let's pretend that Fox, the WB and UPN are The Brady Bunch girls.
Since the surging Fox is the most popular of the three, it would be
Marcia. The upstart, buzz-heavy WB is young and budding with rosy
potential. That makes it Cindy.
</P>
<P>
   UPN?
</P>
<P>
   Well, I guess that leaves poor 'ol Jan. You know, the least
popular Brady girl. She's not the prettiest, nor the youngest.
In-the-middle Jan is just the one with the serious identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Yup, that describes UPN, which rolls out its new fall shows on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   When you think of the other five networks, immediate images
flash through your mind. CBS _ old. Fox _ edgy. NBC _ white,
upscale New York. WB _ hip teens. ABC _ blue-collar.
</P>
<P>
   But viewers don't really know what UPN is. All they know _ and
really care about _ is UPN airs Star Trek: Voyager and Moesha. Even
the network admits it's scrambling to cement its identity. As Tom
Nunan, UPN's entertainment president, glumly acknowledges, ``We're
struggling to find our own audience.''
</P>
<P>
   That search begins in earnest on Monday. But what does the new
schedule say about UPN? It's hard to tell, since the network
appears to be appealing to every known demographic.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, there's a comedy about two single guys (one white,
one black) raising a precocious 6-year-old. There's a post-Civil
War, Dynasty-like soap, a sitcom about a harried transit cop, a
futuristic, ER-like drama, an action-packed adventure about time
travel and a controversial sitcom about President Lincoln's black
butler.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying for an umbrella strategy,'' says Dean Valentine,
UPN's CEO and president.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: We're trying to please everyone.
</P>
<P>
   A noble ambition, yes. Possible? Not likely. But Valentine, the
former president of Walt Disney Television and Walt Disney
Television Animation, is a man with a vision unique in Hollywood.
Unlike the other networks, Valentine doesn't believe in
narrow-casting. He doesn't think it's wise for networks to target
most of their shows to a particular audience. (Can you say,
``NBC?'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any broadcast network that adopts a narrow-cast model
is ultimately doomed to failure,'' argues Valentine. ``I believe
there has to be something that brings America together.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a serious about-face from the network's ill-fated
strategy two years ago. Like Fox, UPN thought it would become the
home for black-themed shows. In September 1996, only 20 months
after its launch, UPN had Good Behavior, Sparks, Homeboys in Outer
Space, The Jamie Foxx Show and Malcolm &AMP; Eddie on its schedule.
Only Malcolm &AMP; Eddie and The Jamie Foxx Show remain.
</P>
<P>
   While Fox was able to establish itself as a serious network with
such black-oriented shows as Martin, Living Single and In Living
Color, UPN was not. When Valentine took over, one of the first
things he did was dump the shows that didn't fit his vision.
</P>
<P>
   But what UPN needs more than anything is a buzz show. It needs a
show everyone is talking about. It needs a Felicity. A Dawson's
Creek. Something. The only UPN show people are talking about is the
absurd The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer. And that's only
because it offended many black groups for poking fun at slavery.
Even hard-core Lincoln fans are complaining. That's not the kind of
attention a hit-starved network needs.
</P>
<P>
   UPN suits like making fun of their WB competitors (and its green
mascot), but that network has found a gold-mine niche and has
exploited it well. Teen girls are playing a more powerful role in
what we see _ and don't see _ on TV. Thank such WB hits as Buffy
the Vampire Slayer and Dawson's Creek for that current trend.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for UPN, it will be forever linked with the WB
like Coke is to Pepsi, Batman to Robin and Lucy to Ricky. Both
started in 1995 and have been battling to become the undisputed
fifth network. But if this battle was a prize fight, it would've
been stopped by now. UPN is badly beaten, bloodied and on the
ropes. Not only did the WB post a higher Nielsen household rating
than UPN last season (3.1 versus 2.8), the network is more
desirable to all-important Madison Avenue execs looking to hawk
their products.
</P>
<P>
   And the perception, which is oh-so-important in Tinseltown, is
that the WB is the cool, up-and-coming network. And that perception
existed before the WB started beating UPN in household ratings.
</P>
<P>
   So, what about UPN's new shows? The network actually has several
decent offerings. 7 Days, about a buff, time-traveling hero
(Jonathan LaPaglia), looks promising. Mercy Point, a sci-fi medical
drama, could possibly be the network's next Voyager. (Tip to UPN:
Plug that show heavily, since Voyager's on the down-slide.) Legacy,
that good-looking Civil War soap, may also catch on, and if UPN is
lucky, might become its Dawson's Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an interesting sort of checkerboard schedule,'' Nunan
says. ``It's not just she-TV one night. It isn't monochromatic.
It's Technicolor. That's a way for us to change our identity and to
get people looking at UPN differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But until something clicks, I'll still think of
identity-challenged Jan when I watch identity-challenged UPN.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
