<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOSTELS-MAIN07-COX     10-05 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSTELS-MAIN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why do these rooms cost $20 or less?
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two skiers were complaining about the high price of lift tickets
as we stood in line on the side of a mountain in the exclusive ski
town of Breckenridge, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   But I really didn't care how much the lift tickets were because
I had already saved the real money.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't staying in a $250-a-night condo.
</P>
<P>
   I was paying $15 a night at a youth hostel. And that included
breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   My friends and I were bunking in clean, warm rooms with modern
shared baths. The lobby had a huge stone fireplace where we stayed
up late talking to other guests _ most of whom were not youths. All
were gregarious and most were serious skiers, including several
European pros.
</P>
<P>
   I've stayed in hostels all over the world, including one on a
historic clipper ship docked in Stockholm, Sweden; a farmhouse in
Australia; and a mountain lodge in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   And they all had cost less than $20 a night.
</P>
<P>
   The hostel experience is far removed, and in my estimation, far
superior to the Marriott experience.
</P>
<P>
   While you won't get room service and SpectraVision at a hostel,
you probably will be staying in an excellent location with a
helpful staff and a friendly assortment of fellow travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Youth'' is a misnomer. Seniors have discovered hostels _ 13
percent of members are 55 or older.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of guests are college-educated or students, who are
sophisticated and curious travelers. Authors and travel experts
Arthur Frommer and Rick Steves frequently stay in hostels.
</P>
<P>
   At Hostelling International New York, a large hostel on
Manhattan's Upper West Side, Darren Leiper, a 21-year-old
university student from Edinburgh, Scotland, was ending a tour of
the United States after staying at hostels across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cheaper than at the hotels, $24 for one night (in New
York),'' he said. ``People are sociable, everybody's traveling. You
find out about things to do, what to see.''
</P>
<P>
   His favorite hostel? ``No doubt, the one in Flagstaff (Arizona)
near the Grand Canyon. That was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Tara Wheeler, 30, who owns a spinning and weaving shop in
Taylor, Texas, was staying at the Abominable Snowman Mansion hostel
in Taos, N.M., last week during a business conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's inexpensive, very friendly, very homey, and a lot more
interesting than staying in a hotel,'' she said. ``Upstairs there
are a group here for mountain biking, and I met a gentleman who's
an expert in natural dyes for wool, which is what I'm interested
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The rate was $16 a night. ``There's a dormitory room, a women's
wing and men's wing, and communal shower. It's really nice,'' she
said. ``You can't beat it during ski season.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe especially, hostels are traditionally a place to share
information _ to find out the most scenic Swiss trains, the bank
that has the best exchange rate, where to buy French Foreign Legion
jackets, etc. _ and, of course, to get recommendations about other
hostels.
</P>
<P>
   The hostels in the nonprofit Hostelling International-American
Youth Hostels, the largest hostel organization, include a
lighthouse on the California coast, a castle in Germany, a former
one-room schoolhouse in the Australian bush, and lodges in Redwood
National Park and Cape Cod National Seashore.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1934, the organization has a network of 5,000 hostels
with 33 million overnight visits each year in more than 70
countries. Franklin D. Roosevelt was honorary president and a big
supporter of the organization in its early days.
</P>
<P>
   And no matter how historic or modern the building, or whether
it's on the Left Bank in Paris or on a ski slope in Aspen, they
cost only $8 to $20 per person per night. (In New York City and at
some ski resorts, the rate can go up to $27.)
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, guests were mainly university students and
teachers, but today they're attracting families and groups. Most
hostels have family rooms with private baths (these cost more than
$20) and meeting rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Hostels are popular with Girl Scouts, Boy Scouts, university
groups and church groups, which all receive free memberships.
</P>
<P>
   The safety and service levels are high _ all hostels in the
organization are inspected annually, and guests are asked to fill
out comment cards, which are reviewed at the organization's
headquarters in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Guests, especially in urban areas such as New York and
Washington, must show membership cards or receipts to be admitted
in the buildings. They also restrict guests to travelers who live
at least 30 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Youth hostels have come a long way since the turn of the century
when Richard Schirrmann, a schoolteacher in a German coal mining
town, became concerned about his students' health and started
taking them into the countryside on weekend field trips for fresh
air and nature study.
</P>
<P>
   Schirrmann used schools, empty on weekends, for overnight
lodging. The first hostel opened in a castle in Altena, Germany, in
1909. Soon, a network of ``youth hostels'' grew rapidly in Germany
with more than 2,000 hostels recording more than 4.5 million
overnight stays each year by 1932.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Europe quickly followed and added other hostels to
the network. In 1932, the first international meeting was held in
Amsterdam and the International Youth Hostel Federation was formed.
</P>
<P>
   American teachers Isabel and Monroe Smith attended the 1933
conference and opened the first youth hostel a year later in
Northfield, Mass., which inspired other hostels throughout New
England.
</P>
<P>
   The network expanded to Asia, Africa and South America.
</P>
<P>
   This European idea is still more popular in Europe than in the
U.S. More than three-fourths of new American members join before
taking a trip to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But as Frommer and Steves know, hostels can save lots of money
in the U.S., too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
