<SLUG> BC-HOSTELS-RUSTIC07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peace, love and palmetto bugs
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ Beep!
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, it's me. In case you never hear from me again, I am
calling from a place called The Hostel in the Forest in Brunswick,
Ga. I'm a little nervous about staying here overnight. This guy
from Germany gave me a tour of the place _ he's a little
scary-looking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the closest thing to a commune I've ever seen. You sleep
in rooms on stilts in the forest, and they have composting toilets,
and they have this 10-foot-deep rainwater pool that is green as an
emerald, with ducks swimming arou ... ''
</P>
<P>
   beep!
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey! Swimming around. So the guy pointed out a bottle of
alcohol to rub in your ears to prevent ear infections. I don't
know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are you, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ``And there're bugs in the rooms. I asked what kind and he said
he didn't know the name but he held his fingers more than an inch
apart. Cockroaches? No. Palmetto bugs? `That's it. They can fly,'
he said. This place is about a half-mile off the road, over this
sandy, bumpy trail through the woods. You are away from absolutely
everything. It's only $12 a night, though, with dinner included. I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   beep!
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom. OK, they have regular toilets, but they put this guilt
trip on you with this sign that says `Toilet of Shame' and inside
the door is this diagram that shows how the `human nutrient cycle'
is broken when you don't use composting toilets. But the showers
are clean and have warm water after a few minutes. I'm going to
stay.''
</P>
<P>
   beep!
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, where are you? It's after midnight! I just wanted to tell
you about this place. It's wild! Every Friday night the hostel
people get together in the VW bus _ of course _ and drive down the
road a mile or two to this place called the Honeydripper. It's a
real juke joint, as the hostel manager, an Australian, called it.
It's this old wooden building just off the road with a Bud sign
blinking in the window. And inside, there are old Schlitz posters
on the walls _ a 1981 calendar! And one old booth and stools by the
wooden counter and a woman named Essie Mae tending ... ''
</P>
<P>
   beep!
</P>
<P>
   ``TENDING BAR _ I hate this machine _ with a big old TV beside
her with the sound off. All the hostel people were drinking big
bottles of Miller High Life at little dinky tables or shooting
pool. There were about six other people there. And there was a
jukebox. We kept playing Strokin', I think it's called, for this
elderly woman named Miss Louise that the hostel people pick up
every week and bring here. She loves that song. There were bare
light bulbs. There's this tiny sign way up on one of the wooden
posts that says `No Loitering' _ that was neat. Great time _ it
really beat staying in a hotel with the stupid TV. Love you!''
</P>
<P>
   beep!
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you're sleeping in? Hey, it's me. Boy, what a night. The
light and fan in my room on stilts didn't work, so I lit two
candles and looked all around at the palmetto bugs. Yuck. But it
rained during the night, and that was cozy. A great view in the
morning from the windows. I hung out a little before leaving and
read some of the guest sign-in books. Lots of praise and bad
poetry, you know. The best thing was a history of the hostel,
written ...''
</P>
<P>
   beep!
</P>
<P>
   ``Written by the guy who built it. A local hippie lawyer with
lots of travel experience started this in 1975 on 90 acres. It was
the first official hostel in the Southeast! People were suspicious
and said it was a hippie hotel, so this lawyer, Tom Dennard, had to
run around and explain it to the local business people. Oh, and the
bad road is deliberate, meant to slow you and your thoughts down.
It does something to you _ here I am eating a pancake that someone
made, just rolled it up and am eating it like a hot dog, no syrup.
I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   beep!
</P>
<P>
   The Hostel in the Forest is on U.S. 82 west of Brunswick, Ga.
Phone: (912) 264-9738. Per night: $12.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
