</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TINPAN-ALLEY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whatever happened to Tin Pan Alley?
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Irving Berlin was in his 90s, he could still
find his way to Tin Pan Alley, or at least what remained of it.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking a cigar, he would walk into Colony Music on the first
floor of the Brill Building on Broadway and 49th Street and ask the
same question each time: ``How is Easter Parade selling?''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Turk, one of the music store's owners, would assure him
it was selling well. ``And he would say `Still selling White
Christmas?''' Turk recalls. ``And I would say `White Christmas will
always sell.'''
</P>
<P>
   Berlin died in 1989 at the age of 101, but Tin Pan Alley lives
on, in the music it produced if not in actuality.
</P>
<P>
   The new play The Tin Pan Alley Rag opens Tuesday (Oct. 6) at the
Coconut Grove Playhouse in Miami, and the Tony-winning Ragtime is a
Broadway hit. Happy Birthday, George Gershwin, a tribute to the Tin
Pan Alley composer on the 100th anniversary of his birth, was
presented at Carnegie Hall and shown on PBS Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Tin Pan Alley was not an alley or a street but a district near
the corner of Broadway and 14th Street, where new music publishers,
mostly Jewish and most of Eastern European descent, set up shop in
the 1880s.
</P>
<P>
   A steady parade of composers followed.
</P>
<P>
   Tin Pan Alley was the MTV of its day, its publishers
aggressively promoting new songs. The name probably came from the
tinny sound of the pianos played by ``song pluggers,'' who played
new songs on the streets, in theaters, music shops and even the big
department stores.
</P>
<P>
   Tin Pan Alley hits ranged from Charles K. Harris' After the
Ball, which sold nearly 5 million copies in 1892, to George M.
Cohan's Give My Regards to Broadway in 1904 to Duke Ellington's Do
Nothin' Till You Hear from Me in 1943.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bold and creative marketing of Tin Pan Alley, music
publishers in cities such as Boston and Philadelphia did not
heavily promote songwriters of the day. Stephen Foster, George Root
and Will Hays survived by word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1880s, the new group of publishers promoted new
songwriters in newspapers and magazines; paid famous singers to
sing the songs, and staged musicals in theaters and the vaudeville
circuits.
</P>
<P>
   The songs were sold as sheet music until the 1920s, when the
music industry began producing recordings and promoting them on
radio. The 1930s brought movie musicals and even bigger business.
</P>
<P>
   After the turn of the century, the publishers moved uptown to
West 42nd Street, and from 1911-19, they congregated in the
vicinity of the Exchange Building at 145 West 45th St. During the
1920s, they moved to an area near 49th Street.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1930s to 1950s, the music industry was centered around
and in the Brill Building, erected in 1931 at 1619 Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Tin Pan Alley died when rock music was born, and music promoters
went elsewhere. The music publishers in the Brill Building have
been replaced by public relations firms and editing companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Tin Pan Alley's best stars, a generation of brilliant young
composers including Irving Berlin, Jerome Kern, Richard Rodgers,
Lorenz Hart and Oscar Hammerstein II, live on in new plays and
movies based on their music.
</P>
<P>
   Music lovers from around the world still stop by the Brill
Building and Colony Music to talk about Tin Pan Alley.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come from Japan, Germany, from all over, and I'm always
surprised by how knowledgeable they are,'' Turk says.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers when the Colony, celebrating its 50th anniversary,
was open all night and had a piano in the corner. Ella Fitzgerald,
Frank Sinatra and Jerry Lewis would stop in to play the piano and
sing.
</P>
<P>
   The Colony still does a brisk business in sheet music. And this
is, indeed, the place to buy Easter Parade.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
