<HEADER>
A0918 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHATDREAMS-HEAVEN07-C     10-05 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHATDREAMS-HEAVEN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What does heaven look like
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heaven is a safe place.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven is fun, full of color, filled with angels, a good place
to visit and the house of God.
</P>
<P>
   That's what some kids at St. Ann Roman Catholic School in West
Palm Beach think about heaven. Last week, they drew pictures of
what heaven looks like to them. Some of them have a more mature
faith than many adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heaven is not a place,'' said Amanda White, an eighth-grade
student from Palm Beach Gardens. ``Heaven is an image that helps us
fulfill our faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Visions of heaven give us hope, remind us of the goodness of God
and help us come to terms with what happens when we die.
</P>
<P>
   We want there to be a place for us where life is full and rich,
love rules, laughter reigns and peace abounds for all. Most of us
call that heaven.
</P>
<P>
   What Dreams May Come is a just-released romantic fantasy
starring Robin Williams that takes place in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Paradise for Williams is an oasis of stunning beauty that
mirrors scenes in his mortal life. The landscapes, fields and
flowers he once loved he finds larger than life in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollywood presents only the latest version of what heaven
might be. Artists, theologians and laity have speculated about the
place of eternal life throughout history.
</P>
<P>
   The mind's eye draws pictures rooted in religious belief. But
they are formed by human experience and shaped by our fondest
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Paradise is a place of bliss and sensual pleasure in some
religious traditions. Muslims think of fresh figs, rivers of honey
and streams of clean, sparkling water.
</P>
<P>
   A popular image of heaven for many Floridians is endless perfect
rounds on a championship golf course.
</P>
<P>
   For others, heaven is the place of quintessential spiritual
growth and the eternal worship of God.
</P>
<P>
   Paradise _ the garden of Eden _ is a huge study hall, a place of
learning, in Judaism. People are about 30 years old, there is no
decay and nearly everyone, Jew and Gentile alike, gets in.
</P>
<P>
   Most traditions insist that, whatever it looks like, heaven
means the place where God is present. And the experience of
paradise is spiritual union with that God.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know anything about heaven except that heaven is
where God is,'' said the Rev. Christopher Kelly, pastor of St.
Christopher's Episcopal Church in West Palm Beach. ``Heaven is not
a geographic place at all. It is a state of being. It is union with
God. Wherever God is, that's where heaven is.''
</P>
<P>
   But, like Robin Williams, we often visualize the eternal,
spiritual bliss of heaven using temporal, secular images.
</P>
<P>
   The Elysian field of Roman and Greek mythology was an idyllic
home for departed heroes and the blessed dead. The perfect climate
was assured by the breezes of Zephyrus.
</P>
<P>
   The Bible and the Koran draw rich and concrete illustrations of
paradise. Walls studded with sapphire and emerald, streets of gold
and the delight of the senses are used to create word pictures of
the heavenly city of God.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the faithful take the images literally. Others
understand them as poetic attempts to explain the unexplainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the limited is dealing with the unlimited, we can only
describe the infinite in finite terms,'' said the Rev. Isaiah
Clark, pastor of Union Missionary Baptist Church in West Palm
Beach. ``My mind doesn't go any further.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clark accepts the literal picture of heaven found in the
Revelation of John, the last book of the Christian Bible. John's
vision of heaven as the new Jerusalem is precise.
</P>
<P>
   The city is 1,500 miles square and has 12 gates adorned with
different gems. Streets are gold. There is no sun or moon. God is
the source of light. There will be no night, and the gates will
never be shut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe John got a peek, a preview, of what heaven looks
like,'' Clark said. ``He wrote it and gave us something so that we
can be a people of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Catholic and Orthodox frescoes and canvas paintings of paradise
make up some of the world's finest art, but official Roman Catholic
teaching does not describe the particulars of heaven, according to
the Rev. William Mayer, pastor of St. Ann Church.
</P>
<P>
   He is delighted his school kids tried their hand at drawing what
heaven looks like, but he doubts that paradise is a place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most traditional teaching of the Church is that heaven is
a state of being in the presence of God,'' Mayer said. ``You're not
complete until you're there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, material pictures help us visualize the spiritual.
Muslims imagine delightful things in paradise, according to Jamal
Badawi, an instructor in Islamic studies at St. Mary's University
in Halifax, Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven is like the taste of fine food, cool water, living in
palaces with a perfect climate and beautiful marriage partners, he
said. But Badawi is quick to insist that the images are not to be
taken literally. They are useful only to feel the inexplicable
pleasure and the nearness of God, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prophet said, `In paradise there are things no eye has
ever seen, no ear has ever heard and no thought could ever
conceive,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Islam has various levels of heaven that determine proximity to
God, but ``no one gets jealous,'' Badawi said.
</P>
<P>
   Mormons and Jews have levels or degrees of paradise as well.
Members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints believe
in three degrees of heaven.
</P>
<P>
   All are kingdoms of glory, said John Winfree, a local patriarch
of the Mormon church from North Palm Beach. Earth will one day
become a kingdom of glory as well, taken from its orbit and put in
the presence of God, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish tradition claims there are degrees of proximity to God in
heaven, which is called the world to come, according to Nathan
Katz, chairman of the religious studies department at Florida
International University in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is how close you get to God,'' Katz said.
``Orchestra seats, mezzanine seats is sort of how it is discussed.
The closer to God's presence, the greater the righteousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Jews and Gentiles are welcome, almost everyone makes it and
lives forever at their best age, about 30, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The world to come is both a garden and a place of learning. The
word for paradise means garden of Eden and rabbi's study, Katz
said.
</P>
<P>
   Elaborate visions of heaven abound in all religious traditions,
but perhaps the best story to describe heaven is an old sermon
illustration about a man and his dog.
</P>
<P>
   The man went to the doctor with his loyal beast alongside. He
left his pet in the waiting room when he entered the doctor's
office. The dog whined and scratched at the closed door that kept
him from his master.
</P>
<P>
   Doctor and patient talked of health, life and death. The patient
asked what heaven was like.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what heaven looks like,'' said the doctor. ``I
don't know the color of the wallpaper or whether our fingernails
grow in heaven, but none of that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your dog doesn't know what this room looks like or what goes
on in here, but he is scratching at the door to come in. He knows
you are here, and he wants to be where his master is. That's what
heaven is like.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
