<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA EXHIBITION SEASON CANCELED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA hit another inauspicious milestone Monday, canceling the
entire exhibition season for the first time in league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, our teams cannot possibly be ready to play any
games before November,'' deputy commissioner Russ Granik said.
``It's sad that we have been unable to have any meaningful
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as NBA owners and players prepared to hold a bargaining
session this Thursday _ the first since Aug. 6 _ the commissioner's
office offered more bad news with the announcement that all 114
exhibition games had been killed by the three-month-old lockout.
</P>
<P>
   The league had already postponed training camps for the first
time ever.
</P>
<P>
   And even the decision by players and owners to meet again
probably won't avoid the inevitable: the cancellation of
regular-season games, scheduled to begin Nov. 3. That announcement
will probably come next week.
</P>
<P>
   Teams need a minimum three to four weeks to sign free agents and
hold training camps, and that window is about to close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they could open Nov. 3 if they wanted to,''
players association spokesman Dan Wasserman said. ``If we reached a
deal Thursday, maybe they could start on time, but I think most
people are gearing up for the long haul at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Granik also wrote off the possibility of an imminent solution:
``There's no reason for me to think that the players are going to
say anything other than what they've said already.''
</P>
<P>
   Today should have marked the opening of all 29 teams' training
camps. Instead, players will hold press conferences in a dozen NBA
cities to state their case. Up to 15 players, possibly including
Lakers Derek Fisher and Elden Campbell, will gather at UCLA's men's
gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose is to get the players' point of view across. And
that it's not a strike, it's a lockout (by NBA owners),'' Wasserman
said. ``The players definitely want to play. We've been trying to
compromise,... but the league wants outright concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Players and owners remain entrenched in their original
bargaining positions. The owners want a ``hard'' salary cap and
elimination of the ``Larry Bird rule'' that allows a team to pay
any amount to re-sign its veteran free agents. The union refuses to
give up the Bird clause and won't agree to anything resembling a
hard cap.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only hope for resolution anytime soon lies with
arbitrator John Feerick. Feerick has until Oct. 19 to rule on the
union's claim that some 220 players with guaranteed contracts must
be paid during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   If Feerick rules for the players, the NBA would have little
incentive to continue the lockout; however, the league is expected
to appeal the ruling in federal court if that happens. The union
believes an appeal would fail and add another 30 to 60 days to the
stalemate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981005.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-05 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-HOUSING-NYT &LR;      10-05 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-HOUSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL NEGOTIATORS AGREE TO CREATE MORE RENT SUBSIDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Senate and House negotiators reached agreement
Monday on a bill that would make rent subsidies available to more
poor families and allow more home buyers to qualify for federally
backed mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which seems assured of passage by Congress and of
President Clinton's signature, would create about 90,000 Section 8
vouchers, or federal rent subsidies for low-income tenants. It
would also raise the loan limits on federally insured mortgages to
$197,621 from $170,362.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts HUD back in the housing business,'' Housing and
Urban Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said that both the rental-subsidy provision and the higher
ceiling for mortgages backed by the Federal Housing Administration
would have wide impact in New York City and other metropolitan
areas, where there are long waiting lists for housing assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said the creation of 90,000 rental vouchers was especially
important, because no new Section 8 vouchers have been authorized
since 1994. Nearly three million households now receive housing
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Only two months ago, HUD negotiators had thought they might
persuade lawmakers to authorize 15,000 new vouchers. Authorization
of the far higher number left housing officials ``ecstatic,'' as
one put it Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said the higher mortgage ceiling would benefit about
70,000 families, many of them members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that the HUD portion passes more or less intact, the
housing agency's funds for the fiscal year that began last Thursday
would increase about $2 billion, to $26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had pushed for measures to prevent housing agencies
from separating working families from the very poor, and thus
fostering racial as well as economic segregation. Republicans had
pushed for measures to help the working poor who live in public
housing. Cuomo, saying the bill met both needs, praised negotiators
from both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., chairman of the Banking Committee's
housing subcommittee, said the House Republican leadership had
eased the way for the bill by combining it with the appropriations
bill for the Department of Veterans Affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
