<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; HOSPITAL GIANTS CHARGED WITH FILING FALSE CLAIMS &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The government sued Columbia/HCA Healthcare and Quorum Health
Group, contending that they had defrauded federal health programs
for more than 14 years through a scheme involving bogus expense
claims.
</P>
<P>
   The suit comes after an investigation into allegations of fraud
at the companies. It contends that the hospital giants routinely
overstated expenses in reports to the government to increase their
compensation from federal programs like Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STOCKS FALL SHARPLY ON GLOBAL UNREST &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks fell, leading the stock market lower as the
troubled world economy seemed to undermine investor sentiment. The
Nasdaq index, which is dominated by technology stocks, plunged
78.29 points, or 4.85 percent, to 1,536.69. Cisco Systems was down
13.3 percent after it was disclosed that the Federal Trade
Commission was investigating whether it held illegal conversations
with Lucent and Northern Telecom about dividing up the networking
market.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON APPEALS FOR UNIFIED ATTACK &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made a direct appeal to a group of the world's
top financial officials to come up with a unified attack on the
global economic crisis, after nearly three days of debate produced
a near-stalemate over immediate cures.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SALES AT GM FELL 3.1 PERCENT LAST MONTH &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sales of General Motors cars and trucks fell 3.1 percent in
September, less of a drop than analysts had expected. Ford Motor
saw its September sales climb 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   GM also plans to combine its domestic and international auto
operations in a shake-up expected to be announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AT&AMP;T BUYING VANGUARD CELLULAR &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T agreed to acquire Vanguard Cellular for $900 million in
stock and cash.
 &UR; LATIN AMERICAN OFFICIALS WANT MORE &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Angry at what they consider the lenient treatment that Russia
received in its $4.5 billion bailout by the International Monetary
Fund, Latin American officials and economists warned that the
programs offered to protect their countries were too paltry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEHMAN EXPOSURE $236 MILLION &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers said that the most it would lose from exposure
to hedge funds and emerging markets was $236 million.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANALYSTS SEE HMO SLUMP LASTING &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The managed care companies that dropped 250,000 elderly Medicare
customers last week will have healthier financial statements, but
many analysts said that the move would not be enough to pull the
health maintenance organizations out of a three-year earnings
slump.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMISSION SUES JOSEPHTHAL &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Equal Opportunity Employment Commission filed suit Oct. 1
against the regional brokerage firm Josephthal, seeking punitive
damages for what the commission called ``malicious'' conduct at its
Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CARLSON AND THOMAS COOK IN DEAL &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Carlson Companies plans to merge its leisure travel business in
Britain with the worldwide travel operations of Thomas Cook in a
deal valued at more than $1 billion.
</P>
