</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NFL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS PRE-GAME SHOW SETTLES FOR FIELD GOALS
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
BY RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After five weeks, CBS's revived ``The NFL Today'' is a decent
show but not a memorable one. The former domain of Brent Musburger
and Greg Gumbel boasts a dandy set, zippy graphics, the old theme
song and a miniature gridiron. It is informative but not
compelling. Jim Nantz, the host, and the analysts, George Seifert,
Marcus Allen and Brent Jones, are amiable but predictable.
</P>
<P>
   The foursome does not possess a zippy chemistry, except when
Jones insults Phil Simms when he checks in from a game site. Jones
is opinionated and animated but almost too eager to prove he's a
studio star. Allen's overeagerness to be authoritative has seen him
try to say too much in too little air time.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert is too laid back but has enough smarts to grow in the
job as Joe Gibbs did at NBC. But CBS did Seifert a disservice by
axing his skillful chalkboard segments last month. Nantz is a
knowledgeable and sincere guide, but he's being relied on too much
to control the flow. If Nantz didn't ask questions of the analysts,
it seems no one would know exactly when to speak.
</P>
<P>
   That's the result of CBS hiring three analysts who require
on-the-job training and need to be guided. So it's not surprising
that the show's stars are its experienced field reporters, Bonnie
Bernstein, formerly of ESPN, and Armen Keteyian, a former ABC News
correspondent. Bernstein's profile of Oakland Coach Jon Gruden and
Keteyian's of Deion Sanders were distinguished works.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL Today'' is tame compared with ``Fox NFL Sunday.'' The
Fox program is a rude and lively brew, which has improved this
season with a toned-down but more amusing Terry Bradshaw, and the
addition of the tart Cris Collinsworth. Combined with Howie Long's
informed menace and James Brown's expanding role in fomenting
dissent, Fox offers a merry spin on the pre-game formula.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to explain on Sunday why Tampa Bay has disappointed him
so much, Bradshaw compared the Buccaneers to the ingratiating beau
who holds doors for his future wife and takes her to fine
restaurants while they date. ``Then you marry the clown,'' he said.
``First thing, he takes his toupee off. Then he takes his teeth
out. He doesn't shave. He belches and picks his nose.''
</P>
<P>
   A piquant analysis, but one that makes you chuckle. Bradshaw was
born verbally unbound, which makes him a focus for playful abuse
from the other Foxians, who often speak as they desire, regardless
of who else is speaking.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS foursome is too restrained to be so loose. It is still
finding its way, exhibiting signs of a tight leash from the
production side.
</P>
<P>
   The segments devoted to panel talk feel shorter on CBS than on
Fox, keeping Nantz &AMP; Co. from building better on-air
schmoozability. Jones has lots of loose-cannon potential, but his
ammunition has been of an average caliber, not as wacky, pointed or
intimidating as what emanates from Fox's studio.
</P>
<P>
   By this time in 1994, the Fox show's first season, its
personality was well defined: Bradshaw had become more antic than
he was at CBS; Long's authoritative mien was a pleasant surprise;
Jimmy Johnson opined as if he didn't care if he ever coached again,
and Brown was a stable, able foil.
</P>
<P>
   CBS need not ape Fox. But it will be compared to Fox's and
ESPN's ``NFL Countdown,'' with their boisterous verbal dust-ups and
strong personalities, from Fox's Bradshaw and Long to ESPN's Chris
Berman and Sterling Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing Fox and CBS's programs this past Sunday places a focus
on a common feature: interviews with Green Bay Coach Mike Holmgren.
CBS focused on three areas: how would his defense handle
Minnesota's receiving corps (Cris Carter, Jake Reed and the rookie
Randy Moss) in last night's game; how he would rate Brett Favre's
season; and would he leave for a general manager-coaching job?
</P>
<P>
   Fox's crew asked sharper questions that strayed from the
obvious, including a newsy one: an Internal Revenue Service
investigation into whether certain Packers did not report income
earned from autograph shows. The chat ended with a mirthful
comparison of Brown, a somewhat full-figured fellow (280 pounds,
Bradshaw claimed), and Gilbert Brown, the fuller-figured Green Bay
tackle.
</P>
<P>
   CBS did well by interviewing Mark Carrier, the Detroit Lion
safety suspended for a week after his helmet-to-helmet hit gave
Tampa Bay's Brice Hunter a concussion, then having Seifert coach
Allen and Jones in avoiding such tactics.
</P>
<P>
   One of CBS's rookie game analysts, Steve Tasker, checked in with
a bright and humorous segment on running back Craig (Ironhead)
Heyward's cross-country trek for a new job, done in the style of a
weather report.
</P>
<P>
   And CBS advanced the discussion about the future coach of the
Cleveland Browns by introducing Mike Lombardi, a former executive
with the old Browns, as its ``insider.'' Lombardi named Gary
Kubiak, Denver's offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, CBS's show is but five weeks old. With time _ and
relaxation techniques _ the analysts should learn to communicate
more comfortably. Already, ``The NFL Today'' can be compared
favorably with NBC's unadventurous old show.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it becomes as entertaining as Fox's _ or as
well-informed as ESPN's _ is CBS's choice. We are waiting _ live! _
for its evolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
