<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE JUDICIARY COMMITTEE VOTES TO BEGIN CLINTON IMPEACHMENT
INQUIRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
and NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee voted along party
lines Monday to launch only the third presidential impeachment
inquiry in the nation's history, an examination of President
Clinton's effort to cover up his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   After rejecting Democrats' efforts to limit the scope and
duration of the investigation, the Republican-controlled panel
approved a resolution to begin a Watergate-style inquiry that could
go beyond independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report on the White
House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was adopted 21-16, with all committee Republicans
in favor and all Democrats opposed. The resolution for an inquiry
now goes to the full House, which is expected to vote by the end of
the week to make Clinton the first president to face such an
impeachment threat since Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we will come to our senses as we move forward,'' said
committee member Sheila Jackson Lee, a Texas Democrat who fought
the Republican proposal and warned that it opens a ``fishing
expedition'' aimed at embarrassing the president.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, chief Republican investigator David Schippers, whose
staff analyzed evidence from Starr's seven-month investigation of
the Clinton-Lewinsky affair, told the committee he believed Clinton
had committed 15 potentially impeachable acts, four more than
alleged by Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers split some counts against Clinton and added others,
alleging that the president engaged in a conspiracy and aided the
filing of a false affidavit to keep secret his relationship with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Schippers dropped abuse of power charges
outlined by Starr, allegations stemming from Clinton's refusal to
voluntarily testify and from administration claims of privilege
designed to keep top presidential aides, White House lawyers and
Secret Service agents from having to cooperate with prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Schippers, a former federal prosecutor with a Democratic voting
history in Chicago, said his team of investigators decided the
president's sexual misbehavior was ``peripheral'' to the key issues
outlined in Starr's Sept. 9 report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assertions of presidential misconduct ... are completely
distinct and involve allegations of an ongoing series of deliberate
and direct assaults by Mr. Clinton upon the justice system of the
United States,'' the former anti-racketeering lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deplorable as the numerous sexual encounters ... may be, we
chose to emphasize the consequences of those acts as they affect
the administration of justice and the unique role the president
occupies in carrying out his oath faithfully to execute the laws of
the nation,'' Schippers told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic chief investigator Abbe Lowell criticized Schippers'
analysis, saying he was adding charges by ``subdividing'' the
existing facts and citing a ``laundry list of laws'' Clinton might
have violated.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell characterized Schippers' inquiry as little more than an
extension of the four-year, $40 million investigation by Starr.
Regardless of how Schippers and his assistants ``may hope to
strengthen their recommendation by finding new offenses to tag on,
one basic allegation _ the president was engaged in an improper
relationship which he did not want disclosed _ is the core charge
that ... triggers this grave constitutional crisis,'' Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Nixon impeachment inquiry during the Watergate
scandal, Lowell pointed out that the Judiciary Committee in 1974
voted against citing the president for backdating income tax
returns. ``If President Nixon's alleged lies to the IRS about his
taxes were not grounds for impeachment in 1974, how then are
alleged lies about President Clinton's private sexual relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky grounds in 1998?'' Lowell asked.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat argued that it is impossible to separate the
allegations from the case's underlying context _ that Clinton
engaged in an extramarital affair and nothing approaching the kind
of government malfeasance warranting impeachment. ``The clothes of
Watergate do not fit the body of the conduct in this referral,''
Lowell said.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Clinton reportedly paid little attention to
what was happening 16 blocks away in Room 2141 of the Rayburn House
Office Building. ``He is not spending any time focusing on what's
going on up on the Hill today,'' said presidential spokesman Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart acknowledged that Clinton continued calling
congressional Democrats over the weekend but declined to disclose
the topics. Lockhart said talks with Democrats about impeachment
``is an ongoing, active process.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeting in the same room where Nixon's impeachment was debated,
Judiciary Committee members spent most of the day arguing about
whether an investigation was needed and, if so, how broad it should
be, discussions that revealed the depth of the partisan rift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not here to pass judgment on anyone,'' said committee
chairman Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican. ``We are here to ask
and answer this one single question _ based on what we now know _
do we have a duty to look further or to look away?''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers, a Michigan Democrat and the top-ranking
Democrat on the committee, decried the resolution for an open-ended
inquiry in Clinton's behavior. ``This is not Watergate,'' Conyers
said. ``It's an extramarital affair. Americans know this and want
us to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., the committee's most ardent critic of the
Clinton administration, drew on rhetoric from the Watergate
investigation when he said the nation is ``witnessing nothing less
than the symptoms of a cancer on the American presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this president is allowed to use the presidency to gratify
his personal desires ... in the same way a corrupt county or parish
boss solicits money for votes, future occupants will sadly do the
same,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that Clinton's action were ``wrong and possibly
illegal,'' Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., suggested that ``censure
or rebuke and not impeachment is the right punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is time to move forward, and not have the Congress and the
American people endure a specter of what could be a yearlong focus
on a tawdry but not impeachable affair,'' Schumer said, arguing in
favor of the Democratic proposal to limit the impeachment inquiry
to the Lewinsky matter and to finish by Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., voiced the ambivalence of the
public as reflected in opinion polls. ``I don't know if censure is
appropriate, we should just drop it or we should throw him out of
office,'' Graham said. ``Is this Watergate or `Peyton Place'? I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, was more certain: ``For many
individuals to say that this is nothing more ... than something
about an illicit or extramarital affair is like saying that
Watergate was about nothing more than lock-picking or that the
Boston Tea Party was about nothing more than an aversion to
caffeine.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, Clinton's private attorney David
Kendall asked Attorney General Janet Reno on Monday night to turn
over information Starr used in seeking an expansion of his
Whitewater probe into Clinton's affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said in a letter to Reno that he wanted to explore
whether Starr's representations to Reno that led to the expansion
were ``both complete and truthful.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said Starr's staff may have used Linda Tripp, Lewinsky's
former friend, to suggest a pattern of behavior to Lewinsky that
later was used to convince Reno to expand the case.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall also questions previously unreported contacts by Tripp
with Paula Jones' lawyers, by Tripp through intermediaries to
Starr's staff and by lawyers working with the Jones team who were
also in contact with Starr's prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Starr dismissed Kendall's letter and said the
standard for expanding his inquiry was ``abundantly satisfied.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
