<HEADLINE>
ROBERT LEE GILL, 87, BUSINESSMAN AND COLLECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Fla.)  (mk) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Lee Gill, a longtime member of the New York
Stock Exchange and a prominent collector of American antiques, died
on Sept. 24 at his home in Manhattan. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Gill was born in South Orange, N.J., in 1911 and educated at
Choate. He joined Shields &AMP; Co. in 1932 and in the late 1940s
formed a company with three other members of the Stock Exchange,
but for most of his career he worked independently. During the
1930s and '40s, he was a prominent member of cafe society whose
friends included Barbara Hutton and Howard Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   Gill's interest in Americana began at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art, where he was a weekly visitor to the American collection from
the time it opened, in 1927, until his death. In the late 1930s, he
began collecting first-edition books and Currier &AMP; Ives prints. He
also made regular visits to the Upper East Side gallery of Israel
Sack, a dealer in Americana and American antiques, eventually
becoming part of the then small world of serious collectors of
American antiques that included Henry Ford, Henry Francis duPont
and Ima Hogg.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, Gill bought his first antique, a lowboy once owned by
John Hancock. Over the next few decades he formed an exceptional
collection of primarily 17th-and 18th-century Boston, Federal and
Newport furniture. He was known for his eye and the beautiful
arrangement of the collection in his apartment, which also included
a widely admired kitchen that was lined floor to ceiling with 16th-
and 17th-century Dutch tile. In the late 1980s, Gill also began
collecting Chinese porcelain.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the U.S government purchased two pieces from his
collection _ a small painting of the White House under construction
and a late federal card table _ that are still on display in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Gill endowed a research fellow scholarship at the
Henry Francis duPont Winterthur Museum in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Gill's first wife, Caroline Townsend Chapman Gill, whom he
married in 1939, died in 1984. He is survived by his wife, Melanie;
a son from his first marriage, Peter Gill of Bronxville, and a
stepson, Jack Chapman of Fort Pierce, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
