<SLUG> BC-ABSENTEE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SMALL BUSINESS: Work Absences at Record High   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Unscheduled absenteeism by American workers is at an all-time high
and small businesses are hit the hardest, according to a new
survey.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until 1994, the absenteeism rate at firms with fewer than 100
employees was below the rate for all businesses, but it now is
higher, according to CCH Inc. of Riverwoods, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The yearly absenteeism rate for small business has soared 46
percent since 1994, from 5.4 missed days per employee to eight days
in 1998, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
   During the same period, the average absenteeism rate for
businesses of all sizes climbed only 8 percent, from about 6.6 to
7.1 missed days per year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Absenteeism means unscheduled time off for any reason,
including sudden illness.
</P>
<P>
   More worrisome than the numbers are the reasons for absenteeism:
More workers are missing work because of stress and because they
feel entitled to time off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a significant increase in the cost and occurrence
of unscheduled absences, and work-life conflicts increasingly are
the reason,'' said Paul Gibson, the CCH editor who conducted the
survey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The survey covered 400 U.S. companies, with a total of 800,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  As the rate of absenteeism for small business soars, so does
the cost. CCH figures that unscheduled absences could cost small
businesses $1,044 per employee this year, or 38 percent more than
the $757 average for all businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem I've had this year _ even more than
competition from Office Depot _ is absenteeism and tardiness,''
said Clifford Waldeck, who owns Waldeck's Office Supplies with
eight employees in San Francisco. ``I've had a full crew maybe 30
percent of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad news for small business is that the problems are
expected to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  In 1995, the first year CCH began tracking the reasons for
absenteeism, nearly half of all unplanned time off was attributed
to personal illness. In the latest survey, only 22 percent of those
who canceled work said they were ill.
</P>
<P>
   Family issues such as a sick child or family emergency are the
biggest reason for unscheduled absences, cited 26 percent of the
time. But that has not changed much during the years.
</P>
<P>
   Personal needs was the reason given 20 percent of the time, but
that hasn't changed much either. CCH says the fastest-growing
reasons for missing work are stress and ``entitlement mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Stress was cited 16 percent of the time (and 20 percent of the
time in small businesses) this year, compared with just 6 percent
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Another 16 percent of employees at all companies (and 19 percent
of small-company workers) felt that they were entitled to skip
work.
</P>
<P>
   Companies can take several steps to alleviate stress and
unscheduled absences. These include job sharing, flexible
scheduling, leave for school functions, emergency child care and a
compressed workweek.
</P>
<P>
   But fewer small businesses than large businesses offer these
programs. Although the CCH study suggests that programs like flex
scheduling and compressed workweeks cost very little to establish,
many small businesses say cost isn't the main issue.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  ``For real small businesses with four or five people, it's
pretty much impossible to be flexible,'' said Scott Hauge,
president of Cal Insurance in San Francisco and chairman of the
California Small Business Association.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  ``We have 28 employees and give everyone but the
receptionist every other Friday off, and it's great for employee
morale,'' he noted. ``But for the owner of a company, it's a
nightmare because we're open five days a week.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Gibson of CCH acknowledges that ``small companies often can't
be as generous'' as big businesses. ``But they can build a culture
that understands that people need flexibility,'' he said. For
example, he suggested trying not to schedule meetings at the start
of the day if workers have particular child care or commute
problems.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage for small businesses ``is they are not entrenched
and have the ability to change quickly,'' said Lynn Ware, founder
of Integral Training Systems, a 10-person Half Moon Bay consulting
firm. She suggests that companies large and small should ``think
about employees the same as customers.'' That means finding out
about their preferences and expectations early and trying to
balance their needs with those of the company and other workers.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say one of the best ways to control unscheduled absences
is to provide employees with paid time off, a bank of hours to be
used for various purposes rather than separate accounts for
vacation, sick leave or personal time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
