r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETIRE-SFCHRON &LR;      10-05 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIRE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SMALL BUSINESS: New Plans Ease Retirement Burden   By Arthur M. Louis  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
In a tight labor market like the present one, small businesses will
have to offer more generous retirement benefits if they hope to
compete for workers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to the Department of Labor, only about one-fifth of
the 5 million U.S. businesses that employ no more than 100 workers
provide employee retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, roughly two-thirds of businesses with more than 100
employees offer such plans.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that small-business proprietors have generally
steered away from retirement plans because they cost thousands of
dollars to set up and because they involve more paperwork than the
proprietors can handle.
</P>
<P>
   But as Secretary of Labor Alexis M. Herman has pointed out, a
new type of retirement plan established last year by Congress
eliminates these burdens. ``Providing these plans can be easier
than many businesspeople think,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The SIMPLE Plan
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  In passing the 1997 Taxpayer Relief Act, Congress created a
retirement plan with the acronym SIMPLE _ for Savings Incentive
Match Plan for Employees.
</P>
<P>
   The SIMPLE plan, as its name implies, is the simplest retirement
option available to small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   It is as free of paperwork and other bureaucratic entanglements
as a retirement plan can be and involves minimal or no startup
costs, notes Russ Orban of the Small Business Administration's
office of advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE plans can either be self-directed Individual Retirement
Accounts _ which allow the employees to manage their own
investments _ or 401(k) plans, in which the money is managed by an
institution, such as a mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   The plans are available to any business with 100 or fewer
employees that does not already have a retirement plan.
</P>
<P>
   To set up a SIMPLE plan, the business proprietor only has to
approach a bank, broker, mutual-fund group or other retirement-plan
administrator and fill out a single form, to be filed with the
Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   The plan administrator does all the remaining paperwork, keeping
the IRS informed over the years about all contributions,
withdrawals and other financial details.
</P>
<P>
   Options, Costs
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Charles Schwab &AMP; Co., the San Francisco discount broker,
administers SIMPLE IRAs, but not SIMPLE 401(k)s, for small
businesses, says spokesman Glen Mathison.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE 401(k)s are administered by mutual-fund groups, such as
Fidelity Investments and other plan administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab will start up a SIMPLE IRA free of charge, but it then
charges the employee a $29 annual fee for accounts that contain
less than $10,000. Once the account reaches $10,000, the fee is
waived permanently.
</P>
<P>
   The main source of income for Schwab is the commissions it
charges when participants buy or sell securities in their SIMPLE
IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   All SIMPLE plans require employers to contribute to the
retirement fund. At the employer's discretion, employees can also
contribute to the fund.
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible for the plan, an employee must have earned a
total of at least $5,000 from the employer in the previous two
years.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan excludes employee contributions, the employer must
put an amount equal to 2 percent of each eligible employee's salary
into the fund _ up to a maximum of $3,200 per employee per year.
</P>
<P>
   $6,000 Annual Limit
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  In plans that include employee contributions, the employee can
contribute up to $6,000 per year _ three times the $2,000 limit for
ordinary IRAs. Usually, the employer must match the employee
contributions dollar for dollar, up to a maximum of 3 percent of
the employee's total compensation.
</P>
<P>
   However, the employer can contribute as little as 1 percent of
the employee's compensation in two years out of any five-year span.
That rule is designed to allow the employer flexibility during
periods when the business may not be flourishing.
</P>
<P>
   Both employer and employee contributions _ along with any
investment gains _ become vested immediately. That means the money
can be withdrawn from the plan at any time. But an employee who
withdraws money before reaching age 591/2 will incur a tax penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty is 25 percent of any amount withdrawn during the
first two years that the employee participates in the plan, and 10
percent thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Further details about SIMPLE plans _ or other types of
retirement plans that may be suitable for small businesses _ can be
obtained by calling the Labor Department's Pension and Welfare
Benefits Administration at (800) 998-7542.
</P>
<P>
   Information about retirement plans is also available on that
agency's Web site at  &LR; www.dol.gov/dol/pwba/public/whatsnew &LR; 
 &LR; /main.htm &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 2254EDT &QL; 
