<SLUG> BC-JOBNETWORK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SMALL BUSINESS: Beyond Basic Training   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
San Francisco's Job Network isn't your usual welfare-to-work
program. Indeed, it claims to be the only one in the country that
trains welfare recipients specifically for jobs in small business.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Most training programs place workers and forget them,'' said
Rich Gunn, an accountant with Burr, Pilger &AMP; Mayer and chairman of
the San Francisco Small Business Network. ``But that is a recipe
for disaster for small businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The typical entrepreneur has neither the time nor human
resources staff to provide counseling and other services for
workers coming off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   That is where Job Network comes in. Beyond basic training, it
promises graduates ``retention services'' for a year, including
personal counseling, help with child care and a free Municipal
Railway pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard part for those moving from welfare to work is not
getting the job but keeping it,'' said Job Network program director
Amy Parkhurst. ``It is not enough to place someone in a job that
pays $6 an hour. We need to help them up the ladder, so that they
can support their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Aid to Small Businesses
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Job Network also provides some unusual assistance to small
businesses. To protect employers from higher unemployment insurance
costs if their new hires do not work out, Job Network will pay the
salaries of its graduates directly during a three-month probation
period and get reimbursed by the employer. This arrangement also is
designed to protect small businesses from potential
wrongful-termination lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   The Small Business Network, which represents 21 business groups,
set up the Job Network 15 months ago after consulting 300 of its
20,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   The network formed an alliance with two organizations that have
substantial experience training new employees. Juma Ventures, a San
Francisco nonprofit that hires at-risk youth to work at two Ben &AMP;
Jerry's franchises, was tapped to train welfare-to-work
participants who are under age 30.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish Vocational Services, a nonprofit job-training
organization, works with those over 30.
</P>
<P>
   The first Job Network class of 18 graduated from the six-week
training course three weeks ago, and the second class of 26, mostly
single mothers, began on Thursday. The goal is to turn out about
200 new workers a year.
</P>
<P>
   Building Hard, Soft Skills
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  On the first day of the new class, &UR;  &LR; Parkhurst talked about the
importance of getting to class and work on time _ one of many
``soft skills.'' After lunch, trainees split into teams to learn
``hard skills,'' such as what to do if someone wants to return an
item but no manager is around to approve it and other customers are
piling up at the checkout counter.
</P>
<P>
   The pool of potential trainees is expanding because welfare
reform, passed two years ago, limits people who are able to work to
five years of welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   And businesses can receive up to $8,500 in tax credits for
hiring an employee off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Job Network gets $1 million a year in financing from big San
Francisco businesses, foundations and government grants.
</P>
<P>
   Another joint venture that is preparing public-assistance
recipients for jobs in small businesses as well as large companies
is San Francisco Works. This alliance of the San Francisco Chamber
of Commerce, United Way and a group of large employers _ called the
Committee on Jobs _ aims to move 400 San Franciscans from welfare
to work each year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
