<SLUG> BC-MANAGERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SMALL BUSINESS: Wooing Sought-After Professionals   By Ilana DeBare  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
It's hard enough for small businesses to hire good sales clerks,
receptionists or office managers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   What about the kinds of people who are tough to find even for
giant Fortune 500 companies _ executives and computer
professionals?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tech jobs are the hardest for small businesses to fill,'' said
Rick Pflugradt of ProTemps Professional Personnel, an Oakland firm
that does recruiting for the insurance industry. ``That's
especially true in the (technology) management area, where
companies need people with enough hands-on technical experience to
lead other people.''
</P>
<P>
   People running small businesses or nonprofit agencies may
tremble these days at the thought of having to hire a new director
of operations or computer network manager.
</P>
<P>
   But personnel experts offer some tips to help land these
hard-to-find professionals:
</P>
<P>
   _ Take a close look at your organization's actual needs before
starting the hiring search. Maybe you don't really need a full-time
computer guru: You could get by with a consultant who steps in when
your clerical staff can't solve a technical problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest mistake people make is that somebody quits and
they just grab the old job description, throw it into an ad, and
cross their fingers,'' said Matthew O'Grady, associate director of
the Management Center, a San Francisco group that does human
resource consulting for nonprofits. ``Take a pause. Use the vacancy
to rethink what's needed, so the job will be current with the needs
of your organization.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't rely simply on help-wanted ads. Do a lot of personal
networking to dig up possible candidates. ``Call up a few
individuals in the field you're trying to fill, and say, `I've got
this position, do you know anyone who might be interested,'''
O'Grady said. ``Then call up the people they mention and tell them
the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Try calling local colleges _ their academic departments as well
as their job placement offices. ``I often call the head of the
computer science departments at Golden Gate University or San Jose
State and ask them if they know of recent grads who might be
available,'' said Gae Shulman, president of the Portable Personnel
Department, which provides human resources help to small
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use the Internet. Some help-wanted sites on the Web charge
employers to list positions. But others don't.
</P>
<P>
   Look around to find a career site &LR;   &LR; that focuses on people with
the skills you're seeking. Or use  &LR; www.dejanews.com &LR;  to find
discussion groups that attract people with those skills _ and post
a note there about your opening.
</P>
<P>
   _ Look for people who bigger companies may be overlooking _ such
as older computer experts. ``There are lot of 40-plus computer
people who with a little retraining could be terrific,'' Shulman
said.
</P>
<P>
   You can post your opening with Forty Plus, a job-networking
group for older workers at (510) 430-2400. Or post it with
Experience Unlimited, a state-funded program that provides job
search help for unemployed professionals: Call (510) 563-5310 for
the number of your local office or visit  &LR; www.caljobs.ca.gov &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Another often-overlooked candidate pool includes people who want
part-time work or flexible schedules. Working Options is a San
Francisco recruiting firm that specializes in placing such people,
at salaries sometimes lower than the market rate. It can be reached
at (415) 835-9466.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consider using a recruiting firm or personnel consultant to
help with your search _ especially if you have little experience in
the hiring process.
</P>
<P>
   The Management Center offers a search service that fills
top-level nonprofit jobs that pay $75,000 or less, at (415)
362-9735. Other small businesses can get referrals to recruiters
through the Northern California Human Resources Association at
(415) 291-1992.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most important, play to your strengths as a small business
when trying to woo candidates. You'll never have the hiring budget
or glamour of a Fortune 500 company, but you have other assets in
your organizational culture.
</P>
<P>
   You can offer an open management style with little bureaucracy.
You can offer a sense of adventure and entrepreneurship. You can
offer family oriented benefits such as flexible schedules,
telecommuting or extra time off. You can offer work that's
technically challenging or that allows individuals to make an
immediate difference. You may even be able to offer an actual
equity stake in the company to your key hires.
</P>
<P>
   Shulman plays up such strengths in help-wanted ads for her
clients that say things like ``Tired of working for only the
giants?''
</P>
<P>
   Other personnel managers have had success with similar
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been able to lure people at salaries that are 10 to 15
percent below market, provided I could offer a management style
that gave them a sense of ownership of their jobs.'' said Larry
Bienati, CEO of Consultants to Management, a Concord human
resources consulting firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
