<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SMALL BUSINESS: Wanted: New Hires _ Firms Find Talent
Among  Disabled, Welfare Recipients   By Peter Sinton  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
Clifford Waldeck used to fill openings at his office supply store
in San Francisco by hiring friends of his employees.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Now they all have jobs,'' said the small-business owner, who
has hired three employees off of welfare.
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that Waldeck and other small-business
employers have felt the brunt of hiring pains in a tight labor
market. After all, they traditionally have provided two-thirds of
U.S. workers with their first jobs and initial training,
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. unemployment rate rose a tad in September _ to 4.6
percent from 4.5 percent the previous month. The California jobless
rate is about a point higher but is still near a seven-year low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hiring has always been the bane of small business owners,''
said Rosalie Bulach, owner of Name.Finders, a San Francisco mailing
list broker. ``We are trainers to the whole world. We hire them,
and they stay just long enough to learn a skill before moving on to
larger businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of the importance of finding, training and retaining
new employees, workforce development was one of 10 areas of focus
at the first San Francisco Small Business Forum that convened three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses still tap the new crop of high school, trade
school and college graduates. They hire from friends and foes and
sometimes temp agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, though, they are turning to those who are on
welfare and who are physically and mentally disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Getting those on government assistance into the workforce has
been especially important since the passage of welfare-to-work
legislation two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans are feeling the heat to get off government
assistance. As a result, many government and private training
programs have been established to help them make the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Hill was on welfare last year when she enrolled in
Goodwill's program to learn computer skills. For the past 14
months, she has worked at Cal Insurance, a San Francisco insurance
brokerage, where she started as a receptionist and, last month, was
promoted to administrative assistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's given me an opportunity to learn about insurance and
create a career for myself,'' said Hill. ``The only real negative
is being away from my kids, who are 12 and 4.''
</P>
<P>
   Cal Insurance President Scott Hauge just hired another
welfare-to-work graduate from another program, Job Network, which
specifically trains new workers for small-business jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most training programs teach you the right buzzwords, how to
dress and react during an interview,'' said Bulach, who has hired
several ``people at risk'' at her 20-person firm and participated
in the city's recent forum. She said Job Network and several other
programs go the essential next step and offer their graduates a
range of support services from counseling to child care.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of folks on the margins of the labor market, the
main issue is not whether they can get a job, but whether they can
keep it,'' added Jed Emerson, executive director of the Roberts
Enterprise Development Fund, which is financed by George Roberts of
the leveraged buyout firm Kohlberg Kravis &AMP; Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of support is needed because excitement about the
initial placement wears off after a few weeks,'' Emerson added.
``Child care, transportation and other problems can make everything
unravel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Roberts fund ( &LR; www.redf.org &LR; ) tries to provide that kind of
support to Bay Area nonprofit organizations that help provide
employment to very low-income and formerly homeless individuals.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new report from the Welfare to Work Partnership
in Washington, D.C., 300 companies that participated in its job
creation program rated former welfare recipients ``good, productive
employees'' 79 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The survey identifies nine practices that significantly help
companies retain workers hired off of welfare. In order of
importance, they are transportation, child care, high performance
standards, quality training programs, one-on-one attention (mentor
programs), medical benefits, career path opportunities, and
partnerships with community/nonprofit and government agencies.
</P>
<P>
   To help ensure that their graduates make it in the work world,
an increasing number of job training programs operate their own
business incubators, where recruits can learn about business in a
controlled and monitored way.
</P>
<P>
   Training programs with in-house businesses have been designed to
train disabled as well as disadvantaged Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as many as two-thirds of the 15 million Americans
classified as disabled do not work, although many would like to.
New training programs, therapies and technology are steering many
of them into the workforce, and fewer than one in three need
special equipment.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Community Vocational Enterprises of San Francisco
helps about 300 individuals with psychiatric disabilities re-enter
the workforce each year. After training, it places many of them at
its own businesses, which include cafes, janitorial and messenger
delivery services, for up to a year. Then it helps match them with
other employers.
</P>
<P>
   In the training process, CVE and other organizations are as
strict as mainstream businesses in insisting that workers show up
on time and are otherwise dependable. ``Up to 70 percent of our
people keep jobs six to nine months,'' said CVE employment
specialist Daryl Henline.
</P>
<P>
   One happy CVE graduate, who asked to be identified only as J.S.,
is taking drugs to treat schizophrenia and obsessive compulsive
disorders and, for the past three months, has worked as a cashier
at a Rite Aid pharmacy in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working at CVE cafes for a year, I learned not to be afraid of
customers or panic because of a long line,'' said J.S. ``It was a
good laboratory, and now I serve about 200 customers a day and have
never been late or missed a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who run nonprofit organizations also are turning to the
new labor markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to find telemarketing workers,'' said Sam
Schuchat, executive director of the California League of
Conservation Voters, a nonprofit group that needs such workers to
make phone calls to solicit money and support for its political
candidates and causes.
</P>
<P>
   He just hired Alejo Hernandez, who is visually impaired and
requires special computer and optical character recognition
software to do the job.
</P>
<P>
   But getting the equipment hasn't been a problem. Several
agencies, including San Francisco Vocational Services, Lighthouse
for the Blind and AccessAbility are providing equipment and
training for Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   After one week on the job, Hernandez said, ``It's a challenge,
but I like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
