<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SMALL BUSINESS: Banks Battle for Customers   By Sam Zuckerman  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Wells Fargo customer Celia Ruiz has gone through the disruption of
one bank merger. Now it's happening again, and Ruiz, partner of a
six-attorney law firm in San Francisco, is dreading it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After Wells bought downstate rival First Interstate two years
ago, she no longer had a banker assigned to her firm's account.
When she had questions about the firm's credit line, she had to
telephone a call center where people unfamiliar with her business
fielded inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally experienced a deterioration in service,'' Ruiz
said. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Now, said Ruiz, Wells Fargo's imminent merger with Minneapolis
banking giant Norwest Corp. ``makes me even more nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank mergers can be tough on customers, especially small
businesses. As branches are closed, employees fired or moved and
computers reprogrammed, service often suffers. After a merger,
banks may adopt new polices, products and prices, which may not be
as attractive as the old offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers Not All Bad
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  That does not mean huge bank mergers are always bad for
small-business customers. In the aftermath, small businesses are
still left with the basic choice of service or price.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller banks tend to provide higher levels of service than
bigger banks, including direct communication with decisionmakers.
But bigger bankers usually offer better loan terms and a wider
variety of deposit accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping small-business customers is crucial for smaller banks,
which lack scale to compete in the corporate and mass consumer
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, mergers do not change the fact that all banks target
small businesses that are well established, profitable and large
enough to qualify for credit. Businesses not deemed creditworthy
may have to rely on alternative forms of financing or draw on the
owner's personal ability to get credit.
</P>
<P>
   Surge of Sales Calls
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  One thing small businesses can expect in the next few months
is a surge of sales calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity for local banks to step forward,''
said accountant Rich Gunn, chairman of the San Francisco Small
Business Network, an umbrella organization representing 21 business
groups.
</P>
<P>
   San Rafael's Westamerica, which makes a point of knowing where
its small business prospects bank &UR; ,  &LR; is targeting customers of Bank
of America, which just completed its merger with North Carolina's
NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   The Mechanics &UR;  &LR; Bank, based in Richmond, is running radio spots
that ask whether listeners know the name of their bankers.
``There's a lot of turmoil. That's when we get our best
customers,'' said Nino Petroni, a regional vice president with the
Mechanics Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial Bank of San Francisco caused a stir months ago when
it draped a banner reading ``We're Not Moving to North Carolina''
in front of its Pine Street office.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the bank mailed a newsletter to some 15,000 Bay
Area businesses appealing to them to ``keep your money in the
city'' as other banks ``merge with out-of-town institutions or move
their headquarters.''
</P>
<P>
   Commercial Bank is offering restaurant gift certificates to
customers who open business checking or money market accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping people have had enough of the larger banks,''
said Lynda Graham-Helwig, Commercial Bank's marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America and Wells Fargo say they will fight to keep
small-business customers but would not provide details.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Wells admits that its service to its small-business customers
suffered after it bought First Interstate. ``We really learned our
lesson,'' said Wells business banking chief Michael James. ``The
most important thing we intend to do is take care of the daily
needs of our small business customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America is assigning ``relationship managers'' to work
one-on-one with its most-profitable small-business customers, says
Barbara Desoer, the bank's Northern California retail banking
chief. The managers' pay depends partly on their success in keeping
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers ``create the perception of vulnerability,'' Desoer says.
``We know the competition will try to fuel that perception.''  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
