<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SMALL BUSINESS: Web Sites Cater to Women With Startups   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Female entrepreneurs now have a new network of sorts to get their
businesses off the ground. Small-business Web sites for women are
big on the Internet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are prominent home pages that offer advice and contacts on
how to jump-start a startup and keep that venture profitable. No
surprise there, industry experts point out, since nearly half of
the Net's users are women today, compared with just 10 percent a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Women own more than 8 million businesses in the United States
that employ 18.5 million people and generate $2.3 trillion in
sales, according to the National Foundation for Women Business
Owners in Silver Spring, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The Web is particularly well suited for entrepreneurs because it
provides low-cost communication, information and networking.
</P>
<P>
   `A Great Connector'
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Because a lot of women start businesses from home, the
Internet is a great connector and equalizer,'' said Ellen Pack,
founder of San Mateo's Women.com Networks ( &LR; www.women.com &LR; ), a Web
portal that is home to six small-business sites.
</P>
<P>
   Women.com Network's properties include MoneyMode and Women's
Wire, which ``give women the tools and resources to start a
company, raise money and acquire office equipment,'' said Laurie
Kretchmar, editor-in-chief of Women's Wire.
</P>
<P>
   Another useful site is WomenConnect.com
( &LR; www.womenconnect.com &LR; ), a McLean, Va., service for female
business owners and professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Started on Prodigy in 1994, it offers tips on handling debt and
equity capital issues (most women finance startups on credit
cards), and a free directory of female business owners for
networking purposes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, WomenConnect.com creates Web sites for nonprofit,
membership-based professional women's business organizations,
according to Gary LaFever, senior vice president of business
development.
</P>
<P>
   Another company, iVillage.com: The Women's Network
( &LR; www.ivillage.com &LR; ), takes the approach of creating Web
communities. It pulls women together through a variety of e-mail,
chat rooms, message boards and content sections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our users want expert advice on what businesses to
start and how to finance a business,'' said iVillage producer
Shelley Pyne-Hanley. ``We point them in the right direction and
offer a nurturing online environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-profile New York company has received backing from
America Online, the Tribune Co. and Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP;
Byers, the influential Menlo Park venture-capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   Sites to Explore
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Other notable Web sites for female business owners:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Women's Work &LR;  ( &LR; wwork.com &LR;   &LR; / &LR; ) boasts plenty of resources for
job seekers, including employment opportunities, a software program
that allows people to electronically post resumes, and a listing of
women's business organizations from California to Maine.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Business Women's Network &LR; 
( &LR; www.tpag.com/BWN/publications.html &LR; ) hawks publications for the
serious female entrepreneur, ranging from the Business Women's
Network Directory 1998-1999 ($110) to the Business Women's Update
Newsletter ($18 a year), a bimonthly calendar of events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
