<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SMALL BUSINESS: Renting Software on the Web   By Benny Evangelista  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
For Bob Curry, renting software is cheaper than buying.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Curry figures he has shaved as much as 75 percent off the cost
of setting up team projects for his small Internet design and
advertising firm by renting software via the Web.
</P>
<P>
   And in the six months since Curry's firm, EmpowerNet Corp. of
Chicago, has used rental applications, business has doubled. Curry
said EmpowerNet gained customer referrals based on its success
using rental applications to quickly set up creative teams of
far-flung graphic artists and advertising representatives for a
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can just go out there and rent it and get it running in
a day, it makes more sense'' than hiring technical personnel to
design and set up a system, Curry said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; EmpowerNet's experience illustrates what some analysts say is
an emerging trend toward the use of rentable applications by small
and medium-size businesses.
</P>
<P>
   These so-called ``rental apps'' are rented or leased for a set
period of time or specific purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Standard business software like Microsoft Office, which is
needed all the time, isn't a good candidate for renting. Programs
tailored for specific tasks like a special event planner or Year
2000 problem-checker are better suited for rent rather than for
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  And rental app proponents believe smaller companies will want
the same features from the latest accounting, payroll or sales
programs used by major corporations, but not the high cost of
buying the software.
</P>
<P>
   Need to Hire Techs Reduced
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  By renting, firms can avoid the cost of hiring in-house
computer technicians to maintain the programs or of buying new
hardware to run the software.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the actual software and data are stored by a
third-party company, such as a software-maker or Internet service
provider that administers and updates the software for a fee. The
firm renting the software accesses it through the Internet. When
the rental period expires, so does an access code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  It is similar, they say, to a driver renting a car for a trip
without worrying about paying for an oil change or tuneup down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the rental applications market is part of a rapidly
growing business trend to outsource work or jobs.
</P>
<P>
   A recent report by Forrester Research Inc. of Cambridge, Mass.,
predicts the market for rental apps will balloon from practically
nothing this year to $6.4 billion annually by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   That's enough to make large producers of corporate software like
Oracle Corp. and PeopleSoft sit up and take notice.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft, in fact, today will announce a new strategy to
market Web-based rentable applications and other outsourcing
services to medium and small companies.
</P>
<P>
   That will be a new target for the Pleasanton company, which has
grown dramatically on the strength of its human resources and other
business software for large corporations that can afford higher
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Renting apps will let PeopleSoft ``appeal economically to a
group of buyers who would not have been interested in our
products,'' said John Haworth, PeopleSoft's director of
outsourcing.
</P>
<P>
   General Ledger Program Online
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Two weeks ago, Oracle Corp. of Redwood Shores launched a
similar pilot venture called Oracle Business OnLine, attempting to
lure smaller companies with programs like Oracle's general ledger
accounting software.
</P>
<P>
   A big company with 30 to 50 users would pay about $200,000 just
for a onetime license for that program. Annual maintenance costs
for such software typically amount to a third of the license cost,
and that is on top of hardware and tech personnel costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're targeting small to medium-sized companies who we found
have as complex requirements as large companies, but less
capability of running these applications,'' said Don Haig, vice
president of Oracle Business OnLine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Netcom On-Line Communication Services of San Jose is planning
to forge partnerships with software vendors, so the Internet
service provider can host software rental services. Mike Kallet,
Netcom's senior vice president for operations engineering, said a
human resources resume-tracking program costing $150,000 would be
too much for many small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   But for a rental fee of $2,500 a month, ``and you can rent it
tomorrow, it becomes somewhat of a no-brainer decision,'' said
Kallet.
</P>
<P>
   For competitive reasons, Curry wouldn't detail exactly how much
EmpowerNet has saved by renting Lotus Corp.'s Instant Teamroom.
With the program, EmpowerNet can link teams formed from its 45
staff members with some of the 400 independent contractors who are
based in far-flung time zones, including San Francisco, the
Philippines and Germany and collaborate online on one project.
</P>
<P>
   And when the project ends, Curry just ends the rental.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have time to buy hardware and try to connect
different servers,'' Curry said. ``We've made a decision that from
now on, this is the only way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   A major drawback so far, though, is that there are only a few
rentable apps currently available.
</P>
<P>
   Rental Apps Web Site
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Interliant Inc., a Houston Internet services firm from whom
Curry rents Instant Teamroom, just launched a new rental apps Web
site with a catalog of five programs for rent. Those include a
program to assess a company's Year 2000 problem liabilities, one to
track and manage resumes, and one to link various parties involved
in a real estate deal.
</P>
<P>
   Interliant hopes to have as many as 50 programs from different
vendors available by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aiming at small to medium-sized businesses that desire
to escape from the hassles of setting up their own infrastructure
and then find and keep high-priced information technology staff,''
said Interreliant marketing director Mark Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   But Ron Rappaport, an analyst with Zona Research of Redwood
City, said the idea of rental software is still little more than a
``marketing pitch'' from companies like Oracle and Lotus that have
catered to major corporations and are now trying to ``move down the
food chain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not seen scores and scores of businesses running out
to this market yet,'' Rappaport said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the success of rental apps will depend on what programs
are made available, whether they are useful to small and
medium-size firms, and whether those firms will rent over and over
again.
</P>
<P>
   Rappaport still questions whether small businesses will entrust
their sensitive internal data to someone else's server.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have compared this to (the question of) do you buy
or lease a car,'' Rappaport said. ``All you leave in a rental car
is some lint and the radio set to your favorite station.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a business that is very concerned about security and is
very comfortable with the notion of a firewall surrounding
everything, I don't think this is going to be the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this a good idea? That isn't going to be answered next
year, it's going to be answered in the year after that,'' Rappaport
said. ``We're a year or two out before we actually see some meat on
the skeleton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
