<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Alza Buying Sequus for $580 Million   By Rebecca Smith  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Alza Corp. said yesterday it will buy its neighbor Sequus
Pharmaceuticals in a $580 million stock-swap deal intended to speed
the development and deployment of powerful new cancer-fighting
drugs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Menlo Park, Calif.-based Alza, which is roughly 10 times as big
as Sequus, is paying a healthy 60 percent premium for the smaller
Palo Alto company.
</P>
<P>
   What does Sequus have that Alza wants enough to orchestrate its
first acquisition?
</P>
<P>
   It's not earnings. The company hasn't turned a quarterly profit
in its 17-year history.
</P>
<P>
   What Sequus possesses is two valuable cancer products coveted by
Alza.
</P>
<P>
   The first is Doxil, a cancer-attacking drug that garnered FDA
approval to be marketed for the treatment of AIDS-related Kaposi's
sarcoma in November 1995. It now shows promise for treating breast
and ovarian cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The second is Sequus' Stealth drug-delivery system that enhances
the effectiveness of cancer-fighting drugs and reduces negative
side effects.
</P>
<P>
   It does so by encapsulating tumor-fighting agents in fat
globules that enter the body through intravenous drips. They remain
in the body's internal ``freeway'' system until they reach
``off-ramps'' _ the naturally leaky sites of fast-growing cancer
cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Stealth system drops its payload into cancer cells,'' said
I. Craig Henderson, chief executive of Sequus and a nationally
known breast cancer physician and oncology researcher at the
University of California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Stealth system enables chemotherapy drugs to bypass
healthy tissue, patients are spared debilitating side effects such
as hair loss, nausea and heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said he believes the therapy has promise in the
treatment of infections, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Mario, chief executive of Alza, said he began talking
with Henderson two years ago about cooperating in the war against
cancer. The discussions graduated into merger talks earlier this
year when Sequus directors concluded they needed the support of a
larger, better-capitalized partner.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Sequus had cumulative losses of $180 million.
Alza, by contrast, has been generally profitable with products
focused on oncology and urology. Its sales have gone from $6
million in 1993 to roughly $50 million last year. They're expected
to more than double this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sequus has been getting close to turning the corner, and a big
company like Alza could help that,'' said Alex Zisson,
biotechnology analyst for Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in New York. ``It looks
like a good strategic fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Zisson expects the companies to trim sales costs by combining
sales forces. That would triple the number of salespeople marketing
Sequus products.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Doxil alone are expected to top $45 million this year.
Analysts believe the drug could generate sales of at least $100
million within a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's potentially a very important anti-cancer drug,'' said
Louis Webb, pharmaceutical analyst for Fahnestock &AMP; Co. in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   As a midsize pharmaceutical company with a market capitalization
of $3.7 billion, Alza has the resources Sequus needs, Henderson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years from now, Alza should be an oncology leader,'' said
Alza's Mario, a physical chemistry Ph.D. ``We are dedicated to
reaching that goal with Sequus and willing to invest heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Alza will swap 0.4 shares of its stock for each share of
Sequus stock. Based on Friday's closing price of $42.43 for Alza,
the company is paying $16.98 for each share of Sequus stock.
</P>
<P>
   Alza shares fell $2.50 yesterday to $39.94 amid concern that it
might be paying too much for a company with unproven products.
Sequus rose $3.19 to $14.06.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
