u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-THORNTON-JAZZ-ART-     10-05 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-THORNTON-JAZZ-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A JAZZ TRIUMPH AFTER DECADES OF BAD BREAKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Mich.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOYCE WADLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teri Thornton began hemorrhaging at the Bern Jazz Festival,
becoming so weak that her manager had to spoon-feed her, and when
she got back to the United States from Switzerland, the doctors
decided that the bladder cancer they had been treating with
chemotherapy and radiation required surgery. This was in June.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thornton's manager, Suzi Reynolds, had seen the 64-year-old
jazz singer through some tough times. When they first hooked up
three years ago, Ms. Thornton slept on her manager's couch. Her
career, in Ms. Reynolds' word, was ``zero.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Ms. Thornton's cancer surgery at Englewood Hospital in
New Jersey, Ms. Reynolds saw her ``really down'' for the first
time. Desperate to give her client a reason to fight, Ms. Reynolds
told Ms. Thornton she was entering her in the Thelonious Monk
Institute of Jazz vocal competition _ three months away.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was really angry with me,'' Ms. Reynolds recalled this
week. ``She said she'd never be ready. I went out in the hallway
and broke into tears. And while I was out there, sobbing, I heard''
_ here Ms. Reynolds sang scales _ `` `Aahhh-aaahhh-aahhh-aahhh.'
She was vocalizing with tubes in her throat!''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ms. Thornton, who has not released a recording since
1963, won the Monk competition in Washington with an emotional
performance that left her accompanist, Norman Simmons, weeping.
</P>
<P>
   Now the recording offers are flooding in, and in a small sun
room at the Actors' Fund Home in Englewood, where she has been
living while receiving medical treatment, Ms. Thornton talked about
her life.
</P>
<P>
   If you need a reminder of how fleeting fame and health can be,
the Actors' Home is a good place. A half dozen elderly actors and
musicians, many in poor health, one in a wheelchair, stop by to
congratulate Ms. Thornton and, occasionally, to remind a reporter
who they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thornton, who gives no indication of the exhaustion she
suffers from her illnesses (she is now cancer-free), brings her own
reminders: a scrapbook of newspaper clippings, from her rising-star
days in the '60s, when she had a hit called ``Somewhere in the
Night'' and was reported to be ``winging'' to tour Australia with
Frank Sinatra. There was also the odd story from the '80s, in which
Ms. Thornton said she had taken time out to raise three children.
</P>
<P>
   But who ever gets the full story?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thornton did not tour Australia with Sinatra _ a corrupt
manager delayed getting her a ticket for so long that by the time
she got there, Sinatra had departed.
</P>
<P>
   She took time off from her career not to raise her children, but
because for a long time, she did not have a career. She had three
husbands and three children, one of whom was born out of wedlock.
She was involved in a custody battle in which she kidnapped her
youngest son.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people who knew Teri Thornton in music knew the other parts
of my life,'' Ms. Thornton says, but only after almost three hours
have passed. ``That I drove a cab, that I saw the inside of a
jail...''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who think that given the choice of a jazz singer
or an alley cat for a mother, you're better off with the cat _ they
stick around longer. Teri Thornton's mother seemed to share that
view. ``Warriors'' is what Ms. Thornton calls her mother and
grandmother, when she first starts talking, setting up a picture of
a loving, tightly knit family in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thornton's father was a Pullman porter. Her mother, Burnieze
Crews, was an actress, published author, poet, playwright,
schoolteacher, civic leader and star of her own radio show, in
which she sang pop standards. Ms. Thornton's grandmother was an
evangelist. When Ms. Thornton was young, she, her mother and
grandmother had a gospel group.
</P>
<P>
   But eventually, the darker side of the story emerges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started drinking from an early age,'' Ms. Thornton says.
``Frustration with family problems. It eased the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   She talks of being a divorced mother of two at 19, living in her
mother's home. The resentment of her children and her mother when
she left her children in her mother's care because she had got
work. Her mother's contempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always the slut,'' Ms. Thornton says. ``Even after being
on national TV, it was, `What's your next move, moron?'''
</P>
<P>
   She talks about relying more and more on drink until one night,
in the '80s, when the smell of alcohol was so strong on her pillow,
Ms. Thornton felt she was being asphyxiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I opened my mouth and no sound came out,'' Ms. Thornton says.
``I knew if I didn't stop I would die. I would die if I couldn't
sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thornton gave up a lot for jazz, she is told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I think about it, I did,'' Ms. Thornton says. ``What
was I going to do? Be miserable to my children because I wasn't
doing what I had to do?''
</P>
<P>
   There is a piano in the room. Ms. Thornton sits down and plays
the music the way she remembers it. Suddenly, ``Billy Boy,'' a
tired old folk song, has bounce and spirit. ``Billy Boy'' is hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``See? Whatever beat you want to put, wherever you want to put
it,'' she says. ``No limit on how far you can take a melody, no
governor on how much you can put between two beats as long as you
leave a little space.''
</P>
<P>
   A thought that seems to apply to the singer as well as the song.
</P>
<P>
   ``Space is just as important as the notes it fills.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
