<SLUG> BC-VERITAS-SEAGATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERITAS SOFTWARE TO ACQUIRE SEAGATE UNIT IN STOCK SWAP
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Veritas Software Corp. said Monday that it
had agreed to acquire a unit of Seagate Software Inc., a
majority-owned subsidiary of Seagate Technology Inc., in a stock
swap valued at $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Veritas, based in Mountain View, Calif., will acquire Seagate
Software's Network and Storage Management Group. Veritas produces
software that manages data storage on large corporate networks,
performing tasks such as backup and recovery of lost information.
Seagate, based in Scotts Valley, Calif., will own about 35 percent
of Veritas after the deal. Seagate, the world's largest maker of
disk drives, will retain a software unit specializing in business
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The companies announced the deal after markets had closed.
Shares of Seagate closed down $1.4375, to $23; Veritas closed down
$$2.875, to $45.375. Seagate shares have languished all year as the
company struggles to generate profits amid deep price cuts for disk
drives. Veritas shares are also trading well below their 52-week
high despite strong earnings growth.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen J. Luczo, Seagate's president and chief executive, said
the merger of his company's software business with Veritas was an
alternative to taking the unit public. ``Even in a going-public
scenario, Seagate's share would have dropped to about 60 percent,''
he said. ``This gives us a smaller stake in a much stronger entity
because the merged company will have a much stronger position than
either company had on its own,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luczo, a former investment banker with Bear, Stearns, succeeded
Alan Shugart, Seagate's founder, in July. Luczo said that the idea
of building a software business independent of the disk-drive
franchise was ``Al's vision, my strategy.'' The software unit was
intended to benefit from the growth of so-called client-server
technology, which spreads software applications and data across
multiple computers on a network.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting company will have 2,300 employees in 16 countries
and projected 1998 revenue of more than $350 million. Mark Leslie,
the president and chief executive of Veritas, will be chairman and
chief executive; Terry Cunningham, the president and chief
operating officer of Seagate Software, will be president and chief
operating officer. Luczo and Greg Kerfoot, chief strategic officer
of Seagate Software, will join the board of Veritas.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ``will form a company with an unprecedented range of
products and immediate market leadership,'' Leslie said in a
statement. ``The merger creates a company with the industry
stature, focus and technology base to lead the storage industry.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Seagate Software's strength in work-group and desktop
computing, and its distribution agreements with the Microsoft
Corp., would complement Veritas' focus on larger information
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Murphy, editor of the California Technology Stock
Letter, said that the price was attractive but that the deal was
risky because it left Seagate more vulnerable than ever to the
cutthroat pricing of the disk-drive industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve clearly has decided he doesn't need the software
business to get better margins,'' he said. ``If the disk-drive
business is going to stage a brilliant recovery, he will look
brilliant; otherwise you have to wonder what the future of this
company is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
