<HEADER>
A1122 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-05 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLOWOKANDI'S CAREER GEAR STUCK IN IDLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Who says there's no news emanating from the idle
NBA? Here it is, the day training camps were supposed to open and
the No.1 overall pick in the June draft hasn't acquired that most
standard of status symbols, the boombox on wheels.
</P>
<P>
   Presses have been stopped for smaller wonders. Of course,
Michael Olowokandi has a practical reason for not purchasing an
automobile, luxury or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi can't drive.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind his implausible journey in just three years' time
from a Nigerian diplomat's son to the NBA's hottest property. To
anybody in the car-conceived sprawl that is L.A., the more amazing
thing is that as soon as the lockout ends the Clippers are going to
hand over the keys to their franchise to a player who has never had
a driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   With a work stoppage applying the brakes to a basketball career
that has accelerated more quickly than a Lamborghini, Olowokandi is
looking into taking driving lessons. Judging by the stalled labor
negotiations, he's liable to have his learner's permit before the
league has a new collective-bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   That's one silver lining for Olowokandi, 23, and one dark cloud
for the NBA, which sorely could use the good vibrations the
7-foot-1 center oozes without so much as breaking a sweat. He's
everything your average boorish, selfish insolent
superstar-in-training is not.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine someone with Sammy Sosa's passion, James Bonds' diction,
Kenneth Starr's tenacity, Ronaldo's nimble feet, Emily Post's
manners and Harvey Keitel's edge. It's obvious why Madison Avenue
already is mad about Olowokandi.
</P>
<P>
   Nike is slashing its spending on endorsements by $100 million,
but that didn't stop the shoe giant from inking a deal with
Olowokandi. The only thing keeping the Kandi Man from being the
nation's newest sweetheart is Olowokandi himself.
</P>
<P>
   He has turned down numerous television appearances because the
exposure strikes him as out of place, like putting the points on
the scoreboard before the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Some No. 1 draft picks feel entitled to whatever perks come with
the prize. Olowokandi, bless his soles, actually wants to earn his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to keep that all low key,'' Olowokandi said,
``because I still have to go out and be an NBA player. I haven't
established that I can do that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not in any actual arenas. It might be January of 1999 at
the earliest before he gets that chance. The welcome news for the
Clippers is that in simulated settings he has more than held his
own, winning many admirers with his shot-blocking, his ambidextrous
jump hook, his agility and his coachability.
</P>
<P>
   In August he shelled out $2,500 to return to Pete Newell's Big
Man Camp in Hawaii. He banged elbows with the likes of veteran
center Andrew Lang, who told Sports Illustrated afterward: ``He's
got some of the quickest feet I've seen. And he learns in a hurry.
And with that body... he's going to be an All-Star for a long, long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for an ex-soccer player whose basketball resume is
thinner than Manute Bol. The sum total of Olowokandi's experience
is the three years he spent at the University of the Pacific upon
alighting from Brunel University in England.
</P>
<P>
   Having traversed an ocean to climb this mountain, Olowokandi
wisely sought out a Sherpa with impeccable credentials to guide
him. Lakers Hall of Famer Kareem Abdul-Jabbar has been working
one-on-one with Olowokandi three times a week at an L.A. health
club.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he speaks, you listen,'' Olowokandi said. ``He doesn't
just explain things, he actually shows you. He's so passionate.''
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi is no stranger to hard work, but he had never seen
the likes of the conditioning program Abdul-Jabbar has introduced
to him. Most days he barely has enough energy left to dial for the
taxi or open the passenger-side car door of his personal assistant,
Deidre Arrington, who sometimes doubles as his driver.
</P>
<P>
   He could hire a car if he cared to. Companies have called him up
offering their services. But Olowokandi doesn't see himself as big
enough for a stretch limousine, even if the leg room is a little
tight in Arrington's Nissan Altima.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever teaches him to drive,'' Arrington said, ``needs a
utility vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever car Olowokandi eventually ends up buying, you can bet
it'll have ample room for passengers. He already has struck up a
friendship with the kids in his Manhattan Beach neighborhood. It's
easy to imagine a lot of ice cream runs in his future.
</P>
<P>
   There probably also will be a flight or two to Northern
California so Olowokandi can cheer on the 5-year-old soccer-playing
son of his agent Bill Duffy. Olowokandi already has requested a
schedule of Treaven Duffy's matches. So far, Treaven's sports
docket looks a lot busier than Michael's.
</P>
<P>
   Olowokandi said he was ``dispirited'' when the lockout was
imposed on July 1. When it will end is anybody's guess, though the
Clippers hiring a head coach might be like a groundhog sighting,
signaling that the end of a long, cold spell is near.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been kind of nice to have training camp begin as
scheduled,'' Olowokandi said. ``But it's out of my control. I'm
going to hang in tight and be patient. The way I'm looking at it is
this is an ample opportunity for me to further harness my
development.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason to believe that whenever the season gets
under way, the opposition will have a hard time restraining him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
