<SLUG> BC-JOSEPHTHAL-DISCRIMINATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWSUIT ACCUSES BROKERAGE FIRM OF DISCRIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Williams, a broker at Josephthal &AMP; Co.'s Washington office
who is black, said when he arrived at work in 1996 he often found
3-by-5 index cards with crude racist cartoons on his desk. Harolyn
Duerr, the receptionist and only woman among 25 people in the
office, said that in late 1995 her computer screen saver was
changed to a picture of two women having sex.
</P>
<P>
   The Equal Opportunity Employment Commission said Monday that it
filed suit Oct. 1 in federal court in Washington against
Josephthal, a small regional brokerage firm, seeking punitive
damages for what the commission called ``malicious'' conduct at
Josephthal's Washington office, which was open from late 1994 until
January.
</P>
<P>
   Tulia L. Diaz, the commission's Washington field office
director, described the case as ``phenomenal'' because ``each
individual employee was subjected to harassment custom-designed to
taunt and humiliate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Josephthal, in a statement, said it has written policies
prohibiting discrimination, but that none of the four workers named
in the lawsuit complained to senior management until after it
closed its Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Slowinski, who was manager of the Josephthal office and
now works for Spencer Trask Securities in Rockville, Md., said it
would be inappropriate for him to comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Former employees, in affidavits given to the commission, said
that Asians, blacks, Hispanics, Jews and women who worked there
were routinely addressed with slurs instead of their names.
</P>
<P>
   ``One man would walk around with his hand down his pants with
his finger sticking out of his zipper,'' Ms. Duerr said. ``This was
my first office job and I thought you had to put up with this,''
she said, explaining why she saw no point in seeking other
employment. Ms. Duerr said she quit after a colleague told her that
such conduct was not tolerated at most offices.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Rice-Brown, the commission lawyer who filed the lawsuit,
said Josephthal management included ``an equal opportunity
harasser'' who routinely and openly denigrated each worker who was
not a white male.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 400 cartoons depicting rape and bestiality,
suggesting Jews be put in microwave ovens and comparing the male
genitals of some Asian brokers to rice kernels were distributed,
said Aaron Blight, a commission investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Duerr, Stevens and others gave the commission affidavits in
which they said that most of the cartoons were drawn by Fred
Stucker, the assistant manager. Stucker, now a broker with Merrill
Lynch in Washington, did not return four calls Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that he had to restrain a colleague who wanted to
hit Stucker one day after hearing him speak disparagingly with
Slowinski about ``the darker races.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that at the seven other securities firms where he
has worked since 1992, ``I never encountered this.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It was horrible. And everyone was subjected to it
who was not a white male.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission, in its lawsuit, says that Josephthal allowed
such a hostile environment that while Ms. Duerr and Williams
resigned they were ``constructively discharged'' and should receive
damages for wrongful termination.
</P>
<P>
   It also seeks damages for harassment of two other brokers,
Donald S. Han and John Blalock.
</P>
<P>
   Josephthal, founded in 1910, has about 1,000 brokers in offices
in eight states and Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
