<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LEADER FOR A NEW GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Oct. 6:
</P>
<P>
   Although only a week has gone by since Germany's voters ended
Helmut Kohl's 16-year tenure as Germany's leader, some things are
already apparent. The voting reflected Germany's metamorphosis into
a more self-confident, tolerant and liberal state. The government
of the next Chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, will have a new tone,
one fitting a country that seems increasingly comfortable with the
new political and cultural diversity brought by unification and
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, 54, and the leaders of the Green Party, his likely
coalition partner, bring the first truly postwar generation into
the German leadership. He came of age when Germany was already an
economic wonder, no longer dependent on American care packages. His
generation is also more distant from the shame of the Nazi past,
freer to focus on the future.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democratic victory also reflects a geographic shift,
away from Kohl's base in the conservative Rhineland surrounding
Bonn to the new Eastern states. Fittingly, the new government will
leave Bonn next year and re-establish the capital in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The election showed that the great majority of Germans accept
that theirs is not a homogeneous nation. Anti-foreigner, right-wing
parties did extremely poorly, and the Schroeder government promises
to display more good will toward foreign residents than did Kohl,
who was slow to condemn racist violence. This may be one of the few
clear policy shifts under Schroeder, who has promised to ease
access to citizenship for foreigners. Citizenship is now granted to
those with German blood and is very difficult for nonethnic
Germans, even those born in Germany, to obtain.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's campaign left many skeptical that he could reduce
Germany's 10 percent unemployment rate. He had promised to restore
the few cuts Kohl made in workers' generous benefits, and his
finance minister is likely to be his party's leader, Oskar
Lafontaine, who is close to Germany's unions. But there are signs
that Schroeder may induce the unions to moderate their demands. He
has also announced a huge job-training program.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's foreign policy team is expected to include leaders
of the Greens, a party that once called for the abolition of
Germany's army. But the Greens, known for their pacifist and
environmental stands, have moderated. Joschka Fischer, the Green
leader mentioned for foreign minister, is a respected pragmatist
who recently blocked the party from calling for Germany to leave
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   While both Schroeder and Fischer are pro-American, they are
likely to be less deferential to Washington and closer to Britain
and France than was the older Kohl. Schroeder visited France three
days after his election. Unlike his predecessor, Schroeder is not
suspected of dreaming about the euro at night. But he has
emphasized that he will continue Kohl's policies of European
integration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
