<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
 
McNOWN NEEDS BETTER SHOWING 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the Bruins to defeat 10th-ranked Arizona on
Saturday, a slew of players must improve upon recent performances,
including quarterback Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital)Especially(end ital) quarterback Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been very average,'' Bruins coach Bob Toledo said. ``He's
directed the offense well, and he's made big plays. But he's out of
sync.''
</P>
<P>
   After a super start to his Heisman Trophy campaign against
Texas, McNown has been McMediocre.
</P>
<P>
   He completed 52.5 percent of his passes in the Houston and
Washington State games, with three touchdowns and three
interceptions. Saturday, he underthrew several receivers as his
ball uncharacteristically fluttered through the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some throws I wish I had back, and I've made some
mistakes,'' McNown said. ``I don't feel like I ever got in the
groove.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, McNown's play proves the theory he and Toledo
proposed during training camp: He'd be a better quarterback this
season than last, but his numbers wouldn't reflect it.
</P>
<P>
   McNown's performance depends on every facet of the offense. The
line must protect him; the running backs must accumulate yards to
keep defenses guessing; the receivers must run correct routes and
catch the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the problem. Danny Farmer is the Bruins' only
experienced receiver, hence his team-leading 13 catches and
21.6-yard average. But Brad Melsby hasn't played in two years,
Brian Poli-Dixon is a sophomore and Jon Dubravac a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Even Freddie Mitchell, for all his big-play ability, has just
begun to learn the offense, read the defense and adjust his routes
when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Where have you gone, Jim McElroy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys are not where they're supposed to be, and it
hurts,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Against Washington State, for example, Poli-Dixon twice ran the
wrong route, Dubravac dropped a sideline pass and tight end Ryan
Neufeld dropped one in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The receivers ultimately decide what sort of quarterback
you'll be,'' McNown said. ``Everybody has to play at their full
potential for your numbers to look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody, including the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned: UCLA athletic director Peter Dalis will decide
whether to reschedule the Miami game within a week.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes have left no doubt: They want to play Dec. 5, the
only date available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my decision, and I'm sure it'll disappoint people one way
or the other,'' Dalis said. ``I've gotten an incredibly mixed
reaction from our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the league's athletic directors vote otherwise, the
cancellation will cost UCLA $507,032 in television revenue. Even if
the game is rescheduled, it's not expected to be televised. CBS has
Army-Navy and a college basketball game that day.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Defensive end Kenyon Coleman (knee) will not
return this week. Defensive end Steve Sua (shoulder) and two
linebackers, Ramogi Huma (hip) and Mike Wiley (ankle), are
questionable. Cornerback Jason Bell (ankle) is probable.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Center Shawn Stuart, cornerback Ryan Roques and
the punt coverage unit were named players/unit of the week. . . .
Offensive tackle Kris Farris and linebacker Tony White will join
the regulars, Larry Atkins and McNown, as captains this week. . . .
Kickoff for the UCLA-Oregon game on Oct. 17 is 12:30 p.m. at the
Rose Bowl. It will be televised regionally by ABC. . . . Several
starters, including McNown, will appear at the UCLA Medical Center
today at noon to make smoothies for kids in the pediatric ward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 2327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
