<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-GOV-DEBATE-835&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT CONNECTICUT GUBERNATORIAL DEBATE, CIVILITY PREVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ U.S. Rep. Barbara Kennelly used the opening
debate of the Connecticut gubernatorial race to go after Gov. John
Rowland with a stick rather than a sword Monday, setting a
dignified tone for the closing month of a campaign in which polls
show the governor holding a huge lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland had to answer for some of the less rosy parts of his
record, including what Mrs. Kennelly considers laxness in the
enforcement of environmental and child-protection laws. But her
criticism was limited mostly to asides as she described her plans
to bolster public education and give new rights to patients insured
by health maintenance organizations. He, too, seemed to be pulling
punches, barely mentioning his differences with her eight-term
record in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland was so confident that during his standard nod of
appreciation to the sponsors at the close of the hourlong debate,
he even thanked Mrs. Kennelly for coming. He said he would focus in
his next term on spreading prosperity to the downtowns of the
state's largest cities but proposed no new plans. ``I think Mrs.
Kennelly sees Connecticut's glass as half-empty,'' he said. ``I see
Connecticut's glass as half-full.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you look ahead, the question becomes, `Why would you
run again?''' he continued. He said that after talking to his wife,
Patricia, ``We decided that the real future of Connecticut is how
we turn our cities around.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to an audience of 500 business leaders from prosperous
Fairfield County, Mrs. Kennelly suggested that much of the
governor's political fortune stemmed from the economy rather than
his policies. ``The years leading to the new millennium are too
crucial to waste by complacency or political posturing _ too
crucial to spend patting yourself on the back about accomplishments
that you didn't have much to do with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Castigating Rowland over his record of enforcing environmental
laws, she said, ``A scandal a month is not good enough for the
state of Connecticut, especially since so many of your companies
came here because of the quality of our life.'' Mrs. Kennelly
accused the governor of an election-year conversion on the
regulation of health insurers, saying of a Connecticut law creating
an appeals process against HMOs, ``You signed it because it was
veto-proof by the time it passed the Legislature, but I am glad
that you did sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Courtney, the Democratic candidate for lieutenant
governor and Mrs. Kennelly's running mate, explained her strategy
after Monday's debate, the first of four. ``The voters are not
going to respond positively to a hammer-and-tong attack,'' Courtney
said. ``The way we win this election is to draw the contrast
between her message and the governor's message.''
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates' contrasting styles were shown most sharply
when they were asked whether the state's death penalty law should
be rewritten to be tougher and more workable. Connecticut last
executed someone three decades ago. The candidates both said
``yes,'' but in very different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly, a Democrat, 62, said the law should be tougher
and clearer, adding, ``Once again, I think we have to get those
lawyers in the room and make sure that we write a law that works.''
Rowland, a Republican, 41, drew laughter when he responded: ``The
last thing I want is lawyers in a room figuring this thing out.
That's why we've got this mess. If anything, get the lawyers out of
the room. Then we can get down to brass tacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Mrs. Kennelly represents the Hartford area in Congress,
Monday's debate served as her introduction to many of the audience
members and television viewers from the New York City suburbs. The
debate was broadcast live over radio and cable television. The
questioners were newspaper editors, and the sponsor was an
association based in Stamford, the Business Council of Southwestern
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates differed most markedly on tax cuts. Rowland, who
years ago abandoned his 1994 campaign promise to end the state
income tax, was asked whether he planned to phase out the tax in a
second term.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always that possibility and that opportunity,'' he
said, pausing for laughter from the crowd, which realized the idea
was long dead. Rowland then acknowledged there was little appetite
for it in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said taxes had been cut $1.7 billion during his term,
including reductions or credits for the income, gas, property and
inheritance taxes. ``We plan to do it over the next four years as
well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly has proposed a 10 percent reduction in property
taxes, which she would accomplish with a state rebate to the cities
and towns that impose and collect the tax. ``I would hope that the
governor would say Monday that he would forget that promise that he
keeps making and never, never does it _ that he says get rid of the
income tax,'' she said. Rowland denounced Mrs. Kennelly's proposal
as ``nothing more than a spending plan, a shell game.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The issue that has dogged Rowland most consistently concerns the
killings of children who were being monitored by the state's
Department of Children and Families. Mrs. Kennelly said: ``It
really is very tragic when a child has to be taken out of his birth
home because of neglect and abuse. But it's more than tragic when a
child under the care of the state has something happen to them.''
She said workers were inadequately trained and social workers'
caseloads too large.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said he had increased spending, staffing and training
for the department. ``With all due respect, Mrs. Kennelly's facts
are entirely wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon's one reference to President Clinton's
troubles, the candidates were asked to what extent a governor was
entitled to a private life. Mrs. Kennelly signaled for the first
time that she planned to vote against impeachment, saying that the
overwhelming response of constituents since the broadcasting of
Clinton's grand jury testimony had been: ```Censor him. Punish him.
But for heaven's sake, Barbara, don't vote for impeachment.'''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland said people wanted Congress to act and move on. ``Lets
get it over with,'' he said. ``Let's have finality. And, by the
way, all people should have a private life, including politicians
and including candidates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
