<SLUG> BC-FBC-OHIOSTATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OSU trying to solve fumble problems
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Dee Miller's eyes bulged when told Ohio State
has fumbled 16 times this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it was that many,'' the wide receiver from
Springfield said Monday, as the Buckeyes began to prepare for
Saturday's game at Illinois (2-3).
</P>
<P>
   Miller was buoyed when informed that the Buckeyes had lost just
five of those fumbles to opponents but admitted, ``that's something
we definitely have to crack down on.''
</P>
<P>
   OSU coach John Cooper has been trying to crack down on fumbles
all season, regularly chasing his players around at practice trying
to pop the ball loose. Despite his efforts, fumbles continue to
plague the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   They had five against West Virginia in their season opener,
three per game vs. Toledo and Missouri and five more against Penn
State last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, players and coaches said, luck has been on their
side. Only one of those fumbles resulted in a touchdown and none
cost the Buckeyes the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely the ball is bouncing our way a little,'' said
quarterback Joe Germaine, who recovered two of his three fumbles
vs. Penn State. ``But fumbles are something we need to nip in the
bud.''
</P>
<P>
   Interceptions have been much less of a problem. Germaine has
thrown just one this season, although it led to the Nittany Lions'
only touchdown Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper says each week he stresses the importance of ball
security to his team. Quarterbacks' coach Tim Salem even played the
game film of one of Germaine's fumbles _ the one poked out from
behind by a Penn State linebacker _ in slow motion for the OSU
quarterback for emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just kind of told me when you run with the ball you need to
keep your elbow closer to your body,'' Germaine said.
</P>
<P>
   OSU cornerback Ahmed Plummer had the Buckeyes' only interception
of the game vs. Penn State and led the team with three pass
break-ups, yet still got some ribbing from his teammates afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We teased Ahmed all weekend,'' strong safety Damon Moore said.
``We said he should've had three or four interceptions. He didn't
get it done, but he made plenty of nice plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Germaine took a couple of hard hits Saturday and said he felt
the after-effects the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up a little stiff in the neck and the ribs on Sunday
morning,'' he said. ``But that's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper worries about his quarterback taking too many hits,
especially since Germaine prides himself on being tough and
``sometimes acts like he doesn't mind taking a shot.'' Germaine
said Cooper need not worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely understand that it's not good to get hit quite
often,'' Germaine said. ``But I'm not going to stand back there and
be afraid of anyone that's going to come in and try to take shots
at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
