<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Safety Bell ready to face old team
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI, Ohio _ Bengals safety Myron Bell knew the day would
come when he'd face his former teammates _ the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   The time is now.
</P>
<P>
   Bell, a star at Michigan State before Pittsburgh took him in the
fifth round of the 1994 draft, started 21of 63 games for the
Steelers before bolting as an unrestricted free agent in the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``My move was a principle-type thing,'' Bell said. ``I wanted to
go somewhere where I could compete for a starting job. With Carnell
Lake being there, I didn't think that was possible any time soon.
So it was best for me to go elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 1-3, so whoever we play this week would be a big game.
It just happens to be the Steelers. Yeah, it's special. We want to
come out with a win and get this thing rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh whipped the Bengals twice in 1997 _ 26-10 here and
20-3 there. Bell remembers all the Steelers fans waving gold
``Terrible Towels'' as the final seconds ticked off the clock at
Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We (the Steelers) called it another home game,'' Bell said.
``That's ridiculous when you have a visiting team come in and have
more fans than the actual home team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I'm on the other side, it's motivating to me. Because
when you travel, you have to carry a different mentality. It so
happens that we're home, but I have to take that mentality with me
out there on Sunday like it's an away game because I'm sure there
will be a lot of Steeler fans there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell said both teams view the AFC Central Division game
differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pittsburgh didn't really push it as a rivalry,'' he said.
``Here, I'm seeing a different side of it. I'll really be able to
tell Wednesday when we go out to practice and see the guys flying
around. I'm going to be out there trying to mix it up a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do whatever it takes to get our practices up-tempo and
get these guys ready to go. Because I'm going to be ready. We need
to start winning some games.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-11, 203-pound Bell has a reputation as a hitter. Now
he gets a chance to tackle Pittsburgh's 250-pound tailback, Jerome
``The Bus'' Bettis, who runs behind a line anchored by perennial
Pro Bowl center Dermontti Dawson.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no secret about it,'' Bell said. ``They're coming in
and trying to run The Bus left and right behind Dermontti. You've
got to wrap him up because he's a load. We have to gang-tackle this
guy and get after him from play one.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he calls Steelers head coach Bill Cowher ``a cocky guy
who believes his way is the right way,'' Bell was careful not to
provide any bulletin board ammunition for his former team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Cowher will read the papers,'' Bell said. ``I don't
want to get them more pumped up than they're already going to be.
We need every little edge we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
