u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NCR-PRIVACY-COX     10-05 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NCR-PRIVACY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCR touts program that gives consumers peek at files
 &HT;    By Jim Dillon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ NCR Corp., which has made millions of dollars
helping big corporations gather huge amounts of personal data about
consumers, is now touting ways for the public to control how that
information is used.
</P>
<P>
   Under a new privacy initiative that NCR unveiled on Monday,
consumers may be able to access corporate databases that contain
information about them and control who else may see it. But it's up
to NCR's customers to actually extend that ability to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Such large retailers as Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and J.C. Penney Co.
use NCR's Teradata software and the company's large computer
systems to build so-called data warehouses. Companies use these big
computer systems to track consumer purchases and preferences and
develop their marketing and advertising campaigns, among other
things, based on the information.
</P>
<P>
   With the new privacy safeguards, consumers could obtain reports
detailing the amount and type of information a company has gathered
on them, govern how the information can be distributed, and correct
any inaccuracies.
</P>
<P>
   NCR believes it is the first data warehouse provider to offer
such safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining consumer privacy has become a major concern
worldwide as more businesses gather and share information about
their customers. Companies like NCR are on the firing line because
their large systems make it possible to catalog and manage huge
amounts of information gathered from consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses such as NCR are eager to develop and adopt their own
privacy safeguards before governments do it for them. Privacy
safeguards also could boost electronic commerce because consumers
would be more willing to do business electronically if they knew
their privacy was protected.
</P>
<P>
   NCR officials said they took action because of privacy
regulations in Europe that take effect later this month, coupled
with lawmakers' desire to boost consumer privacy laws in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that these are coming forth, and . . . we see
ways to help our customers'' comply with the new regulations as
well, said Robert Henderson, vice president of scalable data
warehouse program management for NCR.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we're the first company to step up and bring
consumer privacy to data warehousing,'' said Chris Hankin, director
of government affairs for NCR. ``The biggest driver is the need for
corporations to maintain and build consumers' trust in electronic
commerce, and this is the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan Hendricks, editor of the Washington, D.C.-based Privacy
Times Newsletter, called NCR's new initiative a ``good first
step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Data warehousing raises many privacy concerns about companies
gathering information on individuals without their knowledge and
consent,'' Hendricks said. ``So if NCR is developing software (that
offers more privacy), that's good news.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dillon writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
