A1141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALCS-WRIGHT-COX     10-05 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-WRIGHT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wright to hit batters: 'too bad'
 &HT;    By Tom Withers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jaret Wright likes to pitch inside _ high and inside.
And if his 95 mph fastball happens to thump a batter on the arm or
the hand or in the head, that's just too bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am out there trying to get outs,'' he said Monday. ``I am
out there trying to keep my team in the ballgame, and you know, it
is baseball, people get hit sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright's tendency to hit people _ notably ones wearing Yankee
pinstripes _ has earned him the reputation as a head hunter, a
label he says is unfair and one serving as a major subplot as the
Cleveland Indians prepare to face New York in the AL championship
series.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, who will start Game 1 against David Wells, and the
Yankees have a history. A history and some bad blood.
</P>
<P>
   As a self-assured 21-year-old rookie last October, Wright helped
end the Yankees' season by beating them twice in the division
series. With the world watching and the Bronx breathing down his
neck, he showed poise beyond his years in winning Game 2 in Yankee
Stadium. He followed that by winning the decisive fifth game at
Jacobs Field to move the Indians into their second World Series in
three years.
</P>
<P>
   Wright admits he grew up a little bit on the walk from the
Indians' bullpen to the center stage in New York that night. It's a
walk that has unnerved the steadiest veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took the mound for the first time in the first inning I
remembered how loud it was, and how much the crowd is into it here
on every pitch and how much they don't like the opposition,'' he
said. ``But it was a great experience for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was Cleveland's postseason poster boy, a fresh-faced
California kid who could charm a room full of reporters as easily
as he could fire a fastball at nearly 100 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, however, think they know a different Jaret Wright.
They identify him as the punk who intentionally hit Luis Sojo
during spring training, breaking the infielder's hand, and the one
who threw at Paul O'Neill in a June 19 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, no doubt,'' Sojo said Monday when asked if he thought
Wright was aiming at him last March in Winter Haven, Fla. ``If I
didn't lift my hand up, it would have hit me in the head. That's
why I was so upset. You can't be a head hunter.''
</P>
<P>
   Those two words led to some testiness and verbal brushbacks on
Monday as both teams worked out at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming names, Wells insinuated that Wright head hunted
and New York manager Joe Torre said the right-hander ``throws . . .
uses both sides of the plate. . . . He is very aggressive, very
aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   When Wells' comments were relayed to Cleveland manager Mike
Hargrove, he defended his young pitching star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to get into a word battle with David Wells,''
he said. ``David Wells is very good at what he does. He is a very
good pitcher. He needs to stick with that. . . . Jaret is not a
head hunter.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright tried to defuse any controversy about his relationship
with the Yankees, choosing instead to focus on the job ahead. He
wouldn't elaborate on the Sojo incident or the one with O'Neill in
Cleveland when the two stared at each other while plate umpire John
Shulock escorted the Yankees outfielder to first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much I can say about that,'' he said when asked if
he thought the Yankees held a personal vendetta against him. ``I
don't think we need to turn this thing into anything more than it
is. It's about the third time I have been asked about whether I'm
hitting people or not. . . . But it's nothing, it's not a revenge
factor or anything like that. I don't think.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright went 12-10 during the regular season, 2-1 vs. New York.
He lost his only start here on June 14, allowing six hits and three
runs in six innings. Last week, he didn't think he would have a
chance to face the Yankees or anyone else after lasting just 4 1-3
innings in an 11-3 loss to the Red Sox in Game 1 of the division
series.
</P>
<P>
   But the Indians rallied to win the series, and Tuesday night
Wright will again take the mound at Yankee Stadium and attempt to
beat baseball's best team. Every eye will carefully follow every
pitch. Especially the ones on the inside corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, inside is part of my game, and I am not trying to hurt
anybody or hit anybody,'' he said. ``This is just the way I was
taught to pitch. Hopefully I can get a couple of outs, you know,
pitching inside.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes people get hit.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Withers writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
