<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS GET OK TO SPEAK TO ALOU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers finally received permission Monday to
speak to Montreal manager Felipe Alou after the province of Quebec
rejected the Expos' request for $150 million to help build a new
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone waited almost a week to
hear back from Expos president Claude Brochu about Alou, who is
expected to replace Glenn Hoffman as manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to speak with Felipe soon and meet with him
in the next couple of days and see if we can move forward,'' Malone
said. ``He is the leading candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou, 63, is in his native Dominican Republic assessing the
damage of last week's Hurricane Georges, which hit his home.
Malone, the former Montreal GM, will fly there on Wednesday for
face-to-face discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand his position with the Expos, but I feel he can be
an integral part of baseball in Los Angeles,'' said Malone, who
knows Alou's wife and in-laws are from Montreal. ``He would bring a
tremendous amount of stability, leadership and optimism. I am
encouraged by who he is and what he represents.''
</P>
<P>
   Montreal was hoping to get better news Monday on a proposed
downtown stadium when Brochu and baseball commissioner Bud Selig
met with Quebec's prime minister Lucien Bouchard. They were seeking
$75 million from the provincial government and $75 million from the
federal government to build a complex considered essential for the
Expos' survival in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   When Brochu learned the money wasn't coming, he called Malone.
Brochu offered Alou a contract extension last week and could have
said no to the Dodgers since Alou has one year and $600,000 left on
his Expos deal.
</P>
<P>
   Until this season, Montreal had remained competitive despite a
payroll consistently below $15 million. Under Malone and Alou in
1994, Montreal had the best record in baseball (74-40) when labor
strife shut down the sport and canceled the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Expos tried to develop some stability by
signing young players Vladimir Guerrero (five years, $28 million)
and Ugueth Urbina (four years, $15 million) to long-term contracts.
But the future in Montreal is believed to hinge on the club getting
the new stadium, which now appears unlikely. There is a good chance
the club will be sold and moved.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, with an expected 1999 payroll of $70-75 million,
have their own problems. Their payroll is loaded with multi-year
contracts, limiting Malone's flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   After he hires a manager, Malone must decide what he can do with
third baseman Bobby Bonilla, who was unproductive after coming over
from Florida in the May 15 Mike Piazza trade. Bonilla, 35, has two
years left on his contract worth $11.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   But for now the top priority is hiring a manager and coaching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he spoke twice to Jim Leyland _ who was hired to
manage the Colorado Rockies Monday, a week after resigning as
manager of the Florida Marlins. But Malone knew Leyland was not
keen on coming to Los Angeles, since his family, which lives
outside Pittsburgh, thought even Miami was too far a commute.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he will not speak to any other candidates until he
gets an answer from Alou.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-05-98 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
