<HEADLINE>
CUNNINGHAM AND VIKINGS PICK THE PACKERS APART IN THE RAIN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ It is time to start talking about how the
offense of the Minnesota Vikings may be one of the best of all
time.
</P>
<P>
   After the Vikings pounded the Green Bay Packers Monday night on
national television, much of America got to see what the rest of
the National Football League has suspected for months _ that
Minnesota, behind an awesome offensive attack, is the favorite to
represent the National Football Conference in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That is what a 37-24 victory against the top-ranked defense in
the league before 59,849 at Lambeau Field _ where the Packers had
won 29 straight games _ will do. By sending the Packers to their
first loss of the season, the Vikings, at 5-0, are now the only
undefeated team in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Randall Cunningham, who quarterbacked the best game of
his career, the Vikings amassed more than 500 yards of offense,
with Cunningham going to wide receivers Cris Carter, Jake Reed and
the rookie-of-the-year lock, Randy Moss. Cunningham hit those three
for six passes of at least 30 yards. The Vikings had big catches
for 56 yards (a Reed touchdown), 52 yards (a Moss touchdown), 41
yards (Moss), 33 yards (Carter), 46 yards (Moss) and 44 yards
(another Moss touchdown). Moss finished with five catches for 190
yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who threw for four touchdowns, completed 20 of 31
passes for 442 yards _ the most ever against the Packers. The last
person to throw for more than 400 yards against Green Bay was Joe
Montana in 1990, when he passed for 411.
</P>
<P>
   What about that supposedly suspect Minnesota defense? Green
Bay's offense did not score a touchdown until the game was out of
hand. Brett Favre, who came into this game as maybe the hottest
quarterback in the NFL, was just 13 of 23 for 114 yards and three
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of those shocking, possible season-changing games.
If the Packers aren't careful, this loss could hurt the rest of
their season. The Vikings could use the victory to propel them to a
special year.
</P>
<P>
   While many fans and members of the news media focused on the
Vikings' impressive arsenal _ Carter, Reed and Moss as well as
running back Robert Smith _ the Packers' defensive staff, one of
the best in the league, quietly focused all week on Cunningham, the
man who would be throwing the ball to those players.
</P>
<P>
   Older and wiser, Cunningham, 35, has become more patient in the
pocket. Still, the Packers felt they could confuse Cunningham with
a variety of zone coverages. If those did not work, then they
planned to blitz Cunningham up the middle, because the Packers felt
he still did not respond well to pressure and would get rid of the
football as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers wanted to make Cunningham read all sorts of
coverages. If he figured them out, so be it. But Green Bay was
betting he would not, which would mean interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's first drive was indicative of what would go on all
game. The Packers indeed did a variety of things to try to confuse
Cunningham. They played defensive end Reggie White at nose tackle
to get pressure up the middle. They blitzed a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham was not fazed, however, and the Vikings showed why
they have the most deadly offense in the game. They often went to
four wide receivers. They used screen passes to Smith, threw bombs
to Moss and used reverses by the speedy running back David Palmer.
Cunningham would be surrounded by defenders, then calmly take two
steps into the pocket and deliver a strike. The Packers' blitzers
did not get near Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's first drive went 65 yards in 14 plays and ate seven
minutes off the clock. It ended with a 33-yard field goal by Gary
Anderson as the Vikings elected to put points on the board rather
than go for the first down on fourth-and-1. Green Bay then tied the
score with a 40-yard field goal by Ryan Longwell.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, getting more protection than a Brinks armored car,
dealt what to most teams would have been a demoralizing blow,
throwing a 56-yard bomb to Reed, who had spun cornerback Craig
Newsome like a top. But the Packers rarely get rattled, as they
demonstrated on the kickoff return when Roell Preston, behind a
wall of blockers, scampered 101 yards to tie the score at 10-10. It
was his second 100-yard kick return for a touchdown this year, the
other going for 100 yards against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed the Packers were right back in the game, but the
Vikings' offense was too powerful. They responded with three
incredible plays. The first was another bomb to Moss, this one for
a touchdown of 52 yards. On another drive, Cunningham threw a
41-yard pass to Moss as he outjumped double coverage and gave
Minnesota the ball at the Green Bay 24-yard line. Two plays later,
Smith scored on a 24-yard screen pass to give Minnesota a 24-10
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that play, thunderstorms rolled through the area,
turning the field into a mess.
</P>
</TEXT>
